voca.title: a lot of
voca.explains: many / a lot of / lots of\n

voca.title: abalone
voca.explains: Abalone is a shellfish that you can eat and that has a shiny substance called mother-of-pearl inside its shell.\nThere are a lot of different types, too. You can have porridge with ingredients like abalone, shrimp, chicken, or seafood, depending on your taste.\n

voca.title: abbreviate
voca.explains: If you abbreviate something, especially a word or a piece of writing, you make it shorter.\n

voca.title: abbreviation
voca.explains: An abbreviation is a short form of a word or phrase, made by leaving out some of the letters or by using only the first letter of each word.\nWhat's the abbreviation for 'Saint'?\n

voca.title: abdomen
voca.explains: Your abdomen is the part of your body below your chest where your stomach and intestines are.\n

voca.title: abductor
voca.explains: The abductor did not demand a ransom.\nShe says the artist's impression is an excellent likeness of her abductor.\n

voca.title: aberrant
voca.explains: Aberrant means unusual and not socially acceptable.\n

voca.title: abet
voca.explains: If one person abets another, they help or encourage them to do something criminal or wrong. Abet is often used in the legal expression 'aid and abet'.\n

voca.title: ability
voca.means: [어빌러디]\n능력, 힘, 재능, 기량, 수완, 솜씨, 역량
voca.explains:
Your ability to do something is the fact that you can do it.
Your ability is the quality or skill that you have which makes it possible for you to do something
If you do something to the best of your abilities or to the best of your ability, you do it as well as you can.

voca.title: able
voca.explains:
If you are able to do something, you have skills or qualities which make it possible for you to do it.
If you are able to do something, you have enough freedom, power, time, or money to do it.
Someone who is able is very clever or very good at doing something.

voca.title: abnormal
voca.explains: Someone or something that is abnormal is unusual, especially in a way that is worrying.\n

voca.title: aboard
voca.means: [어^보r-d]\n(배, 기차, 비행기 등에) 탄, 탑승/승선 한
voca.explains: If you are aboard a ship or plane, you are on it or in it.\n

voca.title: abolish
voca.explains: If someone in authority abolishes a system or practice, they formally put an end to it.\n

voca.title: aborigine
voca.explains: Aborigines are members of the tribes that were living in Australia when Europeans arrived there.\n

voca.title: abort
voca.explains: If an unborn baby is aborted, the pregnancy is ended deliberately and the baby is not born alive.\nIf someone aborts a process, plan, or activity, they stop it before it has been completed.\n

voca.title: abortion
voca.explains: If a woman has an abortion, she ends her pregnancy deliberately so that the baby is not born alive.\nWhat are your views on abortion? / We'd like to know what you feel about abortion.\n

voca.title: abortive
voca.explains: An abortive attempt or action is unsuccessful.\n

voca.title: abound
voca.explains:
If things abound, or if a place abounds with things, there are very large numbers of them.
Events Abound for the Lunar New Year!
Theories abound about how the earth began.

voca.title: about
voca.means:
[어바웃t]
약, ~쯤, ~ 경, 거의,
~에 대한(무엇의 주제나 연관성을 나타냄)
~에 관한, ~와 관련된
voca.explains:
around / round / about
You use about to introduce who or what something relates to or concerns.
When you mention the things that an activity or institution is about, you are saying what it involves or what its aims are.
You use about after some adjectives to indicate the person or thing that a feeling or state of mind relates to.
If you do something about a problem, you take action in order to solve it.

voca.title: above
voca.means:
[어^붜-v]
(위치나 지위면에서) ~보다 위에/위로
(나이, 수 등이) ~보다 많은, ~을 넘는
(중요도, 품질 등이) ~보다 위인, ~보다 우위인
위로/위에, ~ 이상으로, ~을 넘어
voca.explains:
above / over
If one thing is above another one, it is directly over it or higher than it.
If an amount or measurement is above a particular level, it is greater than that level.
If you hear one sound above another, it is louder or clearer than the second one.
If someone is above you, they are in a higher social position than you or in a position of authority over you.
If you say that someone thinks they are above something, you mean that they act as if they are too good or important for it.
When they stepped onto the ground, there was a great roar above them.

voca.title: above all
voca.explains: That’s when I decided to go on a diet. I ate less. I ate mostly vegetables. Above all, I started to exercise.\nKorea’s subway system is great. The Seoul Metro is a model of public transportation. It’s convenient. It’s affordable. Above all, it’s easy to use. It really is the full package.\n

voca.title: abroad
voca.explains: If you go abroad, you go to a foreign country, usually one which is separated from the country where you live by an ocean or a sea.\n

voca.title: abruptly
voca.explains: His laugh stopped abruptly.\n

voca.title: absence
voca.explains: Someone's absence from a place is the fact that they are not there.\nThe absence of something from a place is the fact that it is not there or does not exist.\n

voca.title: absent
voca.explains:
If someone or something is absent from a place or situation where they should be or where they usually are, they are not there.
If someone appears absent, they are not paying attention because they are thinking about something else.
An absent parent does not live with his or her children.
If you say that absent one thing, another thing will happen, you mean that if the first thing does not happen, the second thing will happen.

voca.title: absentee
voca.explains:
An absentee is a person who is expected to be in a particular place but who is not there.
Absentee is used to describe someone who is not there to do a particular job in person.
In elections in the United States, if you vote by absentee ballot or if you are an absentee voter, you vote in advance because you will be away.

voca.title: absolute
voca.means:
[엡썰룻t]
완전한, 완벽한, 확실한, 확고한
절대적인, 완전한, 완벽한, 가장 ~한,
제한이 없는, 절대적인
voca.explains:
Absolute means total and complete.
You use absolute to emphasize something that you are saying.
An absolute ruler has complete power and authority over his or her country.
Absolute is used to say that something is definite and will not change even if circumstances change.
An amount that is expressed in absolute terms is expressed as a fixed amount rather than referring to variable factors such as what you earn or the effects of inflation.
An absolute is a rule or principle that is believed to be true, right, or relevant in all situations.

voca.title: absolutely
voca.means:
[엡설^룻리]
전적으로, 틀림없이(사실임을 강조함)
전혀(부정의 의미를 강조함)
극도로, 굉장히, 
절대적으로, 완전히, 전혀
그럼, 물론이지(강한 동의, 허락을 나타냄)
voca.explains:
Absolutely means totally and completely.
Some people say absolutely as an emphatic way of saying yes or of agreeing with someone. They say absolutely not as an emphatic way of saying no or of disagreeing with someone.
"One hundred percent absolutely double-sure guaranteed."

voca.title: absorb
voca.means:
[업죠r-b]
(액체, 가스 등을) 흡수하다, 빨아들이다, 
(정보를) 받아들이다,
(돈이나 시간을) 차지하다/잡아먹다
voca.explains:
If something absorbs a liquid, gas, or other substance, it soaks it up or takes it in.
If something absorbs light, heat, or another form of energy, it takes it in.
If a group is absorbed into a larger group, it becomes part of the larger group.
If something absorbs a force or shock, it reduces its effect.
The roots absorb water and minerals for the plants.
Plants absorb carbon from the atmosphere.

voca.title: abstain
voca.means: [^엡s때인]\n(투표에서) 기권하다\n(특히 자기가 좋아하는 것을 건강, 도덕상의 이유로) 자제하다, 삼가다
voca.explains: If you abstain from something, usually something you want to do, you deliberately do not do it.\nIf you abstain during a vote, you do not use your vote.\n

voca.title: abstain from
voca.explains: to decide not to do or have something, especially something that you like or enjoy, because it is bad for your health or considered morally wrong\n

voca.title: abstain from eating
voca.explains:
On my family's advice, I recently received a medical check-up. It was a comprehensive examination. The day before, I had to abstain from eating.
Abstaining from eating was the hardest thing I've ever done.
I want to lose weight, but I don't want to abstain from eating.

voca.title: abstract
voca.explains:
An abstract idea or way of thinking is based on general ideas rather than on real things and events.
In grammar, an abstract noun refers to a quality or idea rather than to a physical object.
Abstract art makes use of shapes and patterns rather than showing people or things.
Don't most people think philosophy is too abstract for them?
I read the abstract at the meeting.
This is the abstract of the presentation.

voca.title: abstraction
voca.means:
[엡st^뤡션]
추상 관념, 개념, 비실제적 관념
~에만 마음이 쏠려 있음, 정신이 딴데 팔려 있음
추출
voca.explains: An abstraction is a general idea rather than one relating to a particular object, person, or situation.\n

voca.title: abundance
voca.explains:
An abundance of something is a large quantity of it.
North America is a land of abundance.
An abundance of instances is cited.

voca.title: abundant
voca.explains:
Something that is abundant is present in large quantities.
Inside, I feel peaceful and abundant.
I have abundant reason to believe it.
This country is abundant in natural resources.

voca.title: abuse
voca.means:
[업^뷰-s]
남용, 오용, 학대, 욕설
(건강이 상하도록 무엇을) 남용/오용하다
(특히 성적으로) 학대하다
욕을하다
voca.explains:
Abuse of someone is cruel and violent treatment of them.
Abuse is extremely rude and insulting things that people say when they are angry.
Abuse of something is the use of it in a wrong way or for a bad purpose.
If someone is abused, they are treated cruelly and violently.
You can say that someone is abused if extremely rude and insulting things are said to them.

voca.title: abyss
voca.explains: An abyss is a very deep hole in the ground.\nIf someone is on the edge or brink of an abyss, they are about to enter into a very frightening or threatening situation.\n

voca.title: academic
voca.explains:
Academic is used to describe things that relate to the work done in schools, colleges, and universities, especially work which involves studying and reasoning rather than practical or technical skills.
Academic is used to describe things that relate to schools, colleges, and universities.
Academic is used to describe work, or a school, college, or university, that places emphasis on studying and reasoning rather than on practical or technical skills.
Someone who is academic is good at studying.
You can say that a discussion or situation is academic if you think it is not important because it has no real effect or cannot happen.
An academic is a member of a university or college who teaches or does research.

voca.title: academy
voca.explains: Academy is sometimes used in the names of schools and colleges, especially those specializing in particular subjects or skills, or private high schools in the United States.\nAcademy appears in the names of some societies formed to improve or maintain standards in a particular field.\n

voca.title: accelerate
voca.explains: If the process or rate of something accelerates or if something accelerates it, it gets faster and faster.\nWhen a moving vehicle accelerates, it goes faster and faster.\n

voca.title: accent
voca.means: [엑센t]\n~에 악센트를 두다, ~을 강조하다\n강세, 음조, 어조, 말투, 사투리
voca.explains:
Someone who speaks with a particular accent pronounces the words of a language in a distinctive way that shows which country, region, or social class they come from.
An accent is a short line or other mark which is written above certain letters in some languages and which indicates the way those letters are pronounced.
If you put the accent on a particular feature of something, you emphasize it or give it special importance.

voca.title: accept
voca.explains:
If you accept something that you have been offered, you say yes to it or agree to take it.
If you accept an idea, statement, or fact, you believe that it is true or valid.
If you accept a plan or an intended action, you agree to it and allow it to happen.
If you accept an unpleasant fact or situation, you get used to it or recognize that it is necessary or cannot be changed.
If a person, company, or organization accepts something such as a document, they recognize that it is genuine, correct, or satisfactory and agree to consider it or handle it.

voca.title: accept someone's apology
voca.explains:
She acepted my apology.
She was so angry that she didn't accept his apology.
Do you think he will accept my apology?

voca.title: acceptable
voca.explains:
Acceptable activities and situations are those that most people approve of or consider to be normal.
If something is acceptable to someone, they agree to consider it, use it, or allow it to happen.
If you describe something as acceptable, you mean that it is good enough or fairly good.

voca.title: acceptance
voca.means: [엑^셉던s]\n(선물, 제의 등을) 받아들임, 수락\n동의, 승인, 가입 허가, 수용 절차
voca.explains:
Acceptance of an offer or a proposal is the act of saying yes to it or agreeing to it.
If there is acceptance of an idea, most people believe or agree that it is true.
Your acceptance of a situation, especially an unpleasant or difficult one, is an attitude or feeling that you cannot change it and that you must get used to it.
Acceptance of someone into a group means beginning to think of them as part of the group and to act in a friendly way towards them.

voca.title: acceptance speech
voca.explains:
The award recipients give acceptance speeches. There are congratulatory performances by singers.
I'm sorry, but I didn't prepare an acceptance speech.
Her acceptance speech was so touching that everyone cried.

voca.title: access
voca.means: [엑쎄s]\n(장소로의) 접근, 이용, 접속, 출입\n~을 입수/이용하다, ~에 접근하다
voca.explains:
If you have access to a building or other place, you are able or allowed to go into it.
If you have access to something such as information or equipment, you have the opportunity or right to see it or use it.
If you have access to a person, you have the opportunity or right to see them or meet them.
If you access something, especially information held on a computer, you succeed in finding or obtaining it.

voca.title: accessible
voca.explains:
If a place or building is accessible to people, it is easy for them to reach it or get into it. If an object is accessible, it is easy to reach.
If something is accessible to people, they can easily use it or obtain it.
If you describe a book, painting, or other work of art as accessible, you think it is good because it is simple enough for people to understand and appreciate easily.

voca.title: accessory
voca.explains:
Accessories are items of equipment that are not usually essential, but which can be used with or added to something else in order to make it more efficient, useful, or decorative.
Accessories are articles such as belts and scarves which you wear or carry but which are not part of your main clothing.
If someone is guilty of being an accessory to a crime, they helped the person who committed it, or knew it was being committed but did not tell the police.

voca.title: accident
voca.explains:
luck / chance / coincidence / accident / fortune / fate / destiny / providence
An accident happens when a vehicle hits a person, an object, or another vehicle, causing injury or damage.
If someone has an accident, something unpleasant happens to them that was not intended, sometimes causing injury or death.
If something happens by accident, it happens completely by chance.

voca.title: accidental
voca.explains: An accidental event happens by chance or as the result of an accident, and is not deliberately intended.\n

voca.title: accidentally
voca.explains: "Yes, we met a while ago when I accidentally changed myself into a dog!" said Teddy.\n

voca.title: accommodation
voca.means:
[어^커머데이션]
거처, 숙소, 시설
(흔히 식사나 다른 서비스들도 제공하는) 숙박 시설
합의, 협상
voca.explains:
Accommodation is used to refer to buildings or rooms where people live or stay.
Accommodation is space in buildings or vehicles that is available for certain things, people, or activities.
Studio apartments are a fine solution. They provide cozy accommodations at a fraction of the price. Studios are also popular as love nests for newlywed couples.

voca.title: accompany
voca.means:
[어^컴퍼니]
(사람과) 동반하다, 동행하다
(일, 현상 등이) 동반되다, 딸리다
(특히 피아노로) 반주를 해 주다
~을 수행하다
voca.explains:
If you accompany someone, you go somewhere with them.
If one thing accompanies another, it happens or exists at the same time, or as a result of it.
If you accompany a singer or a musician, you play one part of a piece of music while they sing or play the main tune.
Whether they started school and dropped out or never enrolled at all, these CEOs are proof that success doesn't have to be accompanied by a degree.
I accompanied my boss to Seattle for a business trip.

voca.title: accomplice
voca.explains: Someone's accomplice is a person who helps them to commit a crime.\n"People might begin to think you’re my partner in crime. You could be my accomplice, my henchman, my-"\n

voca.title: accomplish
voca.explains:
If you accomplish something, you succeed in doing it.
She accomplished her mission for the lifting of a finger.
She has accomplished much in her short career. / I don't know what they accomplished.
He accomplished what was considered unthinkable.

voca.title: accomplished
voca.means: [어컴플뤼쉬d]\n기량이 뛰어난, 재주가 많은, \n성취된, 수달된, 노련한, 잘 훈련된
voca.explains: If someone is accomplished at something, they are very good at it.\nShe was an elegant and accomplished woman.\n

voca.title: accomplishment
voca.explains: An accomplishment is something remarkable that has been done or achieved.\nYour accomplishments are the things that you can do well or the important things that you have done.\n

voca.title: accord
voca.means: [어코r-d]\n(기관, 국가 간의 공식적인) 합의\n(권위, 지위 등을) 부여하다, 부합하다
voca.explains:
An accord between countries or groups of people is a formal agreement, for example to end a war.
If you are accorded a particular kind of treatment, people act towards you or treat you in that way.
If one fact, idea, or condition accords with another, they are in agreement and there is no conflict between them.
If one person, action, or fact is in accord with another, they are in agreement and there is no conflict between them. You can also say that two people or things are in accord.

voca.title: according
voca.explains:
in proportion; in relation
on the report (of); as stated (by)
in conformity (with); in accordance (with)
depending (on whether)
dependent on

voca.title: accordingly
voca.means: [어코r-딍뤼]\n그에 따라, 따라서, 적절히, 부응해서, 그에 맞춰\n그런 이유로, 그래서
voca.explains: You use accordingly to introduce a fact or situation which is a result or consequence of something that you have just referred to.\nIf you consider a situation and then act accordingly, the way you act depends on the nature of the situation.\n

voca.title: account
voca.means: [어카운t]\n설명하다, 책임을 지다, 생각/간주하다, 여기다\n계좌, 장부, 회계, 기사, 보고
voca.explains:
bill / statement / account / invoice / tab / check
If you have an account with a bank or a similar organization, you have an arrangement to leave your money there and take some out when you need it.
In business, a regular customer of a company can be referred to as an account, especially when the customer is another company.
Accounts are detailed records of all the money that a person or business receives and spends.
An account is a written or spoken report of something that has happened.
f you say that something is true by all accounts or from all accounts, you believe it is true because other people say so.
I will account for the incident.
I need a joint checking account for my husband and me.

voca.title: account for something
voca.explains:
to explain how or why something happened; to be the explanation for something
to be a particular part of something; to be a particular amount
to keep a record of how the money in your care will be spent or has been spent
to consider particular facts or circumstances when you are making a decision about something, especially when you are calculating the cost of something

voca.title: accountant
voca.explains:
An accountant is a person whose job is to keep financial accounts.
What time is the accountant coming?
If you need an accountant, my brother could help you out.

voca.title: accounting
voca.explains:
Accounting is the activity of keeping detailed records of the amounts of money a business or person receives and spends.
In the meantime, use the one in the Accounting Department.
My major was marketing, and my minor, accounting.

voca.title: accrue
voca.explains: If money or interest accrues or if you accrue it, it gradually increases in amount over a period of time.\nIf things such as profits or benefits accrue to someone, they are added to over a period of time.\n

voca.title: accumulate
voca.explains: collect / gather / accumulate / run sth up / amass\nWhen you accumulate things or when they accumulate, they collect or are gathered over a period of time.\n

voca.title: accuracy
voca.explains:
The accuracy of information or measurements is their quality of being true or correct, even in small details.
If someone or something performs a task, for example hitting a target, with accuracy, they do it in an exact way without making a mistake.
That typist does not come up to our standards of accuracy.
The accuracy of what he says is not to be questioned.
At this point, we are one hundred percent accuracy.

voca.title: accurate
voca.explains:
true / right / correct / exact / precise / accurate / spot on
Accurate information, measurements, and statistics are correct to a very detailed level. An accurate instrument is able to give you information of this kind.
An accurate statement or account gives a true or fair judgment of something.
You can use accurate to describe the results of someone's actions when they do or copy something correctly or exactly.
An accurate weapon or throw reaches the exact point or target that it was intended to reach. You can also describe a person as accurate if they fire a weapon or throw something in this way.

voca.title: accusation
voca.explains:
If you make an accusation against someone, you criticize them or express the belief that they have done something wrong.
An accusation is a statement or claim by a witness or someone in authority that a particular person has committed a crime, although this has not yet been proved.
You can bring an accusation against that man. / There was a hint of accusation in her voice.

voca.title: accuse
voca.means:
[어^큐우-z]
고소/고발하다, 혐의를 받다
~에게 죄를 돌리다/씌우다, 모함하다
비난하다, 책망하다
(사건을) 폭로하다, 밝히다
voca.explains:
If you accuse someone of doing something wrong or dishonest, you say or tell them that you believe that they did it.
If you are accused of a crime, a witness or someone in authority states or claims that you did it, and you may be formally charged with it and put on trial.
I don't want to accuse them.
I didn't accuse him of anything.
She completely overreacted. She accused me of being a gossip. I should have let it slide. Instead, I took the bait. We argued bitterly. We traded insults on the phone.

voca.title: accustom
voca.explains: If you accustom yourself or another person to something, you make yourself or them become used to it.\nShe did not accustom herself to her surroundings. / It will do you good to accustom yourself to a regular life.\n

voca.title: accustomed
voca.means: [어^커s덤d]\n익숙한, 적응된, 습관이 된, 늘 하는\n평상시의, 늘 하는
voca.explains:
If you are accustomed to something, you know it so well or have experienced it so often that it seems natural, unsurprising, or easy to deal with.
When your eyes become accustomed to darkness or bright light, they adjust so that you start to be able to see things, after not being able to see properly at first.
You can use accustomed to describe an action that someone usually does, a quality that they usually show, or an object that they usually use.

voca.title: ace
voca.explains:
An ace is a playing card with a single symbol on it. In most card games, the ace of a particular suit has either the highest or the lowest value of the cards in that suit.
If you describe someone such as a sports player as an ace, you mean that they are very good at what they do.
In tennis, an ace is a serve which is so fast that the other player cannot reach the ball.
If you say that something is ace, you think that it is good and you like it a lot.
If you say that someone holds all the aces, you mean that they have all the advantages in a contest or situation.

voca.title: ace it
voca.explains: Terry: Okay. I studied very hard. I think I did okay. I don't know why I'm so worried. I hope I aced it.\n

voca.title: ace out
voca.explains: to defeat somebody in order to obtain an important position or rank\n

voca.title: ache
voca.means:
[^에익k]
(계속 무지근히) 아프다, 못 견디다
(~하고 싶어) 못 견디다
(계속 적인) 아품, 쑤심
voca.explains:
hurt / ache / burn / sting / tingle / throb
If you ache or a part of your body aches, you feel a steady, fairly strong pain.
If you ache for something or your heart aches, you want something very much, and feel very unhappy because you cannot have it.
An ache is a steady, fairly strong pain in a part of your body.

So, for people who like to take notes by computer, there are some advantages of this. If you air clothing or bedding, you put it somewhere warm to make sure that it is completely dry.

voca.title: air one's grievances
voca.explains: Recently, we ran into each other by chance. I swallowed my pride and said hello. We soon broke the ice. We aired our grievances. In a few minutes we were thick as thieves again. In retrospect, our argument was foolish.\n

voca.title: air purifier
voca.explains: Install an air purifier and a water purifier in your house or office.\n

voca.title: air raid
voca.explains: An air raid is an attack by military aircraft in which bombs are dropped. This expression is usually used by the country or group that is suffering the attack.\n

voca.title: airline
voca.explains: An airline is a company which provides regular services carrying people or goods in aeroplanes.\n

voca.title: airport
voca.explains: An airport is a place where aircraft land and take off, which has buildings and facilities for passengers.\n

voca.title: aisle
voca.explains: An aisle is a long narrow gap that people can walk along between rows of seats in a public building such as a church or between rows of shelves in a supermarket.\nThe man stretched his leg out in the aisle of the airplane.\n

voca.title: alarm
voca.means: [알^롸r암]\n불안, 공포, 놀람, 경보, 경보장치\n~을 놀라게 하다
voca.explains:
fear / alarm / apprehension / fright / foreboding
Alarm is a feeling of fear or anxiety that something unpleasant or dangerous might happen.
An alarm is an automatic device that warns you of danger, for example by ringing a bell.
An alarm is the same as an alarm clock.
If something alarms you, it makes you afraid or anxious that something unpleasant or dangerous might happen.
They were flying toward the mountaintop, cawing madly in alarm.

voca.title: albeit
voca.explains: You use albeit to introduce a fact or comment which reduces the force or significance of what you have just said.\n

voca.title: albino
voca.explains: An albino is a person or animal with very white skin, white hair, and pink eyes.\n

voca.title: album
voca.explains:
An album is a record with about 25 minutes of music on each side. You can also refer to a collection of songs that is available on a record, cassette, or CD as an album.
An album is a book in which you keep things such as photographs or stamps that you have collected.
Her new album is all the rage.

voca.title: alcohol
voca.explains: Drinks that can make people drunk, such as beer, wine, and whisky, can be referred to as alcohol.\nAlcohol is a colourless liquid that is found in drinks such as beer, wine, and whisky. It is also used in products such as perfumes and cleaning fluids.\n

voca.title: alert
voca.means:
[얼^럿t]
(위험 등을) 알리다, 경고하다, 경보를 발하다
의식하게 하다, 주의를 환기시키다
경계 태세, 경계 경보
방심하지 않는, 기민한, 민첩한
voca.explains:
If you are alert, you are paying full attention to things around you and are able to deal with anything that might happen.
If you are alert to something, you are fully aware of it.
An alert is a situation in which people prepare themselves for something dangerous that might happen soon.
If you alert someone to a situation, especially a dangerous or unpleasant situation, you tell them about it.
If soldiers or police are on alert, they are ready to deal with anything that may happen.
The Pacific Tsunami Warning System alerts the public of earthquakes or other disturbances that take place at sea.
The warnings alert people to stay away from beaches and move to higher ground.
I’m usually very alert and attentive. However, when it comes to my belongings, I can be a little scatterbrained. I have a knack for misplacing things.
It pays to be alert. That way, you probably won’t lose anything, and you will be safe.

voca.title: alias
voca.means: [엘리어s]\n~라는 가명으로 알려진, 일명 ~라 불리는, \n별명, 별칭, 가명
voca.explains: An alias is a false name, especially one used by a criminal.\nYou use alias when you are mentioning another name that someone, especially a criminal or an actor, is known by.\n

voca.title: alibi
voca.explains: If you have an alibi, you can prove that you were somewhere else when a crime was committed.\nThe suspects all had alibis for the day of the robbery.\n

voca.title: align
voca.explains:
If you align yourself with a particular group, you support them because you have the same political aim.
If you align something, you place it in a certain position in relation to something else, usually parallel to it.
Make sure the shelf is aligned with the top of the cupboard.
Domestic prices have been aligned with those in world markets.

voca.title: alignment
voca.explains: An alignment is support for a particular group, especially in politics, or for a side in a quarrel or struggle.\nThe alignment of something is its position in relation to something else or to its correct position.\n

voca.title: alike
voca.explains:
If two or more things are alike, they are similar in some way.
Alike means in a similar way.
You use alike after mentioning two or more people, groups, or things in order to emphasize that you are referring to both or all of them.

voca.title: A-list
voca.explains: He only invited A-list celebrities to his parties.\nMost stars have great stylists. It's fun to see what A-list stars are wearing on the red carpet.\n

voca.title: alive
voca.explains:
If people or animals are alive, they are not dead.
If you say that someone seems alive, you mean that they seem to be very lively and to enjoy everything that they do.
If an activity, organization, or situation is alive, it continues to exist or function.
If a place is alive with something, there are a lot of people or things there and it seems busy or exciting.

voca.title: all
voca.means:
[오r올]
모든, 최대한의, 
한 가지로만 이루어진, 온통 ~인
어느 ~도, 모든
완전히, 온통, 아주, 몹시, 너무나도, 대단히
voca.explains:
You use all to indicate that you are referring to the whole of a particular group or thing or to everyone or everything of a particular kind.
You use all to refer to the whole of a particular period of time.
You use all in expressions such as in all sincerity and in all probability
You use all to emphasize that something is completely true, or happens everywhere or always, or on every occasion.

voca.title: all abroad
voca.means: 어찌할 바를 몰라, 당황하여\n(짐작 따위가 아주) 얼토당토 않아

voca.title: all along
voca.explains: from the beginning\n

voca.title: all at once
voca.explains: suddenly\nAll at once, he felt very awake.\n

voca.title: all but
voca.explains: almost\nall (the people or things mentioned) except…\n

voca.title: all flash and no substance
voca.means: 겉은 화려하면서 내용이나 영양가는 없는 것
voca.explains: I recently went to a restaurant on a recommendation from a friend. She spoke very highly of it. Perhaps my expectations were too high. But compared to the price, the food was a let-down. It was all flash and no substance.\n

voca.title: all found
voca.explains: with free food and accommodation in addition to your wages\n

voca.title: all in
voca.explains: with nothing extra to pay; inclusive\nvery tired\n

voca.title: all in all
voca.explains:
when everything is considered
We ran out of some food but all in all everyone had a good time at the party.
Yes there were some rough times but all in all life was good.
Nelson: Yes there were some rough times but all in all life was good.
Supporters of the law believe that it will root out corruption. All in all, I hope it will do its job well.
All in all, phone bills in Korea are quite reasonable.

voca.title: all manner of
voca.explains:
many different types of people or things
The park has something for everyone. There are paths for a light stroll. There are lanes set aside for bicycles. There are grassy fields tailor-made for picnics. And there are facilities for all manner of sports.
I met all manner of people while I was traveling.
He has worked at all manner of jobs.

voca.title: all of a sudden
voca.explains: suddenly and unexpectedly\nAll of a sudden it started to rain.\n

voca.title: all of sudden
voca.explains: suddenly and unexpectedly\nAll of a sudden someone grabbed me around the neck.\n

voca.title: all over
voca.explains: everywhere\nwhat you would expect of the person mentioned\n

voca.title: all over again
voca.explains:
once more; for a second time
Francine nodded. "Yeah. But you know, soccer season is coming up. And if you stink at that, I get to tease you all over again."
Most get the day off on Election Day. They wake up early, eager to vote. Elected members stay in office for 4 years. Even people who kick themselves over past votes can start all over again. Korea takes pride in being a democracy.

voca.title: all over the country
voca.explains: There are many public baths in Korea. People frequent these baths all over the country.\n

voca.title: all set to go
voca.explains: The car is packed and we're all set to go on our vacation.\nEddie: That's too early. We have everything packed already. We're all set to go.\n

voca.title: all the best
voca.means: 안녕히 계세요/가세요.\n(작별 인사나 편지 마무리인사로 씀)
voca.explains: used when you are saying goodbye or ending a letter to give somebody your best wishes\n

voca.title: all the way
voca.explains:
during the whole journey/period of time
completely; as much as it takes to achieve what you want
Buster was next. He fouled off two pitches but swung all the way around on the third.
He went on like that all the way out to the bus. I didn’t try to stop him. A good detective knows when to sit back and listen.

voca.title: all there
voca.explains: having a healthy mind; thinking clearly\n

voca.title: all there is to know
voca.explains:
First and foremost, I like the information I can glean. Shopping hosts courteously explain all there is to know about a product. This is a distinct advantage over other methods. Also, sometime home shopping offers bargain basement prices.
She knows all there is to know about it.
The internet site offers all there is to know.

voca.title: all together
voca.explains:
altogether / all together
Assistant: OK, that's not a problem. It's $120 all together.
Jason: So how much is it all together?

voca.title: all too easy
voca.explains: As it stands, it’s all too easy to pick the wrong cycle. In the worst-case scenario, this can ruin your clothes. Believe me, it has happened before.\n

voca.title: all wet
voca.explains: completely wrong\n

voca.title: all year round
voca.explains:
all year; all the time
The mountains in Korea are charming all year round. In the summer, I enjoy the coolness of the mountain streams. Last fall, I went to enjoy the autumn foliage.
The weather there is warm all year round
They are open all year round.

voca.title: all-consuming
voca.explains: The biggest problem was that stock trading is all-consuming. I kept getting side-tracked at work as I checked the stock prices. I couldn’t focus on my day job. I eventually had to give it up. Stock trading just wasn’t my forte.\n

voca.title: allergic
voca.means:
[얼^러r쥑]
(!에 대해) 알레르기가 있는
알레르기성의
~을 몹시 실어하는, 알레르기가 생길 정도인
voca.explains:
If you are allergic to something, you become ill or get a rash when you eat it, smell it, or touch it.
If you have an allergic reaction to something, you become ill or get a rash when you eat it, smell it, or touch it.
"And the baseball hats, are they made of wool? I think Buster's allergic to wool. If he's scratching, I don't think he'll be playing his best."

voca.title: allergist
voca.explains: An allergist is a doctor who specializes in treating people with allergies.\n

voca.title: allergy
voca.explains: If you have a particular allergy, you become ill or get a rash when you eat, smell, or touch something that does not normally make people ill.\n

voca.title: alleviate
voca.explains: If you alleviate pain, suffering, or an unpleasant condition, you make it less intense or severe.\n

voca.title: alley
voca.explains: An alley is a narrow passage or street with buildings or walls on both sides.\nWhen I’m channel surfing, I like to watch home shopping channels. One time, I saw a shirt that was right up my alley. I phoned in and ordered one.\n

voca.title: alliance
voca.explains: An alliance is a group of countries or political parties that are formally united and working together because they have similar aims.\nAn alliance is a relationship in which two countries, political parties, or organizations work together for some purpose.\n

voca.title: alligator
voca.explains: An alligator is a large reptile with short legs, a long tail and very powerful jaws.\n

voca.title: allocate
voca.explains:
If one item or share of something is allocated to a particular person or for a particular purpose, it is given to that person or used for that purpose.
The project is being allocated more resources.
They intend to allocate more places to mature students this year.

voca.title: allocation
voca.explains: An allocation is an amount of something, especially money, that is given to a particular person or used for a particular purpose.\nThe allocation of something is the decision that it should be given to a particular person or used for a particular purpose.\n

voca.title: allot
voca.explains: If something is allotted to someone, it is given to them as their share.\n

voca.title: allow
voca.explains:
admit / acknowledge / concede / confess / allow / grant
If someone is allowed to do something, it is all right for them to do it and they will not get into trouble.
If you are allowed something, you are given permission to have it or are given it.
If you allow something to happen, you do not prevent it.
If one thing allows another thing to happen, the first thing creates the opportunity for the second thing to happen.
If you allow a particular length of time or a particular amount of something for a particular purpose, you include it in your planning.
If you allow that something is true, you admit or agree that it is true.
Some people use Allow me to... as a way of introducing something that they want to say or do.
They allow people to watch 3D movies in private at home.

voca.title: allow me
voca.means: 제가 해 드리겠습니다.\n(정중히 도움을 제의할 때 쓰는 표현)
voca.explains: used to offer help politely\n"Allow me to present my knights," said King Arthur.\n

voca.title: allude
voca.explains: If you allude to something, you mention it in an indirect way.\n

voca.title: allude to
voca.explains: to mention somebody/something indirectly or in a few words\n

voca.title: ally
voca.means: [얼^라이]\n~을 동맹시키다, 결연하다, 지지하다, 편들다\n동맹국, 연합국, 협력자
voca.explains:
A country's ally is another country that has an agreement to support it, especially in war.
The Allies were the armed forces that fought against Germany and Japan in the Second World War.
If you describe someone as your ally, you mean that they help and support you, especially when other people are opposing you.
If you ally yourself with someone or something, you give your support to them.
I will have a mighty ally. / The politician tried to make an ally of the people.

voca.title: almighty
voca.explains:
The Almighty is another name for God. You can also refer to Almighty God.
People sometimes say God Almighty or Christ Almighty to express their surprise, anger, or horror. These expressions could cause offence.
Almighty means very serious or great in extent.

voca.title: almond
voca.explains: Almonds are pale oval nuts. They are often used in cooking.\nAn almond or an almond tree, is a tree on which almonds grow.\n

voca.title: almost
voca.explains: almost / nearly / practically\nYou use almost to indicate that something is not completely the case but is nearly the case.\n

voca.title: almost gone
voca.explains: The milk is almost gone. We have to buy some more.\n

voca.title: aloft
voca.explains: Something that is aloft is in the air or off the ground.\n

voca.title: alone
voca.means: [얼로운]\n혼자, 다른 사람 없이, 단독으로, 외로이, 단지 ~뿐\n혼자, 홀로
voca.explains:
alone / lonely / lone
When you are alone, you are not with any other people.
If one person is alone with another person, or if two or more people are alone, they are together, without anyone else present.
If you say that you are alone or feel alone, you mean that nobody who is with you, or nobody at all, cares about you.
If someone is alone in doing something, they are the only person doing it, and so are different from other people.
You say that one person or thing alone does something when you are emphasizing that only one person or thing is involved.
If you say that one person or thing alone is responsible for part of an amount, you are emphasizing the size of that part and the size of the total amount.

voca.title: along
voca.means: [얼렁]\n~을 (죽, 계속) 따라, ~과 나란히, 앞쪽으로, 계속\n앞으로, ~ 와 함께, 진척되어
voca.explains:
If you move or look along something such as a road, you move or look towards one end of it.
If something is situated along a road, river, or corridor, it is situated in it or beside it.
You use along with to mention someone or something else that is also involved in an action or situation.
When someone or something moves along, they keep moving in a particular direction.
If you say that something is going along in a particular way, you mean that it is progressing in that way.
They walked slowly along the road. / Houses had been built along both sides of the river.
We're going for a swim. Why don't you come along?
Along the brilliant crystal walls of the room were four doorways.

voca.title: along the way
voca.explains: Arthur sighed. "The glove was. But the ball came out along the way and dribbled into the outfield. The runner ended up at third base."\nI saw a lot of people during my walk. Along the way, I stopped at the exercise equipment to stretch and catch my breath.\n

voca.title: along with
voca.explains: The elk, reindeer, rhino, and bison moved along with them at a distance.\nJack gripped the sides of his board as he zoomed along with the others.\n

voca.title: alongside
voca.explains:
If one thing is alongside another thing, the first thing is next to the second.
If you work alongside other people, you all work together in the same place.
A police car pulled up alongside us.
Soon the rowboat pulled alongside the ship.

voca.title: aloof
voca.explains: Someone who is aloof is not very friendly and does not like to spend time with other people.\nIf someone stays aloof from something, they do not become involved with it.\n

voca.title: aloud
voca.means: [어롸우d]\n(다른 사람이 들을 수 있게) 소리내어, 큰 소리로
voca.explains:
loud / loudly / aloud
When you say something, read, or laugh aloud, you speak or laugh so that other people can hear you.
If you think aloud, you express your thoughts as they occur to you, rather than thinking first and then speaking.

voca.title: alphabet
voca.explains: An alphabet is a set of letters usually presented in a fixed order which is used for writing the words of a particular language or group of languages.\n

voca.title: alpine
voca.explains: Alpine means existing in or relating to mountains, especially the ones in Switzerland.\nAlpines are small flowering plants that grow high up on mountains and are sometimes grown in gardens. There are many different types of alpines.\n

voca.title: already
voca.explains: already / just / yet\nYou use already to show that a situation exists at this present moment or that it exists at an earlier time than expected. You use already after the verb 'be' or an auxiliary verb, or before a verb if there is no auxiliary. When you want add emphasis, you can put already at the beginning of a sentence.\n

voca.title: also
voca.explains:
also / as well / too
You can use also to give more information about a person or thing, or to add another relevant fact.
You can use also to indicate that something you have just said about one person or thing is true of another person or thing.

voca.title: also-ran
voca.explains: If you describe someone as an also-ran, you mean that they have been or are likely to be unsuccessful in a contest.\nAt the moment, there are several Korean baseball players in MLB. That’s the most ever. The athletes are active in teams across the US. They are not bench warmers. They are not also-rans. They are star players.\n

voca.title: altar
voca.explains: An altar is a holy table in a church or temple.\n

voca.title: alter
voca.explains: If something alters or if you alter it, it changes.\n

voca.title: alteration
voca.explains:
An alteration is a change in or to something.
The house needed extensive alteration when we moved in.
Faulty clothing alteration makes me upset.

voca.title: alternative
voca.means:
[올타r너티v]
대안, 대체, 다른
대체 가능한, 다안이 되는, 대안적인
선택 가능한 것
voca.explains:
option / choice / alternative / possibility
If one thing is an alternative to another, the first can be found, used, or done instead of the second.
An alternative plan or offer is different from the one that you already have, and can be done or used instead.
Alternative is used to describe something that is different from the usual things of its kind, or the usual ways of doing something, in modern Western society. For example, an alternative lifestyle does not follow conventional ways of living and working.
The alternative to submission is death.
For some Asia countries, one alternative is nuclear power

voca.title: alternatively
voca.explains: You use alternatively to introduce a suggestion or to mention something different to what has just been stated.\nAlternatively, an all-inclusive package might be a good idea.\n

voca.title: although
voca.explains:
although / even though / though
You use although to introduce a subordinate clause which contains a statement which contrasts with the statement in the main clause.
You use although to introduce a subordinate clause which contains a statement which makes the main clause of the sentence seem surprising or unexpected.
You use although to introduce a subordinate clause which gives some information that is relevant to the main clause but modifies the strength of that statement.
You use although when admitting a fact about something which you regard as less important than a contrasting fact.
She waved her hand, although whether she was waving to Arthur or making motions to the phone, it was hard to know.

voca.title: altogether
voca.explains:
altogether / all together
You use altogether to emphasize that something has stopped, been done, or finished completely.
You use altogether in front of an adjective or adverb to emphasize a quality that someone or something has.
You use altogether to modify a negative statement and make it less forceful.
You can use altogether to introduce a summary of what you have been saying.
If several amounts add up to a particular amount altogether, that amount is their total.

voca.title: always
voca.means:
[얼웨이s]
항상, 언제나
(기억하기로) 늘, (앞으로) 언제까지나
언제든 ~ 할 수 있다
voca.explains:
If you always do something, you do it whenever a particular situation occurs. If you always did something, you did it whenever a particular situation occurred.
If something is always the case, was always the case, or will always be the case, it is, was, or will be the case all the time, continuously.
If you say that something is always happening, especially something which annoys you, you mean that it happens repeatedly.
You use always in expressions such as can always or could always when you are making suggestions or suggesting an alternative approach or method.
You can say that someone always was, for example, awkward or lucky to indicate that you are not surprised about what they are doing or have just done.

voca.title: always come first
voca.explains: My family always come first.\nStudying English should always come first.

voca.title: amass
voca.explains: collect / gather / accumulate / run sth up / amass\nIf you amass something such as money or information, you gradually get a lot of it.\n

voca.title: amateur
voca.explains:
An amateur is someone who does something as a hobby and not as a job.
Amateur sports or activities are done by people as a hobby and not as a job.
In one program, amateur singers impersonate famous musicians. Some are so good that even experts are fooled.

voca.title: amaze
voca.explains: surprise / startle / amaze / stun / astonish / take sb aback / astound\nIf something amazes you, it surprises you very much.\n

voca.title: amazement
voca.explains: Amazement is the feeling you have when something surprises you very much.\n

voca.title: amazing
voca.explains: You say that something is amazing when it is very surprising and makes you feel pleasure, approval, or wonder.\nJake zoomed toward the shore with amazing speed.\n

voca.title: ambassador
voca.explains: An ambassador is an important official who lives in a foreign country and represents his or her own country's interests there.\n

voca.title: amber
voca.explains:
Amber is a hard yellowish-brown substance used for making jewellery.
Amber is used to describe things that are yellowish-brown in colour.
An amber traffic light is orange.
The deer was staring up at them with amber eyes.

voca.title: ambiguity
voca.explains: If you say that there is ambiguity in something, you mean that it is unclear or confusing, or it can be understood in more than one way.\nPython uses a few names as special built - in words that it  reserves  for special use to prevent ambiguity\n

voca.title: ambition
voca.explains: If you have an ambition to do or achieve something, you want very much to do it or achieve it.\nAmbition is the desire to be successful, rich, or powerful.\n

voca.title: ambitious
voca.explains:
Someone who is ambitious has a strong desire to be successful, rich, or powerful.
An ambitious idea or plan is on a large scale and needs a lot of work to be carried out successfully.
For example, people with type O blood are thought to be ambitious, outgoing and confident.

voca.title: ambulance
voca.explains: An ambulance is a vehicle for taking people to and from hospital.\n

voca.title: ambush
voca.explains:
If a group of people ambush their enemies, they attack them after hiding and waiting for them.
An ambush is an attack on someone by people who have been hiding and waiting for them.
If someone is lying in ambush, they are hiding and waiting for someone, usually to attack them.

voca.title: amend
voca.explains: If you amend something that has been written such as a law, or something that is said, you change it in order to improve it or make it more accurate.\nIf you make amends when you have harmed someone, you show that you are sorry by doing something to please them.\n

voca.title: amendment
voca.means: [어멘d먼t]\n(법 등의) 개정, 수정\n미국 헌법 수정 조항
voca.explains: An amendment is a section that is added to a law or rule in order to change it.\nAn amendment is a change that is made to a piece of writing.\n

voca.title: amends
voca.explains: recompense or compensation given or gained for some injury, insult, etc\n

voca.title: amenities
voca.explains: I discovered my favorite hotel by chance. It’s not a ritzy or high-end place. Other hotels are more luxurious. But my favorite place strikes the perfect balance between price, service and amenities.\nSoon, our guests showed up. They didn’t come empty-handed. They came bearing gifts. People brought amenities like toilet paper, soap and detergent. They brought food like cake and fruit. The party was Bring Your Own Bottle(BYOB).\n

voca.title: amenity
voca.means:
[어^메니티-]

Amusement is the pleasure that you get from being entertained or from doing something interesting.
Amusements are ways of passing the time pleasantly.
Amusements are games, rides, and other things that you can enjoy, for example at a fairground or at the seaside.

voca.title: amusement park
voca.explains: An amusement park is the same as a funfair.\nB : I think that I would like to go to the amusement park.\n

voca.title: anatomy
voca.explains:
Anatomy is the study of the structure of the bodies of people or animals.
You can refer to your body as your anatomy.
An animal's anatomy is the structure of its body.

voca.title: ancestor
voca.explains:
Your ancestors are the people from whom you are descended.
An ancestor of something modern is an earlier thing from which it developed.
Their caves were filled with the bones of their ancestors.

voca.title: anchor

voca.explains:
An anchor is a heavy hooked object that is dropped from a boat into the water at the end of a chain in order to make the boat stay in one place.
The anchor on a television or radio programme, especially a news programme, is the person who presents it.
When a boat anchors or when you anchor it, its anchor is dropped into the water in order to make it stay in one place.
If you anchor an object somewhere, you fix it to something to prevent it moving from that place.
The person who anchors a television or radio programme, especially a news programme, is the person who presents it and acts as a link between interviews and reports which come from other places or studios.

voca.title: ancient

voca.explains:
Ancient means belonging to the distant past, especially to the period in history before the end of the Roman Empire.
Ancient means very old, or having existed for a long time.
"It is an ancient, enchanted land beyond the edge of the Earth," said Morgan.

voca.title: and everything

voca.title: angel

If you describe someone as an angel, you mean that they seem to be very kind and good.

voca.title: angelic
voca.explains: You can describe someone as angelic if they are, or seem to be, very good, kind, and gentle.\nAngelic means like angels or relating to angels.\n

voca.title: anger
voca.explains: Anger is the strong emotion that you feel when you think that someone has behaved in an unfair, cruel, or unacceptable way.\nIf something angers you, it makes you feel angry.\n

An angle is the difference in direction between two lines or surfaces. Angles are measured in degrees.
An angle is the shape that is created where two lines or surfaces join together.
An angle is the direction from which you look at something.
You can refer to a way of presenting something or thinking about it as a particular angle.
If someone is angling for something, they are trying to get it without asking for it directly.
I love my car, so I baby it a lot. However, one time I grazed the bumper while I was parking. I had nobody to blame. I had simply misjudged the angle.

voca.title: angle for something
voca.explains: to try to obtain something without asking for it directly\n

voca.title: angry

voca.title: animal
voca.explains:
An animal is a living creature such as a dog, lion, or rabbit, rather than a bird, fish, insect, or human being.
Any living creature other than a human being can be referred to as an animal.
Any living creature, including a human being, can be referred to as an animal.
Animal products come from animals rather than from plants.

voca.title: animate
voca.means: [에너메잇t]\n~에 생명을 주다, 생기를 주다\n살아있는, 생명이 있는

voca.title: ankle

voca.title: anklet

voca.title: anniversary
voca.explains: An anniversary is a date which is remembered or celebrated because a special event happened on that date in a previous year.\nMy wife and I will celebrate our twentieth wedding anniversary next week.\n

voca.title: annotate
voca.explains: If you annotate written work or a diagram, you add notes to it, especially in order to explain it.\n

voca.title: annotation
voca.explains: Annotation is the activity of annotating something.\nAn annotation is a note that is added to a text or diagram, often in order to explain it.\n

voca.title: announce
voca.explains:
declare | state | indicate | announce
If you announce something, you tell people about it publicly or officially.
If you announce a piece of news or an intention, especially something that people may not like, you say it loudly and clearly, so that everyone you are with can hear it.
If an airport or railway employee announces something, they tell the public about it by means of a loudspeaker system.
Muffy was wearing a big smile. "Great news, everyone!" she announced. "My parents are having a big party tomorrow at WonderWorld." She paused. "And I can invite anyone I want."

voca.title: announcement
voca.explains:

The announcement of something that has happened is the act of telling people about it.
An announcement in a public place, such as a newspaper or the window of a shop, is a short piece of writing telling people about something or asking for something.

voca.title: annoy
voca.explains: If someone or something annoys you, it makes you fairly angry and impatient.\n

voca.title: annoying
voca.explains: Someone or something that is annoying makes you feel fairly angry and impatient.\nA : You are right. The rent is affordable but my neighbors are just annoying. They party all the time!\n

voca.title: annual
voca.explains:
Annual events happen once every year.
Annual quantities or rates relate to a period of one year.
An annual is a book or magazine that is published once a year.
An annual is a plant that grows and dies within one year.

voca.title: anonymous
voca.explains:
If you remain anonymous when you do something, you do not let people know that you were the person who did it.
Something that is anonymous does not reveal who you are.
If you describe a place as anonymous, you dislike it because it has no unusual or interesting features and seems unwelcoming.

You use another before a word referring to a distance, length of time, or other amount, to indicate an additional amount.
You use one another to indicate that each member of a group does something to or for the other members.

voca.title: another time

All political claims to the mainland are suspended under the Antarctic Treaty of 1959\n

voca.explains:

voca.title: anything
voca.explains:

If two people are apart, they are no longer living together or spending time together, either permanently or just for a short time.

voca.title: apologetic
voca.explains: If you are apologetic, you show or say that you are sorry for causing trouble for someone, for hurting them, or for disappointing them.\n

voca.title: apologize

You can say 'I apologize' as a formal way of saying sorry.\nHowever, it wasn’t green tea, but coffee. I made a complaint at the counter. The barista was courteous and helpful. He apologized for the inconvenience, and gave me a new drink, free of charge.\n

voca.title: apologize for
voca.explains: However, it wasn’t green tea, but coffee. I made a complaint at the counter. The barista was courteous and helpful. He apologized for the inconvenience, and gave me a new drink, free of charge.\n

voca.title: apology
voca.explains:
An apology is something that you say or write in order to tell someone that you are sorry that you have hurt them or caused trouble for them.
If you offer or make your apologies, you apologize.
She acepted my apology.
She was so angry that she didn't accept his apology.
Do you think he will accept my apology?

voca.title: apostrophe
voca.explains: An apostrophe is the mark ' when it is written to indicate that one or more letters have been left out of a word, as in 'isn't' and 'we'll'. It is also added to nouns to form possessives, as in 'Mike's car'.\n

voca.title: apparent
voca.explains:
clear / obvious / apparent / evident / plain / crystal clear
An apparent situation, quality, or feeling seems to exist, although you cannot be certain that it does exist.
If something is apparent to you, it is clear and obvious to you.

voca.title: apparently
voca.means:
[어^페어럿리]
보기에는, 와관상, 분명히, 듣자하니

분명히, 명백히

You use apparently to refer to something that seems to be true, although you are not sure whether it is or not.
