voca.title: appeal
voca.means:
[어^피-일]
간청하다, 호소하다, 상소하다
관심/흥미를 끌다, 매력적이다
호소, 간청, 재심청구, 항소
voca.explains:
If you appeal to someone to do something, you make a serious and urgent request to them.
If you appeal to someone in authority against a decision, you formally ask them to change it. In British English, you appeal against something. In American English, you appeal something.
If something appeals to you, you find it attractive or interesting.
An appeal is a serious and urgent request.
An appeal is an attempt to raise money for a charity or for a good cause.
An appeal is a formal request for a decision to be changed.
The appeal of something is a quality that it has which people find attractive or interesting.
His father shook his head. "I don't understand the appeal of that sugar-coated cardboard. Believe me, all you’ll get from that stuff is a mouthful of cavities."
Whenever I mentioned that I wanted to picked up a new hobby, many people recommended hiking. At first, I didn’t get it. I couldn’t understand the appeal.

voca.title: appear
voca.explains:
If you say that something appears to be the way you describe it, you are reporting what you believe or what you have been told, though you cannot be sure it is true.
If someone or something appears to have a particular quality or characteristic, they give the impression of having that quality or characteristic.
When someone or something appears, they move into a position where you can see them.
When something new appears, it begins to exist or reaches a stage of development where its existence can be noticed.
When something such as a book appears, it is published or becomes available for people to buy.
When someone appears in something such as a play, a show, or a television programme, they take part in it.
When someone appears before a court of law or before an official committee, they go there in order to answer charges or to give information as a witness.

voca.title: appearance
voca.explains:
When someone makes an appearance at a public event or in a broadcast, they take part in it.
Someone's or something's appearance is the way that they look.
The appearance of someone or something in a place is their arrival there, especially when it is unexpected.
The appearance of something new is its coming into existence or use.
If something has the appearance of a quality, it seems to have that quality.
If something is true to all appearances, from all appearances, or by all appearances, it seems from what you observe or know about it that it is true.

voca.title: append
voca.explains: When you append something to something else, especially a piece of writing, you attach it or add it to the end of it.\n

voca.title: appetite
voca.explains:
Your appetite is your desire to eat.
Someone's appetite for something is their strong desire for it.
I just lost my appetite.
How can I regain my appetite? I'm losing my weight continuously.
I don't have much of an appetite.
My appetite improved and I couldn’t stop eating. My wife’s cooking skill was a mixed blessing. Soon, I was packing on the pounds.

voca.title: applaud
voca.explains:
When a group of people applaud, they clap their hands in order to show approval, for example when they have enjoyed a play or concert.
When an attitude or action is applauded, people praise it.
Your appetite is your desire to eat. / Someone's appetite for something is their strong desire for it.

voca.title: applause
voca.explains: Applause is the noise made by a group of people clapping their hands to show approval.\nHis words were met by cheers and polite applause.\n

voca.title: apple
voca.explains: An apple is a round fruit with smooth green, yellow, or red skin and firm white flesh.\nIf you say that someone is the apple of your eye, you mean that they are very important to you and you are extremely fond of them.\n

voca.title: appliance
voca.explains:
An appliance is a device or machine in your home that you use to do a job such as cleaning or cooking. Appliances are often electrical.
The appliance of a skill or of knowledge is its use for a particular purpose.
There are many home appliances I use at home. First of all, probably the most important appliance is the fridge.
We often take our home appliances for granted. But when they break down, we realize how much we depend on them.

voca.title: application
voca.means:
[^에플뤼케이션]
지원/신청(서)
적용, 응용
(페인트, 크림 등을) 바르기, 도포
(법의) 적용
응용 프로그램
voca.explains:
An application for something such as a job or membership of an organization is a formal written request for it.
The application of a rule or piece of knowledge is the use of it in a particular situation.
In computing, an application is a piece of software designed to carry out a particular task.
Application is hard work and concentration on what you are doing over a period of time.
The application of something to a surface is the act or process of putting it on or rubbing it into the surface.
Bluetooth is very widespread now. It’s used for many applications. I use it most often for audio devices.

voca.title: apply
voca.explains:
If you apply for something such as a job or membership of an organization, you write a letter or fill in a form in order to ask formally for it.
If you apply yourself to something or apply your mind to something, you concentrate hard on doing it or on thinking about it.
If something such as a rule or a remark applies to a person or in a situation, it is relevant to the person or the situation.
If you apply something such as a rule, system, or skill, you use it in a situation or activity.
A name that is applied to someone or something is used to refer to them.
If you apply something to a surface, you put it on or rub it into the surface.

voca.title: apply to
voca.explains:
to concern or relate to somebody/something
The main purpose of the law is to ban bribery. It applies to people in various jobs. Public servants, school teachers and journalists cannot receive gifts or receive special requests. Plus, there is a price cap on buying food for others.
Last year, I applied to various companies for work. Finding employment is a tall order these days.

voca.title: appoint
voca.explains: If you appoint someone to a job or official position, you formally choose them for it.\n

voca.title: appointment
voca.means: [어^포인먼t]\n(특히 업무 관련) 약속, 예약, \n임명, 선임, (책임 있는) 직위, 직책
voca.explains:
job / post / position / vacancy / placement / appointment / opening
The appointment of a person to a particular job is the choice of that person to do it.
An appointment is a job or position of responsibility.
If you have an appointment with someone, you have arranged to see them at a particular time, usually in connection with their work or for a serious purpose.
If something can be done by appointment, people can arrange in advance to do it at a particular time.

voca.title: appraisal
voca.means: [어p뤠이졀]\n(가치, 업적, 본질에 대한) 평가, 견적, 감정
voca.explains: If you make an appraisal of something, you consider it carefully and form an opinion about it.\n

voca.title: appraise
voca.explains: If you appraise something or someone, you consider them carefully and form an opinion about them.\nAppraisal is the official or formal assessment of the strengths and weaknesses of someone or something. Appraisal often involves observation or some kind of testing.\n

voca.title: appreciate
voca.explains:
If you appreciate something, for example a piece of music or good food, you like it because you recognize its good qualities.
If you appreciate a situation or problem, you understand it and know what it involves.
If you appreciate something that someone has done for you or is going to do for you, you are grateful for it.
If something that you own appreciates over a period of time, its value increases.
Can you appreciate how hard a writer works to create stories kids will like to read?

voca.title: apprehension
voca.explains:
fear / alarm / apprehension / fright / foreboding
Apprehension is a feeling of fear that something bad may happen.
The apprehension of someone who is thought to be a criminal is their capture or arrest by the police.

voca.title: apprentice
voca.explains:
An apprentice is a young person who works for someone in order to learn their skill.
If a young person is apprenticed to someone, they go to work for them in order to learn their skill.
Their helper was the young sorcerer who was training as Morgan's apprentice!

voca.title: approach
voca.means:
[어p로우취]
접근하다, 다가오다, 접촉하다, 
육박하다, 근접하다, 
접근법, 처리 방법, 다가옴, 접근, 진입, 진입로
voca.explains:
When you approach something, you get closer to it.
If you approach someone about something, you speak to them about it for the first time, often making an offer or request.
When you approach a task, problem, or situation in a particular way, you deal with it or think about it in that way.
As a future time or event approaches, it gradually gets nearer as time passes.
As you approach a future time or event, time passes so that you get gradually nearer to it.
If something approaches a particular level or state, it almost reaches that level or state.

voca.title: appropriate
voca.means:
[어p^러p뤼에잇t]
적절한, 적합한, 어울리는, 타당한
충당하다, 돌려쓰다, 사용하다
(불법적으로나 무단으로) 도용/전용하다
voca.explains:
Something that is appropriate is suitable or acceptable for a particular situation.
If someone appropriates something which does not belong to them, they take it, usually without the right to do so.
Alan: Somebody should. That kind of dress is not appropriate for the workplace.

voca.title: approve
voca.explains:
agree / approve / consent / acquiesce
If you approve of an action, event, or suggestion, you like it or are pleased about it.
If you approve of someone or something, you like and admire them.
If someone in a position of authority approves a plan or idea, they formally agree to it and say that it can happen.

voca.title: approximate
voca.means:
[어p롹시메잇t]
거의 정확한, 근사치인, 
(성격, 양, 자질 등이) 비슷하다, 가깝다
근사치를 내다/계산하다
voca.explains:
An approximate number, time, or position is close to the correct number, time, or position, but is not exact.
An idea or description that is approximate is not intended to be precise or accurate, but to give some indication of what something is like.
If something approximates to something else, it is similar to it but is not exactly the same.

voca.title: apricot
voca.explains: An apricot is a small, soft, round fruit with yellowish-orange flesh and a stone inside.\nApricot is used to describe things that are yellowish-orange in colour.\n

voca.title: April
voca.explains: April is the fourth month of the year in the Western calendar.\n

voca.title: apron
voca.explains: An apron is a piece of clothing that you put on over the front of your normal clothes and tie round your waist, especially when you are cooking, in order to prevent your clothes from getting dirty.\n

voca.title: aptitude
voca.explains: Someone's aptitude for a particular kind of work or activity is their ability to learn it quickly and to do it well.\n

voca.title: aquarius
voca.explains: Aquarius is one of the twelve signs of the zodiac. Its symbol is a person pouring water. People who are born approximately between 20th January and 18th February come under this sign.\nAn Aquarius is a person whose sign of the zodiac is Aquarius.\n

voca.title: arbitrary
voca.explains: If you describe an action, rule, or decision as arbitrary, you think that it is not based on any principle, plan, or system. It often seems unfair because of this.\n

voca.title: arcade
voca.means:
[아r^케이d]
(아치가 이어진) 회랑
아케이드(양쪽에 상점들이 늘어서 있는 아치로 둘러싸인 통로) 
게임 센터
voca.explains: An arcade is a covered passage where there are shops or market stalls.\n"Oh. Well, I was half right. It’s still information. Anyway, I’m not giving up. I’ll find a crime. Maybe I’ll find one at the arcade. My mom’s taking me there this afternoon. Want to come?"\n

voca.title: arch
voca.means:
[아r-취]
아치형 구조물, 아치형 장식(이 붙은 입구, 탑 등)
발바닥의 오목한 부분, 장심
아치형(의 것)
(몸을) 동그랗게 구부리다, 구부러지다, 
아치 모양을 그리다
voca.explains:
An arch is a structure that is curved at the top and is supported on either side by a pillar, post, or wall.
An arch is a curved line or movement.
The arch of your foot is the curved section at the bottom in the middle.
If you arch a part of your body such as your back or if it arches, you bend it so that it forms a curve.
If you arch your eyebrows or if they arch, you move them upwards as a way of showing surprise or disapproval.

voca.title: archer
voca.explains: An archer is someone who shoots arrows using a bow.\nNo archers patrolled the tops of its walls.\n

voca.title: archery
voca.explains: Archery is a sport in which people shoot arrows at a target using a bow.\n

voca.title: architect
voca.explains:
An architect is a person who designs buildings.
You can use architect to refer to a person who plans large projects such as landscaping or railways.
The architect of an idea, event, or institution is the person who invented it or made it happen.

voca.title: architecture
voca.explains:
Architecture is the art of planning, designing, and constructing buildings.
The architecture of a building is the style in which it is designed and constructed.
The architecture of something is its structure.

voca.title: archive
voca.means:
[^아-가이v]
기록 보관소
기록/공문서 보관소, 문서국
기록 보관소에 보관하다
(컴퓨터) 파일을 보관하다
(컴퓨터) 아카이브 (다수의 파일을 압축하여 하나로 모은 것)
voca.explains:
The archive or archives are a collection of documents and records that contain historical information. You can also use archives to refer to the place where archives are stored.
Archive material is information that comes from archives.
You download an application on your phone, pay a small fee, and you can get access to a huge music archive at your fingertips.

voca.title: archway
voca.explains: An archway is a passage or entrance that has a curved roof.\nMorgan led them to a huge archway with two wooden doors.\n

voca.title: arctic
voca.means: [아r틱]\n북극의, 북극(권)의, 북극에서 오는, 북극성 기후의\n북극 지방
voca.explains: The Arctic is the area of the world around the North Pole. It is extremely cold and there is very little light in winter and very little darkness in summer.\nIf you describe a place or the weather as arctic, you are emphasizing that it is extremely cold.\n

voca.title: area
voca.explains:
An area is a particular part of a town, a country, a region, or the world.
Your area is the part of a town, country, or region where you live. An organization's area is the part of a town, country, or region that it is responsible for.
A particular area is a piece of land or part of a building that is used for a particular activity.
An area is a particular place on a surface or object, for example on your body.
The area of a surface such as a piece of land is the amount of flat space or ground that it covers, measured in square units.
You can use area to refer to a particular subject or topic, or to a particular part of a larger, more general situation or activity.

voca.title: arena
voca.explains: An arena is a place where sports, entertainments, and other public events take place. It has seats around it where people sit and watch.\nYou can refer to a field of activity, especially one where there is a lot of conflict or action, as an arena of a particular kind.\n

voca.title: arguably
voca.explains: You can use arguably when you are stating your opinion or belief, as a way of giving more authority to it.\n

voca.title: argue
voca.means:
[^아r-규-]
(논거를 들어) 주장/논쟁하다, 말다툼하다
언쟁하다, 다투다
분명히 보여주다, 입증하다
voca.explains:
If one person argues with another, they speak angrily to each other about something that they disagree about.
If you tell someone not to argue with you, you want them to do or believe what you say without protest or disagreement.
If you argue with someone about something, you discuss it with them, with each of you giving your different opinions.
If you argue that something is true, you state it and give the reasons why you think it is true.
If you argue for something, you say why you agree with it, in order to persuade people that it is right. If you argue against something, you say why you disagree with it, in order to persuade people that it is wrong.
If you argue, you support your opinions with evidence in an ordered or logical way.
If you say that no-one can argue with a particular fact or opinion, you are emphasizing that it is obviously true and so everyone must accept it.
Paul: What did you argue about?
She completely overreacted. She accused me of being a gossip. I should have let it slide. Instead, I took the bait. We argued bitterly. We traded insults on the phone.

voca.title: argue bitterly
voca.explains: She completely overreacted. She accused me of being a gossip. I should have let it slide. Instead, I took the bait. We argued bitterly. We traded insults on the phone.\n

voca.title: argue out
voca.explains: to discuss all the details of an idea, a plan, etc., often in an excited or angry way, until you reach a decision\n

voca.title: argue with something
voca.explains: to disagree with what somebody says; to say or show that something is not right\n

voca.title: argument
voca.explains:
An argument is a statement or set of statements that you use in order to try to convince people that your opinion about something is correct.
An argument is a discussion or debate in which a number of people put forward different or opposing opinions
An argument is a conversation in which people disagree with each other angrily or noisily.
If you accept something without argument, you do not question it or disagree with it.
Your argument is confusing.

voca.title: aries
voca.explains: Aries is one of the twelve signs of the zodiac. Its symbol is a ram. People who are born approximately between 21st March and 19th April come under this sign.\nAn Aries is a person whose sign of the zodiac is Aries.\n

voca.title: aristocracy
voca.explains: The aristocracy is a class of people in some countries who have a high social rank and special titles.\n

voca.title: arithmetic
voca.explains: Arithmetic is the part of mathematics that is concerned with the addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division of numbers.\nYou can use arithmetic to refer to the process of doing a particular sum or calculation.\n

voca.title: arm
voca.explains:
Your arms are the two long parts of your body that are attached to your shoulders and that have your hands at the end.
The arm of a piece of clothing is the part of it that covers your arm.
The arm of a chair is the part on which you rest your arm when you are sitting down.
An arm of an object is a long thin part of it that sticks out from the main part.
An arm of land or water is a long thin area of it that is joined to a broader area.
Arms are weapons, especially bombs and guns.
The arms of a city or of a noble family are its coat of arms. Arms is often used in the names of British pubs.
If you arm someone with a weapon, you provide them with a weapon.

voca.title: armed
voca.explains: Someone who is armed is carrying a weapon, usually a gun.\nAn armed attack or conflict involves people fighting with guns or carrying weapons.\n

voca.title: armistice
voca.explains: An armistice is an agreement between countries who are at war with one another to stop fighting and to discuss ways of making peace.\nIn the United States, Veterans Day is a national holiday held on November 11. On that day in 1918, all sides in World War I stopped fighting. Americans originally called this holiday Armistice Day.\n

voca.title: armload
voca.explains: An armload of something is the same as an armful of something.\n

voca.title: armor
voca.explains:
(armour)
In former times, armour was special metal clothing that soldiers wore for protection in battle.
Armour consists of tanks and other military vehicles used in battle.
Armour is a hard, usually metal, covering that protects a vehicle against attack.
HIs horse was dressed all in green-from the armor that covered his head to the cloth that hung from his saddle.
He caught sight of armor glinting in the sunlight.

voca.title: armpit
voca.explains: Your armpits are the areas of your body under your arms where your arms join your shoulders.\n

voca.title: army
voca.explains: An army is a large organized group of people who are armed and trained to fight on land in a war. Most armies are organized and controlled by governments.\nAn army of people, animals, or things is a large number of them, especially when they are regarded as a force of some kind.\n

voca.title: aromatherapy
voca.means: [아^로-마테롸삐]\n방향 요법, 아로마세라피\n향기를 사용하여 사람의 기분이나 행위를 바꾸는 치료법.
voca.explains: Aromatherapy is a type of treatment which involves massaging the body with special fragrant oils.\n

voca.title: around
voca.means:
[어롸운d]
약, ~ 쯤,
사방에서, 빙 둘러, 
굴러서, 둘레(수치가) ~인,
이리저리, 여기저기, 하릴없이
주변에 있는, 마련할 수 있는,
둘레에, 주위에, 둥굴게, 빙 돌아
voca.explains:
around / round / about
To be positioned around a place or object means to surround it or be on all sides of it. To move around a place means to go along its edge, back to your starting point.
If you move around a corner or obstacle, you move to the other side of it. If you look around a corner or obstacle, you look to see what is on the other side.
If you move around a place, you travel through it, going to most of its parts. If you look around a place, you look at every part of it.
If someone moves around a place, they move through various parts of that place without having any particular destination.
You use around to say that something happens in different parts of a place or area.
The people around you are the people who you come into contact with, especially your friends and relatives, and the people you work with.
If something such as a film, a discussion, or a plan is based around something, that thing is its main theme.
When you are giving measurements, you can use around to talk about the distance along the edge of something round.
If you turn around, you turn so that you are facing in the opposite direction.
If you go around to someone's house, you visit them.
You use around in expressions such as sit around and hang around when you are saying that someone is spending time in a place and not doing anything very important.
If you move things around, you move them so that they are in different places.
You use around in expressions such as this time around or to come around when you are describing something that has happened before or things that happen regularly.
The villagers gathered around.

voca.title: around and around
voca.explains: They just kept going around and around in their joyous circle.\n

voca.title: around the clock
voca.explains:
for twenty-four hours without stopping
Some places deliver around the clock.
Our store is open around the clock.
He stayed next to her bed around the clock.
Luckily, high-quality EBS programs are on-air around the clock. There are programs on offer for every skill level.
Convenience stores are open around the clock.
She was rady to work aroud the clock.

voca.title: around the corner
voca.means: 모퉁이를 돌아\n아주 가까운, \n목전에 있는, 코앞에 와 있는
voca.explains:
It helps to remember that autumn is just around the corner.
The store you mentioned is just around the corner.
Exam season is just around the corner.

voca.title: arrange
voca.explains:
If you arrange an event or meeting, you make plans for it to happen.
If you arrange with someone to do something, you make plans with them to do it.
If you arrange something for someone, you make it possible for them to have it or to do it.
If you arrange things somewhere, you place them in a particular position, usually in order to make them look attractive or tidy.
If a piece of music is arranged by someone, it is changed or adapted so that it is suitable for particular instruments or voices, or for a particular performance.
She carefully arranged the folds around them.

voca.title: array
voca.explains: An array of different things or people is a large number or wide range of them.\nAn array of objects is a collection of them that is displayed or arranged in a particular way.\n

voca.title: arrest
voca.means:
[어뤠st]
체포하다, 구속하다, 검거하다
(무엇의 진행을) 막다, 저지하다
체포, 검거, 억제, 정지
voca.explains:
If the police arrest you, they take charge of you and take you to a police station, because they believe you may have committed a crime.
If something or someone arrests a process, they stop it continuing.
If something interesting or surprising arrests your attention, you suddenly notice it and then continue to look at it or consider it carefully.

voca.title: get concerned about
voca.explains: When Ana skipped her classes, I got really concerned about her.\n

voca.title: arrive
voca.means: [어^롸이v]\n(특히 여정 끝에) 도착하다, 도달하다, 배달되다\n도래하다, 찾아오다
voca.explains:
When a person or vehicle arrives at a place, they come to it at the end of a journey.
When you arrive at a place, you come to it for the first time in order to stay, live, or work there.
When something such as letter or meal arrives, it is brought or delivered to you.
When something such as a new product or invention arrives, it becomes available.
When a particular moment or event arrives, it happens, especially after you have been waiting for it or expecting it.
When you arrive at something such as a decision, you decide something after thinking about it or discussing it.

voca.title: arrive at something
voca.explains: to agree on something or to find something after discussing and thinking about it\n

voca.title: arrive at the conclusion that
voca.explains: All the houses that I liked were out of my league. I put in the footwork, visiting various candidates. I arrived at the conclusion that I needed a bank loan.\n

voca.title: arrive on time
voca.explains:
In the middle of the flight, we experienced turbulence. The plane shook a lot, and I tensed up. The captain turned on the seatbelt sign. Soon, everything was back to normal. We arrived in Thailand on time.
If we leave now, we can arrive on time.
I arrived on time, but she was late.

voca.title: arrogant
voca.explains: Someone who is arrogant behaves in a proud, unpleasant way towards other people because they believe that they are more important than others.\n

voca.title: arrow
voca.explains: An arrow is a long thin weapon which is sharp and pointed at one end and which often has feathers at the other end. An arrow is shot from a bow.\nAn arrow is a written or printed sign that consists of a straight line with another line bent at a sharp angle at one end. This is a printed arrow: . The arrow points in a particular direction to indicate where something is.\n

voca.title: arson
voca.explains: Arson is the crime of deliberately setting fire to a building or vehicle.\n

voca.title: art
voca.explains:
Art consists of paintings, sculpture, and other pictures or objects which are created for people to look at and admire or think deeply about.
Art is the activity or educational subject that consists of creating paintings, sculptures, and other pictures or objects for people to look at and admire or think deeply about.
The arts are activities such as music, painting, literature, cinema, and dance, which people can take part in for enjoyment, or to create works which express serious meanings or ideas of beauty.
At a university or college, arts are subjects such as history, literature, or languages in contrast to scientific subjects.
If you describe an activity as an art, you mean that it requires skill and that people learn to do it by instinct or experience, rather than by learning facts or rules.

voca.title: artery
voca.explains: Arteries are the tubes in your body that carry blood from your heart to the rest of your body. Compare vein.\nYou can refer to an important main route within a complex road, railway, or river system as an artery.\n

voca.title: arthritis
voca.explains: Arthritis is a medical condition in which the joints in someone's body are swollen and painful.\n

voca.title: arthropod
voca.explains: any invertebrate of the phylum Arthropoda, having jointed limbs, a segmented body, and an exoskeleton made of chitin. The group includes the crustaceans, insects, arachnids, and centipedes\n

voca.title: article
voca.means:
[아-뤼끌]
(신물, 잡지의) 글, 기사, 
(합의서, 계약서의) 조항,

기사, 조항, 관사
voca.explains:
An article is a piece of writing that is published in a newspaper or magazine.
You can refer to objects as articles of some kind.
An article of a formal agreement or document is a section of it which deals with a particular point.
Someone who is in articles is being trained as a lawyer or accountant by a firm with whom they have a written agreement.
In grammar, an article is a kind of determiner. In English, 'a' and 'an' are called the indefinite article, and 'the' is called the definite article.
If you describe something as the genuine article, you are emphasizing that it is genuine, and often that it is very good.

voca.title: artifact
voca.means: [아릐풱t]\n(천연물과 대비하여) 인공물, 공예품, 유물\n인공 유물, 만들어낸 것

voca.title: artificial
voca.explains:
artificial / synthetic / false / man-made / fake / imitation
Artificial objects, materials, or processes do not occur naturally and are created by human beings, for example using science or technology.
An artificial state or situation exists only because someone has created it, and therefore often seems unnatural or unnecessary.
If you describe someone or their behaviour as artificial, you disapprove of them because they pretend to have attitudes and feelings which they do not really have.

voca.title: artificial seasoning
voca.explains: In the past, restaurants did everything they could to make the food taste good. They used a lot of sugar and artificial seasoning.\n

voca.title: as
voca.means:
[^에s]
~ 처럼, 같이
(가격, 기능 등이) ~ 로서
~만큼 ~ 한
~하는 것과 같이, ~ 듯이
~하는 동안에
~대로
voca.explains:
If something happens as something else happens, it happens at the same time.
You use as to say how something happens or is done, or to indicate that something happens or is done in the same way as something else.
You use as to introduce short clauses which comment on the truth of what you are saying.
You can use as to mean 'because' when you are explaining the reason for something.
You use the structure as...as when you are comparing things.
You use as...as to emphasize amounts of something.
You say as it were in order to make what you are saying sound less definite.
You use expressions such as as it is, as it turns out, and as things stand when you are making a contrast between a possible situation and what actually happened or is the case.
You use as when you are indicating what someone or something is or is thought to be, or what function they have.
If you do something as a child or as a teenager, for example, you do it when you are a child or a teenager.
You use as in expressions like as a result and as a consequence to indicate how two situations or events are related to each other.
You use as for and as to at the beginning of a sentence in order to introduce a slightly different subject that is still connected to the previous one.
You use as to to indicate what something refers to.
If you say that something will happen as of, or in British English as from, a particular date or time, you mean that it will happen from that time on.

voca.title: as a matter of course
voca.explains: A while ago, I was swamped with work. To make matters worse, I had to go to several staff dinners. As a matter of course, we went to a noraebang after some drinking. While singing, I gave my all.\n

voca.title: as a result
voca.explains: On most days, I check the weather forecast on my phone. However, one time the forecast betrayed me. It said that there would be no rain. As a result, I didn't have an umbrella on me.\nInternet security is a hot topic. Everybody and their dog are online these days. As a result, Internet users are juicy targets for hackers.\n

voca.title: as a reward
voca.explains: However, the bear kept at it. As a reward, it was turned into a beautiful woman.\n

voca.title: as a rule
voca.explains: usually\nAs a rule, pharmacists in Korea are well-versed at their jobs. If you tell them your symptoms, they can offer a recommendation.\n

voca.title: as a whole
voca.explains: considered as one general group\nThe biggest change was that we expanded the living room out to the balcony. This made the house feel more spacious as a whole.\n

voca.title: as always
voca.explains: as usually happens or is expected\n

voca.title: as before
voca.explains: Just as before, the dancers didn't seem to notice.\n

voca.title: as blind as a bat

When the lights went out. She was as blind as a bat.
He can't be a pilot because he is as blind as a bat.

voca.title: as clean as a whistle

voca.title: as good as
voca.explains: so close to something happening that you consider that it has happened\n

voca.explains:
I swapped in new batteries and it was as good as new.
After you clean it, it will be as good as new.
It was almost as good as new.

voca.title: as if
voca.explains:
His arms felt as if they were being pulled out of their sockets.
It had wings that looked as if they'd been spun from a thousand spiderwebs.
Muffy was warming up with some painful screeches on her violin. They sounded as if she had accidentally stepped on a cat’s tail.

voca.title: as it is
voca.explains:

The painting looks good as it is.
If you leave it as it is, it may go bad.

voca.title: as it stands
voca.explains: As it stands, it’s all too easy to pick the wrong cycle. In the worst-case scenario, this can ruin your clothes. Believe me, it has happened before.\n

voca.title: as long as

voca.explains:

As long as the family kept the diamond safe, they would have good fortune.
Lisa: Sure, as long as it's not a long distance call!
It is used to give conditional situation. For example, A will happen as long as you continue to do B. The same with 'so that’, this expression is also used to give reasons for something.

voca.title: as luck would have it
voca.explains:
There are many mouth-watering foods in the world. As luck would have it, I seem to like almost all of them. In other words, I am by no means picky with food.
As luck would have it, the bus arrived right on time.
There was doctor nearby, as luck would have it.

voca.title: as much as
voca.explains: A: Are these free give-away products? B: Yes, you can take as much as you like.\n

voca.title: as of now
voca.explains: from now on; from this moment on\nAs of now, I prefer living in the States.\n

voca.title: as often as not
voca.explains: frequently; usually\n

voca.title: as opposed to
voca.explains: used to make a contrast between two things\n

voca.title: as per usual

voca.explains: Sophie: I'm not feeling well. And yesterday, I was (as) sick as a dog.\n

voca.title: as something is being updated
voca.explains: A friend told me about an app that shows weather updates on the home screen. It shows the weather conditions as they’re being updated. It also displays the forecast for a certain period of time.\n

She lowered her WonderWorld hand to her knees, as though it was holding something heavy. The other hand shot up. "No contest."\n

Finally, I also make sure to bring along my first-aid kit. An extra towel always comes in handy as well.
"This is our little girl." Ed Crosswire continued. He held up Muffy's hand. "We started PAWS because of her, but we care about all of you as well."

voca.title: as well as
voca.explains: in addition to somebody/something; too\n

voca.title: as with most things

voca.title: as yet
voca.explains: until now or until a particular time in the past\n

voca.title: ash
voca.explains:
Ash is the grey or black powdery substance that is left after something is burnt. You can also refer to this substance as ashes.
A dead person's ashes are their remains after their body has been cremated.
An ash is a tree that has smooth grey bark and loses its leaves in winter.

voca.title: ashamed
voca.explains:
ashamed / embarrassed
If someone is ashamed, they feel embarrassed or guilty because of something they do or they have done, or because of their appearance.
If you are ashamed of someone, you feel embarrassed to be connected with them, often because of their appearance or because you disapprove of something they have done.
If someone is ashamed to do something, they do not want to do it because they feel embarrassed about it.

voca.title: ashore
voca.explains: Someone or something that comes ashore comes from the sea onto the shore.\n

voca.title: Asian
voca.explains: Someone or something that is Asian comes from or is associated with Asia. British people use this term especially to refer to India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh. Americans use this term especially to refer to China, Korea, Thailand, Japan, or Vietnam.\n

voca.title: Asian glow
voca.explains:
Most people look flushed after a few drinks but my Asian glow is on another level. Even my neck and arms turn blotchy and red.
I don't like to drink because I get the Asian glow.
Everyone assumed I was drunk because of my Asian glow.

voca.title: aside
voca.means:
[어^사이d]
한쪽으로, (길을) 비켜, 
(나중에 쓰려고) 따로, 별도로 하고, 
곁에, 조금 떨어져
방백, 소리낮춰 하는 말, 여담
voca.explains:
If you move something aside, you move it to one side of you.
If you take or draw someone aside, you take them a little way away from a group of people in order to talk to them in private.
If you move aside, you get out of someone's way.
If you set something such as time, money, or space aside for a particular purpose, you save it and do not use it for anything else.
If you brush or sweep aside a feeling or suggestion, you reject it.
An aside is a comment that a character in a play makes to the audience, which the other characters are supposed not to be able to hear.
A long, heavy tapestry had been pulled aside to reveal a small door in the stone wall.
The curtain covering the window moved aside.

voca.title: ask
voca.explains:
ask / enquire / demand / query
If you ask someone something, you say something to them in the form of a question because you want to know the answer.
If you ask someone to do something, you tell them that you want them to do it.
If you ask to do something, you tell someone that you want to do it.
If you ask for something, you say that you would like it.
If you ask for someone, you say that you would like to speak to them.
If you ask someone's permission, opinion, or forgiveness, you try to obtain it by putting a request to them.
If you ask someone to an event or place, you invite them to go there.
If someone is asking a particular price for something, they are selling it for that price.
You reply 'don't ask me' when you do not know the answer to a question, usually when you are annoyed or surprised that you have been asked.

voca.title: ask a favor
voca.explains: However, there are some personality traits I would like to fix. First of all, I can’t say no to a friend. If someone asks a favor, I almost always say yes.\n

voca.title: ask after each other
voca.explains:
My friends and I ask after each other.
We asked after each other before the meeting.
We asked after each other on the first day of class.

voca.title: ask for a recommendation
voca.explains: I often suffer from back pain. Recently, it was so bad that I had to do something about it. I went to a pharmacy and asked for a recommendation. The pharmacist gave me a medicated patch.\n

voca.title: ask for directions
voca.explains:
Before long, it became very dark. I had to stop at a store to ask for directions.
Why don't you ask for directions?
I think we should ask for directions.

voca.title: ask somebody out
voca.explains: Are you asking me out?\n

voca.title: asleep
voca.explains:
asleep / fall asleep / go to sleep / get to sleep / drift off / nod off / drop off
Someone who is asleep is sleeping.
When you fall asleep, you start sleeping.
Someone who is fast asleep or sound asleep is sleeping deeply.
The stag ran past flocks of sheep and herds of goats asleep in the meadows.

voca.title: aspect
voca.explains:
An aspect of something is one of the parts of its character or nature.
The aspect of a building or window is the direction in which it faces.
In grammar, aspect is the way that a verb group shows whether an activity is continuing, is repeated, or is completed. For example, in 'They were laughing', the verb is in the progressive aspect and shows that the action was continuing. Compare tense.
Still, in all other aspects of society, age is a key factor in relationships in Korea.

voca.title: aspiration
voca.explains: Someone's aspirations are their desire to achieve things.\n

voca.title: aspire
voca.explains: If you aspire to something such as an important job, you have a strong desire to achieve it.\n

voca.title: aspire to
voca.explains: to have a strong desire to gain or achieve something\n

voca.title: ass
voca.explains:
An ass is an animal which is related to a horse but which is smaller and has long ears.
If you describe someone as an ass, you think that they are silly or do silly things.
Your ass is your bottom.
Saying that someone can kiss your ass is a very rude way of expressing anger or disagreement.

voca.title: assassin
voca.explains: An assassin is a person who assassinates someone.\n

voca.title: assassinate
voca.explains: When someone important is assassinated, they are murdered as a political act.\n

voca.title: assault

[어썰-t]
폭행, (점거를 위한)공격, 비난, 습격, 
맹렬히 공격하다, 폭행을 가하다
(청각, 후각 등을) 괴롭히다
voca.explains:
An assault by an army is a strong attack made on an area held by the enemy.
An assault on a person is a physical attack on them.
An assault on someone's beliefs is a strong criticism of them.
Assault weapons such as rifles are intended for soldiers to use in battle rather than for purposes such as hunting.

voca.title: assemble
voca.explains:
build / construct / assemble / erect / set up / put up / put together
When people assemble or when someone assembles them, they come together in a group, usually for a particular purpose such as a meeting.
To assemble something means to collect it together or to fit the different parts of it together.

voca.title: assembler
voca.explains: An assembler is a person, a machine, or a company which assembles the individual parts of a vehicle or a piece of equipment such as a computer.\n

voca.title: assembly
voca.means:
[엇쎔블뤼]
집회, 모임, 회합, 의회(입법부)
(학교에서의) 조례
(차량, 가구 등의) 조립
voca.explains:
An assembly is a large group of people who meet regularly to make decisions or laws for a particular region or country.
An assembly is a group of people gathered together for a particular purpose.
When you refer to rights of assembly or restrictions on assembly, you are referring to the legal right that people have to gather together.
In a school, assembly is a gathering of all the teachers and pupils at the beginning of every school day.
The assembly of a machine, device, or object is the process of fitting its different parts together.

voca.title: assert
voca.explains:
If someone asserts a fact or belief, they state it firmly.
If you assert your authority, you make it clear by your behaviour that you have authority.
If you assert your right or claim to something, you insist that you have the right to it.
If you assert yourself, you speak and act in a forceful way, so that people take notice of you.

voca.title: assertion
voca.explains: claim / allegation / assertion / contention\n

Something or someone that is an asset is considered useful or helps a person or organization to be successful.
The assets of a company or a person are all the things that they own.
My friends are my greatest asset. A while ago, I was going through a rough patch at work. I felt like my career was at a dead end. I fell into a funk. Thankfully, I have good friends who helped me snap out of it.

voca.explains: If one person calls another person an asshole, they think that person is extremely stupid or has behaved in a stupid way.\n

voca.title: assign

[어싸인]
(일, 책임 등을) 맡기다, 배정하다, 부과하다, 양도하다
선임하다, 파견하다, (사람을) 배치하다
(가치, 기능 등을) 부여하다
voca.explains:
If you assign a piece of work to someone, you give them the work to do.
If you assign something to someone, you say that it is for their use.
If someone is assigned to a particular place, group, or person, they are sent there, usually in order to work at that place or for that person.
If you assign a particular function or value to someone or something, you say they have it.

voca.title: assignment
voca.explains:
task / duties / mission / job / assignment / chore
An assignment is a task or piece of work that you are given to do, especially as part of your job or studies.
You can refer to someone being given a particular task or job as their assignment to the task or job.
If you don't turn in your assignments, you won't pass the class.
The assignment took all day to finish.

voca.title: assist
voca.explains:
If you assist someone, you help them to do a job or task by doing part of the work for them.
If you assist someone, you give them information, advice, or money.
If something assists in doing a task, it makes the task easier to do.

voca.title: assistant
voca.explains:
Assistant is used in front of titles or jobs to indicate a slightly lower rank. For example, an assistant director is one rank lower than a director in an organization.
Someone's assistant is a person who helps them in their work.
An assistant is a person who works in a shop selling things to customers.

voca.title: associate
voca.means:
[어쏘시에잇t]
관련시키다, 제휴/연합시키다
(좋지 않은 사람들과) 어울리다
동료, 친구, 공범, 제휴한
동료의, 친구의
voca.explains:
If you associate someone or something with another thing, the two are connected in your mind.
If you are associated with a particular organization, cause, or point of view, or if you associate yourself with it, you support it publicly.
If you say that someone is associating with another person or group of people, you mean they are spending a lot of time in the company of people you do not approve of.
Your associates are the people you are closely connected with, especially at work.
Associate is used before a rank or title to indicate a slightly different or lower rank or title.

voca.title: associated
voca.explains: If one thing is associated with another, the two things are connected with each other.\nAssociated is used in the name of a company that is made up of a number of smaller companies which have joined together.\n

voca.title: association
voca.explains:
An association is an official group of people who have the same job, aim, or interest.
Your association with a person or a thing such as an organization is the connection that you have with them.
If something has particular associations for you, it is connected in your mind with a particular memory, idea, or feeling.
If you do something in association with someone else, you do it together.

voca.title: assume
voca.means:
[어^수움]
(사실일 것으로) 추정/상정하다,
생각하다, 가정하다, 추측하다
(권력, 책임을) 맡다
(특질, 양상을) 따다/취하다
voca.explains:
If you assume that something is true, you imagine that it is true, sometimes wrongly.
If something assumes a particular quality, it begins to have that quality.
You can use let us assume or let's assume when you are considering a possible situation or event, so that you can think about the consequences.

voca.title: assume power
voca.explains: If someone assumes power or responsibility, they take power or responsibility.\n

voca.title: assumption
voca.explains: If you make an assumption that something is true or will happen, you accept that it is true or will happen, often without any real proof.\nSomeone's assumption of power or responsibility is their taking of it.\n

voca.title: assure
voca.explains:
If you assure someone that something is true or will happen, you tell them that it is definitely true or will definitely happen, often in order to make them less worried.
To assure someone of something means to make certain that they will get it.
You use phrases such as I can assure you or let me assure you to emphasize the truth of what you are saying.

voca.title: asterisk
voca.explains: An asterisk is the sign *. It is used especially to indicate that there is further information about something in another part of the text.\n

voca.title: asthma
voca.explains: Asthma is a lung condition which causes difficulty in breathing.\n

voca.title: astrologer
voca.explains: An astrologer is a person who uses astrology to try to tell you things about your character and your future.\nThe zodiac is a diagram used by astrologers to represent the positions of the planets and stars. It is divided into twelve sections, each of which has its own name and symbol. The zodiac is used to try to calculate the influence of the planets, especially on someone's life.\n

voca.title: astronaut
voca.explains: An astronaut is a person who is trained for travelling in a spacecraft.\n

voca.title: astronomer
voca.explains: An astronomer is a scientist who studies the stars, planets, and other natural objects in space.\n

voca.title: astronomy
voca.explains: Astronomy is the scientific study of the stars, planets, and other natural objects in space.\n

voca.title: at a loss

voca.explains: uncertain about what to do or how to do something\n

voca.title: at a snail's pace
voca.means: 매우 느린 속도로, \n거북이 걸음으로,\n달팽이 같은 속도로(느릿느릿)

very slowly

He was walking at a snail's pace.
We climbed the mountain at a snail's pace.

voca.title: at a time

voca.title: at all

voca.explains: whatever has to be done, suffered, etc\nHe must pass his exams at all costs.\n

always

voca.title: at distance

voca.title: at fault

잘못해서, ~에 대해 죄/책임이 있어
어찌할 바를 모르고, 당황해서

voca.title: at first

voca.title: at first glance

as things seem at first; judging by first appearances

voca.title: at full stretch
voca.explains: to the full extent of your powers, abilities, etc\n

voca.title: at gaze
voca.means: 빤히 바라보다\n(사슴이) 몸을 옆으로 하고 정면을 응히사고(있는)

voca.title: at heart
voca.explains: used to say what somebody is really like even though they may seem to be different\n

voca.title: at large
voca.means: 전체적인, 대체적인, 일반적으로\n(위험한 사람, 동물이) 잡히지 않은, 활개치고 다니는
voca.explains: as a whole, in general\nfree; not captured\n

voca.title: at least
voca.means: 적어도, 최소한\n(부정적인 상황에 대해 긍정적인 말을 덧붙일때)
voca.explains:
not less than
the minimum somebody should do
used for talking about the only advantage or good point of somebody/something
used to show you are not completely sure of something

voca.title: at once
voca.explains: immediately\nat the same time\n

voca.title: at one's fingertips
voca.means: 손끝에, 즉시 이용할 수 있는\n잘 알고 있는, 즉시 이용할 수 있는.\n가까이에
voca.explains:
You download an application on your phone, pay a small fee, and you can get access to a huge music archive at your fingertips.
There are many ways to shop in Korea. There are more stores than you can shake a stick at. Online shopping and social commerce are at your fingertips.
The world is at your fingertips.
She had the answer at her fingertips.

voca.title: at short notice
voca.explains: with very little warning; without much time to prepare\n

voca.title: at the end of the day
at the end of the year
voca.explains:
In Korea, many awards ceremonies are held at the end of the year.
I like to meet my friends at the end of the year.
At the end of the year, I always clean up my room.

voca.title: at the latest
voca.explains:
On most days, I got to bed at midnight or 1 a.m. at the latest.
I will be there by 8 o'clock at the latest.
I need that report by tomorrow at the latest.

voca.title: at the moment
voca.explains:
At the moment, I don't have any cash on me.
Secretary: I'm sorry, he's out of the office at the moment.
At the moment, there are several Korean baseball players in MLB. That’s the most ever. The athletes are active in teams across the US. They are not bench warmers. They are not also-rans. They are star players.
At the moment, I’m passing all of my classes.
I am sorry. The line is busy at the moment. Please hold on.

voca.title: at the outset
voca.explains: at/from the beginning of something\n

voca.title: at the same time
voca.explains: A smartphone costs a pretty penny. Losing it is a big deal. I’ve lost track of my phone several times. I’ve also lost my wallet occasionally. Sometimes it was even more upsetting because the lost wallet was a gift with sentimental value. One time, I lost my phone and wallet at the same time.\n

voca.title: at the time
voca.explains: I first found it through an internet search. I chose it at the time because it was within my price range.\n

voca.title: at the very least
voca.explains: used after amounts to show that the amount is the lowest possible\nThe washing machine we have at home is a huge time-saver. It really lessens the load of housework. Keeping a home in order is a big ask. At the very least, having a washer gets laundry out of the way. That’s a big leg up.\n

voca.title: at your service
voca.means: 당신에 대한 서비스입니다.\n당신을 위해서라면 뭐든지 할 수 있어요.
voca.explains: My car is at your service.

voca.title: ate
voca.explains: Ate is the past tense of eat.\n

voca.title: athlete
voca.explains: An athlete is a person who does a sport, especially athletics, or track and field events.\nYou can refer to someone who is fit and athletic as an athlete.\n

voca.title: athletics
voca.explains: Athletics refers to track and field sports such as running, the high jump, and the javelin.\nAthletics refers to any kind of physical sports, exercise, or games.\n

voca.title: atlas
voca.explains: An atlas is a book of maps.\n

voca.title: atmosphere
voca.explains:
A planet's atmosphere is the layer of air or other gases around it.
The atmosphere of a place is the air that you breathe there.
The atmosphere of a place is the general impression that you get of it.
If a place or an event has atmosphere, it is interesting.
Korea is filled with a romantic atmosphere at Christmas. It is a very festive holiday.

voca.title: atom
voca.explains: An atom is the smallest amount of a substance that can take part in a chemical reaction.\n

voca.title: attach
voca.means:
[어^테-취]
붙이다, 첨부하다, 
~을 붙이다, 첨부하다, 참가하다
연관되다, 연관짓다, 부여하다
voca.explains:
If you attach something to an object, you join it or fasten it to the object.
If someone attaches himself or herself to you, they join you and stay with you, often without being invited to do so.
If people attach a quality to someone or something, or if it attaches to them, people consider that they have that quality.
If you attach conditions to something such as an agreement, you state that specific things must be done before the agreement is valid.
In computing, if you attach a file to a message that you send to someone, you send it with the message but separate from it.

voca.title: attack
voca.explains:
To attack a person or place means to try to hurt or damage them using physical violence.
If you attack a person, belief, idea, or act, you criticize them strongly.
If something such as a disease, a chemical, or an insect attacks something, it harms or spoils it.
If you attack a job or a problem, you start to deal with it in an energetic way.
In games such as football, when one team attacks the opponent's goal, they try to score a goal.
An attack of an illness is a short period in which you suffer badly from it.

voca.title: attempt
voca.means: [어템pt]\n~을 시도하다, 애써 해보다\n(특히 힘든일에 대한)시도, 기도, 노력, 미수, 살해기도
voca.explains:
If you attempt to do something, especially something difficult, you try to do it.
If you make an attempt to do something, you try to do it, often without success.
An attempt on someone's life is an attempt to kill them.

voca.title: attend
voca.explains:
If you attend a meeting or other event, you are present at it.
If you attend an institution such as a school, college, or church, you go there regularly.
If you attend to something, you deal with it. If you attend to someone who is hurt or injured, you care for them.
For ordinary desk jockeys, a planner is a must-have. On most workdays, I keep a small planner with me at all times. It’s useful to me in many ways. I use it to draft to-do lists. When I attend a meeting, I jot down important notes.
He has to leave to attend a meeting.
She can't answer the phone because she's attending a meeting.

voca.title: attend a funeral
voca.explains: When I was younger, a relative was diagnosed with cancer. He was sick for a long time. I went to visit him before he passed away. He was in a lot of pain. It made me feel very sad. I attended the funeral a few weeks later.\n

voca.title: attend to
voca.explains:
to deal with or take responsibility for something; to give practical help to somebody who needs it
When I stop by the bank, I try to make hay while the sun shines. Instead of just one errand, I attend to several errands at once.
She has too much to attend to by herself.
Please wait while I attend to this problem.

voca.title: attendance
voca.explains:
Someone's attendance at an event or an institution is the fact that they are present at the event or go regularly to the institution.
The attendance at an event is the number of people who are present at it.
If someone is in attendance at a place or an event, they are there.
John: Yes. We have two classes with very low registration and attendance.

voca.title: attendant
voca.means: [어^텐던t]\n시중드는 사람, 출석자, 안내원\n출석해 있는, 동석한, 수반하는
voca.explains:
An attendant is someone whose job is to serve or help people in a place such as a petrol station, a car park, or a cloakroom.
You use attendant to describe something that results from a thing already mentioned or that is connected with it.
Jason: Hey! I've been waiting for the attendant for at least 10 minutes now.
The flight attendants gave a safety demonstration. Soon, we took off. After a while, the attendants came by with the beverage cart. Later on, we had our in-flight meal.

voca.title: attention
voca.means:
[어^텐션]
주의, 집중, 주목
관심, 흥미
(관심을 끌기 위한) 행동/배려
(구령으로) 차려
voca.explains:
If you give someone or something your attention, you look at it, listen to it, or think about it carefully.
Attention is great interest that is shown in someone or something, particularly by the general public.
If someone or something is getting attention, they are being dealt with or cared for.
You can refer to someone's efforts to help you, or the interest they show in you, as their
If you bring something to someone's attention or draw their attention to it, you tell them about it or make them notice it.
If someone or something attracts your attention or catches your attention, you suddenly notice them.
If you pay attention to someone, you watch them, listen to them, or take notice of them. If you pay no attention to someone, you behave as if you are not aware of them or as if they are not important.
"Stay out of this, Arthur." said Francine. "You need to concentrate all your attention on holding on to the ball."

voca.title: attentive
voca.explains:
If you are attentive, you are paying close attention to what is being said or done.
Someone who is attentive is helpful and polite.
I’m usually very alert and attentive. However, when it comes to my belongings, I can be a little scatterbrained. I have a knack for misplacing things.

voca.title: attic
voca.explains: An attic is a room at the top of a house just below the roof.\n

voca.title: attire
voca.explains: Your attire is the clothes you are wearing.\n

voca.title: attitude
voca.explains:
Your attitude to something is the way that you think and feel about it,
If you refer to someone as a person with attitude, you mean that they have a striking and individual style of behaviour, especially a forceful or aggressive one.
It's not a matter of age. It's more about attitude.

voca.title: attorney
voca.explains: In the United States, an attorney or attorney at law is a lawyer.\n

voca.title: attract
voca.means:
[어튜^뤡t]
마음을 끌다, 매혹하다
(어떤 반응을) 불러 일으키다/끌다
(자석이나 중력이) 끌어 당기다
voca.explains:
If something attracts people or animals, it has features that cause them to come to it.
If someone or something attracts you, they have particular qualities which cause you to like or admire them. If a particular quality attracts you to a person or thing, it is the reason why you like them.
If you are attracted to someone, you are interested in them sexually.
If something attracts support, publicity, or money, it receives support, publicity, or money.
If one object attracts another object, it causes the second object to move towards it.
He's attracted to people who can make him crack up.
She was attracted to him because of his inviting face.

voca.title: attraction
voca.means:
[어t^뤡션]
(성적으로) 끌림, 
(사람을 끄는) 명소, 명물
매력(적인 요소)
끌어당기는 힘, 인력
voca.explains:
Attraction is a feeling of liking someone, and often of being sexually interested in them.
An attraction is a feature which makes something interesting or desirable.
An attraction is something that people can go to for interest or enjoyment, for example a famous building.

voca.title: attractive
voca.explains:
beautiful / pretty / handsome / attractive / lovely / good-looking / gorgeous
A person who is attractive is pleasant to look at.
Something that is attractive has a pleasant appearance or sound.
You can describe something as attractive when it seems worth having or doing.

voca.title: attribute
voca.means:
[어튜뤼뷰t]
~로 여기다, 때문이라고 생각한다
(~을 ~의) 결과로 보다
특성, 속성, 자질
voca.explains:
If you attribute something to an event or situation, you think that it was caused by that event or situation.
If you attribute a particular quality or feature to someone or something, you think that they have got it.
If a piece of writing, a work of art, or a remark is attributed to someone, people say that they wrote it, created it, or said it.
An attribute is a quality or feature that someone or something has.

voca.title: atypical
voca.explains: Someone or something that is atypical is not typical of its kind.\n

voca.title: auction
voca.explains: An auction is a public sale where goods are sold to the person who offers the highest price.\nIf something is auctioned, it is sold in an auction.\n

voca.title: auction something off
voca.explains: to sell something at an auction, especially something that somebody no longer needs or wants\n

voca.title: audience
voca.means: [^어-디언s]\n(연극, 음악회, 강연 등의) 청중, 관객, 시청자, 독자\n접견, 알현
voca.explains:
interview / interrogation / audience / consultation
The audience at a play, concert, film, or public meeting is the group of people watching or listening to it.
The audience for a television or radio programme consists of all the people who watch or listen to it.
The audience of a writer or artist is the people who read their books or look at their work.
If you have an audience with someone important, you have a formal meeting with them.

voca.title: audiophile
voca.explains: a person who has a great interest in high-fidelity sound reproduction\n

voca.title: audition
voca.means:
[어^딧션]
(가수, 배우 등의) 오디션
오디션을 보다, 오디션에 참가하다
오디션을 실시하다
voca.explains:
An audition is a short performance given by an actor, dancer, or musician so that a director or conductor can decide if they are good enough to be in a play, film, or orchestra.
If you audition or if someone auditions you, you do an audition.
After a few minutes of crunching, the auditions began.

voca.title: auditorium
voca.explains: An auditorium is the part of a theatre or concert hall where the audience sits.\nAn auditorium is a large room, hall, or building which is used for events such as meetings and concerts.\n

voca.title: augment
voca.explains: To augment something means to make it larger, stronger, or more effective by adding something to it.\n

voca.title: August
voca.explains: August is the eighth month of the year in the Western calendar.\nSomeone or something that is august is dignified and impressive.\n

voca.title: aunt
voca.explains: Someone's aunt is the sister of their mother or father, or the wife of their uncle.\n

voca.title: aura
voca.means: [오롸]\n(어떤 사람, 장소에 서려있는 독특한) 기운, 분위기
voca.explains: An aura is a quality or feeling that seems to surround a person or place or to come from them.\n

voca.title: author
voca.explains:
The author of a piece of writing is the person who wrote it.
An author is a person whose job is writing books.
The author of a plan or proposal is the person who thinks of it and works out the details.
Sophie: Do you have the Win-cooking book from this author?

voca.title: authoritarian
voca.explains: If you describe a person or an organization as authoritarian, you are critical of them controlling everything rather than letting people decide things for themselves.\n

voca.title: authority
voca.means:
[어^쏘r뤼디]
지휘권, 권한, 
재가, 인가, 권위자,
권위, 권력, 권한, 지휘권
당국, 공공사업 기관, 공사
voca.explains:
The authorities are the people who have the power to make decisions and to make sure that laws are obeyed.
An authority is an official organization or government department that has the power to make decisions.
Authority is the right to command and control other people.
If someone has authority, they have a quality which makes other people take notice of what they say.
Authority is official permission to do something.
Someone who is an authority on a particular subject knows a lot about it.
If you say you have it on good authority that something is true, you mean that you believe it is true because you trust the person who told you about it.
The authorities should crack down on people who litter. They should impose steep fines. Prevention is even more important than punishment. A sense of civic pride is key. It’s something we should teach our kids from an early age.

voca.title: authorize
voca.explains: If someone in a position of authority authorizes something, they give their official permission for it to happen.\n

voca.title: autobiography
voca.explains: Your autobiography is an account of your life, which you write yourself.\nLinda : Michael Jackson’s autobiography, 'Moon Walk'.\n

voca.title: autograph
voca.explains: An autograph is the signature of someone famous which is specially written for a fan to keep.\nIf someone famous autographs something, they put their signature on it.\n

voca.title: automatically
voca.explains: Last night, I was a little tipsy and I was unfit to drive. I had to call a designated driver service, but there were no drivers nearby. So, I used a smartphone app instead. The app detected my location automatically.\nOffice workers carry a card case filled with their business cards. People have piles of cards at their desks. It’s easy to save contacts on a phone. Some apps even scan business cards automatically.\n

voca.title: automobile
voca.explains: An automobile is a car.\n

voca.title: automotive
voca.explains: Automotive is used to refer to things relating to cars.\n

voca.title: autonomous
voca.explains:
An autonomous country, organization, or group governs or controls itself rather than being controlled by anyone else.
An autonomous person makes their own decisions rather than being influenced by someone else.
Helsinki, Finland is road-testing autonomous buses as part of the effort to make the city car-free within a decade.

voca.title: autumn
voca.explains:
Autumn is the season between summer and winter when the weather becomes cooler and the leaves fall off the trees.
The autumn leaves crunched and crackled under their leather shoes.
Autumn leaves twirled to the ground.

voca.title: autumn foliage
voca.explains: The mountains in Korea are charming all year round. In the summer, I enjoy the coolness of the mountain streams. Last fall, I went to enjoy the autumn foliage.\n

voca.title: auxiliary
voca.explains:
An auxiliary is a person who is employed to assist other people in their work. Auxiliaries are often medical workers or members of the armed forces.
In grammar, an auxiliary or auxiliary verb is a verb which is used with a main verb, for example to form different tenses or to make the verb passive. In English, the basic auxiliary verbs are 'be', 'have', and 'do'. Modal verbs such as 'can' and 'will' are also sometimes called auxiliaries.
Auxiliary staff and troops assist other staff and troops.

voca.title: available
voca.means: [어^베일러벌]\n가능한, 사용할 수 있는, 유용한\n(사람들을 만날) 시간/여유이 있는
voca.explains: If something you want or need is available, you can find it or obtain it.\nSomeone who is available is not busy and is therefore free to talk to you or to do a particular task.\n

voca.title: avalanche
voca.explains: An avalanche is a large mass of snow that falls down the side of a mountain.\nSomeone who is available is not busy and is therefore free to talk to you or to do a particular task.\n

voca.title: average
voca.explains:
An average is the result that you get when you add two or more numbers together and divide the total by the number of numbers you added together.
You use average to refer to a number or size that varies but is always approximately the same.
An amount or quality that is the average is the normal amount or quality for a particular group of things or people.
An average person or thing is typical or normal.
Something that is average is neither very good nor very bad, usually when you had hoped it would be better.
To average a particular amount means to do, get, or produce that amount as an average over a period of time.
You say on average or on an average to indicate that a number is the average of several numbers.

voca.title: average Joe
voca.explains:
Alternative form of Joe Average A typical, average person.
Someone who is just like everyone else; a normal person. 'Average' means 'in the middle' or 'not extreme', and 'Joe' is a common male name. So 'average Joe' refers to a man who is not extremely different from everyone else.
Parliamentary elections in Korea determine the nation’s lawmakers. Members of parliament are those who deal with the country’s headaches. But the truth is, they are tasked with helping the average Joe.
The average Joe dosen't care about that.
They are popular among average Joes.

voca.title: average out
voca.explains: to result in a fair or equal amount over a period of time\n

voca.title: average-looking
voca.explains: I'm an average-looking person. However, I do have crooked teeth.\n

voca.title: avert
voca.explains: If you avert something unpleasant, you prevent it from happening.\nIf you avert your eyes or gaze from someone or something, you look away from them.\n

voca.title: avid
voca.explains: You use avid to describe someone who is very enthusiastic about something that they do.\nIf you say that someone is avid for something, you mean that they are very eager to get it.\n

voca.title: avid reader
voca.explains:
Most successful people are avid readers. This is no coincidence. Books contain a lot of knowledge and wisdom.
She is an avid reader of sci-fi novels.
Many avid readers are waiting for his next book.

voca.title: avoid
voca.explains:
If you avoid something unpleasant that might happen, you take action in order to prevent it from happening.
If you avoid doing something, you choose not to do it, or you put yourself in a situation where you do not have to do it.
If you avoid a person or thing, you keep away from them. When talking to someone, if you avoid the subject, you keep the conversation away from a particular topic.
If a person or vehicle avoids someone or something, they change the direction they are moving in, so that they do not hit them.
In Korea, there is a very convenient service for drivers who have been drinking. People can request a designated driver for a fee. It's a great way to avoid driving under the influence.

voca.title: avoid notice
voca.means: 남의 눈을 피하다, 눈에 띄지 않게 하다

voca.title: await
voca.explains:
If you await someone or something, you wait for them.
Something that awaits you is going to happen or come to you in the future.
"Back to the bus, everyone!" he ordered. "The picnic awaits."

voca.title: awake
voca.means:
[어^웨익k]
(아직) 잠들지 않은, 깨어있는, 
깨다, 잠에서 깨다, 자각시키다
깨어서, 잠자지 않고
voca.explains:
awake / awaken / wake up / waken
Someone who is awake is not sleeping.
Someone who is wide awake is fully awake and unable to sleep.
When you awake or when something awakes you, you wake up.
All at once, he felt very awake.
"Are you still awake, Arthur?" D.W. was standing in the doorway.

voca.title: awake to something
voca.explains: to become aware of something and its possible results; to realize or understand something\n

voca.title: award
voca.means:
[어^워r-d]
(부상이 딸린) 상, 상금
(보수) 인상분, (판결 승소자에 대한 보상금 지급) 액수
수여하다, 보답하다, 재정하다
voca.explains:
An award is a prize or certificate that a person is given for doing something well.
In law, an award is a sum of money that a court decides should be given to someone.
A pay award is an increase in pay for a particular group of workers.
If someone is awarded something such as a prize or an examination mark, it is given to them.
To award something to someone means to decide that it will be given to that person.

voca.title: award category
voca.explains: The top 3 broadcast stations each have their own events in each category. With so many award categories, sometimes it is hard to keep up.\n

voca.title: award ceremony
voca.explains: In Korea, many awards ceremonies are held at the end of the year. There are separate award ceremonies for acting, music and comedy.\n

voca.title: award recipient
voca.explains: The award recipients give acceptance speeches.\n

voca.title: aware
voca.means:
[어웨어]
알고있는, 인식하는, 깨달은
눈치 채고 있는
~에 대한 의식이 높은/관심이 많은
voca.explains:
If you are aware of something, you know about it.
If you are aware of something, you realize that it is present or is happening because you hear it, see it, smell it, or feel it.
Someone who is aware notices what is happening around them or happening in the place where they live.

voca.title: awareness
voca.means: [어웨어네s]\n(무엇의 중요성에 대한) 의식/관심,\n알아채고 있음, 인식, 의식, 지각, 인지도

voca.title: away
voca.means: [어웨이]\n(시간적, 공간적으로) 떨어져, 사라져, 끊임없이\n다른데로, 자리에 없는, 결석한
voca.explains:
If someone or something moves or is moved away from a place, they move or are moved so that they are no longer there. If you are away from a place, you are not in the place where people expect you to be.
If you look or turn away from something, you move your head so that you are no longer looking at it.
If you put or tidy something away, you put it where it should be. If you hide someone or something away, you put them in a place where nobody can see them or find them.
You use away to talk about future events. For example, if an event is a week away, it will happen after a week.

voca.title: awe
voca.explains:
Awe is the feeling of respect and amazement that you have when you are faced with something wonderful and often rather frightening.
If you are awed by someone or something, they make you feel respectful and amazed, though often rather frightened.
If you are in awe of someone or if you stand in awe of them, you have a lot of respect for them and are slightly afraid of them.

voca.title: aweigh
voca.explains: (of an anchor) no longer hooked into the bottom; hanging by its rode\n

voca.title: awesome
voca.explains:
great / cool / fantastic / fabulous / terrific / brilliant / awesome
An awesome person or thing is very impressive and often frightening.
A : I thought it was really fantastic and the special effects were awesome.

voca.title: awful
voca.explains:
terrible / awful / horrible / dreadful / vile / foul
If you say that someone or something is awful, you dislike that person or thing or you think that they are not very good.
If you say that something is awful, you mean that it is extremely unpleasant, shocking, or bad.
If you look or feel awful, you look or feel ill.
You can use awful with noun groups that refer to an amount in order to emphasize how large that amount is.

voca.title: awfully
voca.explains: I'm awfully sorry about that problem the other day.\n

voca.title: awhile
voca.explains: Awhile means for a short time. It is more commonly spelled 'a while', which is considered more correct, especially in British English.\n

voca.title: awkward
voca.explains:
An awkward situation is embarrassing and difficult to deal with.
Something that is awkward to use or carry is difficult to use or carry because of its design. A job that is awkward is difficult to do.
An awkward movement or position is uncomfortable or clumsy.
Someone who feels awkward behaves in a shy or embarrassed way.

voca.title: awkward silence
voca.explains: Last weekend, we decided to go watch a movie. We bonded over our mutual interest in movies. Everything was smooth sailing, so we continued our talk over dinner. Surprisingly, there were no awkward silences in our conversation.\n

voca.title: awkwardly
voca.explains: Teddy turned awkwardly with his books.\n

voca.title: axe

도끼
해고, (기관의) 폐쇄, (사업의) 중단
(인원, 지원금 등을) 대폭 삭감/축소하다
voca.explains:
An axe is a tool used for cutting wood. It consists of a heavy metal blade which is sharp at one edge and attached by its other edge to the end of a long handle.
If a person or institution is facing the axe, that person is likely to lose their job or that institution is likely to be closed, usually in order to save money.
If someone's job or something such as a public service or a television programme is axed, it is ended suddenly and without discussion.

voca.title: baboon
voca.explains: A baboon is a large monkey that lives in Africa.\n

voca.title: baby

[^베이비-]
