어린, 작은
아기처럼 다루다
voca.explains:
A baby is a very young child, especially one that cannot yet walk or talk.
A baby animal is a very young animal.
Some people use baby as an affectionate way of addressing someone, especially a young woman, or referring to them.
Baby vegetables are vegetables picked when they are very small.

voca.title: baby shower
voca.means: 베이비 샤워 (임신한 것을 축하하기 위해 친구들이 아기 용품을 선물하는 축하 파티)

voca.title: baby something
voca.explains: I love my car, so I baby it a lot. However, one time I grazed the bumper while I was parking. I had nobody to blame. I had simply misjudged the angle.\n

voca.title: baby stroller
voca.explains: We also went shopping together. We bought baby clothes, diapers and nursing bottles. We also bought toys and a baby stroller.\n

voca.title: babysit
voca.explains: If you babysit for someone or babysit their children, you look after their children while they are out.\n

voca.title: babysitter
voca.means: [^베이비씻허r]\n(보통 돈을 받고) 아이를 봐 주는 사람

voca.title: bachelor
voca.means: [베췔러r]\n미혼 남자, 독신 남자, \n학사 학위 소지자, 대학 졸업자
voca.explains: A bachelor is a man who has never married.\n

voca.title: bachelorette
voca.explains:
a young unmarried professional woman
another word for bachelor apartment
Many people are fine with staying single. It is not strange to be a bachelor or a bachelorette.

voca.title: back
voca.means: [베엑k]\n등/허리, 등뼈, 척추, 뒷면, 뒤쪽, 뒷 부분\n후원하다, 후퇴하다, 도와주다
voca.explains:
If you move back, you move in the opposite direction to the one in which you are facing or in which you were moving before.
If you go back somewhere, you return to where you were before.
If someone or something is back in a particular state, they were in that state before and are now in it again.
A person's or animal's back is the part of their body between their head and their legs that is on the opposite side to their chest and stomach.
The back of something is the side or part of it that is towards the rear or farthest from the front. The back of something is normally not used or seen as much as the front.

voca.title: back and forth
voca.explains:
They used a crushed mild carton as a puck, hitting it back and forth the lenght of the table.
Buster and Arthur were walking along the sidewalk with their baseball gloves. As they walked, they tossed a ball back and forth.
Coach Frensky paced back and forth in front of his bench. "Okay, team, this is our first game. The Penguins are pretty good, I hear." He took a deep breath. "But I want you to play just the way you have in practice. Just go out and have fun."

voca.title: back away
voca.explains: to move backwards away from somebody/something frightening or unpleasant\nMuffy backed away. "Um, no thanks. My mom won't let me-too much fat and sugar." She shut her eyes. "Take it away. Please!"\n

voca.title: back down
voca.explains: to take back a claim or a demand that you have made, or something that you have said, usually because somebody forces you to\n

voca.title: back down from
voca.means: ~에서 뒷걸음치다, ~에서 손을 때다\n(주장 등을) 철회하다, 포기하다

voca.title: back in the day
voca.explains:
He founded the company back in 2001.
Back in the day, paying for something was simple. You only had to choose between cash or credit. But now, smartphones have paved the way for more payment methods. There are so many options, it can be dizzying.
Music was better back in the day.
Back in the day, plane tickets used to be pricey.

voca.title: back into
voca.explains: Sue Ellen nodded. She stepped back into the batter’s box.\n

voca.title: back off
voca.explains:
to stop threatening or annoying somebody
to decide not to continue to do something or support an idea, in order to avoid a difficult or unpleasant situation
I'm going to back off on giving my students so much homework.

voca.title: back out
voca.explains:
to withdraw (from an agreement, etc)
Now that he had started making up a story, he couldn't back out.
"The best thing to do is to go right back out," said Boka.

voca.title: back out of
voca.means: 약속을 저버리다\n약속을 취소하다, 철회하다\n~를 취소하다, 번복하다

to decide not to do something that you had agreed or promised to do

Shawn: I'm going to call him and back out of it.
The airline backed out of the deal.

voca.title: back something into
voca.explains:

He backed the car into a parking spot.
She backed herself into a corner.

voca.title: back street
voca.explains:
A back street in a town or city is a small, narrow street with very little traffic.
The back streets of a town or city are the areas of small, old, poor streets rather than the richer or newer areas.
Back street activities are carried out unofficially, secretly, and often illegally.
Another time, I put the car in reverse on a back street. By accident, I backed it into a wall. The rear fender was in shambles.

voca.title: back then
voca.explains: When I was in junior high, we didn't have Facebook back then.\nWhat types of music did you enjoy back then?\n

voca.explains:
to move backwards a short distance, especially in a vehicle; to make somebody/something move backwards a short distance
if traffic backs up or is backed up, it cannot move and forms a long line
I went to a repair shop for an estimate. The quote was eye-popping. I didn’t want to charge it to insurance, because it was my own fault. Since then, I’m much more careful when backing up.

voca.title: backbone
voca.explains: Your backbone is the column of small linked bones down the middle of your back.\nThe backbone of an organization or system is the part of it that gives it its main strength.\n

(사진 등의) 배경, 
출신, 경력
voca.explains:
environment / setting / surroundings / background / backdrop / situation
Your background is the kind of family you come from and the kind of education you have had. It can also refer to such things as your social and racial origins, your financial status, or the type of work experience that you have.
The background to an event or situation consists of the facts that explain what caused it.
The background is sounds, such as music, which you can hear but which you are not listening to with your full attention.
You can use background to refer to the things in a picture or scene that are less noticeable or important than the main things or people in it.

voca.explains: Time for my fastball, thought Francine. She gripped the ball firmly-and threw. The ball sailed high over everything-her father, Binky, even the backstop.\n

voca.title: backward

baggage / luggage

If someone is bailed, they are released while they are waiting for their trial, after paying an amount of money to the court.

voca.explains: save / rescue / bail out / redeem\nto pay somebody's bail (= the money that somebody accused of a crime has to pay if they do not appear at\n

미끼(가 되는 사람, 물건)
미끼를 놓다/달다
(일부러) 화를 돋우다
voca.explains:

To use something as bait means to use it to trick or persuade someone to do something.
If you bait a hook or trap, you put bait on it or in it.

voca.explains:
If you bake, you spend some time preparing and mixing together ingredients to make bread, cakes, pies, or other food which is cooked in the oven.
When a cake or bread bakes or when you bake it, it cooks in the oven without any extra liquid or fat.
If places or people become extremely hot because the sun is shining very strongly, you can say that they bake.
A vegetable or fish bake is a dish that is made by chopping up and mixing together a number of ingredients and cooking them in the oven so that they form a fairly dry solid mass.

voca.title: balance
voca.explains:
If you balance something somewhere, or if it balances there, it remains steady and does not fall.
If you balance one thing with something different, each of the things has the same strength or importance.
If you balance one thing against another, you consider its importance in relation to the other one.
Balance is the ability to remain steady when you are standing up.

If you say that the balance tips in your favour, you start winning or succeeding, especially in a conflict or contest.

Jack tried to regain his balance, but it was too late!

voca.title: balcony
voca.explains:
A balcony is a platform on the outside of a building, above ground level, with a wall or railing around it.
The balcony in a theatre or cinema is an area of seats above the main seating area.
Other rooms in the apartment are the living room, the kitchen, the bathroom, the storage closet, and the balcony.

A bald statement is in plain language and contains no extra explanation or information.

voca.title: baldy
voca.explains: People sometimes refer to a bald person as a baldy, especially if they are talking about them or to them in a friendly or humorous way.\n

When you ball something or when it balls, it becomes round.
If you say that the ball is in someone's court, you mean that it is his or her responsibility to take the next action or decision in a situation.

voca.title: ball field

voca.title: ballet
voca.explains:
Ballet is a type of very skilled and artistic dancing with carefully planned movements.
A ballet is an artistic work that is performed by ballet dancers.
She has good posture from learning ballet.

voca.title: ballistic
voca.explains:
Ballistic means relating to ballistics.
If someone goes ballistic, they suddenly become very angry.
If something goes ballistic, it suddenly becomes very much greater or more powerful, often in a surprising or unwanted way.

[벌루운]

부푼, 늘어난

When something balloons, it increases rapidly in amount.

voca.title: ballroom
voca.explains: A ballroom is a very large room that is used for dancing.\n

voca.title: bamboo

voca.title: ban
voca.explains:
To ban something means to state officially that it must not be done, shown, or used.
If you are banned from doing something, you are officially prevented from doing it.
A ban is an official ruling that something must not be done, shown, or used.
"There's a whole article in today's paper about the book ban and an interview with the people behind it. I'll skip to the important part."

We have to ban bribery in our society.
The candidate promised voters that he would ban bribery.

voca.title: band

밴드, (함께 어울려 다니는) 무리, 묶는 것, 띠, 끈

띠/줄무늬를 두르다, 일정한 범위로 나누다

A band is a strip of something such as colour, light, land, or cloth which contrasts with the areas on either side of it.
A band is a strip or loop of metal or other strong material which strengthens something, or which holds several things together.
A band is a range of numbers or values within a system of measurement.

voca.title: bandage

voca.title: bang

[^벵]
~을 (세게 소리내어) 치다, 부딪치다
쾅 하고 닫다/닫히다, 
굉음, 쿵 하는 소리, 강타

A bang is a sudden loud noise such as the noise of an explosion.

If something bangs, it makes a sudden loud noise, once or several times.
If you bang a door or if it bangs, it closes suddenly with a loud noise.

voca.explains: I first found it through an internet search. I chose it at the time because it was within my price range. I was happily surprised. The food was first-rate. The staff were courteous and helpful. The rooms were clean and spacious. It was just a lot of bang for the buck.\n

voca.title: bang on

은행, (노름판의) 판돈/물주, 둑, 제방
둑을 쌓다, 쌓이다
통장에 돈을 넣다, 예금하다
쌓다, 싸아 올리다

voca.title: bank loan
voca.explains:
Most people who buy a home need to get a bank loan, Buying real estate can be a good investment. However, speculative buyers drive up prices even more.
I got a bank loan to buy a new car.
I don't want to get a bank loan if I could avoid it.
All the houses that I liked were out of my league. I put in the footwork, visiting various candidates. I arrived at the conclusion that I needed a bank loan.

voca.title: bank up
voca.explains: to form into a large pile; to make something form a large pile\n

voca.title: bankbook
voca.explains: Also called : passbook a book held by depositors at certain banks, in which the bank enters a record of deposits, withdrawals, and earned interest\nThese include taking out a loan or opening an account. When I stop by the bank, I try to make hay while the sun shines. Instead of just one errand, I attend to several errands at once. For example, I make it a point to update my bankbook whenever I go to the bank.\n

voca.title: bankroll
voca.means: [뱅k롤]\n(사업 등에) 자금을 대다\n재정 지원, 재원, 지폐뭉치
voca.explains: To bankroll a person, organization, or project means to provide the financial resources that they need.\nA bankroll is the financial resources used to back a person, project, or institution.\n

voca.title: banner
voca.explains:
A banner is a long strip of cloth with something written on it. Banners are usually attached to two poles and carried during a protest or rally.
If someone does something under the banner of a particular cause, idea, or belief, they do it saying that they support that cause, idea, or belief.
No banners waved from its turrets.

voca.title: banquet
voca.explains: A banquet is a grand formal dinner.\nIt shone on a long banquet table. The table was littered with bread crumbs, candle wax, and the petals of dead flowers.\n

voca.title: baptism
voca.explains: A baptism is a Christian ceremony in which a person is baptized. Compare christening.\n

voca.title: baptize
voca.explains: When someone is baptized, water is put on their heads or they are covered with water as a sign that their sins have been forgiven and that they have become a member of the Christian Church. Compare christen.\n

voca.title: bar
voca.means:
[바아r]
빗장, 막대, 술집
막대기, (악보의) 마디
~에 빗장걸다, 잠그다, (길을) 막다, 차단하다
~에게 (~하는 것을) 금지하다
~을 제외하고
voca.explains:
A bar is a place where you can buy and drink alcoholic drinks.
A bar is a room in a pub or hotel where alcoholic drinks are served.
A bar is a counter on which alcoholic drinks are served.
A bar is a long, straight, stiff piece of metal.
If you bar a door, you place something in front of it or a piece of wood or metal across it in order to prevent it from being opened.
If you bar someone's way, you prevent them from going somewhere or entering a place, by blocking their path.
If someone is barred from a place or from doing something, they are officially forbidden to go there or to do it.

voca.title: barbecue
voca.means: [^바r뷔큐우]\n바비큐용 그릴, 바비큐 파티\n바비큐하다, 숯불위에 그릴을 얹고 굽다
voca.explains:
A barbecue is a piece of equipment which you use for cooking on in the open air.
If someone has a barbecue, they cook food on a barbecue in the open air.
If you barbecue food, especially meat, you cook it on a barbecue.

voca.title: barber
voca.explains:
A barber is a man whose job is cutting men's hair.
A barber's is a shop where a barber works.
The sound blasted through the closed windows. Bob was startled-and clipped off most of her bangs.

voca.title: bare
voca.means:
[베어r]
~을 드러내다, ~에서 제거하다
벌거벗은, 맨-, 노출된, 아무것도 안 덮인, 
꾸밈없는, 극소량의, 가장 기본적인 (것만 갖춘)
voca.explains:
naked / bare
If a part of your body is bare, it is not covered by any clothing.
A bare surface is not covered or decorated with anything.
If a tree or a branch is bare, it has no leaves on it.
If you bare something, you uncover it and show it.
The tree house was in the tallest tree in a grove of tall, bare trees.

voca.title: bare feet
voca.explains: Jack felt the water rising around his bare feet.\n

voca.title: barefoot
voca.explains: Someone who is barefoot or barefooted is not wearing anything on their feet.\nThey were all barefoot and wore wreaths of flowers around their necks.\n

voca.title: barely
voca.explains:
hardly / scarcely / barely / no sooner
You use barely to say that something is only just true or only just the case.
If you say that one thing had barely happened when something else happened, you mean that the first event was followed immediately by the second.

voca.title: barely have time
voca.explains:
However, the restaurant was overwhelmed with orders. It took the better part of an hour for our food to arrive. By then, it was well past our lunchtime. We barely had time to eat.
I barely had time to brush my teeth in the morning.
He barely had time to catch his breath.

voca.title: barely noticeable
voca.explains:
My excuse was that I didn’t have time to work out. At first, the weight gain was barely noticeable. But in a flash, I had gained almost 10 kilograms.
The stain on the shirt is barely noticeable.
It was barely noticeable, but it still bothered her.

voca.title: bargain
voca.means:
[^바r-겐]
흥정하다
매매계약, 특가품, 싸게 팜, 떨이
(정상가 보다) 싸게사는 물건
voca.explains:
Something that is a bargain is good value for money, usually because it has been sold at a lower price than normal.
A bargain is an agreement, especially a formal business agreement, in which two people or groups agree what each of them will do, pay, or receive.
When people bargain with each other, they discuss what each of them will do, pay, or receive.
If people drive a hard bargain, they argue with determination in order to achieve a deal which is favourable to themselves.
You use into the bargain when mentioning an additional quantity, feature, fact, or action, to emphasize the fact that it is also involved. You can also say in the bargain in American English.

voca.title: bargain basement price
voca.explains:
First and foremost, I like the information I can glean. Shopping hosts courteously explain all there is to know about a product. This is a distinct advantage over other methods. Also, sometime home shopping offers bargain basement prices.
I bought it at a bargain basement price.
She finds items at bargain basement prices.

voca.title: bargain something away
voca.explains: to give away something valuable or important in exchange for something less valuable or important\n

voca.title: barge
voca.explains:
A barge is a long, narrow boat with a flat bottom. Barges are used for carrying heavy loads, especially on canals.
If you barge into a place or barge through it, you rush or push into it in a rough and rude way.
If you barge into someone or barge past them, you bump against them roughly and rudely.

voca.title: barista
voca.explains: a person who makes and serves coffee in a coffee bar\nI received my cup and took a sip. However, it wasn’t green tea, but coffee. I made a complaint at the counter. The barista was courteous and helpful.\n

voca.title: bark
voca.explains:
When a dog barks, it makes a short, loud noise, once or several times.
If you bark at someone, you shout at them aggressively in a loud, rough voice.
Bark is the tough material that covers the outside of a tree.
Boka was pounding a wide strip of bark with a wooden club.

voca.title: bark out
voca.explains: to shout something loudly\n

voca.title: barley
voca.explains: Barley is a grain that is used to make food, beer, and whisky.\n

voca.title: barn
voca.explains: A barn is a building on a farm in which crops or animal food can be kept.\n

voca.title: barrel
voca.means:
[붸럴]
(목제 금속으로 된 대통) 통, 배럴, 맥주통, 
(총의) 총렬
(통제가 안되게) 쏜살같이 달리다/질주하다
voca.explains:
A barrel is a large, round container for liquids or food.
In the oil industry, a barrel is a unit of measurement equal to 159 litres.
The barrel of a gun is the tube through which the bullet moves when the gun is fired.
If a vehicle or person is barreling in a particular direction, they are moving very quickly in that direction.

voca.title: barren
voca.explains:
A barren landscape is dry and bare, and has very few plants and no trees.
Barren land consists of soil that is so poor that plants cannot grow in it.
If you describe something such as an activity or a period of your life as barren, you mean that you achieve no success during it or that it has no useful results.
If you describe a room or a place as barren, you do not like it because it has almost no furniture or other objects in it.
A barren woman or female animal is unable to have babies.
He had never been to such a colorless, barren place.

voca.title: barrette
voca.explains: a clasp or pin for holding women's hair in place\n

voca.title: barrier
voca.means:
[^붸뤼어r]
(통행을 막는) 장벽
(어떤 일에 대한) 장애물
(둘 사이를 갈라놓는) 장벽
(넘기 힘든) 벽, 한계
voca.explains:
A barrier is something such as a rule, law, or policy that makes it difficult or impossible for something to happen or be achieved.
A barrier is a problem that prevents two people or groups from agreeing, communicating, or working with each other.
A barrier is something such as a fence or wall that is put in place to prevent people from moving easily from one area to another.
A barrier is an object or layer that physically prevents something from moving from one place to another.
You can refer to a particular number or amount as a barrier when you think it is significant, because it is difficult or unusual to go above it.

voca.title: barrow
voca.means: [바러우]\n(과일, 야채 등을 파는 행상의) 수레\n(고대의) 고분, 무덤
voca.explains:
A barrow is the same as a wheelbarrow.
A barrow is a cart from which fruit or other goods are sold in the street.
A barrow is a large structure made of earth that people used to build over graves in ancient times.

voca.title: base
voca.means:
[베이s]
(사상, 사실 등의) 기초, 기반, 토대, 
근거지, 본부, 본사, 
~의 기초를 쌓다, ~에 근거를 두다
기본의, 기초의
voca.explains:
basis / foundation / base
The base of something is its lowest edge or part.
The base of something is the lowest part of it, where it is attached to something else.
The base of an object such as a box or vase is the lower surface of it that touches the surface it rests on.
The base of an object that has several sections and that rests on a surface is the lower section of it.
A base is a layer of something which will have another layer added to it.
A position or thing that is a base for something is one from which that thing can be developed or achieved.
A company's client base or customer base is the group of regular clients or customers that the company gets most of its income from.

voca.title: base on
voca.explains: A big part of Korean tradition is based on Confucian culture.\n

voca.title: baseball
voca.explains: In America, baseball is a game played by two teams of nine players. Each player from one team hits a ball with a bat and then tries to run around three bases and get to the home base before the other team can get the ball back.\nA baseball is a small hard ball which is used in the game of baseball.\n

voca.title: based on
voca.explains: Shoulder pain is a chronic problem for many modern people. Based on personal experience, I think good posture is most important. Periodic stretching and exercise help, too. Plus, using your shoulder a lot can help cure the pain.\n

voca.title: basement
voca.explains: The basement of a building is a floor built partly or completely below ground level.\nAnd they both went down to the basement-where there was nothing more to be heard.\n

voca.title: bash
voca.explains:
hit / knock / bang / strike / bump / bash
A bash is a party or celebration, especially a large one held by an official organization or attended by famous people.
If you get a bash on a part of your body, someone or something hits you hard, or you bump into something.
If someone bashes you, they attack you by hitting or punching you hard.
If you bash something, you hit it hard in a rough or careless way.
To bash someone means to criticize them severely, usually in a public way.

voca.title: bash about
voca.explains: to hit or strike somebody/something and treat them/it in a rough way\n

voca.title: bash away
voca.explains: to work very hard at something for a period of time\n

voca.title: bash something out
voca.means: ~을 후딱 만들어 내다, \n(짧은 시간 안에 많은 양을 만들어 내지만 질은 썩 좋지 않음을 나타냄)
voca.explains: to write something very quickly, without taking much care\n

voca.title: basic
voca.means:
[베이쥑]
(다른 것의 발전, 전개에) 기본/근본 적인, 
기초, 근본, 기본원리
기본적인, 기초적인, 근본적인
(모든 사람들에게) 기본적인, 필수적인
voca.explains:
You use basic to describe things, activities, and principles that are very important or necessary, and on which others depend.
Basic goods and services are very simple ones which every human being needs. You can also refer to people's basic needs for such goods and services.
If one thing is basic to another, it is absolutely necessary to it, and the second thing cannot exist, succeed, or be imagined without it.
You can use basic to emphasize that you are referring to what you consider to be the most important aspect of a situation, and that you are not concerned with less important details.
You can use basic to describe something that is very simple in style and has only the most necessary features, without any luxuries.
Basic is used to describe a price or someone's income when this does not include any additional amounts.

voca.title: basic necessities
voca.explains: I went to a pet shop to buy the basic necessities. I picked up some dog food and treats.\n

voca.title: basin
voca.means:
[베이슨]
대야, 세면기, 물웅덩이, 작은 연못, 
(지질) 분지
(강의) 유역
voca.explains:
A basin is a large or deep bowl that you use for holding liquids, or for mixing or storing food.
A basin is the same as a washbasin.
A basin is a partially enclosed area of deep water where boats or ships are kept.
The river basin contains over half of the rain forests in the world.

voca.title: basis
voca.explains:
basis / foundation / base
If something is done on a particular basis, it is done according to that method, system, or principle.
If you say that you are acting on the basis of something, you are giving that as the reason for your action.
The basis of something is its starting point or an important part of it from which it can be further developed.
The basis for something is a fact or argument that you can use to prove or justify it.

voca.title: baskets
voca.explains:
A basket is a stiff container that is used for carrying or storing objects. Baskets are made from thin strips of materials such as straw, plastic, or wire woven together.
In economics, a basket of currencies or goods is the average or total value of a number of different currencies or goods.
In basketball, the basket is a net hanging from a ring through which players try to throw the ball in order to score points.
Teddy's lantern shone on a brick oven, a stone hearth, baskets of apples, and strings of onions hanging from the rafters.

voca.title: bastion
voca.means: [베s티언]\n(생활 방식, 주의 등의) 수호자\n보루, 요새, 성채
voca.explains: If a system or organization is described as a bastion of a particular way of life, it is seen as being important and effective in defending that way of life. Bastion can be used both when you think that this way of life should be ended and when you think it should be defended.\n

voca.title: bat
voca.explains:
A bat is a specially shaped piece of wood that is used for hitting the ball in baseball, softball, cricket, rounders, or table tennis.
A bat is a small flying animal that looks like a mouse with wings made of skin. Bats are active at night.
When you bat, you have a turn at hitting the ball with a bat in baseball, softball, cricket, or rounders.
When something surprising or shocking happens, if someone doesn't bat an eyelid in British English, or doesn't bat an eye in American English, they remain calm and do not show any reaction.
Annie batted the animal's paws.
When the lights went out, she was as blind as a bat.

voca.title: bath
voca.explains:
bath / bathe / swim / sunbathe
A bath is a container, usually a long rectangular one, which you fill with water and sit in while you wash your body.
When you have or take a bath, or when you are in the bath, you sit or lie in a bath filled with water in order to wash your body.
A bath or a baths is a public building containing a swimming pool, and sometimes other facilities that people can use to have a wash or a bath.
A bath is a container filled with a particular liquid, such as a dye or an acid, in which particular objects are placed, usually as part of a manufacturing or chemical process.
If you bath someone, especially a child, you wash them in a bath.
Everything was bathed in a golden red glow.

voca.title: bathe
voca.means:
[베잇쓰]
(몸을) 씻다, 세척하다, 
목욕하다, 적시다, 담그다, 씻다
(바다, 강에서 하는) 멱/수영
voca.explains:
bath / bathe / swim / sunbathe
If you bathe in a sea, river, or lake, you swim, play, or wash yourself in it. Birds and animals can also bathe.
When you bathe, you have a bath.
If you bathe someone, especially a child, you wash them in a bath.
If you bathe a part of your body or a wound, you wash it gently or soak it in a liquid.
If a place is bathed in light, it is covered with light, especially a gentle, pleasant light.

voca.title: bathing
voca.means: [^베이딩]\n(강, 바다 등에서 하는) 수영, \n목욕, 수영, 해수욕
voca.explains: "No, I want to go home and change out of my bathing suit." said Jack.\n

voca.title: bathrobe
voca.explains: A bathrobe is a loose piece of clothing made of the same material as towels. You wear it before or after you have a bath or a swim.\nA bathrobe is a dressing gown.\n

voca.title: bathtub
voca.explains: A bathtub is a long, usually rectangular container which you fill with water and sit in to wash your body.\n

voca.title: battalion
voca.explains: A battalion is a large group of soldiers that consists of three or more companies.\nA battalion of people is a large group of them, especially a well-organized, efficient group that has a particular task to do.\n

voca.title: batter
voca.means:
[베러r]
(특히 심한 손상이 가해지도록 계속) 두드리다, 
때리다, 구타하다
(튀김, 팬케이크용) 반죽, 튀김 옷
케이크 반죽
voca.explains:
beat / batter / pound / pummel / lash / hammer
If someone is battered, they are regularly hit and badly hurt by a member of their family or by their partner.
To batter someone means to hit them many times, using fists or a heavy object.
If a place is battered by wind, rain, or storms, it is seriously damaged or affected by very bad weather.
If you batter something, you hit it many times, using your fists or a heavy object.
Batter is a mixture of flour, eggs, and milk that is used in cooking.
In sports such as baseball and softball, a batter is a person who hits the ball with a wooden bat.
Feeling bruised and battered, he fell onto the sand.

voca.title: batter something down
voca.explains: to hit something repeatedly until it breaks and falls down\n

voca.title: battery
voca.explains:
Batteries are small devices that provide the power for electrical items such as radios and children's toys.
A car battery is a rectangular box containing acid that is found in a car engine. It provides the electricity needed to start the car.
A battery of equipment such as guns, lights, or computers is a large set of it kept together in one place.
A battery of people or things is a very large number of them.
A battery of tests is a set of tests that is used to assess a number of different aspects of something, such as your health.
Battery farming is a system of breeding chickens and hens in which large numbers of them are kept in small cages, and used for their meat and eggs.

voca.title: battery life
voca.explains: I am on my phone 24/7, which tends to drain my battery at lightning speed. I peruse e-mail(s), the latest headlines, and social media posts. However, the collective act of reading doesn’t even come close to what video clips do to a smartphone’s battery life.\n

voca.title: battle
voca.explains:
campaign / battle / struggle / drive / war / fight
A battle is a violent fight between groups of people, especially one between military forces during a war.
A battle is a conflict in which different people or groups compete in order to achieve success or control.
You can use battle to refer to someone's efforts to achieve something in spite of very difficult circumstances.
To battle with an opposing group means to take part in a fight or contest against them. In American English, you can also say that one group or person is battling another.
To battle means to try hard to do something in spite of very difficult circumstances. In British English, you battle against something or with something. In American English, you battle something.

voca.title: be a big chunk of
voca.explains:
They are a big chunk of entertainment programs on TV these days.
Reading the news is a big chunk of what I do in the morning.
The money I earn here is a big chunk of my total income.

voca.title: be a big deal
voca.explains:
It was a big deal to go to the fast food place when I was young.
It seems like it is a big deal now, but it won't later.
These days, finding a jo is a big deal.

voca.title: be a big fan of
voca.explains:
I’m a big fan of taking selfies. Some might say that I am a selfie enthusiast.
She is a big fan of that actor.
We are big fans of the soccer team.

voca.title: be a blast
voca.explains: Last year. I traveled abroad. It was a blast. This year, I’m changing things up. I want to search for hidden gems.\n

voca.title: be a bundle of nerves
voca.explains:
Another time, I was wearing a formal suit. The pants got caught on something. With a flatulent sound, they ripped in the seat. All day, I was a bundle of nerves.
She drank so much coffee that she was a bundle of nerves.
He was a bundle of nerves before his interview.

voca.title: be a creature of habit
voca.means: ~가 습관에서 벗어나지 않는 사람이다, 버릇대로 한다
voca.explains: My grandfather is a creature of habit. He vacations in the same place every year.\n

voca.title: be a first
voca.explains:
For me, it was a first.
It was a first for him to try raw fish.
If we finish in one day, it will be a first.

voca.title: be a little tipsy
voca.explains:
Last night, I was a little tipsy and I was unfit to drive.
She talks a lot when she is a little tipsy.
He only had one drink, but he was already a little tipsy.

voca.title: be a long time before
voca.explains:
Then, I smelled something burning. With a sinking sensation, I ran back to the kitchen. The room was filled with acrid smoke. The pot was burned beyond repair, to say nothing of the soup. It was a long time before the smell went away.
It was a long time before I could understand the subject.
It will be a long time before we get another chance.

voca.title: be a lot of bang for the buck
voca.explains: I first found it through an internet search. I chose it at the time because it was within my price range. I was happily surprised. The food was first-rate. The staff were courteous and helpful. The rooms were clean and spacious. It was just a lot of bang for the buck.\n

voca.title: be a mass of
voca.explains: be full of or covered with something\n

voca.title: be a match for
voca.explains: For instance, Korea now has a bullet train called the KTX. Its top speed was unthinkable in the past. Now, it only takes half the time to get somewhere in Korea. In fact, the trains are even a match for airplanes.\n

voca.title: be a model of
voca.explains:
Korea’s subway system is great. The Seoul Metro is a model of public transportation. It’s convenient. It’s affordable. Above all, it’s easy to use. It really is the full package.
EBS is a model of English broadcasting.
The house is a model of cleanliness.

voca.title: be a pain
voca.explains:
I once broke a wine glass in my kitchen, and learned it can be extremely hazardous. The shards are razor-sharp. They can cut skin like a knife through butter. The smallest pieces can be a real pain to find.
My little brother can be a real pain.
All that homework was a real pain.

voca.title: be a regular
voca.explains:
We were regulars at the fast food place.
He knew what we wanted, because we are regulars.
The food here is so good, I want to be a regular.

voca.title: be a series of
voca.explains: People in Korea love year-end parties. December is a series of year-end parties for most people.\n

voca.title: be a snap
voca.explains: be very easy to do\n

voca.title: be a sucker for
voca.explains: I am a sucker for tear-jerking videos. My friends call em a crybaby.\nI am a sucker for coffee. I almost always have a cup at hand. However, I don’t want to go through too many disposable cups. That’s way I use a tumbler. It takes a little effort, but it’s worth it.\n

voca.title: be a tall order
voca.explains:
Last year, I applied to various companies for work. Finding employment is a tall order these days.
It's a tall order to finish this on time.
What you're asking for is a tall order.

voca.title: be a treat
voca.explains:
Usually, traveling is a treat. However, any number of things can go wrong while traveling. Sometimes, a problem can ruin an entire trip.
It is a treat to meet you.

With the advent of digital TV in Korea, it’s easy to use VOD services with the remote. I don’t need to fuss over broadcast schedules any more. With VOD, my viewing schedule is up to me. I just have to pay a little extra on my cable bill.
The decision is up to you.
It's up to her whether she goes or not.

voca.explains: B : I don't know. What's upper most in my mind is that they are healthy.\n

voca.title: be urgently needed
voca.explains: A growing number of people now feel that marriage isn’t absolutely necessary. It is a valid option. However, the low birthrate causes a misbalance in the population. It’s a problem on a national scale. A solution is urgently needed.\n

voca.title: be valued at
voca.explains: Korea’s currency is the Korean Won. The bills come in denominations of one, five, ten and fifty thousand Won. The coins are valued at 10, 50, 100 and 500 won.\n

voca.title: be very addictive
voca.explains: Pettitoes are a very popular dish in Korea. They are delicious, and are very addictive.\n

voca.title: be very driven
voca.explains: If I set a goal, I work diligently. I don’t like to leave something unfinished. I have to see it through to the end. I am very driven to succeed.\n

voca.title: be very forgetful
voca.explains:
Also, I am very forgetful. I often misplace things like my wallet and phone.
I lose things often because I am very forgetful.
If you are very forgetful, try writing things down.

voca.title: be visible
voca.explains: With age, it becomes easier to put on weight. If my weight rises by as little as 2 kilograms, it still bothers me. My clothes don’t fit well. The difference is visible around the jawline.\n

voca.title: be vulnerable to
voca.explains:
However, there is a trade-off. Security is a pressing issue. Online payments are vulnerable to hacking. Users must take precautions. For example, they should change their passwords periodically.
This area is vulnerable to earthquakes.
The site was vulnerable to personal information leakage.

voca.title: be wary
voca.explains:
It’s common knowledge that accidents are most likely to happen at home. One of the things people need to be wary about is breaking glass.
Children should be wary of strangers.
Be wary of distractions when you study.

voca.title: be wasteful
voca.explains:
Letting food go bad is wasteful, but it can also be dangerous. A bad case of food poisoning is no joke. To be on the safe side, it’s best to put food in the refrigerator right away.
I think paper cups are wasteful.
It's wasteful to use it just once.

voca.title: be well past
voca.explains:
However, the restaurant was overwhelmed with orders. It took the better part of an hour for our food to arrive. By then, it was well past our lunchtime.
It is well past time for you to go to sleep.
When he gave me his report, it was well past the deadline.

voca.title: be widely commercialized
voca.explains:
In eco-friendly cars, fuel efficiency is getting better every year. Drivers can protect the environment, and also save some cash. Hybrid cars have already been widely commercialized.
Tablet PCs have been widely commercialized.
How long will it take before this is widely commercialized?

voca.title: be widely used
voca.explains:
Bluetooth technology is widely used in cars.
Garlic is widely used in Korean cooking.
This book is widely used as a textbook among business students.

voca.title: be widespread
voca.explains:
The number of people who read books these days is shrinking. It seems like nobody has any free time. Also, mobile devices are more widespread. As a result, books have gone out of style. This is a shame.
Bluetooth is very widespread now. It’s used for many applications. I use it most often for audio devices. 
Coffee shops are widespread in Korea.
Surfing the internet on smartphone is widespread.

voca.title: be willing to
voca.explains: However, I am willing to endure it. It's the price to pay to feel confident when I smile.\nB : Yape! This semester I'm trying to get a study group together. I have friends who are willing to cram all night with me.\n

voca.title: be wipe from one's memory
voca.explains: Soon, our guests showed up. They didn’t come empty-handed. They came bearing gifts. People brought amenities like toilet paper, soap and detergent. They brought food like cake and fruit. The party was Bring Your Own Bottle(BYOB). The party was a riot. Everyone had fun. All the hard work was wiped from our memory.\n

voca.title: be within one's price range
voca.explains:
I first found it through an internet search. I chose it at the time because it was within my price range.
I want to buy it, but it's not within my price range.
Only look at things that are within your price range.

voca.title: be worse off
voca.explains: be poorer, unhappier, etc. than before or than somebody else\n

voca.title: be worth it
voca.explains:
The views are worth it.
It was difficult, but it was worth it.
It was worth it to go all the way over there.
I am a sucker for coffee. I almost always have a cup at hand. However, I don’t want to go through too many disposable cups. That’s way I use a tumbler. It takes a little effort, but it’s worth it.
Raising a child is hard, but it's worth it.
The new mirror was expensive, but it was worth it.

voca.title: be worth the trouble
voca.explains:
The only downside was that there were enormous crowds. Everyone wanted to take in the view. Still, it was worth the trouble.
It was a lot of work, but it was worth the trouble.
Was it worth the trouble to go there?
I even drive a small car to make parking less of a chore. It’s easier to navigate through cramped parking lots. Still, finding room to park is so difficult that I wonder if it’s worth the trouble.
She didn't think that the reward was worth the trouble.
It's not worth the trouble to try fixing it.

voca.title: beach
voca.explains:
coast / beach / seaside / coastline / shoreline / sand / seashore
A beach is an area of sand or stones beside the sea.
If something such as a boat beaches, or if it is beached, it is pulled or forced out of the water and onto land.

voca.title: bead
voca.explains:
Beads are small pieces of coloured glass, wood, or plastic with a hole through the middle. Beads are often put together on a piece of string or wire to make jewellery.
A bead of liquid or moisture is a small drop of it.
He wore a fur robe and white beads.

voca.title: beaded
voca.explains: A beaded dress, cushion, or other object is decorated with beads.\nIf something is beaded with a liquid, it is covered in small drops of that liquid.\n

voca.title: beak
voca.explains:
A bird's beak is the hard curved or pointed part of its mouth.
Moonlight shone on its sleek blue-black wings, its shaggy throat feathers, its thick neck and big beak.
His raven heart thumping, he walked to the diamond and nudged it with his beak.

voca.title: beam
voca.means:
[^비임]
광선, 빔, 빛줄기
기둥, 
(열, 빛을) 발하다, 보내다, 방송하다, 빛나다
활짝웃다,
voca.explains:
If you say that someone is beaming, you mean that they have a big smile on their face because they are happy, pleased, or proud about something.
If something beams radio signals or television pictures or they are beamed somewhere, they are sent there by means of electronic equipment.
If something such as the sun or a lamp beams down, it sends light to a place and shines on it.
A beam is a line of energy, radiation, or particles sent in a particular direction.
A beam of light is a line of light that shines from an object such as a lamp.
D.W. just laughed. "You sent that crummy thing in? And it won?" She beamed. "Of course, I have much better songs than that!"

voca.title: bean
voca.explains:
Beans such as green beans, French beans, or broad beans are the seeds of a climbing plant or the long thin cases which contain those seeds.
Beans such as soya beans and kidney beans are the dried seeds of a bean plant.
Beans such as coffee beans or cocoa beans are the seeds of plants that are used to produce coffee, cocoa, and chocolate.
If someone is full of beans, they are very lively and have a lot of energy and enthusiasm.

voca.title: bear
voca.means:
[^베어r]
낳다, 참다, 견디다
~ 할 만한 것이 못되다, 
(책임 등을) 떠맞다, 감당하다, 
(무개를) 지탱하다, 견디다, 
(아이를) 낳다
곰
voca.explains:
bear - bore - borne
If you bear something somewhere, you carry it there or take it there.
If you bear something such as a weapon, you hold it or carry it with you.
If one thing bears the weight of something else, it supports the weight of that thing.
If something bears a particular mark or characteristic, it has that mark or characteristic.
If you bear an unpleasant experience, you accept it because you are unable to do anything about it.
If you can't bear someone or something, you dislike them very much.
If someone bears the cost of something, they pay for it.
Sophie: I think so. I can't bear the pain anymore. I'll check it out.

voca.title: bear down on something
voca.explains:
to move towards somebody/something in a determined or threatening way
if a problem or a difficult situation bears down on you, it makes you feel very worried and has a severe effect on you
to press or push on somebody/something

voca.title: bear gifts
voca.explains: Soon, our guests showed up. They didn’t come empty-handed. They came bearing gifts. People brought amenities like toilet paper, soap and detergent. They brought food like cake and fruit. The party was Bring Your Own Bottle(BYOB).\n

voca.title: bear the brunt of
voca.explains:
Another time, I let my mind wander while I was climbing some stairs. I caught myself as I fell over. However, my wrist bore the brunt of the fall. It swelled up.
The class president bore the brunt of the teacher's anger.
The southern part of the country bore the brunt of the pyphoon.

voca.title: bear up against
voca.explains: to remain cheerful and in control in a difficult situation\n

voca.title: beard
voca.explains: A man's beard is the hair that grows on his chin and cheeks.\nTheir hair and beards were long and scraggly.\n

voca.title: bearded
voca.explains: A bearded man has a beard.\n

voca.title: bearing
voca.means:
[^베어륑]
관련, 영향, 
태도, 관계, 
(일정한 지점에서 나침반으로 측정한) 방위, 방향, 
방향감각
(기계의) 베어링
voca.explains:
If something has a bearing on a situation or event, it is relevant to it.
If you get your bearings or find your bearings, you find out where you are or what you should do next. If you lose your bearings, you do not know where you are or what you should do next.
Someone's bearing is the way in which they move or stand.
If you take a bearing with a compass, you use it to work out the direction in which a particular place lies or in which something is moving.
Bearings are small metal balls that are placed between moving parts of a machine in order to make them move smoothly and easily over each other.

voca.title: beast

[^비잇-t]
~을 치다, 이기다, 
통제/억제 하다
때리기, 맥박, 박자
녹초가 되다

beat / batter / pound / pummel / lash / hammer
If you beat someone or something, you hit them very hard.
To beat on, at, or against something means to hit it hard, usually several times or continuously for a period of time.
When your heart or pulse beats, it continually makes regular rhythmic movements.
If you beat a drum or similar instrument, you hit it in order to make a sound. You can also say that a drum beats.
If you beat eggs, cream, or butter, you mix them thoroughly using a fork or beater.

voca.title: beat it
voca.explains: go away\n

voca.title: beat the heat
voca.explains:
The hot weather reaches a peak during the dog days of summer. That’s when people opt for cool foods and drinks to beat the heat.

voca.means: ~을 기습하다, 허를 찌르다, 모집하다, 써서 낡은, 못쓰게 된

voca.title: beautiful
voca.explains:
beautiful / pretty / handsome / attractive / lovely / good-looking / gorgeous
A beautiful person is very attractive to look at.
If you describe something as beautiful, you mean that it is very attractive or pleasing.
You can describe something that someone does as beautiful when they do it very skilfully.
He pictured a beautiful, glowing castle lit with candles and filled with knights and ladies feasting and singing.
The bear was turned into a beautiful woman.

voca.title: beauty
voca.means: [^뷰리]\n아름다움, 미, 미인, 아름다운 것\n멋진 사례/보기, 멋진 점, 장점
voca.explains:
Beauty is the state or quality of being beautiful.
A beauty is a beautiful woman.
You can say that something is a beauty when you think it is very good.
The beauties of something are its attractive qualities or features.
If you say that a particular feature is the beauty of something, you mean that this feature is what makes the thing so good.
Beauty is used to describe people, products, and activities that are concerned with making women look beautiful.

voca.title: beauty sleep
voca.explains: sleep, esp sleep before midnight\nI’ve downloaded an application on my phone to monitor my sleep patterns. Apparently, I’m not getting enough REM (Rapid Eye Movement) sleep, which in layman’s terms, translates to not enough beauty sleep.\n

voca.title: because
voca.explains:
You use because when stating the reason for something.
You use because when stating the explanation for a statement you have just made.
If an event or situation occurs because of something, that thing is the reason or cause.
You use just because when you want to say that a particular situation should not necessarily make you come to a particular conclusion.

voca.title: because of
voca.explains:

voca.title: beckon

[벡겐]
(오라고) 손짓하여 부르다, 신호하다, 유혹하다
아주 매력적으로 보이다, 유혹의 손짓을 하다
(부르는 신호, 동의를 나타내는) 손짓, 고갯짓

If you beckon to someone, you signal to them to come to you.

voca.title: become
voca.explains:
become / get / go / turn
If someone or something becomes a particular thing, they start to change and develop into that thing, or start to develop the characteristics mentioned.
If something becomes someone, it makes them look attractive or it seems right for them.
If you wonder what has become of someone or something, you wonder where they are and what has happened to them.

voca.title: become mainstream
voca.explains:
Wireless devices have become mainstream these days.

You won't become very seasick on a larger boat.

voca.title: become widespread
voca.explains:
3D TVs are becoming widespread. They allow people to watch 3D movies in private at home.

voca.title: bed

[베d]

(강, 바다 등의) 바닥, 지층
침대, 취침시간
voca.explains:

A bed of shellfish or plants is an area in the sea or in a lake where a particular type of shellfish or plant is found in large quantities.
The sea bed or a river bed is the ground at the bottom of the sea or of a river.
A bed of rock is a layer of rock that is found within a larger area of rock.
If a recipe or a menu says that something is served on a bed of a food such as rice or vegetables, it means it is served on a layer of that food.

voca.title: bedspread
voca.explains: A bedspread is a decorative cover which is put over a bed, on top of the sheets and blankets.\n

voca.title: beef
voca.explains: Beef is the meat of a cow, bull, or ox.\nThen we went to the butcher's counter for beef and pork.\n

voca.title: beef something up
voca.explains: to make something bigger, stronger, more interesting, etc.\n

voca.title: beefy
voca.means: [^비뤼]\n우람한, 뚱뚱한 \n살집이 좋은, 뚱뚱한, 근육이 우람한, 둔중한, 무거운.

voca.title: beehive house
voca.explains: a prehistoric circular building found in various parts of Europe, usually of stone and having a dome-shaped roof\n

voca.title: beep
voca.means:
[^빕]
(전자 기기나 자동차 경적에서 나는) 삐/빵 소리
삐 소리를 내다
(자동차 경적이) 빵 소리를 내다/울리다

voca.title: beer
voca.explains: Beer is a bitter alcoholic drink made from grain.\n

voca.title: beer hall
voca.explains: I also worked for a while at a beer hall. It was hard work. But the boss was a stand-up guy. I worked for an hourly wage. It was fun. However, working late hours became too difficult. I had to quit after about six months.\n

voca.title: before
voca.means:
[비^포어r]
(시간 상으로 ~보다) 전에, 앞에
~하기 전에, ~하기까지, 
직전, 전에, 예전에
voca.explains:
If something happens before a particular date, time, or event, it happens earlier than that date, time, or event.
If you do one thing before doing something else, you do it earlier than the other thing.
If someone is before something, they are in front of it.
You use before when you are talking about time. For example, if something happened the day before a particular date or event, it happened during the previous day.
If someone has done something before, they have done it on a previous occasion. If someone has not done something before, they have never done it.
Before we could even go tell our mother and father, we began to fade away.

voca.title: before long
voca.explains:
Harry: Summer will be here before long.
I recently got lost when my GPS didn't work. The system couldn't detect a signal. I became disoriented. I tried to follow the road signs. However, they were in a different language. I couldn't make sense of them. Before long, it became very dark. I had to stop at a store to ask for directions.
One time, I was instant messaging a friend while on a bus. Before long, I had a bad case of motion sickness. I had a throbbing headache. My stomach was turning. To make things even worse, the traffic congestion was severe.
He cleaned the dust from the filters. He recharged the refrigerant. Before long, the air conditioner was a good as new. It was just a few days, but having no AC was the pits.

voca.title: before the alarm goes off
voca.explains:
I always set my alarm to 6 o’clock. I have done this for so long that I usually wake up just before the alarm goes off.
He was already up before the alarm went off.
We need to finish before the alarm goes off.

voca.title: before you know it
voca.explains:
The weather in the summer is hot and humid, so food can spoil before you know it. Recently, I bought some rice cakes. I wasn’t very hungry, so I just had a few and left the rest on the table. At room temperature, they went bad the next morning.
You'll get there before you know it.
Before we knew it, the parcel had arrived.

voca.title: beforehand
voca.explains:
If you do something beforehand, you do it earlier than a particular event.
Do some research beforehand, if you don't want to feel cheated.
Getting lost in unfamiliar settings can be frightening. Researching local transportation beforehand helps me not get lost.

They made the decision beforehand.

voca.title: beg

If you beg someone to do something, you ask them very anxiously or eagerly to do it.

You say 'I beg to differ' when you are politely emphasizing that you disagree with someone.
If you say that something is going begging, you mean that it is available but no one is using it or accepting it.
I became very seasick. I took some medicine, but it was too little too late. I emptied my stomach. I felt disoriented. I broke out in a cold sweat. I was all but begging to get off the boat. It was not a very enjoyable experience.

voca.title: beg off
voca.explains: to ask to be excused from something; to say that you cannot do something that you are expected or have promised to do\n

voca.title: beg the question
voca.means: 질문을 하게 만들다\n(사실이 아닐지도 모르는 일을) 단정짓다
voca.explains: make somebody want to ask a question that has not yet been answered\ntalk about something as if it were definitely true, even though it might not be\n

voca.title: beggar
voca.means:
[베거r]
거지, 걸인, 비렁뱅이
가난하게 만들다, 빈곤하게 하다
빈약하게 하다, 불가능하게 하다
voca.explains:
A beggar is someone who lives by asking people for money or food.
If something beggars a person, country, or organization, it makes them very poor.
If something beggars belief, it is impossible to believe it. If something beggars description, it is impossible to describe it.

voca.title: beggar belief
voca.explains: be too strange and unusual to be believed/described\n

voca.title: begin
voca.explains:
begin - began - begun
begin / start
To begin to do something means to start doing it.
When something begins or when you begin it, it takes place from a particular time onwards.
If you begin with something, or begin by doing something, this is the first thing you do.
You use begin to mention the first thing that someone says.
If one thing began as another, it first existed in the form of the second thing.
If you say that a thing or place begins somewhere, you are talking about one of its limits or edges.

voca.title: beginning
voca.explains:
The beginning of an event or process is the first part of it.
The beginnings of something are the signs or events which form the first part of it.
The beginning of a period of time is the time at which it starts.
The beginning of a piece of written material is the first words or sentences of it.
If you talk about the beginnings of a person, company, or group, you are referring to their backgrounds or origins.

voca.title: behalf
