voca.title: behave
voca.explains:
The way that you behave is the way that you do and say things, and the things that you do and say.
If you behave or behave yourself, you act in the way that people think is correct and proper.
In science, the way that something behaves is the things that it does.

voca.title: behaviour
voca.explains: People's or animals' behaviour is the way that they behave. You can refer to a typical and repeated way of behaving as a behaviour.\nIn science, the behaviour of something is the way that it behaves.\n

voca.title: behind
voca.means:
[비^하인d]
(위치가) 뒤에, 뒤의, 후방의
(어떤 사람의) 과거에
뒤에 숨은, 배후의
~의 뒤쪽에, 늦어서, 과거에, 숨겨진
voca.explains:
at the back / at the rear / behind
Your behind is the part of your body that you sit on.
If something is behind a thing or person, it is on the other side of them from you, or nearer their back rather than their front.
If you stay behind, you remain in a place after other people have gone.
When you shut a door or gate behind you, you shut it after you have gone through it.
"There's a whole article in today's paper about the book ban and an interview with the people behind it. I'll skip to the important part."

voca.title: behind schedule
voca.explains: I am terribly behind schedule.\n

voca.title: behold
voca.explains: If you behold someone or something, you see them.\n

voca.title: being
voca.explains:
Being is the present participle of be.
Being is used in non-finite clauses where you are giving the reason for something.
You can refer to any real or imaginary creature as a being.
Being is existence. Something that is in being or comes into being exists.
You can use being as to introduce a reason for what you are saying.

voca.title: belief
voca.means: [빌리-f]\n믿음, 신념, 생각, 소신\n(특히 종교적으로) 믿는 사항/믿음
voca.explains:
Belief is a feeling of certainty that something exists, is true, or is good.
Your religious or political beliefs are your views on religious or political matters.
If it is your belief that something is the case, it is your strong opinion that it is the case.
You use beyond belief to emphasize that something is true to a very great degree or that it happened to a very great degree.
You use contrary to popular belief to introduce a statement that is the opposite to what is thought to be true by most ordinary people.

voca.title: believe
voca.means:
[블뤼-v]
믿다, 
(무엇이 사실일 것으로, 가능하다고) 생각하다, 여기다
~라는 의견을 갖다, ~라고 믿다
voca.explains:
think / believe / feel / reckon / be under the impression / be of the opinion
If you believe that something is true, you think that it is true, but you are not sure.
If you believe someone or if you believe what they say or write, you accept that they are telling the truth.
If you believe in fairies, ghosts, or miracles, you are sure that they exist or happen. If you believe in a god, you are sure of the existence of that god.
If you believe in a way of life or an idea, you are in favour of it because you think it is good or right.
If you believe in someone or what they are doing, you have confidence in them and think that they will be successful.

voca.title: believe in
voca.explains:
to feel sure that somebody/something exists
to have confidence in somebody/something, to feel sure that they/it will be successful or achieve something
Arthur wandered outside to think some more. Why did sticking up for what you believe in have to be so difficult?

voca.title: believe in something
voca.explains: trust / depend on / rely on / count on / believe in\nto feel that something is right or valuable; to approve of something\n

voca.title: believe it or not
voca.explains: it is true, even though it does not sound likely\n

voca.title: believe me
voca.explains: used for emphasizing a statement, a promise or a threat\n

voca.title: bellow
voca.means: [벨로우]\n큰소리로 울다, 짖다, 고함치다\n울부짓기, 포효, 으르렁거리는 소리
voca.explains:
If someone bellows, they shout angrily in a loud, deep voice.
When a large animal such as a bull or an elephant bellows, it makes a loud and deep noise.
A bellows is or bellows are a device used for blowing air into a fire in order to make it burn more fiercely.

voca.title: bellow off
voca.means: ~을 호통을 쳐서 쫓아버리다, 말을 못하게 하다

voca.title: belly
voca.explains: The belly of a person or animal is their stomach or abdomen. In British English, this is an informal or literary use.\nIf a company goes belly up, it does not have enough money to pay its debts.\n

voca.title: bellyache
voca.explains:
Bellyache is a pain inside your abdomen, especially in your stomach.
If you say that someone is bellyaching, you mean they complain loudly and frequently about something and you think this is unreasonable or unjustified.
Harry: But you'll probably bellyache about it being too hot.

voca.title: belong
voca.means:
[빌^렁]
속하다, ~의 것이다, 
(어떤 상태에) 알맞다, 있어야 한다, 어울리다
(~에) 관계하고 있다
제자리에 있다, ~에 속하다, 소유이다
voca.explains:
If something belongs to you, you own it.
You say that something belongs to a particular person when you are guessing, discovering, or explaining that it was produced by or is part of that person.
If someone belongs to a particular group, they are a member of that group.
If something or someone belongs in or to a particular category, type, or group, they are of that category, type, or group.
If something belongs to a particular time, it comes from that time.
If you say that something belongs to someone, you mean that person has the right to it.
If you say that a time belongs to a particular system or way of doing something, you mean that that time is or will be characterized by it.
Who does it belong to?
It belongs to my mother.
I thought it belongs to you.

voca.title: belong to
voca.explains: There is a get-together for almost every group you belong to. You are likely to go party with your co-workers, friends, or members of a club or hobby group.\n

voca.title: belong to somebody
voca.explains:
to be the property of somebody; to be owned by somebody
if a time or an event belongs to a team, a group of people, etc., they are the most successful, popular or important
if a job, a duty, etc. belongs to you, it is your responsibility

voca.title: belong to something
voca.explains:
to be a member of something, for example a club, an organization or a family
to be part of a particular group or system
to be part of something or connected with a particular time or place

voca.title: belong with
voca.means: ~와 관계가 있다\n~의 자격이 있다, ~의 일원으로 적합하다

voca.title: belonging
voca.explains:
Please make sure all belongings are with you
I’m usually very alert and attentive. However, when it comes to my belongings, I can be a little scatterbrained. I have a knack for misplacing things.
Keep your belongings with you at all times.
We can keep your belongings here for a while.
Moving in Korea can be relatively painless. I hired professional movers to make the move easier. We took inventory of all my belongings and the movers packed them up in the boxes.

voca.title: beloved
voca.means: [빌러비d]\n총애 받는, 인기 많은, \n가장 사랑하는, 소중한, 애인, 연인
voca.explains: A beloved person, thing, or place is one that you feel great affection for.\nYour beloved is the person that you love.\n

voca.title: below
voca.explains:
If something is below something else, it is in a lower position.
If something is below a particular amount, rate, or level, it is less than that amount, rate, or level.
If someone is below you in an organization, they are lower in rank.
If something is below ground or below the ground, it is in the ground.
You use below in a piece of writing to refer to something that is mentioned later.

voca.title: bemuse
voca.means: [버뮤z]\n~을 멍하게 하다, 어리벙벙하게 하다, 생각에 잠기게 하다, \n~을 곤혹케 하다
voca.explains: If something bemuses you, it puzzles or confuses you.\n

voca.title: bench
voca.explains:
A bench is a long seat of wood or metal that two or more people can sit on.
A bench is a long, narrow table in a factory or laboratory.
In parliament, different groups sit on different benches. For example, the government sits on the government benches.
In a court of law, the bench is the judge or magistrates.

voca.title: bench warmer
voca.explains: At the moment, there are several Korean baseball players in MLB. That’s the most ever. The athletes are active in teams across the US. They are not bench warmers. They are not also-rans. They are star players.\n

voca.title: benchmark
voca.explains: A benchmark is something whose quality or quantity is known and which can therefore be used as a standard with which other things can be compared.\n

voca.title: bend
voca.means:
[벤d]
구부리다, 굽히다, 숙이다, 
(방향이) 구부러지다, 휘어지다, (방향을) 틀다, 휘다
굽히기, 구부러짐
voca.explains:
bend - bent - bent
When you bend, you move the top part of your body downwards and forwards. Plants and trees also bend.
When you bend your head, you move your head forwards and downwards.
When you bend a part of your body such as your arm or leg, or when it bends, you change its position so that it is no longer straight.
If you bend something that is flat or straight, you use force to make it curved or to put an angle in it.
When a road, beam of light, or other long thin thing bends, or when something bends it, it changes direction to form a curve or angle.
If someone bends to your wishes, they believe or do something different, usually when they do not want to.If you bend rules or laws, you interpret them in a way that allows you to do something they would not normally allow you to do.

voca.title: bend over
voca.means: 몸을 ~위로 굽히다\n(벌을 받기 위하여) 몸을 앞으로 숙이다\n쓸데없는 참견이다!
voca.explains: to lean over; to bend from the waist\n

voca.title: bend the rules
voca.explains: allow somebody to break the rules to some extent because you think there is a good reason\n

voca.title: bend the truth
voca.explains: say something that is not completely true\n

voca.title: beneath
voca.means:
[베니-쓰]
밑/아래에, 낮은 곳에, 바로 밑에
(수준 등이) ~보다 못한
~ 보다 낮은 곳에, ~의 바로 밑에. ~ 보다 낮게
voca.explains:
Something that is beneath another thing is under the other thing.
If you talk about what is beneath the surface of something, you are talking about the aspects of it which are hidden or not obvious.
If you say that someone or something is beneath you, you feel that they are not good enough for you or not suitable for you.
It says The gold doth lie beneath the whale's eye.
During the late Ice Age in Europe, they sometimes lived in caves beneath cliffs.
Not only was his body missing, but the fog beneath the bridge was moving in a wild, spinning whirl.

voca.title: benefit
voca.explains:
The benefit of something is the help that you get from it or the advantage that results from it.
If something is to your benefit or is of benefit to you, it helps you or improves your life.
If you have the benefit of some information, knowledge, or equipment, you are able to use it so that you can achieve something.
Benefit is money that is given by the government to people who are poor, ill, or unemployed.
A benefit, or a benefit concert or dinner, is an event that is held in order to raise money for a particular charity or person.
If you benefit from something or if it benefits you, it helps you or improves your life.
If you give someone the benefit of the doubt, you treat them as if they are telling the truth or as if they have behaved properly, even though you are not sure that this is the case.
A : Then which course offers the most benefits to you?
"Ah, here's what I was looking for."
He pulled out a clown costume. "Just what I need for this afternoon's children's hospital benefit."

voca.title: benefit from
voca.explains: I sometimes post reviews of my favorite eateries on social media. It’s not just to brag. It’s in the hopes that other people will be able to benefit from the information.\n

voca.title: benefit of doubt
voca.explains:
To believe someone even when you are unsure about their genuineness.
When Mary didn’t do her homework, the teacher didn’t give her the benefit of doubt and decided to punish her.
When she saw her husband talking over the phone very secretly, Samantha gave him the benefit of doubt rather than suspecting him.
Even though Sarah was unsure about the claims made by the anti-aging cream, she decided to give it the benefit of doubt and bought it.
Sally’s colleagues are tired of giving her the benefit of doubt whenever she calls in sick. They no longer believe it to be genuine.
While narrating her experience with ghosts, Juliet refused to believe it and didn’t bother giving her friend the benefit of doubt.
When mother realized that her daughter had developed the habit of smoking, she refused to listen to any justifications and didn’t give her daughter the benefit of doubt.
To save a few bucks, Michelle had to give the store keeper the benefit of doubt while buying her new phone from the grey market.
When the coach yelled at his team for no reason, they didn’t react as they knew he was disturbed about something and gave him the benefit of doubt that day.

voca.title: benign
voca.explains:
You use benign to describe someone who is kind, gentle, and harmless.
A benign substance or process does not have any harmful effects.
A benign tumour will not cause death or serious harm.
Benign conditions are pleasant or make it easy for something to happen.

voca.title: bent
voca.explains:
Bent is the past tense and past participle of bend.
If an object is bent, it is damaged and no longer has its correct shape.
If a person is bent, their body has become curved because of old age or disease.
If someone is bent on doing something, especially something harmful, they are determined to do it.
If you say that someone in a position of responsibility is bent, you mean that they are dishonest or do illegal things.
If you have a bent for something, you have a natural ability to do it or a natural interest in it.
One of its tail feathers was bent.

voca.title: bent over
voca.means: 몸을 ~위로 굽히다\n(벌을 받기 위하여) 몸을 앞으로 숙이다
voca.explains: to lean over; to bend from the waist\nHe bent over, and Annie climbed on piggyback.\n

voca.title: beside
voca.explains:
beside / besides
Something that is beside something else is at the side of it or next to it.
If you are beside yourself with anger or excitement, you are extremely angry or excited.
Beside the king sat a woman in a plain gray robe.

voca.title: beside the point
voca.explains: of no importance to the matter being discussed; irrelevant\nSome people like to put on luxurious hiking gear. To me, that seems beside the point.\n

voca.title: beside yourself with something
voca.means: (감정이 북받쳐) 어쩔 줄을 모르는, 제정신이 아닌

voca.title: besides
voca.means:
[비^사이z]
~ 외에, 
게다가, 그리고 또, 그밖에
또 다른 한가지는
voca.explains:
beside / besides
Besides something or beside something means in addition to it.
Besides is used to emphasize an additional point that you are making, especially one that you consider to be important.
"Besides, you were a vampire last Halloween."
His mother sighed. "putting off bad news doesn't make it get any better. And sometimes it makes it worse. Besides, Dad and I can't help you with a problem if we don't know you have one."
Arthur stood in front of the newly formed Crunch Bunch band. Besides Buster and Francine, it included Binky, Muffy, the Brain, Sue Ellen, Prunella, and Grandma Thora.
Arthur walked over to her. "Auditions are over, D.W. Besides, you don't even play an instrument."
I like helping my aunt. Besides she's not feeling well today.
What do you have to drink besides soda?

voca.title: best
voca.means:
[베st]
최상/최고의, 제일 좋은, 가장 알맞은/좋은, 최적의
가장, 가장 잘/알맞게
~을 이기다, ~보다 잘 하다
voca.explains:
Best is the superlative of good.
Best is the superlative of well.
The best is used to refer to things of the highest quality or standard.
Someone's best is the greatest effort or highest achievement or standard that they are capable of.
If you say that something is the best that can be done or hoped for, you think it is the most pleasant, successful, or useful thing that can be done or hoped for.
If you like something best or like it the best, you prefer it.
You use best of all to indicate that what you are about to mention is the thing that you prefer or that has most advantages out of all the things you have mentioned.

voca.title: best bet
voca.means: 가장 안전한 선택\n가장 안전하고 확실한 방책/수단\n가장 좋은 방법
voca.explains: When in doubt, bottled water is the best bet.\nIt’s important to know how to cherry-pick the right fruits. For instance, to determine the ripeness of a watermelon, your best bet is to tap the outside and listen for a hollow sound.\n

voca.title: best trait
voca.explains: I think I have a very unique personality. My best trait is that I have a strong sense of purpose. If I set a goal, I work diligently.\n

voca.title: bestow
voca.means: [비s토우]\n(특히 존경의 뜻으로) 수여하다, 주다, \n(시간 등)들이다, 쓰다
voca.explains: To bestow something on someone means to give or present it to them.\n

voca.title: bet
voca.explains:
If you bet on the result of a horse race, football game, or other event, you give someone a sum of money which they give you back with extra money if the result is what you predicted, or which they keep if it is not.
If someone is betting that something will happen, they are hoping or expecting that it will happen.
A bet is a sum of money which you give to someone when you bet.
You use expressions such as 'I bet', 'I'll bet', and 'you can bet' to indicate that you are sure something is true.

voca.title: betray
voca.means:
[빗^츄뤠이]
(적에게 정보를) 넘겨주다, 팔아먹다
~을 배신하다, 배반하다, 누설/폭로하다
(원칙 등을) 저버리다
(감정, 정보 등을) 무심코 노출시키다
voca.explains:
cheat / fool / deceive / betray / take in / trick / con
If you betray someone who loves or trusts you, your actions hurt and disappoint them.
If someone betrays their country or their friends, they give information to an enemy, putting their country's security or their friends' safety at risk.
If you betray an ideal or your principles, you say or do something which goes against those beliefs.
If you betray a feeling or quality, you show it without intending to.
On most days, I check the weather forecast on my phone. However, one time the forecast betrayed me.

voca.title: better
voca.means:
[^베러r]
더 좋은, 나은
더 잘하는, 더 알맞은, 
더 잘, 더 많이, 더 좋은
voca.explains:
If you like one thing better than another, you like it more.
If you are better after an illness or injury, you have recovered from it. If you feel better, you no longer feel so ill.
You use had better or 'd better when you are advising, warning, or threatening someone, or expressing an opinion about what should happen.
You can say that someone is better doing one thing than another, or it is better doing one thing than another, to advise someone about what they should do.
If something changes for the better, it improves.

voca.title: better and better
voca.explains: "And it just gets better and better." said D.W. She shook her head in time with the music.\n

voca.title: better known as
voca.explains: A while ago, I had conjunctivitis, better known as pink eye. I had blurred vision. My eyes turned bloodshot.\n

voca.title: better off
voca.explains: Les: Well I think the country will be better off with Republicans and Democrats sharing the power.\n

voca.title: better than
voca.explains: It is very popular expression when you’re comparing two different products or situations. So 'A is better than B’.\n

voca.title: between
voca.means:
[비^t위인-]
(위치가) 사이에, 중간에
(양, 수치가) 사이에, 가운데
(두 지점) 사이에 (놓인)
~끼리 힘을 모아
(여러 가지 다른 일과 함께) ~을 하느라
그 사이에(둘 이상의 지점, 물체, 날짜, 행사 등에 대해 씀)
voca.explains:
If something is between two things or is in between them, it has one of the things on one side of it and the other thing on the other side.
If people or things travel between two places, they travel regularly from one place to the other and back again.
A relationship, discussion, or difference between two people, groups, or things is one that involves them both or relates to them both.
If something stands between you and what you want, it prevents you from having it.
If something is between two amounts or ages, it is greater or older than the first one and smaller or younger than the second one.
If something happens between or in between two times or events, it happens after the first time or event and before the second one.

voca.title: between the two extremes
voca.explains: I am somewhere between the two extremes. I’m not a very snappy dresser, but I do like to be presentable. Therefore, the bulk of my clothes are tried-and-true classics. My outfits aren’t eye-catching, but they’re not out of place in any setting.\n

voca.title: bevel
voca.explains:
Also called : cant a surface that meets another at an angle other than a right angle Compare chamfer
Also, we did not bevel the edges nicely.
a bevel edge
to cut a bevel on (a piece of timber, etc)

voca.title: beverage
voca.explains: Beverages are drinks.\nThe flight attendants gave a safety demonstration. Soon, we took off. After a while, the attendants came by with the beverage cart. Later on, we had our in-flight meal.\n

voca.title: beware
voca.explains: If you tell someone to beware of a person or thing, you are warning them that the person or thing may harm them or be dangerous.\nEnjoy your journey! But beware-in the world of Merlin the magician, anything can happen…\n

voca.title: beware of
voca.explains: Yes, You must go alone. And beware of the samurai\n

voca.title: bewildered
voca.explains: If you are bewildered, you are very confused and cannot understand something or decide what you should do.\nThe king looked bewildered. "You found them-?"\n

voca.title: beyond
voca.means:
[비^얀-d]
~ 저편에/너머, 
(특정한 시간을) 지나/이후
~ 이상, (능력, 한계 등을) 넘어서는, 
~ 할 수 없는
건너편에, 그 너머에, 그 이후에
voca.explains:
If something is beyond a place or barrier, it is on the other side of it.
If something happens beyond a particular time or date, it continues after that time or date has passed.
If something extends beyond a particular thing, it affects or includes other things.
You use beyond to introduce an exception to what you are saying.
On a hillside beyond the meadow, red and purple flowers sparkled like bright buttons.
Her father thought for a moment. "As coach, I have to look beyond any one player's needs. I have to consider the whole team."

voca.title: beyond belief
voca.explains: (in a way that is) too great, difficult, etc. to be believed\n

voca.title: beyond measure
voca.explains: very much\n

voca.title: beyond recognition
voca.explains:
Just last week, I did the laundry. I put some sweaters in the washing machine. I made sure to use the gentle cycle. Despite my best efforts, the sweaters were ruined. They had shrunk beyond recognition. Next time, I will just entrust everything to the laundromat.
He gained so much weight that he is beyond recognition.
Your baby has grown beyond recognition.

voca.title: beyond repair
voca.explains:
Then, I smelled something burning. With a sinking sensation, I ran back to the kitchen. The room was filled with acrid smoke. The pot was burned beyond repair, to say nothing of the soup.
The car was crushed beyond repair.
The vase was broken beyond repaire.

voca.title: beyond reproach
voca.means: 나무랄 데 없는, 탓할 곳이 없는
voca.explains: Your behavior was beyond reproach.\n

voca.title: biased
voca.explains: If someone is biased, they prefer one group of people to another, and behave unfairly as a result. You can also say that a process or system is biased.\nIf something is biased towards one thing, it is more concerned with it than with other things.\n

voca.title: bib
voca.explains: A bib is a piece of cloth or plastic which is worn by very young children to protect their clothes while they are eating.\n

voca.title: bid
voca.means:
[^비d]
(특히 경매에서) 값을 부르다/제의하다
값을 매기다, 입찰하다, 말하다
가격제시, 호가
voca.explains:
A bid for something or a bid to do something is an attempt to obtain it or do it.
A bid is an offer to pay a particular amount of money for something that is being sold.
If you bid for something or bid to do something, you try to obtain it or do it.
If you bid for something that is being sold, you offer to pay a particular amount of money for it.

voca.title: bidder
voca.explains: A bidder is someone who offers to pay a certain amount of money for something that is being sold. If you sell something to the highest bidder, you sell it to the person who offers the most money for it\nA bidder for something is someone who is trying to obtain it or do it.\n

voca.title: bide
voca.means:
[바이d]
~ 을 기다리다
(부정문에서) ~을 견디다
살다, 머무르다, 기다리다, (어떤 상태가) 계속되다
voca.explains: If you bide your time, you wait for a good opportunity before doing something.\n

voca.title: big
voca.means:
[^비익]
(치수, 정도, 양 등이) 큰
나이가 더 많은, 성장한, 
(중요도가) 큰, 심각한, 
거대한, 거창한
열성적인
voca.explains:
big / large / great
A big person or thing is large in physical size.
Something that is big consists of many people or things.
If you describe something such as a problem, increase, or change as a big one, you mean it is great in degree, extent, or importance.
A big organization employs many people and has many customers.
If you say that someone is big in a particular organization, activity, or place, you mean that they have a lot of influence or authority in it.
If you call someone a big bully or a big coward, you are emphasizing your disapproval of them.
Children often refer to their older brother or sister as their big brother or sister.
Capital letters are sometimes referred to as big letters.
Big words are long or rare words which have meanings that are difficult to understand.

voca.title: big ask
voca.explains:
The washing machine we have at home is a huge time-saver. It really lessens the load of housework. Keeping a home in order is a big ask.
It's a big ask to finish so quickly.
I don't want to bother you with a big ask.

voca.title: big deal
voca.means: 큰일, \n(반어적, 비격식) 그게 무슨 대수라고!\n(역설적으로) 대단한 일, 대수로운 일
voca.explains:
used for suggesting that something is not as important or impressive as somebody else thinks it is
A smartphone costs a pretty penny. Losing it is a big deal. I’ve lost track of my phone several times. I’ve also lost my wallet occasionally. Sometimes it was even more upsetting because the lost wallet was a gift with sentimental value. One time, I lost my phone and wallet at the same time.
What's the big deal about the movie? I didn't like it.

voca.title: big family
voca.explains: On the first day of the long weekend, I will paying a visit to my parents. It will be a big family gathering, since my sister and her husband will also be there.\n

voca.title: big family gathering
voca.explains:
On the first day of the long weekend, I will paying a visit to my parents. It will be a big family gathering, since my sister and her husband will also be there.
There are many things to prepare for a big family gathering.
It was a big family gathering, so the house was full.

voca.title: big hassle
voca.explains:
Going to the bank used to be a big hassle. Now, I almost never have to go to the bank. Most stores accept credit cards or debit cards, so I don’t need a lot of cash.
The wallet was gone. A lot of important things were in that wallet. Credit cards, cash, coupons, photographs, you name it. I had no choice but to cancel all of the cards. I also had to visit the district office to get my ID re-issued. It was a big hassle.
Cooking is a big hassle compared to ordering in.
It won't be a big hassle if you start early.

voca.title: big hit
voca.explains: The show puts a new spin on songs that are already well-known to the public. These programs are all big hits these days.\n

voca.title: big mess
voca.explains: We flagged a waiter to ask what had happened. We found out our order hadn’t gone through. We had been served food that was ordered by another table. It was a big mess.\n

voca.title: big on
voca.explains: For a while, I was big on the stock market. I used a multi-pronged approach. I tried both short-term trading and long-term funds.\n

voca.title: big story
voca.explains: One of the biggest stories this year was the earthquake in September. It took place in Gyeongju. It had a magnitude of 5.8.\n

voca.title: big toe
voca.explains: Your big toe is the largest toe on your foot.\nI stubbed my toe. When I took my shoe off, my big toe was swollen. It took a long time to heal.\n

voca.title: big twist
voca.explains:
I liked the big twist at the end.
The last scen of "The Sixth Sense" is a big twist.
Her new mystery novel has many big twists.

voca.title: big-ticket
voca.explains: If you describe something as a big-ticket item, you mean that it costs a lot of money.\n

voca.title: big-ticket item
voca.explains: If you describe something as a big-ticket item, you mean that it costs a lot of money.\nWith the new bed, it's easier to get a good night's sleep. The bed is the second big-ticket item in our house.\n

voca.title: bilingual
voca.explains: Bilingual means involving or using two languages.\nSomeone who is bilingual can speak two languages equally well, usually because they learned both languages as a child.\n

voca.title: bill
voca.explains:
bill / statement / account / invoice / tab / check
A bill is a written statement of money that you owe for goods or services.
The bill in a restaurant is a piece of paper on which the price of the meal you have just eaten is written and which you are given before you pay.
A bill is a piece of paper money.
In government, a bill is a formal statement of a proposed new law that is discussed and then voted on.
The bill of a show or concert is a list of the entertainers who will take part in it.
If someone is billed to appear in a particular show, it has been advertised that they are going to be in it.
If you bill a person or event as a particular thing, you advertise them in a way that makes people think they have particular qualities or abilities.

voca.title: bill and coo
voca.explains: B : They were at the table billing and cooing like a pair of love birds.\n

voca.title: billed
voca.explains: ~billed combines with adjectives to indicate that a bird has a beak of a particular kind or appearance.\n

voca.title: billion
voca.explains: A billion is a thousand million.\nIf you talk about billions of people or things, you mean that there is a very large number of them but you do not know or do not want to say exactly how many.\n

voca.title: billow
voca.means:
[^빌로우]
(바람에) 부풀어 오르다,
(연기, 구름 등이) 피어 오르다
자욱하게 피어오르는 것
voca.explains:
When something made of cloth billows, it swells out and moves slowly in the wind.
When smoke or cloud billows, it moves slowly upwards or across the sky.
A billow of smoke or dust is a large mass of it rising slowly into the air.
The fire sizzled and smoke billowed up.
The red cloak billowed behind them.
The red cloak billowed around Jack and Annie, keeping them warm and safe.
He had silky feathers for hair, a beak for a nose, sharp claws, and a billowing feathered cape that glistened in the moonlight like shiny black armor.

voca.title: bin
voca.explains:
A bin is a container that you put rubbish in.
A bin is a container that you keep or store things in.
If you bin something, you throw it away.

voca.title: bind
voca.explains:
bind - bound - bound
If something binds people together, it makes them feel as if they are all part of the same group or have something in common.
If you are bound by something such as a rule, agreement, or restriction, you are forced or required to act in a certain way.
If you bind something or someone, you tie rope, string, tape, or other material around them so that they are held firmly.
When a book is bound, the pages are joined together and the cover is put on.

voca.title: bind off
voca.means: 중단시키다, 하나씩 빼다\n(혈액순환을) (붕대를 동여매) 멎게 하다
voca.explains: All the other animals bouned off.\n

voca.title: bind somebody over
voca.explains: to warn somebody that they will have to appear in court if they break the law again\n

voca.title: bio
voca.explains: short for biography\nBio- is used at the beginning of nouns and adjectives that refer to life or to the study of living things.\n

voca.title: biography
voca.explains: A biography of someone is an account of their life, written by someone else.\nBiography is the branch of literature which deals with accounts of people's lives.\n

voca.title: biomass
voca.explains: the total number of living organisms in a given area, expressed in terms of living or dry weight per unit area\nvegetable matter used as a source of energy\n

voca.title: bird
voca.explains: A bird is a creature with feathers and wings. Female birds lay eggs. Most birds can fly.\nSome men refer to young women as birds. This use could cause offence.\n

voca.title: bird's-eye view
voca.explains: The view also happens to be breathtaking during the fall season. You will be blown away. I guarantee that it will live up to your expectations. If you want a bird’s-eye view of the capital city, you’ve got to check out Namsan.\n

voca.title: birdsong
voca.explains: Birdsong is the sound of a bird or birds calling in a way which sounds musical.\n

voca.title: birth
voca.explains:
When a baby is born, you refer to this event as his or her birth.
You can refer to the beginning or origin of something as its birth.
Some people talk about a person's birth when they are referring to the social position of the person's family.

voca.title: birth certificate
voca.explains: Your birth certificate is an official document which gives details of your birth, such as the date and place of your birth, and the names of your parents.\n

voca.title: birthday
voca.explains: Your birthday is the anniversary of the date on which you were born.\n

voca.title: birthrate
voca.explains: The birth rate in a place is the number of babies born there for every 1000 people during a particular period of time\nKorea ranks near the bottom in the world for birthrate. There are many reasons.\n

voca.title: bison
voca.explains: A bison is a large hairy animal with a large head that is a member of the cattle family. They used to be very common in North America and Europe.\n

voca.title: bit
voca.explains:
A bit of something is a small amount of it.
A bit of something is a small part or section of it.
A bit of something is a small piece of it.
You can use bit to refer to a particular item or to one of a group or set of things. For example, a bit of information is an item of information.
In computing, a bit is the smallest unit of information that is held in a computer's memory. It is either 1 or 0. Several bits form a byte.

voca.title: bit by bit
voca.explains: a small amount at a time; gradually\n

voca.title: bite
voca.means: [바잇t]\n(이빨로) 물다/베어물다, ~을 물다\n물기, 한 입(베어문 조각), 소량의 음식
voca.explains:
bite - bit - bitten
If you bite something, you use your teeth to cut into it, for example in order to eat it or break it. If an animal or person bites you, they use their teeth to hurt or injure you.
If a snake or a small insect bites you, it makes a mark or hole in your skin, and often causes the surrounding area of your skin to become painful or itchy.
When an action or policy begins to bite, it begins to have a serious or harmful effect.
If an object bites into a surface, it presses hard against it or cuts into it.
A bite of something, especially food, is the action of biting it.
If you have a bite to eat, you have a small meal or a snack.

voca.title: bite back
voca.explains: to react when somebody has harmed you and try to harm or criticize them\n

voca.title: bite into something
voca.explains: to cut or press into the surface of something\nto have an unpleasant effect on something, especially by making it smaller\n

voca.title: bite one's lip
voca.means: (고통, 노여움·웃음 따위를 참기 위하여) 입술을 깨물다, 꾹 참다\n입술을 깨물다, 감정을 억누르다
voca.explains: Muffy bit her lip.\n

voca.title: bite something back
voca.explains: to stop yourself from saying something or from showing how you feel\n

voca.title: bite the bullet
voca.means: (하기는 싫지만 피할 수는 없는 일을) 이를 악물고 하다\n큰 결심을 하다, 결단을 내리다
voca.explains: realize that you cannot avoid something unpleasant, and so accept it\nAll the houses that I liked were out of my league. I put in the footwork, visiting various candidates. I arrived at the conclusion that I needed a bank loan. I bit the bullet and went to the bank. I was able to receive a loan at a low interest rate.\n

voca.title: bite the dust
voca.explains: fail, or be defeated or destroyed\n

voca.title: bite your lip
voca.explains: force yourself not to express the negative emotions that you are feeling\n

voca.title: bite your tongue
voca.explains: stop yourself from saying something that might upset somebody or cause an argument, although you want to speak\n

voca.title: bits of
voca.explains: They also get in the way when I eat. Bits of food always get stuck in the wires.\n

voca.title: bitter
voca.means:
[비러r]
쓴맛, 괴로움, 격렬한,
쓴, 견디기 어려운, 혹독한
몹시, 심하게, 혹독한, 매서운
voca.explains:
bitter / pungent / sour / acrid / sharp / acid
In a bitter argument or conflict, people argue very angrily or fight very fiercely.
If someone is bitter after a disappointing experience or after being treated unfairly, they continue to feel angry about it.
A bitter experience makes you feel very disappointed. You can also use bitter to emphasize feelings of disappointment.
Bitter weather, or a bitter wind, is extremely cold.
A bitter taste is sharp, not sweet, and often slightly unpleasant.
Bitter is a kind of beer that is light brown in colour.
If you say that you will continue doing something to the bitter end, especially something difficult or unpleasant, you are emphasizing that you will continue doing it until it is completely finished.

voca.title: bitter chill
voca.explains: A bitter chill crept over the room.\n

voca.title: bitterly
voca.explains: You use bitterly when you are describing an attitude which involves strong, unpleasant emotions such as anger or dislike.\n

voca.title: bittersweet
voca.means: [비러rs윗t]\n고통이 섞인 쾌감\n쓰고도 단, 달콤 쌉쌀한, 시원섭섭한
voca.explains: If you describe an experience as bittersweet, you mean that it has some happy aspects and some sad ones.\nA bittersweet taste seems bitter and sweet at the same time.\n

voca.title: bizarre
voca.explains:
Something that is bizarre is very odd and strange.
Staring at the bizarre creature, Jack remembered the story of the Raven King-how the king had wanted to be a bird, how he had stolen a spell from the Wizard of Winter, how the spell had worked only halfway and left him half bird and half human.
B : I'm disappointed with the movie. I mean, the story somewhat bizarre.

voca.title: blabber
voca.explains:
a person who blabs
idle chatter
to talk without thinking; chatter

voca.title: black
voca.explains:
Something that is black is of the darkest colour that there is, the colour of the sky at night when there is no light at all.
A black person belongs to a race of people with dark skins, especially a race from Africa.
Black coffee or tea has no milk or cream added to it.
If you describe a situation as black, you are emphasizing that it is very bad indeed.
If someone is in a black mood, they feel very miserable and depressed.
Black humour involves jokes about sad or difficult situations.
People who believe in black magic believe that it is possible to communicate with evil spirits.
Black people are sometimes referred to as blacks. This use could cause offence.

voca.title: black and tan
voca.means: 검정 바탕에 갈색 얼룩인\n백인과 흑인이 출입하는\n흑백 혼혈인

voca.title: black out
voca.explains: to become unconscious or lose your memory for a short time\n

voca.title: black something out
voca.means: ~을 깜깜하게 만들다\n(보도 통제로 기사, 방송을) 검게 지우다, 보이지 않게 하다
voca.explains: to turn out lights completely or cover windows, etc. so that light cannot be seen from outside\n

voca.title: blackboard
voca.explains: A blackboard is a dark-coloured board that you can write on with chalk. Blackboards are often used by teachers in the classroom.\n

voca.title: blacken
voca.explains:
burn / char / blacken / scald / scorch / singe
To blacken something means to make it black or very dark in colour. Something that blackens becomes black or very dark in colour.
If someone blackens your character, they make other people believe that you are a bad person.

voca.title: blackness
voca.explains: Blackness is the state of being very dark.\nHe kept going deeper into the smelly blackness.\n

voca.title: blackout
voca.means:
[^블랙아웃t]
정전, 
(정부, 경찰에 의한) 보도 통제/정지
등화관제, 일시적인 기억/의식 상실
voca.explains:
A blackout is a period of time during a war in which towns and buildings are made dark so that they cannot be seen by enemy planes.
If a blackout is imposed on a particular piece of news, journalists are prevented from broadcasting or publishing it.
If there is a power blackout, the electricity supply to a place is temporarily cut off.
If you have a blackout, you temporarily lose consciousness.
We had a blackout at the office.
Blackouts aren't common anymore.

voca.title: blacksmith
voca.explains: A blacksmith is a person whose job is making things by hand out of metal that has been heated to a high temperature.\nA blacksmith was pounding his anvil.\n

voca.title: bladder
voca.explains: Your bladder is the part of your body where urine is stored until it leaves your body.\n

voca.title: blade
voca.means: [블레이d]\n(칼 등의) 날, 칼날, 검, 다리, 날개
voca.explains:
The blade of a knife, axe, or saw is the edge, which is used for cutting.
The blades of a propeller are the long, flat parts that turn round.
The blade of an oar is the thin flat part that you put into the water.
A blade of grass is a single piece of grass.

voca.title: blame
voca.means:
[블^레임]
~을 탓하다, 비난하다, 나무라다
(~에게) 책임지우다, ~의 탓으로 돌리다
비난, 책망
책임, 탓
voca.explains:
If you blame a person or thing for something bad, you believe or say that they are responsible for it or that they caused it.
If you say that you do not blame someone for doing something, you mean that you consider it was a reasonable thing to do in the circumstances.
The blame for something bad that has happened is the responsibility for causing it or letting it happen.
If someone is to blame for something bad that has happened, they are responsible for causing it.
He blamed magic for all of Camelot's woes.
B : It can happen. Don't blame her.
"Don't blame other people for disappointing you, Blame yourself for expecting too much from them"
I love my car, so I baby it a lot. However, one time I grazed the bumper while I was parking. I had nobody to blame. I had simply misjudged the angle.
I have been tossing and turning at night for quite some time. I blame my stress levels hitting an all-time high.
She blamed me for spilling the coffee but I didn't do it.

voca.title: blank
voca.means:
[블^뤵k]
(글자가 없는) 빈, 녹음 되지 않은, 
멍한, 무표정한, 
공백, 빈터, 공란
~을 보이지 않게 하다
voca.explains:
Something that is blank has nothing on it.
If you look blank, your face shows no feeling, understanding, or interest.
A blank is a space which is left in a piece of writing or on a printed form for you to fill in particular information.
If your mind or memory is a blank, you cannot think of anything or remember anything.
Blanks are gun cartridges which contain explosive but do not contain a bullet, so that they cause no harm when the gun is fired.
If you draw a blank when you are looking for someone or something, you do not succeed in finding them.
If your mind goes blank, you are suddenly unable to think of anything appropriate to say, for example in reply to a question.

voca.title: blank out
voca.explains: if you blank out or your mind blanks out, you cannot remember anything or you become confused\n

voca.title: blank something out
voca.means: ~을 (안 보이게) 지우다, 가리다\n(불쾌한 것을) 머리 속에서 지워 버리다
voca.explains: to deliberately forget something unpleasant\nto cover something written or printed, for example, with black ink so that it cannot be read\n

voca.title: blanket
voca.means:
[블^랭켓t]
담요, 모포
포관적인, 일괄적인, 전면적인
~을 담요로 덮다, (완전히) 뒤집다
voca.explains:
A blanket is a large square or rectangular piece of thick cloth, especially one which you put on a bed to keep you warm.
A blanket of something such as snow is a continuous layer of it which hides what is below or beyond it.
If something such as snow blankets an area, it covers it.
You use blanket to describe something when you want to emphasize that it affects or refers to every person or thing in a group, without any exceptions.
Kate turned in her sleep, and her blanket slipped off her.

voca.title: blankly
voca.explains: Arthur looked at his friend blankly.\n

voca.title: blast
voca.means:
[블^뤠-st]
폭발, (훅 밀려드는 한줄기의) 강한 바람/공기
(악기, 호각, 경적 등이) 빵/삑 하는 소리
맹비난/비평, 
폭발시키다, 폭발/발파하다
(특히 음악이) 쾅쾅 울리다
voca.explains:
A blast is a big explosion, especially one caused by a bomb.
If something is blasted into a particular place or state, an explosion causes it to be in that place or state. If a hole is blasted in something, it is created by an explosion.
If workers are blasting rock, they are using explosives to make holes in it or destroy it, for example so that a road or tunnel can be built.
To blast someone means to shoot them with a gun.
If someone blasts their way somewhere, they get there by shooting at people or causing an explosion.
If something blasts water or air somewhere, it sends out a sudden, powerful stream of it.
He felt a blast of heat.

voca.title: blast away
voca.explains: if a gun or somebody using a gun blasts away, the gun fires loudly and continuously\n

voca.title: blast off
voca.explains: when a spacecraft blasts off, it leaves the ground and goes up into space\n

voca.title: blaze
voca.means:
[블^레이-z]
활활 타다, 눈부시게 빛나다, 
(화가 나서 눈이) 이글거리다
(총이) 불을 뿜다, (총을) 쏘아대다
(대형) 화재, 불길, 걷잡을 수 없는 (감정)
voca.explains:
When a fire blazes, it burns strongly and brightly.
If something blazes with light or colour, it is extremely bright.
If guns blaze, or blaze away, they fire continuously, making a lot of noise.
A blaze is a large fire which is difficult to control and which destroys a lot of things.
A blaze of publicity or attention is a great amount of it.
The fire blazed with leaping purple flames.
A fire blazed in the hearth.
There was a mighty roar, a blast of heat, and a blaze of light!
Buster crouched down in a batting stance. "It's just you and the pitcher. Nothing else matters. You raise your bat. Ready. Waiting. The pitch blazes in. You can feel the heat as the ball passes by."

voca.title: blaze up
voca.explains: if a fire blazes up, it suddenly starts burning more strongly\n

voca.title: bleach
voca.explains:
If you bleach something, you use a chemical to make it white or pale in colour.
If the sun bleaches something, or something bleaches, its colour gets paler until it is almost white.
Bleach is a chemical that is used to make cloth white, or to clean things thoroughly and kill germs.

voca.title: bleachers
voca.explains: The bleachers are a part of an outdoor sports stadium, or the seats in that area, which are usually uncovered and are the least expensive place where people can sit.\nHis parents cheered from the bleachers.\n

voca.title: bleak
voca.explains:
If a situation is bleak, it is bad, and seems unlikely to improve.
If you describe a place as bleak, you mean that it looks cold, empty, and unattractive.
When the weather is bleak, it is cold, dull, and unpleasant.
If someone looks or sounds bleak, they look or sound depressed, as if they have no hope or energy.
How do you come to be in Camelot on this bleak night?

voca.title: bleed
voca.explains:
bleed - bled - bled
When you bleed, you lose blood from your body as a result of injury or illness.
If the colour of one substance bleeds into the colour of another substance that it is touching, it goes into the other thing so that its colour changes in an undesirable way.
If someone is being bled, money or other resources are gradually being taken away from them.
Well, can't you see I'm bleeding now? I think taking me to the hospital is a good idea!

voca.title: bleeding
voca.explains: Bleeding is used by some people to emphasize what they are saying, especially when they feel strongly about something or dislike something.\n

voca.title: blend
voca.means:
[블렌-d]
섞다, 혼합하다, 섞이다,
(보기 좋게) 조합하다, 
혼합하여 만들다, 블렌드하다
(같은 물질에 속하는 여러 종류의) 혼합, 조합
voca.explains:
mix / stir / mingle / blend
If you blend substances together or if they blend, you mix them together so that they become one substance.
When colours, sounds, or styles blend, they come together or are combined in a pleasing way.
If you blend ideas, policies, or styles, you use them together in order to achieve something.
A blend of things is a mixture or combination of them that is useful or pleasant.
The hula is a blend of dancing and chanting poetry.

voca.title: blend in
voca.explains: if something blends in with something else or with its surroundings, it looks similar to it/them or matches well\n

voca.title: blend into
voca.explains: to look or sound so similar to something that it is difficult for anyone to see or hear it\n

voca.title: blend something in
voca.explains: to add another substance to something and mix them together\n

voca.title: blender
voca.explains: A blender is an electrical kitchen appliance used for mixing liquids and soft foods together or turning fruit or vegetables into liquid.\n

voca.title: bless
voca.explains:
When someone such as a priest blesses people or things, he asks for God's favour and protection for them.
Bless is used in expressions such as 'God bless' or 'bless you' to express affection, thanks, or good wishes.
You can say 'bless you' to someone who has just sneezed.

voca.title: blessing in disguise
voca.explains: Through trial and error, I have come to terms with the fact that I am also allergic to alcohol. This is a blessing in disguise as no one makes me drink at company dinners anymore.\n

voca.title: blind
voca.means:
[블라인d]
눈멀게 하다, 보이지 않게 하다, 어둡게 하다
눈먼, 이해하지 않는, 
맹목적인, 무작정, 무모하게
voca.explains:
blind / blindly
Someone who is blind is unable to see because their eyes are damaged.
If you are blind with something such as tears or a bright light, you are unable to see for a short time because of the tears or light.
If you say that someone is blind to a fact or a situation, you mean that they ignore it or are unaware of it, although you think that they should take notice of it or be aware of it.
You can describe someone's beliefs or actions as blind when you think that they seem to take no notice of important facts or behave in an unreasonable way.
A blind corner is one that you cannot see round because something is blocking your view.
If something blinds you, it makes you unable to see, either for a short time or permanently.

voca.title: blind date
voca.explains: A blind date is an arrangement made for you to spend a romantic evening with someone you have never met before.\n

voca.title: blind drunk
voca.explains: extremely drunk\n

voca.title: blindfold
voca.explains:
A blindfold is a strip of cloth that is tied over someone's eyes so that they cannot see.
If you blindfold someone, you tie a blindfold over their eyes.
If someone does something blindfold, they do it while wearing a blindfold.
If you say that you can do something blindfold, you are emphasizing that you can do it easily, for example because you have done it many times before.
I could get there blindfolded with one hand tied behind my back.

voca.title: blinding
voca.means: [블라인딩]\n눈이 부신, 눈을 뜰 수 없을 정도인\n아주 좋은/즐거운
voca.explains:
A blinding light is extremely bright.
You use blinding to emphasize that something is very obvious.
Blinding pain is very strong pain.

voca.title: blindly
voca.explains: blind / blindly\nIf you say that someone does something blindly, you mean that they do it without having enough information, or without thinking about it.\n

voca.title: blink
voca.explains: When you blink or when you blink your eyes, you shut your eyes and very quickly open them again.\nWhen a light blinks, it flashes on and off.\n

voca.title: bliss
voca.explains: Bliss is a state of complete happiness.\n

voca.title: blissful
voca.explains:
happy / satisfied / content / contented / joyful / blissful
A blissful situation or period of time is one in which you are extremely happy.
If someone is in blissful ignorance of something unpleasant or serious, they are totally unaware of it.
As a newlywed, marriage was a blissful time for me. However, there was one unforeseen drawback. I started to gain weight.

voca.title: blister
voca.explains: A blister is a painful swelling on the surface of your skin. Blisters contain a clear liquid and are usually caused by heat or by something repeatedly rubbing your skin.\nWhen your skin blisters or when something blisters it, blisters appear on it.\n

voca.title: blizzard
voca.explains: A blizzard is a very bad snowstorm with strong winds.\n

voca.title: block
voca.means:
[블락k]
(단단한) 사각형 덩어리, (건물) 단지, 구역, 블록, 
(지나가지 못하게) 막다, 차단하다, 
방해하다, 저지하다,
voca.explains:
building / property / premises / complex / structure / block / edifice
A block of flats or offices is a large building containing them.
A block in a town is an area of land with streets on all its sides.
A block of a substance is a large rectangular piece of it.
A block of something such as tickets or shares is a large quantity of them, especially when they are all sold at the same time and are in a particular sequence or order.
If you have a mental block or a block, you are temporarily unable to do something that you can normally do which involves using, thinking about, or remembering something.
To block a road, channel, or pipe means to put an object across it or in it so that nothing can pass through it or along it.
If something blocks your view, it prevents you from seeing something because it is between you and that thing.
If you block someone's way, you prevent them from going somewhere or entering a place by standing in front of them.

voca.title: block something in
voca.explains: to stop a vehicle from being driven away by parking too close to it\n

voca.title: block something off
voca.explains: to close a road or another place by placing a barrier across it to stop somebody/something going in or coming out\nto reserve a period of time for a particular activity\n

voca.title: block something up
voca.explains: to fill something such as a hole completely so that nothing can get through it\n

voca.title: blockage
voca.means: [블^럭-케이지]\n(흐름을) 막는 것, 장애(물), 학힌 상태\n막힌 상태, 폐색
voca.explains: A blockage in a pipe, tube, or tunnel is an object which blocks it, or the state of being blocked.\nI did an Internet search for some home remedies. A post showed how to bend a clothes hanger into a hook. You can then use it to get at the blockage.\n

voca.title: blood
voca.explains:
Blood is the red liquid that flows inside your body, which you can see if you cut yourself.
You can use blood to refer to the race or social class of someone's parents or ancestors.
If you say that there is bad blood between people, you mean that they have argued about something and dislike each other.
If you say that something makes your blood boil, you are emphasizing that it makes you very angry.
If something violent and cruel is done in cold blood, it is done deliberately and in an unemotional way.
If you say that something makes your blood run cold or makes your blood freeze, you mean that it makes you feel very frightened.
"I told you our blood would boil if we went out there" he said.

voca.title: blood bank
voca.explains: A blood bank is a place where blood which has been taken from blood donors is stored until it is needed for people in hospital.\nThe last time I donated was last week. I visited a local blood bank. When I got there, I filled out a form with my personal information. A nurse took a blood sample for a simple test.\n

voca.title: blood donor's certificate
voca.explains:
After I was finished, I was given a light snack and some movie tickets. I also received a blood donor’s certificate.
I have a blood donor's certificate in my wallet.
You can receive blood sooner if you have a blood donor's certificate.

voca.title: blood group
voca.explains: Someone's blood group is the type of blood that they have in their body. There are four main types: A, B, AB, and O\n

voca.title: blood pressure
voca.explains: Your blood pressure is the amount of force with which your blood flows around your body.\nThe check-up got under way with simple measurements. Members of the staff measured my height, weight, eyesight, blood pressure and lung capacity. A nurse drew some blood.\n

voca.title: blood sugar
voca.explains: the glucose concentration in the blood: the normal fasting value is between 3.9 and 5.6 mmol/l\n

voca.title: blood type
voca.explains: Someone's blood type is the same as their blood group.\nMany people in Korea believe that a person’s personality is determined by their blood type. This idea includes all blood types: A, B, AB and O.\n

voca.title: bloodshot
voca.explains: If your eyes are bloodshot, the parts that are usually white are red or pink. Your eyes can be bloodshot for a variety of reasons, for example because you are tired or you have drunk too much alcohol.\n

voca.title: bloom
voca.explains:
A bloom is the flower on a plant.
If something such as someone's skin has a bloom, it has a fresh and healthy appearance.
A plant or tree that is in bloom has flowers on it.
When a plant or tree blooms, it produces flowers. When a flower blooms, it opens.
If someone or something blooms, they develop good, attractive, or successful qualities.

voca.title: blooper
voca.explains: A blooper is a silly mistake.\nFern was the next batter. She hit a blooper to right field, advancing Sue Ellen to second.\n

voca.title: blossom
voca.explains:
Blossom is the flowers that appear on a tree before the fruit.
If someone or something blossoms, they develop good, attractive, or successful qualities.
When a tree blossoms, it produces blossom.

voca.title: blot
voca.explains:
If something is a blot on a person's or thing's reputation, it spoils their reputation.
A blot is a drop of liquid that has fallen on to a surface and has dried.
If you blot a surface, you remove liquid from it by pressing a piece of soft paper or cloth onto it.
If you describe something such as a building as a blot on the landscape, you mean that you think it is very ugly and spoils an otherwise attractive place.

voca.title: blot something out
voca.means: ~을 완전히 덮다, 가리다\n(안 좋은 기억, 생각을) 애써 잊다
voca.explains: to stop light or noise coming in; to cover or hide something\n

voca.title: blotchy
voca.explains: Something that is blotchy has blotches on it.\nMost people look flushed after a few drinks but my Asian glow is on another level. Even my neck and arms turn blotchy and red.\n

voca.title: blouse
voca.explains: A blouse is a kind of shirt worn by a girl or woman.\nSophie: Hey, look at me! I think I look great in this blouse. What do you think?\n

voca.title: blow
voca.means:
[^블로우]
(입으로) 불다, 
(바람이) 불다, 바람에 날리다
(폭탄으로) 날려버리다, 폭파하다
(기회를) 날리다
강타, 타격, 정신적 타격
(슬픔, 절망을 가져온) 충격
voca.explains:
blow - blew - blown
When a wind or breeze blows, the air moves.
If the wind blows something somewhere or if it blows there, the wind moves it there.
If you blow, you send out a stream of air from your mouth.
If you blow something somewhere, you move it by sending out a stream of air from your mouth.
If you blow bubbles or smoke rings, you make them by blowing air out of your mouth through liquid or smoke.
When a whistle or horn blows or someone blows it, they make a sound by blowing into it.
When you blow your nose, you force air out of it through your nostrils in order to clear it.
Her white hair blew in the wind.

voca.title: blow off
voca.explains: to permit (a gas under pressure, esp steam) to be released\n"I'll hold on to the hood so it won't blow off," she said.\n

voca.title: blow off something
voca.explains:
In retrospect, the lights flickered on and off for a few days prior to the incident. However, I ignored the red flag and blew off the responsibility until the very last minute.
I'm going to sleep in and blow off my meeting today.
We are leaning towards blowing off all our plans for the day.

voca.title: blow one's mind
voca.means: ~를 깜짝 놀래키다\n흥분하여 어쩔 줄 모르다\n(마약으로) 환각에 빠지다
voca.explains: His mind was blown when his wife told him she wanted a divorce.\n

voca.title: blow one's nose
voca.explains:
My nose was stuffy and I had to blow my nose all day. It was hard to breathe.
I blew my nose so many times today.
It's impolite to blow your nose at the table.

voca.title: blow out
voca.means: (불꽃이 바람 등에) 꺼지다\n(유정, 가스층이 기름이나 가스를) 내뿜다
voca.explains:
if a flame blows out or somebody/something blows it out, it is put out by the wind or some air
if a window blows out, or an explosion, etc. blows it out, the force makes it fall out
(in surfing) if the waves blow out or the wind blows out the waves, they become too low for surfing in a particular place
He blew out a puff of air, then broke into a leaping run.
He blew out a frosty puff of air, then leaped away, vanishing into the mist.
After taking a shower in the pitch-black darkness, I twisted out the bulb from the socket to change the lightbulb. Unfortunately, I blew out the fuse. The sudden flash of light scared the life out of me.

voca.title: blow up
voca.means: 폭파하다, 터뜨리다, \n거세지다/고조되다\n~을 위로 불다, 화내다, 과장하다
voca.explains:
explode / blow up / go off / burst / erupt / rupture / implode
to explode; to be destroyed by an explosion
to start suddenly and with force
(informal) (at somebody) to become very angry
(slang) to become very successful or popular

voca.title: bluish
voca.explains: Something that is bluish is slightly blue in colour.\n

voca.title: blunt
voca.explains:
honest / frank / direct / open / outspoken / straight / blunt
If you are blunt, you say exactly what you think without trying to be polite.
A blunt object has a rounded or flat end rather than a sharp one.
A blunt knife or blade is no longer sharp and does not cut well.
If something blunts an emotion, a feeling or a need, it weakens it.

voca.title: blur
voca.means:
[^블러r]
흐릿한 형체, (기억이) 희미한, 흐릿한 것
흐릿해지다, 흐릿하게 만들다
모호해지다, 모호하게 만들다
voca.explains:
A blur is a shape or area which you cannot see clearly because it has no distinct outline or because it is moving very fast.
When a thing blurs or when something blurs it, you cannot see it clearly because its edges are no longer distinct.
If something blurs an idea or a distinction between things, that idea or distinction no longer seems clear.
If your vision blurs, or if something blurs it, you cannot see things clearly.
He peeked through a crack in the barrel and saw a blur of cowboys and horses go by.
A blur of people gathered around him and Annie.

voca.title: blurry
voca.explains: A blurry shape is one that has an unclear outline.\nWell, my vision has gotten blurry and I can't see well at night.\n

voca.title: blurt
voca.explains: call / cry out / exclaim / blurt / burst out\nIf someone blurts something, they say it suddenly, after trying hard to keep quiet or to keep it secret.\n

voca.title: blush
voca.means:
[블롸쉬]
얼굴을 붉히다, 얼굴이 빨개지다
~에 부끄러워하다, 당황하다
(당황하거나 수치스러워) 얼굴이 붉어짐
voca.explains: When you blush, your face becomes redder than usual because you are ashamed or embarrassed.\n

voca.title: board
voca.means:
[^보r-d]
판자, 게시판, 위원회, 이사회
(탈것에) 타다, 승선/승차/탑승하다
하숙하다, 학교 기숙사에서 살다
voca.explains:
A board is a flat, thin, rectangular piece of wood or plastic which is used for a particular purpose.
A board is a square piece of wood or stiff cardboard that you use for playing games such as chess.
You can refer to a blackboard or a noticeboard as a board.
Boards are long flat pieces of wood which are used, for example, to make floors or walls.
The board of a company or organization is the group of people who control it and direct it.
Board is used in the names of various organizations which are involved in dealing with a particular kind of activity.
Board is the food which is provided when you stay somewhere, for example in a hotel.
For my vacation last summer, I went to Thailand. I boarded the plane and found my way to my seat. I put my carry-on suitcase in the overhead compartment.

voca.title: board something up
voca.explains: to cover a window or a door with boards\n

voca.title: boast
voca.explains:
If someone boasts about something that they have done or that they own, they talk about it very proudly, in a way that other people may find irritating or offensive.
If someone or something can boast a particular achievement or possession, they have achieved or possess that thing.
Keep in mind that some mountains are more challenging to travel on foot. Of course, you can go at your own pace. Undoubtedly, chiaksan boasts one of the most difficult trails. Seoraksan is a favorite amongst novice mountaineers.

voca.title: bob
voca.means:
[바압]
(특히 물 위에서) 깐닥거리다, 까닥거리다
단발머리를 자르다
(머리, 몸을) 까닥거림, 단발머리
voca.explains:
If something bobs, it moves up and down, like something does when it is floating on water.
If you bob somewhere, you move there quickly so that you disappear from view or come into view.
When you bob your head, you move it quickly up and down once, for example when you greet someone.
A bob is a fairly short hair style for women in which the hair is the same length all the way round, except for the front.
It bobbed up and down.

voca.title: bob up
voca.explains:
to come to the surface quickly
to appear suddenly
When his head bobbed up above the water, he choked and coughed.

voca.title: bobbed
voca.explains: If a woman's hair is bobbed, it is cut in a bob.\n

voca.title: bodily
voca.explains: Your bodily needs and functions are the needs and functions of your body.\nYou use bodily to indicate that an action involves the whole of someone's body.\n

voca.title: body
voca.means:
[봐듸]
몸, 신체, (머리 팔 다리를 제외한) 몸통
(인간, 동물의) 사체, 시체
많은 양/모음, 물체,
voca.explains:
Your body is all your physical parts, including your head, arms, and legs.
You can also refer to the main part of your body, except for your arms, head, and legs, as your body.
You can refer to a person's dead body as a body.
A body is an organized group of people who deal with something officially.
A body of people is a group of people who are together or who are connected in some way.
The body of something such as a building or a document is the main part of it or the largest part of it.

voca.title: body and soul
voca.explains: physically and mentally; completely\n

voca.title: bogeyman
voca.means: [^부긔맨]\n(아이들에게 겁을 줄 때 들먹이는) 귀신, 부기맨
voca.explains: A bogeyman is someone whose ideas or actions are disapproved of by some people, and who is described by them as evil or unpleasant in order to make other people afraid.\nA bogeyman is an imaginary evil spirit. Some parents tell their children that the bogeyman will catch them if they behave badly.\n

voca.title: bogue
voca.means:
[보우g]
가짜의 위조의
마약이 떨어진, 마약을 필요로 하는
금단 증상

voca.title: bogus
voca.explains: If you describe something as bogus, you mean that it is not genuine.\n

voca.title: boil
voca.means:
[보일]
(물이나 액체가) 끊다, 끊이다, 
삼다, 데치다
끓이기, 종기, 부스럼
voca.explains:
When a hot liquid boils or when you boil it, bubbles appear in it and it starts to change into steam or vapour.
When you boil a kettle or pan, or put it on to boil, you heat the water inside it until it boils.
When a kettle or pan is boiling, the water inside it has reached boiling point.
When you boil food, or when it boils, it is cooked in boiling water.
If you are boiling with anger, you are very angry.

voca.title: boil down
voca.explains: to make a liquid less in quantity by boiling it\nto make something smaller by removing unimportant parts and leaving only the essential things\n

voca.title: boil over
voca.explains: if a liquid in a pan, etc. boils over, it boils and flows over the side of the pan\nif anger, an argument, etc. boils over, it changes and becomes very violent and difficult to control\n

voca.title: boil something up
voca.explains: to heat a liquid or some food until it boils\n

voca.title: boil up
voca.explains: if anger, an argument, etc. boils up, it starts to become stronger or more violent\n

voca.title: bold
voca.explains:
Someone who is bold is not afraid to do things which involve risk or danger.
Someone who is bold is not shy or embarrassed in the company of other people.
A bold colour or pattern is very bright and noticeable.
Bold lines or designs are drawn in a clear, strong way.
Bold is print which is thicker and looks blacker than ordinary printed letters.

voca.title: bolster
voca.means:
[^보울s터r]
북돋우다, 강화/개선하다
(학설·운동 등을) 지지하다; 보강하다
기운내게 하다, 튼튼하게 하다
(베개 밑에 까는 긴) 베개 받침
받침, 지지물 (서까래·받침대 등)
voca.explains:
If you bolster something such as someone's confidence or courage, you increase it.
If someone tries to bolster their position in a situation, they try to strengthen it.
A bolster is a firm pillow shaped like a long tube which is sometimes put across a bed under the ordinary pillows.

voca.title: bolt
voca.means:
[보울t]
빗장을 걸다, 갑자기 튀어나오다
빗장, 걸쇠, 볼트, 돌진, 도망, 번갯불
느닷없이, 갑자기, 똑바로
voca.explains:
A bolt is a long metal object which screws into a nut and is used to fasten things together.
A bolt on a door or window is a metal bar that you can slide across in order to fasten the door or window.
A bolt of lightning is a flash of lightning that is seen as a white line in the sky.
When you bolt one thing to another, you fasten them firmly together, using a bolt.
When you bolt a door or window, you slide the bolt across to fasten it.
If a person or animal bolts, they suddenly start to run very fast, often because something has frightened them.
If you bolt your food, you eat it so quickly that you hardly chew it or taste it.
The four of them bolted back from the edge of the rocky slope.
Suddenly, Jack felt like he'd been hit by a bolt of lightning.
They bolted across the room.

voca.title: bomb
voca.means:
[^바암]
폭탄, 폭발물
많은(큰) 돈, 분무기
~을 폭격하다, 폭발하다
(차량을 타고) 질주하다, 
(시험을) 완정히 망치다, 크게 실패하다
voca.explains:
A bomb is a device which explodes and damages or destroys a large area.
Nuclear weapons are sometimes referred to as the bomb.
When people bomb a place, they attack it with bombs.

voca.title: bomb one's test
voca.explains: He bombed his biology test.\nSandra: Because you bombed your test she doesn't know how to teach?\n

voca.title: bomb shelter
voca.explains: "Well, I’m not taking any chances. We spent all that money on a bomb shelter. We may as well use it."\n

voca.title: bombard
voca.explains: If you bombard someone with something, you make them face a great deal of it. For example, if you bombard them with questions or criticism, you keep asking them a lot of questions or you keep criticizing them.\nWhen soldiers bombard a place, they attack it with continuous heavy gunfire or bombs.\n

voca.title: bombardment
voca.explains:
A bombardment is a strong and continuous attack of gunfire or bombing.
A bombardment of ideas, demands, questions, or criticisms is an aggressive and exhausting stream of them.
Volunteers pull a girl through a tiny gap, high up in the wreckage of a partially-destroyed building as Aleppo bombardment continues.

voca.title: bond
voca.means:
[^반-d]
유대, 끈, 
채권, 보석금, 속박, 굴레, 접착, 접합
접착/접합/결합 시키다, 
유대감을 형성하다
voca.explains:
A bond between people is a strong feeling of friendship, love, or shared beliefs and experiences that unites them.
A bond between people or groups is a close connection that they have with each other, for example because they have a special agreement.
When people bond with each other, they form a relationship based on love or shared beliefs and experiences. You can also say that people bond or that something bonds them.
When a government or company issues a bond, it borrows money from investors. The certificate which is issued to investors who lend money is also called a bond.
When one thing bonds with another, it sticks to it or becomes joined to it in some way. You can also say that two things bond together, or that something bonds them together.
The bond between a mare and her young is very strong.

voca.title: bond over something
voca.explains:
Last weekend, we decided to go watch a movie. We bonded over our mutual interest in movies. Everything was smooth sailing, so we continued our talk over dinner. Surprisingly, there were no awkward silences in our conversation.
We have nothing to bond over.
I need something to bond over with my husband.

voca.title: bone
voca.explains:
Your bones are the hard parts inside your body which together form your skeleton.
If you bone a piece of meat or fish, you remove the bones from it before cooking it.
A bone tool or ornament is made of bone.
The bare bones of something are its most basic parts or details.

voca.title: bone dry
voca.explains: If you say that something is bone dry, you are emphasizing that it is very dry indeed.\nTed: My throat is bone dry.\n

voca.title: bonfire
voca.explains: A bonfire is a fire that is made outdoors, usually to burn rubbish. Bonfires are also sometimes lit as part of a celebration.\n

voca.title: bony
voca.means: [보우늬]\n뼈의, 뼈 같은, 골질의\n뼈가 다 드러나는, 앙상한
voca.explains: Someone who has a bony face or bony hands, for example, has a very thin face or very thin hands, with very little flesh covering their bones.\nThe bony parts of a person's or animal's body are the parts made of bone.\n

voca.title: boob
voca.means: [부-웁]\n젗통, 바보, 멍청이, 큰 실패\n바보같은 실수를 하다
voca.explains: A woman's boobs are her breasts.\nIf you boob, you make a mistake.\n

voca.title: book
voca.explains:
A book is a number of pieces of paper, usually with words printed on them, which are fastened together and fixed inside a cover of stronger paper or cardboard. Books contain information, stories, or poetry, for example.
A book of something such as stamps, matches, or tickets is a small number of them fastened together between thin cardboard covers.
A company's or organization's books are its records of money that has been spent and earned or of the names of people who belong to it.
When you book something such as a hotel room or a ticket, you arrange to have it or use it at a particular time.
When a referee books a football player who has seriously broken the rules of the game, he or she officially writes down the player's name.
When a police officer books someone, he or she officially records their name and the offence that they may be charged with.

voca.title: book a flight
voca.explains:
Thanks to the Internet, finding travel information has become a walk in the park. There are seemingly endless travel sites and blogs online. You don’t even need a computer. Everything from finding information to booking a flight or hotel can be done on smartphones.
He saved money by booking a flight in advance.
Compare prices before you book a flight.

voca.title: book a restaurant
voca.explains:
My father prefers home-cooked meals. Instead of booking a restaurant, we had a potluck dinner. Everyone contributed their signature dish.
Did you book a restaurant for your blind date?
When I travel, booking a restaurant is the first thing I do.

voca.title: book tickets
voca.explains:
Korea's bullet train, the KTX, was launched in 2004. I go on business trips often using the KTX. On my last trip, I traveled to Busan. I was able to book tickets through an app.
Did you book tickets for the movie?
You can save money if you book your tickets early.

voca.title: bookcase
voca.explains: A bookcase is a piece of furniture with shelves that you keep books on.\n

voca.title: bookkeeper
voca.explains: A bookkeeper is a person whose job is to keep an accurate record of the money that is spent and received by a business or other organization.\n

voca.title: booklet
voca.explains: A booklet is a small book that has a paper cover and that gives you information about something.\n

voca.title: bookstore
voca.explains: A bookstore is a shop where books are sold.\nRoger: Yes. But you do have to pay tax if you buy it from a market or bookstore.\n

On a boat, the boom is the long pole which is attached to the bottom of the sail and to the mast and which you move when you want to alter the direction in which you are sailing.
If the economy or a business is booming, the amount of things being bought or sold is increasing.
When something such as someone's voice, a cannon, or a big drum booms, it makes a loud, deep sound that lasts for several seconds.

"Camelot is dying!" the Christmas Knight boomed.

voca.title: boost

Boots are strong, heavy shoes which cover your ankle and which have thick soles. You wear them to protect your feet, for example when you are walking or taking part in sport.
The boot of a car is a covered space at the back or front, in which you carry things such as luggage and shopping.
If you boot something such as a ball, you kick it hard.
If you get the boot or are given the boot, you are told that you are not wanted any more, either in your job or by someone you are having a relationship with.

voca.title: boot up
voca.explains: if a computer boots up, or somebody boots it up, it is turned on and becomes ready to use\nLast week, I tried to fire up my laptop, but nothing happened. It simply refused to boot up. I called up my computer guru friend. He gave me a few pointers. None of them worked. My computer had given up the ghost.\n

voca.title: booth

voca.title: booty
voca.explains: Booty is a collection of valuable things stolen from a place, especially by soldiers after a battle.\n

voca.title: booze
voca.explains: Booze is alcoholic drink.\nIf people booze, they drink alcohol.\n

If something is bordered by another thing, the other thing forms a line along the edge of it.

without limits
not constrained by the presence of international borders

voca.title: born
voca.explains:
When a baby is born, it comes out of its mother's body at the beginning of its life. In formal English, if you say that someone is born of someone or to someone, you mean that person is their parent.
If someone is born with a particular disease, problem, or characteristic, they have it from the time they are born.
You can use be born in front of a particular name to show that a person was given this name at birth, although they may be better known by another name.
You use born to describe someone who has a natural ability to do a particular activity or job. For example, if you are a born cook, you have a natural ability to cook well.

voca.title: born and bred
voca.explains: born and brought up (in a place)\n

If you borrow money from someone or from a bank, they give it to you and you agree to pay it back at some time in the future.
If you borrow a book from a library, you take it away for a fixed period of time.
If you borrow something such as a word or an idea from another language or from another person's work, you use it in your own language or work.
Someone who is living on borrowed time or who is on borrowed time has continued to live or to do something for longer than was expected, and is likely to die or be stopped from doing it soon.

voca.title: boss

If you say that someone bosses you, you mean that they keep telling you what to do in a way that is irritating.
If you are your own boss, you work for yourself or make your own decisions and do not have anyone telling you what to do.
top dog

우두머리 행세를 하다, 
다른 사람을 쥐고 흔들다, 
암소, 송아지, 두목 노릇하는
voca.explains: If you describe someone as bossy, you mean that they enjoy telling people what to do.\n"Humph!" muttered D.W. "Big brothers can be so bossy."\n

voca.title: botanical
voca.explains: Botanical books, research, and activities relate to the scientific study of plants.\nBotanicals are drugs which are made from plants.\n

voca.title: botch
voca.explains: If you botch something that you are doing, you do it badly or clumsily.\nIf you make a botch of something that you are doing, you botch it.\n

You don't want to botch up this presentation.

voca.title: bother

신경 쓰다, 애를 쓰다, 
신경 쓰이게 하다, 괴롭히다,

골칫거리, 귀찮은 일, 성가심
