If you do not bother to do something or if you do not bother with it, you do not do it, consider it, or use it because you think it is unnecessary or because you are too lazy.
If something bothers you, or if you bother about it, it worries, annoys, or upsets you.
If someone bothers you, they talk to you when you want to be left alone or interrupt you when you are busy.
Bother means trouble or difficulty. You can also use bother to refer to an activity which causes this, especially when you would prefer not to do it or get involved with it.
If you say that you can't be bothered to do something, you mean that you are not going to do it because you think it is unnecessary or because you are too lazy.

A : In that case, I'm sorry to bother you. Take as much time as you need.

voca.title: bottle it
voca.explains: not do something, or not finish something, because you are frightened\n

voca.title: bottle out

voca.title: bottle something up

voca.title: bottom
voca.explains:

The bottom of something is the lowest or deepest part of it.
The bottom of an object is the flat surface at its lowest point. You can also refer to the inside or outside of this surface as the bottom.
If you say that the bottom has dropped or fallen out of a market or industry, you mean that people have stopped buying the products it sells.
The bottom of a street or garden is the end farthest away from you or from your house.
The bottom of a table is the end farthest away from where you are sitting. The bottom of a bed is the end where you usually rest your feet.
The bottom of an organization or career structure is the lowest level in it, where new employees often start.
Judy searched her top drawer and her bottom drawer and even her underwear drawer.

voca.title: bottom out
voca.explains: if markets, prices or bad situations bottom out, they reach their lowest point and then stop getting worse\n

voca.title: bought

If something bounces or if something bounces it, it swings or moves up and down.
If you bounce on a soft surface, you jump up and down on it repeatedly.

If a cheque bounces or if a bank bounces it, the bank refuses to accept it and pay out the money, because the person who wrote it does not have enough money in their account.

voca.title: bound and determined
voca.explains: very determined to do something\n

voca.title: boundary
voca.explains:
border / boundary / line / frontier

The boundaries of something such as a subject or activity are the limits that people think that it has.

voca.title: bouquet

The bow of a violin or other stringed instrument is a long thin piece of wood with fibres stretched along it, which you move across the strings of the instrument in order to play it.

Your bowels are the tubes in your body through which digested food passes from your stomach to your anus.
You can refer in a polite way to someone getting rid of the waste from their body by saying that they move, open, or empty their bowels.
You can refer to the parts deep inside something such as the earth, a building, or a machine as the bowels of that thing.

voca.title: bowel movements
voca.explains:
the discharge of faeces; defecation
the waste matter discharged; faeces
I also drink yogurt when I’m having problems with bowel movements.

voca.title: box

Some people say 'boy' or 'oh boy' in order to express feelings of excitement or admiration.

voca.explains:
Your brain is the organ inside your head that controls your body's activities and enables you to think and to feel things such as heat and pain.
Your brain is your mind and the way that you think.
If someone has brains or a good brain, they have the ability to learn and understand things quickly, to solve problems, and to make good decisions.
If someone is the brains behind an idea or an organization, he or she had that idea or makes the important decisions about how that organization is managed.

voca.title: brainwash
voca.explains: If you brainwash someone, you force them to believe something by continually telling them that it is true, and preventing them from thinking about it properly.\n

voca.title: branch
voca.means:
[b뤤취]
나뭇가지, 지사, 분점, (큰 조직의) 분과/부서
(강, 도로, 철도 등의) 지류, 지선
가지를 뻗다, (둘 이상으로) 갈라지다, 분기하다, 나뉘다
voca.explains:
The branches of a tree are the parts that grow out from its trunk and have leaves, flowers, or fruit growing on them.
A branch of a business or other organization is one of the offices, shops, or groups which belong to it and which are located in different places.
A branch of an organization such as the government or the police force is a department that has a particular function.
A branch of a subject is a part or type of it.
A branch of your family is a group of its members who are descended from one particular person.

voca.title: branch off
voca.explains: if a road or path branches off, it leaves a larger one and goes in a different direction\nif a person branches off, they leave a road or path and travel in a different direction\n

voca.title: branch out
voca.explains: to begin to do a new job or an activity that you do not usually do\n

voca.title: brand
voca.means:
[b^뤤d]
상표, 브랜드
(특정한) 종류, 유형
(동물의 주인을 나타내는) 낙인
(특히 부당하게) 낙인을 찍다
(동물에게 주인을 표시하는) 낙인을 찍다
voca.explains:
A brand of a product is the version of it that is made by one particular manufacturer.
A brand of something such as a way of thinking or behaving is a particular kind of it.
If someone is branded as something bad, people think they are that thing.
When you brand an animal, you put a permanent mark on its skin in order to show who it belongs to, usually by burning a mark onto its skin.

voca.title: brand new
voca.explains: A brand-new object is completely new.\n

voca.title: bratty
voca.explains: The bratty monkey was back.\n

voca.title: brave
voca.explains:
Someone who is brave is willing to do things which are dangerous, and does not show fear in difficult or dangerous situations.
If you brave unpleasant or dangerous conditions, you deliberately expose yourself to them, usually in order to achieve something.
If someone is putting on a brave face or is putting a brave face on a difficult situation, they are pretending that they are happy or satisfied when they are not.

voca.title: bray
voca.explains: When a donkey brays, it makes a loud harsh sound.\n

voca.title: bread
voca.explains:
Bread is a very common food made from flour, water, and yeast.
If food such as fish or meat is breaded, it is covered in tiny pieces of dry bread called breadcrumbs. It can then be fried or grilled.
I can't go to the movies because I don't have any bread.

voca.title: breadth
voca.explains:
The breadth of something is the distance between its two sides.
The breadth of something is its quality of consisting of or involving many different things.
If you say that someone does something or something happens throughout or across the length and breadth of a place, you are emphasizing that it happens everywhere in that place.

voca.title: break
voca.means:
[b^뤠익k]
부수다, 중단하다
고장나다, (법, 약속을) 어기다, 
파괴, 틈, 중단, 휴식
voca.explains:
break - broke - broken
When an object breaks or when you break it, it suddenly separates into two or more pieces, often because it has been hit or dropped.
If you break a part of your body such as your leg, your arm, or your nose, or if a bone breaks, you are injured because a bone cracks or splits.
If a surface, cover, or seal breaks or if something breaks it, a hole or tear is made in it, so that a substance can pass through.
When a tool or piece of machinery breaks or when you break it, it is damaged and no longer works.
If you break a rule, promise, or agreement, you do something that you should not do according to that rule, promise, or agreement.
If you break free or loose, you free yourself from something or escape from it.
If someone breaks something, especially a difficult or unpleasant situation that has existed for some time, they end it or change it.

voca.title: break down
voca.means: 고장나다, 실패하다, 아주 나빠지다\n감정을 주체하지 못하다/허불어지다\n무너지다, 절연 파괴되다
voca.explains:
if a vehicle, etc. breaks down, it stops working because of a fault
if talks, a marriage, etc. break down, they fail
to lose control of your feelings and start crying
if your health breaks down, it becomes very bad
(into something) to be divided into parts so that it is easier to discuss, to analyse or to deal with
(into something) if a substance breaks down, it separates into different parts or changes into something else in a chemical process
The elevator broke down again at work. We all had to use the stairs.
The washer started to break down.
The product hasn't broken down for a long time.
Turn it off before it breaks down.
For many years, my washer had given me no trouble. However, it started to break down a few weeks ago.
The car broke down on the highway.
It sounds like it's going to break down.
We often take our home appliances for granted. But when they break down, we realize how much we depend on them.
Our car broke down on the highway.
My computer broke down again.

voca.title: break free from
voca.explains: break free from a prison\n

voca.title: break in
voca.explains: to enter a building illegally or by force\n(on something) to interrupt somebody when they are speaking or doing something\n

voca.title: break into something
voca.means:
(건물에) 침입하다, 
(자동차 문 등을) 억지로 열다
(갑자기) ~하기 시작하다, 
(갑자기) (더 빨리) 달리기 시작하다
진입하다
voca.explains:
to enter a building, open a car, etc. illegally and by force
to suddenly begin to do something such as laugh, shout, run, etc.
to use a note/bill of high value to buy something costing less
to interrupt somebody's thoughts
to start to get involved in an activity and be successful at it, especially when this is difficult
to open and use something that you have been saving for an emergency or a special occasion
He blew out a puff of air, then broke into a leaping run.
They broke into the circle on either side of the knights.
He broke into a big grin.

voca.title: break off
voca.explains:
(break something off something) to separate something from something else, using force; to become separated from something in this way
to stop speaking or stop doing something suddenly before you have finished
Annie broke off a leaf and sniffed it.

voca.title: break out
voca.explains:
if something unpleasant such as a fire, a war, etc. breaks out, it starts suddenly
(break out of something) to escape from a place or from a situation
if something breaks out on your skin, your skin becomes covered in something
Dermatologists label my skin type as combination as opposed to dry or oily. It’s a nightmare. I break out in the t-zone but can’t use harsh acne medication because it will result in dry, flaky skin.
Stress at work made me break out.
Unhealthy diets can cause breakouts.

voca.title: break out in a cold sweat
voca.explains:
Another time, I went on a fishing trip with some friends. Out on the open water, the wind picked up. The waves grew fierce. I became very seasick. I took some medicine, but it was too little too late. I emptied my stomach. I felt disoriented. I broke out in a cold sweat. I was all but begging to get off the boat. It was not a very enjoyable experience.
The nightmare made me break out in a cold sweat.
This flu will make you break out in a cold sweat.

voca.title: break out in hives
voca.explains:
I am highly allergic to peanuts. My tonsils swell up and my throat closes up. I sound like I’ve lost my voice or I’m choking on something. To add to the pain, I also break out in hives and hyperventilate.
A single peanut will make me break out in hives.
After spending a long day out in the sun, I broke out in hives.

voca.title: break room
voca.explains: After lunch, I was barely able to keep my eyes open. I kept nodding off. I had to take a quick cat nap in the breakroom.\n

voca.title: break something in
voca.means: ~을 길들이다, 훈련시키다\n(특히 새 신을) 길을 들이다
voca.explains:
if you break in new shoes or boots, you wear them until they become comfortable
(in the past) to prepare the engine of a new car for normal use by driving it slowly and carefully
to train a person so that they get used to a new job or situation; to train a horse so that you can ride it
Once, I was walking in a new pair of heels. I had not yet broken them in. I walked too quickly, and tripped. I had runs in my stockings. My knees turned black and blue. My shins were scuffed and bled.

voca.title: break something off
voca.explains: to end something such as a relationship\n

voca.title: break sweat
voca.explains: use a lot of physical effort\n

voca.title: break the bank
voca.means: 돈이 많이 들다\n(일반적으로) 파산시키다, \n무일푼이 되게 하다
voca.explains: I like to go hiking whenever I get the chance. It's a great way to work up a sweat, and it doesn't break the bank.\n

voca.title: break the ice
voca.means: (특히 회의, 파티 등을 시작할 때) 서먹서먹한/딱딱한 분위기를 깨다\n어색함을 풀다
voca.explains:
make a social situation more informal and relaxed, especially at the beginning of a meeting, party, etc
We ended up falling out of touch. Recently, we ran into each other by chance. I swallowed my pride and said hello. We soon broke the ice.
I was so nervous on my blind date that I couldn't break the ice.

voca.title: break through
voca.means: (무력으로 ~을) 뚫고 나아가다, 돌파하다\n돌파구를 찾다\n(해, 달이 구름 뒤에서) 나타나다
voca.explains: to make a way through a barrier using force\nto appear from behind something\n

voca.title: break through something
voca.explains: to become greater in size or quantity than a particular level\nto succeed in dealing with a problem, such as an attitude that somebody has\n

voca.title: break up
voca.means: 부서지다, 끝이 나다, 파하다\n(휴대전화의 통화가) 끊기다\n헤어지다
voca.explains:
(especially BrE) if a school or the children in it break up, school closes for the holidays at the end of a period of the school year (a term)
to come to an end; to stop working together
(usually used in the progressive tenses) if the connection between two telephones, or two radios that are used for sending and receiving messages, is breaking up, the people speaking can no longer hear each other clearly
(into something) if a group of people or a family breaks up, or somebody breaks it up, the members separate and do not stay together
if a group of people who are gathered together break up, or somebody breaks them up, they go away in different directions
Puppy love was tricky. I wore my heart on my sleeve and it was shattered. Driven by jealousy, my first boyfriend cheated on me and it left me heartbroken. It was a clear sign to break up but I was hung up on my first love.
I think you need to break up with her.
We broke up because we couldn't set aside our differences.

voca.title: break up with
voca.explains:
I'm thinking about breaking up with Tom.
I'm thinking about breaking up with ABC company.
What year did the Beatles break up?

voca.title: breakdown
voca.means:
[^b뤠익k다운]
(차량, 기계의) 고장
(관계, 논의, 시스템의) 실패, 결렬, 와해
명세(서)
분해
voca.explains:
The breakdown of something such as a relationship, plan, or discussion is its failure or ending.
If you have a breakdown, you become very depressed, so that you are unable to cope with your life.
If a car or a piece of machinery has a breakdown, it stops working.
A breakdown of something is a list of its separate parts.

voca.title: breakfast
voca.explains:
Breakfast is the first meal of the day. It is usually eaten in the early part of the morning.
When you breakfast, you have breakfast.
A : Have you had breakfast?

voca.title: breaking news
voca.explains: I often hear about breaking news this way.\nKoreans crave breaking news. News is on the internet before any other medium. Therefore, people who read the news on their smartphones can stay ahead of the curve.\n

voca.title: breakout
voca.means:
[b^뤠익k아웃]
(보통 집단적인) 탈옥
(화재, 전쟁, 전염병 따위의) 발생, 발발.
피부 드러블
voca.explains: If there has been a break-out, someone has escaped from prison.\n

voca.title: breakthrough
voca.means:
[b^뤠익k뜨루-]
돌파구
(군사) 돌파 (작전)
(과학 등의) 큰 발전, 약진, (귀중한) 새 발견
(난관의) 돌파(구), 타개(책), (난문제의) 해명
voca.explains: A breakthrough is an important development or achievement.\n

voca.title: breakup
voca.means:
[b^뤠익껍]
분해, 분열, 붕괴 
(조직의) 해체, 해산.
(친구·부부 간 등의) 이별, 불화, 별거, 파탄.
voca.explains:
to separate or cause to separate
to put an end to (a relationship) or (of a relationship) to come to an end
to dissolve or cause to dissolve; disrupt or be disrupted
(of a person making a telephone call) to be inaudible at times, owing to variations in the signal
to lose or cause to lose control of the emotions
break-up a separation or disintegration
All breakups are bound to be bad. If two people were compatible, they would still be together.

voca.title: breast
voca.means:
[b^뤠st]
가슴, 유방, 가슴살
(꼭데기에) 오르다
가슴으로 받다, 가슴으로 밀다, 
~을 향햐여 가슴을 내밀다
voca.explains:
A woman's breasts are the two soft, round parts on her chest that can produce milk to feed a baby.
A person's breast is the upper part of his or her chest.
A bird's breast is the front part of its body.
The breast of a shirt, jacket, or coat is the part which covers the top part of the chest.
You can refer to piece of meat that is cut from the front of a bird or lamb as breast.

voca.title: breast-feed
voca.explains: When a woman breast-feeds her baby, she feeds it with milk from her breasts, rather than from a bottle.\nWe decided to have a natural birth. Everything went smoothly. After our baby arrived, I spent two weeks at a post-natal care center. I learned how to breast-feed our baby there.\n

voca.title: breastplate
voca.explains: A breastplate is a piece of armour that covers and protects the chest.\nThey saw rows of helmets, breastplates, gauntlets, shields, spears, and swords.\n

voca.title: breaststroke
voca.explains: Breaststroke is a swimming stroke which you do lying on your front, moving your arms and legs horizontally in a circular motion.\n

voca.title: breath
voca.explains:
Your breath is the air that you let out through your mouth when you breathe. If someone has bad breath, their breath smells unpleasant.
When you take a breath, you breathe in once.
"Oh man" he breathed.

voca.title: breathe
voca.explains:
When people or animals breathe, they take air into their lungs and let it out again. When they breathe smoke or a particular kind of air, they take it into their lungs and let it out again as they breathe.
If someone breathes something, they say it very quietly.
If you do not breathe a word about something, you say nothing about it, because it is a secret.
If someone breathes life, confidence, or excitement into something, they improve it by adding this quality.

voca.title: breathe in
voca.explains: to take air into your lungs through your nose or mouth\n

voca.title: breathe out
voca.explains: to send air out of your lungs through your nose or mouth\n

voca.title: breather
voca.explains:
break / rest / breather / breathing space / respite / time out
If you take a breather, you stop what you are doing for a short time and have a rest.
One of the things I love about my apartment is that there is a nice park nearby. Our neighborhood park is just a stone’s throw away.
You've worked so hard, you deserve a breather.
Take a breather every hour.

voca.title: breathless
voca.means:
[b뤠쓰뤠s]
숨이 가쁜, 숨을 가쁘게 하는
(격한 감정으로) 숨을 쉴수 없는, 숨이 막힐 듯 한
voca.explains: If you are breathless, you have difficulty in breathing properly, for example because you have been running or because you are afraid or excited.\nYou use breathless for emphasis when you are describing feelings of excitement or exciting situations.\n

voca.title: breathtaking
voca.means: [b^뤠쓰텍킹]\n(너무 아름답거나 놀라워서) 숨이 막히는/멎는 듯한\n숨막힐 정도로 아름다운
voca.explains:
If you say that something is breathtaking, you are emphasizing that it is extremely beautiful or amazing.
The mountains are breathtaking in the autumn.
You look breathtaking in that dress.
The night view was breathtaking.
When it snows, the mountains are breathtaking.

voca.title: breed
voca.means: [b^뤼-d]\n(새끼를) 낳다, 기르다, 사육하다\n품종, 종족, 혈통, 종류, 유형
voca.explains:
A breed of a pet animal or farm animal is a particular type of it. For example, terriers are a breed of dog.
You can refer to someone or something as one of a particular breed of person or thing when you want to talk about what they are like.
If you breed animals or plants, you keep them for the purpose of producing more animals or plants with particular qualities, in a controlled way.
When animals breed, they have babies.
If you say that something breeds bad feeling or bad behaviour, you mean that it causes bad feeling or bad behaviour to develo

voca.title: breed of dog
voca.explains: Our puppy is a Maltese. It’s my favorite breed of dog. She was so cute that she was the apple of my eye.\n

voca.title: breeze
voca.explains:
A breeze is a gentle wind.
If you breeze into a place or a position, you enter it in a very casual or relaxed manner.
If you breeze through something such as a game or test, you cope with it easily.
As they passed the cornfield, the dried stalks swayed in the breeze.
Sounds of music and laughter floated on the breeze.

voca.title: brew
voca.explains:
If you brew tea or coffee, you make it by pouring hot water over tea leaves or ground coffee.
If a person or company brews beer, they make it.
If a storm is brewing, large clouds are beginning to form and the sky is becoming dark because there is going to be a storm.
If an unpleasant or difficult situation is brewing, it is starting to develop.
A brew is a particular kind of tea or coffee. It can also be a particular pot of tea or coffee.

voca.title: brew up
voca.explains: to prepare a hot drink of tea or coffee\n

voca.title: briar
voca.means: [b롸이어r]\n등장미(의 일종)\n브라이어(뿌리가 단단해서 담배 파이프를 만드는 데 쓰이는 관목); 브라이어 파이프
voca.explains: A briar is a wild rose with long, prickly stems.\nbriar = brier\n

voca.title: bribe
voca.explains: A bribe is a sum of money or something valuable that one person offers or gives to another in order to persuade him or her to do something.\nIf one person bribes another, they give them a bribe.\n

voca.title: bribery
voca.explains: Bribery is the act of offering someone money or something valuable in order to persuade them to do something for you.\n

voca.title: brick
voca.explains: Bricks are rectangular blocks of baked clay used for building walls, which are usually red or brown. Brick is the material made up of these blocks.\n

voca.title: bride
voca.explains: A bride is a woman who is getting married or who has just got married.\n

voca.title: bridge
voca.explains:
A bridge is a structure that is built over a railway, river, or road so that people or vehicles can cross from one side to the other.
A bridge between two places is a piece of land that joins or connects them.
If something or someone acts as a bridge between two people, groups, or things, they connect them.
The bridge is the place on a ship from which it is steered.
To bridge the gap between two people or things means to reduce it or get rid of it.

voca.title: bridle
voca.means:
[b^롸이들]
(말에게 씌우는) 굴레
(말에게) 굴레를 씌우다
(기분 나쁜 듯) 고개를 치켜들다
voca.explains:
A bridle is a set of straps that is put around a horse's head and mouth so that the person riding or driving the horse can control it.
If you bridle, you show that you are angry or offended by moving your head and body upwards in a proud way.
Saddles and bridles hung from pegs on the walls.

voca.title: brief
voca.means:
[b뤼-f]
(시간이) 짧은, 잠시 동안의, 잠시의, 짧은, 
(말, 글이) 간단한, 간결한
요약하다, 개요를 알리다
간결한 문서, 개요, 요약서
voca.explains:
Something that is brief lasts for only a short time.
A brief speech or piece of writing does not contain too many words or details.
If you are brief, you say what you want to say in as few words as possible.
You can describe a period of time as brief if you want to emphasize that it is very short.
Men's or women's underpants can be referred to as briefs.
If someone briefs you, especially about a piece of work or a serious matter, they give you information that you need before you do it or consider it.

voca.title: briefcase
voca.explains: A briefcase is a case used for carrying documents in.\n

voca.title: briefly
voca.explains:
Something that happens or is done briefly happens or is done for a very short period of time.
If you say or write something briefly, you use very few words or give very few details.
You can say briefly to indicate that you are about to say something in as few words as possible.
Can you briefly tell me what happened last night?

voca.title: brier
voca.explains: any of various thorny shrubs or other plants, such as the sweetbrier and greenbrier\na variant spelling of briar\n

voca.title: bright
voca.means:
[b롸잇t]
(빛이) 밝은, 눈부신, 빛나는, 
선명한, 영리한, 똑똑한
밝게, 환히
voca.explains:
bright / brilliant / fluorescent / luminous / vivid / vibrant
A bright colour is strong and noticeable, and not dark.
A bright light, object, or place is shining strongly or is full of light.
If you describe someone as bright, you mean that they are quick at learning things.
A bright idea is clever and original.
If someone looks or sounds bright, they look or sound cheerful and lively.
On a hillside beyond the meadow, red and purple flowers sparkled like bright buttons.

voca.title: brighten
voca.means:
[b^롸잇은]
밝아지다, 반짝이다, 밝히다, 반짝이게 하다
(얼굴 등이) 생기가 나다, 환해지다, 환해 보이게 하다
(기쁨, 희망으로) 밝아지다, 밝히다
~에 활기를 주다
맑아지다, 개다
voca.explains:
If someone brightens or their face brightens, they suddenly look happier.
If your eyes brighten, you suddenly look interested or excited.
If someone or something brightens a place, they make it more colourful and attractive.
If someone or something brightens a situation or the situation brightens, it becomes more pleasant, enjoyable, or favourable.
When a light brightens a place or when a place brightens, it becomes brighter or lighter.
If the weather brightens, it becomes less cloudy or rainy, and the sun starts to shine.

voca.title: brilliant
voca.explains:
bright / brilliant / fluorescent / luminous / vivid / vibrant
A brilliant person, idea, or performance is extremely clever or skilful.
You can say that something is brilliant when you are very pleased about it or think that it is very good.
A brilliant career or success is very successful.
Along the brilliant crystal walls of the room were four doorways.

voca.title: brim
voca.means:
[b^륌]
(컵, 사발 등의) 위 끝부분 
(모자의) 챙 
(넘칠 듯) 그득하다; 그득 채우다
voca.explains:
The brim of a hat is the wide part that sticks outwards at the bottom.
If someone or something is brimming with a particular quality, they are full of that quality.
When your eyes are brimming with tears, they are full of fluid because you are upset, although you are not actually crying.
If something brims with particular things, it is packed full of them.
If something, especially a container, is filled to the brim or full to the brim with something, it is filled right up to the top.
"No." Buster pushed back the brim of his hat. "But I did pick up some secret information."

voca.title: brimmed
voca.explains: Miraculously, the silver cup still brimmed with water form the cauldron.\n

voca.title: brimming
voca.explains: Parks are a welcome respite in the busy city. There’s no sign of nature in the streets, but parks are brimming with green. Our neighborhood is blessed with a stellar park.\n

voca.title: bring
voca.means:
[b^륑]
가져오다, 데려오다, 가져다 주다/제공하다
(특정 방향, 방식으로) 움직이게 하다
기소/고발 하다
(간신히) ~을 하다
voca.explains:
bring - brought - brought
If you bring someone or something with you when you come to a place, they come with you or you have them with you.
If you bring something somewhere, you move it there.
If you bring something that someone wants or needs, you get it for them or carry it to them.
To bring something or someone to a place or position means to cause them to come to the place or move into that position.
If you bring something new to a place or group of people, you introduce it to that place or cause those people to hear or know about it.
To bring someone or something into a particular state or condition means to cause them to be in that state or condition.
If something brings a particular feeling, situation, or quality, it makes people experience it or have it.
While brushing his teeth, Arthur brought his face right up to the mirror. His teeth lined up in little square rows.

voca.title: bring along
voca.means:
~을 데리고 오다/가다, 
~을 가지고 오다/가다,
챙기다,
(선수 등을) 양성하다, 
(식물의) 성장을 촉진하다
voca.explains:
to bring somebody/something somewhere with you
I bring along my first-aid kit.
You can bring along your dog.
She remembered to bring along her laptop.
I'm going to bring along my flashlight. I might need it.
Carol: I'm going to bring along some food for us to eat in the car.
My biggest regret is not spending more time with my family. That’s why I want to spend quality time with them this summer. If possible, I’d like to bring my parents along.
When I travel, I like to bring my guitar along.
She brought her cousin along to the party.

voca.title: bring down
voca.means: 내리다, 떨어뜨리다, \n파멸/도산 시키다, 붕괴시키다, 콧대를 꺽다
voca.explains: to cause to fall\nto cause to be elated and then suddenly depressed, as from using drugs\n

voca.title: bring out
voca.means:
갖고/데리고 나가다, 
판매 개시하다, 출판하다, 
(의미를) 분명히 하다
(재능을) 발휘하다
~을 끌어내다, 부각시키다
voca.explains:
My breakouts have subsided, so now I pop my own pimples. But when my skin acts up again, I visit the dermatologist for professional extractions. Clear complexion brings out the best in everyone.
He brings the best out in me.
That color really brings out your eyes.

voca.title: bring somebody in
voca.explains: (on something) to get somebody involved in something, especially to advise or help, etc.\nif the police bring somebody in, they take them to a police station to question them or arrest them\n

voca.title: bring something about
voca.explains:
to make something happen
I'm shocked! What brought this about?
Protest can bring about change in the law.

voca.title: bring something down
voca.means: ~을 줄이다/낮추다\n(항공기를) 착륙시키다, 격추하다\n(짐승, 새를) 거꾸러뜨리다, 떨어뜨리다
voca.explains: to make something smaller in size or amount\nto make an aircraft land\n

voca.title: bring something off
voca.explains: to manage to do something difficult successfully\n

voca.title: bring something on
voca.explains: to make something unpleasant happen\n

voca.title: bring something up
voca.explains:
to move something from a lower to a higher position
to mention a subject and start to talk about it
(to something) to increase a total, a price, a number, etc. to a higher level or amount
to bring food from the stomach back out through the mouth
Paul always brings up political questions.
Sharon: Doesn't anyone bring it up with the teacher?

voca.title: bring up
voca.means: ~을 기르다, 훈육하다, 가르치다,\n 내놓다, 제출하다, 투입하다\n언급하다, 주제를 꺼내다
voca.explains: to care for a child until he/she is grown up; to teach a child a particular way to behave, etc.\nUsually, someone brings up sports. We could discuss politics. When we do that, sometimes we get into arguments.\n

voca.title: Bring Your Own Bottle
voca.explains:
Soon, our guests showed up. They didn’t come empty-handed. They came bearing gifts. People brought amenities like toilet paper, soap and detergent. They brought food like cake and fruit. The party was Bring Your Own Bottle(BYOB). The party was a riot.
It was a BYOB party.
Please remember to BYOB.

voca.title: Britain
voca.explains: another name for Great Britain, United Kingdom\n

voca.title: broach
voca.means:
[b로웃취]
(하기 힘들 이야기를) 꺼내다, 
처음으로 입밖에 내다, ~에 구멍을 뚫다
쇠꼬챙이, 송곳
voca.explains: When you broach a subject, especially a sensitive one, you mention it in order to start a discussion on it.\n

voca.title: broad
voca.explains:
wide / broad
Something that is broad is wide.
A broad smile is one in which your mouth is stretched very wide because you are very pleased or amused.
You use broad to describe a feeling or opinion that is shared by many people, or by people of many different kinds.

voca.title: broad minded
voca.explains: If you describe someone as broad-minded, you approve of them because they are willing to accept types of behaviour which other people consider immoral.\n

voca.title: broadband
voca.explains: Broadband is a method of sending many electronic messages at the same time, using a wide range of frequencies.\nKorea has an excellent internet infrastructure. Broadband connections are available everywhere. As a result, online lectures are very commonplace. Students prep for college entrance exams through online lectures.\n

voca.title: broadband connection
voca.explains:
Korea has an excellent internet infrastructure. Broadband connections are available everywhere. As a result, online lectures are very commonplace. Students prep for college entrance exams through online lectures.
The broadband connection is so fast.
It takes longer to download files without the broadband connection.

voca.title: broadcast
voca.explains: A broadcast is a programme, performance, or speech on the radio or on television.\nTo broadcast a programme means to send it out by radio waves, so that it can be heard on the radio or seen on television.\n

voca.title: broadcast station
voca.explains: The top 3 broadcast stations each have their own events in each category.\n

voca.title: broke
voca.explains:
Broke is the past tense of break.
If you are broke, you have no money.
If a company or person goes broke, they lose money and are unable to continue in business or to pay their debts.
If you go for broke, you take the most extreme or risky of the possible courses of action in order to try and achieve success.

voca.title: bronco
voca.explains: In the western United States, especially in the 19th century, a wild horse was sometimes referred to as a bronco.\nIt bucked like a bronco.\n

voca.title: bronze
voca.explains:
Bronze is a yellowish-brown metal which is a mixture of copper and tin.
A bronze is a bronze medal.
Something that is bronze is yellowish-brown in colour.

voca.title: brook
voca.explains: A brook is a small stream.\nIf someone in a position of authority will brook no interference or opposition, they will not accept any interference or opposition from others.\n

voca.title: broom
voca.explains:
A broom is a kind of brush with a long handle. You use a broom for sweeping the floor.
Broom is a wild bush with a lot of tiny yellow flowers.
Jack caught sight of a straw broom in the corner.
Jack dropped his broom and whirled around.
When he finished, he started balancing the broom on his nose.
Arthur took a breath and started along the rope, balancing himself with a broom.

voca.title: brose through
voca.explains: to look through a book, a magazine, etc. without paying close attention or reading everything\n

voca.title: brother
voca.means: [b뤄더r]\n형, 오빠, 남동생, \n(같은 단체의) 형제, 수도사, 수사
voca.explains:
Your brother is a boy or a man who has the same parents as you.
You can describe a man as your brother if he belongs to the same race, religion, country,
Brothers is used in the names of some companies and shops.
Brother is a title given to a man who belongs to a religious community such as a monastery.

voca.title: brotherly
voca.explains: A man's brotherly feelings are feelings of love and loyalty which you expect a brother to show.\n

voca.title: brow
voca.explains:
Your brow is your forehead.
Your brows are your eyebrows.
The brow of a hill is the top part of it.

voca.title: brown
voca.explains:
Something that is brown is the colour of earth or of wood.
You can describe a white-skinned person as brown when they have been sitting in the sun until their skin has become darker than usual.
A brown person is someone who belongs to a race of people who have brown-coloured skins.
Brown is used to describe grains that have not had their outer layers removed, and foods made from these grains.
When food browns or when you brown food, you cook it, usually for a short time on a high flame.

voca.title: brown out
voca.explains: to reduce the amount of electrical power, water, etc. that is supplied to a particular machine, area, etc.\n

voca.title: browse
voca.means:
[b롸우z]
(가게 안의 물건을) 둘러보다, 훑어보다, 
(책, 신문 등을) 대강 읽다/훑어보다, 
풀을 뜯어 먹다, 대강 훑어보다
voca.explains:
If you browse in a shop, you look at things in a fairly casual way, in the hope that you might find something you like.
If you browse through a book or magazine, you look through it in a fairly casual way.
If you browse on a computer, you search for information in computer files or on the Internet, especially on the World Wide Web.
When animals browse, they feed on plants.

voca.title: bruise
voca.means:
[b^루-z]
타박상을 입히다, 멍들게 하다
의기소침하게 만들다, 마음의 상처를 주다
타박상, 상처, 흠, 멍
voca.explains:
injure / wound / hurt / bruise / maim / sprain / pull / twist / strain
A bruise is an injury which appears as a purple mark on your body, although the skin is not broken.
If you bruise a part of your body, a bruise appears on it, for example because something hits you. If you bruise easily, bruises appear when something hits you only slightly.
If a fruit, vegetable, or plant bruises or is bruised, it is damaged by being handled roughly, making a mark on the skin.
If you are bruised by an unpleasant experience, it makes you feel unhappy or upset.
Feeling bruised and battered, he fell onto the sand.
I lost my balance and fell over. I got scrapes on my elbows and knees. I also had some light bruising.

voca.title: brunt
voca.explains: To bear the brunt or take the brunt of something unpleasant means to suffer the main part or force of it.\n

voca.title: brush
voca.means:
[b뤄쉬]
솔, 붓질, 화법, 
덤블이 우거진 땅, 여우의 꼬리
(~의 위에) 가볍게 닿음/스침
솔질하다, 이를 닦다, 머리를 빗질하다
~을 스치다, 스치듯 지나가다
voca.explains:
A brush is an object which has a large number of bristles or hairs fixed to it. You use brushes for painting, for cleaning things, and for tidying your hair.
If you have a brush with someone, you have an argument or disagreement with them. You use brush when you want to make an argument or disagreement sound less serious than it really is.
If you have a brush with a particular situation, usually an unpleasant one, you almost experience it.
Brush is an area of rough open land covered with small bushes and trees. You also use brush to refer to the bushes and trees on this land.
If you brush something or brush something such as dirt off it, you clean it or tidy it using a brush.
If you brush something with a liquid, you apply a layer of that liquid using a brush.
If one thing brushes against another or if you brush one thing against another, the first thing touches the second thing lightly while passing it.

voca.title: brush against
voca.explains: to touch somebody/something lightly when you move close to them/it\nA gentle wind brushed against his skin.\n

voca.title: brush fire
voca.means: (대규모의 산불과 구분해서)\n관목/잡목 지대의 화제, 소규모의 전투
voca.explains: a fire in bushes and scrub\na minor local war\n

voca.title: brush off
voca.explains: if mud, dust, etc. brushes off, or you brush it off, it is removed by brushing\nThen they brushed off their hands.\n

voca.title: brush something down
voca.explains: to clean something by brushing it thoroughly\n

voca.title: brush something off
voca.explains: to clean something quickly by brushing it\nto refuse to listen to, discuss or accept something\n

voca.title: brutal
voca.explains:
A brutal act or person is cruel and violent.
If someone expresses something unpleasant with brutal honesty or frankness, they express it in a clear and accurate way, without attempting to disguise its unpleasantness.
Brutal is used to describe things that have an unpleasant effect on people, especially when there is no attempt by anyone to reduce their effect.

voca.title: brute
voca.means:
[b룻-t]
짐승, 짐슴 같은 사람, 망나니
동물/짐승의, 이성/지성이 없는, 야만적인
신체적인 힘/폭력에만 의존하는
외면할 수 없는
voca.explains:
If you call someone, usually a man, a brute, you mean that they are rough, violent, and insensitive.
When you refer to brute strength or force, you are contrasting it with gentler methods or qualities.
Or we'll be meat for those evil brutes!

voca.title: bubble
voca.means:
[바블]
거품, 비눗방울, 기포, 과열
거품일다, 보글보글 끓다, 
(어떤 감정이) 달아 오르다, 가득하다, 
차오르다, 체우다
voca.explains:
Bubbles are small balls of air or gas in a liquid.
A bubble is a hollow ball of soapy liquid that is floating in the air or standing on a surface.
A bubble is a situation in which large numbers of people want to buy shares in a company that is new or not yet financially successful, and pay more than the shares are worth. When it becomes clear that the shares are worth less than people paid for them, you can say that the bubble has burst.
In a cartoon, a speech bubble is the shape which surrounds the words which a character is thinking or saying.
When a liquid bubbles, bubbles move in it, for example because it is boiling or moving quickly.
A feeling, influence, or activity that is bubbling away continues to occur.
Someone who is bubbling with a good feeling is so full of it that they keep expressing the way they feel to everyone around them.

voca.title: bubble over
voca.means: 거품이 일어 넘치다, \n(비유적) 흥분/열광을 억제하지 못하다
voca.explains: to be full of excitement, enthusiasm, ideas, etc.\n

voca.title: bubble up
voca.means: (샘물이) 콸콸 솟다, 끊어 오르다, \n거품이 일다, 번영하다
voca.explains: if a liquid bubbles up from the ground, etc., it rises up in the form of bubbles or making the sound of bubbles\nif an emotion, etc. bubbles up, it becomes stronger and starts to be heard or seen\n

voca.title: buck
voca.means:
[^벅k]
날뛰다, (위 아래로) 걷잡을 수 없이 흔들리다
(미국, 호주, 뉴즐랜드의) 달러
저항하다, 맞서 싸우다
수사슴, 달러
voca.explains:
A buck is a US or Australian dollar.
A buck is the male of various animals, including the deer, antelope, rabbit and kangaroo.
If a horse bucks, it kicks both of its back legs wildly into the air, or jumps into the air wildly with all four feet off the ground.
If you buck the trend, you obtain different results from others in the same area. If you buck the system, you get what you want by breaking or ignoring the rules.
If you get more bang for the buck, you spend your money wisely and get more for your money than if you were to spend it in a different way.
It bucked like a bronco.
Oh come on. You're making big bucks.
He's paying his lawyer big bucks.
B : They only gave it a once-over and charged me 500 bucks.

voca.title: buck up
voca.explains: to become, or to make somebody, more cheerful\nused to tell somebody to hurry up\n

voca.title: bucket
voca.explains: A bucket is a round metal or plastic container with a handle attached to its sides. Buckets are often used for holding and carrying water.\n

voca.title: bucket down
voca.explains: to rain heavily\n

voca.title: buckle
voca.means:
[^벅끌]
버클, 잠금장치
버클로 잠그다/잠기다
찌그러지다, 휘어지다, 찌그리다, 휘다
(다리의 힘이) 풀리다, 풀다
voca.explains:
A buckle is a piece of metal or plastic attached to one end of a belt or strap, which is used to fasten it.
When you buckle a belt or strap, you fasten it.
If an object buckles or if something buckles it, it becomes bent as a result of very great heat or force.
If your legs or knees buckle, they bend because they have become very weak or tired.

voca.title: buckle up
voca.explains:
to fasten the belt that you wear in a car, etc. to keep you in your seat if there is an accident (a seat belt)
Then I sat down and buckled up. The flight attendants gave a safety demonstration. Soon, we took off.
You should always buckle up when you get in a car.
Please buckle up, even in the back seat.

voca.title: buckskin
voca.explains: Buckskin is soft, strong leather made from the skin of a deer or a goat.\n

voca.title: bud
voca.means: [닫]\n싹, 눈, 봉오리, 미성년\n싹(눈)트다, 봉오리지다, 싹트게 하다
voca.explains:
A bud is a small pointed lump that appears on a tree or plant and develops into a leaf or flower.
When a tree or plant is budding, buds are appearing on it or are beginning to open.
When a tree or plant is in bud or has come into bud, it has buds on it.
If you nip something such as bad behaviour in the bud, you stop it before it can develop very far.
Put the seed in the ground when the oak-tree bud is as small as a mouse's ear.

voca.title: budge
voca.means: [받쥐]\n약간 움직이다, 움직이게 하다, 꼼짝하다, 움직이기 시작하다, \n바꾸다, 의견을 바꾸다
voca.explains: If someone will not budge on a matter, or if nothing budges them, they refuse to change their mind or to come to an agreement.\nIf someone or something will not budge, they will not move. If you cannot budge them, you cannot make them move.\n

voca.title: budge up
voca.means: (다른 사람이 들어올 공간이 생기게) 움직여 주다
voca.explains: to move up; to make more room for somebody else\n

voca.title: budget
voca.means:
[^버쥣t]
예산, 예산안, 재정, 경비, 운영비
~의 예산을 세우다, 예산을 짜다
저가의, 저렴한
voca.explains:
cheap / competitive / budget / affordable / reasonable / inexpensive
Your budget is the amount of money that you have available to spend. The budget for something is the amount of money that a person, organization, or country has available to spend on it.
The budget of an organization or country is its financial situation, considered as the difference between the money it receives and the money it spends.
In Britain, the Budget is the financial plan in which the government states how much money it intends to raise through taxes and how it intends to spend it. The Budget is also the speech in which this plan is announced.
If you budget certain amounts of money for particular things, you decide that you can afford to spend those amounts on those things.
Budget is used in advertising to suggest that something is being sold cheaply.

voca.title: budget for
voca.means: ~의 예산을 짜다, ~을 예산에 넣다\n~을 고려에 넣다, (참조하다)
voca.explains: to plan to save or provide an amount of money for a particular purpose\n

voca.title: buffalo
voca.explains: A buffalo is a wild animal like a large cow with horns that curve upwards. Buffalo are usually found in southern and eastern Africa.\nHe saved us on the Titanic. And he saved us from a buffalo stampede!"\n

voca.title: buffet
voca.explains:
A buffet is a meal of cold food that is displayed on a long table at a party or public occasion. Guests usually serve themselves from the table.
On a train, the buffet or the buffet car is the carriage or car where meals and snacks are sold.
If something is buffeted by strong winds or by stormy seas, it is repeatedly struck or blown around by them.
If an economy or government is buffeted by difficult or unpleasant situations, it experiences many of them.
A buffet is a good way to sample many dishes.

voca.title: bug
voca.explains:
disease / illness / disorder / infection / condition / ailment / bug
A bug is an insect or similar small creature.
A bug is an illness which is caused by small organisms such as bacteria.
If there is a bug in a computer program, there is a mistake in it.
A bug is a tiny hidden microphone which transmits what people are saying.
You can say that someone has been bitten by a particular bug when they suddenly become very enthusiastic about something.
If someone bugs a place, they hide tiny microphones in it which transmit what people are saying.
God, he was bugging me all day about the money I owed him.

voca.title: bug off
voca.explains: used to tell somebody to stop bothering you\na rude way of telling somebody to go away\n

voca.title: bug out
voca.explains:
if your eyes bug out, they suddenly open fully because you are surprised or excited
(especially of a group of soldiers, etc.) to leave a place quickly, especially to avoid duty or injury
to become very upset or angry

voca.title: buggy
voca.means:
[봐기]
(특정 목적을 위해 쓰는, 지붕도 문도 없는) 사륜차, 카트, 
유모차, 사륜차, 자동차
한 필의 말이 끄는 경마차
voca.explains:
A buggy is the same as a baby buggy.
A buggy is a small lightweight carriage pulled by one horse.
The buggy stopped with a jerk.

voca.title: bugle
voca.explains: A bugle is a simple brass musical instrument that looks like a small trumpet. Bugles are often used in the army to announce when activities such as meals are about to begin.\n

voca.title: bugler
voca.explains: A bugler is someone who plays the bugle.\n

voca.title: build
voca.means:
[빌d]
(건물을) 짓다, 건축/건설하다, 만들다, 세우다
커지다, 쌓이다
(사람의) 체구
voca.explains:
build / construct / assemble / erect / set up / put up / put together
If you build something, you make it by joining things together.
If you build something into a wall or object, you make it in such a way that it is in the wall or object, or is part of it.
If people build an organization, a society, or a relationship, they gradually form it.
If you build an organization, system, or product on something, you base it on it.
If you build something into a policy, system, or product, you make it part of it.
To build someone's confidence or trust means to increase it gradually. If someone's confidence or trust builds, it increases gradually.
If you build on the success of something, you take advantage of this success in order to make further progress.
If pressure, speed, sound, or excitement builds, it gradually becomes greater.

voca.title: build team spirit
voca.explains:
These days, staff dinners are more family-friendly. Some teams go to see a play or a movie together. The gatherings tend to end earlier than in the past. That way, workers can build team spirit, but still spend time with family.
Camping trips are a great way to build team spirit.
The purpose of this project is to build team spirit.

voca.title: built
voca.explains: Built is the past tense and past participle of build.\nIf you say that someone is built in a particular way, you are describing the kind of body they have.\n

voca.title: bulb
voca.explains: A bulb is the glass part of an electric lamp, which gives out light when electricity passes through it.\nA bulb is a root shaped like an onion that grows into a flower or plant.\n

voca.title: bulge
voca.means:
[^벌-쥐]
(~으로) 가득 차다/불룩하다
(동그랗게) 툭 튀어/불거져 나오다
툭 튀어/불거져 나온 것, 불룩한 것 
(불거져 나온 몸의) 지방/살
급증
voca.explains:
If something such as a person's stomach bulges, it sticks out.
If someone's eyes or veins are bulging, they seem to stick out a lot, often because the person is making a strong physical effort or is experiencing a strong emotion.
If you say that something is bulging with things, you are emphasizing that it is full of them.
Bulges are lumps that stick out from a surface which is otherwise flat or smooth.
If there is a bulge in something, there is a sudden large increase in it.
Arthur’s eyes bulged. It was all there right in front of him. All he had to do was change the Nadine part.

voca.title: bulk
voca.means:
[벍k]
(부피가)커지다, 많아지다, 증대하다
크기, 부피, 대량의, 대규모의, 대부분
~의 대부분
voca.explains:
You can refer to something's bulk when you want to emphasize that it is very large.
You can refer to a large person's body or to their weight or size as their bulk.
The bulk of something is most of it.
If you buy or sell something in bulk, you buy or sell it in large quantities.

voca.title: bulk up
voca.explains: to increase in size or weight; to make somebody/something increase in size or weight\n

voca.title: bulky
voca.explains: Something that is bulky is large and heavy. Bulky things are often difficult to move or deal with.\nBulky white suits hung from hangers.\n

voca.title: bull
voca.means: [부울-]\n황소, 코끼리(고래 및 큰 동물)의 수컷\n교황의 칙령/칙서
voca.explains:
A bull is a male animal of the cow family.
Some other male animals, including elephants and whales, are called bulls.
On the stock market, bulls are people who buy shares in expectation of a price rise, in order to make a profit by selling the shares again after a short time. Compare bear.
If you say that something is bull or a load of bull, you mean that it is complete nonsense or absolutely untrue.
If you take the bull by the horns, you do something that you feel you ought to do even though it is difficult, dangerous, or unpleasant.

voca.title: bullet
voca.explains: A bullet is a small piece of metal with a pointed or rounded end, which is fired out of a gun.\nIf someone bites the bullet, they accept that they have to do something unpleasant but necessary.\n

voca.title: bullet train
voca.explains:
a passenger train that travels at very high speed
For instance, Korea now has a bullet train called the KTX.
Korea's bullet train, the KTX, was launched in 2004. I go on business trips often using the KTX.
In Korea, many travelers take the bullet train, called the KTX. They are fast and reliable. Plus, driving is less of a chore now, since most cars have GPS.

voca.title: bulletin
voca.means: [블러튄]\n공표하다, 알리다, 공시하다\n게시, 공시, 속보, (라디오, TV의) 단신뉴스
voca.explains:
A bulletin is a short news report on the radio or television.
A bulletin is a short official announcement made publicly to inform people about an important matter.
A bulletin is a regular newspaper or leaflet that is produced by an organization or group such as a school or church.

voca.title: bulletin board
voca.explains: At the ball field, a bunch of kids were huddled around the bulletin board, looking at the team rosters.\n

voca.title: bullhorn
voca.explains: A bullhorn is a device for making your voice sound louder in the open air.\n"Children!" Mr. Haney shouted through his bullhorn. "Please board the school bus now."\n

voca.title: bullpen
voca.means:
[^불-페엔]
불펜(야구장에서 투수가 시합 전에 투구 연습을 하는 곳)
구원 투수진
(개별 공간을 벽으로 막지 않은) 툭 트인 넓은 사무실
(죄수들이 재판을 기다리는) 대기실
voca.explains:
a large cell where prisoners are confined together temporarily
a part of a baseball field where relief pitchers warm up
This is a part of the baseball field where the pitchers warm up during the game.

voca.title: bull's-eye
voca.means:
(과녁의) 중심, 정곡, 적중, 명중
두꺼운 볼록 렌즈가 달린 각등
(채광용의) 둥근 창
눈깔사탕
voca.explains:
The bull's-eye is the small circular area at the centre of a target.
In shooting or the game of darts, a bull's-eye is a shot or throw of a dart that hits the bull's-eye.
If something that you do or say hits the bull's eye, it has exactly the effect that you intended it to have.
"Bull's-eye!" cried D.W. "I'll bull's-eye you right back." said Arthur.

voca.title: bully
voca.means:
[불리]
(약자를) 괴롭히는 사람, 불량배, 공갈배, 따돌림, 폭력, 왕따, 
~을 못살게 굴다, 왕따시키다, 협박하다
훌륭한, 멋진, 근사한, 혈기왕성한
voca.explains:
A bully is someone who uses their strength or power to hurt or frighten other people.
If someone bullies you, they use their strength or power to hurt or frighten you.
If someone bullies you into something, they make you do it by using force or threats.
"Leave him alone, you bully!" she cried.

voca.title: bump
voca.means:
[^범p]
(도로의) 튀어나온 부분, 요철
충돌, 충격, 타박상, 혹
~에 쿵하고 부딪치다, 충돌하다
(다름 무리로) 이동시키다, 쫒아내다
voca.explains:
hit / knock / bang / strike / bump / bash
If you bump into something or someone, you accidentally hit them while you are moving.
If a vehicle bumps over a surface, it travels in a rough, bouncing way because the surface is very uneven.
A bump is the action or the dull sound of two heavy objects hitting each other.
A bump is a minor injury or swelling that you get if you bump into something or if something hits you.
If you have a bump while you are driving a car, you have a minor accident in which you hit something.
Her hand bumped his. / Annie drove the moon buggy over bumps and hollows.

voca.title: bump along
voca.explains: to continue in the same way as before, without making any progress or improvement\n

voca.title: bump into
voca.explains:
to meet somebody by chance
to hit somebody/something by accident
The good news was that D.W. suddenly stopped singing. The bad news was that she stopped because she had bumped into her mother.
I bumped into a friend.
I don't want to bump into my ex-boyfriend.
I was happy to bump into her yesterday.

voca.title: bump somebody up
voca.explains: to move somebody to a more expensive seat in a plane without charging them extra, because there are not enough seats at the price they have paid\n

voca.title: bump something up
voca.explains: to increase or raise something\n

voca.title: bumper to bumper
voca.explains: Starting at 4 p.m., traffic usually becomes bumper to bumper.\n

voca.title: bumpy
voca.explains: A bumpy road or path has a lot of bumps on it.\nA bumpy journey is uncomfortable and rough, usually because you are travelling over an uneven surface.\n

voca.title: bun
voca.means: [번]\n햄버거용 둥근 빵, 소형 롤 빵\n쪽(을 찐 머리)
voca.explains:
Buns are small bread rolls. They are sometimes sweet and may contain dried fruit or spices.
Buns are small sweet cakes. They often have icing on the top.
If a woman has her hair in a bun, she has fastened it tightly on top of her head or at the back of her head in the shape of a ball

voca.title: bunch
voca.means:
[^번취]
다발, 묶음, 송이
(양, 수가) 많음, (한 무리의) 사람들
갈래머리
단단해지다, 단단하게 만들다,
voca.explains:
A bunch of people is a group of people who share one or more characteristics or who are doing something together.
A bunch of flowers is a number of flowers with their stalks held or tied together.
A bunch of bananas or grapes is a group of them growing on the same stem.
A bunch of keys is a set of keys kept together on a metal ring.
A bunch of things is a number of things, especially a large number.

voca.title: bundle
voca.means:
[^번덜]
꾸러미, 묶음, 보따리, 
묶음, 다발, 덩어리
끼워팔다, ~을 다발짓다, 짐을 꾸리다
voca.explains:
A bundle of things is a number of them that are tied together or wrapped in a cloth or bag so that they can be carried or stored.
If you describe someone as, for example, a bundle of fun, you are emphasizing that they are full of fun. If you describe someone as a bundle of nerves, you are emphasizing that they are very nervous.
If you refer to a bundle of things, you are emphasizing that there is a wide range of them.
If someone is bundled somewhere, someone pushes them there in a rough and hurried way.
To bundle software means to sell it together with a computer, or with other hardware or software, as part of a set.

voca.title: bundle something up
voca.explains: to make somebody feel warmer by putting warm clothes on them or covering them with blankets\n

voca.title: bundle up
voca.explains:
Because of the weather, it's important to bundle up.
My mother always tells me to bundle up.
If you don't bundle up, you might catch a cold.

voca.title: bungle
voca.explains: If you bungle something, you fail to do it properly, because you make mistakes or are clumsy.\n

voca.title: bungle up
voca.explains:
Someone bungled up the reservation.
I bungled up the dish.
You will bungle up the interview unless you prepare.

voca.title: bunk
voca.explains: A bunk is a bed that is fixed to a wall, especially in a ship or caravan.\nIf you describe something as bunk, you think that it is foolish or untrue.\n

voca.title: bunk off
voca.explains: to stay away from school or work when you ought to be there; to leave school or work early, especially without permission\n

voca.title: burden
voca.means: [붜-r든]\n부담, 부담감, 짐, 책임\n부담/짐을 지우다, (무거운) 짐을 나르다
voca.explains:
If you describe a problem or a responsibility as a burden, you mean that it causes someone a lot of difficulty, worry, or hard work.
A burden is a heavy load that is difficult to carry.
If someone burdens you with something that is likely to worry you, for example a problem or a difficult decision, they tell you about it.

voca.title: burdensome
voca.means: [^버r든썸]\n부담스러운, 힘든\n(견딜 수 없이) 부담이 되는, 귀찮은, 성가신, 고된, 어려운
voca.explains: If you describe something as burdensome, you mean it is worrying or hard to deal with.\nAlso, more and more couples are having just one child. That’s because the cost of raising a child is very burdensome. There is even a new term, “DINK.” It is an acronym for “double income, no kids.” It refers to couples without kids who both work.\n

voca.title: bureau
voca.means:
[뷰어로우]
(보통 뚜껑을 여닫을 수 있는) 책상, 침실용 옷장
(특정 주제에 대한 정보를 제공하는) 사무실, 단체
~국, 부, 사무국,
voca.explains:
A bureau is an office, organization, or government department that collects and distributes information.
A bureau is an office of a company or organization which has its main office in another town or country.
A bureau is a writing desk with shelves and drawers and a lid that opens to form the writing surface.
A bureau is a chest of drawers.

voca.title: burglar
voca.explains: A burglar is a thief who enters a house or other building by force.\n

voca.title: burglary
voca.means: [버r글뤄뤼]\n강도죄, 주거 침입, 가택 침입 강도, 빈집털이
voca.explains: If someone commits a burglary, they enter a building by force and steal things. Burglary is the act of doing this.\n

voca.title: burial
voca.explains: A burial is the act or ceremony of putting a dead body into a grave in the ground.\n

voca.title: burlap
voca.explains: Burlap is a thick, rough fabric that is used for making sacks.\n

voca.title: burn
voca.means:
[^버r언]
(불이) 타오르다, 타다, ~을 불태우다
태워 없애다, 데다, 화상을 입다
화끈 거리다, 열이 많이 나다
화상, 덴 상처(자국)
voca.explains:
burn / char / blacken / scald / scorch / singe
If there is a fire or a flame somewhere, you say that there is a fire or flame burning there.
If something is burning, it is on fire.
If you burn something, you destroy or damage it with fire.
If you burn a fuel or if it burns, it is used to produce heat, light, or energy.
If you burn something that you are cooking or if it burns, you spoil it by using too much heat or cooking it for too long.
If you burn part of your body, burn yourself, or are burnt, you are injured by fire or by something very hot.
If someone is burnt or burnt to death, they are killed by fire.
If you are burning with an emotion or are burning to do something, you feel that emotion or the desire to do that thing very strongly.

voca.title: burn down
voca.explains: if a building burns down, or somebody burns it down, it is destroyed by fire\nif a fire burns down, it becomes less strong and burns with smaller flames\n

voca.title: burn out
voca.means: 에너지를 소진하다, 소진하게 만들다\n(가열되어) 고장이 나다, 나게 하다\n다 타다, 다 타고 꺼지다
voca.explains: to stop burning because there is no more fuel\nif a machine or part of a machine burns out or somebody/something burns it out, it stops working because it has been used too much or has got too hot\n

voca.title: burn the midnight oil
voca.explains:
I am a night owl, so sometimes I like to burn the midnight oil. But when I sit at my desk for too long, my shoulders flare up. At times, the pain is so bad, I’m hardly able to move.
They burned the midnight oil before their exams.
There's a lot of time, so you don't need to burn the midnight oil.

voca.title: burn up
voca.explains:
to be destroyed by heat
(usually used in the progressive tenses) to have a fever or a high temperature
if a fire burns up, it gets stronger and has larger flames

voca.title: burnt
voca.explains: Burnt is a past tense and past participle of burn.\n

voca.title: burp
voca.explains: When someone burps, they make a noise because air from their stomach has been forced up through their throat.\n

voca.title: burst
voca.means:
[버r-st]
파열/폭발하다, 부풀어올라 터지다, 갑자기 ~ 하다
(~에 가득) 차있다, (~으로) 터질 듯 하다
파열, 폭발, 째진부분, 돌발, 격발
voca.explains:
explode / blow up / go off / burst / erupt / rupture / implode
If something bursts or if you burst it, it suddenly breaks open or splits open and the air or other substance inside it comes out.
If a dam bursts, or if something bursts it, it breaks apart because the force of the river is too great.
When a door or lid bursts open, it opens very suddenly and violently because someone pushes it or there is great pressure behind it.
A burst of something is a sudden short period of it.
By the time they got to the white dome, he was ready to burst.

voca.title: burst in
voca.explains: to enter a room, a building, etc. suddenly and noisily, interrupting the people who are in it.\nHe apologized for bursting in on our meeting.\n

voca.title: burst into something
voca.explains: to start producing or doing something suddenly and with great force\n

voca.title: burst on/onto
voca.explains: to appear somewhere suddenly in a dramatic or unusual way.\nThey burst onto the bank of a river.\n

voca.title: burst out
voca.explains: open suddenly or violently; make something open in this way.\nThe door burst open.\n

voca.title: bury
voca.means:
[^베어뤼]
(시신을) 묻다, 매장하다, 
파묻다, 매장하다, ~을 감추다, 
(땅속에) 숨기다, 
(흙, 낙엽 등으로) 뒤덮다, 가리다
voca.explains:
To bury something means to put it into a hole in the ground and cover it up with earth.
To bury a dead person means to put their body into a grave and cover it with earth.
If someone says they have buried one of their relatives, they mean that one of their relatives has died.
If you bury something under a large quantity of things, you put it there, often in order to hide it.
If something buries a place or person, it falls on top of them so that it completely covers them and often harms them in some way.
If you bury your head or face in something, you press your head or face against it, often because you are unhappy.
He found a picture of pirate burying a treasure chest.
Jake buried his face in his hands.

voca.title: bury in
voca.explains: Jake buried his face in his hands.\n

voca.title: bus
voca.explains:
A bus is a large motor vehicle which carries passengers from one place to another. Buses drive along particular routes, and you have to pay to travel in them.
When someone is bussed to a particular place or when they bus there, they travel there on a bus.
In some parts of the United States, when children are bused to school, they are transported by bus to a school in a different area so that children of different races can be educated together.

voca.title: bush
voca.explains:
A bush is a large plant which is smaller than a tree and has a lot of branches.
The wild, uncultivated parts of some hot countries are referred to as the bush.
If you tell someone not to beat about the bush, you mean that you want them to tell you something immediately and quickly, rather than in a complicated, indirect way.

voca.title: bushy
voca.explains:
Bushy hair or fur is very thick.
A bushy plant has a lot of leaves very close together.
Merlin raised a bushy eyebrow.

voca.title: business
voca.means: [^비z니s]\n사업, 상업, 장사\n(직장의) 일, 업무, (관여되는) 일, 소관
voca.explains:
Business is work relating to the production, buying, and selling of goods or services.
Business is used when talking about how many products or services a company is able to sell. If business is good, a lot of products or services are being sold and if business is bad, few of them are being sold.
A business is an organization which produces and sells goods or which provides a service.
Business is work or some other activity that you do as part of your job and not for pleasure.
You can use business to refer to a particular area of work or activity in which the aim is to make a profit.
You can use business to refer to something that you are doing or concerning yourself with.
You can use business to refer to important matters that you have to deal with.

voca.title: business card
voca.explains: A person's business card or their card is a small card which they give to other people, and which has their name and details of their job and company printed on it.\n

voca.title: business settings
voca.explains: Business cards are not limited to business settings. Friends exchange them as well.\n

voca.title: business trip
voca.explains:
Korea's bullet train, the KTX, was launched in 2004. I go on business trips often using the KTX. On my last trip, I traveled to Busan.
She was on a business trip in Europe.
He will have to take a business trip next week.

voca.title: bust
voca.means:
[버st]
부수다, 고장내다, 폭발시키다
불시 단속을 벌이다, 급습하다
(계급을) 강등 시키다.
상반신, 흉상, 실패작
(특히 여성의 의류나 신체 치수를 말한때) 가슴(둘레)
voca.explains:
If you bust something, you break it or damage it so badly that it cannot be used.
If someone is busted, the police arrest them.
If police bust a place, they go to it in order to arrest people who are doing something illegal.
A company or fund that is bust has no money left and has been forced to close down.
If a company goes bust, it loses so much money that it is forced to close down.
A bust is a statue of the head and shoulders of a person.
You can use bust to refer to a woman's breasts, especially when you are describing their size.

voca.title: bust on
voca.means: ~을 마구 때리다, ~을 몹시 비판/질책 하다\n~을 웃음 거리로 만들다\n~을 알리다/밀고하다

voca.title: bust something up
voca.explains: to end something such as a meeting or a relationship by disturbing or ruining it\n

voca.title: bustle
voca.explains:
If someone bustles somewhere, they move there in a hurried way, often because they are very busy.
A place that is bustling with people or activity is full of people who are very busy or lively.
Bustle is busy, noisy activity.

voca.title: busy
voca.means:
[^비지]
(할 일이 많아) 바쁜, (~하느라) 바쁜, ~에 열심인
통화중인
붐비는, 번화한, 사용중인
voca.explains:
When you are busy, you are working hard or concentrating on a task, so that you are not free to do anything else.
A busy time is a period of time during which you have a lot of things to do.
If you say that someone is busy thinking or worrying about something, you mean that it is taking all their attention, often to such an extent that they are unable to think about anything else.
A busy place is full of people who are doing things or moving about.
When a telephone line is busy, you cannot make your call because the line is already being used by someone else.
If you busy yourself with something, you occupy yourself by dealing with it.

voca.title: but
voca.means:
[벗t]
그러나, 하지만, 그렇지만
~ 이외에, ~을 빼고/제외하고
단지, 다만, 겨우
voca.explains:
You use but to introduce something which contrasts with what you have just said, or to introduce something which adds to what you have just said.
You use but when you are about to add something further in a discussion or to change the subject.
You use but after you have made an excuse or apologized for what you are just about to say.
You use but to introduce a reply to someone when you want to indicate surprise, disbelief, refusal, or protest.
But is used to mean 'except'.
But is used to mean 'only'.
You use buts in expressions like 'no buts' and 'ifs and buts' to refer to reasons someone gives for not doing something, especially when you do not think that they are good reasons.

voca.title: but (ever) now
voca.means: 지금은, 이제는, 하지만, 그러나 현재, 사실

voca.title: but then
voca.means: 아니 정반대로, \n그도 그럴 것이\n하기는, 하지만 또

voca.title: butcher
voca.means:
[^붓쳐r]
정육점 주인, 도살업자
정육점
잔인하게 살해하다, 학살하다
~을 엉망진창으로 만들다
voca.explains:
A butcher is a shopkeeper who cuts up and sells meat. Some butchers also kill animals for meat and make foods such as sausages and meat pies.
You can refer to someone as a butcher when they have killed a lot of people in a very cruel way, and you want to express your horror and disgust.
A butcher or a butcher's is a shop where meat is sold.
To butcher an animal means to kill it and cut it up for meat.
You can say that someone has butchered people when they have killed a lot of people in a very cruel way, and you want to express your horror and disgust.
Then we went to the butcher's counter for beef and pork.

voca.title: butter
voca.explains: Butter is a soft yellow substance made from cream. You spread it on bread or use it in cooking.\nIf you butter something such as bread or toast, you spread butter on it.\n

voca.title: butter somebody up
voca.explains: to say nice things about somebody because you want them to do something for you or give you something\n

voca.title: butterfingers
voca.explains: a person who drops things inadvertently or fails to catch things\nMy hand-eye coordination is not very good. I have butterfingers. I am constantly dropping things.\n

voca.title: buttock
voca.explains: Your buttocks are the two rounded fleshy parts of your body that you sit on.\n

voca.title: button
voca.means:
[벋은]
(옷의) 단추, (기계 작동을 위해 노르는) 버튼
(글자가 새겨진) 배지
단추를 잠그다, 단추로 잠그게 되어 있다
voca.explains:
Buttons are small hard objects sewn on to shirts, coats, or other pieces of clothing. You fasten the clothing by pushing the buttons through holes called buttonholes.
A button is a small object on a machine or electrical device that you press in order to operate it.
A button is a small piece of metal or plastic which you wear in order to show that you support a particular movement, organization, or person. You fasten a button to your clothes with a pin.
If you button a shirt, coat, or other piece of clothing, you fasten it by pushing its buttons through the buttonholes.
He pulled it arund his shoulders and buttoned it at the neck.

voca.title: buy
voca.means: [바-이]\n사다, 사 주다, 구입하다\n(돈으로) 매수하다, (대가를 치르고) 얻다
voca.explains:
buy - bought - bought
If you buy something, you obtain it by paying money for it.
If you talk about the quantity or standard of goods an amount of money buys, you are referring to the price of the goods or the value of the money.
If you buy something like time, freedom, or victory, you obtain it but only by offering or giving up something in return.
If you say that a person can be bought, you are criticizing the fact that they will give their help or loyalty to someone in return for money.
If you buy an idea or a theory, you believe and accept it.
If something is a good buy, it is of good quality and not very expensive.

voca.title: buy somebody off
voca.explains: to pay somebody to stop them acting against you, causing trouble for you, etc.\n

voca.title: buy something in
voca.explains: to buy something or a large amount of something for a special occasion or in order to have a supply for the future\n

voca.title: buy something up
voca.explains: to buy quickly all of something or as much as you can\n

voca.title: buzz
voca.means:
[^버-z]
윙윙거리다, 윙하는 소리를 내다
부산스럽다, 활기가 넘치다
윙윙거림, 웅성거림, 수군거림,
voca.explains:
If something buzzes or buzzes somewhere, it makes a long continuous sound, like the noise a bee makes when it is flying.
If people are buzzing around, they are moving around quickly and busily.
If questions or ideas are buzzing around your head, or if your head is buzzing with questions or ideas, you are thinking about a lot of things, often in a confused way.
If a place is buzzing with activity or conversation, there is a lot of activity or conversation there, especially because something important or exciting is about to happen.
If an aircraft buzzes a place, it flies low over it, usually in a threatening way.
You can use buzz to refer to a long continuous sound, usually caused by lots of people talking at once.
"Pizza? Pizza! For real?" The room buzzed with excitement.

voca.title: buzz in
voca.explains: to let somebody enter a building by opening the door using an electronic device\n

voca.title: buzz off
voca.explains: used to tell somebody, not very politely, to go away\n

voca.title: buzzword
voca.explains:
A buzzword is a word or expression that has become fashionable in a particular field and is being used a lot by the media.
The biggest buzzword in the movie industry these days is 3D or 4D.
That isn't a buzzword anymore.
I made a list of buzzwords.

voca.title: by accident
voca.explains: in a way that is not planned or organized\n

voca.title: by and large
voca.explains: used when you are saying something that is generally, but not completely, true\n

voca.title: by any chance
voca.explains:
used especially in questions, to ask whether something is true, possible, etc
Jason: Really? Can you put my name on the waiting list by any chance?
You can also use 'possibly' or 'do you happen to ~'.

voca.title: by attorney
voca.explains: She is allowed to take his mom's money by attorney.\n

voca.title: by chance
voca.explains:
Some were very memorable. I discovered my favorite hotel by chance. It’s not a ritzy or high-end place. Other hotels are more luxurious. But my favorite place strikes the perfect balance between price, service and amenities.
We met each other by chance.
I learned about the movie by chance.

voca.title: by choice
voca.explains: because you have chosen\n

voca.title: by default
voca.means: (달리 손을 쓰지 않아서) 자연스럽게/자동적으로\n(경기, 시함에서) 부전승으로
voca.explains: if something happens by default, it happens because you have not made any other decision or choices which would make things happen differently\na game or competition can be won by default if there are no other competitors\n

voca.title: by degrees
voca.explains:
little by little; gradually
I painted the whole house by degrees.
Mark : We'll fix the place up ourselves by degrees.

voca.title: by fair means or foul
voca.explains: even if unfair methods are used\n

voca.title: by far
voca.explains: by a very great amount; much\n

voca.title: by hand
voca.means: (기계가 아닌) 사람의 손으로\n(편지 전달이 우편으로가 아닌) 인편으로
voca.explains: if a letter is delivered by hand, it is delivered by the person who wrote it, or by messenger rather than by post\nmade/done without using machinery\n

voca.title: by happy coincidence
voca.explains: By happy coincidence, we visited during a local festival. It was a prawn festival. Everyone in my family loves seafood, so we were in seventh heaven.\n

voca.title: by heart
voca.explains: using only your memory\n

voca.title: by lot
voca.explains: using a method of choosing somebody to do something in which each person takes a piece of paper, etc. from a container and the one whose paper has a special mark is chosen\n

voca.title: by me
voca.explains: There's a park by me. We can play tennis there.\n

voca.title: by means of something
voca.explains: with the help of something\n

voca.title: by mistake
voca.explains: accidentally; without intending to\n

voca.title: by name
voca.explains: using the name of somebody/something\n

voca.title: by popular demand
voca.explains: because a lot of people have asked for something\n

voca.title: by the book
voca.explains: strictly following the rules or the official way of doing something\n

voca.title: by the end of the week
voca.explains:
I’ll have it done by the end of the week.
I’ll be back by the end of the week.
He’ll call you by the end of the week.

voca.title: by the name of
voca.explains: who is called\n

voca.title: by the time
voca.explains: By the time they got to the white dome, he was ready to burst.\nThe majority of the ceremonies take place in the last week of December. They are aired live. By the time they wrap up, it's often very late.\n

voca.title: by the way
voca.explains:
used for introducing something you have just thought of, which may or may not be connected to what has just been said
used for saying that something is not important in the present situation or discussion
This very famous expression is used to give more information or when an idea popped in your brain while you were talking about something else or something related. You can also say 'one more thing'.

voca.title: by then
voca.explains: B : So I have to be better by then.\n

voca.title: by way of something
voca.explains: passing through a place\nas a kind of something; as something\n

voca.title: bypass
voca.means:
[^바이페-s]
우회 도로
(수술) 우회 혈관, 심장동맥두름길 
우회하다 
(정해진 절차, 순서를 거치지 않고) 건너뛰다
voca.explains:
If you bypass someone or something that you would normally have to get involved with, you ignore them, often because you want to achieve something more quickly.
If a surgeon bypasses a diseased artery or other part of the body, he or she performs an operation so that blood or other bodily fluids do not flow through it.
If a road bypasses a place, it goes around it rather than through it.
If you bypass a place when you are travelling, you avoid going through it.
A bypass is a surgical operation performed on or near the heart, in which the flow of blood is redirected so that it does not flow through a part of the heart which is diseased or blocked.
A bypass is a main road which takes traffic around the edge of a town rather than through its centre.

voca.title: cab
voca.explains:
A cab is a taxi.
The cab of a truck or train is the front part in which the driver sits.
A : I'm at the station. I'm so sorry for being late, but the train was late. I'm waiting for a cab.

voca.title: cabbage
voca.explains: A cabbage is a round vegetable with white, green or purple leaves that is usually eaten cooked.\n

voca.title: cabin
voca.explains:
A cabin is a small room in a ship or boat.
A cabin is one of the areas inside a plane.
A cabin is a small wooden house, especially one in an area of forests or mountains.

voca.title: cabin fever
voca.explains:
