acute depression resulting from being isolated or sharing cramped quarters in the wilderness, esp during the long northern winter
If I stay in this house one more day I'm going to have cabin fever.
Ken : Yesterday I had cabin fever so bad I yelled at my family for no reason at all.

voca.title: cabinet
voca.means:
[케버넛t]
내각, 국무, 각료, 
장식장, 장롱, 찬장
내각의, 비밀의, 기밀의
voca.explains: A cabinet is a cupboard used for storing things such as medicine or alcoholic drinks or for displaying decorative things in.\nThe Cabinet is a group of the most senior ministers in a government, who meet regularly to discuss policies.\n

voca.title: cackle
voca.explains: If someone cackles, they laugh in a loud unpleasant way, often at something bad that happens to someone else.\nThe creatures cackled and rattled and hissed.\n

voca.title: cactus
voca.explains: A cactus is a thick fleshy plant that grows in many hot, dry parts of the world. Cacti have no leaves and many of them are covered in prickles.\n

voca.title: caesarean
voca.explains: A Caesarean or a Caesarean section is an operation in which a baby is lifted out of a woman's womb through an opening cut in her abdomen.\n

voca.title: cage
voca.explains: A cage is a structure of wire or metal bars in which birds or animals are kept.\nIf someone rattles your cage, they do something which is intended to make you feel nervous.\n

voca.title: cake
voca.means:
[^케익k]
케이크, (둥글 납작하게 만든) 빵
(얇고 납작한) 단단한 덩어리, 
(마르면 딱딱해 지는 것을) 두껍게 바르다,
(마르면서) 딱딱해 지다
들러붙다, 뭉쳐지다, 덩어리지다
voca.explains:
A cake is a sweet food made by baking a mixture of flour, eggs, sugar, and fat in an oven. Cakes may be large and cut into slices or small and intended for one person only.
Food that is formed into flat round shapes before it is cooked can be referred to as cakes.
A cake of soap is a small block of it.
If you think that someone wants the benefits of doing two things when it is only reasonable to expect the benefits of doing one, you can say that they want to have their cake and eat it.
If you think something is very easy to do, you can say it is a piece of cake. People often say this to stop someone feeling worried about doing something they have to do.
If someone has done something very stupid, rude, or selfish, you can say that they take the cake or that what they have done takes the cake, to emphasize your surprise at their behaviour.

voca.title: calculate
voca.explains: If you calculate a number or amount, you discover it from information that you already have, by using arithmetic, mathematics, or a special machine.\nIf you calculate the effects of something, especially a possible course of action, you think about them in order to form an opinion or decide what to do.\n

voca.title: calculate on
voca.explains: to depend or rely on something happening or being true, especially as part of a plan\n

voca.title: calculus
voca.explains: Calculus is a branch of advanced mathematics which deals with variable quantities.\n

voca.title: calf
voca.explains:
A calf is a young cow.
Some other young animals, including elephants and whales, are called calves.
Your calf is the thick part at the back of your leg, between your ankle and your knee.

voca.title: calisthenics
voca.explains: Calisthenics are simple exercises that you can do to keep fit and healthy.\n

voca.title: call
voca.means:
[^코올]
이름을 지어주다, ~라고 부르다,/칭하다, 
~라고 묘사하다, 여기다, 
부르다, 전화하다
전화(통화), 들름, 방문, 요청, 요구
voca.explains:
call / cry out / exclaim / blurt / burst out
If you call someone or something by a particular name or title, you give them that name or title.
If you call someone or something a particular thing, you suggest they are that thing or describe them as that thing.
If you call something, you say it in a loud voice, because you are trying to attract someone's attention.
If you call someone, you telephone them.
If you call someone such as a doctor or the police, you ask them to come to you, usually by telephoning them.
If you call someone, you ask them to come to you by shouting to them.
When you make a telephone call, you telephone someone.
If there is a call for something, someone demands that it should happen.

voca.title: call for a taxi
voca.explains:
When you're in a rush, it can be tough to catch a taxi. Nowadays, many people use a messaging app to call for a taxi.
You should call for a taxi since there aren't any buses at this hour.
Do you want to walk, or call for a taxi?

voca.title: call for something
voca.explains:
Online accounts are susceptible to hacking. Privacy leaks can even hit major sites or servers. Experts call for stronger security measures.
In Korea, cash is a common and widely-accepted gift. Many different occasions call for cash gifts. For example, elderly parents often receive pocket money from their children.
Nowadays, internet and mobile banking are the norm. Trips to the bank are few and far between. Even so, some services call for a visit. Certain tasks require sitting face to face with a teller.
The victory calls for a celebration.
Desperate times call for desperate measures.

voca.title: call in sick
voca.means: 아파서 못나가겠다고 전화하다\n전화로 병결을 알리다\n병가를 내다
voca.explains:
I have to call in sick because my cold is getting worse.
Dina: Yes. If I don't feel better in the morning I'll call in sick.
A : Hi, Mina, this is Jason, and I need to call in sick today.

voca.title: call it a day
voca.explains: decide to stop doing something, especially something you have been doing for a long time\nA : Let’s call it a day, Cindy.\n

voca.title: call it quits
voca.means: 무승부로 하다, 비긴것으로 하다\n~을 그만하기로 하다
voca.explains:
decide to end an argument, a disagreement, etc. at a point where both sides are equal
It's five o'clock. I'm going to call it quits and go home.
Terry: Just one more mile and I'm calling it quits.

voca.title: call on
voca.explains: to visit somebody for a short time\nto ask somebody in a class, etc. to answer a question or give their opinion\n

voca.title: call somebody off
voca.explains: to order soldiers, dogs, etc. to stop attacking somebody, searching for somebody/something, etc.\n

voca.title: call somebody out
voca.means: (특히 위급한 상황에서) ~를 부르다, 호출하다\n파업을 명하다, 권하다
voca.explains:
to ask somebody to come to help you, when there is an emergency
to order or ask workers to stop work as a protest
(for something) to criticize somebody's actions

voca.title: call somebody up
voca.means: ~에게 전화를 걸다\n(군대에) ~를 소집하다\n(특히 국가간 경기에) ~를 출전시키다
voca.explains:
to officially ask somebody to go to do training in the army, navy or air force or to fight in a war
to ask somebody to join something or take part in something; to choose somebody to play in a team
to bring a player from a minor league team onto a major league team
Without further ado, we called up a repairman. The repairman arrived and worked his magic. He gave the air conditioner a once-over. Then he got to work.

voca.title: call someone in
voca.explains: He called me in to tell me about the company picnic.\n

voca.title: call something off
voca.explains:
to cancel or abandon something that has been planned or that has already started
Let’s call off our schedule.
Eric: Hmm… Sure, thanks. 80% is very high! Do you think I should call the guys to call off the plan?

voca.title: call something up
voca.explains:
to obtain information that is stored on a computer
to bring something back to your mind; to make you remember and think about something
to use a quality that you have

voca.title: call well in advance
voca.explains:
The most popular places require reservations. You need to call well in advance to make a reservation.
I called well in advance, but there were no tickets.
You will be fine if you call well in advance.

voca.title: calm
voca.explains:
calm / calmness
A calm person does not show or feel any worry, anger, or excitement.
If someone says that a place is calm, they mean that it is free from fighting or public disorder, when trouble has recently occurred there or had been expected.
If the sea or a lake is calm, the water is not moving very much and there are no big waves.
Calm weather is pleasant weather with little or no wind.
If you calm someone, you do something to make them feel less angry, worried, or excited.
To calm a situation means to reduce the amount of trouble, violence, or panic there is.
He felt calm and safe as the stag sped like a white comet throught the wintry countryside.
A : It'll help calm your cough.

voca.title: calm down
voca.explains: to become calmer; to make a situation calmer\nif somebody calms down, or you calm them down, they stop being angry or excited and become calm\n

voca.title: calorie
voca.means: [^캴로뤼]\n열량, 칼로리(식품의 에너지를 측정하는 단위)\n칼로리(열량을 측정하는 단위)
voca.explains: Calories are units used to measure the energy value of food. People who are on diets try to eat food that does not contain many calories.\n

voca.title: camel
voca.explains: A camel is a large animal that lives in deserts and is used for carrying goods and people. Camels have long necks and one or two lumps on their backs called humps.\n

voca.title: camera
voca.explains:
A camera is a piece of equipment that is used for taking photographs, making films, or producing television pictures
If someone or something is on camera, they are being filmed.
If you do something or if something happens off camera, you do it or it happens when not being filmed.
If a trial is held in camera, the public and the press are not allowed to attend.
I’m a big fan of taking selfies. Some might say that I am a selfie enthusiast. Taking selfies is a snap these days because most smartphones are equipped with cameras.

voca.title: camouflage
voca.means:
[케뭐플롸쥐]
(군인, 장비의) 위장, 변장, 속임수
(보호색이나 형태 등을 통한 동물들의) 위장
위장하다, 변장하다
voca.explains:
hide / conceal / cover / disguise / mask / camouflage
Camouflage consists of things such as leaves, branches, or brown and green paint, which are used to make it difficult for an enemy to see military forces and equipment.
If military buildings or vehicles are camouflaged, things such as leaves, branches, or brown and green paint are used to make it difficult for an enemy to see them.
If you camouflage something such as a feeling or a situation, you hide it or make it appear to be something different.
This is called camouflage.

voca.title: camp
voca.means:
[케엠p]
야양지, 텐트, 수용소, (군인들의) 막사
야영하다,
(남의 집에서, 잠깐) 머둘다, 지내다
voca.explains:
A camp is a collection of huts and other buildings that is provided for a particular group of people, such as refugees, prisoners, or soldiers, as a place to live or stay.
A camp is an outdoor area with buildings, tents, or caravans where people stay on holiday.
A camp is a collection of tents or caravans where people are living or staying, usually temporarily while they are travelling.
You can refer to a group of people who all support a particular person, policy, or idea as a particular camp.
If you camp somewhere, you stay or live there for a short time in a tent or caravan, or in the open air.
If you describe someone's behaviour, performance, or style of dress as camp, you mean that it is exaggerated and amusing, often in a way that is thought to be typical of some male homosexuals.

voca.title: camp out
voca.means: 진을 치다, 야영하다\n(집 밖) 다른 곳에서 (오랜 시간) 있다 캠핑하다
voca.explains: to sleep outside, usually in a tent; to sleep on the floor somewhere for a short time\nWe camped out in the desert under the stars. It was great.\n

voca.title: campaign
voca.means: [템페인]\n캠패인, (사회, 정치적 목적을 위한 조직적인) 운동/활동, \n선거운동, 군사행동
voca.explains:
campaign / battle / struggle / drive / war / fight
A campaign is a planned set of activities that people carry out over a period of time in order to achieve something such as social or political change.
In a war, a campaign is a series of planned movements carried out by armed forces.
If someone campaigns for something, they carry out a planned set of activities over a period of time in order to achieve their aim.

voca.title: campus
voca.explains: A campus is an area of land that contains the main buildings of a university or college.\n

voca.title: can never get enough
voca.explains:
I can never get enough seafood. The fish market is one of my favorite places to visit. I recently went there with some friends for some raw fish.
I can never get enoug of his music.
We can never get enough of that show.

voca.title: can of worms
voca.means: 까다로운 상황, 골칫거리\n뜻밖의(복잡하고 까다로운) 여러 가지 문제(상황)의 불씨(소지).
voca.explains:
Parents’ birthdays can be a real can of worms. Don’t get me wrong. I love my parents. I enjoy celebrating their birthdays. But the fly in the ointment is shopping for their gifts.
Arguing with her is a real can of worms.
He's opening up a can of worms.

voca.title: canal
voca.explains: A canal is a long, narrow stretch of water that has been made for boats to travel along or to bring water to a particular area.\nA canal is a narrow tube inside your body for carrying food, air, or other substances.\n

voca.title: cancel
voca.means: [켄슬]\n취소하다, 철회하다, 정지/중지하다, 무효화 하다\n취소, 파기, 삭제
voca.explains:
If you cancel something that has been arranged, you stop it from happening. If you cancel an order for goods or services, you tell the person or organization supplying them that you no longer wish to receive them.
If someone in authority cancels a document, an insurance policy, or a debt, they officially declare that it is no longer valid or no longer legally exists.
To cancel a stamp or a cheque means to mark it to show that it has already been used and cannot be used again.

voca.title: cancel out
voca.explains: if two or more things cancel out or one cancels out the other, they are equally important, but have an opposite effect on a situation so that the situation does not change\n

voca.title: cancellation
voca.explains: Assistant: Yes, I'll let you know if there's a cancellation.\n

voca.title: cancer
voca.explains: Cancer is a serious disease in which cells in a person's body increase rapidly in an uncontrolled way, producing abnormal growths.\nCancer is one of the twelve signs of the zodiac. Its symbol is a crab. People who are born approximately between the 21st of June and the 22nd of July come under this sign.\n

voca.title: candidate
voca.explains:
A candidate is someone who is being considered for a position, for example someone who is running in an election or applying for a job.
A candidate is someone who is taking an examination.
A candidate is someone who is studying for a degree at a college.
A candidate is a person or thing that is regarded as being suitable for a particular purpose or as being likely to do or be a particular thing.
That’s why everyone must do their part. People in Korea gather information in many ways. They pore over newspapers. They follow the news. They weigh the pros and cons of the candidates.

voca.title: candle
voca.explains:
A candle is a stick of hard wax with a piece of string called a wick through the middle. You light the wick in order to give a steady flame that provides light.
If you burn the candle at both ends, you try to do too many things in too short a period of time so that you have to stay up very late at night and get up very early in the morning to get them done.
He pictured a beautiful, glowing castle lit with candles and filled with knights and ladies feasting and singing.

voca.title: cane
voca.means: [케인]\n(대나무처럼 속이 빈)줄기, 지팡이, 막대기, 사탕수수\n회초리(막대기)로 때리다
voca.explains:
Cane is used to refer to the long, hollow, hard stems of plants such as bamboo. Strips of cane are often used to make furniture, and some types of cane can be crushed and processed to make sugar.
A cane is a long thin stick with a curved or round top which you can use to support yourself when you are walking, or which in the past was fashionable to carry with you.
A cane is a long, thin, flexible stick which in the past was used to hit people, especially children at school, as a punishment.

voca.title: canine
voca.explains: Canine means relating to dogs.\n

voca.title: cannon
voca.explains:
A cannon is a large gun, usually on wheels, which used to be used in battles.
A cannon is a heavy automatic gun, especially one that is fired from an aircraft.
If someone is a loose cannon, they do whatever they want and nobody can predict what they are going to do.

voca.title: canoe
voca.explains: A canoe is a small, narrow boat that you move through the water using a stick with a wide end called a paddle.\n"It looks like a canoe" said Jack.\n

voca.title: canopy
voca.means: [케너삐]\n(침대위에 지붕처럼 늘어뜨린) 뎦개\n(숲의 나뭇가지들이) 지붕모양으로 우거진 것
voca.explains:
A canopy is a decorated cover, often made of cloth, which is placed above something such as a bed or a seat.
A canopy is a layer of something that spreads out and covers an area, for example the branches and leaves that spread out at the top of trees in a forest.
They followed Peanut all the way up to the canopy of the rain forest.

voca.title: cant
voca.means: [켄-t]\n(특히 종교, 도덕적인 쟁점에 대해) 위선적인 말\n비스듬하다, 비스듬히 놓다
voca.explains: If you refer to moral or religious statements as cant, you are criticizing them because you think the person making them does not really believe what they are saying.\n

voca.title: can't stand
voca.explains:
Meanwhile, some of my friends can't stand singing. A few of them are completely tone-deaf.
I can't stand people who are rude.
I can't stand this cold weather.

voca.title: can't wait to
voca.explains: This year, I plan to head to the beach. I can’t wait to jump in the water. I want to eat all sorts of seafood and try the local delicacies.\n

voca.title: canteen
voca.explains:
A canteen is a place in a factory, shop, or college where meals are served to the people who work or study there.
A canteen is a small plastic bottle for carrying water and other drinks. Canteens are used by soldiers.
A canteen of cutlery is a set of knives, forks, and spoons in a specially designed box.

voca.title: canter
voca.explains: When a horse canters, it moves at a speed that is slower than a gallop but faster than a trot.\nThe horses neighed and cantered over to the knights.\n

voca.title: capable
voca.means: [케이퍼벌]\n(능력, 특질상) ~을 할 수 있는, 유능한, \n능력있는, 가능성있는, 가능한
voca.explains: If a person or thing is capable of doing something, they have the ability to do it.\nSomeone who is capable has the skill or qualities necessary to do a particular thing well, or is able to do most things well.\n

voca.title: capacity
voca.means:
[커^페시릐]
용량, 수용력, 생산 능력
(~을 이해하거나 할 수 있는) 능력
배기량
voca.explains:
Your capacity for something is your ability to do it, or the amount of it that you are able to do.
The capacity of something such as a factory, industry, or region is the quantity of things that it can produce or deliver with the equipment or resources that are available.
The capacity of a piece of equipment is its size or power, often measured in particular units.
The capacity of a container is its volume, or the amount of liquid it can hold, measured in units such as litres or gallons.
The capacity of a building, place, or vehicle is the number of people or things that it can hold. If a place is filled to capacity, it is as full as it can possibly be.

voca.title: cape
voca.explains:
A cape is a large piece of land that sticks out into the sea from the coast.
A cape is a short cloak.
He had silky feathers for hair, a beak for a nose, sharp claws, and a billowing feathered cape that glistened in the moonlight like shiny black armor.

voca.title: capes
voca.means:
[케입s]
제대로 도정하지 않은 곡물
탈곡 후에도 껍질이 붙어 있는 옥수수
곡식이 충분히 건조되지 않은 때 제분에서 나오는 거친 가루.

voca.title: capital
voca.explains:
Capital is a large sum of money which you use to start a business, or which you invest in order to make more money.
You can use capital to refer to buildings or machinery which are necessary to produce goods or to make companies more efficient, but which do not make money directly.
Capital is the part of an amount of money borrowed or invested which does not include interest.
The capital of a country is the city or town where its government or parliament meets.
If a place is the capital of a particular industry or activity, it is the place that is most famous for it, because it happens in that place more than anywhere else.
Capitals or capital letters are written or printed letters in the form which is used at the beginning of sentences or names. 'T', 'B', and 'F' are capitals.
A capital offence is one that is so serious that the person who commits it can be punished by death.

voca.title: capitalize
voca.explains: If you capitalize on a situation, you use it to gain some advantage for yourself.\nIn business, if you capitalize something that belongs to you, you sell it in order to make money.\n

voca.title: capricorn
voca.means: [캬p릐코r운]\n염소자리, 마갈궁 (황도 십이궁의 열째 자리)\n염소자리 태생인 사람 (생일이 12월 21일~1월 20일경 사이인 사람)
voca.explains: Capricorn is one of the twelve signs of the zodiac. Its symbol is a goat. People who are born approximately between the 22nd of December and the 19th of January come under this sign.\nA Capricorn is a person whose sign of the zodiac is Capricorn.\n

voca.title: captain
voca.explains:
In the army, navy, and some other armed forces, a captain is an officer of middle rank.
The captain of a sports team is the player in charge of it.
The captain of a ship is the sailor in charge of it.
The captain of an aeroplane is the pilot in charge of it.
In the United States and some other countries, a captain is a police officer or fireman of fairly senior rank.
If you captain a team or a ship, you are the captain of it.

voca.title: caption
voca.explains: A caption is the words printed underneath a picture or cartoon which explain what it is about.\nHe read the caption to Annie.\n

voca.title: captive
voca.means:
[켑디v]
사로잡힌, 억류된
달이 어쩔 도리가 없는, 그 자리를 뜰 수가 없는
포로
voca.explains:
prisoner / hostage / captive / detainee / prisoner of war
A captive person or animal is being kept imprisoned or enclosed.
A captive audience is a group of people who are not free to leave a certain place and so have to watch or listen. A captive market is a group of people who cannot choose whether or where to buy things.
If you take someone captive or hold someone captive, you take or keep them as a prisoner.

voca.title: captivity
voca.explains: Captivity is the state of being kept imprisoned or enclosed.\n

voca.title: capture
voca.means:
[켑쳐r]
포로로 잡다, 억류하다, 포획하다
함락시키다, 점유하다, 차지하다
~의 관심/상상력/흥미를 사로잡다
생포, 포획, 함락, 구금, 억류
voca.explains:
If you capture someone or something, you catch them, especially in a war.
If something or someone captures a particular quality, feeling, or atmosphere, they represent or express it successfully.
If something captures your attention or imagination, you begin to be interested or excited by it. If someone or something captures your heart, you begin to love them or like them very much.
If an event is captured in a photograph or on film, it is photographed or filmed.
If you capture something that you are trying to obtain in competition with other people, you succeed in obtaining it.

voca.title: caput
voca.explains: a technical name for the head\nthe main or most prominent part of an organ or structure\n

voca.title: car
voca.explains:
A car is a motor vehicle with room for a small number of passengers.
A car is one of the separate sections of a train.
Railway carriages are called cars when they are used for a particular purpose.

voca.title: carbohydrate
voca.explains: Carbohydrates are substances, found in certain kinds of food, that provide you with energy. Foods such as sugar and bread that contain these substances can also be referred to as carbohydrates.\n

voca.title: carbon
voca.explains: Carbon is a chemical element that diamonds and coal are made up of.\n

voca.title: carbonate
voca.explains: Carbonate is used in the names of some substances that are formed from carbonic acid, which is a compound of carbon dioxide and water.\n

voca.title: carbonated drink
voca.explains:
Drinks were on our grocery list. We got some carbonated drinks and juice.
Carbonated drinks are bad for your health.
I like to drink icy cold carbonated drinks when the weather is hot.

voca.title: cardboard
voca.explains: Cardboard is thick, stiff paper that is used, for example, to make boxes and models.\nHis father shook his head. "I don't understand the appeal of that sugar-coated cardboard. Believe me, all you'll get from that stuff is a mouthful of cavities."\n

voca.title: cardinal
voca.explains:
A cardinal is a high-ranking priest in the Catholic church.
A cardinal is a common North American bird. The male has bright red feathers.
A cardinal rule or quality is the one that is considered to be the most important.

voca.title: cardiologist
voca.explains: A cardiologist is a doctor who specializes in the heart and its diseases.\n

voca.title: cardiovascular
voca.explains: Cardiovascular means relating to the heart and blood vessels.\n

voca.title: care
voca.means: [케어r]\n돌봄, 걱정, 조심, 주의\n걱정하다, 염려하다, 상관하다, 관심을 가지다,
voca.explains:
care/ caution / prudence / discretion / wariness
If you care about something, you feel that it is important and are concerned about it.
If you care for someone, you feel a lot of affection for them.
If you care for someone or something, you look after them and keep them in a good state or condition.
If you say that you do not care for something or someone, you mean that you do not like them.
If you say that someone does something when they care to do it, you mean that they do it, although they should do it more willingly or more often.
Children who are in care are looked after by the state because their parents are dead or unable to look after them properly.
If you do something with care, you give careful attention to it because you do not want to make any mistakes or cause any damage.
Your cares are your worries, anxieties, or fears.

voca.title: career
voca.explains:
work / employment / career / profession / occupation / trade
A career is the job or profession that someone does for a long period of their life.
Your career is the part of your life that you spend working.
Careers advice or guidance in British English, or career advice or guidance in American English, consists of information about different jobs and help with deciding what kind of job you want to do.
If a person or vehicle careers somewhere, they move fast and in an uncontrolled way.
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, the NBA's all-time leading scorer and former basketball superstar who helped lead the LA Lakers to five NBA championships during his decorated career, was honored with the Presidential Medal of Freedom at a White House ceremony.

voca.title: careful
voca.explains:
cautious / careful
If you are careful, you give serious attention to what you are doing, in order to avoid harm, damage, or mistakes. If you are careful to do something, you make sure that you do it.
Careful work, thought, or examination is thorough and shows a concern for details.
If you tell someone to be careful about doing something, you think that what they intend to do is probably wrong, and that they should think seriously before they do it.
If you are careful with something such as money or resources, you use or spend only what is necessary.

voca.title: carefully
voca.explains: She carefully arranged the folds around them.\n

voca.title: careless
voca.explains:
If you are careless, you do not pay enough attention to what you are doing, and so you make mistakes, or cause harm or damage.
If you say that someone is careless of something such as their health or appearance, you mean that they do not seem to be concerned about it, or do nothing to keep it in a good condition.
"But a warning, my boy: you are hasty and careless with your magic rhymes.

voca.title: carelessness
voca.explains: It was just that sort of carelessness that had cost Susie so dearly in Night of the Cornstalker.\n

voca.title: caribou
voca.explains: A caribou is a large north American deer.\n

voca.title: caring
voca.explains:
If someone is caring, they are affectionate, helpful, and sympathetic.
The caring professions are those such as nursing and social work that are involved with looking after people who are ill or who need help in coping with their lives.
And Morgan le Fay looked like the statue of a caring friend.

voca.title: carmaker
voca.explains: Car technology is an important field of research. Carmakers are competing against each other to develop the best new vehicles.\n

voca.title: carnival
voca.explains:
A carnival is a public festival during which people play music and sometimes dance in the streets.
A carnival is a travelling show which is held in a park or field and at which there are machines to ride on, entertainments, and games.
"Wow!" said Arthur. WonderWorld was the best carnival and theme park around.

voca.title: carpenter
voca.explains: A carpenter is a person whose job is making and repairing wooden things.\n

voca.title: carpet
voca.means:
[카r펫t]
카펫, 양탄자
(방의 크기대로 바닥 전체에 까는) 카펫, 융단
융단(처럼 푹신하게 깔린 것)
카펫을 깔다
(~을 융단처럼 푹신하게) 덮다
voca.explains:
A carpet is a thick covering of soft material which is laid over a floor or a staircase.
A carpet of something such as leaves or plants is a layer of them which covers the ground.
If a floor or a room is carpeted, a carpet is laid on the floor.
If the ground is carpeted with something such as leaves or plants, it is completely covered by them.

voca.title: carpool
voca.explains: A car pool is an arrangement where a group of people take turns driving each other to work, or driving each other's children to school. In American English, car pool is sometimes used to refer simply to people travelling together in a car.\n

voca.title: carrot
voca.explains: Carrots are long, thin, orange-coloured vegetables. They grow under the ground, and have green shoots above the ground.\nSomething that is offered to people in order to persuade them to do something can be referred to as a carrot. Something that is meant to persuade people not to do something can be referred to in the same sentence as a 'stick'.\n

voca.title: carry
voca.means:
[^케뤼]
(이동 중이) 들고/데리고 있다. ~을 나르다, 
휴대하다, 가지고 다니다, 가지고가다
실어 나르다, (병을) 옮기다
취급하다, 판매하다
voca.explains:
If you carry something, you take it with you, holding it so that it does not touch the ground.
If you carry something, you have it with you wherever you go.
If something carries a person or thing somewhere, it takes them there.
If a person or animal is carrying a disease, they are infected with it and can pass it on to other people or animals.
If an action or situation has a particular quality or consequence, you can say that it carries it.
If a quality or advantage carries someone into a particular position or through a difficult situation, it helps them to achieve that position or deal with that situation.
This store carries various brands.
I'm sorry, but we don't carry that product.

voca.title: carry away
voca.means: ~을 가져가 버리다, 운반해 가다, \n(파도, 바닷물이 배에서) ~을 휩쓸어 가다\n~의 넋을 잃게 하다, ~을 열중하게 하다, ~을 흥붑시키다
voca.explains: "Don't get carried away," whispered Jake.\n"No, no... Look, Arthur, maybe I have gotten a little carried away lately. I’m sorry. But now my dad says I have to make sure the team works together."\n

voca.title: carry on
voca.explains:
(with something) to continue doing something or moving in a particular direction, without stopping
to manage to continue living or working in your usual way in spite of difficult or unpleasant circumstances
(with something) to continue speaking or doing something after a short pause
to last for a particular time

voca.title: carry out
voca.explains: to do something that you said you would do or that you have been asked to do\nto do and complete a task\n

voca.title: carry over
voca.explains: to delay something until a later time\nto keep something from one situation and use or deal with it in a new situation\n

voca.title: carry something forward
voca.explains: to move a total sum of money, or a total amount, from one page or column to the next, or from one week or year to the next\nto help something to make progress or succeed\n

voca.title: carry something off
voca.explains: if a disease carries somebody off, they die as a result of it\nto capture somebody\n

voca.title: carry something out
voca.explains: to do something that you said you would do or that you have been asked to do\nto do and complete a task\n

voca.title: carry the torch
voca.explains: The parliamentary elections guarantee that anyone can voice their opinion. They carry the torch of Korean democracy.\n

voca.title: carry-on suitcase
voca.explains:
For my vacation last summer, I went to Thailand. I boarded the plane and found my way to my seat. I put my carry-on suitcase in the overhead compartment.
I only need my carry-on suitcase for a short trip.
The wheel on my carry-on suitcase is broken.

voca.title: cart
voca.means: [카r-t]\n카트, 수레, 우마차, \n(수레나 차량으로) 운반하다, ~을 짐차로 나르다
voca.explains:
A cart is an old-fashioned wooden vehicle that is used for transporting goods or people. Some carts are pulled by animals.
A cart is a small vehicle with a motor.
A cart or a shopping cart is a large metal basket on wheels which is provided by shops such as supermarkets for customers to use while they are in the shop.
If you cart things or people somewhere, you carry them or transport them there, often with difficulty.

voca.title: cart away
voca.explains: to take somebody/something away with some difficulty\n

voca.title: carton
voca.means: [^카r은]\n(특히 음식이나 음료를 담는) 곽, 통\n(작게 포장된 것 여러 개가 든 큰) 상자
voca.explains:
A carton is a plastic or cardboard container in which food or drink is sold.
A carton is a large, strong cardboard box in which goods are stored and transported.
They used a crushed mild carton as a puck, hitting it back and forth the lenght of the table.

voca.title: cartoon
voca.explains: A cartoon is a humorous drawing or series of drawings in a newspaper or magazine.\nA cartoon is a film in which all the characters and scenes are drawn rather than being real people or objects.\n

voca.title: carve
voca.explains:
If you carve an object, you make it by cutting it out of a substance such as wood or stone. If you carve something such as wood or stone into an object, you make the object by cutting it out.
If you carve writing or a design on an object, you cut it into the surface of the object.
If you carve a piece of cooked meat, you cut slices from it so that you can eat it.
Jack placed the mango on the M carved into the floor.

voca.title: carve out
voca.means: (명성, 자위 따위를) 노력하여 얻다, 자수성가 하다\n(진로, 토지 따위를) 개척하다, 트다\n자르다, 잘라내다
voca.explains: to make a physical feature in the earth's surface over a long period of time through the action of water, ice, weather, etc.\nto build a successful career, a good reputation, etc., often with difficulty or hard work\n

voca.title: carve something up
voca.explains: to divide a company, an area of land, etc. into parts and share them out\n

voca.title: case
voca.means:
[케이s]
(특정한 상황의) 경우, 실정, 사실, 사건, 
용기, 상자, 통, 
(질병, 부상의) 사례/환자,
voca.explains:
example / case / instance / specimen / illustration
A particular case is a particular situation or incident, especially one that you are using as an individual example or instance of something.
A case is a person or their particular problem that a doctor, social worker, or other professional is dealing with.
If you say that someone is a sad case or a hopeless case, you mean that they are in a sad situation or a hopeless situation.
A case is a crime or mystery that the police are investigating.
The case for or against a plan or idea consists of the facts and reasons used to support it or oppose it.
In law, a case is a trial or other legal inquiry.

voca.title: case in point
voca.means: (논의 중인 문제, 상황 등에) 딱 들어맞는 사례
voca.explains: a clear example of the problem, situation, etc. that is being discussed\n

voca.title: case the joint
voca.means: (범행 계획을 세우기 위해 건물을) 미리 잘 살피다
voca.explains: look carefully around a building so that you can plan how to steal things from it at a later time\n

voca.title: case-sensitive
voca.explains: In computing, if a written word such as a password is case-sensitive, it must be written in a particular form, for example using all capital letters or all small letters, in order for the computer to recognize it.\n

voca.title: cash
voca.explains:
money / cash
Cash is money in the form of notes and coins rather than cheques.
Cash means the same as money, especially money which is immediately available.
If you cash a cheque, you exchange it at a bank for the amount of money that it is worth.

voca.title: cash in
voca.means: 손을 떼다, 청산하다, 일의 결말은 짓다, 성공하다

voca.title: cash up
voca.explains: to count the money that has been taken in a shop/store, restaurant, etc. at the end of the day\n

voca.title: cast
voca.means:
[^케st]
(시선, 미소 등을) 던지다/보내다, 
(빛을) 발하다, (그림자를) 드리우다, 
(뱀이) 허물을 벗다
~을 던지다, 배열하다
(어떤 연극이나 영화의) 출연자들/배역진
주물, 거푸집, 주형
던지기, 배역, 깁스
voca.explains:
The cast of a play or film is all the people who act in it.
A cast is a model that has been made by pouring a liquid such as plaster or hot metal onto something or into something, so that when it hardens it has the same shape as that thing.
A cast is the same as a plaster cast.
To cast an actor in a play or film means to choose them to act a particular role in it.
To cast someone in a particular way or as a particular thing means to describe them in that way or suggest they are that thing.
If you cast your eyes or cast a look in a particular direction, you look quickly in that direction.
If something casts a light or shadow somewhere, it causes it to appear there.
To cast doubt on something means to cause people to be unsure about it.
After you left, Arthur defeated him, but not before Mordred's Dark Wizard cast a spell over the whole kingdom.
A : And he has to put up with a cast on his leg for 3 weeks.
It hurt a lot. I went to the hospital for an X-ray. I learned my wrist was broken, and I had to were a plaster cast.

voca.title: cast one's vote
voca.explains: Korean voters are well-informed and active. Many are encouraging people to cast their vote. A decision can be swayed by the slimmest of margins.\n

voca.title: castle
voca.explains:
A castle is a large building with thick, high walls. Castles were built by important people, such as kings, in former times, especially for protection during wars and battles.
He pictured a beautiful, glowing castle lit with candles and filled with knights and ladies feasting and singing.
"I was looking out a window in the castle and saw a bright flash in the orchard," said Morgan.

voca.title: casual
voca.means:
[^케주얼]
태평스러운(듯한), 무심한, 대충하는, 건성의
격식을 차리지 않는, 임시의, 우연한 
(관계가) 가벼운
임시노동자, 평상복, 파견병
우연한, 격의없는, 평상시의, 무심한, 대충하는
voca.explains:
If you are casual, you are, or you pretend to be, relaxed and not very concerned about what is happening or what you are doing.
A casual event or situation happens by chance or without planning.
Casual clothes are ones that you normally wear at home or on holiday, and not on formal occasions.
Casual work is done for short periods and not on a permanent or regular basis.

voca.title: casual remark
voca.explains: What you mean as a casual remark could be misinterpreted.\n

voca.title: casually
voca.means: [^케-쥬얼뤼]\n우연히, 아무 생각 없이, 무심코, \n훌쩍, 문득, 임시로, 약식으로
voca.explains: Many people tune into radio shows on EBS to learn English. As with most things, EBS programs are most effective when they are used strategically. Tuning in casually is good.\n

voca.title: casualty
voca.explains:
A casualty is a person who is injured or killed in a war or in an accident.
A casualty of a particular event or situation is a person or a thing that has suffered badly as a result of that event or situation.
Casualty is the part of a hospital where people who have severe injuries or sudden illnesses are taken for emergency treatment.

voca.title: cat
voca.explains: A cat is a furry animal that has a long tail and sharp claws. Cats are often kept as pets.\nCats are lions, tigers, and other wild animals in the same family.\n

voca.title: catastrophe
voca.explains: A catastrophe is an unexpected event that causes great suffering or damage.\n

voca.title: catch
voca.means:
[^케엣치]
(움직이는 물체를) 잡다, 받다, 붙잡다, 
별견하다, 때마침 만나다, (병에) 걸리다
잡기, 포획량
voca.explains:
catch - caught - caught
see / spot / catch / glimpse / clap / lay / set eyes on
If you catch a person or animal, you capture them after chasing them, or by using a trap, net, or other device.
If you catch an object that is moving through the air, you seize it with your hands.
If you catch a part of someone's body, you take or seize it with your hand, often in order to stop them going somewhere.
If one thing catches another, it hits it accidentally or manages to hit it.
If something catches on or in an object or if an object catches something, it accidentally becomes attached to the object or stuck in it.
If you catch yourself doing something, especially something surprising, you suddenly become aware that you are doing it.
"We'll paddle out to catch a big wave!" said Boka.

voca.title: catch fire
voca.explains:
My neighbor was using an electric cushion last winter. There was a short circuit, and the cushion caught fire.
An enire forest can catch fire because of just one cigarette.
The whole building caught fire.

voca.title: catch it
voca.explains: be punished or spoken to angrily about something\n

voca.title: catch on
voca.explains: to understand something; to realize the truth of something\nto become popular or fashionable\n

voca.title: catch on with
voca.explains:
These places are catching on with foreign visitors and tourists. Sometimes, some public baths can serve as makeshift motels, because they have areas where you can get some sleep.
Do you think this book will catch on with readers?
The new program soon caught on with youngsters.

voca.title: catch one's breath
voca.explains:
Along the way, I stopped at the exercise equipment to stretch and catch my breath. It was just the right amount of exercise.
Let me first catch my breath.
You should rest for a moment and catch your breath.

voca.title: catch oneself
voca.means: 하던 말/일을 갑자기 멈추다\n몸을 가누다, 균형을 잡다
voca.explains: She liked turtles! But she caught herself just in time. "No. I like toads." Judy cracked up again.\nAnother time, I let my mind wander while I was climbing some stairs. I caught myself as I fell over. However, my wrist bore the brunt of the fall. It swelled up.\n

voca.title: catch somebody out
voca.explains: to trick somebody into making a mistake or doing something wrong; to discover that somebody does not know much or is doing something wrong\nif a situation, bad weather, etc. catches somebody out, it surprises them and puts them into a difficult situation\n

voca.title: catch up
voca.means: (먼저간 사람을) 따라잡다, 따라가다\n(정도나 수준이 앞선 것을) 따라잡다
voca.explains:
to spend extra time doing all the work, tasks, etc. that you should have done earlier
to find out about things that have happened
to reach somebody/something ahead of you by going faster than them/it
to reach the same level or standard as somebody/something else that was better or more advanced
Amy: I'd love to but I've got some catching up to do.
"Exactly. But I never tried to pretend I knew what I was doing again. And you shouldn't, either. Don't be afraid to ask for help or advice. You'll catch up soon enough."

voca.title: catch up on something
voca.means:
(뒤떨어진 일을) 만회하다, 
(소식, 정보를) 일아내다
뒤쳐진 일을 보충하다,
(하지 못했던, 미뤄 뒀던 일 등)을 하다
(~에 대해) 그 뒤의 소식을 듣다
밀린 ~를 보충하다
voca.explains:
to spend extra time doing all the work, tasks, etc. that you should have done earlier
to find out about things that have happened
Linda : I go to the park, walk around, and catch up on reading.
I have a lot of work to catch up on.
I need to catch up on some housework.
I couldn’t sleep a wink for the last three days, so I should catch up on my sleep.

voca.title: catch up with
voca.means: ~을 뒤따라 잡다\n따라가다, 따라잡다, 체포하다.\n~와 밀린 이야기를 하다
voca.explains:
It's nice to catch up with friends.
We meet once a month to catch up with each other.
I want to catch up with you when I see ou tomorrow.

voca.title: catchy
voca.explains: If you describe a tune, name, or advertisement as catchy, you mean that it is attractive and easy to remember.\nAs he fell through the bridge, he could hear D.W. humming. Why couldn’t she have hummed that tune earlier? It was catchy. It had a good beat. He could have played it right across the bridge.\n

voca.title: cater
voca.explains: In British English, to cater for a group of people means to provide all the things that they need or want. In American English, you say you cater to a person or group of people.\nIn British English, to cater for something means to take it into account. In American English, you say you cater to something.\n

voca.title: cater for
voca.explains: to provide everything that somebody, a group of people or a situation needs or wants\n

voca.title: cater to
voca.explains: to provide something that satisfies what a particular type of person wants\n

voca.title: caterer
voca.explains: Caterers are people or companies that provide food and drink for a place such as an office or for special occasions such as weddings and parties.\n

voca.title: caterpillar
voca.explains: A caterpillar is a small, worm-like animal that feeds on plants and eventually develops into a butterfly or moth.\n

voca.title: catnap
voca.explains: A catnap is a short sleep, usually one which you have during the day.\nAfter lunch, I was barely able to keep my eyes open. I kept nodding off. I had to take a quick cat nap in the breakroom.\n

voca.title: cattle
voca.explains: Cattle are cows and bulls.\n

voca.title: caught
voca.explains: Caught is the past tense and past participle of catch.\n

voca.title: cauldron
voca.explains:
A cauldron is a very large, round metal pot used for cooking over a fire. In stories and fairy tales, a cauldron is used by witches for their spells.
There you will find a cauldron.
Over the flames hung a gleaming golden cauldron.

voca.title: causative
voca.explains: Causative factors are ones which are responsible for causing something.\n

voca.title: cause
voca.means: [^커-z]\n원인, 이유, 근거, 까닭, 소송\n원인이 되다, 야기하다, 일으키다
voca.explains:
reason / grounds / excuse / motive / need / justification / cause / pretext
The cause of an event, usually a bad event, is the thing that makes it happen.
If you have cause for a particular feeling or action, you have good reasons for feeling it or doing it.
A cause is an aim or principle which a group of people supports or is fighting for.

voca.title: caution
voca.means:
[^커-션]
조심, 경고
(위험에 대한) 경고/주의문
(~에게) ~하지 말라고 주의/경고를 주다
(다시 ~을 저지르면 처벌될 것임을) ~에게 경고하다
voca.explains:
care/ caution / prudence / discretion / wariness
Caution is great care which you take in order to avoid possible danger.
If someone cautions you, they warn you about problems or danger.
If someone who has broken the law is cautioned by the police, they are warned that if they break the law again official action will be taken against them.
If someone who has been arrested is cautioned, the police warn them that anything they say may be used as evidence in a trial.
If you throw caution to the wind, you behave in a way that is not considered sensible or careful.
Superstitious people believe that broken glass is very unlucky. Some may scoff at such superstitions, but I am not so dismissive. Any custom that encourages caution is valuable in my book.

voca.title: cautionary
voca.explains: A cautionary story or a cautionary note to a story is one that is intended to give a warning to people.\n

voca.title: cautious
voca.explains:
cautious / careful
Someone who is cautious acts very carefully in order to avoid possible danger.
If you describe someone's attitude or reaction as cautious, you mean that it is limited or careful.

voca.title: cautiously
voca.explains: "Are you prepared, Arthur?" Francine asked. Arthur eyed her cautiously. "What do you mean?"\n

voca.title: cave
voca.explains: A cave is a large hole in the side of a cliff or hill, or one that is under the ground.\nThe cave was filled with dancing streams of purple light.\n

voca.title: cave in
voca.explains:
if a roof, wall, etc. caves in, it falls down and towards the centre
to finally do what somebody wants you to do after you have resisted for a long time
The ground caved in and Jack went with it.

voca.title: cavern
voca.explains: At the end of the tunnel was a huge cavern with a high ceiling.\n

voca.title: cavity
voca.explains:
A cavity is a space or hole in something such as a solid object or a person's body.
In dentistry, a cavity is a hole in a tooth, caused by decay.
His father shook his head. "I don't understand the appeal of that sugar-coated cardboard. Believe me, all you'll get from that stuff is a mouthful of cavities."

voca.title: caw
voca.explains: When a bird such as a crow or a rook caws, it makes a loud harsh sound.\nThey were flying toward the mountaintop, cawing madly in alarm.\n

voca.title: cease
voca.explains:
If something ceases, it stops happening or existing.
If you cease to do something, you stop doing it.
If you cease something, you stop it happening or working.

voca.title: ceasefire
voca.explains: A ceasefire is an arrangement in which countries or groups of people that are fighting each other agree to stop fighting.\n

voca.title: ceaseless
voca.explains: If something, often something unpleasant, is ceaseless, it continues for a long time without stopping or changing.\n

voca.title: cedar
voca.explains: A cedar is a large evergreen tree with wide branches and small thin leaves called needles.\nThe cloud spread quickly throughout the great hall, filling the room with wonderful smells-the scent of cedar smoke and evergreen, of roses and almonds.\n

voca.title: ceiling
voca.explains: A ceiling is the horizontal surface that forms the top part or roof inside a room.\nA ceiling on something such as prices or wages is an official upper limit that cannot be broken.\n

voca.title: celebrate
voca.explains:
If you celebrate, you do something enjoyable because of a special occasion or to mark someone's success.
If an organization or country is celebrating an anniversary, it has existed for that length of time and is doing something special because of it.
When priests celebrate Holy Communion or Mass, they officially perform the actions and ceremonies that are involved.

voca.title: celebrate in style
voca.explains:
On our 10th wedding anniversary, my wife and I wanted to celebrate in style.
I don't have enough money to celebrate in style.
We wanted to celebrate in style, but we didn't have time.

voca.title: celebrate the occasion
voca.explains: My family recently moved into a new house. To celebrate the occasion, we invited some friends and co-workers to a housewarming party.\n

voca.title: celebration
voca.explains:
A celebration is a special enjoyable event that people organize because something pleasant has happened or because it is someone's birthday or anniversary.
The celebration of something is praise and appreciation which is given to it.
The Brain read some more. "'We started PAWS to save other kids.' added Millicent's husband, Ed. 'We're having a big rally for concerned parents at the library tomorrow. Afterward, all our supporters-young and old-can join us for a celebration at WonderWorld.'"

voca.title: celebrity
voca.explains:
A celebrity is someone who is famous, especially in areas of entertainment such as films, music, writing, or sport.
If a person or thing achieves celebrity, they become famous, especially in areas of entertainment such as films, music, writing, or sport.
Famous celebrities are often trend-setters.

voca.title: cell
voca.means: [쎄엘]\n세포, 전지, 독방/감방, 칸\n(작은 규모의 정치적 비밀) 조직
voca.explains:
A cell is the smallest part of an animal or plant that is able to function independently. Every animal or plant is made up of millions of cells.
A cell is a small room in which a prisoner is locked. A cell is also a small room in which a monk or nun lives.
You can refer to a small group of people within a larger organization as a cell.

voca.title: cellar
voca.explains: A cellar is a room underneath a building, which is often used for storing things in.\nA person's or restaurant's cellar is the collection of different wines that they have.\n

voca.title: Celsius
voca.explains:
Celsius is a scale for measuring temperature, in which water freezes at 0 degrees and boils at 100 degrees. It is represented by the symbol C.
On the coldest days, it drops to as low as -10 degrees Celsius, or even more.
The summertime weather in Korea can be sweltering. The mercury rises and the humidity is high. It is not out of the ordinary for temperatures to go over 30 degrees Celsius.

voca.title: Celt
voca.means: [켈t]\n켈트족\n켈트족 후예 (특히 아일랜드, 웨일스, 스코틀랜드, 콘월 등)
voca.explains: If you describe someone as a Celt, you mean that they are part of the racial group which comes from Scotland, Wales, Ireland, and some other areas such as Brittany.\n

voca.title: Celtic
voca.explains: If you describe something as Celtic, you mean that it is connected with the people and the culture of Scotland, Wales, Ireland, and some other areas such as Brittany.\n

voca.title: cement
voca.means:
[씨^멘-t]
시멘트 (가루), (굳은) 시멘트
(사람들을) 결속시키는 것
A와 B를 접합시키다
A와 B를 결속시키다, 
A와 B의 관계를 강화하다
voca.explains:
Cement is a grey powder which is mixed with sand and water in order to make concrete.
Cement is the same as concrete.
Glue that is made for sticking particular substances together is sometimes called cement.
Something that cements a relationship or agreement makes it stronger.
If things are cemented together, they are stuck or fastened together.

voca.title: cement one's decision
voca.explains: People in Korea gather information in many ways. They pore over newspapers. They follow the news. They weigh the pros and cons of the candidates. Finally, they cement their decision.\n

voca.title: cemetery
voca.means: [쎄메퉤어뤼]\n(특히 교회 옆에 있지 않은) 묘지, 묘역, 무덤, 공동 묘지
voca.explains: A cemetery is a place where dead people's bodies or their ashes are buried.\n

voca.title: central
voca.explains:
main / major / key / central / principal / chief / prime
Something that is central is in the middle of a place or area.
A place that is central is easy to reach because it is in the centre of a city, town, or particular area.
A central group or organization makes all the important decisions that are followed throughout a larger organization or a country.
The central person or thing in a particular situation is the most important one.

voca.title: century
voca.explains:
A century is a period of a hundred years that is used when stating a date. For example, the 19th century was the period from 1801 to 1900.
A century is any period of a hundred years.
In cricket, a century is a score of one hundred runs or more by one batsman.

voca.title: cereal
voca.means:
[^씨뤼얼]
곡식이 되는 작물, 곡류(벼, 보리, 밀 등)
곡물
시리얼, 가공 곡물
voca.explains: Cereal or breakfast cereal is a food made from grain. It is mixed with milk and eaten for breakfast.\nCereals are plants such as wheat, corn, or rice that produce grain.\n

voca.title: cerebral
voca.explains:
If you describe someone or something as cerebral, you mean that they are intellectual rather than emotional.
Cerebral means relating to the brain.
This chef is incorporating marijuana in 5-star fine dining.
This is a cerebral experience. Whit each bite, you're literally changing your brain chemistry.

voca.title: ceremony
voca.explains:
A ceremony is a formal event such as a wedding.
Ceremony consists of the special things that are said and done on very formal occasions.
If you do something without ceremony, you do it quickly and in a casual way.

voca.title: certain
voca.means:
[^써r-은]
확실한, 틀림없는, 확신하는, 확실한, 
어떤, 무슨 (구체적인 정보 없이 사람, 사물을 언급할 때)
(사람 이름과 함께 쓰여) ~라는
어느정도의, 약간의
voca.explains:
certain / bound / sure / definite / as sured
If you are certain about something, you firmly believe it is true and have no doubt about it. If you are not certain about something, you do not have definite knowledge about it.
If you say that something is certain to happen, you mean that it will definitely happen.
If you say that something is certain, you firmly believe that it is true, or have definite knowledge about it.

voca.title: certain way
voca.explains: His father smiled. "For a few minutes. But then we had to make salad dressing in a blender. Everyone else knew that the lid needed to be locked a certain way. I didn't. So when I turned it on…"\n

voca.title: certainly
voca.explains:
surely / certainly
You use certainly to emphasize what you are saying when you are making a statement.
You use certainly when you are agreeing with what someone has said.
You say certainly not when you want to say 'no' in a strong way.
They are not the healthiest choice, but they certainly do the job when you want a quick bite.

voca.title: certificate
voca.explains:
A certificate is an official document stating that particular facts are true.
A certificate is an official document that you receive when you have completed a course of study or training. The qualification that you receive is sometimes also called a certificate.
"We also have a certificate proclaiming the winner of the Crunch Cereal Jingle Contest."

voca.title: certification
voca.explains: A certificate is an official document stating that particular facts are true.\nA certificate is an official document that you receive when you have completed a course of study or training. The qualification that you receive is sometimes also called a certificate.\n

voca.title: chaildrearing cost
voca.explains: Weddings can cost a fortune. Housing is expensive, too. The high childrearing costs are another disincentive to marriage.\n

voca.title: chain
voca.explains:
A chain consists of metal rings connected together in a line.
If prisoners are in chains, they have thick rings of metal round their wrists or ankles to prevent them from escaping.
A chain of things is a group of them existing or arranged in a line.
A chain of shops, hotels, or other businesses is a number of them owned by the same person or company.
A chain of events is a series of them happening one after another.
If a person or thing is chained to something, they are fastened to it with a chain.

voca.title: chair
voca.explains:
A chair is a piece of furniture for one person to sit on. Chairs have a back and four legs.
At a university, a chair is the post of professor.
The person who is the chair of a committee or meeting is the person in charge of it.
The chair is the same as the electric chair.
If you chair a meeting or a committee, you are the person in charge of it.
As he sat tall and straight in the heavy wooden chair, Jack looked at the king and his knights.
He leaped up from his chair and tried to grab her.

voca.title: chairperson
voca.explains: The chairperson of a meeting, committee, or organization is the person in charge of it.\n

voca.title: chalk
voca.explains:
Chalk is a type of soft white rock. You can use small pieces of it for writing or drawing with.
Chalk is small sticks of chalk, or a substance similar to chalk, used for writing or drawing with.
If you chalk something, you draw or write it using a piece of chalk.

voca.title: challenge
voca.means:
[^췔린지]
도전, 문제, 난제, 이의신청
이의를 제기하다, 도전하다, 의심하다
검문하다,
voca.explains:
A challenge is something new and difficult which requires great effort and determination.
A challenge to something is a questioning of its truth or value. A challenge to someone is a questioning of their authority.
If you challenge ideas or people, you question their truth, value, or authority.
If you challenge someone, you invite them to fight or compete with you in some way.

voca.title: challenged
voca.explains: If you say that someone is challenged in a particular way, you mean that they have a disability in that area. Challenged is often combined with inappropriate words for humorous effect.\n

voca.title: challenging
voca.explains:
difficult / hard / challenging / demanding / taxing / testing
A challenging task or job requires great effort and determination.
If you do something in a challenging way, you seem to be inviting people to argue with you or compete against you in some way.

voca.title: chamber
voca.means:
[췌임버r]
방, 침실, 공무 집행실, 회의장
방에 가두다, 밀어 넣다, 방을 만들다
실내용의, 실내 음악의
voca.explains:
A chamber is a large room, especially one that is used for formal meetings.
You can refer to a country's parliament or to one section of it as a chamber.
A chamber is a room designed and equipped for a particular purpose.

voca.title: chamfer
voca.means: [췜퍼r]\n(직각이 아니라) 약간 경사지게 깍은 모서리, 가각면
voca.explains:
a narrow flat surface at the corner of a beam, post, etc, esp one at an angle of 45° Compare bevel
to cut such a surface on (a beam, etc)
another word for chase

voca.title: champagne
voca.explains: Champagne is an expensive French white wine with bubbles in. It is often drunk to celebrate something.\nA : Can I have a bottle of champagne, filet mignon, medium-rare?\n

voca.title: champion
voca.means:
[쳄피언]
챔피언, 선수권 대회 우슨장
(집단, 신념을 위해 싸우는) 투사, 전사, 옹호자
~을 위해 싸우다, ~을 옹호하다
voca.explains:
A champion is someone who has won the first prize in a competition, contest, or fight.
If you are a champion of a person, a cause, or a principle, you support or defend them.
If you champion a person, a cause, or a principle, you support or defend them.

voca.title: chance
voca.explains:
luck / chance / coincidence / accident / fortune / fate / destiny / providence
If there is a chance of something happening, it is possible that it will happen.
If you have a chance to do something, you have the opportunity to do it.
A chance meeting or event is one that is not planned or expected.
If you chance to do something or chance on something, you do it or find it although you had not planned or tried to.
If you chance something, you do it even though there is a risk that you may not succeed or that something bad may happen.

voca.title: chance your arm
voca.explains: take a risk (especially when you are unlikely to succeed)\n

voca.title: chances
voca.explains: Penny: Chances are it's going to rain tomorrow.\n

voca.title: chances are
voca.explains:
Chances are you’ll see that the coins and bills are beautiful. In fact, they are works of art. They are adorned with symbols of Korea. They include portraits of historical dignitaries. The money is a glimpse into Korea’s past and present.
Chances are she's right.
Chances are he will like it.

voca.title: change
voca.means:
[^췌인쥐]
변하다, 달라지다, ~을 바꾸다
(상태, 위치, 방향이) 바꾸다
변화, 교환, 전환
동전, 잔돈
voca.explains:
If there is a change in something, it becomes different.
If you say that something is a change or makes a change, you mean that it is enjoyable because it is different from what you are used to.
A change of clothes is an extra set of clothes that you take with you when you go to stay somewhere or to take part in an activity.
Your change is the money that you receive when you pay for something with more money than it costs because you do not have exactly the right amount of money.
If you change from one thing to another, you stop using or doing the first one and start using or doing the second.
When something changes or when you change it, it becomes different.

voca.title: change hands
voca.explains: pass to a different owner\n

voca.title: change of pace
voca.explains: Sometimes, for a change of pace, we rearrange the furniture in the apartment.\n

voca.title: change on me
voca.explains: Young: Thanks. I want to buy a newspaper but I don't have any change on me.\nI have change on me. Here, use this for the parking meter.\n

voca.title: change one's itinerary
voca.explains:
You don’t even need a computer. Everything from finding information to booking a flight or hotel can be done on smartphones. Smartphones also make it easier to change one’s itinerary. It can all be done while on the move, and in real time.
Would you like to change your itinerary?
I had to change my itinerary because of a delayed filght.

voca.title: change things up
voca.explains: Last year. I traveled abroad. It was a blast. This year, I’m changing things up. I want to search for hidden gems.\n

voca.title: channel
voca.means:
[^체-늘]
(텔레비전, 라디오의) 채널
주파수대, 채널
(의사소통) 경로, 수단
(물품) 유통 체계/수단
(특히 땅 속, 강바닥 등의) 수로
(강이나 해안가의 배가 다닐 수 있는) 물길
(돈, 감정, 생각 등을) (~에) 쏟다, 돌리다
(돈, 도움 등을) (~을 통해) 보내다
(물, 빛 등을) 나르다, 보내다
voca.explains:
A channel is a television station.
A channel is a band of radio waves on which radio messages can be sent and received.
If you do something through a particular channel, or particular channels, that is the system or organization that you use to achieve your aims or to communicate.
A channel is a passage along which water flows.
A channel is a route used by boats.
The Channel or the English Channel is the narrow area of water between England and France.
If you channel money or resources into something, you arrange for them to be used for that thing, rather than for a wider range of things.
If you channel your energies or emotions into something, you concentrate on or do that one thing, rather than a range of things.

voca.title: channel surfing
voca.explains: When I’m channel surfing, I like to watch home shopping channels. One time, I saw a shirt that was right up my alley. I phoned in and ordered one.\n

voca.title: chant
voca.means:
[^췐t]
(연이어 외치는) 구호, 
(단순하고 반복적인 곡조의) 성가
구호/성가를 (거듭) 외치다, 연호하다
성가를 부르다, (잛은) 기도문을 읍조리다
voca.explains:
A chant is a word or group of words that is repeated over and over again.
A chant is a religious song or prayer that is sung on only a few notes.
If you chant something or if you chant, you repeat the same words over and over again.
If you chant or if you chant something, you sing a religious song or prayer.

The hula is a blend of dancing and chanting poetry.
Kama chanted about going out into the water.

voca.title: chaos
voca.explains: Chaos is a state of complete disorder and confusion.\n

voca.title: chaotic
voca.explains: Something that is chaotic is in a state of complete disorder and confusion.\n

voca.title: chaperon
voca.means:
[^샤뻐로운]
(사교계에 나가는 젊은 여성의) 여성 보호자, 샤프롱
(젊은 여성의) 보호자로서 동반하다(escort)
