voca.explains:
cold / cool / freezing / chilly / lukewarm / tepid
Something that is chilly is unpleasantly cold.
If you feel chilly, you feel rather cold.
You say that relations between people are chilly or that a person's response is chilly when they are not friendly, welcoming, or enthusiastic.
I feel chilly.

voca.title: chime
voca.means: [차임]\n차임을 울리다, (종을) 치다\n차임, 종, 선율, 조화가 잘 된 음
voca.explains:
When a bell or a clock chimes, it makes ringing sounds.
A chime is a ringing sound made by a bell, especially when it is part of a clock.
Chimes are a set of small objects which make a ringing sound when they are blown by the wind.

voca.title: chime in with
voca.explains: to join in a conversation suddenly or interrupt somebody\n

voca.title: chimney
voca.explains: A chimney is a pipe through which smoke goes up into the air, usually through the roof of a building.\nChimney smoke rose into the dusky sky.\n

voca.title: chimpanzee
voca.explains: A chimpanzee is a kind of small African ape.\n

voca.title: chin
voca.explains: Your chin is the part of your face that is below your mouth and above your neck.\nHer father stroked his chin. "It's natural for you to be concerned. After all, he is one of your best friends."\n

voca.title: Chinese
voca.explains: Something that is Chinese relates or belongs to China or its languages or people.\nThe languages that are spoken in China, especially Mandarin, are often referred to as Chinese.\n

voca.title: chip
voca.means:
[^칍]
(그릇이나 연장의) 이가빠진 흔적
(물건에서 떨어져 나간) 조각, 부스러기
감자튀김, 
(도박판의) 칩
이가 빠지다/빠지게 하다
(도구를 써서 조금씩) 쪼다, 깍다
voca.explains:
Chips are long, thin pieces of potato fried in oil or fat and eaten hot, usually with a meal.
Chips or potato chips are very thin slices of fried potato that are eaten cold as a snack.
A silicon chip is a very small piece of silicon with electronic circuits on it which is part of a computer or other piece of machinery.
A chip is a small piece of something or a small piece which has been broken off something.
A chip in something such as a piece of china or furniture is where a small piece has been broken off it.
Chips are plastic counters used in gambling to represent money.
In discussions between people or governments, a chip or a bargaining chip is something of value which one side holds, which can be exchanged for something they want from the other side.
If you chip something or if it chips, a small piece is broken off it.
Arthur went outside, but he wasn’t happy about it. He started rolling a giant snowball. Then he started chipping pieces out of it. The snowball was beginning to look like a giant piece of Crunch cereal.

voca.title: chip in
voca.means: (~을 들먹이며 대화에) 끼어들다, 합류하다\n(돈을) 각출하다, 조금씩 내다
voca.explains:
to join in or interrupt a conversation; to add something to a conversation
to give some money so that a group of people can buy something together
How about getting a bottle of champagne? I'll chip-in a few extra dollars.

voca.title: chiropractor
voca.explains: A chiropractor is a person who treats injuries by chiropractic.\nI twisted my wrist. I also hurt my back. I had to see a chiropractor.\n

voca.title: chirp
voca.explains: When a bird or an insect such as a cricket or grasshopper chirps, it makes short high-pitched sounds.\n

voca.title: chisel
voca.explains: A chisel is a tool that has a long metal blade with a sharp edge at the end. It is used for cutting and shaping wood and stone.\nIf you chisel wood or stone, you cut and shape it using a chisel.\n

voca.title: chitchat
voca.explains: talk of a gossipy nature\nto gossip\n

voca.title: choice
voca.explains:
choice / favourite / preference / selection / pick
If there is a choice of things, there are several of them and you can choose the one you want.
Your choice is someone or something that you choose from a range of things.
Choice means of very high quality.

voca.title: choicest
voca.explains: I recently went to a large discount store with my family. We picked up a lot of fresh produce. My wife likes to pick and choose the choicest vegetables.\n

voca.title: choke
voca.means: [^쵸욱k]\n질식시키다, 막다, 막히다, 숨이 막히다, 목을 조르다\n질식, 사레
voca.explains:
When you choke or when something chokes you, you cannot breathe properly or get enough air into your lungs.
To choke someone means to squeeze their neck until they are dead.
If a place is choked with things or people, it is full of them and they prevent movement in it.
The choke in a car, truck, or other vehicle is a device that reduces the amount of air going into the engine and makes it easier to start.
When his head bobbed up above the water, he choked and coughed.

voca.title: choke on something
voca.explains: I am highly allergic to peanuts. My tonsils swell up and my throat closes up. I sound like I’ve lost my voice or I’m choking on something. To add to the pain, I also break out in hives and hyperventilate.\n

voca.title: choke something back
voca.explains: to try to stop yourself from showing a strong emotion, or saying something that might upset somebody\n

voca.title: choke something off
voca.explains: to prevent or stop something\nto stop or interrupt something\n

voca.title: choke up
voca.explains: to become, or to make somebody, so upset that you/they are unable to speak\n

voca.title: chomp
voca.explains: If a person or animal chomps their way through food or chomps on food, they chew it noisily.\n

voca.title: choose
voca.explains:
choose - chose - chosen
choose / select / pick / opt / go for / single out
If you choose someone or something from several people or things that are available, you decide which person or thing you want to have.
If you choose to do something, you do it because you want to or because you feel that it is right.
"Then you choose your fate," said the Christmas Knight.

voca.title: choose up
voca.means: 선수를 선발하다, 팀을 구성하다\n(선수를 뽑아 팀, 편따위를) 만들다

voca.title: chop
voca.means:
[^챠압]
썰다, 잘게 자르다, 난도질하다
(대폭) 삭감하다, 중단하다
자르기, 절단, 잘라낸 조각
voca.explains: If you chop something, you cut it into pieces with strong downward movements of a knife or an axe.\nA chop is a small piece of meat cut from the ribs of a sheep or pig.\n

voca.title: chop something off
voca.explains: to remove something by cutting it with a sharp heavy tool\n

voca.title: chore
voca.explains:
task / duties / mission / job / assignment / chore
A chore is a task that you must do but that you find unpleasant or boring.
Chores are tasks such as cleaning, washing, and ironing that have to be done regularly at home.
"We've finished our chores," said Kama.
"Our mission has to be harder than just doing chores," said Jack.
In Korea, it’s very easy to take care of bank-related chores. Most of the time, I do my banking on my phone.

voca.title: chorus
voca.means:
[^코r-러s]
후렴, (큰 음악 작품의 일부로서) 합창곡
합창단, 
합창을 하다, 이구동성으로 말하다
voca.explains:
A chorus is a part of a song which is repeated after each verse.
A chorus is a large group of people who sing together.
A chorus is a piece of music written to be sung by a large group of people.
A chorus is a group of singers or dancers who perform together in a show, in contrast to the soloists.
When there is a chorus of criticism, disapproval, or praise, that attitude is expressed by a lot of people at the same time.
As he and Annie sailed down form the mountaintop, a chorus of KRAKs split the night.

voca.title: christen
voca.explains:
When a baby is christened, he or she is given a name during the Christian ceremony of baptism. Compare baptize.
You say that you christen a person, place, or object a particular name if you choose a name for them and start calling them by that name.
You say that you christen something new when you use it for the first time, especially if you do something special to mark the occasion.

voca.title: christianity
voca.explains: Christianity is a religion that is based on the teachings of Jesus Christ and the belief that he was the son of God.\n

voca.title: chromosome
voca.explains: A chromosome is a part of a cell in an animal or plant. It contains genes which determine what characteristics the animal or plant will have.\n

voca.title: chronic
voca.explains:
A chronic illness or disability lasts for a very long time. Compare acute.
You can describe someone's bad habits or behaviour as chronic when they have behaved like that for a long time and do not seem to be able to stop themselves.
A chronic situation or problem is very severe and unpleasant.

voca.title: chronic fatigue
voca.explains: A while ago, I felt under the weather. It persisted for a long time. It wasn’t a specific ailment. It was just chronic fatigue.\n

voca.title: chronic pain
voca.explains:
I don't want to suffer from chronic pain.
My chronic pain gets worse when it rains.
She took medicine for the chronic pain.
Shoulder pain is a chronic problem for many modern people. Based on personal experience, I think good posture is most important. Periodic stretching and exercise help, too. Plus, using your shoulder a lot can help cure the pain.
Sleep loss is a chronic problem for her.
I hope this doesn't turn into a chronic problem.

voca.title: chubby
voca.explains: A chubby person is rather fat.\n

voca.title: chuckle
voca.explains: When you chuckle, you laugh quietly.\n

voca.title: chunk
voca.means: [^청k]\n(두툼한) 덩어리, 큰 덩어리, 상당히 많은 량\n규모가 큰
voca.explains: Chunks of something are thick solid pieces of it.\nA chunk of something is a large amount or large part of it.\n

voca.title: church
voca.explains: A church is a building in which Christians worship. You usually refer to this place as church when you are talking about the time that people spend there.\nA Church is one of the groups of people within the Christian religion, for example Catholics or Methodists, that have their own beliefs, clergy, and forms of worship.\n

voca.title: churn
voca.means:
[쳐언]
(물, 흙탕물 등이) 마구 휘돌다, 휘젓다
(걱정, 역겨움 등으로) (속이) 뒤틀리다, 뒤틀리게 하다
(마음속에 분노, 혼란스러움 등이) 부글거리다, 들끓다
(버터를 만들기 위해) 우유를 휘젓다
(과거 농장에서 우유를 운반하던) 대형 우유통
voca.explains:
A churn is a container which is used for making butter.
If something churns water, mud, or dust, it moves it about violently.
If you say that your stomach is churning, you mean that you feel sick. You can also say that something churns your stomach.
Jack twisted and turned in the churning water.

voca.title: churn something out
voca.explains: to produce something quickly in large amounts\n

voca.title: cinch
voca.means:
[^씬취-]
아주 쉬운 일
확실한 일, 틀림없이 ~을 할 사람
(무엇을/이) 허리에 단단히 매다/매여 있다
(말의) 배에 두르는 끈을 매다
~을 확실히 하다
안장띠, (말의) 뱃대끈
voca.explains: If you say that something is a cinch, you mean that you think it is very easy to do.\nBluetooth is very widespread now. It’s used for many applications. I use it most often for audio devices. I can link my phone to headphones, speakers or even my car. Then, it’s a cinch to play music using a music streaming app.\n

voca.title: cinema
voca.explains:
A cinema is a place where people go to watch films for entertainment.
You can talk about the cinema when you are talking about seeing a film in a cinema.
Cinema is the business and art of making films.
Korean movies have created a sensation in the world of cinema. Critics and audiences gush over the latest Korean films.

voca.title: cinnamon
voca.explains: Cinnamon is a sweet spice used for flavouring food.\n

voca.title: circle
voca.means:
[^서r-끌]
원형, 동그라미, 원, 둥글게(원을 그리며) 모여 있는 것
범위, 집단
(특히 공중에서) 빙빙 돌다, 
~의 둘레를 돌다, 선회하다
voca.explains:
A circle is a shape consisting of a curved line completely surrounding an area. Every part of the line is the same distance from the centre of the area.
A circle of something is a round flat piece or area of it.
A circle of objects or people is a group of them arranged in the shape of a circle.
You can refer to a group of people as a circle when they meet each other regularly because they are friends or because they belong to the same profession or share the same interests.
In a theatre or cinema, the circle is an area of seats on the upper floor.
If something circles an object or a place, or circles around it, it forms a circle around it.
If an aircraft or a bird circles or circles something, it moves round in a circle in the air.
To circle around someone or something, or to circle them, means to move around them.
If you circle something on a piece of paper, you draw a circle around it.
They just kept going around and around in their joyous circle.

voca.title: circle the drain
voca.explains:
if something circles the drain it continues to become worse so that it may not be able to survive much longer
She is circling the drain.
The restaurant where I work is circling the drain.
The stock is circling the drain.

voca.title: circuit
voca.means:
[^써r-낏t]
회로, 배선도, 순환, 정기적 순회
(스포츠) 연맹전
(자동차나 오토바이) 경주로
순회, 술례
voca.explains:
An electrical circuit is a complete route which an electric current can flow around.
A circuit is a series of places that are visited regularly by a person or group, especially as a part of their job.
A racing circuit is a track on which cars, motorbikes, or cycles race.

voca.title: circumference
voca.explains: The circumference of a circle, place, or round object is the distance around its edge.\nThe circumference of a circle, place, or round object is its edge.\n

voca.title: circumstance
voca.means:
[써r컴s텐s]
(일, 사건 등을 둘러싼) 환경, 상황, 정황, 
(개인의 특히 제정적인) 형편, 처지, 
부수적인 일
어떤 상황(상태, 환경)에 놓이다
voca.explains:
The circumstances of a particular situation are the conditions which affect what happens.
The circumstances of an event are the way it happened or the causes of it.
Your circumstances are the conditions of your life, especially the amount of money that you have.
You can emphasize that something must not or will not happen by saying that it must not or will not happen under any circumstances.
Events and situations which cannot be controlled are sometimes referred to as circumstance.

voca.title: cite
voca.means:
[싸잇t]
(이유, 예를) 들다/끌어대다, 인용하다, 
~을 인용하다, ~을 언급하다, 예로들다
인용문구
표창하다
voca.explains:
mention / refer to / cite / quote / allude to
If you cite something, you quote it or mention it, especially as an example or proof of what you are saying.
To cite a person means to officially name them in a legal case. To cite a reason or cause means to state it as the official reason for your case.
If someone is cited, they are officially ordered to appear before a court.

voca.title: citizen
voca.explains: Someone who is a citizen of a particular country is legally accepted as belonging to that country.\nThe citizens of a town or city are the people who live there.\n

voca.title: city
voca.explains: A city is a large town.\nThe City is the part of London where many important financial institutions have their main offices. People often refer to these financial institutions as the City.\n

voca.title: city hall
voca.explains: The city hall is the building which a city council uses as its main offices.\n

voca.title: civic
voca.explains: You use civic to describe people or things that have an official status in a town or city.\nYou use civic to describe the duties or feelings that people have because they belong to a particular community.\n

voca.title: civic-minded
voca.means: 시민 의식이 투철한\n공공심이 있는, 사회 복지에 열심인
voca.explains:
Most vacationers are responsible and civic-minded. However, there are those who are very irresponsible and leave their trash behind.
Even kids can be civic-minded.
A civic-minded person wouldn't litter.

voca.title: civil
voca.explains:
You use civil to describe events that happen within a country and that involve the different groups of people in it.
You use civil to describe people or things in a country that are not connected with its armed forces.
You use civil to describe things that are connected with the state rather than with a religion.
You use civil to describe the rights that people have within a society.
Someone who is civil is polite in a formal way, but not particularly friendly.

voca.title: civilian
voca.explains: In a military situation, a civilian is anyone who is not a member of the armed forces.\nIn a military situation, civilian is used to describe people or things that are not military.\n

voca.title: civilization
voca.explains: A civilization is a human society with its own social organization and culture.\nCivilization is the state of having an advanced level of social organization and a comfortable way of life.\n

voca.title: claim
voca.means:
[클레임]
(~이 사실이라고) 주장하다, 
(자기 권리나 재산이라고 여겨) 요구/요청하다
(관심을) 끌다, 사로잡다
요구, 청구, 주장
voca.explains:
claim / allegation / assertion / contention
If you say that someone claims that something is true, you mean they say that it is true but you are not sure whether or not they are telling the truth.
If you say that someone claims responsibility or credit for something, you mean they say that they are responsible for it, but you are not sure whether or not they are telling the truth.
If you claim something, you try to get it because you think you have a right to it.
If someone claims a record, title, or prize, they gain or win it.
If you claim money from the government, an insurance company, or another organization, you officially apply to them for it, because you think you are entitled to it according to their rules.
A claim is something which someone says which they cannot prove and which may be false.
If you have a claim on someone or their attention, you have the right to demand things from them or to demand their attention.

voca.title: claim something back
voca.explains: to ask for something to be returned to you\n

voca.title: clam
voca.explains: Clams are a kind of shellfish which can be eaten.\n

voca.title: clam up
voca.means: (누가 묻는 사항에 대해) 입을 꼭 다물다, 말을 안하다
voca.explains: to refuse to speak about something because you are afraid, or want to keep it secret\n

voca.title: clammy
voca.explains: Something that is clammy is unpleasantly damp or sticky.\n

voca.title: clamshell
voca.explains:
a dredging bucket that is hinged like the shell of a clam
an aircraft cockpit canopy hinged at the front and rear
the hinged door of a cargo aircraft
another name for eyelid (sense 2)
any of a variety of objects hinged like the shell of a clam, such as a container for takeaway food, a portable computer, etc

voca.title: clang
voca.means: [클레엥]\n(금속이 부딪치며 울리듯) 쨍그랑/땡그랑 하는 소리를 내다
voca.explains: When a large metal object clangs, it makes a loud noise.\nShe pushed the gate back. It shut with a clang.\n

voca.title: clap
voca.explains:
When you clap, you hit your hands together to show appreciation or attract attention.
If you clap your hand or an object onto something, you put it there quickly and firmly.
A clap of thunder is a sudden and loud noise of thunder.
He was clapping his hands together.
Jack clapped his hand over his mouth.
The coach clapped his hands. "Okay, team. Let's go!"

voca.title: clap on
voca.means:
(옷 따위를) 재빨리 몸에 걸치다, 입다
(수갑을) 탁 채우다
(브레이크)를 갑자기 밟다
~에 (세금 따위를) 부과하다

voca.title: clap out
voca.means: ~을 녹초가 되도록 피곤하게 하다\n(손뼉을 쳐서) 박자를 맞추다

voca.title: clap up
voca.means: ~을 급조하다, 서둘러 준비하다\n(거래 따위를) 서둘러 결정짓다, 체결하다\n~을 투옥하다

voca.title: clash
voca.means:
[k^뤠쉬]
(두 집단간의 짧은 물리적) 충돌, 
(대립되는 두 가지 사이의) 충돌/차이, 
(시합 등에서) 맞붙다, 격돌하다, 
충돌하다, 차이를 보이다, 
부딪치다, 상반되다, 겹치다
voca.explains:
fight / clash / brawl / struggle / scuffle / tussle
When people clash, they fight, argue, or disagree with each other.
Beliefs, ideas, or qualities that clash with each other are very different from each other and therefore are opposed.
If one event clashes with another, the two events happen at the same time so that you cannot attend both of them.
If one colour or style clashes with another, the colours or styles look ugly together. You can also say that two colours or styles clash.

voca.title: clash with
voca.explains: There are many things to take into consideration when choosing furniture. The price should be reasonable. It shouldn't clash with the furniture you already have.\n

voca.title: clasp
voca.means:
[클^레-습]
(꽉) 움켜쥐다, 움켜잡다
(꽉) 껴안다
(걸쇠를 걸어) 잠그다
(가방이나 보석류의) 걸쇠, 잠금쇠
움켜쥐기, 잡기
voca.explains:
hold / hold on / cling / clutch / grip / grasp / clasp / hang on
If you clasp someone or something, you hold them tightly in your hands or arms.
A clasp is a small device that fastens something.
She clasped her hand across her mouth as her parents surrounded her.

voca.title: class
voca.explains:
A class is a group of pupils or students who are taught together.
A class is a course of teaching in a particular subject.
If you do something in class, you do it during a lesson in school.
The students in a school or university who finish their course in a particular year are often referred to as the class of that year.
Class refers to the division of people in a society into groups according to their social status.
A class of things is a group of them with similar characteristics.
If someone or something is classed as a particular thing, they are regarded as belonging to that group of things.

voca.title: class act
voca.explains: He's got stunning looks and he is a class act.\nThe principal is a class act (man) who has greatly improved the school.\n

voca.title: classes in school
voca.explains: I have studied English for many years. I first learned it during classes in school.\n

voca.title: classical
voca.explains:
classic / classical
You use classical to describe something that is traditional in form, style, or content.
Classical music is music that is considered to be serious and of lasting value.
Classical is used to describe things which relate to the ancient Greek or Roman civilizations.

voca.title: classification
voca.explains: A classification is a division or category in a system which divides things into groups or types.\n

voca.title: classmate
voca.explains: Your classmates are students who are in the same class as you at school or college.\nTerry: It's not bad but there's a lot of writing to do. Sometimes it's hard to keep up with my classmates.\n

voca.title: classroom
voca.explains:
A classroom is a room in a school where lessons take place.
She would have to get used to a new desk and a new classroom.
Her new classroom would not have a porcupine named Roger.

voca.title: classy
voca.explains: If you describe someone or something as classy, you mean they are stylish and sophisticated.\n

voca.title: clatter
voca.means: [클^뤠러r]\n(접시, 포크 등이) 덜걱/달가락 하는 소리를 내다\n달그락/털커덕 거리며 가다/움직이다
voca.explains: If you say that people or things clatter somewhere, you mean that they move there noisily.\nIf something hard clatters, it makes repeated short noises as it hits against another hard thing.\n

voca.title: clatter along
voca.means: 덜커덕덜커덕 소리를 내며 달려가다\n발굽 소리를 내며 말을 달리다

voca.title: clause
voca.means: [클롸-z]\n절, (주어와 동사가 갖춰진 문장 구성 성분)\n문구, 조항, 규정
voca.explains: A clause is a section of a legal document.\nIn grammar, a clause is a group of words containing a verb. Sentences contain one or more clauses. There are finite clauses and non-finite clauses.\n

voca.title: claw
voca.means:
[^클롸]
(새, 짐승의) 발톱, (곤충의) 발톱, 집게발
~을 할퀴다, ~을 손톱으로 긁어 만들다
해집고 나아가다.
voca.explains:
The claws of a bird or animal are the thin, hard, curved nails at the end of its feet.
The claws of a lobster, crab, or scorpion are the two pointed parts at the end of its legs which are used for holding things.
If an animal claws at something, it scratches or damages it with its claws.
To claw at something mean to try very hard to get hold of it.
If you claw your way somewhere, you move there with great difficulty, trying desperately to find things to hold on to.
The bands had spikes like claws on them.
It had glowing red eyes and long, curled claws.
His legs were spindly twigs that ended in four long, skinny toes with curved claws.
He had silky feathers for hair, a beak for a nose, sharp claws, and a billowing feathered cape that glistened in the moonlight like shiny black armor.

voca.title: claw at
voca.explains: to try to catch somebody/something or scratch or tear somebody/something with claws or with your nails\n

voca.title: clay
voca.explains:
soil / mud / clay / land / earth / dirt / ground
Clay is a kind of earth that is soft when it is wet and hard when it is dry. Clay is shaped and baked to make things such as pots and bricks.
In tennis, matches played on clay are played on courts whose surface is covered with finely crushed stones or brick.

voca.title: clean
voca.means:
[클^리-인]
(더럽지 않아) 깨끗한, 깔끔한, 정확한, 산뜻한
청소하다, 깨끗해 지다, 
완전히, 감쪽같이
voca.explains:
clean / wash / rinse / cleanse / dry-clean / bathe
Something that is clean is free from dirt or unwanted marks.
You say that people or animals are clean when they keep themselves or their surroundings clean.
A clean fuel or chemical process does not create many harmful or polluting substances.
If you clean something or clean dirt off it, you make it free from dirt and unwanted marks, for example by washing or wiping it. If something cleans easily, it is easy to clean.
If someone has a clean reputation or record, they have never done anything illegal or wrong.
Clean is used to emphasize that something was done completely.
A clean game or fight is carried out fairly, according to the rules.
If you clean a room or house, you make the inside of it and the furniture in it free from dirt and dust.

voca.title: clean something down
voca.explains: to clean something thoroughly by rubbing it with a cloth, etc. or brushing it\n

voca.title: clean something out
voca.explains: to clean the inside of something thoroughly\nto use up or take all somebody's money; to take or buy the whole supply of something that somebody has\n

voca.title: clean something up
voca.explains: to remove criminals, crime or immoral behaviour from a place or an organization\n

voca.title: clean up
voca.explains:
to remove dirt, etc. from a place and make it clean
to wash yourself or make yourself clean
to be very successful; to win a lot of money or prizes

voca.title: clean up after oneself
voca.explains:
When I went to a beach recently, the entire beach was covered with trash. It was truly an eyesore. I guess the people who created that mess just couldn’t clean up after themselves.
Tell the children to clean up after themselves.
I remembered to clean up after myself.

voca.title: cleanliness
voca.explains: Cleanliness is the degree to which people keep themselves and their surroundings clean.\nThe house is a model of cleanliness.\n

voca.title: clear
voca.means:
[^클뤼어r]
알아듣기 쉬운, 분명한, (의심할 여지 없이) 확실한
(특히 어려운 가운데도) 냉철한, 또렷한
투명한, 맑은
(양심에) 거리낄 게 없는, 결백한
전체의, 온전한
~을 깨끗/분명하게 하다,
밝은, 맑은, 보통의
분명히, 완전히
(어떤 장소에서 사람들을) 내보내다, 쫓아내다
맑아지다
voca.explains:
clear / obvious / apparent / evident / plain / crystal clear
Something that is clear is easy to understand, see, or hear.
Something that is clear is obvious and impossible to be mistaken about.
If you are clear about something, you understand it completely.
If your mind or your way of thinking is clear, you are able to think sensibly and reasonably, and you are not affected by confusion or by a drug such as alcohol.
To clear your mind or your head means to free it from confused thoughts or from the effects of a drug such as alcohol.
If you say that your conscience is clear, you mean you do not think you have done anything wrong.
If something or someone is clear of something else, it is not touching it or is a safe distance away from it.
If an animal or person clears an object or clears a certain height, they jump over the object, or over something that height, without touching it.
When a bank clears a cheque or when a cheque clears, the bank agrees to pay the sum of money mentioned on it.

voca.title: clear away
voca.explains: to remove things that you have been using and no longer need in order to leave a clear space\nto make somebody leave a place\n

voca.title: clear off
voca.explains: to go or run away\n

voca.title: clear out
voca.explains: to make something empty and clean by removing what you do not want\nI hired professional movers to make the move easier. We took inventory of all my belongings and the movers packed them up in the boxes. In no time, we cleared out my old place.\n

voca.title: clear out of
voca.explains: to make something empty and clean by removing what you do not want\n

voca.title: clear sign
voca.explains: Driven by jealousy, my first boyfriend cheated on me and it left me heartbroken. It was a clear sign to break up but I was hung up on my first love.\n

voca.title: clear up
voca.explains:
to make something clean and neat
to solve a problem; to find an explanation for something
if the weather clears up, it becomes brighter and rain, etc. moves away

voca.title: clear your throat
voca.explains: cough slightly, especially before speaking or to attract somebody's attention\n

voca.title: clearing
voca.explains: A clearing is a small area in a forest where there are no trees or bushes.\n

voca.title: clearly
voca.means: [^클릐어뤼]\n또렷하게, 분명하게, 알기 쉽게\n(자신이 하는말을 강조하여) 분명히

voca.title: cleat
voca.means: [클^릿t]\n(신발의 고무로 된) 미끄럼 방지용 밑창\n미끄럼 방지용 밑창이 붙은 신발(흔히 운동화)
voca.explains: A cleat is a kind of hook with two ends which is used to hold ropes, especially on sailing boats.\n

voca.title: cleats
voca.explains: Now Binky came to the plate. He tapped the dirt from his cleats and cocked his bat.\n

voca.title: clement
voca.explains: Clement weather is pleasantly mild and dry.\n

voca.title: clench
voca.means:
[클뤤취]
(주먹을) 꽉 쥐다, (이를) 악물다, 
~을 거머쥐다
(~에 대고) ~을 단단히 고정시키다
voca.explains:
When you clench your fist or your fist clenches, you curl your fingers up tightly, usually because you are very angry.
When you clench your teeth or they clench, you squeeze your teeth together firmly, usually because you are angry or upset.
If you clench something in your hand or in your teeth, you hold it tightly with your hand or your teeth.

voca.title: clerk
voca.explains:
A clerk is a person who works in an office, bank, or law court and whose job is to look after the records or accounts.
In a hotel, office, or hospital, a clerk is the person whose job is to answer the telephone and deal with people when they arrive.
A clerk is someone who works in a store.
To clerk means to work as a clerk.

voca.title: clever
voca.explains:
intelligent / smart / clever / brilliant / bright
Someone who is clever is intelligent and able to understand things easily or plan things well.
A clever idea, book, or invention is extremely effective and shows the skill of the people involved.

voca.title: click
voca.means:
[^클릑]
찰칵/딸깍 하는 소리를 내다
(마우스를) 클릭하다, 누리다
(불현듯) 딱 분명해 지다, 이해가 되다
즉각 좋아하게 되다, 인기를 얻다
손발이 잘 맞다
찰칵/딸깍 (하는 소리), (마우스) 클릭함, 
흡착음, 혀 차는 소리
통하다
voca.explains:
If something clicks or if you click it, it makes a short, sharp sound.
If you click on an area of a computer screen, you point the cursor at that area and press one of the buttons on the mouse in order to make something happen.
When you suddenly understand something, you can say that it clicks.
Some hit sticks together to make clicking sounds.
There was something effortless about our heart-to-heart. It was clear that something clicked. A small gesture like opening a door made a world of difference.

voca.title: client
voca.means: [^클라이언t]\n(전문가의 서비스를 받는) 고객, 의뢰인, 거래처\n서버에 연결된 컴퓨터
voca.explains: A client of a professional person or organization is a person or company that receives a service from them in return for payment.\n

voca.title: cliff
voca.explains:
A cliff is a high area of land with a very steep side, especially one next to the sea.
Beyond the plain were high rocky cliffs.
Rocks tumbled down from the cliff.
The stag finally came to a halt on the ledge of a steep cliff.

voca.title: climate
voca.explains: The climate of a place is the general weather conditions that are typical of it.\nYou can use climate to refer to the general atmosphere or situation somewhere.\n

voca.title: climb
voca.means: [클롸임]\n오르다, 올라가다, 등반하다, 상승하다\n등반, 등산, (가치, 양 등의) 상승, 증가
voca.explains:
If you climb something such as a tree, mountain, or ladder, or climb up it, you move towards the top of it. If you climb down it, you move towards the bottom of it.
If you climb somewhere, you move there carefully, for example because you are moving into a small space or trying to avoid falling.
When something such as an aeroplane climbs, it moves upwards to a higher position. When the sun climbs, it moves higher in the sky.

voca.title: climb down (over something)
voca.explains: to admit that you are wrong or have made a mistake; to change your position in an argument\n

voca.title: climb the walls
voca.explains: I was climbing the walls when my son was in the hospital.\n

voca.title: cling
voca.means: [클링]\n꼭 붙잡다, 매달리다, 착 들러붙다, 달라붙다\n애착을 갖다
voca.explains:
cling - clung - clung
hold / hold on / cling / clutch / grip / grasp / clasp / hang on
If you cling to someone or something, you hold onto them tightly.
If someone clings to a position or a possession they have, they do everything they can to keep it even though this may be very difficult.

voca.title: cling to
voca.explains: to hold something/somebody tightly; to not let go of something/somebody\n

voca.title: clinic
voca.explains:
A clinic is a building where people go to receive medical advice or treatment.
At times, the pain is so bad, I’m hardly able to move. I went to the hospital once for an expert opinion. I got acupuncture treatment at an oriental medicine clinic. I’ve also tried getting massages for my shoulder pain. However, I never got more than temporary relief.
I went to the clinic because of a bad cold.
She visited a dental clinic to remove a tooth.

voca.title: clink
voca.explains: If objects made of glass, pottery, or metal clink or if you clink them, they touch each other and make a short, light sound.\n

voca.title: clip
voca.means:
[^클립]
핀, 클립, 
(무엇을 짧게) 깍음, 자르기, 깍기
클립으로 고정하다
(가위같은 것으로) 깍다, 자르다, 잘라내다, 오려내다
스치다, 부딧치다
voca.explains:
A clip is a small device, usually made of metal or plastic, that is specially shaped for holding things together.
A clip from a film or a radio or television programme is a short piece of it that is broadcast separately.
When you clip things together or when things clip together, you fasten them together using a clip or clips.
If you clip something, you cut small pieces from it, especially in order to shape it.
If you clip something out of a newspaper or magazine, you cut it out.
If something clips something else, it hits it accidentally at an angle before moving off in a different direction.

voca.title: clipper
voca.explains: Clippers are a tool used for cutting small amounts from something, especially from someone's hair or nails.\n

voca.title: cloak
voca.explains:
A cloak is a long, loose, sleeveless piece of clothing which people used to wear over their other clothes when they went out.
A cloak of something such as mist or snow completely covers and hides something.
If you refer to something as a cloak, you mean that it is intended to hide the truth about something.
To cloak something means to cover it or hide it.
She wore a long cloak and carried a lantern.
The knight was dressed all in red-from his shining helmet to the long cloak on his back.

voca.title: clock
voca.means:
[클롹k]
(벽에 걸거나 실내에 두는) 시계
(경주 등에서 시간을) 기록하다, 
(속도를) 재다/측정하다
voca.explains:
A clock is an instrument, for example in a room or on the outside of a building, that shows what time of day it is.
A time clock in a factory or office is a device that is used to record the hours that people work. Each worker puts a special card into the device when they arrive and leave, and the times are recorded on the card.
In a car, the clock is the instrument that shows the speed of the car or the distance it has travelled.
To clock a particular time or speed in a race means to reach that time or speed.
If something or someone is clocked at a particular time or speed, their time or speed is measured at that level.
If you are doing something against the clock, you are doing it in a great hurry, because there is very little time.

voca.title: clock in
voca.explains: to record the time that you arrive at work, especially by putting a card into a machine; to do this for somebody or check the time they arrive at work\n

voca.title: clock out
voca.explains: to record the time that you leave work, especially by putting a card into a machine; to do this for somebody\n

voca.title: clockwise
voca.explains: When something is moving clockwise, it is moving in a circle in the same direction as the hands on a clock.\n

voca.title: clod
voca.explains: A clod of earth is a large lump of earth.\n

voca.title: clog
voca.means:
[클^롸g]
~의 행동/운동 등을 방해하다, 막히다
방해하는 것, 장애물, 고장
나막신
voca.explains:
When something clogs a hole or place, it blocks it so that nothing can pass through.
Clogs are heavy leather or wooden shoes with thick wooden soles.
The drain is completely clogged with hair.

voca.title: clone
voca.means:
[클^로운]
클론, 복제 (생물)
복사품 (같은 물건이나 사람)
호환 기종(비싼 컴퓨터와 기능이 동일한 컴퓨터)
복제하다
voca.explains:
If someone or something is a clone of another person or thing, they are so similar to this person or thing that they seem to be exactly the same as them.
A clone is an animal or plant that has been produced artificially, for example in a laboratory, from the cells of another animal or plant. A clone is exactly the same as the original animal or plant.
To clone an animal or plant means to produce it as a clone.

voca.title: clop
voca.explains: to make or move along with a sound as of a horse's hooves striking the ground\na sound of this nature\n

voca.title: close
voca.means:
[클로우-z]
(시간적, 공간적으로) 가까운, (사이가) 가까운, 친밀한
거의/곧 ~ 할 것 같은, 아슬아슬 한
촘촘한, 빽빽한, (감시 등이) 철저한
가까이, 바싹

(문, 커튼 등을) 닫다/치다, (눈을) 감다
(일시적으로 상점 등의) 문을 닫다/패쇄하다
끝나다/마감되다,
voca.explains:
near / close
If one thing or person is close to another, there is only a very small distance between them.
You say that people are close to each other when they like each other very much and know each other very well.
Your close relatives are the members of your family who are most directly related to you, for example your parents and your brothers or sisters.

When you close something such as a door or lid or when it closes, it moves so that a hole, gap, or opening is covered.
When you close something such as an open book or umbrella, you move the different parts of it together.
If you close something such as a computer file or window, you give the computer an instruction to remove it from the screen.
When you close your eyes or your eyes close, your eyelids move downwards, so that you can no longer see.

voca.title: close at hand
voca.explains: near in distance or time\n

voca.title: close by
voca.explains:
at a short distance (from somebody/something)
Alright. Text me when you are close by.
His surfboard was close by.
These countries are close by and they have a lot to offer.

voca.title: close game
voca.explains:
B : I really wanted to go, but I was too busy. So what was the score?
A : Our team won 5-4.
B : Man! That was a really close game.

voca.title: close in
voca.explains: to come nearer to and surround somebody/something in a frightening way or in order to attack them\nwhen the days close in, they gradually become shorter\n

voca.title: close on
voca.explains: almost; nearly\n

voca.title: close to
voca.explains: in a position very near to something\n

voca.title: close up
voca.means: (잠깐 동안 상점 등의) 문을 닫다\n모여들다, 모으다\n좁아지다, 점점 막히다
voca.explains:
to close completely
to hide your thoughts and feelings
if people or vehicles close up, they move nearer to each other
I am highly allergic to peanuts. My tonsils swell up and my throat closes up. I sound like I’ve lost my voice or I’m choking on something. To add to the pain, I also break out in hives and hyperventilate.

voca.title: closer
voca.means:
[클로우써r]
닫는 것(사람), 최종회
(종료를 알리는 신호가 되는) 행위/곡
close 비교급, 더욱, 가까이, 자세히

voca.title: closet
voca.means:
[클^롸짓t]
벽장, 작은 방, 헛간
드러나지 않은, 본인만 알고 있는
밀실에 들어앉히다
voca.explains:
A closet is a piece of furniture with doors at the front and shelves inside, which is used for storing things.
in BRIT, use cupboard
A closet is a very small room for storing things, especially one without windows.
Closet is used to describe a person who has beliefs, habits, or feelings which they keep secret, often because they are embarrassed about them. Closet is also used of their beliefs, habits, or feelings.

voca.title: cloth
voca.explains:
material / fabric / cloth / textile
Cloth is fabric which is made by weaving or knitting a substance such as cotton, wool, silk, or nylon. Cloth is used especially for making clothes.
A cloth is a piece of cloth which you use for a particular purpose, such as cleaning something or covering something.
The cloth is sometimes used to refer to Christian priests and ministers.
Then my father pastes the sheets together to make cloth for us.

voca.title: clothes
voca.explains: clothes / clothing / garment / dress / wear / gear\nClothes are the things that people wear, such as shirts, coats, trousers, and dresses.\n

voca.title: clothes hanger
voca.explains: I did an Internet search for some home remedies. A post showed how to bend a clothes hanger into a hook.\n

voca.title: clothespin
voca.explains: A clothespin is the same as a clothes peg.\n

voca.title: cloud
voca.means:
[클^라우d]
구름, (먼지, 연기, 메뚜기 떼 등이 구름같이) 자욱한 것
구름모양의 것, 연기
~을 구름으로 덮다, 구름이 끼다
(기억력, 판단력 등을) 흐리다, 흐려지다,
어두워지다, ~을 어둡게하다
voca.explains:
A cloud is a mass of water vapour that floats in the sky. Clouds are usually white or grey in colour.
A cloud of something such as smoke or dust is a mass of it floating in the air.
If you say that something clouds your view of a situation, you mean that it makes you unable to understand the situation or judge it properly.
If you say that something clouds a situation, you mean that it makes it unpleasant.
If glass clouds or if moisture clouds it, tiny drops of water cover the glass, making it difficult to see through.
If you say that someone is on cloud nine, you are emphasizing that they are very happy.
Puffy snow clouds were moving in.
Thousands of roosting ravens rose into the sky like a giant black cloud.

voca.title: cloud nine
voca.explains: A : I'm on cloud nine today and I feel like I can fly!\n

voca.title: cloud over
voca.explains: if the sky or the weather clouds over, clouds cover the sky and the sun disappears\nif your face, expression, etc. clouds over, you start to look sad, worried or angry\n

voca.title: clove
voca.means: [^클로우v]\n정향(열대성 정향나무의 꽃을 말린 것. 향신료로 씀)\n마늘 한 쪽
voca.explains: Cloves are small dried flower buds which are used as a spice.\nA clove of garlic is one of the sections of a garlic bulb.\n

voca.title: clown
voca.explains:
A clown is a performer in a circus who wears funny clothes and bright make-up, and does silly things in order to make people laugh.
If you say that someone is a clown, you mean that they say funny things or do silly things to amuse people.
If you describe someone as a clown, you disapprove of them and have no respect for them.
If you clown, you do silly things in order to make people laugh.

voca.title: club
voca.means:
[클럽]
(특정한 활동, 스포츠 등을 위한) 클럽, 동호회,
나이트 클럽, 사교단체, 팀, 동아리, 구단, 곤봉
곤봉으로 때리다
voca.explains:
A club is an organization of people interested in a particular activity or subject who usually meet on a regular basis.
A club is a place where the members of a club meet.
A club is a team which competes in sporting competitions.
A club is the same as a nightclub.
A club is a long, thin, metal stick with a piece of wood or metal at one end that you use to hit the ball in golf.
To club a person or animal means to hit them hard with a thick heavy stick or a similar weapon.
Boka was pounding a wide strip of bark with a wooden club.

voca.title: club together
voca.explains: if people club together, they each give an amount of money so that the total can be used for a particular purpose\n

voca.title: clue
voca.explains:
A clue to a problem or mystery is something that helps you to find the answer to it.
A clue is an object or piece of information that helps someone solve a crime.
A clue in a crossword or game is information which is given to help you to find the answer to a question.
I wonder if she left any other clues.
"First, we have to find a clue that tells us where to begin" he said.
"Didn't Mr. Haney give you any clues at all?" Francine asked.
Tara: She doesn't have a clue.
Pay attention, or else you'll miss an important clue.

voca.title: clump
voca.means:
[^클럼p]
(촘촘히 붙어 자라는 나무 등의) 무리, 무더기
쿵(하는 발자국 소리)
숲, 덤블, 무거운 발소리
(발로) 쿵쾅거리다
무거운 걸음으로 걷다, 엉겨붙다
무리[떼]를 짓다, 함께 모이다[모으다]
voca.explains:
A clump of things such as trees or plants is a small group of them growing together.

voca.title: coax
voca.explains:
If you coax someone into doing something, you gently try to persuade them to do it.

voca.title: come apart
voca.explains: to break or fall into pieces\n

voca.title: come around
voca.means:
빙 돌아오다, 회람하다, 다시 시작하다
(날짜나 정기적인 행사가) 돌아오다 
건강을 회복하다, 화를 풀다
다시 의식을 차리다, 정신이 돌아오다
(처음과 달리) 마음을 바꿔 동의하다
voca.explains:
It took a while but my husband finally came around to my way of thinking.
So you have finally come around?
Mr. Franklin: Yes. The class comes around every three months.
My wife always surprises me every time my birthday comes around.
Even though the cold is hard to bear at times, I'm glad winter comes around each year.

voca.title: come back
voca.explains:
return / come back / go back / get back / turn back
to return to the place where the speaker is
to begin to exist or happen again
to return to school or work after a break
to become popular, successful or fashionable again
to be given in answer to a message, letter, etc. that you have sent or a question that you have asked
to return to your memory, often suddenly
What time are you going to come back?!
When they did not come back, Arthur turned against his magicians.

voca.title: come between
voca.means: ~사이에 오다/위치하다\n~의 사이를 가르다, 이간질하다\n사이가 벌어지도록 만들다
voca.explains: His heavy drinking is coming between him and his wife.\nSteve: Are you going to let this come between us?\n

voca.title: come by
voca.explains: The flight attendants gave a safety demonstration. Soon, we took off. After a while, the attendants came by with the beverage cart. Later on, we had our in-flight meal.\n

voca.title: come close
voca.explains: almost reach or do something\nI am on my phone 24/7, which tends to drain my battery at lightning speed. I peruse e-mail(s), the latest headlines, and social media posts. However, the collective act of reading doesn’t even come close to what video clips do to a smartphone’s battery life.\n

voca.title: come down
voca.means:
(항공기가) 착륙하다; 추락하다
(비, 눈 등이) 오다, 내리다, 내려오다
(가격, 기온, 비율 등이) 내리다, 떨어지다
(찬부를) 결정하다, 표명하다
(길이가 특정 위치까지) 내려오다
voca.explains:
to travel from one place to another, especially from the north of a country to the south
if a price, a level or an amount comes down, it becomes lower or less than before
to break and fall to the ground
to fall from the sky; to be brought down to the ground
to decide that you support or oppose somebody/something and say so publicly
when the curtain in a theatre comes down, it is the end of the performance

voca.title: come down with something
voca.explains:
to get an illness, often not a very serious one
I came down with a cold.
You can come down with a cold even in the summer.
I took some medicine because I had come down with a cold.

voca.title: come first
voca.explains: be treated as the most important person or thing in somebody's life\n

voca.title: come forward
voca.explains: to offer to give help, information, etc.\n

voca.title: come in handy
voca.means: 쓸모있다, 편리하다, 도움이 되다, \n유용하다, 유용하게 사용되다
voca.explains:
An extra towel always comes in handy.
I didn't know this would come in so handy.
Extra water always comes in handy.
"It makes sense to learn about everything." said his mother. "You can't tell when it might come in handy later on."
I keep a flashlight in my car and it comes in handy a lot.

voca.title: come into
voca.explains:
to begin to exist, happen, etc.
to receive a large sum of money when somebody dies
to be important in a particular situation

voca.title: come into effect
voca.explains:
A new anti-graft law came into effect last year. Its’ commonly referred to as the Kim Young-ran law.
The ew rules will come into effect starting next season.
She bought a lot of them before the new prices came into effect.

voca.title: come of age
voca.explains: reach the age when you are considered by the law to be an adult\nbecome established and accepted\n

voca.title: come off
voca.means:
때어낼/제거할 수 있다, 
일어나다, 이루어지다, 
성공하다, 바라던 대로 되다, 
(시합 등에서) 잘 하다, 잘못하다, 
끝내다, 그만두다, 일어나다, 실현되다
voca.explains:
to become separated from something
to fall from something
to move away from something large or important and go in a different direction
to leave the stage, the sports field, etc. during a play or a game
to leave something such as a vehicle or a road
if an amount of money comes off a price, the price becomes lower by that amount

voca.title: come off worse
voca.explains: lose a fight, competition, etc. or suffer more compared with others\n

voca.title: come out
voca.means:
(해, 달, 별 이) 나오다, 생산/출간되다
알려지다, 드러나다, 분명히 보여지다
나오다, 분명해지다, 합쳐지다, 
오다, 풀리다, 해결되다
voca.explains:
when the sun, moon or stars come out, they appear in the sky
when flowers come out, they open
to become known after a time when it has been secret
"That means we'll be here when the vampire bats come out" said Annie.
Proceed onward with courage, and you will come out into the light."
Arthur sighed. "The glove was. But the ball came out along the way and dribbled into the outfield. The runner ended up at third base."
He tilted the pot and tried to spoon some into her bowl. But nothing came out. The oatmeal had hardened like cement.
His teacher nodded. "Don’t give up. I’m sure the truth will come out in the end."

voca.title: come out of nowhere
voca.explains:
I was completely caught off guard when the lightbulb went out in my bathroom while I was taking a shower a few weeks ago. Because it came out of nowhere, I thought we were having a blackout.
Disasters always seem to come out of nowhere.
The news of their breakup came out of nowhere.

voca.title: come over
voca.means: (어떤 기분이) 갑자기 들다, \n집에 오다, 들르다, ~ 넘어서 오다,\n ~의 위를 통과하다, 바꾸다
voca.explains:
(to somebody/something) to move across a room, a road, an ocean, etc. towards where the speaker is
(to something) to visit somebody for a short time, usually at their home
Can you come over on Sunday?
A : I need somebody to come over and fix my internet.

voca.title: come past
voca.explains: to pass in front of the speaker or the place where the speaker is\n

voca.title: come right on the heels of
voca.explains:
But these days, I just use video-on-demand (VOD) services. Program uploads come right on the heels of the original broadcast.
The thunder came right on the heels of the lightning.
The rusults came right on the heels of the new change.

voca.title: come second
voca.means: 둘째가 되다, 둘째로 오다, 차위가 되다

voca.title: come short
voca.explains: have an accident; get into trouble\n

voca.title: come to life
voca.explains: become more interesting, exciting or full of activity\nstart to act or move as if alive\n

voca.title: come to mind
voca.explains: if something comes or springs to mind, you suddenly remember or think of it\n

voca.title: come to rest
voca.explains: stop moving\nA huge yellow leaf fluttered through the open window and came to rest at Jack's feet.\n

voca.title: come to someone's rescue
voca.explains:
It informed me that I had just five percent left on my battery. Thankfully, my friend gave me a ring before my phone died. Just a few minutes after we hung up, she came to my rescue with a portable battery. I was to glad I wasn’t left hanging.
I knew you'd come to my rescue.
They had come to my rescue.

voca.title: come to something
voca.explains: to add up to something; to be equal to something\nto reach a particular state or condition; to arrive at something\n

voca.title: come to stay
voca.means: (기후 따위가) 오래 계속 되다, \n변하지 않다, \n(외래의 습관 따위가) 토착화 되다

voca.title: come to terms with something
voca.means: ~을 깨닫다, ~을 인정하다\n(좋지 않은 일을) 받아들이는 법을 배우다, 받아들이려고 애쓰다
voca.explains: learn to accept something that is difficult or unpleasant\nThrough trial and error, I have come to terms with the fact that I am also allergic to alcohol.\n

voca.title: come together
voca.explains: if two or more people or things come together, they form one group or one piece\n

voca.title: come under something
voca.means: (특정 집단속에) 포함되다, 들어가다\n(공격, 비난을) 받게되다\n(무엇의 통제, 영향을) 받다
voca.explains:
to be included within a particular group or collection of things
to be managed, controlled or owned by a particular group or organization
if you come under attack, criticism, etc., somebody attacks, criticizes, etc. you

voca.title: come up
voca.means:
(땅울 뚫고) 나오다, 위로 오다, ~쪽으로 오다,
생기다, 발생하다,  나타나다, 
도달하다, 도착하다, 준비가 다 되어가다, 
마련하다
voca.explains:
to travel from one place to another, usually from a smaller place to a larger one, or from the south of a country to the north
(to somebody/something) to go towards a person in order to talk to them
to appear above the ground
when the sun or moon comes up, it rises in the sky
to rise to the surface of water or another liquid
(always used in the progressive tenses) be coming upto be going to happen very soon
to be talked about or discussed
When he came up, he plunged forward, desperately trying to get to shore.
B : Does the internet come up at all?
B : Apparently, something has come up and she couldn't come.
B : Yes, she said something suddenly came up.

voca.title: come up in conversation
voca.explains:
Those topics do come up in conversation.
I hope it desn't come up in conversation.
If it comes up in conversation, you should explain.

voca.title: come up with
voca.means:
~을 따라잡다, 제안하다, 해내다, 
~을 고안해 내다
~을 꺼내놓다
~을 생각해 내다
(해답을) 찾아내다, 고안해 내다
voca.explains:
I can't come up with any place she might be.
I can come up with better rhymes than him anyway.
"How did you come up with that rhyme?"
They come up with a lot of user-created content (UCC). Plus, they access the Internet with their phones a lot.
A new anti-graft law came into effect last year. Its’ commonly referred to as the Kim Young-ran law. It was named after the person who came up with it.
"Who came up with this stupid idea?"
"If you had more musicians." Buster went on, "it would be easy to come up with a tune."
"It’s good, but it isn't enough. I'll never come up with anything more."
Over the years, I have failed to come up with a proper morning routine. I have told myself time and time again to get a jump-start on my day by waking up bright and early.
Did you come up with a plan to get us out of here?
Why don't you come up with a proposal?

voca.title: come upon
voca.explains: to be almost a particular time or age\nto meet or encounter unexpectedly\n

voca.title: come what may
voca.explains: whatever may happen\n

voca.title: come with
voca.explains: to be included with or as part of something\nI love it except for a few things. It doesn't come with a sun roof and a GPS unit.\n

voca.title: comedy
voca.explains:
Comedy consists of types of entertainment, such as plays and films, or particular scenes in them, that are intended to make people laugh.
A comedy is a play, film, or television programme that is intended to make people laugh.
The comedy of a situation involves those aspects of it that make you laugh.

voca.title: comes in handy
voca.explains: My flashlight near my bed at night comes in handy.\nLisa: Yes! That class came in handy.\n

voca.title: comet
voca.explains: A comet is a bright object with a long tail that travels around the sun.\nHe felt calm and safe as the stag sped like a white comet throught the wintry countryside.\n

voca.title: comfort
voca.means:
[캄퍼rt]
위로, 위안, 안도감, 안심, 편안
위로하다, 격려하다
위안을 주는(위로가 되는) 사람/것
voca.explains:
If you are doing something in comfort, you are physically relaxed and contented, and are not feeling any pain or other unpleasant sensations.
Comfort is a style of life in which you have enough money to have everything you need.
Comfort is what you feel when worries or unhappiness stop.
If you refer to a person, thing, or idea as a comfort, you mean that it helps you to stop worrying or makes you feel less unhappy.
If you comfort someone, you make them feel less worried, unhappy, or upset, for example by saying kind things to them.
If you say that something is, for example, too close for comfort, you mean you are worried because it is closer than you would like it to be.

voca.title: comfortable
voca.means: [^컴풔더벌]\n편안한, 안락한, 쾌적한\n풍족한, 넉넉한, 많은 차이가 나는
voca.explains:
rich / wealthy / prosperous / affluent / well off / comfortable
If a piece of furniture or an item of clothing is comfortable, it makes you feel physically relaxed when you use it, for example because it is soft.
If a building or room is comfortable, it makes you feel physically relaxed when you spend time in it, for example because it is warm and has nice furniture.
If you are comfortable, you are physically relaxed because of the place or position you are sitting or lying in.
If you say that someone is comfortable, you mean that they have enough money to be able to live without financial problems.
A : Do you have anything with more comfortable fit?
"I'm not very comfortable yet. The other day I was playing second base. I fielded a sharp grounder but I couldn't get it out of my glove. It was like the ball was stuck with glue."

voca.title: comforting
voca.explains: If you say that something is comforting, you mean it makes you feel less worried or unhappy.\n

voca.title: comfy
voca.explains:
A comfy item of clothing, piece of furniture, room, or position is a comfortable one.
Comfy clothes and hiking boots are all you need. Then you're good to go.
The theater was packed with people. However, the seats were comfy, so I didn’t mind.

voca.title: comic
voca.explains:
funny / amusing / entertaining / witty / humorous / comic / hilarious
If you describe something as comic, you mean that it makes you laugh, and is often intended to make you laugh.
Comic is used to describe comedy as a form of entertainment, and the actors and entertainers who perform it.
A comic is an entertainer who tells jokes in order to make people laugh.
A comic is a magazine that contains stories told in pictures.

voca.title: coming
voca.explains: A coming event or time is an event or time that will happen soon.\n

voca.title: coming in
voca.explains: "My plane is coming in at 1 pm tomorrow."\nJerry: My sister is coming in from New York to visit. I'm meeting her at the airport.\n

voca.title: coming up
voca.explains: Your birthday is coming up isn't it?\n

voca.title: command
voca.means: [커멘d]\n명령, 지령, 사령부, 지휘\n명령하다, 지시하다, ~을 지배/억제 하다
voca.explains:
order / tell / instruct / direct / command
If someone in authority commands you to do something, they tell you that you must do it.
If you command something such as respect or obedience, you obtain it because you are popular, famous, or important.
If an army or country commands a place, they have total control over it.
In the armed forces, a command is a group of officers who are responsible for organizing and controlling part of an army, navy, or air force.
In computing, a command is an instruction that you give to a computer.

voca.title: commemorate
voca.explains: To commemorate an important event or person means to remember them by means of a special action, ceremony, or specially created object.\nOctover 3rd is the day when Koreans commemorate the founding of this ancient nation.\n

voca.title: commendable
voca.means: [커멘더벌]\n칭찬할 만한, 추천할 만한, 훌륭한\n명령/지배할 수 있는
voca.explains: If you describe someone's behaviour as commendable, you approve of it or are praising it.\n

voca.title: comment
voca.means: [^커멘t]\n말, 발언, 논평, 언급, 의견\n주석을 달다, 논평하다, 견해를 밝히다
voca.explains:
comment / note / remark / observe
If you comment on something, you give your opinion about it or you give an explanation for it.
A comment is something that you say which expresses your opinion of something or which gives an explanation of it.
If an event or situation is a comment on something, it reveals something about that thing, usually something bad.

voca.title: commerce
voca.explains: Commerce is the activities and procedures involved in buying and selling things.\n

voca.title: commercial
voca.explains:
ad / advertisement / commercial / promotion / advert / trailer
Commercial means involving or relating to the buying and selling of goods.
Commercial organizations and activities are concerned with making money or profits, rather than, for example, with scientific research or providing a public service.
A commercial product is made to be sold to the public.
A commercial vehicle is a vehicle used for carrying goods, or passengers who pay.

voca.title: commercialize
voca.explains: If something is commercialized, it is used or changed in such a way that it makes money or profits, often in a way that people disapprove of.\n

voca.title: commit
voca.means:
[커^밋t]
(그릇된 일, 범쥐를)저지르다, 자살하다,
(병원, 교도소 등에) 수용/수감하다
(재판에) 회부하다
약속하다, 전념하다
(공개적으로) 의사/결정을 밝히다
~을 적어두다
voca.explains:
If someone commits a crime or a sin, they do something illegal or bad.
If someone commits suicide, they deliberately kill themselves.
If you commit money or resources to something, you decide to use them for a particular purpose.
If you commit yourself to something, you say that you will definitely do it. If you commit yourself to someone, you decide that you want to have a long-term relationship with them.
If you do not want to commit yourself on something, you do not want to say what you really think about it or what you are going to do.
If someone is committed to a hospital, prison, or other institution, they are officially sent there for a period of time.
If you commit something to paper or to writing, you record it by writing it down. If you commit something to memory, you learn it so that you will remember it.

voca.title: commit a crime
voca.explains: There is a price to pay for committing a crime.\n

voca.title: commitment
voca.explains:
Commitment is a strong belief in an idea or system.
A commitment is something which regularly takes up some of your time because of an agreement you have made or because of responsibilities that you have.
If you make a commitment to do something, you promise that you will do it.
Commitment is the process of officially sending someone to a prison or to hospital.

voca.title: committee
voca.explains: A committee is a group of people who meet to make decisions or plans for a larger group or organization that they represent.\n

voca.title: common
voca.means:
[^커믄]
흔한, 공동의, 공통의, 
보통의, 평범한
(한 도시나 마을에서 넓게 트인) 공유지, 공원
공유지, 평민
(학교 등의) 식당
voca.explains:
If something is common, it is found in large numbers or it happens often.
If something is common to two or more people or groups, it is done, possessed, or used by them all.
When there are more animals or plants of a particular species than there are of related species, then the first species is called common.
Common is used to indicate that someone or something is of the ordinary kind and not special in any way.
Common decency or common courtesy is the decency or courtesy which most people have. 
You can use common to describe knowledge, an opinion, or a feeling that is shared by people in general.
If you describe someone or their behaviour as common, you mean that they show a lack of taste, education, and good manners.
A common is an area of grassy land, usually in or near a village or small town, where the public is allowed to go.
The Commons is the same as the House of Commons. The members of the House of Commons can also be referred to as the Commons.

voca.title: common knowledge
voca.explains: It’s common knowledge that accidents are most likely to happen at home. One of the things people need to be wary about is breaking glass.\n

voca.title: common sense
voca.explains: Your common sense is your natural ability to make good judgments and to behave in a practical and sensible way.\n"Yes, I am, Edward." She walked up the steps. "I'm glad to see your memory hasn't failed you-even if your common sense has."\n

voca.title: commonality
voca.explains: Commonality is used to refer to a feature or purpose that is shared by two or more people or things.\nFinding Commonalities in Two Dictionaries\n

voca.title: commonly
voca.explains: A new anti-graft law came into effect last year. Its’ commonly referred to as the Kim Young-ran law.\n

voca.title: commonplace
voca.means:
[^커-먼플레이s]
아주 흔한
흔히 있는 일, 다반사
진부한 말, 상투어
voca.explains:
If something is commonplace, it happens often or is often found, and is therefore not surprising.
A commonplace is a remark or opinion that is often expressed and is therefore not original or interesting.
Korea has an excellent internet infrastructure. Broadband connections are available everywhere. As a result, online lectures are very commonplace. Students prep for college entrance exams through online lectures.

voca.title: commotion
voca.explains: A commotion is a lot of noise, confusion, and excitement.\n

voca.title: communicate
voca.means:
[커뮤니케잇t]
연락을 주고받다, 의사소통을 하다, 
(정보 등을) 전달하다, 
소통하다, 
(병을) 전염시키다
voca.explains:
talk / discuss / speak / communicate
If you communicate with someone, you share or exchange information with them, for example by speaking, writing, or using equipment. You can also say that two people communicate.
If you communicate information, a feeling, or an idea to someone, you let them know about it.
If one person communicates with another, they successfully make each other aware of their feelings and ideas. You can also say that two people communicate.

voca.title: communication
voca.explains: Communications are the systems and processes that are used to communicate or broadcast information, especially by means of electricity or radio waves.\nA communication is a message.\n

voca.title: community
voca.explains:
The community is all the people who live in a particular area or place.
A particular community is a group of people who are similar in some way.
Community is friendship between different people or groups, and a sense of having something in common.

voca.title: commute
voca.explains:
If you commute, you travel a long distance every day between your home and your place of work.
If a death sentence or prison sentence is commuted to a less serious punishment, it is changed to that punishment.
A commute is the journey that you make when you commute.
I like to listen to music on the go while commuting. This is why the latest trend of streaming music on a smartphone excites me. It’s quick, cost-efficient and you don’t have to be tech-savvy to use it.

voca.title: compact
voca.means:
[컴^펙t]
(같은 종류의 일반적인 제품보다) 소형의, 간편한
소형의, 간편한, (공간이) 작은
꽉 채우다, ~을 굳히다, 응축/압축하다
꽉찬, 빽빽한, 작고 경제적인, 간결한
(사람들이나 국가 간의 정식) 합의[협정]
소형차
voca.explains:
Compact things are small or take up very little space. You use this word when you think this is a good quality.
A compact person is small but strong.
A compact cassette, camera, or car is a small type of cassette, camera, or car.
To compact something means to press it so that it becomes more solid.

voca.title: companion
voca.explains: A companion is someone who you spend time with or who you are travelling with.\n

voca.title: company
voca.means:
[^컴퍼니]
회사, 친구, 교제, 함께 있음
(함께 일하거나 공연하는) 단체
중대
voca.explains:
A company is a business organization that makes money by selling goods or services.
A company is a group of opera singers, dancers, or actors who work together.
A company is a group of soldiers that is usually part of a battalion or regiment, and that is divided into two or more platoons.
Company is having another person or other people with you, usually when this is pleasant or stops you feeling lonely.
If you say that someone is in good company, you mean that they should not be ashamed of a mistake or opinion, because some important or respected people have made the same mistake or have the same opinion.
If you have company, you have a visitor or friend with you.
When you are in company, you are with a person or group of people.
If you keep someone company, you spend time with them and stop them feeling lonely or bored.
If you keep company with a person or with a particular kind of person, you spend a lot of time with them.
If two or more people part company, they go in different directions after going in the same direction together.
If you part company with someone, you end your association with them, often because of a disagreement.

voca.title: comparative
voca.means:
[컴^페뤄듸v]
(무엇에 대한 연구가) 비교를 통한, 비교의
상대적인, 비교적
비교급의
voca.explains:
You use comparative to show that you are judging something against a previous or different situation. For example, comparative calm is a situation which is calmer than before or calmer than the situation in other places.
A comparative study is a study that involves the comparison of two or more things of the same kind.
In grammar, the comparative form of an adjective or adverb shows that something has more of a quality than something else has. For example, 'bigger' is the comparative form of 'big', and 'more quickly' is the comparative form of 'quickly'. Compare superlative.

voca.title: compare
voca.explains:
When you compare things, you consider them and discover the differences or similarities between them.
If you compare one person or thing to another, you say that they are like the other person or thing.
If one thing compares favourably with another, it is better than the other thing. If it compares unfavourably, it is worse than the other thing.
If you say that something does not compare with something else, you mean that it is much worse.

voca.title: compared to
voca.explains: What you’re getting now is chicken-feed compared to what you could earn in Europe.\n

voca.title: comparison
voca.explains:
When you make a comparison, you consider two or more things and discover the differences between them.
When you make a comparison, you say that one thing is like another in some way.
If you say, for example, that something is large or small in comparison with, in comparison to, or by comparison with something else, you mean that it is larger or smaller than the other thing.
If you say there is no comparison between one thing and another, you mean that you think the first thing is much better than the second, or very different from it.

voca.title: compartment
voca.means: [컴^파r-t먼t]\n(기차안의 칸막이를 한) 객실, 구획, 격실, 모듈\n~을 구분하다, 구획으로 나누다
voca.explains: A compartment is one of the separate spaces into which a railway carriage is divided.\nA compartment is one of the separate parts of an object that is used for keeping things in.\n

voca.title: compatible
voca.means:
[컴^풰듸블]
(특히 컴퓨터가) 호환이 되는
양립될 수 있는
(두 사람이 생각, 흥미 등이 비승하여) 화합할 수 있는, 잘 맞는
voca.explains:
If things, for example systems, ideas, and beliefs, are compatible, they work well together or can exist together successfully.
If you say that you are compatible with someone, you mean that you have a good relationship with them because you have similar opinions and interests.
If one make of computer or computer equipment is compatible with another make, especially IBM, they can be used together and can use the same software.
All breakups are bound to be bad. If two people were compatible, they would still be together.

voca.title: compel
voca.explains: If a situation, a rule, or a person compels you to do something, they force you to do it.\nIf you feel compelled to do something, you feel that you must do it, because it is the right thing to do.\n

voca.title: compelling
voca.means:
[컴풸링]
(너무나 흥미로워서) 주목하지 않을 수 없는, 
강렬한, 설득력 있는, 강력한, 
강제적인, 강력한, 억지의
voca.explains:
interesting / fascinating / compelling / stimulating / gripping / absorbing
A compelling argument or reason is one that convinces you that something is true or that something should be done.
If you describe something such as a film or book, or someone's appearance, as compelling, you mean you want to keep looking at it or reading it because you find it so interesting.

voca.title: compensation
voca.explains: Compensation is money that someone who has experienced loss or suffering claims from the person or organization responsible, or from the state.\nIf something is some compensation for something bad that has happened, it makes you feel better.\n

voca.title: compete
voca.explains:
When one firm or country competes with another, it tries to get people to buy its own goods in preference to those of the other firm or country. You can also say that two firms or countries compete.
If you compete with someone for something, you try to get it for yourself and stop the other person getting it. You can also say that two people compete for something.
If you compete in a contest or a game, you take part in it.

voca.title: compete against each other
voca.explains:
There is another show where top singers compete against each other.
Students must compete against each other to get into college.
You will learn more if you compete against each other.
Car technology is an important field of research. Carmakers are competing against each other to develop the best new vehicles.
There are shows in which chefs compete against each other. There are shows in which seasoned experts teach cooking to newcomers. There are even shows in which celebrities reveal their original recipes. And of course, there are countless recipes online.

voca.title: competence
voca.explains: Competence is the ability to do something well or effectively.\n

voca.title: competency
voca.explains: Competency means the same as competence.\n

voca.title: competition
voca.explains:
Competition is a situation in which two or more people or groups are trying to get something which not everyone can have.
The competition is the person or people you are competing with.
Competition is an activity involving two or more firms, in which each firm tries to get people to buy its own goods in preference to the other firms' goods.
The competition is the goods that a rival organization is selling.
A competition is an event in which many people take part in order to find out who is best at a particular activity.
Many Korean people are talented signers. Most people have a go-to song that they like to sing. Because singing is so popular, there are many music competition programs.

voca.title: competitior
voca.explains: A company's competitors are companies who are trying to sell similar goods or services to the same people.\nA competitor is a person who takes part in a competition or contest.\n

voca.title: competitive
voca.explains:
cheap / competitive / budget / affordable / reasonable / inexpensive
Competitive is used to describe situations or activities in which people or firms compete with each other.
A competitive person is eager to be more successful than other people.
Goods or services that are at a competitive price or rate are likely to be bought, because they are less expensive than other goods of the same kind.
Your idea sounds competitive.
The company launched a competitive product.
The price range of these cosmetics is pretty reliable and competitive.

voca.title: compilation
voca.means:
[컴펄레이션]
(특히 여러 다른 책이나 음반에서 내용을 딴)
모음집, 편집본, 
편집, 편찬
voca.explains: A compilation is a book, CD, or programme that contains many different items that have been gathered together, usually ones which have already appeared in other places.\n

voca.title: compile
voca.means: [컴파일]\n(여러 출처에서 자료를 따와) 엮다, 편집/편찬하다\n(컴퓨터) 명령어를 번역/컴파일 하다
voca.explains: When you compile something such as a report, book, or programme, you produce it by collecting and putting together many pieces of information.\n

voca.title: complacent
voca.explains: A complacent person is very pleased with themselves or feels that they do not need to do anything about a situation, even though the situation may be uncertain or dangerous.\nPark: I don't want you to get complacent and stop working hard.\n

voca.title: complain
voca.explains:
complain / protest / object / grumble / moan / whine / whinge
If you complain about a situation, you say that you are not satisfied with it.
If you complain of pain or illness, you say that you are feeling pain or feeling ill.
Francine was busy complaining. "Our problem is batting." she said. "We don't have good batting."

voca.title: complaint
voca.explains:
A complaint is a statement in which you express your dissatisfaction with a particular situation.
A complaint is a reason for complaining.
You can refer to an illness as a complaint, especially if it is not very serious.
I received my cup and took a sip. However, it wasn’t green tea, but coffee. I made a complaint at the counter.

voca.title: complement
voca.means:
[^컴플러먼t]
보충하다, 덧붙이다, 보완하다,
보충 (부족한 것을 완전하게), 
(필요하거나 허용되는) 전체 수/량
(문법) 보어
voca.explains:
compliment / complement
If one thing complements another, it goes well with the other thing and makes its good qualities more noticeable.
If people or things complement each other, they are different or do something different, which makes them a good combination.
Something that is a complement to something else complements it.
The complement of things or people that something has is the number of things or people that it normally has, which enable it to function properly.

voca.title: complete
voca.means:
[검플뤼t]
(강조의 의미로) 가능한 최대의, 완벽한,
필요한 모든 것이 갖춰진, 완전한, 완성된
~을 완결하다, 끝마치다, 
(서식을 빠짐없이) 기입하다/작성하다
voca.explains:
You use complete to emphasize that something is as great in extent, degree, or amount as it possibly can be.
You can use complete to emphasize that you are referring to the whole of something and not just part of it.
If something is complete, it contains all the parts that it should contain.
The complete works of a writer are all their books or poems published together in one book or as a set of books.
If something is complete, it has been finished.
To complete a set or group means to provide the last item that is needed to make it a full set or group.

voca.title: completely
voca.explains: I was completely caught off guard when the lightbulb went out in my bathroom while I was taking a shower a few weeks ago. Because it came out of nowhere, I thought we were having a blackout.\n

voca.title: completely overreact
voca.explains: She completely overreacted. She accused me of being a gossip. I should have let it slide. Instead, I took the bait. We argued bitterly. We traded insults on the phone.\n

voca.title: complex
voca.means:
[^컴플렉s]
복잡한, 합성의, 복합의, 까다로운
복합체, 합성물, 콤플렉스, 강박 관념
(관련 있는 것들의) 덩어리, 집합체
~을 복잡하게 하다
voca.explains:
building / property / premises / complex / structure / block / edifice
Something that is complex has many different parts, and is therefore often difficult to understand.
In grammar, a complex sentence contains one or more subordinate clauses as well as a main clause. Compare compound.
A complex is a group of buildings designed for a particular purpose, or one large building divided into several smaller areas.
If someone has a complex about something, they have a mental or emotional problem relating to it, often because of an unpleasant experience in the past.

voca.title: complexion
voca.means:
[^컴플렉션]
안색, 혈색, 얼굴빛, 얼굴 피부
(사태의) 외관, 형편, 양상
체질, 성격
voca.explains:
When you refer to someone's complexion, you are referring to the natural colour or condition of the skin on their face.
The complexion of something is its general nature or character.
My breakouts have subsided, so now I pop my own pimples. But when my skin acts up again, I visit the dermatologist for professional extractions. Clear complexion brings out the best in everyone.

voca.title: complexity
voca.explains: Complexity is the state of having many different parts connected or related to each other in a complicated way.\n

voca.title: complicate
voca.explains: To complicate something means to make it more difficult to understand or deal with.\n

voca.title: complicated
