voca.explains: If you say that something is complicated, you mean it has so many parts or aspects that it is difficult to understand or deal with.\n"I don't know what's so complicated." said D.W. She put out her hands as though she were balancing things in a scale. "Some creepy books here. Free WonderWorld here." She lowered her WonderWorld hand to her knees, as though it was holding something heavy. The other hand shot up. "No contest."\n

voca.title: complication
voca.explains: A complication is a problem or difficulty that makes a situation harder to deal with.\nA complication is a medical problem that occurs as a result of another illness or disease.\n

voca.title: compliment
voca.explains:
compliment / complement
A compliment is a polite remark that you say to someone to show that you like their appearance, appreciate their qualities, or approve of what they have done.
You can refer to your compliments when you want to express thanks, good wishes, or respect to someone in a formal way.
If you compliment someone, you pay them a compliment.
If you say that someone returns the compliment, you mean that they do the same thing to someone else as that person has done to them.
The compliments did wonders for my confidence.
The other kind of detective likes to take a bow, to be recognized for doing good work. He doesn’t duck the well-deserved compliment. I could see both sides, and I understood that some detectives would be shy about taking credit for untangling things.

voca.title: complimentary
voca.explains:
If you are complimentary about something, you express admiration for it.
A complimentary seat, ticket, or book is given to you free.
I especially liked the complimentary breakfast.
I found a hotel that serves complimentary breakfast.

voca.title: component
voca.means: [컴^포우넌t]\n성분, 구성요소, 부품, 부분\n구성하는, 구성 요소를 이루는
voca.explains: The components of something are the parts that it is made of.\nThe component parts of something are the parts that make it up.\n

voca.title: compose
voca.explains:
The things that something is composed of are its parts or members. The separate things that compose something are the parts or members that form it.
When someone composes a piece of music, they write it.
If you compose something such as a letter, poem, or speech, you write it, often using a lot of concentration or skill.
If you compose yourself or if you compose your features, you succeed in becoming calm after you have been angry, excited, or upset.

voca.title: composite
voca.explains: A composite object or item is made up of several different things, parts, or substances.\n

voca.title: composition
voca.means:
[컴퍼^지션]
구성 요소들, 구성, 
(음악, 미술, 시) 작품
작곡, 작성, 작곡법
(학교에서 하는) 작문, 짧은 에세이
(그림, 사진의) 구도
voca.explains:
structure / framework / composition / construction / fabric / make-up
When you talk about the composition of something, you are referring to the way in which its various parts are put together and arranged.
The compositions of a composer, painter, or other artist are the works of art that they have produced.
A composition is a piece of written work that children write at school.
Composition is the technique or skill involved in creating a work of art.

voca.title: compost
voca.explains:
Compost is a mixture of decayed plants and vegetable waste which is added to the soil to help plants grow.
Compost is specially treated soil that you buy and use to grow seeds and plants in pots.
To compost things such as unwanted bits of plants means to make them into compost.

voca.title: compound
voca.means:
[컴^파운d]
복합체, 혼합물, 복합적인 요소, 화합물
혼합하다, 조제하다, 만들다, 조립하다
악화시키다, 더 심각하게 만들다
~으로 구성되다/이루어지다
섞다, 혼합하다.
(이자를) 복리로 지불하다/청구하다
합성의,  혼합/복합의
voca.explains:
A compound is an enclosed area of land that is used for a particular purpose.
In chemistry, a compound is a substance that consists of two or more elements.
If something is a compound of different things, it consists of those things.
Compound is used to indicate that something consists of two or more parts or things.
In grammar, a compound sentence is one that is made up of two or more main clauses. Compare complex.
To compound a problem, difficulty, or mistake means to make it worse by adding to it.

voca.title: comprehend
voca.explains: understand / see / get / follow / grasp / comprehend\nIf you cannot comprehend something, you cannot understand it.\n

voca.title: comprehension
voca.explains:
Comprehension is the ability to understand something.
Comprehension is full knowledge and understanding of the meaning of something.
When pupils do comprehension, they do an exercise to find out how well they understand a piece of spoken or written language.

voca.title: comprehensive
voca.explains: Something that is comprehensive includes everything that is needed or relevant.\nIn Britain, a comprehensive is a state school in which children of all abilities are taught together.\n

voca.title: comprehensive examination
voca.explains: On my family's advice, I recently received a medical check-up. It was a comprehensive examination.\n

voca.title: compressibility
voca.explains: the ability to be compressed\nsymbol k the reciprocal of the bulk modulus; the ratio of volume strain to stress at constant temperature\n

voca.title: compression
voca.means: [컴p^뤠션]\n압축, 압착(된 것),\n(사상, 언어 등의) 요약, 압축

voca.title: comprise
voca.explains: If you say that something comprises or is comprised of a number of things or people, you mean it has them as its parts or members.\nThe things or people that comprise something are the parts or members that form it.\n

voca.title: compromise
voca.explains:
A compromise is a situation in which people accept something slightly different from what they really want, because of circumstances or because they are considering the wishes of other people.
If you compromise with someone, you reach an agreement with them in which you both give up something that you originally wanted. You can also say that two people or groups compromise.
If someone compromises themselves or compromises their beliefs, they do something which damages their reputation for honesty, loyalty, or high moral principles.

voca.title: computation
voca.explains: Computation is mathematical calculation.\n

voca.title: computer
voca.explains: A computer is an electronic machine that can store and deal with large amounts of information.\n

voca.title: computer guru
voca.explains:
Last week, I tried to fire up my laptop, but nothing happened. It simply refused to boot up. I called up my computer guru friend. He gave me a few pointers. None of them worked. My computer had given up the ghost. I took it to a service center.
It was an easy problem for the computer grou to fix.
Why don't you ask a computer grou for advice?

voca.title: computer peripheral
voca.explains: Computer peripherals like printers, scanners, mouses and keyboards can also be connected with Bluetooth. This frees up space on one's desk.\n

voca.title: concatenate
voca.means:
[콘케러네잇t]
사슬같이 잇다, 연쇄시키다
(사건 등을) 결부/연결 시키다, 연관시키다
연쇄된, 이어진, 연결된
voca.explains: to link or join together, esp in a chain or series\nlinked or joined together\n

voca.title: conceal
voca.explains:
hide / conceal / cover / disguise / mask / camouflage
If you conceal something, you cover it or hide it carefully.
If you conceal a piece of information or a feeling, you do not let other people know about it.
If something conceals something else, it covers it and prevents it from being seen.

voca.title: concentrate
voca.explains:
If you concentrate on something, or concentrate your mind on it, you give all your attention to it.
If something is concentrated in an area, it is all there rather than being spread around.
Concentrate is a liquid or substance from which water has been removed in order to make it stronger, or to make it easier to store.
"Stay out of this, Arthur." said Francine. "You need to concentrate all your attention on holding on to the ball."
"If we concentrate on learning the fundamentals." said the Brain, "our chances of winning will improve over time."

voca.title: concentrate on
voca.explains: to spend more time doing one particular thing than others\n"Sometimes it feels like everyone is concentrating on what a bad job I'm doing. Not Coach Frensky, though. He's always encouraging. He says I'm making good progress."\n

voca.title: concentration
voca.means:
[^컨센츄뤠이션]
정신 집중, (노동 등의) 집중
(무엇이 한군데에 모이는) 집중
농도
voca.explains:
Concentration on something involves giving all your attention to it.
A concentration of something is a large amount of it or large numbers of it in a small area.
The concentration of a substance is the proportion of essential ingredients or substances in it.
Buster was sitting on his couch, deep in concentration.
"That's perfectly natural." said Mr. Read. "Be patient, Arthur. You're paying attention, and that's what's important. Baseball is ninety-nine percent concentration."

voca.title: concept
voca.explains: A concept is an idea or abstract principle.\nMany movies are shot 3D. Others are shot normally, and are converted 3D later on. It felt unfamiliar at first, but more people are getting used to the concept.\n

voca.title: concern
voca.means:
[컨^써r-n]
(사람에게) 영향을 미치다, 관련되다, 
(무엇에) 관련된 것이다, 
~을 걱정스럽게 만들다, 염려하다, 걱정하다, 관여하다
~에 흥미/관심을 갖다,
관계, 이해관계, 관심사, 염려
회사, 업체
voca.explains:
Concern is worry about a situation.
A concern is a fact or situation that worries you.
Someone's concern with something is their feeling that it is important.
Concern for someone is a feeling that you want them to be happy, safe, and well. If you do something out of concern for someone, you do it because you want them to be happy, safe, and well.
If something concerns you, it worries you.
If a situation or problem is your concern, it is something that you have a duty or responsibility to be involved with.
If you concern yourself with something, you give it attention because you think that it is important.
You can refer to a company or business as a concern, usually when you are describing what type of company or business it is.
If something such as a book or a piece of information concerns a particular subject, it is about that subject.
When it comes to travelling, safety is a major concern.

voca.title: concerned
voca.explains:
worried / concerned / nervous / anxious / uneasy
If you are concerned to do something, you want to do it because you think it is important.
You look so concerned.
Her father stroked his chin. "It's natural for you to be concerned. After all, he is one of your best friends."

voca.title: concerning
voca.explains: You use concerning to indicate what a question or piece of information is about.\n

voca.title: concession
voca.means:
[컨^쎄션]
(언쟁을 끝내거나 상황을 개선하기 위한) 양보, 양해
인정
할인, 할인표
(특히 정부나 고용주가 집단, 단체 등에 부여하는) 권리, 혜택
voca.explains:
If you make a concession to someone, you agree to let them do or have something, especially in order to end an argument or conflict.
A concession is a special right or privilege that is given to someone.
A concession is a special price which is lower than the usual price and which is often given to old people, students, and the unemployed.
A concession is an arrangement where someone is given the right to sell a product or to run a business, especially in a building belonging to another business.

voca.title: concession stand
voca.explains: The theater was a big multiplex. It was located in a mall, so we ate dinner at the food court. We went to the concession stand before the movie to buy popcorn.\n

voca.title: conclude
voca.means:
[컨클루-d]
결론/결판을 내리다, 결론짓다,
끝내다, 마치다, 
(협정, 조약을 ) 맺다, 체결하다,
voca.explains:
If you conclude that something is true, you decide that it is true using the facts you know as a basis.
When you conclude, you say the last thing that you are going to say.
When something concludes, or when you conclude it, you end it.
If one person or group concludes an agreement, such as a treaty or business deal, with another, they arrange it. You can also say that two people or groups conclude an agreement.

voca.title: conclusion
voca.explains:
When you come to a conclusion, you decide that something is true after you have thought about it carefully and have considered all the relevant facts.
The conclusion of something is its ending.
The conclusion of a treaty or a business deal is the act of arranging it or agreeing it.
You can refer to something that seems certain to happen as a foregone conclusion.

voca.title: concrete
voca.means:
[컨k뤼-t]
콘크리트로 된, 
콘크리트로 굳히다, 응고하다, 굳어지다
콘크리트, 구체적 관념, 결합체
구체적인, 현실에 근거한, 실제적인
voca.explains:
Concrete is a substance used for building which is made by mixing together cement, sand, small stones, and water.
When you concrete something such as a path, you cover it with concrete.
You use concrete to indicate that something is definite and specific.
A concrete object is a real, physical object.
A concrete noun is a noun that refers to a physical object rather than to a quality or idea.
If a plan or idea is set in concrete or embedded in concrete, it is fixed and cannot be changed.

voca.title: concurrent
voca.explains: Concurrent events or situations happen at the same time.\n

voca.title: condemn
voca.means:
[컨^뎀-]
(보통 도덕적인 이유로) 규탄/비난하다
선고를 내리다
(좋지 않은 상황에) 처하게 만들다
유죄를 시사하다(보여주다)
voca.explains:
If you condemn something, you say that it is very bad and unacceptable.
If someone is condemned to a punishment, they are given this punishment.
If circumstances condemn you to an unpleasant situation, they make it certain that you will suffer in that way.
If authorities condemn a building, they officially decide that it is not safe and must be pulled down or repaired.
"Answer the question." said the voice. "Have you read the books you're condemning?

voca.title: condition
voca.means:
[컨^딧션]
상태, 조건, 상황, 날씨
(치유가 안 되는 만성) 질환, 문제
(생활, 작업 등의) 환경, 상황
(물리적) 환경, (특정 시기의) 날씨
(요구) 조건
길들이다, 훈련시키다, 
좌우하다, 영향을 미치다
voca.explains:
condition / state
If you talk about the condition of a person or thing, you are talking about the state that they are in, especially how good or bad their physical state is.
The conditions under which something is done or happens are all the factors or circumstances which directly affect it.
The conditions in which people live or work are the factors which affect their comfort, safety, or health.
A condition is something which must happen or be done in order for something else to be possible, especially when this is written into a contract or law.
If someone has a particular condition, they have an illness or other medical problem.
To condition your hair or skin means to put something on it which will keep it in good condition.
If you say that someone is in no condition to do something, you mean that they are too ill, upset, or drunk to do it.
When you agree to do something on condition that something else happens, you mean that you will only do it if this other thing also happens.
If someone is conditioned by their experiences or environment, they are influenced by them over a period of time so that they do certain things or think in a particular way.
I will help you, but only under one condition.

voca.title: conditional
voca.explains: If a situation or agreement is conditional on something, it will only happen or continue if this thing happens.\nIn grammar, a conditional clause is a subordinate clause which refers to a situation which may exist or whose possible consequences you are considering. Most conditional clauses begin with 'if' or 'unless', for example 'If that happens, we'll be in big trouble' and 'You don't have to come unless you want to'.\n

voca.title: conduct
voca.means:
[컨^덕-t]
(특정한 활동을) 하다, 지휘하다
(어떤 장소를 이리저리) 안내하다
행동하다, 처신하다
(열이나 전기를) 전도하다
(특정한 장소나 상황에서의) 행동
경영, 수행, 처리
voca.explains:
When you conduct an activity or task, you organize it and carry it out.
If you conduct yourself in a particular way, you behave in that way.
When someone conducts an orchestra or choir, they stand in front of it and direct its performance.
If something conducts heat or electricity, it allows heat or electricity to pass through it or along it.
The conduct of a task or activity is the way in which it is organized and carried out.
Someone's conduct is the way they behave in particular situations.

voca.title: conductor
voca.means:
[큰^덕터r]
(합창, 합주의) 지휘자
여행 안내원
(버스나 기차의) 안내원, 승무원
(전기나 열의) 전도체
voca.explains:
A conductor is a person who stands in front of an orchestra or choir and directs its performance.
On a bus, the conductor is the person whose job is to sell tickets to the passengers.
On a train, a conductor is a person whose job is to travel on the train in order to help passengers and check tickets.
A conductor is a substance that heat or electricity can pass through or along.

voca.title: cone
voca.means:
[^코운]
원뿔, 원뿔형 물체
(도로 공사 구간 등에 세우는) 원뿔형 교통 표지
(아이스크림용) 콘
(소나무나 전나무의) 원뿔형 열매/방울
voca.explains:
A cone is a shape with a circular base and smooth curved sides ending in a point at the top.
A cone is the fruit of a tree such as a pine or fir.
A cone is a thin, cone-shaped biscuit that is used for holding ice cream. You can also refer to an ice cream that you eat in this way as a cone.

voca.title: confederate
voca.means:
[컨풰더뤳t]
공범, 공모자
동맹한, 연맹한, 연맹에 속한, 연합의
공모한, 결탁한
voca.explains: Someone's confederates are the people they are working with in a secret activity.\n

voca.title: confer
voca.means:
[컨^풔r-]
상의하다, 상담하다
수여하다, 주다, 협의하다
(상, 학위, 명예, 자격을) 수여/부여하다
voca.explains:
When you confer with someone, you discuss something with them in order to make a decision. You can also say that two people confer.
To confer something such as power or an honour on someone means to give it to them.
He wanted to confer with his colleagues before reaching a decision.

voca.title: conference
voca.means:
[^컨풔런s]
(보통 여러 날 동안 대규모로 열리는) 회의, 학회
(공식) 회담, 협의
(스포츠) 연맹
voca.explains: A conference is a meeting, often lasting a few days, which is organized on a particular subject or to bring together people who have a common interest.\nA conference is a meeting at which formal discussions take place.\n

voca.title: confess
voca.means:
[컨풰s]
(죄, 잘못을) 자백하다, 
(수치스럽거나 당황스러운 것을) 고백하다, 
시인/인정하다
고해/고백 성사를 하다
voca.explains:
admit / acknowledge / concede / confess / allow / grant
If someone confesses to doing something wrong, they admit that they did it.
If someone confesses or confesses their sins, they tell God or a priest about their sins so that they can be forgiven.
You use expressions like 'I confess', 'I must confess', or 'I have to confess' to apologize slightly for admitting something you are ashamed of or that you think might offend or annoy someone.
'I did it,' Jack confessed.

voca.title: confession
voca.means: [컨^풰션]\n(죄의) 자백, 고백/인정, 고해 성사\n(종교적 신념 등의) 고백
voca.explains:
A confession is a signed statement by someone in which they admit that they have committed a particular crime.
Confession is the act of admitting that you have done something that you are ashamed of or embarrassed about.
If you make a confession of your beliefs or feelings, you publicly tell people that this is what you believe or feel.
In the Catholic church and in some other churches, if you go to confession, you privately tell a priest about your sins and ask for forgiveness.

voca.title: confidence
voca.explains:
If you have confidence in someone, you feel that you can trust them.
If you have confidence, you feel sure about your abilities, qualities, or ideas.
If you can say something with confidence, you feel certain it is correct.
If you tell someone something in confidence, you tell them a secret.
I need more confidence.
What you need is some more confidence.
If you’re full of confidence, you don’t need to worry about anything.
A : Barbara, I’d like to apply for a certain position. But I lack confidence.

voca.title: confident
voca.explains:
sure / confident / convinced / certain / positive
If you are confident about something, you are certain that it will happen in the way you want it to.
If a person or their manner is confident, they feel sure about their own abilities, qualities, or ideas.
If you are confident that something is true, you are sure that it is true. A confident statement is one that the speaker is sure is true.
For example, people with type O blood are thought to be ambitious, outgoing and confident.

voca.title: confidential
voca.explains: Information that is confidential is meant to be kept secret or private.\nIf you talk to someone in a confidential way, you talk to them quietly because what you are saying is secret or private.\n

voca.title: configuration
voca.means: [컨^퓌겨뤠이션]\n배열, 배치, 배열/배치 형태\n구성, 형상, 상대적 배치, 요소의 조합
voca.explains: A configuration is an arrangement of a group of things.\nThe configuration of a computer system is way in which all its parts, such as the hardware and software, are connected together in order for the computer to work.\n

voca.title: configure
voca.explains: If you configure a piece of computer equipment, you set it up so that it is ready for use.\n

voca.title: confirm
voca.means:
[컨^퍼r-엄]
(특히 증거를 들어) 사실임을 보여주다, 확인해 주다
(지위, 합의 등을) 확정하다, 공식화하다
확인하다, 입증하다, 승인하다
voca.explains:
If something confirms what you believe, suspect, or fear, it shows that it is definitely true.
If you confirm something that has been stated or suggested, you say that it is true because you know about it.
If you confirm an arrangement or appointment, you say that it is definite, usually in a letter or on the telephone.
If someone is confirmed, they are formally accepted as a member of a Christian church during a ceremony in which they say they believe what the church teaches.
If something confirms you in your decision, belief, or opinion, it makes you think that you are definitely right.
If someone confirms their position, role, or power, they do something to make their power, position, or role stronger or more definite.
If something confirms you as something, it shows that you definitely deserve a name, role, or position.

voca.title: confirm one's identity
voca.explains: Last week, I entered the wrong number too many times. The bank blocked my account. I had to go to the bank to confirm my identity.\n

voca.title: confirmation
voca.means:
[^컨퍼r메이션]
확인(무엇이 사실이거나 확정되었음을 보여주는 진술, 편지 등)
(기독교의) 견진 성사
유대교에서 16세 이상의 청소년을 위한 종교 의식

voca.title: confirmation number
voca.explains: A : Hello. I called to give you your confirmation number.\n

voca.title: conflict
voca.means:
[^컨플뤽t]
(사람이나 국가들 사이의 이해관계로 인한) 갈등, 충돌,
(국가간의 물리적) 충돌, 
(심리적 또는 의견들 간의) 갈등
출동하다, 겹치다, 상충하다
voca.explains:
Conflict is serious disagreement and argument about something important. If two people or groups are in conflict, they have had a serious disagreement or argument and have not yet reached agreement.
Conflict is a state of mind in which you find it impossible to make a decision.
Conflict is fighting between countries or groups of people.
A conflict is a serious difference between two or more beliefs, ideas, or interests. If two beliefs, ideas, or interests are in conflict, they are very different.
If ideas, beliefs, or accounts conflict, they are very different from each other and it seems impossible for them to exist together or to each be true.

voca.title: conflict of interest
voca.means: 이해의 충돌 (두 가지 일, 목적, 역할 등이 동시에 동등하고 공정하게 양립하기 어려운 상황)
voca.explains: a situation in which there are two jobs, aims, roles, etc. and it is not possible for both of them to be treated equally and fairly at the same time\n

voca.title: confront
voca.means:
[컨f^뤈t]
닥치다, (문제나 곤란한 상황에) 맞서다
(위험한 상황 등에) 정면으로 부딪치다, 마주치다
(힘들거나 좋지 않은 것에) 직면하게 만들다
~에 직면하다, 마주치다
voca.explains:
If you are confronted with a problem, task, or difficulty, you have to deal with it.
If you confront a difficult situation or issue, you accept the fact that it exists and try to deal with it.
If you are confronted by something that you find threatening or difficult to deal with, it is there in front of you.
If you confront someone, you stand or sit in front of them, especially when you are going to fight, argue, or compete with them.

voca.title: Confucian
voca.explains:
of or relating to the doctrines of Confucius
a follower of Confucius
A big part of Korean tradition is based on Confucian culture.

voca.title: confuse
voca.means: [컨^퓨-z]\n(사람을) 혼란시키다, A와 B를 혼동하다, \n~을 혼란시키다, 혼동하다
voca.explains:
If you confuse two things, you get them mixed up, so that you think one of them is the other one.
To confuse someone means to make it difficult for them to know exactly what is happening or what to do.
To confuse a situation means to make it complicated or difficult to understand.
I was confused, because she uses the lunar calendar.
Even on days when my schedule is hectic, I don’t get confused. I just check my itinerary in my planner.

voca.title: confusing
voca.explains:
Something that is confusing makes it difficult for people to know exactly what is happening or what to do.
It is very confusing to know what to eat.
Almost everyone has a mobile phone these days, but everyone pays a different amount. There are many different types of data plans. Sometimes it can be very confusing. I use a fixed-rate plan.
Your argument is confusing.
It can be confusing to be at a new place.

voca.title: confusion
voca.explains: If there is confusion about something, it is not clear what the true situation is, especially because people believe different things.\nConfusion is a situation in which everything is in disorder, especially because there are lots of things happening at the same time.\n

voca.title: congestion
voca.explains:
If there is congestion in a place, the place is extremely crowded and blocked with traffic or people.
Congestion in a part of the body is a medical condition in which the part becomes blocked.
A : It sounds like you have some congestion in your lungs.

voca.title: conglomerate
voca.means:
[컨g^러머러t]
(거대) 복합 기업, 대기업
(잡다한 물건의) 집합체, 복합체
(지리) 역암
voca.explains: A conglomerate is a large business firm consisting of several different companies.\nLast year, I applied to various companies for work. Finding employment is a tall order these days. I submitted my resume and took the entrance exam for a major conglomerate.\n

voca.title: congratulate
voca.explains:
If you congratulate someone, you say something to show you are pleased that something nice has happened to them.
If you congratulate someone, you praise them for something good that they have done.
If you congratulate yourself, you are pleased about something that you have done or that has happened to you

voca.title: congratulations
voca.explains: You say 'Congratulations' to someone in order to congratulate them on something nice that has happened to them or something good that they have done.\nIf you offer someone your congratulations, you congratulate them on something nice that has happened to them or on something good that they have done.\n

voca.title: congratulatory
voca.explains: A congratulatory message expresses congratulations.\n

voca.title: congratulatory performance
voca.explains: The award recipients give acceptance speeches. There are congratulatory performances by singers.\n

voca.title: congress
voca.means:
[^컨g뤠s]
(여러 단체의 대표들이 모이는) 회의
(미국 및 일부 다른 국가들의) 의회, 국회
의회, 국회, 회의, 집합, 회합
voca.explains: A congress is a large meeting that is held to discuss ideas and policies.\nCongress is the elected group of politicians that is responsible for making the law in the United States. It consists of two parts: the House of Representatives and the Senate.\n

voca.title: conjunction
voca.explains:
A conjunction of two or more things is the occurrence of them at the same time or place.
In grammar, a conjunction is a word or group of words that joins together words, groups, or clauses. In English, there are co-ordinating conjunctions such as 'and' and 'but', and subordinating conjunctions such as 'although', 'because', and 'when'.
If one thing is done or used in conjunction with another, the two things are done or used together.

voca.title: conjunctivitis
voca.explains: Conjunctivitis is an eye infection which causes the thin skin that covers the eye to become red.\nA while ago, I had conjunctivitis, better known as pink eye. I had blurred vision. My eyes turned bloodshot.\n

voca.title: conk
voca.explains:
to strike (someone) a blow, esp on the head or nose
a punch or blow, esp on the head or nose
the head or (esp Brit and NZ) the nose

voca.title: conk off
voca.explains: I can't conk off.\n

voca.title: conk out
voca.means: (기계 등이) 멈춰 서 버리다\n(사람이) 잠이 들다
voca.explains:
if a vehicle or a machine conks out, it stops working
if a person conks out, they fall asleep because they are very tired
to collapse or become unconscious
to die

voca.title: conk out completely
voca.explains:
It made a strange noise whenever I turned it on. Finally, it conked out completely. I called the service center for help.
I had to sweep the floor because the vacuum cleaner had conked out completely.
Very soon, it will conk out completely.
You should fix it before it conks out completely.
Did it conk out completely, or can it still be fixed?

voca.title: connect
voca.means:
[커^넥t]
잇다, 연결하다; 이어지다, 연결되다
(전원, 가스, 수도 등을) 연결/접속하다
~와 관련/연고이 있다
(사람, 사물, 사건들을 서로) 관련짓다, 관련성을 알아보다
(교통편이) 연결되다
(통화가 되도록 전화를) 연결하다
친해지다
voca.explains:
If something or someone connects one thing to another, or if one thing connects to another, the two things are joined together.
If a piece of equipment or a place is connected to a source of power or water, it is joined to that source so that it has power or water.
If a telephone operator connects you, he or she enables you to speak to another person by telephone.
If two things or places connect or if something connects them, they are joined and people or things can pass between them.
If one train or plane, for example, connects with another, it arrives at a time which allows passengers to change to the other one in order to continue their journey.
If you connect to a particular plane or train, or if another plane or train connects you to it, you change to that plane or train from another one in order to continue your journey.
If you connect a person or thing with something, you realize that there is a link or relationship between them.
Something that connects a person or thing with something else shows or provides a link or relationship between them.

voca.title: connection
voca.means:
[커^넥션]
(두 가지 사실, 생각 등의) 관련성, 연관성
연결, 접속,
(교통) 연결편, 운행 수단, 운행편
연줄이 닿는/있는 사람/기관
인척, 먼 친척
voca.explains:
A connection is a relationship between two things, people, or groups.
A connection is a joint where two wires or pipes are joined together.
If a place has good road, rail, or air connections, many places can be directly reached from there by car, train, or plane.
If you get a connection at a station or airport, you catch a train, bus, or plane, after getting off another train, bus, or plane, in order to continue your journey.
Your connections are the people who you know or are related to, especially when they are in a position to help you.
If you write or talk to someone in connection with something, you write or talk to them about that thing.

voca.title: connotation
voca.explains:
The connotations of a particular word or name are the ideas or qualities which it makes you think of.
It has a wholly different connotation.
Red has a connotation of warmth.
The use of the word "purpose" has wide connotations.

voca.title: conquest
voca.explains:
Conquest is the act of conquering a country or group of people.
Conquests are lands that have been conquered in war.
If someone makes a conquest, they succeed in attracting and usually sleeping with another person. You usually use conquest when you want to indicate that this relationship is not important to the person concerned.
You can refer to the person that someone has succeeded in attracting as their conquest.
The conquest of something such as a problem is success in ending it or dealing with it.

voca.title: conscious
voca.means:
[^컨셔s]
의식하는, 자각하는, 
의식적인, 의도적인, 
알고있는, 판단 기능이 정상인
특별한 관심이 있는
voca.explains:
If you are conscious of something, you notice it or realize that it is happening.
If you are conscious of something, you think about it a lot, especially because you are unhappy about it or because you think it is important.
A conscious decision or action is made or done deliberately with you giving your full attention to it.
Someone who is conscious is awake rather than asleep or unconscious.
Conscious memories or thoughts are ones that you are aware of.

voca.title: consciousness
voca.means:
[^컨셔s니s]
의식(지각, 판단 기능이 정상인 상태)
(무엇에 대한) 자각, 의식
(한 사람이나 단체의) 생각, 의식
voca.explains:
Your consciousness is your mind and your thoughts.
The consciousness of a group of people is their set of ideas, attitudes, and beliefs.
You use consciousness to refer to an interest in and knowledge of a particular subject or idea.
Consciousness is the state of being awake rather than being asleep or unconscious. If someone loses consciousness, they become unconscious, and if they regain consciousness, they become conscious after being unconscious.
The doctor suggested that I get an endoscopy. They put me under, I went through the process while I was asleep. After I regained consciousness, I received the test results.

voca.title: consecutive
voca.explains: Consecutive periods of time or events happen one after the other without interruption.\nShe was absent for nine consecutive days.\nThe water rate has not dropped for three consecutive months.

voca.title: consequence
voca.explains:
effect / result / consequence / outcome / repercussion
The consequences of something are the results or effects of it.
If one thing happens and then another thing happens in consequence or as a consequence, the second thing happens as a result of the first.
Something or someone of consequence is important or valuable. If something or someone is of no consequence, or of little consequence, they are not important or valuable.
If you tell someone that they must take the consequences or face the consequences, you warn them that something unpleasant will happen to them if they do not stop behaving in a particular way.

voca.title: conservative
voca.means: [컨^써r-버디v]\n보수적인, (실제 수나 양보다) 적게 잡은\n보수주의자, 보수적인 사람
voca.explains:
A Conservative politician or voter is a member of or votes for the Conservative Party in Britain.
Someone who is conservative has right-wing views.
Someone who is conservative or has conservative ideas is unwilling to accept changes and new ideas.
If someone dresses in a conservative way, their clothes are conventional in style.
A conservative estimate or guess is one in which you are cautious and estimate or guess a low amount which is probably less that the real amount.
That company is very conservative. They have a dress code that everyone must follow.
I am somewhere in between conservative and liberal.

voca.title: conserve
voca.means:
[컨^서r-v]
아끼다, 아껴쓰다, 
~을 보존하다, 보호하다, 절약하다
(과일을 통째로나 굵게 썰어 만든) 과일 설탕 조림
voca.explains:
If you conserve a supply of something, you use it carefully so that it lasts for a long time.
To conserve something means to protect it from harm, loss, or change.
Conserve is jam containing a large proportion of fruit, usually in whole pieces.

voca.title: consider
voca.explains:
regard / consider / see / view / perceive
If you consider a person or thing to be something, you have the opinion that this is what they are.
If you consider something, you think about it carefully.
If you are considering doing something, you intend to do it, but have not yet made a final decision whether to do it.
He accomplished what was considered unthinkable.
Her father thought for a moment. "As coach, I have to look beyond any one player's needs. I have to consider the whole team."

voca.title: consider something an honor
voca.explains:
Many people get up early on Election Day to vote. I consider it an honor to have a say in the voting process.
She considered it an honor to be invited.
You should consider it an honor to be here.

voca.title: considerable
voca.explains: Considerable means great in amount or degree.\n

voca.title: considerate
voca.explains: Someone who is considerate pays attention to the needs, wishes, or feelings of other people.\n

voca.title: consideration
voca.explains:
Consideration is careful thought about something.
If something is under consideration, it is being discussed.
If you show consideration, you pay attention to the needs, wishes, or feelings of other people.
A consideration is something that should be thought about, especially when you are planning or deciding something.
Lisa: Maybe I will. Thanks for your consideration.

voca.title: considered
voca.means: [컨씨더r-d]\n깊이 생각한 (후의)\n(부사 앞에 두어) 존경받는, 중히 여겨지는
voca.explains: A considered opinion or act is the result of careful thought.\n

voca.title: consist
voca.means:
[컨^씨st]
(부분, 요소로) 되어 있다, 이루어져 있다
(~에) 존재하다
(~와) 양립/일치하다, (사물이) 공존하다
voca.explains: Something that consists of particular things or people is formed from them.\nSomething that consists in something else has that thing as its main or only part.\n

voca.title: consist in something
voca.explains: to have something as the main or only feature\n

voca.title: consist of something
voca.explains: to be formed from the things or people mentioned\n

voca.title: consistent
voca.explains:
Someone who is consistent always behaves in the same way, has the same attitudes towards people or things, or achieves the same level of success in something.
If one fact or idea is consistent with another, they do not contradict each other.
An argument or set of ideas that is consistent is one in which no part contradicts or conflicts with any other part.

voca.title: console
voca.explains: If you console someone who is unhappy about something, you try to make them feel more cheerful.\nA console is a panel with a number of switches or knobs that is used to operate a machine.\n

voca.title: consonant
voca.explains: A consonant is a sound such as 'p', 'f', 'n', or 't' which you pronounce by stopping the air flowing freely through your mouth. Compare vowel.\n

voca.title: constant
voca.means:
[^칸s턴t]
정수, 상수, 항수
불변의, 변함없는, 끊임없는, 거듭되는
규칙적으로 되풀이되는
voca.explains:
You use constant to describe something that happens all the time or is always there.
If an amount or level is constant, it stays the same over a particular period of time.
A constant is a thing or value that always stays the same.
This job is a constant headache for me.

voca.title: constantly
voca.explains: My hand-eye coordination is not very good. I have butterfingers. I am constantly dropping things.\n

voca.title: constellation
voca.explains: A constellation is a group of stars which form a pattern and have a name.\nYou know how you draw a constellation?\n

voca.title: constitute
voca.means:
[컨s티튯t]
~이 되는 것으로 여겨지다, ~이 되다
~을 구성하다, 이루다
(어떤 단체를) 설립/설치 하다
voca.explains:
If something constitutes a particular thing, it can be regarded as being that thing.
If a number of things or people constitute something, they are the parts or members that form it.
When something such as a committee or government is constituted, it is formally established and given authority to operate.

voca.title: constitution
voca.explains: The constitution of a country or organization is the system of laws which formally states people's rights and duties.\nYour constitution is your health.\n

voca.title: constrain
voca.explains: To constrain someone or something means to limit their development or force them to behave in a particular way.\nIf you feel constrained to do something, you feel that you must do it, even though you would prefer not to.\n

voca.title: constrain oneself
voca.explains: She was so angry that she could hardly constrain herself.\n

voca.title: constraint
voca.explains:
limit / restriction / control / constraint / restraint / limitation
A constraint is something that limits or controls what you can do.
Constraint is control over the way you behave which prevents you from doing what you want to do.

voca.title: construct
voca.means:
[컨st^뤅t]
건설하다, 만들다, 세우다, 구성하다
(도형을) 그리다
(이런저런 증거들에 기반을 두고 마음속으로 구성한) 생각
건축물, 구성 계념
voca.explains:
build / construct / assemble / erect / set up / put up / put together
If you construct something such as a building, road, or machine, you build it or make it.
If you construct something such as an idea, a piece of writing, or a system, you create it by putting different parts together.

voca.title: construction
voca.means:
[컨s^t럭션]
(특히 도로, 빌딩, 교량 등의) 건설, 공사
건축 양식
건축물, 건축 구조물
(어구나 문장의) 구조
(사상, 이론 등의) 구성
voca.explains:
structure / framework / composition / construction / fabric / make-up
Construction is the building of things such as houses, factories, roads, and bridges.
The construction of something such as a vehicle or machine is the making of it.
The construction of something such as a system is the creation of it.
You can refer to an object that has been built or made as a construction.
You use construction to refer to the structure of something and the way it has been built or made.
A grammatical construction is a particular arrangement of words in a sentence, clause, or phrase.

voca.title: construction site
voca.explains: One summer, I worked at a construction site. It was my first time doing physical labor.\n

voca.title: consumable
voca.explains: Consumable goods are items which are intended to be bought, used, and then replaced.\n

voca.title: consume
voca.means:
[컨쑤-움]
(특히 연료, 에너지, 시간을) 소모하다
먹다, 마시다, 
(강렬한 감저이) 사로잡다/휩쓸리다
voca.explains:
If you consume something, you eat or drink it.
To consume an amount of fuel, energy, or time means to use it up.
If a feeling or idea consumes you, it affects you very strongly indeed.

voca.title: consumer
voca.explains: A consumer is a person who buys things or uses services.\n

voca.title: consumerism
voca.explains: Consumerism is the belief that it is good to buy and use a lot of goods.\nConsumerism is the protection of the rights and interests of consumers.\n

voca.title: consuming
voca.means: [컨^쑤밍]\n소비하는, 지치게 하는\n엄청나게 강렬한, 온 마음을 사로잡는
voca.explains: A consuming passion or interest is more important to you than anything else.\n

voca.title: contact
voca.means:
[^컨텍t]
(남과의 특히 정기적인) 연락, 접촉
(무엇에) 닿음, 접촉
접함, 관계, 연줄(이 닿는 사람)
전기 접촉/접속
(전화, 편지 등으로) 연락하다
voca.explains:
Contact involves meeting or communicating with someone, especially regularly.
If you come into contact with someone or something, you meet that person or thing in the course of your work or other activities.
When people or things are in contact, they are touching each other.
Radio contact is communication by means of radio.
A contact is someone you know in an organization or profession who helps you or gives you information.
If you are in contact with someone, you regularly meet them or communicate with them.
If you make contact with someone, you find out where they are and talk or write to them.
If you lose contact with someone who you have been friendly with, you no longer see them, speak to them, or write to them.

voca.title: contactable
voca.explains: able to be communicated with\n

voca.title: contagious
voca.means: [컨^테이져s]\n(접촉을 통해) 전염되는, 전염성의 \n(사람이 접촉성) 전염병에 걸린
voca.explains:
A disease that is contagious can be caught by touching people or things that are infected with it. Compare infectious.
A feeling or attitude that is contagious spreads quickly among a group of people.
D.W. turned back to Nadine. Sometimes her brother was more than a little strange. She shrugged, hoping it wasn’t contagious.

voca.title: contain
voca.means:
[큰^테인]
~이 들어있다, 함유되어 있다
(감정을) 억누르다/참다
(좋지 않은 일을) 방지하다, 억제하다
voca.explains:
If something such as a box, bag, room, or place contains things, those things are inside it.
If a substance contains something, that thing is a part of it.
If writing, speech, or film contains particular information, ideas, or images, it includes them.
If a group or organization contains a certain number of people, those are the people that are in it.
If you contain something, you control it and prevent it from spreading or increasing.
If you cannot contain a feeling such as excitement or anger, or if you cannot contain yourself, you cannot prevent yourself from showing your feelings.

voca.title: container
voca.explains: A container is something such as a box or bottle that is used to hold or store things in.\nA container is a very large metal or wooden box used for transporting goods so that they can be loaded easily onto ships and lorries.\n

voca.title: contemporary
voca.means: [컨^텐풔뤠어뤼]\n현대의, 동시대의, 최신의, 동년배의\n(어떤 사람과) 동년배, 동시대인
voca.explains:
Contemporary things are modern and relate to the present time.
Contemporary people or things were alive or happened at the same time as something else you are talking about.
Someone's contemporary is a person who is or was alive at the same time as them.

voca.title: content
voca.means:
[콘텐t]
(어떤 것의) 속에든 것들, 내용물, 
내용, 취지, 용량, 부피, 면적
만족하고 있는, 기꺼이~하는
voca.explains:
happy / satisfied / content / contented / joyful / blissful
The contents of a container such as a bottle, box, or room are the things that are inside it.
If you refer to the content or contents of something such as a book, speech, or television programme, you are referring to the subject that it deals with, the story that it tells, or the ideas that it expresses.
The contents of a book are its different chapters and sections, usually shown in a list at the beginning of the book.
The content of something such as an educational course or a programme of action is the elements that it consists of.
You can use content to refer to the amount or proportion of something that a substance contains.
If you are content with something, you are willing to accept it, rather than wanting something more or something better.
If you are content, you are fairly happy or satisfied.
If you content yourself with something, you accept it and do not try to do or have other things.

voca.title: contest

[컨^테st]
대회, 콘테스트, 논쟁
논쟁/경쟁하다,항의하다, 반대하다
(결정이나 진술에) 이의를 제기하다
voca.explains:
A contest is a competition or game in which people try to win.
A contest is a struggle to win power or control.
If someone contests an election or competition, they take part in it and try to win it.
If you contest a statement or decision, you object to it formally because you think it is wrong or unreasonable.
"I don't know what's so complicated." said D.W. She put out her hands as though she were balancing things in a scale. "Some creepy books here. Free WonderWorld here." She lowered her WonderWorld hand to her knees, as though it was holding something heavy. The other hand shot up. "No contest."

voca.title: context
voca.means: [^콘텍st]\n(어떤 일의) 맥락, 전후 사정,\n(글의) 문맥, 전후 관계, 배경, 상황
voca.explains:
The context of an idea or event is the general situation that relates to it, and which helps it to be understood.
The context of a word, sentence, or text consists of the words, sentences, or text before and after it which help to make its meaning clear.
If something is seen in context or if it is put into context, it is considered together with all the factors that relate to it.
the pieces of writing in a passage which surround a particular word or phrase and which contribute to the full meaning of the word.

voca.title: continent
voca.explains: A continent is a very large area of land, such as Africa or Asia, that consists of several countries.\nPeople sometimes use the Continent to refer to the continent of Europe except for Britain.\n

voca.title: continental
voca.means:
[^컨티넨틀]
(영국, 아일랜드를 포함하지 않는) 유럽 대륙의
북미 대룩의
대륙의
(유럽 대륙에 사는) 유럽인
voca.explains:
Continental means situated on or belonging to the continent of Europe except for Britain.
If you describe someone or something as continental, you think that they are typical of the continent of Europe.
Continental is used to refer to something that belongs to or relates to a continent.
The continental United States consists of all the states which are situated on the continent of North America, as opposed to Hawaii and territories such as the Virgin Islands.
Continental means existing or happening in the American colonies during the American Revolution.
A continental is someone who comes from the continent of Europe.
Continentals were soldiers who fought in the Continental Army against the British in the American Revolution.

분견대, 파견대
파견단, 선수단, 분담액, 배당액
조건으로 하는, 의존적인, 우발적인
(~의) 여부에 따라

A contingent of police, soldiers, or military vehicles is a group of them.
A contingent is a group of people representing a country or organization at a meeting or other event.
If something is contingent on something else, the first thing depends on the second in order to happen or exist.

voca.title: continuation
voca.means: [컨^틴뉴에이션]\n계속, 지속, 연속, \n(어떤 것에) 연속 되는 것
voca.explains: The continuation of something is the fact that it continues, rather than stopping.\nSomething that is a continuation of something else is closely connected with it or forms part of it.\n

voca.means:
[컨^틴유-]

(특정 직장이나 상태에) 계속 있다
(같은 방향으로) 계속 가다, 이어지다
(한동안 멈췄던 일을[이]) 계속하다, 재개하다
voca.explains:
If someone or something continues to do something, they keep doing it and do not stop.
If something continues or if you continue it, it does not stop happening.
If you continue with something, you start doing it again after a break or interruption.
If something continues or if you continue it, it starts again after a break or interruption.
If you continue, you begin speaking again after a pause or interruption.
If you continue as something or continue in a particular state, you remain in a particular job or state.
If you continue in a particular direction, you keep walking or travelling in that direction.

voca.title: continuous
voca.means:
[컨^티뉴어s]
계속되는, 지속적인
(선 같은 것이 끊어짐 없이) 계속 이어지는
(여러 번) 반복된, 거듭된
voca.explains:

A continuous line or surface has no gaps or holes in it.
In English grammar, continuous verb groups are formed using the auxiliary 'be' and the present participle of a verb, as in 'I'm feeling a bit tired' and 'She had been watching them for some time'. Continuous verb groups are used especially when you are focusing on a particular moment. Compare simple.

voca.title: contract
voca.means:
[^컨t뤡t]
계약, 계약서, 청부살인
계약을 맺다, 단축/축소 하다
줄어들다, 수축하다, 수축시키다, 
(병에) 걸리다
voca.explains:
A contract is a legal agreement, usually between two companies or between an employer and employee, which involves doing work for a stated sum of money.
If there is a contract on a person or on their life, someone has made an arrangement to have them killed.
If you contract with someone to do something, you legally agree to do it for them or for them to do it for you.
When something contracts or when something contracts it, it becomes smaller or shorter.
When something such as an economy or market contracts, it becomes smaller.
If you contract a serious illness, you become ill with it.
I'm going to sign a new contract tomorrow.

voca.title: contraction
voca.explains: When a woman who is about to give birth has contractions, she experiences a very strong, painful tightening of the muscles of her womb.\nA contraction is a shortened form of a word or words.\n

voca.title: contractor
voca.explains: A contractor is a person or company that does work for other people or organizations.\n

voca.title: contrast

[컨t^롸st]
(둘 이상의 사람, 사물을 비교했을때 나타나는 뚜렸한) 
차이, 대조, 대비, 현저한 차이
대조하다, 대조를 이루다, (뚜렷한) 대조를 보이다
(텔레비전 화면의) 명암
voca.explains:
A contrast is a great difference between two or more things which is clear when you compare them.
If one thing is a contrast to another, it is very different from it.
Contrast is the degree of difference between the darker and lighter parts of a photograph, television picture, or painting.

voca.title: contribute
voca.explains:
If you contribute to something, you say or do things to help to make it successful.
To contribute money or resources to something means to give money or resources to help pay for something or to help achieve a particular purpose.
If something contributes to an event or situation, it is one of the causes of it.
If you contribute to a magazine, newspaper, or book, you write things that are published in it.
My father prefers home-cooked meals. Instead of booking a restaurant, we had a potluck dinner. Everyone contributed their signature dish.

voca.title: contribute to
voca.explains: to help to cause something\n

voca.title: contribution
voca.means:
[^컨트뤄뷰션]
기부금, 성금, 기부, 기증
(의료 보혐, 연금 등의) 개인 분담금
기여, 기바지, 원인제공
voca.explains:
If you make a contribution to something, you do something to help make it successful or to produce it.
A contribution is a sum of money that you give in order to help pay for something.
A contribution to a magazine, newspaper, or book is something that you write to be published in it.
"Nonsense." said Mr. Read. "I'm sure you're making a positive contribution. There are probably people talking about it even now."

voca.title: control
voca.explains:
limit / restriction / control / constraint / restraint / limitation
Control of an organization, place, or system is the power to make all the important decisions about the way that it is run.
If you have control of something or someone, you are able to make them do what you want them to do.
If you show control, you prevent yourself behaving in an angry or emotional way.
The people who control an organization or place have the power to take all the important decisions about the way that it is run.
To control a piece of equipment, process, or system means to make it work in the way that you want it to work.

voca.title: controversial
voca.explains: If you describe something or someone as controversial, you mean that they are the subject of intense public argument, disagreement, or disapproval.\n

voca.title: controversial remark
voca.means: 논란의 여지가 있는 말\n물의를 빚는 말

voca.title: convenience
voca.explains:
If something is done for your convenience, it is done in a way that is useful or suitable for you.
If you describe something as a convenience, you mean that it is very useful.
Conveniences are pieces of equipment designed to make your life easier.
A public convenience is a building containing toilets which is provided in a public place for anyone to use.

voca.title: convenience store
voca.explains: A convenience store is a shop which sells mainly food and which is usually open until late at night.\nConvenience stores in Korea are a good place to grab a bite. They have everything you could ask for.\n

voca.title: convenient
voca.explains:
If a way of doing something is convenient, it is easy, or very useful or suitable for a particular purpose.
If you describe a place as convenient, you are pleased because it is near to where you are, or because you can reach another place from there quickly and easily.
A convenient time to do something, for example to meet someone, is a time when you are free to do it or would like to do it.
If you describe someone's attitudes or actions as convenient, you think they are only adopting those attitudes or performing those actions in order to avoid something difficult or unpleasant.
In Korea, there is a very convenient service for drivers who have been drinking. People can request a designated driver for a fee. It's a great way to avoid driving under the influence.

voca.title: convention
voca.means:
[큰^벤션]
관습, 관례, 
(전문직 종사자 들이나 정당의 대규모)집회, 대회, 회의,
(문학, 예술의) 전통/관습 (적인 방법)
협약, 관습, 컨벤션
voca.explains:
A convention is a way of behaving that is considered to be correct or polite by most people in a society.
In art, literature, or the theatre, a convention is a traditional method or style.
A convention is an official agreement between countries or groups of people.
A convention is a large meeting of an organization or political group.

voca.title: conversation
voca.explains:
discussion / conversation / dialogue / talk / consultation / chat / gossip
If you have a conversation with someone, you talk with them, usually in an informal situation.
If you say that people are in conversation, you mean that they are talking together.
If you make conversation, you talk to someone in order to be polite and not because you really want to.

voca.title: converse
voca.explains: If you converse with someone, you talk to them. You can also say that two people converse.\nThe converse of a statement is its opposite or reverse.\n

voca.title: conversion
voca.explains: Conversion is the act or process of changing something into a different state or form.\nIf someone changes their religion or beliefs, you can refer to their conversion to their new religion or beliefs.\n

voca.title: convert
voca.means:
[컨^버r-t]
(형태, 목적, 시스템 등을) 전환시키다, 개조하다
개종하다; 전향하다
(의견, 습관 등을) 바꾸다
전향자, 개종자
voca.explains:
If one thing is converted or converts into another, it is changed into a different form.
If someone converts a room or building, they alter it in order to use it for a different purpose.
If you convert a vehicle or piece of equipment, you change it so that it can use a different fuel.
If you convert a quantity from one system of measurement to another, you calculate what the quantity is in the second system.
If someone converts you, they persuade you to change your religious or political beliefs. You can also say that someone converts to a different religion.
If someone converts you to something, they make you very enthusiastic about it.
A convert is someone who has changed their religious or political beliefs.
If you describe someone as a convert to something, you mean that they have recently become very enthusiastic about it.

voca.title: convince
voca.explains:
persuade / convince
If someone or something convinces you of something, they make you believe that it is true or that it exists.
If someone or something convinces you to do something, they persuade you to do it.
There's still a few I have to convince.
She was not convinced. "What was in that mysterious envelope?"

voca.title: convinced
voca.explains: sure / confident / convinced / certain / positive\nIf you are convinced that something is true, you feel sure that it is true.\n

voca.title: cook
voca.explains:
When you cook a meal, you prepare food for eating by heating it.
When you cook food, or when food cooks, it is heated until it is ready to be eaten.
A cook is a person whose job is to prepare and cook food, especially in someone's home or in an institution.
If you say that someone is a good cook, you mean they are good at preparing and cooking food.
If you say that someone has cooked the books, you mean that they have changed figures or a written record in order to deceive people.
"But no cooks or servants," said Annie.

voca.title: cook something from scratch
voca.explains:
We were too busy to cook everyting from scratch.
My mother usually cooks dinner from scratch.
Eating instant food is easier than cooking something from scratch.

voca.title: cook something up
voca.explains: to cook something, especially very quickly\nto invent a story, an excuse or a plan, especially a very clever or dishonest one\n

voca.title: cookbook
voca.explains: A cookbook is a book that contains recipes for preparing food.\n

voca.title: cookout
voca.explains: A cookout is the same as a barbecue.\n

voca.title: cool
voca.means:
[^쿠울]
식다, 차게하다
서늘한 곳, 냉정, 침착
서늘한, 냉정한
멋지다, 끝내주다,
voca.explains:
cold l cool / freezing / chilly / lukewarm / tepid
Something that is cool has a temperature which is low but not very low.
If it is cool, or if a place is cool, the temperature of the air is low but not very low.
Clothing that is cool is made of thin material so that you do not become too hot in hot weather.
Cool colours are light colours which give an impression of coolness.

voca.title: cornfield

Going to college should not cost a fortune.

I received my cup and took a sip. However, it wasn’t green tea, but coffee. I made a complaint at the counter. The barista was courteous and helpful. He apologized for the inconvenience, and gave me a new drink, free of charge.
