voca.explains: His father made a face. "For a moment I thought my life was over. The teacher was covered in goop. He shook his fist at me, and goop dropped off his hand onto the floor."\n

voca.title: cover something up
voca.means: ~을 완전히 덮다, 가리다\n(범행, 실수 등을) 숨기다, 은폐하다
voca.explains: to put something over somebody/something in order to hide or protect them/it\n

voca.title: cover up
voca.explains: to try hard to stop people finding out about a mistake, a crime, etc.; to hide the truth about something\nto put on more clothes\n

voca.title: cow
voca.means:
[^카우]
소, 젖소, 암소
(코끼리, 고래, 그 외 일부 동물의) 암컷
겁을 주다
voca.explains:
A cow is a large female animal that is kept on farms for its milk. People sometimes refer to male and female animals of this species as cows.
Some female animals, including elephants and whales, are called cows.
If someone describes a woman as a cow, they dislike her and think that she is unpleasant or stupid.
If someone is cowed, they are made afraid, or made to behave in a particular way because they have been frightened or badly treated.

voca.title: coward
voca.explains: If you call someone a coward, you disapprove of them because they are easily frightened and avoid dangerous or difficult situations.\n

voca.title: cowherd
voca.explains: a person employed to tend cattle\n

voca.title: co-worker
voca.explains:
Your co-workers are the people you work with, especially people on the same job or project as you.
At my office, often we are strapped for time. When that happens, my co-workers and I order in lunch.
My family recently moved into a new house. To celebrate the occasion, we invited some friends and co-workers to a housewarming party.

voca.title: coyote
voca.explains: A coyote is a small wolf which lives in the plains of North America.\n

voca.title: cozy
voca.explains:
A house or room that is cosy is comfortable and warm.
If you are cosy, you are comfortable and warm.
You use cosy to describe activities that are pleasant and friendly, and involve people who know each other well.
It's not very cozy today. / I felt cozy sitting by the fire.
This one looked cozy and safe and worm.

voca.title: cozy atmosphere
voca.explains:
There are even tent bars on the street called pojangmacha. I love their cozy atmosphere and affordable prices.
The hotel room had a cozy atmosphere.
The hospital tried to create a cozy atmosphere for the patients.

voca.title: cozy up to somebody
voca.means: (특히 자기에게 쓸모가 있을 것 같은 사람에게)\n친하게 굴다
voca.explains: to try to become friendly with somebody, especially in order to gain an advantage for yourself\n

voca.title: crab
voca.explains: A crab is a sea creature with a flat round body covered by a shell, and five pairs of legs with large claws on the front pair. Crabs usually move sideways.\n

voca.title: crack
voca.means:
[k^뤡k]
갈라지다, 금이가다, 깨지다
(짧고 세게) 때리다, 찧다
갈라지는 소리가 나다
(목소리가) 갈라지다, 잠기다
(압박을 받아) 제 기능을 못하다, 무너지다
날카로운 소리, 균열, 금, 결함
voca.explains:
If something hard cracks, or if you crack it, it becomes slightly damaged, with lines appearing on its surface.
If something cracks, or if you crack it, it makes a sharp sound like the sound of a piece of wood breaking.
If you crack a hard part of your body, such as your knee or your head, you hurt it by accidentally hitting it hard against something.
When you crack something that has a shell, such as an egg or a nut, you break the shell in order to reach the inside part.
If you crack a problem or a code, you solve it, especially after a lot of thought.
If someone cracks, they lose control of their emotions or actions because they are under a lot of pressure.
If your voice cracks when you are speaking or singing, it changes in pitch because you are feeling a strong emotion.
If you crack a joke, you tell it.
Then she and Jack squeezed through the narrow crack and strode through the bright crystal cave.
"At the crack of the bat, the ball is headed your way. Everyone is staring, watching your every move."

voca.title: crack down
voca.explains: to try harder to prevent people breaking a rule, using something harmful, committing a crime, etc. and deal severely with those who do\n

voca.title: crack down on
voca.means:
~에 단호한 조취를 취하다, 
~을 엄중 단속하다, 탄압하다
~을 통렬하게 비난하다
~에 대한 단속을 강화하다
voca.explains:
The authorities should crack down on people who litter. They should impose steep fines. Prevention is even more important than punishment. A sense of civic pride is key. It’s something we should teach our kids from an early age.
The police started to crack down on drunk driving.
The teachers are creacking down on student smoking.

voca.title: crack of dawn
voca.explains:
The worst was when I got a cramp in my sleep. I was fast asleep when I felt a stitch in my side. I woke up with a start. It took a long time for my muscles to loosen up. I didn’t doze off again until the crack of dawn.
My family recently moved into a new house. To celebrate the occasion, we invited some friends and co-workers to a housewarming party. The preparations took all day. We woke up at the crack of dawn to get ready.
He was ready to go at the crack of dawn.
Not many people were awake at the crack of dawn.

voca.title: crack someone up
voca.explains:
My friend and I both really enjoyed the movie. It was touching, but it was also very funny. Some scenes really cracked me up.
I like him because he always cracks me up.
I heard a joke that will crack you up.

voca.title: crack the whip
voca.explains: use your authority or power to make somebody work very hard, usually by treating them in a strict way\n

voca.title: crack up
voca.means: (중압감을 못 이기고 정신적으로나 육체적으로) \n무너지다/쓰러지다\n마구 웃기 시작하다
voca.explains:
to start laughing a lot; to make somebody laugh a lot
to become physically or mentally ill because you are under pressure
"Hello, Mr. Toad," said Judy. She cracked herself up.
I enjoy watching video clips on the Internet. I feel like I’ve seen it all. Recently, I saw a real knee-slapper. It was a short clip of a comedy program. It made me crack up.
I cracked her up with a joke.
He's attracted to people who can make him crack up.

voca.title: crackle
voca.means: [k^뤠끌]\n(불꽃 등이) 탁탁 소리를 내다\n~ 을 탁탁 소리나게 하다
voca.explains:
If something crackles, it makes a rapid series of short, harsh noises.
He heard a crackling sound.
The autumn leaves crunched and crackled under their leather shoes.

voca.title: cradle
voca.explains:
A cradle is a baby's bed with high sides. Cradles often have curved bases so that they rock from side to side.
The cradle is the part of a telephone on which the receiver rests while it is not being used.
A cradle is a frame which supports or protects something.
A place that is referred to as the cradle of something is the place where it began.
If you cradle someone or something in your arms or hands, you hold them carefully and gently.
If something affects you from the cradle to the grave, it affects you throughout your life.

voca.title: craft
voca.means:
[k^뤠-ft]
기능, 기술, 공예, 솜씨, 
술책, 술수
작은 배, 비행기, 우주선
(특히 손으로) 공예품을 만들다, 공들여 만들다
voca.explains:
You can refer to a boat, a spacecraft, or an aircraft as a craft.
A craft is an activity such as weaving, carving, or pottery that involves making things skilfully with your hands.
You can use craft to refer to any activity or job that involves doing something skilfully.
If something is crafted, it is made skilfully.

voca.title: craggy
voca.explains:
A craggy cliff or mountain is steep and rocky.
A craggy face has large features and deep lines.
When they came close to the craggy mountains, Jack was sure the stag would stop.
In the distance, a craggy mountain rose into the moonlit sky.

voca.title: crake
voca.explains: any of several rails that occur in the Old World, such as the corncrake and the spotted crake\n

voca.title: cram
voca.means:
[k^뤰]
(좁은 공간에 억지로) 밀어넣다, 쑤셔 넣다, 
(좁은 공간으로) 잔뜩 들어가다,
게걸스럽게 먹다
단기간의 집중(벼락치기) 시험 공부
voca.explains:
If you cram things or people into a container or place, you put them into it, although there is hardly enough room for them.
If people cram into a place or vehicle or cram a place or vehicle, so many of them enter it at one time that it is completely full.
If you are cramming for an examination, you are learning as much as possible in a short time just before you take the examination.

voca.title: cram into
voca.explains: to go into a place or space that is too small for everyone/everything; to push or force somebody/something into a place or space that is too small\n

voca.title: cram school
voca.explains: I also had to do a lot of test prep for the Korean SAT. I gave my all the get ready. I paid attention in class. I also went to cram schools after classes and got private tutoring.\n

voca.title: crammed
voca.means:
[k^뤰-d]
가득 찬, 꽉 찬
(~이/으로) 잔뜩 들어 있는, 가득 찬
(사람들이) 비좁게 있는
voca.explains: If a place is crammed with things or people, it is full of them, so that there is hardly room for anything or anyone else.\nIf people or things are crammed into a place or vehicle, it is full of them.\n

voca.title: cramp
voca.means:
[k^뤰p]
(근육에 생기는) 경련, 쥐
위경련
(무엇의 발달이나 진행을) 막다, 방해하다
voca.explains:
Cramp is a sudden strong pain caused by a muscle suddenly contracting. You sometimes get cramp in a muscle after you have been making a physical effort over a long period of time.
If someone or something cramps your style, their presence or existence restricts your behaviour in some way.
They have to warm up before they go into the water. If not, they can get cramps or even a heart attack.

voca.title: cramp up
voca.explains: I recently went for a run at the park. As I was jogging, my leg seized up. I keeled over. I massaged my leg, but it cramped up again and again.\nHe had to withdraw because his leg kept cramping up.\n

voca.title: cramped
voca.means:
[k^뤰-t]
(방 등이) 비좁은
비좁게/답답하게 있는
(글씨가) 작고 갑갑한, 알아보기 힘든
voca.explains: A cramped room or building is not big enough for the people or things in it.\nI even drive a small car to make parking less of a chore. It’s easier to navigate through cramped parking lots. Still, finding room to park is so difficult that I wonder if it’s worth the trouble.\n

voca.title: crane
voca.means:
[^k뤠인]
기중기, 크레인
학, 두루미
(무엇을 더 잘 보려고 몸이나 목을) 길게 빼다
voca.explains:
A crane is a large machine that moves heavy things by lifting them in the air.
A crane is a kind of large bird with a long neck and long legs.
If you crane your neck or head, you stretch your neck in a particular direction in order to see or hear something better.

voca.title: crank
voca.means:
[k^뤵k]
(기계의) 크랭크
(못마땅함) 괴짜, 화 짜증을 잘 내는 사람
크랭크로 돌리다/돌다
voca.explains:
If you call someone a crank, you think their ideas or behaviour are strange.
A crank is a device that you turn in order to make something move.
If you crank an engine or machine, you make it move or function, especially by turning a handle.

voca.title: cranny
voca.means: [k^뤠니-]\n(특히 벽에 난 아주 작은) 구멍, 틈
voca.explains: Crannies are very narrow openings or spaces in something.\nRegardless, I was fully moved in and squared away in just half a day. I made sure to clean every nook and cranny of my new home. Now that I’m all settled in, I’m going all out with furnishing my new place.\n

voca.title: crap
voca.means:
[k뢥]
허튼소리, 헛소리,
쓰레기 같은 것, 개 같은 수작
똥, 똥누기
voca.explains:
If you describe something as crap, you think that it is wrong or of very poor quality.
Crap is sometimes used to refer to faeces.
Craps or crap is a gambling game, played mainly in North America, in which you throw two dice and bet what the total will be.
To crap means to get rid of faeces from your body.

voca.title: crap about
voca.means: 바보같은 짓을 하다\n농땡이 부리다\n(시시한 일에) 구애되다

voca.title: crappy
voca.explains: If you describe something as crappy, you think it is of very poor quality. Many people consider this word offensive.\n

voca.title: crash
voca.means:
[k뤠쉬]
(자동차, 충돌, 항공기 추락) 사고, 
(무엇이 떨어지거나 부서질 때 나는) 요란한 소리, 굉음
충돌하다, 추락하다, 붕괴하다
충돌, 추락, 불시착
voca.explains:
crash / slam / collide / smash / wreck
A crash is an accident in which a moving vehicle hits something and is damaged or destroyed.
A crash is a sudden, loud noise.
If a moving vehicle crashes or if the driver crashes it, it hits something and is damaged or destroyed.
If something crashes somewhere, it moves and hits something else violently, making a loud noise.
If a business or financial system crashes, it fails suddenly, often with serious effects.
If a computer or a computer program crashes, it fails suddenly.

voca.title: crash out
voca.explains: to go to sleep because you are very tired\n

voca.title: crate
voca.means:
[k^뤠잇t]
(물품 운송용 대형 나무) 상자, 
한 상자 (분량)
(운송용 대형) 상자에 담다
voca.explains:
A crate is a large box used for transporting or storing things.
A crate is a plastic or wire box divided into sections which is used for carrying bottles.
If something is crated, it is packed in a crate so that it can be transported or stored somewhere safely.
He motioned to his partner, who dropped a huge crate of boxes onto the Reads’ driveway.

voca.title: crater
voca.explains: The land was filled with giant craters and tall mountains.\nOver time, their craters rose above the water.\n

voca.title: crave
voca.explains: If you crave something, you want to have it very much.\nKoreans crave breaking news. News is on the internet before any other medium. Therefore, people who read the news on their smartphones can stay ahead of the curve.\n

voca.title: crawl
voca.means:
[k로울]
(엎드려) 기다, (곤충이) 기어가다, 
오싹해지다, 느릿느릿 다리다
기어가기,  서행, (수영의) 크롤
voca.explains:
When you crawl, you move forward on your hands and knees.
When an insect crawls somewhere, it moves there quite slowly.
If someone or something crawls somewhere, they move or progress slowly or with great difficulty.
If you say that a place is crawling with people or animals, you are emphasizing that it is full of them.
The crawl is a kind of swimming stroke which you do lying on your front, swinging one arm over your head, and then the other arm.
The four real keepers of the cauldron crawled closer to Jack and Annie, hissing and snorting blue fire.

voca.title: crawl out
voca.explains: She must have crawled out when we were looking at the paintings.\nA giant, slimy, mud-colored creature crawled out throught on of the doorways.\n

voca.title: crazy
voca.means:
[^k레이지]
미친듯한, 
(말이나 행동이) 정상이 아닌, 말도안되는
미친 듯이 화가 난
~을 대단히 좋아하는
미치광이
voca.explains:
mad / crazy / nuts / batty / out of your mind / (not) in your right mind
If you describe someone or something as crazy, you think they are very foolish or strange.
Someone who is crazy is insane.
If you are crazy about something, you are very enthusiastic about it. If you are not crazy about something, you do not like it.
If you are crazy about someone, you are deeply in love with them.
If something or someone makes you crazy or drives you crazy, they make you extremely annoyed or upset.
You use like crazy to emphasize that something happens to a great degree.

voca.title: creak
voca.explains:
If something creaks, it makes a short, high-pitched sound when it moves.
Slowly the doors creaked open.
"Look! The doors are opening." They all turned to watch. The library doors creaked open slowly.

voca.title: creaky
voca.explains:
A creaky object creaks when it moves.
If you describe something as creaky, you think it is bad in some way because it is old or old-fashioned.
The fog parted up ahead, revealing a creaky bridge. It was strung with rope and wooden planks. The planks were painted white and black-like the keys of a piano. They swayed in the wind.

voca.title: create
voca.means:
[k뤼에잇t]
창조하다, 창작하다, 만들어내다
(어떤 느낌이나 인상을) 자아내다, 불러일으키다
(계급이나 작위를) 수여하다
voca.explains:
make / create / develop / produce / generate / form
To create something means to cause it to happen or exist.
When someone creates a new product or process, they invent it or design it.

voca.title: create a sensation
voca.means: 선풍을 일으키다, 큰 인기를 끌다\n큰 이야깃거리가 되다, 센세이션을 일으키다.
voca.explains:
Korean movies have created a sensation in the world of cinema. Critics and audiences gush over the latest Korean films. Glowing reviews of Korean movies come from all corners of the world.
This song is going to create a sensation.
The big news created a sensation.

voca.title: creation
voca.means:
[^k뤼에이션]
창조, 창작, 창출, 창작품
(성서에 묘사된 하나님의) 천지창조
온 세상, 생물, 우주만물
voca.explains:
In many religions, creation is the making of the universe, earth, and creatures by God.
People sometimes refer to the whole universe as creation.
You can refer to something that someone has made as a creation, especially if it shows skill, imagination, or artistic ability.
Mr. Read stood in front of the kitchen stove, bringing his latest creation to life. The steam from the pot swirled up toward the frosted window.

voca.title: creative
voca.explains:
A creative person has the ability to invent and develop original ideas, especially in the arts.
Creative activities involve the inventing and making of new kinds of things.
If you use something in a creative way, you use it in a new way that produces interesting and unusual results.
"Recharge your creative batteries. Clear your head. Why don't you go make a snowman?"

voca.title: creature
voca.explains:
You can refer to any living thing that is not a plant as a creature, especially when it is of an unknown or unfamiliar kind. People also refer to imaginary animals and beings as creatures.
If you say that someone is a particular type of creature, you are focusing on a particular quality they have.
A giant, slimy, mud-colored creature crawled out throught on of the doorways.
"He's a terrifying creature who comes from the Otherwordl," said Teddy.
Instead, perched on the ledge of the nursery window was a horrifying creature.

voca.title: creature of habit
voca.explains: a person who always does certain things at certain times\nMy grandfather is a creature of habit. He vacations in the same place every year.\n

voca.title: credentials
voca.explains: Someone's credentials are their previous achievements, training, and general background, which indicate that they are qualified to do something.\nSomeone's credentials are a letter or certificate that proves their identity or qualifications.\n

voca.title: credibility
voca.explains: If someone or something has credibility, people believe in them and trust them.\n

voca.title: credit
voca.means:
[k^뤠딧t]
신용, 신용거래, (계좌) 잔고, 공제액
명성, 학점
~을 믿다, 인정하다, ~을 ~으로 여기다
voca.explains:
If you are allowed credit, you are allowed to pay for goods or services several weeks or months after you have received them.
If someone or their bank account is in credit, their bank account has money in it.
A credit is a sum of money which is added to an account.
A credit is an amount of money that is given to someone.
If you get the credit for something good, people praise you because you are responsible for it, or are thought to be responsible for it.
When a sum of money is credited to an account, the bank adds that sum of money to the total in the account.
If people credit someone with an achievement or if it is credited to them, people say or believe that they were responsible for it.

voca.title: credit card bill
voca.explains: At the end of the month, I received my credit card bill. I couldn’t muster up the money to pay it. I fell behind in payment.\n

voca.title: credit to
voca.explains: Assistant: We will credit it to your credit card account.\n

voca.title: creditable
voca.explains: A creditable performance or achievement is of a reasonably high standard.\nIf you describe someone's actions or aims as creditable, you mean that they are morally good.\n

voca.title: creek
voca.explains:
A creek is a narrow place where the sea comes a long way into the land.
A creek is a small stream or river.
If someone is up the creek, they are in a bad or difficult situation, or are wrong in some way. You can also say that someone is up the creek without a paddle.

voca.title: creep
voca.means: [k륍]\n기어가다, 서행하다, 살금살금 움직이다\n네발로 기기, 서행, 몰래 다가가기
voca.explains:
creep - crept - crept
When people or animals creep somewhere, they move quietly and slowly.
If something creeps somewhere, it moves very slowly.
If you describe someone as a creep, you mean that you dislike them a great deal, especially because they are insincere and flatter people.
They crept between the huge trees and past hanging vines.
She was creeping over the dead leaves - right toward Annie.
Jank and Annie crept to the cave and peeked inside.
The sabertooth crept forward.
Then he crept down the stairs

voca.title: creep in
voca.explains: to start happening or affecting somebody/something gradually\n

voca.title: creep on all fours
voca.explains: He began creeping on all fours forward the buffalo.\n

voca.title: creep out
voca.explains: to make somebody feel frightened and not safe\n

voca.title: creep over
voca.means: ~에 살금살금 다가가다,\n~위에 얽혀 퍼지다\n(공포 따위가) ~을 엄습하다
voca.explains:
if a feeling creeps over you, or an expression creeps over your face, it gradually affects you
A feeling of dread crept over Jack.
A bitter chill crept over the room.

voca.title: creep up
voca.explains: if a price, an amount, etc. creeps up, it rises very gradually\nto move nearer to somebody/something slowly and quietly without being seen or heard\n

voca.title: creepy
voca.explains:
If you say that something or someone is creepy, you mean they make you feel very nervous or frightened.
"It feels creepy to be invisible," she said.
"I don't know what's so complicated." said D.W. She put out her hands as though she were balancing things in a scale. "Some creepy books here. Free WonderWorld here." She lowered her WonderWorld hand to her knees, as though it was holding something heavy. The other hand shot up. "No contest."

voca.title: crept
voca.explains: Crept is the past tense and past participle of creep.\n

voca.title: crescent
voca.means: [^k뤠센t]\n초승달 모양\n크레센트 (집이 죽 늘어서 있는 초승달 모양의 거리)
voca.explains:
A crescent is a curved shape that is wider in the middle than at its ends, like the shape of the moon during its first and last quarters. It is the most important symbol of the Islamic faith.
Crescent is sometimes used as part of the name of a street or row of houses that is usually built in a curve.
His partly eaten hamburger sat on the edge of his plate like a crescent moon.

voca.title: crest
voca.means:
[k뤠st]
산마루, 물마루
(닭) 벼슬, 관모, (말 등의) 목덜미, 갈기
(특히 오랜 역사를 지닌 가문, 조직 등을 상징하는) 문장
~에 깃장식을 달다
꼭데기/정상에 이르다, 최고조에 이르다
voca.explains:
The crest of a hill or a wave is the top of it.
A bird's crest is a group of upright feathers on the top of its head.
A crest is a design that is the symbol of a noble family, a town, or an organization.

voca.title: cretaceous
voca.explains: of, denoting, or formed in the last period of the Mesozoic era, between the Jurassic and Tertiary periods, lasting 80 million years during which chalk deposits were formed and flowering plants first appeared\nthe Cretaceous the Cretaceous period or rock system\n

voca.title: crew
voca.explains:
The crew of a ship, an aircraft, or a spacecraft is the people who work on and operate it.
A crew is a group of people with special technical skills who work together on a task or project.
You can use crew to refer to a group of people you disapprove of.
If you crew a boat, you work on it as part of the crew.

voca.title: crib
voca.means:
[k^륍b]
유아용, 침대, 
구유, 여물통
(흔히 시험 때 이용하는) 커닝 쪽지
거처, 집
(다른 학생 과제나 책을 보고 몰래) 베끼다
voca.explains: A crib is a bed for a small baby.\n

voca.title: cricket
voca.means: [k^릐낏]\n귀뚜라미\n크리켓(영국과 영연방 국가들에서 주로 하며, 11명으로 이뤄진 두 팀이 벌이는 야구 비슷한 경기)
voca.explains:
Cricket is an outdoor game played between two teams. Players try to score points, called runs, by hitting a ball with a wooden bat.
A cricket is a small jumping insect that produces short, loud sounds by rubbing its wings together.
Crickets chirped loudly.

voca.title: crickets chirp
voca.explains: He could hear Miss Tingley typing in the next room. The clicking on the keyboard made Arthur think of crickets chirping. At least crickets were free to do what they wanted. They didn’t have to worry about quarters or picnics or unexpected mysteries.\n

voca.title: crime
voca.explains: A crime is an illegal action or activity for which a person can be punished by law.\nIf you say that doing something is a crime, you think it is very wrong or a serious mistake.\n

voca.title: cringe
voca.explains: If you cringe at something, you feel embarrassed or disgusted, and perhaps show this feeling in your expression or by making a slight movement.\n

voca.title: crisis
voca.means: [k롸이씨s]\n위기, 문제, 사태, 혼란, 불황\n최악의 고비, 중대 기로
voca.explains: A crisis is a situation in which something or someone is affected by one or more very serious problems.\n

voca.title: crisp
voca.explains:
Food that is crisp is pleasantly hard, or has a pleasantly hard surface.
Weather that is pleasantly fresh, cold, and dry can be described as crisp.
Crisp cloth or paper is clean and has no creases in it.
If food crisps or if you crisp it, it becomes pleasantly hard, for example because you have heated it at a high temperature.
Crisps are very thin slices of fried potato that are eaten cold as a snack.
The air felt crisp and cool.

voca.title: criterion
voca.explains: A criterion is a factor on which you judge or decide something.\n

voca.title: critic
voca.means:
[k^뤼딕]
비평가, 비판가, 
(무엇의 나쁜 점을, 특히 공적으로) 비판하는 사람
타인의 결정을 들추는 사람
voca.explains: A critic is a person who writes about and expresses opinions about things such as books, films, music, or art.\nSomeone who is a critic of a person or system disapproves of them and criticizes them publicly.\n

voca.title: critical
voca.means:
[^k뤼디컬]
(안 좋은 점을 들어 말하는) 비판적인, 비난하는
대단히 중요한, 중대한
위태로운,
비판적인, 비평하는
voca.explains:
essential / vital / crucial / critical / decisive / indispensable
A critical time, factor, or situation is extremely important.
A critical situation is very serious and dangerous.
If a person is critical or in a critical condition in hospital, they are seriously ill.
To be critical of someone or something means to criticize them.
A critical approach to something involves examining and judging it carefully.
If something or someone receives critical acclaim, critics say that they are very good.

voca.title: critical component
voca.explains: I called the service center for help. They sent over a repairman. He looked at the washer and took it apart. He said that a critical component for the motor had broken.\n

voca.title: critical error
voca.explains: My computer had given up the ghost. I took it to a service center. The technician there ran some diagnostics. He said that the culprit was a critical error in the hard drive.\n

voca.title: criticism
voca.explains:
Criticism is the action of expressing disapproval of something or someone. A criticism is a statement that expresses disapproval.
Criticism is a serious examination and judgment of something such as a book or play.
"Congratulations. Would that be Assistant Coach in Charge of Criticism?"

voca.title: criticize
voca.explains: If you criticize someone or something, you express your disapproval of them by saying what you think is wrong with them.\n

voca.title: croak
voca.means:
[k로욱k]
(개구리나 까마귀가) 개골개골/깍깍 하다
(낮고 거친 목소리로) 꺽꺽거리듯 말하다
개골개골, 깍깍(하는 소리)
voca.explains:
When a frog or bird croaks, it makes a harsh, low sound.
If someone croaks something, they say it in a low, rough voice.
"ROK," the raven croaked.
He fluffed out his feathers and croaked, Wait, you guys!

voca.title: crocodile
voca.means:
[k^뤄커다일]
악어 (아프리카산)
악어가죽
(특히 어린이들이 짝을 지어 걸어가는) 긴 행렬
voca.explains: A crocodile is a large reptile with a long body and strong jaws. Crocodiles live in rivers and eat meat.\n

voca.title: Cro-Magnon
voca.explains: Cro-Magnons scraped reindeer skins with flint rocks to make them soft.\n

voca.title: crook
voca.explains:
A crook is a dishonest person or a criminal.
The crook of your arm or leg is the soft inside part where you bend your elbow or knee.
A crook is a long pole with a large hook at the end. A crook is carried by a bishop in religious ceremonies, or by a shepherd.
If you crook your arm or finger, you bend it.
If someone says they will do something by hook or by crook, they are determined to do it, even if they have to make a great effort or use dishonest means.

voca.title: crop
voca.means:
[k뢉p]
잘라내다, 수확하다, 경작하다
농작물, 수확, 곡물
(승마때 쓰는) 채찍
머리를 아주 짧게 깍다, 
(사진이나 그림의 일부를) 잘라내다
voca.explains:
Crops are plants such as wheat and potatoes that are grown in large quantities for food.
The plants or fruits that are collected at harvest time are referred to as a crop.
You can refer to a group of people or things that have appeared together as a crop of people or things.
A crop is a short hairstyle.
When a plant crops, it produces fruits or parts which people want.

voca.title: crop up
voca.explains: to appear, happen, etc. when it is not expected\n

voca.title: cross
voca.means:
[^k뤄s]
십자, 십자가, 고난
(가로질러) 건너다, 가로지르다, 교차시키다,
서로 겹치게 놓다
A와 B를 이종교배하다
voca.explains:
angry / mad / indignant / cross / irate
If you cross something such as a room, a road, or an area of land or water, you move or travel to the other side of it. If you cross to a place, you move or travel over a room, road, or area of land or water in order to reach that place.
A road, railway, or bridge that crosses an area of land or water passes over it.
Lines or roads that cross meet and go across each other.
If someone or something crosses a limit or boundary, for example the limit of acceptable behaviour, they go beyond it.
A cross is a shape that consists of a vertical line or piece with a shorter horizontal line or piece across it. It is the most important Christian symbol.
A shadow crossed the king's face.

voca.title: cross one's mind
voca.explains:
The thought of plummeting to my death suddenly crossed my mind. It scared me silly.
It didn't cross my mind earlier to drop by the bank.
It never crossed my mind to call you ahead of time.

voca.title: cross over
voca.explains: to go from one side of something, for example a road/street, a room, etc. to the other\nto move from one style or type of music, culture, politics, etc. to another; to combine parts of different styles or types\n

voca.title: cross with somebody
voca.explains: Now he was cross with Morgan.\n

voca.title: crossbow
voca.explains: A crossbow is a weapon consisting of a small, powerful bow that is fixed across a piece of wood, and aimed like a gun.\n

voca.title: crosswalk
voca.explains: A crosswalk is a place where pedestrians can cross a street and where drivers must stop to let them cross.\n

voca.title: crouch
voca.means:
[k^롸웃취]
숙이다, 구부리다, 쭈그리다, 움츠리다
웅크린 자세, 움츠리기,
구부리기, 쭈그려 앉기
voca.explains:
If you are crouching, your legs are bent under you so that you are close to the ground and leaning forward slightly.
Jack crouched below the window. / Annie crouched beside him.
Jack crouched down.
Crouching down, he hurried toward her.
Jack and Annie crouched in the grass.
The bird was crouching, slightly spreading its wings.
Hidden in the shadows, they crouched together, their dark feathers touching.
Buster crouched down in a batting stance. "It's just you and the pitcher. Nothing else matters. You raise your bat. Ready. Waiting. The pitch blazes in. You can feel the heat as the ball passes by."
All during practice, Arthur fingered the good-luck charm. But since no tough balls were hit to him, he couldn't be sure if it was working. When Francine came up to bat, he crouched down to be ready.
"About pitching your fastball." He crouched down into a catching stance. "Come on, fire it in here."

voca.title: crow
voca.means:
[^k로우]
까마귀
숫탉 울음소리(같은 소리), 환성
(특히 이른 새벽에)'꼬끼오'하고 울다
voca.explains:
A crow is a large black bird which makes a loud, harsh noise.
When a cock crows, it makes a loud sound, often early in the morning.
If you say that someone is crowing about something they have achieved or are pleased about, you disapprove of them because they keep telling people proudly about it.
Roosters crowed.

voca.title: crowd
voca.means:
[^k롸우d]
(길거리나 스포츠 경기장 등에 모인) 사람들, 군중, 무리, 
일반 대중, 보통 사람, 다수
모여들다, 붐비다, (어떤 장소를) 가득 메우다
voca.explains:
A crowd is a large group of people who have gathered together, for example to watch or listen to something interesting, or to protest about something.
A particular crowd is a group of friends, or a set of people who share the same interests or job.
When people crowd around someone or something, they gather closely together around them.
If people crowd into a place or are crowded into a place, large numbers of them enter it so that it becomes very full.
If a group of people crowd a place, there are so many of them there that it is full.
If people crowd you, they stand very closely around you trying to see or speak to you, so that you feel uncomfortable.

voca.title: crowd in
voca.explains: if high buildings, mountains, etc. crowd in, they seem to surround you and threaten you or have a strong effect on you\nto move in large numbers into a small place\n

voca.title: crowd out
voca.explains: if a number of people or things crowd out other people or things, they are present in such large numbers that there is no room for anyone or anything else\n

voca.title: crowd something out
voca.means: (더 이상 공간이 없어) ~을 몰아내다\n~이 설 자리를 없게 만들다
voca.explains: if a number of people or things crowd out other people or things, they are present in such large numbers that there is no room for anyone or anything else\n

voca.title: crowd the streets
voca.explains: On both Christmas Eve and the day of, young people crowd the streets.\n

voca.title: crowded
voca.means: [k롸우딛d]\n(사람들이) 붐비는, 복잡한, 혼잡한, 꽉찬\n~이 가득한, 빡빡한
voca.explains:
If a place is crowded, it is full of people.
If a place is crowded, a lot of people live there.
If your timetable, your life, or your mind is crowded, it is full of events, activities, or thoughts.

voca.title: crowded place
voca.explains:
I don't like going to crowded places.
I feel nervous when I am in crowded places.
I couldn't hear you because I was in a crowded place.

voca.title: crown
voca.means:
[k롸-운]
왕관, 왕위, 왕권
화관, 월계관
왕관을 씌우다, 왕위에 앉히다
voca.explains:
A crown is a circular ornament, usually made of gold and jewels, which a king or queen wears on their head at official ceremonies. You can also use crown to refer to anything circular that is worn on someone's head.
The government of a country that has a king or queen is sometimes referred to as the Crown. In British criminal cases the prosecutor is the Crown.
Your crown is the top part of your head, at the back.
A crown is an artificial top piece fixed over a broken or decayed tooth.
When a king or queen is crowned, a crown is placed on their head as part of a ceremony in which they are officially made king or queen.

voca.title: crud
voca.means:
[^k롸d]
허풍, 과장, 변명
더러운 것, 오물
혐오스러운 놈, 비열한 놈
voca.explains:
a sticky substance, esp when dirty and encrusted
an undesirable residue from a process, esp one inside a nuclear reactor
something or someone that is worthless, disgusting, or contemptible
the crud a disease; rot
an expression of disgust, disappointment, etc

voca.title: cruel
voca.explains:
Someone who is cruel deliberately causes pain or distress to people or animals.
A situation or event that is cruel is very harsh and causes people distress.
"It's cruel. You better let him go, or else!"

voca.title: cruise
voca.means:
[쿠르-s]
유람선 여행, 
유람선을 타고 다니다, (꾸준한 속도로) 순항하다, 나아가다
(특히 무엇을 찾아) 천천히 달리다, 
수월히 이기다/이루다
voca.explains:
A cruise is a holiday during which you travel on a ship or boat and visit a number of places.
If you cruise a sea, river, or canal, you travel around it or along it on a cruise.
If a car, ship, or aircraft cruises somewhere, it moves there at a steady comfortable speed.
If a team or sports player cruises to victory, they win easily.

voca.title: cruiser
voca.explains:
A cruiser is a motor boat which has an area for people to live or sleep.
A cruiser is a large fast warship.
A cruiser is a police car.
A police officer was standing outside. Her cruiser was out on the street. The lights were flashing.

voca.title: crumb
voca.means: [k^뤔]\n(빵, 케이크의) 부스러기, 작은 것, 약간, 소량
voca.explains:
Bread crumbs
Crumbs are tiny pieces that fall from bread, biscuits, or cake when you cut it or eat it.
A crumb of something, for example information, is a very small amount of it.
It shone on a long banquet table. The table was littered with bread crumbs, candle wax, and the petals of dead flowers.

voca.title: crumble
voca.explains:
If something crumbles, or if you crumble it, it breaks into a lot of small pieces.
If an old building or piece of land is crumbling, parts of it keep breaking off.
If something such as a system, relationship, or hope crumbles, it comes to an end.
If someone crumbles, they stop resisting or trying to win, or become unable to cope.
A crumble is a baked pudding made from fruit covered with a mixture of flour, butter, and sugar.
She crumbled the leaf into the chowder.
The volcanic rock crumbled and turned to soil.

voca.title: crunch
voca.explains:
If you crunch something hard, such as a sweet, you crush it noisily between your teeth.
If something crunches or if you crunch it, it makes a breaking or crushing noise, for example when you step on it.
If you crunch across a surface made of very small stones, you move across it causing it to make a crunching noise.
To crunch numbers means to do a lot of calculations using a calculator or computer.
You can refer to an important time or event, for example when an important decision has to be made, as the crunch.
A situation in which a business or economy has very little money can be referred to as a crunch.
The autumn leaves crunched and crackled under their leather shoes.
Jack, Annie, and Teddy crunched through fallen leaves until they came to Merlin's oak.

voca.title: crunchy
voca.explains: Food that is crunchy is pleasantly hard or crisp so that it makes a noise when you eat it.\n

voca.title: crush
voca.means:
[k^롸쉬]
으스러뜨리다, 쭈그려뜨리다, 
눌러 부수다, 부서지다, 망가지다
분쇄, 압착, 압도, 홀딱 반함, 일시적 열중
voca.explains:
To crush something means to press it very hard so that its shape is destroyed or so that it breaks into pieces.
To crush a protest or movement, or a group of opponents, means to defeat it completely, usually by force.
If you are crushed by something, it upsets you a great deal.
A crush is a crowd of people close together, in which it is difficult to move.
If you have a crush on someone, you are in love with them but do not have a relationship with them.
They used a crushed mild carton as a puck, hitting it back and forth the lenght of the table.
Francine crushed the next pitch to deep right field. Arthur ran back, watching it the whole way.

voca.title: crush in
voca.means: (몸, 차의 일부)를 부수다\n(여럿이) 확 밀치고 들어가다, 밀어 넣다

voca.title: crush on
voca.explains: Jason: I have a big crush on you. I had it since the moment I saw you.\n

voca.title: crush out
voca.means:
(~을) 부수고 나가다, 탈옥하다
(~에서) 몰아내다, 짜내다
(희망 따위를) 빼앗다
(질병을) 박멸하다

voca.title: crustacean
voca.explains: A crustacean is an animal with a hard shell and several pairs of legs, which usually lives in water. Crabs, lobsters, and shrimps are crustaceans.\n

voca.title: crutch
voca.explains:
A crutch is a stick whose top fits round or under the user's arm, which someone with an injured foot or leg uses to support their weight when walking.
If you refer to someone or something as a crutch, you mean that they give you help or support.
Your crutch is the same as your crotch.

voca.title: crux
voca.means: [k^럭s]\n(문제나 쟁점의) 가장 중요한[곤란한] 부분\n(crux란 ’십자가’를 뜻하는 말이다)
voca.explains: The crux of a problem or argument is the most important or difficult part of it which affects everything else.\n

voca.title: crux of the matter
voca.explains: We have to find a suitable compromise. The crux of the matter is finding something meaningful and affordable. It can’t be solved by throwing money at it.\n

voca.title: cry
voca.means:
[k롸이]
(기분이 안좋거나 아파서) 울다, 외치다,
(불쾌한 소리로) 울다, 울부짖다, 
비명, 고함, 외침, (새나 동물의) 울음 소리, 
울음, 울기,
voca.explains:
When you cry, tears come from your eyes, usually because you are unhappy or hurt.
If you cry something, you shout it or say it loudly.
A cry is a loud, high sound that you make when you feel a strong emotion such as fear, pain, or pleasure.
A cry is a shouted word or phrase, usually one that is intended to attract someone's attention.
You can refer to a public protest about something or an appeal for something as a cry of some kind.
A bird's or animal's cry is the loud, high sound that it makes.
Finally, the hugging and crying and laughing died down.

voca.title: cry off
voca.explains: to decide not to do something you have promised or agreed to do\n

voca.title: cry out
voca.means: (아품, 공포, 놀람 등으로) 비명을 지르다\n~을 외치다
voca.explains:
call / cry out / exclaim / blurt / burst out
to make a loud sound without words because you are hurt, afraid, surprised, etc.
to shout something loudly

voca.title: cry out for something
voca.explains: to clearly need something very quickly\n

voca.title: crybaby
voca.explains: If someone calls a child a crybaby, they mean that the child cries a lot for no good reason.\nI am a sucker for tear-jerking videos. My friends call em a crybaby.\n

voca.title: crystal
voca.explains:
A crystal is a small piece of a substance that has formed naturally into a regular symmetrical shape.
Crystal is a transparent rock that is used to make jewellery and ornaments.
Crystal is a high quality glass, usually with patterns cut into its surface.
Glasses and other containers made of crystal are referred to as crystal
Along the brilliant crystal walls of the room were four doorways.
Amid all the treasure was a blue-white crystal.

voca.title: cub
voca.explains: A cub is a young wild animal such as a lion, wolf, or bear.\n

voca.title: cubby
voca.explains: "Class, please hang your backpacks on the hooks and put your lunches in the cubbies," said Mr.Todd.\n

voca.title: cubbyhole
voca.explains: a small enclosed space or room\nany small compartment, such as a pigeonhole\n

voca.title: cubicle
voca.means: [^큐-비끌]\n칸막이한 좁은 장소, 개인 열람석\n(큰 방 한 쪽을 칸막이 해 만든) 좁은 방
voca.explains: A cubicle is a very small enclosed area, for example one where you can have a shower or change your clothes.\n

voca.title: cuckoo
voca.explains: A cuckoo is a bird that has a call of two quick notes, and lays its eggs in other birds' nests.\n

voca.title: cuddle
voca.explains: If you cuddle someone, you put your arms round them and hold them close as a way of showing your affection.\n

voca.title: cuisine
voca.explains:
The cuisine of a country or district is the style of cooking that is characteristic of that place.
The skill or profession of cooking unusual or interesting food can be referred to as cuisine.
My favorite dishes include everything from junk food to haute cuisine. This has been a real boon in my life, since I can find something yummy almost anywhere.

voca.title: culinary
voca.explains: Culinary means concerned with cooking.\n

voca.title: culprit
voca.explains:
When you are talking about a crime or something wrong that has been done, you can refer to the person who did it as the culprit.
When you are talking about a problem or bad situation, you can refer to its cause as the culprit.
He found a bunch of cotton swabs in the piping. I felt bad, because I was the culprit.
I checked the black box footage. The culprit was caught on camera. I reported him to the police, and made him pay for (the) repairs.
My computer had given up the ghost. I took it to a service center. The technician there ran some diagnostics. He said that the culprit was a critical error in the hard drive.

voca.title: cultural
voca.means:
[^컬춰럴]
(한 사회의) 문화와 관련된, 문화의
(음악, 미술, 문학 등과 관련된) 문화의
교양의, 문화의
voca.explains: Cultural means relating to a particular society and its ideas, customs, and art.\nCultural means involving or concerning the arts.\n

voca.title: culture
voca.means:
[^컬춰]
(한 국가나 집단의) 문화
(고유의 문화를 지닌) 문화 (공동체)
(특정 조직이나 단체의) 사고방식, 문화
재배, 양식, 사육
배양균, 배양 조직
(미생물, 조직 등을) 배양하다
voca.explains:
Culture consists of activities such as the arts and philosophy, which are considered to be important for the development of civilization and of people's minds.

voca.title: cupboard
voca.explains: A cupboard is a piece of furniture that has one or two doors, usually contains shelves, and is used to store things. In British English, cupboard refers to all kinds of furniture like this. In American English, closet is usually used instead to refer to larger pieces of furniture\nA cupboard is a very small room that is used to store things, especially one without windows.\n

If an action or event cures someone of a habit or an attitude, it makes them stop having it.
When food, tobacco, or animal skin is cured, it is dried, smoked, or salted so that it will last for a long time.
A cure for an illness is a medicine or other treatment that cures the illness.
A cure for a problem is something that will bring it to an end.

Working up a sweat is a good way to cure a hangover.

A current is a steady flowing movement of air.
An electric current is a flow of electricity through a wire or circuit.
A particular current is a particular feeling, idea, or quality that exists within a group of people.
Current means happening, being used, or being done at the present time.

voca.title: curriculum

If you say that there is a curse on someone, you mean that there seems to be a supernatural power causing unpleasant things to happen to them.

Buster nodded. "Yeah. How about Curse of the Mummy's Breath? Talk about not brushing your teeth..."

voca.explains:

if somebody/something damps down an emotion or a feeling, it becomes less strong
if somebody/something damps down a situation or an activity, it becomes slower or weaker
to make a surface slightly wet by spraying a small amount of water over it

사악한, 음흉한, 암울한, 음울한
voca.explains:
When it is dark, there is not enough light to see properly, for example because it is night.
If you describe something as dark, you mean that it is black in colour, or a shade that is close to black.
If someone has dark hair, eyes, or skin, they have brown or black hair, eyes, or skin.
If you describe a white person as dark, you mean that they have brown or black hair, and often a brownish skin.
A dark period of time is unpleasant or frightening.
A dark place or area is mysterious and not fully known about.
Dark thoughts are sad, and show that you are expecting something unpleasant to happen.
Dark looks or remarks make you think that the person giving them wants to harm you or that something horrible is going to happen.
If you describe something as dark, you mean that it is related to things that are serious or unpleasant, rather than light-hearted.
When you use dark to describe a colour, you are referring to a shade of that colour which is close to black, or seems to have some black in it.

voca.title: dark look on one's face
voca.explains:
I recently went to a restaurant to wine and dine my wife for our anniversary. The food was top notch. However, the bad service was a problem. Our waiter had a bad attitude. He just left our menus on the table without any explaining. He took our orders with a dark look on his face.
She spoke with a dark look on her face.
He has a dark look on his face every Monday.

voca.title: darken
voca.means: [다r끈]\n어두워지다, 캄캄해지다, 어둡게 만들다\n우울하게/불행하게 만들다, 우울해지다, 불행해지다
voca.explains:
If something darkens or if a person or thing darkens it, it becomes darker.
If someone's mood darkens or if something darkens their mood, they suddenly become rather unhappy.
If someone's face darkens, they suddenly look angry.

voca.title: darling
voca.means:
[^달-륑]
여보, 자기, 얘야
가장 사람하는 사람
가장 사랑하는, 귀여운, 마음에 드는
(대단히) 사랑하는; 굉장히 멋진, 특별한
voca.explains:
You call someone darling if you love them or like them very much.
If you describe someone as a darling, you are fond of them and think that they are nice.
The darling of a group of people is someone who is especially liked by that group.
Some people use darling to describe someone or something that they love or like very much.

voca.title: darn
voca.means:
[다r안]
(옷의 구멍난 곳을) 꿰메다, 짜깁다
(옷의) 꽤맨 잘
(damn 대신에 쓰는 가벼운 욕설로) 젠장맞을, 빌어먹을
voca.explains:
If you darn something knitted or made of cloth, you mend a hole in it by sewing stitches across the hole and then weaving stitches in and out of them.
People sometimes use darn or darned to emphasize what they are saying, often when they are annoyed.
You can say I'll be darned to show that you are very surprised about something.

voca.title: dart
voca.means:
[다r-t]
(무기용의 작은) 화살, (다트 놀이용) 화살, 
다늘고 짧은 화살, 급격한 동작, 돌진
날쎄게 움직이다, 돌진하다, 쏜살같이 달리다
(~에게) 휙 눈길을 던지다, (~을) 흘깃 쳐다보다
voca.explains:
If a person or animal darts somewhere, they move there suddenly and quickly.
If you dart a look at someone or something, or if your eyes dart to them, you look at them very quickly.
A dart is a small, narrow object with a sharp point which can be thrown or shot.
Darts is a game in which you throw darts at a round board which has numbers on it.
She darted into the woods.
He hovered in the cold night air, his eyes darting from right to left.

voca.title: dart down
voca.explains: The short ninja darted down the ladder.\n

voca.title: dash
voca.explains:
If you dash somewhere, you run or go there quickly and suddenly.
If you say that you have to dash, you mean that you are in a hurry and have to leave immediately.
If you dash something against a wall or other surface, you throw or push it violently, often so hard that it breaks.
If an event or person dashes someone's hopes or expectations, it destroys them by making it impossible that the thing that is hoped for or expected will ever happen.
A dash of something is a small quantity of it which you add when you are preparing food or mixing a drink.
Jack held on tightly to Annies as the stag dashed across a frost-covered field.

voca.title: dash out
voca.explains: I often choose to linger in bed and hit the snooze button on my phone. This usually makes me spring out of bed in a hurry. A sense of urgency is reinforced with the fear of running late. I dash out but always with a cup of coffee in hand. I have always had a soft spot for morning coffee.\n

voca.title: dash something off
voca.explains: to write or draw something very quickly\n

voca.title: dash-cam
voca.means: 차의 계기판에 부착되어 도로를 촬영하는 카메라\n(차량용) 블랙박스
voca.explains: However, the other driver was at greater fault. I was able to prove it using dash-cam footage.\nI also saw several clips of traffic accidents from dash cams in cars. It made me feel sick to my stomach. It remined me again that when driving, safety is paramount.\n

voca.title: date
voca.means:
[^데잇t]
(특정한) 날짜
(과거나 미래의 어느) 시기, 때, 시대
(남녀간의) 데이트, 
(특정한 날짜를 정해서 만나기로 하는) 약속
대추(대추야자 나무의 열매)
날짜를 적다/기입하다
구식이 되다, 유행에 뒤떨어지게 되다
voca.explains:
A date is a specific time that can be named, for example a particular day or a particular year.
If you want to refer to an event without saying exactly when it will happen or when it happened, you can say that it will happen or happened at some date in the future or past.
A date is an appointment to meet someone or go out with them, especially someone with whom you are having, or may soon have, a romantic relationship.
If you have a date with someone with whom you are having, or may soon have, a romantic relationship, you can refer to that person as your date.
A date is a small, dark-brown, sticky fruit with a stone inside. Dates grow on palm trees in hot countries.
If you date something, you give or discover the date when it was made or when it began.
When you date something such as a letter or a cheque, you write that day's date on it.
If something dates, it goes out of fashion and becomes unacceptable to modern tastes.
If your ideas, what you say, or the things that you like or can remember date you, they show that you are quite old or older than the people you are with.
If you are dating someone, you go out with them regularly because you are having, or may soon have, a romantic relationship with them. You can also say that two people are dating.

voca.title: daughter
voca.explains: Someone's daughter is their female child.\n

voca.title: daunt
voca.explains: If something daunts you, it makes you feel slightly afraid or worried about dealing with it.\nIt can seem daunting at first. However, you soon get into the spirit.\n

voca.title: dawn
voca.means:
[^도온]
새벽, 여명, 동이 틀 무렵, 시작, 시초
(날이)새다, 밝아오다
분명해지다, 이해가 되기 시작하다
voca.explains:
Dawn is the time of day when light first appears in the sky, just before the sun rises.
The dawn of a period of time or a situation is the beginning of it.
If something is dawning, it is beginning to develop or come into existence.
When you say that a particular day dawned, you mean it arrived or began, usually when it became light.
Jason: Cool, let's drink till dawn.

voca.title: dawn on something
voca.explains: It dawned on me last night that you were right about this job.\n

voca.title: day
voca.means:
[^데-이]
(24시간 동안의) 하루, 날, 요일
(아침부터 해가 지기까지의 시간인) 하루, 주간
낮 (동안)
(특정한 때나 역사적인) 시기, 시대/시절
voca.explains:
A day is one of the seven twenty-four hour periods of time in a week.
Day is the time when it is light, or the time when you are up and doing things.
You can refer to a particular period in history as a particular day or as particular days.

voca.title: day after day
voca.explains: for many days, one after the other\n

voca.title: day in and day out
voca.explains:
Young children need to be supervised day in and day out.
Now it's just work day in and day out.
Some people think that fashion is a waste of time. They say they prefer to spend their time on more important issue. They even wear the same thing day in and day out.

voca.title: day job
voca.explains:
If someone tells you not to give up the day job, they are saying that they think you should continue doing what you are good at, rather than trying something new which they think you will fail at.
The biggest problem was that stock trading is all-consuming. I kept getting side-tracked at work as I checked the stock prices. I couldn’t focus on my day job. I eventually had to give it up. Stock trading just wasn’t my forte.
He pays more attention to his hobby than to his day job.
Few peopel are happy at their day job.

voca.title: day to day
voca.explains: Day-to-day things or activities exist or happen every day as part of ordinary life.\n

voca.title: daybreak
voca.explains: Daybreak is the time in the morning when light first appears.\n

voca.title: daydream
voca.means:
[^데이듀륌]
몽상, 상상, 백일몽, 
실현 불가능한 계획
한가로이 상상하다, 공상하다
voca.explains:
If you daydream, you think about pleasant things for a period of time, usually about things that you would like to happen.
A daydream is a series of pleasant thoughts, usually about things that you would like to happen.
A fun way to kill time is to sneak a peek at the weather in other places. I can see what it’s like where my loved ones are living. I also like to check the weather at getaway destinations, and daydream about going there.
I daydreamed about going on vacation.
My daydream was about going on vacation.

voca.title: daylight robbery
voca.means: (백주 대낮의) 날강도짓\n(무엇에 대한 대금을 터무니없이 청구하는 것을 나타냄)
voca.explains: a price or fee that you think is far too high\n

voca.title: daytime
voca.explains: The daytime is the part of a day between the time when it gets light and the time when it gets dark.\nDaytime television and radio is broadcast during the morning and afternoon on weekdays.\n

voca.title: day-to-day
voca.means: (장기적으로 계획하는 것이 아니라) 그날그날 꾸려가는\n(일이) 매일 행해지는, 그날그날의
voca.explains: Day-to-day things or activities exist or happen every day as part of ordinary life.\n

voca.title: day-to-day life
voca.explains:
My laptop computer is an indispensable part of my day-to-day life. For both work and play, I can’t make do without it.
Day-to-day life can be boring at times.
Her day-to-day life is exhausting.

voca.title: daze
voca.means: [데이z]\n~을 멍해지게 하다, 정신이 아찔하게 하다\n멍해진 상태, 아찔해진 상태
voca.explains: If someone is in a daze, they are feeling confused and unable to think clearly, often because they have had a shock or surprise.\n

voca.title: dazzle
voca.means:
[데즐]
(강한 빛이) 눈이 부시게 하다, 
(미모, 솜씨 등으로) 눈부시게 하다, 황홀하게 하다
눈부심, 황홀함
voca.explains:
If someone or something dazzles you, you are extremely impressed by their skill, qualities, or beauty.
If a bright light dazzles you, it makes you unable to see properly for a short time.
The dazzle of something is a quality it has, such as beauty or skill, which is impressive and attractive.
The dazzle of a light is its brightness, which makes it impossible for you to see properly for a short time.

voca.title: dazzling
voca.explains: Something that is dazzling is very impressive or beautiful.\nA dazzling light is very bright and makes you unable to see properly for a short time.\n

voca.title: deactivate
voca.means: [디^엑디베잇t]\n(어떤 장치의 작동을) 정지시키다, \n(화학 작용 등을) 비활성화시키다
voca.explains: If someone deactivates an explosive device or an alarm, they make it harmless or impossible to operate.\nThis gun is designed specifically to deactivate drones.\n

voca.title: dead
voca.means:
[^덷d]
죽은, 생명을 읽은
아주, 전적으로, 완전히
더 이상 믿어지지 않는, 과거의, 케케묵은
딱, 완전히, 정확히, 되게, 몹시
voca.explains:
A person, animal, or plant that is dead is no longer living.
If you describe a place or a period of time as dead, you do not like it because there is very little activity taking place in it.
Something that is dead is no longer being used or is finished.
If you say that an idea, plan, or subject is dead, you mean that people are no longer interested in it or willing to develop it any further.
A dead language is no longer spoken or written as a means of communication, although it may still be studied.
A telephone or piece of electrical equipment that is dead is no longer functioning, for example because it no longer has any electrical power.
In sport, when a ball is dead, it has gone outside the playing area, or a situation has occurred in which the game has to be temporarily stopped, and none of the players can score points or gain an advantage.

voca.title: dead end
voca.means: (도로, 통로 등이 한쪽 끝이 막힌) 막다른 길\n(더 이상 앞으로 나아갈 수 없는) 막다른 지경
voca.explains:
If a street is a dead end, there is no way out at one end of it.
A dead end job or course of action is one that you think is bad because it does not lead to further developments or progress.
We had to put the car in reverse at a dead end.

voca.title: dead giveaway
voca.explains: A secret that it is obvious to everyone.\n

voca.title: dead meat
voca.explains: in serious trouble\n

voca.title: deadline
voca.explains:
A deadline is a time or date before which a particular task must be finished or a particular thing must be done.
"I can’t, Mom. The deadline is getting closer."
Can you get it done by the deadline?
I’m sure I can finish it by the deadline.
There were too many things to be done, so it was tough to finish them by the deadline.

voca.title: deadly
voca.means:
[덷뤼]
생명을 앗아가는, 치명적인
극도의, 완전한, 틀림없이 정확한, 아무도 막을 수 없는
극도로, 지독히
voca.explains:
If something is deadly, it is likely or able to cause someone's death, or has already caused someone's death.
If you describe a person or their behaviour as deadly, you mean that they will do or say anything to get what they want, without caring about other people.
A deadly situation has unpleasant or dangerous consequences.
Deadly enemies or rivals fight or compete with each other in a very aggressive way.
You can use deadly to emphasize that something has a particular quality, especially an unpleasant or undesirable quality.

voca.title: deaf
voca.explains: Someone who is deaf is unable to hear anything or is unable to hear very well.\nIf you say that someone is deaf to people's requests, arguments, or criticisms, you are criticizing them because they refuse to pay attention to them.\n

voca.title: deafen
voca.means: [데픈]\n(심한 소음으로) 귀를 먹먹하게 만들다\n귀를 먹게 만들다
voca.explains: If a noise deafens you, it is so loud that you cannot hear anything else at the same time.\nIf you are deafened by something, you are made deaf by it, or are unable to hear for some time.\n

voca.title: deafening
voca.means: [^데f닝]\n귀청이 터질 듯한, 귀가 먹먹한\n방음 장치, 방음 재료
voca.explains:
A deafening noise is a very loud noise.
If you say there was a deafening silence, you are emphasizing that there was no reaction or response to something that was said or done.
A deafening wind roared through the room.
Everyone stopped. The silence was deafening.

voca.title: deal
voca.means:
[디얼]
다루다, 처리하다, 나누어주다
(카드 게임에서 카드를) 돌리다
거래, 계획, 대우, 취급
(거래서, 사업상의) 합의
많은, 많이
voca.explains:
deal - dealt - dealt
If you make a deal, do a deal, or cut a deal, you complete an agreement or an arrangement with someone, especially in business.
If someone has had a bad deal, they have been unfortunate or have been treated unfairly.
If a person, company, or shop deals in a particular type of goods, their business involves buying or selling those goods.
If someone deals illegal drugs, they sell them.
If you deal playing cards, you give them out to the players in a game of cards.

voca.title: deal in something
voca.means: (특별한 상품을) 취급/거래하다\n(결정, 태도, 행동의 기준으로) 받아들이다, 다루다
voca.explains:
to do business; to make money by buying and selling a particular product or kind of goods
to make money by buying and selling goods illegally, especially drugs
to be concerned with or involved in something

voca.title: deal something in
voca.explains: to include somebody in an activity\n

voca.title: deal something out
voca.explains:
to share something among a number of people, groups of people or organizations
(in a game of cards) to give cards to each player
to give somebody a particular punishment; to say what punishment somebody should have

voca.title: deal with
voca.explains:
to look after, talk to or control people in an appropriate way, especially as part of your job
to take appropriate action in a particular situation or according to who you are talking to, etc.
to take appropriate action to punish somebody who has done something wrong
to solve a problem, carry out a task, etc.
to be about something
if you deal with an emotion such as anger or sadness, you learn to control it or become less affected by it
"Don't complain." said Arthur. "I'm eating it, too. And I've still got the hard part to deal with."
We should deal with the pressing issues first.

voca.title: dealing
voca.means:
[^딜링]
관계, 거래(행위, 관계),
친한 관계, 행동, 행위
매매, 거래

voca.title: deallocate
voca.explains: TRUNCATE removes the data by deallocating the data pages used to store the table's data, and only the page deallocations are recorded in the transaction log.\n

voca.title: dear
voca.means:
[^디어r]
(~가) 사랑하는, (~에게) 소중한
(편지 첫 부분에 수신자의 이름앞에 써서) ~에게
친절한/상냥한 사람, 
비싸게, 비싼 값에
(감탄사) 이런/저런/맙소사/어머나
voca.explains:
expensive / costly / overpriced / pricey / dear
You use dear to describe someone or something that you feel affection for.
If something is dear to you or dear to your heart, you care deeply about it.
You use dear in expressions such as 'my dear fellow', 'dear girl', or 'my dear Richard' when you are addressing someone whom you know and are fond of. You can also use expressions like this in a rude way to indicate that you think you are superior to the person you are addressing.
Dear is written at the beginning of a letter, followed by the name or title of the person you are writing to.
If you say that something is dear, you mean that it costs a lot of money, usually more than you can afford or more than you think it should cost.

voca.title: dearly
voca.explains:
If you love someone dearly, you love them very much.
If you would dearly like to do or have something, you would very much like to do it or have it.
If you pay dearly for doing something or if it costs you dearly, you suffer a lot as a result.
It was just that sort of carelessness that had cost Susie so dearly in Night of the Cornstalker.

voca.title: death
voca.explains:
Death is the permanent end of the life of a person or animal.
A particular kind of death is a particular way of dying.
The death of something is the permanent end of it.
If you say that someone is at death's door, you mean they are very ill indeed and likely to die.
If you say that you will fight to the death for something, you are emphasizing that you will do anything to achieve or protect it, even if you suffer as a consequence.
If you refer to a fight or contest as a fight to the death, you are emphasizing that it will not stop until the death or total victory of one of the opponents.

voca.title: deathly
voca.explains:
If you say that someone is deathly pale or deathly still, you are emphasizing that they are very pale or still, like a dead person.
If you say that there is a deathly silence or a deathly hush, you are emphasizing that it is very quiet.
In an instant, the room fell deathly quiet.

voca.title: debate
voca.explains:
A debate is a discussion about a subject on which people have different views.
A debate is a formal discussion, for example in a parliament or institution, in which people express different opinions about a particular subject and then vote on it.
If people debate a topic, they discuss it fairly formally, putting forward different views. You can also say that one person debates a topic with another person.
If you debate whether to do something or what to do, you think or talk about possible courses of action before deciding exactly what you are going to do.
This will be a major issue in the debate.

voca.title: debit
voca.means:
[^데빗t]
(통장이나 장부의) 차변
인출/출금액
(은행에서 어떤 계좌의 돈을) 인출하다
voca.explains: When your bank debits your account, money is taken from it and paid to someone else.\nA debit is a record of the money taken from your bank account, for example when you write a cheque.\n

voca.title: debit card
voca.explains: I have had several problems with my credit card and debit card.\n

voca.title: debris
voca.means: [듸b^뤼-]\n(무엇이 파괴된 후의) 잔해, 파편, 부스러기\n(어디에 쓸모없게 남게되는) 쓰레기
voca.explains: Debris is pieces from something that has been destroyed or pieces of rubbish or unwanted material that are spread around.\n

voca.title: debt
voca.means:
[덷t]
빚, 부채, 채무, 부족
빚/부채를 진 상태
은혜를 입음, 신세를 짐
voca.explains:
A debt is a sum of money that you owe someone.
Debt is the state of owing money.
You use debt in expressions such as I owe you a debt or I am in your debt when you are expressing gratitude for something that someone has done for you

voca.title: decade
voca.explains: A decade is a period of ten years, especially one that begins with a year ending in 0, for example 1980 to 1989.\nHelsinki, Finland is road-testing autonomous buses as part of the effort to make the city car-free within a decade. \n

voca.title: decay
voca.means:
[딕^케이]
부패, 썩음, 충치(부분), 
(사회, 제도 등의) 쇠퇴, 쇠약
부패하다, 썩다, 상하다
(건물?지역이) 퇴락하다
voca.explains: When something such as a dead body, a dead plant, or a tooth decays, it is gradually destroyed by a natural process.\nIf something such as a society, system, or institution decays, it gradually becomes weaker or its condition gets worse.\n

voca.title: deceive
voca.explains:
cheat / fool / deceive / betray / take in / trick / con
If you deceive someone, you make them believe something that is not true, usually in order to get some advantage for yourself.
If you deceive yourself, you do not admit to yourself something that you know is true.
If something deceives you, it gives you a wrong impression and makes you believe something that is not true.

voca.title: December
voca.explains: December is the twelfth and last month of the year in the Western calendar.\nThe majority of the ceremonies take place in the last week of December.\n

voca.title: decent
voca.means:
[^디슨t]
(수준, 질이) 괜찮은, 제대로 된
품위 있는, 예의 바른, 
(상황에) 적절한/온당한
voca.explains:
Decent is used to describe something which is considered to be of an acceptable standard or quality.
Decent is used to describe something which is morally correct or acceptable.
Decent people are honest and behave in a way that most people approve of.
I made a mental note of all the decent restaurants in town.
