입증, 논증, 증명
voca.explains:
A demonstration is a march or gathering which people take part in to show their opposition to something or their support for something.
A demonstration of something is a talk by someone who shows you how to do it or how it works.
A demonstration of a fact or situation is a clear proof of it.
A demonstration of a quality or feeling is an expression of it.
What? You didn't know there is a demonstration going on?
The flight attendants gave a safety demonstration. Soon, we took off. After a while, the attendants came by with the beverage cart. Later on, we had our in-flight meal.

voca.title: den
voca.means:
[^덴]
(야생 동물이 사는) 굴
(특히 부정한 행위를 하기 위한) 소굴
편안히 쉴 수 있는 방, 은신처
voca.explains:
A den is the home of certain types of wild animals such as lions or foxes.
Your den is a quiet room in your house where you can go to study, work, or carry on a hobby without being disturbed.
A den is a secret place where people meet, usually for a dishonest purpose.
If you describe a place as a den of a particular type of bad or illegal behaviour, you mean that a lot of that type of behaviour goes on there.
I petted a goat, fed a giraffe, and then went on a tour to visit the lion’s den.

voca.title: Dene
voca.means: [데인]\n덴마크 사람\n데인 족 (9~10세기에 영궁에 침입한 북유럽 사람)

voca.title: denomination
voca.means:
[디^노미네이션]
(특히 돈의) 액면가
(화폐 등의) 단위 (명칭); (화폐·증권의) 액면 금액
명칭, 호칭.
계급, 종류.
(기독교의) 종파, 교파
voca.explains:
A particular denomination is a particular religious group which has slightly different beliefs from other groups within the same faith.
The denomination of a banknote or coin is its official value.
Korea’s currency is the Korean Won. The bills come in denominations of one, five, ten and fifty thousand Won. The coins are valued at 10, 50, 100 and 500 won.

voca.title: denominator
voca.explains: In mathematics, the denominator is the number which appears under the line in a fraction.\n

voca.title: density
voca.explains: Density is the extent to which something is filled or covered with people or things.\nIn science, the density of a substance or object is the relation of its mass or weight to its volume.\n

voca.title: dent
voca.means:
[덴-t]
(단단한 표면을 세게 쳐서) 움푹 들어가게 만들다
찌그러뜨리다, 
(자신감, 명성 등을) 회손하다
움푹 들어간/찌그러진 곳
voca.explains: If you dent the surface of something, you make a hollow area in it by hitting or pressing it.\nIf something dents your ideas or your pride, it makes you realize that your ideas are wrong, or that you are not as good or successful as you thought.\n

voca.title: dental
voca.explains: Dental is used to describe things that relate to teeth or to the care and treatment of teeth.\n

voca.title: dental braces
voca.explains: The problem is that dental braces are very pricey.\n

voca.title: dentist
voca.explains: A dentist is a person who is qualified to examine and treat people's teeth.\n

voca.title: denture
voca.explains: a partial or full set of artificial teeth\na set of natural teeth\n

voca.title: deny
voca.means:
[디^나이]
(무엇이) 사실이 아니라고 말하다, 
부인/부정하다
~에 동의하지 않다, 거부하다, 허락하지 않다
~을 자제하다
voca.explains:
When you deny something, you state that it is not true.
If you deny someone something that they need or want, you refuse to let them have it.
I received a speial request, but I denied it.

voca.title: depart
voca.explains:
When something or someone departs from a place, they leave it and start a journey to another place.
If you depart from a traditional, accepted, or agreed way of doing something, you do it in a different or unexpected way.
If someone departs from a job, they resign from it or leave it. In American English, you can say that someone departs a job.

voca.title: depart from
voca.explains: to behave in a way that is different from what is usual or expected\nJust two and a half hours after departing from Seoul, I arrived at Busan Station.\n

voca.title: brochure
voca.explains: A brochure is a magazine or thin book with pictures that gives you information about a product or service.\nDo you have any brochures on your latest products?\n

voca.title: call back
voca.means: (전화를 해 왔던 사람이나 누구에게) 다시 전화를 하다\n나중에 다시 전화하다
voca.explains: to telephone somebody again or to telephone somebody who telephoned you earlier\nCould you have him call me back?\n

voca.title: department
voca.means: [디^파r-t먼t]\n(정부, 기업체, 대학 등과 같은 조직의 한) 부서,  학과
voca.explains:
A department is one of the sections in an organization such as a government, business, or university. A department is also one of the sections in a large shop.
If you say that a task or area of knowledge is not your department, you mean that you are not responsible for it or do not know much about it.
Can you connect me to the Sales Department, please?

voca.title: department store
voca.explains: A department store is a large shop which sells many different kinds of goods.\nI recently went to a department store to shop for some shoes.\n

voca.title: departure
voca.means:
[디^파r-춰r]
출발, 떠남, 이탈, 사임
(항공기, 기차 등의) 출발(편)
(정도, 일상 등으로부터) 벗어남, 일탈
voca.explains:
Departure or a departure is the act of going away from somewhere.
The departure of a person from a job, or a member from an organization, is their act of leaving it or being forced to leave it.
If someone does something different or unusual, you can refer to their action as a departure.

voca.title: departure time
voca.explains: The app is very user-friendly. You can choose your departure time and even your seat. The app even gives you a digital ticket, so you don't need to print one out.\n

voca.title: depend
voca.explains:
If you say that one thing depends on another, you mean that the first thing will be affected or determined by the second.
If you depend on someone or something, you need them in order to be able to survive physically, financially, or emotionally.
If you can depend on a person, organization, or law, you know that they will support you or help you when you need them.
You use depend in expressions such as it depends to indicate that you cannot give a clear answer to a question because the answer will be affected or determined by other factors.

voca.title: depend on
voca.means:
~에 따라, 달렸다,
~에 따라 다르다 
의존/의지하다
~할 거라 믿다
voca.explains:
It depends on the kind of hawk. Some hawks eat fish some eat rodents. Hey we're running out of light.
"That's what Merlin must have meant when he said the future of Camelot depends on us," said Annie.
B : Well, that all depends on the traffic.
Donna: It depends on the favor, but tell me anyway.
Staff dinners are quite common in Korea. In Korean office culture, co-workers often eat dinner together. The frequency of staff dinners depends on the company, and the team.
We often take our home appliances for granted. But when they break down, we realize how much we depend on them.

voca.title: depend upon
voca.explains:
to need help or support from somebody/something in order to live or to manage in a particular situation
to be affected by or decided by somebody/something
"The whole future of our kingdom depends upon your success," said Merlin.

voca.title: dependent
voca.explains: To be dependent on something or someone means to need them in order to succeed or be able to survive.\nIf one thing is dependent on another, the first thing will be affected or determined by the second.\n

voca.title: depending on
voca.explains:
Depending on the type, they have different names. Some are called "saunas." Others, called jjimjilbang, are more like spas.
The fare varies depending on the departure date.
That can be possible depending on when you leave.
I’ll hire him depending on his attitude and work ethic.

voca.title: deplete
voca.means: [디플륏t]\n(남아있는게 충분하지 않을 정도로) 고갈시키다, \n다 써버리다, 비우다
voca.explains: To deplete a stock or amount of something means to reduce it.\n

voca.title: deposit
voca.means:
[디^퐈짓]
(지불할 돈의 일부로 처음에 내는) 착수금, 보증금
집세/전세 보증금
(은행) 예금/예치금
(광물) 매장층, 광상, 침전물
(특정한 곳에) 두다, 놓다
(서서히) 침전시키다
예금/예치하다
보증금/착수금/공탁금을 내다
voca.explains:
payment / premium / subscription / repayment / deposit / instalment
A deposit is a sum of money which is part of the full price of something, and which you pay when you agree to buy it.
A deposit is a sum of money which you pay when you start renting something. The money is returned to you if you do not damage what you have rented.
A deposit is a sum of money which is in a bank account or savings account, especially a sum which will be left there for some time.
A deposit is a sum of money which you have to pay if you want to be a candidate in a parliamentary or European election. The money is returned to you if you receive more than a certain percentage of the votes.
A deposit is an amount of a substance that has been left somewhere as a result of a chemical or geological process.
To deposit someone or something somewhere means to put them or leave them there.
If you deposit something somewhere, you put it where it will be safe until it is needed again.
If you deposit a sum of money, you pay it into a bank account or savings account.

voca.title: deprecate
voca.explains: If you deprecate something, you criticize it.\n

voca.title: deprecated
voca.means: 중요도가 떨어져 더 이상 사용되지 않고 앞으로는 사라지게 될 (컴퓨터 시스템 기능 등)

voca.title: depress
voca.means:
[디p뤠s]
우울하게하다, 하락시키다
(사업, 거래 등을) 부진하게 만들다, 침체시키다
(물가, 임금을)  떨어뜨리다, 하락시키다
voca.explains: If someone or something depresses you, they make you feel sad and disappointed.\nIf something depresses prices, wages, or figures, it causes them to become less.\n

voca.title: deprivation
voca.explains: If you suffer deprivation, you do not have or are prevented from having something that you want or need.\n

voca.title: depth
voca.means:
[^뎁p]
(위 표면에서 아래쪽 바닥까지의) 깊이
(감정의) 깊이
(지식, 이해력 등의) 깊이, 심도
(빛깔의) 농도
깊이, 입체감
voca.explains:
The depth of something such as a river or hole is the distance downwards from its top surface, or between its upper and lower surfaces.
The depth of something such as a cupboard or drawer is the distance between its front surface and its back.
If an emotion is very strongly or intensely felt, you can talk about its depth.
The depth of a situation is its extent and seriousness.
The depth of someone's knowledge is the great amount that they know.
If you say that someone or something has depth, you mean that they have serious and interesting qualities which are not immediately obvious and which you have to think about carefully before you can fully understand them.
The depths are places that are a long way below the surface of the sea or earth.
If you talk about the depths of an area, you mean the parts of it which are very far from the edge.
If you are in the depths of an unpleasant emotion, you feel that emotion very strongly.
If something happens in the depths of a difficult or unpleasant period of time, it happens in the middle and most severe or intense part of it.
If you deal with a subject in depth, you deal with it very thoroughly and consider all the aspects of it.
If you say that someone is out of their depth, you mean that they are in a situation that is much too difficult for them to be able to cope with it.

voca.title: derby
voca.means: [^더r-비]\n(동일 지역 내의 스포츠팀들끼리 하는) 시합, 경기\n경주, 경마 (대회)
voca.explains: A derby is a sporting event involving teams from the same area or city.\nA derby is a sports competition or race where there are no restrictions or limits on who can enter.\n

voca.title: dermatologist
voca.explains: A dermatologist is a doctor who specializes in the study of skin and the treatment of skin diseases.\nDermatologists label my skin type as combination as opposed to dry or oily. It’s a nightmare. I break out in the t-zone but can’t use harsh acne medication because it will result in dry, flaky skin.\n

voca.title: descend
voca.explains:
If you descend or if you descend a staircase, you move downwards from a higher to a lower level.
When a mood or atmosphere descends on a place or on the people there, it affects them by spreading among them.
If a large group of people arrive to see you, especially if their visit is unexpected or causes you a lot of work, you can say that they have descended on you.
When night, dusk, or darkness descends, it starts to get dark.

voca.title: descend into something
voca.explains: to get into a very bad condition or state\n

voca.title: descendant
voca.explains:
Someone's descendants are the people in later generations who are related to them.
Something modern which developed from an older thing can be called a descendant of it.
These tough, fast horses were descendants of run away Spanish horses.

voca.title: describe
voca.explains: If you describe a person, object, event, or situation, you say what they are like or what happened.\nIf a person describes someone or something as a particular thing, he or she believes that they are that thing and says so.\n

voca.title: desert
voca.means:
[^데저rt]
사막, 황무지, 황야
(도와주거나 부양하지 않고) 버리다, 유기하다, 
비우다, 포기하다
voca.explains:
A desert is a large area of land, usually in a hot region, where there is almost no water, rain, trees, or plants.
If people or animals desert a place, they leave it and it becomes empty
If someone deserts you, they go away and leave you, and no longer help or support you.
If you desert something that you support, use, or are involved with, you stop supporting it, using it, or being involved with it.
If a quality or skill that you normally have deserts you, you suddenly find that you do not have it when you need it or want it.
If someone deserts, or deserts a job, especially a job in the armed forces, they leave that job without permission.
"Arthur, stop! Listen, I would never desert you. I’m no rat leaving a sinking ship. Why, even if you went to jail, I would write you. I would come visit. Well, you know..."

voca.title: deserve
voca.means:
[디^져r-v]
~을 받을만 하다, 
~할만한 가치가 있다
~을 해야 마땅하다
voca.explains:
If you say that a person or thing deserves something, you mean that they should have it or receive it because of their actions or qualities.
If you say that someone got what they deserved, you mean that they deserved the bad thing that happened to them, and you have no sympathy for them.
You've worked so hard, you deserve a breather.
"A great practice deserves ice cream!" said the coach. He went off to see about getting some tables pushed together.

voca.title: design
voca.means:
[디^쟈-인]
(건물, 책, 기계 등의) 디자인(된 형태)
디자인(술), 설계(법)
설계도, 도안
무늬, 계획, 의도
(상품, 건축물 등을) 디자인.설계/도안하다
(체제, 방법 등을) 설계하다
(특정한 목적, 용도를 위해) 만들다, 고안하다
voca.explains:
When someone designs a garment, building, machine, or other object, they plan it and make a detailed drawing of it from which it can be built or made.
When someone designs a survey, policy, or system, they plan and prepare it, and decide on all the details of it.
If something is designed for a particular purpose, it is intended for that purpose.
Design is the process and art of planning and making detailed drawings of something.
The design of something is the way in which it has been planned and made.
A design is a drawing which someone produces to show how they would like something to be built or made.
A design is a pattern of lines, flowers, or shapes which is used to decorate something.
A design is a general plan or intention that someone has in their mind when they are doing something.
If something happens or is done by design, someone does it deliberately, rather than by accident.
If someone has designs on something, they want it and are planning to get it, often in a dishonest way.

voca.title: designate
voca.means:
[^데지g네잇t]
지정/지적 하다, 
(특정한 자리나 직책에) 지명하다
(특정한 기호 등을 써서) 표기/표시 하다
voca.explains:
When you designate someone or something as a particular thing, you formally give them that description or name.
If something is designated for a particular purpose, it is set aside for that purpose.
When you designate someone as something, you formally choose them to do that particular job.
Designate is used to describe someone who has been formally chosen to do a particular job, but has not yet started doing it.
In 1863, President Abraham Lincoln designated the last Thursday in November as a national day of Thanksgiving.

voca.title: designated
voca.explains: corresponding to truth in a two-valued logic, or having one of the analogous values in a many-valued logic\n

voca.title: designated area
voca.explains: People go tenting there, and have barbecues in designated areas. It's a great place to enjoy the breeze and a fun place to go people-watching.\n

voca.title: designated driver
voca.means: 지명 운전자(함께 파티나 바 등에 가면서 나중에 운전을 하기 위해 술을 마시지 않기로 한 사람)
voca.explains: The designated driver in a group of people travelling together is the one who has agreed to drive, or who is insured to drive.\n

voca.title: desirable
voca.means:
[디^자이러붤]
바람직한, 호감가는, 가치있는,
성적 매력이 있는, 섹시한
바람직한 사람, 훌륭한 사람
voca.explains: Something that is desirable is worth having or doing because it is useful, necessary, or popular.\nSomeone who is desirable is considered to be sexually attractive.\n

voca.title: desire
voca.explains:
A desire is a strong wish to do or have something.
Desire for someone is a strong feeling of wanting to have sex with them.
If you desire something, you want it.
He knows you both have a great desire to fight for the good.

voca.title: desk
voca.means:
[^데sk]
책상
(공항, 호텔 등의) 프런트, 접수처
(신문사, 방송국 등에서 특정한 주제를 다루는) 데스크
voca.explains:
A desk is a table, often with drawers, which you sit at to write or work.
The place in a hotel, hospital, airport, or other building where you check in or obtain information is referred to as a particular desk.
A particular department of a broadcasting company, or of a newspaper or magazine company, can be referred to as a particular desk.

voca.title: desk jockey
voca.explains: For ordinary desk jockeys, a planner is a must-have. On most workdays, I keep a small planner with me at all times. It’s useful to me in many ways. I use it to draft to-do lists. When I attend a meeting, I jot down important notes.\n

voca.title: desperate
voca.means:
[^데s퍼럿]
자포자기한, 될 대로 되라는 식으로
(다른 모든 것이 실패한 뒤 시도하는)필사적인, 
간절히 필요로 하는
절실한, 절박한, 절망적인, 극도의
voca.explains:
If you are desperate, you are in such a bad situation that you are willing to try anything to change it.
If you are desperate for something or desperate to do something, you want or need it very much indeed.
A desperate situation is very difficult, serious, or dangerous.
Desperate times call for desperate measures.

voca.title: desperately
voca.explains: When he came up, he plunged forward, desperately trying to get to shore.\nHe wished desperately that he still had the Diamond of Destiny to give him strength and courage.\n

voca.title: despite
voca.explains:
You use despite to introduce a fact which makes the other part of the sentence surprising.
If you do something despite yourself you do it although you did not really intend or expect to.
Despite all the positive reviews, the movie was a let-down.
Despite his illness, his recovery had a silver lining.

voca.title: despite one's best efforts
voca.explains: Just last week, I did the laundry. I put some sweaters in the washing machine. I made sure to use the gentle cycle. Despite my best efforts, the sweaters were ruined. They had shrunk beyond recognition. Next time, I will just entrust everything to the laundromat.\n

voca.title: dessert
voca.explains: Dessert is something sweet, such as fruit or a pudding, that you eat at the end of a meal.\n

voca.title: destabilize
voca.explains: To destabilize something such as a country or government means to create a situation which reduces its power or influence\n

voca.title: destination
voca.explains: The destination of someone or something is the place to which they are going or being sent.\nUsers enter their location and destination into the app. They can even select the level of service they want. Then, a nearby driver is dispatched.\n

voca.title: destined
voca.explains: If something is destined to happen or if someone is destined to behave in a particular way, that thing seems certain to happen or be done.\nIf someone is destined for a particular place, or if goods are destined for a particular place, they are travelling towards that place or will be sent to that place.\n

voca.title: destiny
voca.explains:
luck / chance / coincidence / accident / fortune / fate / destiny / providence
A person's destiny is everything that happens to them during their life, including what will happen in the future, especially when it is considered to be controlled by someone or something else.
Destiny is the force which some people believe controls the things that happen to you in your life.

voca.title: destroy
voca.means: [디st^로-이]\n파괴하다, 회손시키다\n(아프거나 원치 않는 동물을) 죽이다, 살처분하다
voca.explains:
To destroy something means to cause so much damage to it that it is completely ruined or does not exist any more.
To destroy someone means to ruin their life or to make their situation impossible to bear.
If an animal is destroyed, it is killed, either because it is ill or because it is dangerous.

voca.title: destruction
voca.explains: Destruction is the act of destroying something, or the state of being destroyed.\n

voca.title: destructive
voca.explains: Something that is destructive causes or is capable of causing great damage, harm, or injury.\n

voca.title: detach
voca.means:
[디^텟취]
(더 큰 것에서) 떼다, 분리하다, 분리되다
(~에서) 몸을 떼어내다/떠나다
(군인 등을) 파견하다
voca.explains: If you detach one thing from another that it is fixed to, you remove it. If one thing detaches from another, it becomes separated from it.\nIf you detach yourself from something, you become less involved in it or less concerned about it than you used to be.\n

voca.title: detail
voca.means:
[^디테일]
~을 자세히 말하다, 상세히 말하다, 열거하다,
파견하다, 특별 임무를 부여하다
(작고 덜 중요한) 세부 사항
세부, 상세, 자세한 정보
voca.explains:
The details of something are its individual features or elements.
Details about someone or something are facts or pieces of information about them.
A detail is a minor point or aspect of something, as opposed to the central ones.
If you detail things, you list them or give information about them.

voca.title: detect
voca.means: [디^텍t]\n(특히 알아내기 쉽지 않은 것을) \n발견하다, 알아내다, 감지하다
voca.explains:
notice / note / detect / observe / witness / perceive
To detect something means to find it or discover that it is present somewhere by using equipment or making an investigation.
If you detect something, you notice it or sense it, even though it is not very obvious.
Christina: Do I detect some hostility?
Bluetooth is also an easy way to manage PC peripherals such as a mouse or a keyboard. Best of all, it’s all automatic. Once a device has been paired, it detects and connects on its own.

voca.title: detect signal
voca.explains:
I recently got lost when my GPS didn't work. The system couldn't detect a signal. I became disoriented.
I can't detect a signal on my phone here.

Your dignity is the sense that you have of your own importance and value, and other people's respect for you.

voca.title: digs
voca.explains: lodgings\nStudio rooms are easy on the wallet. They have adequate space for two people. As a result, they are becoming increasingly common. Most people would like luxurious digs, but studio apartments are a good starting point.\n

voca.title: diligent
voca.explains: Someone who is diligent works hard in a careful and thorough way.\n

voca.title: diligently
voca.explains: I think I have a very unique personality. My best trait is that I have a strong sense of purpose. If I set a goal, I work diligently.\n

voca.title: dim
voca.means:
[^딤]
(빛이) 어둑한, 흐릿한, 
(형채가) 흐릿한
어둑하게 하다, 어둑해지다, 희미해지다
어둑한, 희미한, 흐릿한, 어렴풋한
voca.explains:
Dim light is not bright.
A dim place is rather dark because there is not much light in it.
A dim figure or object is not very easy to see, either because it is in shadow or darkness, or because it is far away.
If you have a dim memory or understanding of something, it is difficult to remember or is unclear in your mind.
If the future of something is dim, you have no reason to feel hopeful or positive about it.
If your future, hopes, or emotions dim or if something dims them, they become less good or less strong.
If you dim a light or if it dims, it becomes less bright.
In the dim light, Jack saw a tiny mouse.

voca.title: dim view
voca.explains: The officer looked at her notes. "Someone thought a cat was being tortured. We take a pretty dim view of that around here. Do you have a cat?"\n

voca.title: dime
voca.explains: A dime is an American coin worth ten cents.\n

voca.title: dime a dozen
voca.explains:
So common as to be practically worthless.
Single person households are a dime a dozen in Korea. Often, it doesn’t make sense for them to live in large apartments. 
Nowadays, smartphones are a dime a dozen.
Bad TV shows are a dime a dozen.

voca.title: dimension
voca.means:
[디^멘션]
(공간의) 크기, (높이, 넓이, 길이의) 치수, 
(상황의) 규모, 범위
규모, 범위, 차원
voca.explains:
A particular dimension of something is a particular aspect of it.
If you talk about the dimensions of a situation or problem, you are talking about its extent and size.
A dimension is a measurement such as length, width, or height. If you talk about the dimensions of an object or place, you are referring to its size and proportions.

voca.title: dimly
voca.explains: A pair of torched dimly lit the drafty entrance hall of the castle.\n

voca.title: dimmer
voca.explains: A dimmer or a dimmer switch is a switch that allows you to gradually change the brightness of an electric light.\n

voca.title: dimple
voca.explains: A dimple is a small hollow in someone's cheek or chin, often one that you can see when they smile.\n

voca.title: dine
voca.explains: When you dine, you have dinner.\nI recently went to a restaurant to wine and dine my wife for our anniversary. The food was top notch. However, the bad service was a problem.\n

voca.title: dinner
voca.explains:
Dinner is the main meal of the day, usually served in the early part of the evening.
Any meal you eat in the middle of the day can be referred to as dinner.
A dinner is a formal social event at which a meal is served. It is held in the evening.

voca.title: dinosaur
voca.explains: Dinosaurs were large reptiles which lived in prehistoric times.\nIf you refer to an organization as a dinosaur, you mean that it is large, inefficient, and out of date.\n

voca.title: dip
voca.means:
[^딥]
(액체에) 살짝 담그다/적시다, (아래로) 내려가다
하락, 감소, (도로 등의) 움푹 페인 부분
(음식을 먹기 전에 살짝 적시는) 소스
voca.explains:
If you dip something in a liquid, you put it into the liquid for a short time, so that only part of it is covered, and take it out again.
If you dip your hand into a container or dip into the container, you put your hand into it in order to take something out of it.
If something dips, it makes a downward movement, usually quite quickly.
If an area of land, a road, or a path dips, it goes down quite suddenly to a lower level.
A dip is a thick creamy sauce. You dip pieces of raw vegetable or biscuits into the sauce and then eat them.

voca.title: dip down
voca.explains: He said the thermometer will dip down to 10 degrees.\n

voca.title: dip one's toe(s) in/into
voca.explains: Dipping your toe into python\n

voca.title: diploma
voca.explains: A diploma is a qualification which may be awarded to a student by a university or college, or by a high school in the United States.\n

voca.title: diplomacy
voca.explains: Diplomacy is the activity or profession of managing relations between the governments of different countries.\nDiplomacy is the skill of being careful to say or do things which will not offend people.\n

voca.title: dipping sauce
voca.explains:
It's typical to use fermented shrimp as dipping sauce.
I ordered some dipping sauce with the pizza.
I asked the server for more dipping sauce.

voca.title: dire
voca.means: [^다이어r]\n대단히 심각한, 엄청난, 지독한,\n무서운 긴급한, 극심한, 끔직한
voca.explains: Dire is used to emphasize how serious or terrible a situation or event is.\nIf you describe something as dire, you are emphasizing that it is of very low quality.\n

voca.title: direct
voca.means:
[뒤^뤡t]
(중간에 제삼자나 매개물이 없이) 직접적인,
직행의
지시하다, ~로 향하다, 겨냥하다, 
감독하다, 지휘하다, 총괄하다
똑바로, 직접의, 솔직한, 정확한, 
딱 부러지는, 단도직입적인
직행으로, 똑바로
voca.explains:
honest / frank / direct / open / outspoken / straight / blunt
Direct means moving towards a place or object, without changing direction and without stopping, for example in a journey.
If something is in direct heat or light, it is strongly affected by the heat or light, because there is nothing between it and the source of heat or light to protect it.
You use direct to describe an experience, activity, or system which only involves the people, actions, or things that are necessary to make it happen.
If you direct something at a particular thing, you aim or point it at that thing.
If you describe a person or their behaviour as direct, you mean that they are honest and open, and say exactly what they mean.
When someone directs a project or a group of people, they are responsible for organizing the people and activities that are involved.

voca.title: direction
voca.means:
[더^뤡션]
(위치, 이동의) 방향, 지시, 목적, 목표
지시, 명령, 지휘, 통솔
(영화의) 감독
voca.explains:
A direction is the general line that someone or something is moving or pointing in.
A direction is the general way in which something develops or progresses.
Directions are instructions that tell you what to do, how to do something, or how to get somewhere.
The direction of a film, play, or television programme is the work that the director does while it is being made.
B : Hello, my name is James Park. Could you give me directions to your hotel?

voca.title: directive
voca.explains: A directive is an official instruction that is given by someone in authority.\n

voca.title: directly
voca.means:
[뒤^뤡t뤼]
곧장, 직접적으로, 
곧바로, 즉시, 곧
(특정한 위치) 발 ~ 에, 
~하자마자 바로
voca.explains:
If something is directly above, below, or in front of something, it is in exactly that position.
If you do one action directly after another, you do the second action as soon as the first one is finished.
If something happens directly, it happens without any delay.

voca.title: directory
voca.means:
[듸^뤡더뤼]
명단, 목록, 
지도서, 예배 규칙서, 안내책자
지휘하는, 지도/지시 적인
(컴퓨터의) 디렉토리
voca.explains: A directory is a book which gives lists of facts, for example people's names, addresses, and telephone numbers, or the names and addresses of business companies, usually arranged in alphabetical order.\nA directory is an area of a computer disk which contains one or more files or other directories.\n

voca.title: dirt
voca.means: [더r-t]\n먼지, 때, 흙\n(사람의 평판을 해칠 수 있는) 좋지않은 정보
voca.explains:
soil / mud / clay / land / earth / dirt / ground
If there is dirt on something, there is dust, mud, or a stain on it.
A dirt road or track is made from hard earth. A dirt floor is made from earth without any cement, stone, or wood laid on it.
Annie stuck another stick into the dirt.
If someone dishes the dirt on you, they say bad things about you, without worrying if they are true or not, or if they will damage your reputation.
If you say that someone treats you like dirt, you are angry with them because you think that they treat you unfairly and with no respect.

voca.title: dirt road
voca.explains: an unsealed country road\n

voca.title: dirty
voca.means:
[^더r-리]
더러운, 지저분한
추잡한, 더러운
정직하지 못한, 비열한
~을 더럽히다
비열하게, 치사하게
voca.explains:
dirty / dusty / filthy / soiled / grubby
If something is dirty, it is marked or covered with stains, spots, or mud, and needs to be cleaned.
If you describe an action as dirty, you disapprove of it and consider it unfair, immoral, or dishonest.
If you describe something such as a joke, a book, or someone's language as dirty, you mean that it refers to sex in a way that some people find offensive.
Dirty is used before words of criticism to emphasize that you do not approve of someone or something.
To dirty something means to cause it to become dirty.
If you say that someone washes their dirty linen in public, you disapprove of their discussing or arguing about unpleasant or private things in front of other people. There are several other forms of this expression, for example wash your dirty laundry in public, or in American English, air your dirty laundry in public.
If someone gives you a dirty look, they look at you in a way which shows that they are angry with you.
Dirty old man is an expression some people use to describe an older man who they think shows an unnatural interest in sex.
To do someone's dirty work means to do a task for them that is dishonest or unpleasant and which they do not want to do themselves.

voca.title: disability
voca.explains: A disability is a permanent injury, illness, or physical or mental condition that tends to restrict the way that someone can live their life.\nDisability is the state of being disabled.\n

voca.title: disable
voca.means:
[딧^쎄이벌]
(신체에) 장애를 입히다, 장애자로 만들다
~을 무능하게 하다
망가뜨리다
voca.explains: If an injury or illness disables someone, it affects them so badly that it restricts the way that they can live their life.\nIf someone or something disables a system or mechanism, they stop it working, usually temporarily.\n

voca.title: disabled
voca.explains: disabled / handicapped\nSomeone who is disabled has an illness, injury, or condition that tends to restrict the way that they can live their life, especially by making it difficult for them to move about.\n

voca.title: disadvantage
voca.means: [딧서d^벤뒤지]\n불리한 점, 약점, 난점\n(사람을) 불리하게 하다; ~에게 손해 입히다
voca.explains:
A disadvantage is a factor which makes someone or something less useful, acceptable, or successful than other people or things.
If you are at a disadvantage, you have a problem or difficulty that many other people do not have, which makes it harder for you to be successful.
If something is to your disadvantage or works to your disadvantage, it creates difficulties for you.

voca.title: disagree
voca.means:
[^딧써g뤼-]
동의하지 않는다, 일치하지 않다
의견이 다르다
(진술, 보고서 들이) 내용이 다르다/일치하지 않는다
voca.explains: If you disagree with someone or disagree with what they say, you do not accept that what they say is true or correct. You can also say that two people disagree.\nIf you disagree with a particular action or proposal, you disapprove of it and believe that it is wrong.\n

voca.title: disagreement
voca.means:
[딧어g^뤼-먼t]
의견 충돌/차이, 다툼, 논쟁
(같아야 할 두 가지 사이의) 불일치, 차이
(체질에) 안 맞음, 부적합
voca.explains: Disagreement means objecting to something such as a proposal.\nWhen there is disagreement about something, people disagree or argue about what should be done.\n

voca.title: disappear
voca.means:
[디써^피어r]
(눈앞에서) 사라지다, 보이지 않게 되다
(존재하던 것이) 사라지다, 없어지다
실종되다, 없어지다
voca.explains:
If you say that someone or something disappears, you mean that you can no longer see them, usually because you or they have changed position.
If someone or something disappears, they go away or are taken away somewhere where nobody can find them.
If something disappears, it stops existing or happening.

voca.title: disappearance
voca.explains:
If you refer to someone's disappearance, you are referring to the fact that nobody knows where they have gone.
If you refer to the disappearance of an object, you are referring to the fact that it has been lost or stolen.
The disappearance of a type of thing, person, or animal is a process in which it becomes less common and finally no longer exists.

voca.title: disappoint
voca.means: [디s어^포인t]\n실망시키다, 실망을 안겨 주다\n(바라던 일을) 좌절 시키다, 망치다
voca.explains: If things or people disappoint you, they are not as good as you had hoped, or do not do what you hoped they would do.\n"We're very disappointed in you." said her father. "And I'm disappointed in you, too." Muffy's mother said to her husband.\n

voca.title: disappointment
voca.explains: Disappointment is the state of feeling disappointed.\nSomething or someone that is a disappointment is not as good as you had hoped.\n

voca.title: disapproval
voca.explains: If you feel or show disapproval of something or someone, you feel or show that you do not approve of them.\n

voca.title: disapprove
voca.means: [디써p^루-v]\n탐탁찮아 하다, 못마땅해 하다, 반대하다\n~을 승인/인가/찬성하지 않다, 불만을 나타내다
voca.explains: If you disapprove of something or someone, you feel or show that you do not like them or do not approve of them.\n

voca.title: disassemble
voca.explains: To disassemble something means to take it to pieces.\n

voca.title: disaster
voca.explains:
A disaster is a very bad accident such as an earthquake or a plane crash, especially one in which a lot of people are killed.
If you refer to something as a disaster, you are emphasizing that you think it is extremely bad or unacceptable.
Disaster is something which has very bad consequences for you.

voca.title: disband
voca.explains: If someone disbands a group of people, or if the group disbands, it stops operating as a single unit.\n"I will disband PAWS on one condition." said Mr. Crosswire. Everyone fell silent.\n

voca.title: disbelief
voca.explains: Disbelief is not believing that something is true or real.\nThe kids were stunned. They let out a shriek of disbelief.\n

voca.title: discard
voca.means: [디s카rd]\n(불필요한 것을) 버리다, 포기/폐기하다, 제거하다\n버리기, 포기, 버려진 것
voca.explains: If you discard something, you get rid of it because you no longer want it or need it.\n

voca.title: discharge
voca.means:
[디s^촤r-쥐]
 (어떤 장소나 직무에서) 떠나는 것을 허락하다
제대하다, 방출/해고하다, 퇴원하다
(에너지를) 방출하다, 발사/발포하다
(임무 등을) 이행하다
짐부리기, 방출, 해방, 퇴원, 수행, 이행
voca.explains:
When someone is discharged from hospital, prison, or one of the armed services, they are officially allowed to leave, or told that they must leave.
If someone discharges their duties or responsibilities, they do everything that needs to be done in order to complete them.
If someone discharges a debt, they pay it.
If something is discharged from inside a place, it comes out.
When there is a discharge of a substance, the substance comes out from inside somewhere.

voca.title: discipline
voca.means:
[^디써플뤤]
훈련, 훈육, 징계, 규율, 기강, 절제력
단련법, 수련법
징계하다, 훈육하다, 스스로(심신을) 단련하다
voca.explains:
Discipline is the practice of making people obey rules or standards of behaviour, and punishing them when they do not.
Discipline is the quality of being able to behave and work in a controlled way which involves obeying particular rules or standards.
A discipline is a particular area of study, especially a subject of study in a college or university.
If someone is disciplined for something that they have done wrong, they are punished for it.
If you discipline yourself to do something, you train yourself to behave and work in a strictly controlled and regular way.

voca.title: discomfort
voca.means:
[디s컴퍼rt]
(신체적으로) 불편/가벼운 통증, 불안, 불쾌, 고생
불편하게 하는 것
(마음을) 불편하게 하다
voca.explains:
Discomfort is a painful feeling in part of your body when you have been hurt slightly or when you have been uncomfortable for a long time.
Discomfort is a feeling of worry caused by shame or embarrassment.
Discomforts are conditions which cause you to feel physically uncomfortable.

voca.title: disconnect
voca.means:
[디s커넥t]
(어떤 장치의 가수, 수도, 전기) 연결/접속을 끊다, 
(수도, 가스, 전기의) 공급을 끊다, 
~과 연락을 끊다, ~을 분리하다
voca.explains:
To disconnect a piece of equipment means to separate it from its source of power or to break a connection that it needs in order to work.
If you are disconnected by a gas, electricity, water, or telephone company, they turn off the connection to your house, usually because you have not paid the bill.
If you disconnect something from something else, you separate the two things.

voca.title: discount
voca.explains:
A discount is a reduction in the usual price of something.
If a shop or company discounts an amount or percentage from something that they are selling, they take the amount or percentage off the usual price.
If you discount an idea, fact, or theory, you consider that it is not true, not important, or not relevant.
Also, most coffee shop offer a discount for using a tumbler. When you drink coffee as much as I do, the saving add up.

voca.title: discourage
voca.means: [디s^껄릐지]\n(무엇을 어렵게 만들거나 반대하여) 막다, 말리다, \n의욕/열의를 껃다, 좌절시키다
voca.explains: If someone or something discourages you, they cause you to lose your enthusiasm about your actions.\nTo discourage an action or to discourage someone from doing it means to make them not want to do it.\n

voca.title: discover
voca.explains:
If you discover something that you did not know about before, you become aware of it or learn of it.
If a person or thing is discovered, someone finds them, either by accident or because they have been looking for them.
When someone discovers a new place, substance, scientific fact, or scientific technique, they are the first person to find it or become aware of it.
If you say that someone has discovered a particular activity or subject, you mean that they have tried doing it or studying it for the first time and that they enjoyed it.
When a actor, musician, or other performer who is not well-known is discovered, someone recognizes that they have talent and helps them in their career.
I discovered my favorite hotel by chance. It’s not a ritzy or high-end place. Other hotels are more luxurious. But my favorite place strikes the perfect balance between price, service and amenities.

voca.title: discreet
voca.explains:
If you are discreet, you are polite and careful in what you do or say, because you want to avoid embarrassing or offending someone.
If you are discreet about something you are doing, you do not tell other people about it, in order to avoid being embarrassed or to gain an advantage.
If you describe something as discreet, you approve of it because it is small in size or degree, or not easily noticed.
The best part about my personality is that I can make friends with almost anyone. I like to lend a helping hand. I am always read to strike up a conversation. Also, I am discreet.

voca.title: discus
voca.explains: A discus is a heavy circular object which athletes try to throw as far as they can as a sport.\nThe discus is the sport of throwing a discus.\n

voca.title: discuss
voca.explains:
talk / discuss / speak / communicate
If people discuss something, they talk about it, often in order to reach a decision.
If you discuss something, you write or talk about it in detail.
I soaked up advice like a sponge. I tried things that bank employees recommended. I discussed the ins and outs of the market with my friends. I also did my homework, reading books and taking online classes.

voca.title: discussion
voca.means: [디s꺼션]\n토론, 논의, 토의, 평의, 심의, 검토, 해설, 논문
voca.explains:
discussion / conversation / dialogue / talk / consultation / chat / gossip
If there is discussion about something, people talk about it, often in order to reach a decision.
A discussion of a subject is a piece of writing or a lecture in which someone talks about it in detail.
A discussion document or paper is one that contains information and usually proposals for people to discuss.

voca.title: disease
voca.explains: disease / illness / disorder / infection / condition / ailment / bug\nA disease is an illness which affects people, animals, or plants, for example one which is caused by bacteria or infection.\n

voca.title: disembark
voca.explains: When passengers disembark from a ship, aeroplane, or bus, they leave it at the end of their journey.\n

voca.title: disembarkation card
voca.explains: A : Your passport and disembarkation card, please.\n

voca.title: disgrace
voca.explains:
If you say that someone is in disgrace, you are emphasizing that other people disapprove of them and do not respect them because of something that they have done.
If you say that something is a disgrace, you are emphasizing that it is very bad or wrong, and that you find it completely unacceptable.
You say that someone is a disgrace to someone else when you want to emphasize that their behaviour causes the other person to feel ashamed.
If you say that someone disgraces someone else, you are emphasizing that their behaviour causes the other person to feel ashamed.
I would rather die than live in disgrace.

voca.title: disguise
voca.means:
[디s^가이z]
변장/위장하다, 가장하다, 숨기다
(사실을) 숨기다, (의도, 감정을) 속이다, 감추다
변장/가장 (도구), 변장술
voca.explains:
hide / conceal / cover / disguise / mask / camouflage
If you are in disguise, you are not wearing your usual clothes or you have altered your appearance in other ways, so that people will not recognize you.
If you disguise yourself, you put on clothes which make you look like someone else or alter your appearance in other ways, so that people will not recognize you.
To disguise something means to hide it or make it appear different so that people will not know about it or will not recognize it.

voca.title: disgusting
voca.explains:
disgusting / revolting / foul / repulsive / offensive / gross / nauseating
If you say that something is disgusting, you are criticizing it because it is extremely unpleasant.
If you say that something is disgusting, you mean that you find it completely unacceptable.

voca.title: dish
voca.explains:
A dish is a shallow container with a wide uncovered top. You eat and serve food from dishes and cook food in them.
The contents of a dish can be referred to as a dish of something.
Food that is prepared in a particular style or combination can be referred to as a dish.
All the objects that have been used to cook, serve, and eat a meal can be referred to as the dishes.
You can use dish to refer to anything that is round and hollow in shape with a wide uncovered top.
The ingredients were turned into a delicious dish.

voca.title: dish it out
voca.explains: to criticize somebody or attack them\n

voca.title: dish something out
voca.means: (흔히 많은 사람들에게 또는 많은 양을) 주다\n(식사때 음식을) 담아주다
voca.explains: to give something out to large numbers of people or in large amounts\nto serve food to somebody by putting it on plates\n

voca.title: dish up
voca.explains: to serve food by putting it on plates\n

voca.title: dish up something
voca.explains: to present or offer something to somebody, usually something not very good\n

voca.title: dishes made from
voca.explains: Dishes made from pig and cow intestines, or gopchang, are popular Korean delicacies.\n

voca.title: dishonest
voca.explains: If you say that a person or their behaviour is dishonest, you mean that they are not truthful or honest and that you cannot trust them.\n

voca.title: dishwasher
voca.explains: A dishwasher is an electrically operated machine that washes and dries plates, saucepans, and cutlery.\nAnother very convenient appliance is the dishwasher. Doing the dishes is my least favorite chore. Thanks to this appliance, I don't need to worry about it.\n

voca.title: disignated
voca.explains: (of a truth value) corresponding to truth in a two-valued logic, or having one of the analogous values in a many-valued logic\n

voca.title: disincentive
voca.explains: A disincentive is something which discourages people from behaving or acting in a particular way.\nWeddings can cost a fortune. Housing is expensive, too. The high childrearing costs are another disincentive to marriage.\n

voca.title: disinfect
voca.explains: If you disinfect something, you clean it using a substance that kills germs.\n

voca.title: disinfectant
voca.explains: Disinfectant is a substance that kills germs. It is used, for example, for cleaning kitchens and bathrooms.\n

voca.title: disinterest
voca.explains: If there is disinterest in something, people are not interested in it.\n

voca.title: dislike
voca.explains:
hate / dislike / can't stand / despise / can't bear / loathe / detest
If you dislike someone or something, you consider them to be unpleasant and do not like them.
Dislike is the feeling that you do not like someone or something.
Your dislikes are the things that you do not like.
If you take a dislike to someone or something, you decide that you do not like them.

voca.title: dismay
voca.means:
[디s^메이]
(충격을 받은 뒤의) 실망, 경악
경악, 당황, 의기소침, 실망, 낙담
크게 놀라게 하다, 당황하게 하다
voca.explains:
Dismay is a strong feeling of fear, worry, or sadness that is caused by something unpleasant and unexpected.
If you are dismayed by something, it makes you feel afraid, worried, or sad.
You can't imagine my dismay when you started to take off for dinosaur times.

voca.title: dismiss
voca.means:
[디s^밋s]
(고려할 가치가 없다고) 묵살/일축해 버리다, 
(생각, 느낌을) 떨쳐 버리다, 해고하다, 
(소송, 재판을) 기각하다, 
해고, 기각, 무시하다, 해산시키다
(군대/구령) 해산!
voca.explains:
If you dismiss something, you decide or say that it is not important enough for you to think about or consider.
If you dismiss something from your mind, you stop thinking about it.
When an employer dismisses an employee, the employer tells the employee that they are no longer needed to do the job that they have been doing.
If you are dismissed by someone in authority, they tell you that you can go away from them.
When a judge dismisses a case against someone, he or she formally states that there is no need for a trial, usually because there is not enough evidence for the case to continue.

voca.title: dismiss as
voca.explains: It's easy to dismiss this as a trifling matter.\nIt's easy to dismiss this as a cliche.\n

voca.title: dismissive
voca.explains: If you are dismissive of someone or something, you say or show that you think they are not important or have no value.\nSuperstitious people believe that broken glass is very unlucky. Some may scoff at such superstitions, but I am not so dismissive. Any custom that encourages caution is valuable in my book.\n

voca.title: dismount
voca.means: [디s^마운t]\n(말, 자전거) 내리다, 떼어내다\n말에서 내림, 하차, 떼내기
voca.explains: If you dismount from a horse or a bicycle, you get down from it.\n

voca.title: disorder
voca.means:
[디s오r더r]
엉망, 어수선함, 
(많은 사람들에 의한)난동, 무질서
(친체 기능의) 장애/이상
voca.explains:
disease / illness / disorder / infection / condition / ailment / bug
A disorder is a problem or illness which affects someone's mind or body.
Disorder is a state of being untidy, badly prepared, or badly organized.
Disorder is violence or rioting in publi

voca.title: disorganized
voca.means: [디s^오r거나이zd]\n무질서한, 통합이 안된, 지리멸렬한\n계획이 잘못된; (사람이) 체계적이지 못한
voca.explains: Something that is disorganized is in a confused state or is badly planned or managed.\nSomeone who is disorganized is very bad at organizing things in their life.\n

voca.title: disorient
voca.means:
[디s^오r-뤼언t]
~의 방향 감각을 혼란시키다
(낯선 상황에 처하게 하여) 갈피를 못 잡게 하다, 
어리둥절하게 하다
voca.explains: If something disorients you, you lose your sense of direction, or you generally feel lost and uncertain, for example because you are in an unfamiliar environment.\n

voca.title: disoriented
voca.explains: I recently got lost when my GPS didn’t work. The system couldn’t detect a signal. I became disoriented. I tried to follow the road signs.\n

voca.title: disparity
voca.explains: If there is a disparity between two or more things, there is a noticeable difference between them.\n

voca.title: dispatch
voca.means:
[디s^풰취]
(특별한 목적을 위해) 보내다, 파견하다
(편지, 소포, 메시지를) 보내다/발송하다
신속히 해치우다, 처리하다
파견, 특파, 신속한 처리, 배치
voca.explains:
If you dispatch someone to a place, you send them there for a particular reason.
If you dispatch a message, letter, or parcel, you send it to a particular person or destination.
To dispatch a person or an animal means to kill them.
A dispatch is a special report that is sent to a newspaper or broadcasting organization by a journalist who is in a different town or country.
A dispatch is a message or report that is sent, for example, by army officers or government officials to their headquarters.
We'll dispatch a squad car shortly

voca.title: dispense
voca.means:
[디s^뺀s]
나누어 주다, 내놓다
(특히 서비스를) 제공하다/베풀다
(약사가 약을) 조제하다
voca.explains:
If someone dispenses something that they own or control, they give or provide it to a number of people.
If you obtain a product by getting it out of a machine, you can say that the machine dispenses the product.
When a chemist dispenses medicine, he or she prepares it, and gives or sells it to the patient or customer.

voca.title: dispense with something
voca.explains: to get rid of something; to stop using somebody/something because they are/it is no longer necessary\n

voca.title: dispenser
voca.means: [디s^뻰서r]\n분배자, 집행자, 관리자, 자동판매기\n(손잡이, 단추 등을 눌러 안에 든 것을 바로 뽑아 쓸수 있는) 기계, 용기
voca.explains: A dispenser is a machine or container designed so that you can get an item or quantity of something from it in an easy and convenient way.\n

voca.title: disposable
voca.means: [디s^뽀우저블]\n사용 후 버리게 되어 있는, 일회용의\n처분할 수 있는, 쓰고 버릴 수 있는
voca.explains: A disposable product is designed to be thrown away after it has been used.\nYour disposable income is the amount of income you have left after you have paid income tax and social security charges.\n

voca.title: disposable cut
voca.explains:
I am a sucker for coffee. I almost always have a cup at hand. However, I don’t want to go through too many disposable cups. That’s way I use a tumbler.
Do you want a disposable cup, or a mug?
Please recycle the disposable cups.

voca.title: disposal
voca.means: [디s^뽀우졀]\n(무엇을 없애기 위한) 처리, 처분, 폐기\n(사업체, 부동산 등의) 처분
voca.explains: If you have something at your disposal, you are able to use it whenever you want, and for whatever purpose you want. If you say that you are at someone's disposal, you mean that you are willing to help them in any way you can.\nDisposal is the act of getting rid of something that is no longer wanted or needed.\n

voca.title: disposition
voca.means: [^디s퍼짓션]\n(타고난) 기질, 성격\n기질, 성질, 기분, 경향, 배치, 배열, 준비
voca.explains:
Someone's disposition is the way that they tend to behave or feel.
A disposition to do something is a willingness to do it.
If you refer to the disposition of a number of objects, you mean the pattern in which they are arranged or their positions in relation to each other.
The disposition of money or property is the act of giving or distributing it to a number of people.

voca.title: dispute
voca.means:
[디s쀼웃-t]
논쟁, 논의, 언쟁, 분쟁
토의/토론하다, 경쟁하다
반박하다, 이의를 제기하다, 
(무엇을 차지하기 위해) 다투다
voca.explains:
A dispute is an argument or disagreement between people or groups.
If you dispute a fact, statement, or theory, you say that it is incorrect or untrue.
When people dispute something, they fight for control or ownership of it. You can also say that one group of people dispute something with another group.

voca.title: distance
voca.means: [디s떤s]\n(공간상, 시간상 떨어진) 거리, 먼곳, 간격\n~에 관여/개입하지 않다,
voca.explains:
The distance between two points or places is the amount of space between them.
When you want to emphasize that two people or things do not have a close relationship or are not the same, you can refer to the distance between them.
Distance learning or distance education involves studying at home and sending your work to a college or university, rather than attending the college or university in person.
If you distance yourself from a person or thing, or if something distances you from them, you feel less friendly or positive towards them, or become less involved with them.

voca.title: distant
voca.means:
[^디s떤t]
먼, (멀리) 떨어져 있는,
멀리있는, 원격의, 냉담한
(~와) 동떨어진/다른
(사람에게) 거리를 두는, 다정하지 않은
다른 생각을 하는, 생각이 딴 데 가 있는
voca.explains:
Distant means very far away.
You use distant to describe a time or event that is very far away in the future or in the past.
A distant relative is one who you are not closely related to.
If you describe someone as distant, you mean that you find them cold and unfriendly.
If you describe someone as distant, you mean that they are not concentrating on what they are doing because they are thinking about other things.

voca.title: distinct
voca.explains:
If something is distinct from something else of the same type, it is different or separate from it.
If something is distinct, you can hear, see, or taste it clearly.
If an idea, thought, or intention is distinct, it is clear and definite.
You can use distinct to emphasize that something is great enough in amount or degree to be noticeable or important.
You can use several different methods to join distinct strings together.

voca.title: distinct advantage
voca.explains: First and foremost, I like the information I can glean. Shopping hosts courteously explain all there is to know about a product. This is a distinct advantage over other methods. Also, sometime home shopping offers bargain basement prices.\n

voca.title: distinct smell
voca.explains:
Pettitoes are a very popular dish in Korea. They are delicious, and are very addictive. Pettitoes have a distinct smell.
Most of the foods in Thailand have a distinct smell.
This flower has a distinct smell.

voca.title: distinction
voca.means:
[디s띵션]
(비슷하거나 관련있는 것들 사이의 뚜렷한) 차이/대조
뛰어남, 탁월함
구별, 차이, 차별, 우대, 훈장
voca.explains:
A distinction between similar things is a difference.
Distinction is the quality of being very good or better than other things of the same type.
A distinction is a special award or honour that is given to someone because of their very high level of achievement.
If you say that someone or something has the distinction of being something, you are drawing attention to the fact that they have the special quality of being that thing. Distinction is normally used to refer to good qualities, but can sometimes also be used to refer to bad qualities.

voca.title: distinctive
voca.explains: Something that is distinctive has a special quality or feature which makes it easily recognizable and different from other things of the same type.\n

voca.title: distinguish
voca.means:
[디s^팅궈쉬]
구별하다, 구분하다, 분간하다
(보거나 듣고) 식별하다, 알아보다
유명하게 되다
voca.explains:
identify / recognize / make out / discern / pick out / distinguish
If you can distinguish one thing from another or distinguish between two things, you can see or understand how they are different.
A feature or quality that distinguishes one thing from another causes the two things to be regarded as different, because only the first thing has the feature or quality.
If you can distinguish something, you can see, hear, or taste it although it is very difficult to detect.
If you distinguish yourself, you do something that makes you famous or important.

voca.title: distract
voca.means: [디st^뤡t]\n(정신이) 집중이 안되게 하다, 산만하게 하다\n(주의를) 딴데로 돌리다
voca.explains:
If something distracts you or your attention from something, it takes your attention away from it.
I'll distract the guards.
You're just copying word for word, you're not actually doing anything active with the material you're listening to. So, working with a computer-and I've seen this in my university-a lot of students also end up going on Facebook during the lesson or lecture. So, a lot of  the times they get very distracted. When they should be listening, they're actually not.
I like to keep my surroundings well-organized. Having too many things on my desk distracts me when I work. That’s why I adore Bluetooth. It eliminates the need for messy wires.
Nothing can distract her when she's concentrating.
Don't let anything distract you when you're driving.

voca.title: distracting
voca.explains: If you say that something is distracting, you mean that it makes it difficult for you to concentrate properly on what you are doing.\nB : I like to listen to music while I'm working, but nothing too distracting. I get really easily distracted.\n

voca.title: distraction
voca.means:
[디st^뤡션]
(주의) 집중을 방해하는 것, 머리를 식히게 해 주는 것
오락 (활동)
정신이 흩어짐, 주의 산만, 방심
voca.explains:
A distraction is something that turns your attention away from something you want to concentrate on.
A distraction is an activity which is intended to entertain and amuse you.
If you say that something or someone drives you to distraction, you are emphasizing that they annoy you a great deal.
Be wary of distractions when you study.

voca.title: distress
voca.means:
[디st뤠s]
(정신적) 고통, 괴로움
고충, 곤경, 조난(위험)
괴롭히다, 고통스럽게 하다
voca.explains:
Distress is a state of extreme sorrow, suffering, or pain.
Distress is the state of being in extreme danger and needing urgent help.
If someone or something distresses you, they cause you to be upset or worried.

voca.title: distribute
voca.means:
[^디st뤼뷰t]
(사람들에게) 나누어 주다, 분배하다,
~을 분배하다, 공급/유통하다
(상품을) 유통시키다
 (어느 범위에 걸쳐) 나누어 퍼뜨리다, 분포시키다
voca.explains:
If you distribute things, you hand them or deliver them to a number of people.
When a company distributes goods, it supplies them to the shops or businesses that sell them.
If you distribute things among the members of a group, you share them among those members.
To distribute a substance over something means to scatter it over it.

voca.title: distributed
voca.explains: If things are distributed throughout an area, object, or group, they exist throughout it.\n

voca.title: distribution
voca.means:
[^디st러뷰-션]
유통, 배급, 배포, 분배, 분포
나누어 줌, 배부, 배급
유통
voca.explains: The distribution of things involves giving or delivering them to a number of people or places.\nThe distribution of something is how much of it there is in each place or at each time, or how much of it each person has.\n

voca.title: district
voca.means: [^디s츄릑t]\n(특정한 특징이 있는)지구/구역\n(한 국가 내에서 공공 업무 편의상 나눠 놓은) 구역
voca.explains: A district is a particular area of a town or country.\nA district is an area of a town or country which has been given official boundaries for the purpose of administration.\n

voca.title: district office
voca.explains: I had no choice but to cancel all of the cards. I also had to visit the district office to get my ID re-issued. It was a big hassle.\n

voca.title: disturb
voca.means:
[디s^떠r-v]
(작업, 수면 등을) 방해하다, 
(재자리에 있는 것을) 건드리다/흩뜨리다
혼란시키다, 불안하게 하다
voca.explains:
If you disturb someone, you interrupt what they are doing and upset them.
If something disturbs you, it makes you feel upset or worried.
If something is disturbed, its position or shape is changed.
If something disturbs a situation or atmosphere, it spoils it or causes trouble.
I don't want to disturb her.
Jason: I'm sorry to disturb you, but may I use your cell phone for a real quick call, please?

voca.title: disturbance
voca.means:
[디s터r번s]
방해(물), 폐해, 어긋남, 
불안, 장애, 
(공공장소에서의) 소란, 소동
(심리적) 장애
voca.explains:
A disturbance is an incident in which people behave violently in public.
Disturbance means upsetting or disorganizing something which was previously in a calm and well-ordered state.
You can use disturbance to refer to a medical or psychological problem, when someone's body or mind is not working in the normal way.
The Pacific Tsunami Warning System alerts the public of earthquakes or other disturbances that take place at sea.

voca.title: disturbing
voca.explains: Something that is disturbing makes you feel worried or upset.\n

voca.title: ditch
voca.means:
[^딛취]
(들판, 도로가의) 배수로
(더 이상 원치 않거나 불필요한 것을) 버리다, 
(교제하던 사람을) 차 버리다
voca.explains:
A ditch is a long narrow channel cut into the ground at the side of a road or field.
If you ditch something that you have or are responsible for, you abandon it or get rid of it, because you no longer want it.
If someone ditches someone, they end a relationship with that person.
If a pilot ditches an aircraft or if it ditches, the pilot makes an emergency landing.

voca.title: ditch class
voca.explains: Let' s ditch school and go to the beach.\nHyejin: Okay, so I've ditched a few classes.\n

voca.title: dive
voca.means:
[다이-v]
(물속으로 거꾸로) 뛰어들다, 다이빙하다, 
잠수하다, 강하하다
다이빙, (물 속으로) 뛰어들기, 잠수
voca.explains:
If you dive into some water, you jump in head-first with your arms held straight above your head.
If you dive, you go under the surface of the sea or a lake, using special breathing equipment.
When birds and animals dive, they go quickly downwards, head-first, through the air or through water.
If an aeroplane dives, it flies or drops down quickly and suddenly.
If you dive in a particular direction or into a particular place, you jump or move there quickly.
If you dive into a bag or container, you put your hands into it quickly in order to get something out.
If shares, profits, or figures dive, their value falls suddenly and by a large amount.
Annie rose from a dive.

voca.title: dive in
voca.explains: to start doing something with enthusiasm and without stopping to think\nto start eating with enthusiasm\n

voca.title: dive into
voca.explains: to move your hand quickly into something such as a pocket or bag to try to find something\n

voca.title: dive into something
voca.means: (가방, 호주머니 등 속에) 손을 쑥 집어 넣다
voca.explains: to move your hand quickly into something such as a pocket or bag to try to find something\n

voca.title: diver
voca.explains: A diver is a person who swims under water using special breathing equipment.\n

voca.title: diverse
voca.explains: If a group or range of things is diverse, it is made up of a wide variety of things.\nDiverse people or things are very different from each other.\n

voca.title: diversity
voca.explains: The diversity of something is the fact that it contains many very different elements.\nA diversity of things is a range of things which are very different from each other.\n

voca.title: divert
voca.means:
[다이버r-t]
방향을 바꾸게 하다, 전환시키다, 우회시키다
(돈, 재료 등을) 전용/유용하다
(생각, 관점 등을) 다른데로 돌리다
voca.explains:
To divert vehicles or travellers means to make them follow a different route or go to a different destination than they originally intended. You can also say that someone or something diverts from a particular route or to a particular place.
To divert money or resources means to cause them to be used for a different purpose.
To divert a phone call means to send it to a different number or place from the one that was dialled by the person making the call.
If you say that someone diverts your attention from something important or serious, you disapprove of them behaving or talking in a way that stops you thinking about it.

voca.title: divide
voca.means:
[디^바-이d]
(여러 부분들로) 나뉘다, 갈라지다, 나누다, 가르다
(몫을) 나누다
(시간, 에너지 등을) 쪼개 쓰다
(경계선이) 나누다, 가르다
나뉘다, 갈라지다
(사람들의 집단을 구분하는) 차이점
voca.explains:
When people or things are divided or divide into smaller groups or parts, they become separated into smaller parts.
If you divide something among people or things, you separate it into several parts or quantities which you distribute to the people or things.
If you divide a larger number by a smaller number or divide a smaller number into a larger number, you calculate how many times the smaller number can fit exactly into the larger number.
If a border or line divides two areas or divides an area into two, it keeps the two areas separate from each other.
If people divide over something or if something divides them, it causes strong disagreement between them.
A divide is a significant distinction between two groups, often one that causes conflict.
A divide is a moment in time or a point in a process when there is a complete change from one situation to another.
You use divide and rule to refer to a policy which is intended to keep someone in a position of power by causing disagreements between people who might otherwise unite against them.

voca.title: divide off
voca.explains: to separate two things or two people with a barrier such as a wall or fence; to form a barrier between two things or people\n

voca.title: divide up
voca.means: 분배하다, 나눠 갖다, 분담하다\n(의견 따위가) 갈리다, 분열되다
voca.explains: When your programs get larger, you'll want to divide them up into separate components.\n

voca.title: division
voca.means:
[디^비젼]
분리, 분할, 나눗셈,
(특히 사회, 단체 내의) 분열 
(육군의) 사단
voca.explains:
The division of a large unit into two or more distinct parts is the act of separating it into these parts.
The division of something among people or things is its separation into parts which are distributed among the people or things.
Division is the arithmetical process of dividing one number into another number.
A division is a significant distinction or argument between two groups, which causes the two groups to be considered as very different and separate.
In some sports, such as football, baseball, and basketball, a division is one of the groups of teams which make up a league. The teams in each division are considered to be approximately the same standard, and they all play against each other during the season.

voca.title: divorce
voca.explains:
A divorce is the formal ending of a marriage by law.
A divorce of one thing from another, or a divorce between two things is a separation between them which is permanent or is likely to be permanent.
If a man and woman divorce or if one of them divorces the other, their marriage is legally ended.
If you say that one thing cannot be divorced from another, you mean that the two things cannot be considered as different and separate things.

voca.title: divorced
voca.explains:
Someone who is divorced from their former husband or wife has separated from them and is no longer legally married to them.
If you say that one thing is divorced from another, you mean that the two things are very different and separate from each other.
If you say that someone is divorced from a situation, you mean that they act as if they are not affected by it in any way.

voca.title: divulge
voca.explains: If you divulge a piece of secret or private information, you tell it to someone.\n

voca.title: dizzy
voca.means:
[^디지]
어지러운, 현기증나는
(너무 변화가 심해) 아찔한, 어지러울 정도인
멍청한
voca.explains:
If you feel dizzy, you feel that you are losing your balance and are about to fall.
You can use dizzy to describe a woman who is careless and forgets things, but is easy to like.
If you say that someone has reached the dizzy heights of something, you are emphasizing that they have reached a very high level by achieving it.
I'm dizzy and feel like fainting.

voca.title: do
voca.explains:
do - did - done
When you do something, you take some action or perform an activity or task. Do is often used instead of a more specific verb, to talk about a common action involving a particular thing. For example you can say 'do your teeth' instead of 'brush your teeth'.
Do can be used to stand for any verb group, or to refer back to another verb group, including one that was in a previous sentence.
You can use do in a clause at the beginning of a sentence after words like 'what' and 'all', to give special emphasis to the information that comes at the end of the sentence.
If you do a particular thing with something, you use it in that particular way.
If you do something about a problem, you take action to try to solve it.
If an action or event does a particular thing, such as harm or good, it has that result or effect.
You can use do to talk about the degree to which a person, action, or event affects or improves a particular situation.
You can talk about what someone or something does to a person to mean that they have a very harmful effect on them.
If you ask someone what they do, you want to know what their job or profession is.
If you are doing something, you are busy or active in some way, or have planned an activity for some time in the future.
If you say that someone or something does well or badly, you are talking about how successful or unsuccessful they are.
If a person or organization does a particular service or product, they provide that service or sell that product.
You can use do when referring to the speed or rate that something or someone achieves or is able to achieve.
If you do a subject, author, or book, you study them at school or college.
If you do a particular person, accent, or role, you imitate that person or accent, or act that role.
If someone does drugs, they take illegal drugs.
If you say that something will do or will do you, you mean that there is enough of it or that it is of good enough quality to meet your requirements or to satisfy you.

voca.title: do a lot of catching up
voca.explains:
We did a lot of catching up.
We didn't have time to do a lot of catching up.
We did a lot of catching up the next time we met.

voca.title: do a lot of homework
voca.explains:
It shouldn't clash with the furniture you already have. To find the best deals, you need to do a lot of homework.
He did a lot of homework for the meeting.
The people who did a lot of homework had better results.

voca.title: do a number on someone
voca.explains: Last night, I was kept awake by mosquitoes. Their whining was driving me up the wall. When I woke up, I saw they had done a number on me. I was covered with mosquito bites.\n

voca.title: do credit to
voca.explains: show somebody's good qualities; make somebody deserve praise\n

voca.title: do everything one can
voca.explains: In the past, restaurants did everything they could to make the food taste good. They used a lot of sugar and artificial seasoning.\n

voca.title: do good
voca.explains: be kind and generous to people who need help, for example by working for a charity\n

voca.title: do okay
voca.explains: I did okay in the early stages of my pregnancy. However, the morning sickness was unpleasant. Thankfully, my husband was by my side all the time.\n

voca.title: do one's banking
voca.explains:
In Korea, it’s very easy to take care of bank-related chores. Most of the time, I do my banking on my phone. Almost anything can be done with mobile banking.
I didn't have time to do my banking last week.
I can do my banking wherever I am.

voca.title: do one's homework
voca.explains:
I soaked up advice like a sponge. I tried things that bank employees recommended. I discussed the ins and outs of the market with my friends. I also did my homework, reading books and taking online classes.
The project won't be hard if you do your homework.
She had obviously done her homework.

voca.title: do one's job
voca.explains: Supporters of the law believe that it will root out corruption. All in all, I hope it will do its job well.\n

voca.title: do one's part
voca.explains:
Korean voters are well-informed and active. Many are encouraging people to cast their vote. A decision can be swayed by the slimmest of margins. That’s why everyone must do their part.
I tried to do my part.
She did her part for the project.

voca.title: do poorly
voca.explains: When I was in college, I had a part-time job as a tutor. I taught English and math to two middle school students. At first, I felt pressured. If the students did poorly, it would be on me. I needn’t have worried. The students cooperated.\n

voca.title: do right away
voca.explains: Also, to be honest, I’m a little lazy. I procrastinate all the time. I always put off things that I should do right away.\n

voca.title: do something about it
voca.explains: I often suffer from back pain. Recently, it was so bad that I had to do something about it.\n

voca.title: do something special
voca.explains: I would like to do something special on my wedding anniversary each year. However, it's difficult to get out of the house because we have kids.\n

voca.title: do test prep
voca.explains:
I also had to do a lot of test prep for the Korean SAT.
Your score wil be high if you do enough test prep.
I can't go out this weekend because I have to do test prep.

voca.title: do the dished
voca.explains: Last week, I was doing the dishes. I lost my grip on a wine glass, and dropped it, It shattered into pieces.\n

voca.title: do the job
voca.means: 제 역할을 하다\n(원하는 대로) 효과가 있다, 성공하다
voca.explains:
do what is needed or wanted
Convenience store food certainly does the job.
To get there, this bus will do the job.
This isn't the best choice but it will do the job.

voca.title: do the laundry
voca.explains: Just last week, I did the laundry. I put some sweaters in the washing machine. I made sure to use the gentle cycle. Despite my best efforts, the sweaters were ruined. They had shrunk beyond recognition. Next time, I will just entrust everything to the laundromat.\n

voca.title: do the trick
voca.explains:
My wife recently whipped up some soup. She even went through the trouble of boiling it again to prevent it from spoiling. That usually does the trick. That time, it wasn’t enough. The next day, we had to throw away the leftovers.
Tightening this screw should do the trick.
I took his advice and it did the trick.

voca.title: do what something is supposed to do
voca.explains: Finally, I’ve also seen several movie trailers online. The one that stood out for me was the one for “Captain America-Civil War.” I made my way through many versions. The trailers did what they were supposed to do. They made me go watch the flick.\n

voca.title: do wonders
voca.means: 효과가 뛰어나다, 큰 도움이 되다\n놀라운 일을 하다
voca.explains:
One of my favorite ways to cure a hangover is Korean-style hangover relief soup. There are many different types. Most of them are hearty and piping hot. Working up a sweat with a hot dish of soup can do wonders.
The compliments did wonders for my confidence.
Your suggestion did wonders.

voca.title: do your worst
voca.means: (사람이) 최악으로 굴다, 최대한 많은 손상을 입히다
voca.explains: be as harmful, unpleasant, violent, etc. as you can\n

voca.title: docile
voca.explains: A person or animal that is docile is quiet, not aggressive, and easily controlled.\n

voca.title: dock
voca.means:
[닥k]
선창, 부두, 
(항구에서 선박 수리, 물품 보관 등을 하는) 독
(배를) 부두에 대다, 
(우주선을) 도킹하다/시키다, 
(임금 등에서) ~을 빼다/공제하다
voca.explains:
A dock is an enclosed area in a harbour where ships go to be loaded, unloaded, and repaired.
A dock is a platform for loading vehicles or trains.
A dock is a small structure at the edge of water where boats can tie up, especially one that is privately owned.
In a law court, the dock is where the person accused of a crime stands or sits.
When a ship docks or is docked, it is brought into a dock.
When one spacecraft docks or is docked with another, the two crafts join together in space.
If you dock someone's wages or money, you take some of the money away. If you dock someone points in a contest, you take away some of the points that they have.

voca.title: doctor
voca.explains:
A doctor is someone who is qualified in medicine and treats people who are ill.
A dentist or veterinarian can also be called doctor.
The doctor's is used to refer to the surgery or office where a doctor works.
A doctor is someone who has been awarded the highest academic or honorary degree by a university.
If someone doctors something, they change it in order to deceive people.

voca.title: document
voca.means:
[닥퀴먼t]
문서, 서류, 기록
(상세한 내용을) 기록하다
서류로 입증하다, 뒷받침하다
voca.explains:
A document is one or more official pieces of paper with writing on them.
A document is a piece of text or graphics, for example a letter, that is stored as a file on a computer and that you can access in order to read it or change it.
If you document something, you make a detailed record of it in writing or on film or tape.

voca.title: documentation
voca.means: [닥퀴먼테이션]\n(무엇에 요구되는, 또는 무엇을 입증할) 서류\n(문서로 하는) 기록, 문서화, 기록문서
voca.explains: Documentation consists of documents which provide proof or evidence of something, or are a record of something.\n

voca.title: dodge
voca.means:
[^다-쥐]
재빨리 몸을 피하다, 속이다, 
발뺌하다, 둘러대다
회피, 재빨리 피하기, 속임수
voca.explains:
If you dodge, you move suddenly, often to avoid being hit, caught, or seen.
If you dodge something, you avoid it by quickly moving aside or out of reach so that it cannot hit or reach you.
If you dodge something, you deliberately avoid thinking about it or dealing with it, often by being deceitful.
Francine dodged left and flipped the carton past Arthur's hand.
Arthur did his best, but finally the third ball dodged the right flipper and sank into the hole.
One kind of detective fades back into the shadows once a case is solved. For that detective, solving the mystery is its own reward. He dodges the bright lights of the television cameras and the front page of the newspaper.

voca.title: dog
voca.means:
[^독g]
개, (개, 여우, 늑대의) 수컷
저질 물건, 실패작
(오랫동안) 괴롭히다
(누구 뒤를) 바싹 따라가다
voca.explains:
A dog is a very common four-legged animal that is often kept by people as a pet or to guard or hunt. There are many different breeds of dog.
You use dog to refer to a male dog, or to the male of some related species such as wolves or foxes.
If someone calls a man a dog, they strongly disapprove of him.
People use dog to refer to something that they consider unsatisfactory or of poor quality.
If problems or injuries dog you, they are with you all the time.

voca.title: dole
voca.means:
[^도올]
베풀다, (구호품을) 주다, 조금씩 나누어주다
시주, 구호품, 의연품, 분배물, 얼마 안 되는 몫
실업 수당
