voca.explains: The dole or dole is money that is given regularly by the government to people who are unemployed.\nSomeone who is on the dole is registered as unemployed and receives money from the government.\n

voca.title: dole out
voca.explains: to give money, food, etc. to a group of people\nWhen we got to the picnic site, we sprang into action. I lit the fire. My friends prepped the ingredients and doled out drinks. Soon, the barbecue was in full swing. The meat was mouth-watering. We cooked the steaks just so. We enjoyed the meal and each other’s company.\n

voca.title: doll
voca.explains: A doll is a child's toy which looks like a small person or baby.\n

voca.title: dolphin
voca.explains: A dolphin is a mammal which lives in the sea and looks like a large fish with a pointed mouth.\n

voca.title: dome
voca.explains: A dome is a round roof.\nA dome is any object that has a similar shape to a dome.\n

voca.title: domestic
voca.explains:
Domestic political activities, events, and situations happen or exist within one particular country.
Domestic duties and activities are concerned with the running of a home and family.
Domestic items and services are intended to be used in people's homes rather than in factories or offices.
A domestic situation or atmosphere is one which involves a family and their home.
A domestic, a domestic help, or a domestic worker is a person who is paid to come to help with the work that has to be done in a house such as the cleaning, washing, and ironing.

voca.title: dominate
voca.means:
[^도미네잇t]
(특히 불쾌한 방식으로) 지배, 군림하다
(~의) 가장 중요한/두드러지는 특징이 되다
(어떤 장소에서) 가장 크다/높다/두드러지다
(경기에서) 압도적으로 우세하다
voca.explains:
To dominate a situation means to be the most powerful or important person or thing in it.
If one country or person dominates another, they have power over them.
If a building, mountain, or other object dominates an area, it is so large or impressive that you cannot avoid seeing it.
Here in Korea, we have gotten accustomed to what’s been dubbed “mobile gifts.” In the most-wired country in the world, one free messaging application dominates the market.

voca.title: donate
voca.explains: If you donate something to a charity or other organization, you give it to them.\nIf you donate your blood or a part of your body, you allow doctors to use it to help someone who is ill.\n

voca.title: donate blood
voca.explains:
I want to donate blood, but I'm scared of drawing blood.
I saw in the news that fewer and fewer people are donating blood these days. That’s why I’ve been donating blood on a regular basis for almost a year.
I am too scared to donate blood.
Only healthy people can donate blood.

voca.title: donation
voca.explains: A donation is something which someone gives to a charity or other organization.\n

voca.title: dongkey
voca.explains: A donkey is an animal which is like a horse but which is smaller and has longer ears.\nFor donkey's years means for a very long time.\n

voca.title: dongkey's years
voca.explains: a very long time\nIn some countries, home shopping is state-of-the-art. Korea is so ultra-modern that it’s considered old hat. But even though it’s been around for donkey’s years, I have a soft spot for TV home shopping.\n

voca.title: donor
voca.explains:
A donor is someone who gives a part of their body or some of their blood to be used by doctors to help a person who is ill.
A donor is a person or organization who gives something, especially money, to a charity, organization, or country that needs it.
Donor organs or parts are organs or parts of the body which people allow doctors to use to help people who are ill.

voca.title: don't mind
voca.explains: For the food, we cooked some dishes ourselves. My wife and I both enjoy cooking, so we didn't mind.\n

voca.title: doodad
voca.means: [^듀-덷]\n작은 장식물, 값싼 장식품, 거시기\n하찮은 장식품, 값싼 것; 장치, 물건
voca.explains: A doodad is the same as a doodah.\n

voca.title: doodle
voca.means: [^두들]\n(특히 지루해 하거나 딴 생각을 하면서) 뭔가를 끄적거리다
voca.explains: A doodle is a pattern or picture that you draw when you are bored or thinking about something else.\nWhen someone doodles, they draw doodles.\n

voca.title: doom
voca.means: [^듀움]\n죽음, 파멸, (피할 수 없는) 비운\n불행한 운명/결말을 맞게 하다
voca.explains:
Doom is a terrible future state or event which you cannot prevent.
If you have a sense or feeling of doom, you feel that things are going very badly and are likely to get even worse.
If a fact or event dooms someone or something to a particular fate, it makes certain that they are going to suffer in some way.
Those who don't learn their history are doomed to repeat it.

voca.title: doom and gloom
voca.explains: a general feeling of having lost all hope and of pessimism (= expecting things to go badly)\n

voca.title: doomsday
voca.explains: Doomsday is a day or time when you expect something terrible or unpleasant is going to happen.\nIn the Christian religion, Doomsday is the last day of the world, on which God will judge everyone.\n

voca.title: door
voca.explains:
A door is a piece of wood, glass, or metal, which is moved to open and close the entrance to a building, room, cupboard, or vehicle.
A door is the space in a wall when a door is open.
Doors is used in expressions such as a few doors down or three doors up to refer to a place that is a particular number of buildings away from where you are.

voca.title: doorbell
voca.explains: A doorbell is a bell on the outside of a house which you can ring so that the people inside know that you want to see them.\nHe was interrupted by the doorbell.\n

voca.title: doorway
voca.explains:
A doorway is a space in a wall where a door opens and closes.
A doorway is a covered space just outside the door of a building.
Annie was peering through a doorway off the hall.
A giant, slimy, mud-colored creature crawled out throught on of the doorways.
He held out his hand and waved Jack and Annie through the open doorway.

voca.title: dormitory
voca.explains:
A dormitory is a large bedroom where several people sleep, for example in a boarding school.
A dormitory is a building in a college or university where students live.
If you refer to a place as a dormitory suburb or town, you mean that most of the people who live there travel to work in another, larger town a short distance away.

voca.title: dosage
voca.means: [^도우시쥐]\n(보통 약의) 정량, 투약량, 조제, 투약, 복용량
voca.explains: A dosage is the amount of a medicine or drug that someone takes or should take.\n

voca.title: dose
voca.means:
[^도우s]
복용하다, 투약하다
1회 복용량, 1회분, 복용
(어느 정도의) 양, 약간
voca.explains:
A dosage is the amount of a medicine or drug that someone takes or should take.
You can refer to an amount of something as a dose of that thing, especially when you want to emphasize that there is a great deal of it.
If you dose a person or animal with medicine, you give them an amount of it.

voca.title: dot
voca.means:
[^닷]
(특히 인쇄된 동그란) 점
(이메일 주소 등에 쓰이는) 점
~에 점을 찍다, 
여기저기 흩어 놓다; 여기저기 흩어져 있다, 산재하다
voca.explains:
dot / mark / spot
A dot is a very small round mark, for example one that is used as the top part of the letter 'i', as a full stop, or as a decimal point.
You can refer to something that you can see in the distance and that looks like a small round mark as a dot.
When things dot a place or an area, they are scattered or spread all over it.
If you arrive somewhere or do something on the dot, you arrive there or do it at exactly the time that you were supposed to.
Dark rocks dotted the side of the mountain.

voca.title: double
voca.means:
[^더블]
(보통 양이나 수의) 두 배의, 갑절의
(똑같거나 비슷한 것이) 두 개/부분로 된
2인용의, 두 개용의
두 가지가 혼합된, 이중의
두 배, 갑절
꼭 닮은 사람/물건
대역 배우
voca.explains:
double / dual
You use double to indicate that something includes or is made of two things of the same kind.
You use double before a singular noun to refer to two things of the same type that occur together, or that are connected in some way.
You use double to describe something which is twice the normal size or can hold twice the normal quantity of something.
A double room is a room intended for two people, usually a couple, to stay or live in.
A double bed is a bed that is wide enough for two people to sleep in.
You use double to describe a drink that is twice the normal measure.
Double is used when you are spelling a word or telling someone a number to show that a letter or digit is repeated.
If something is double the amount or size of another thing, it is twice as large.
When something doubles or when you double it, it becomes twice as great in number, amount, or size.
If a person or thing doubles as someone or something else, they have a second job or purpose as well as their main one.
If you refer to someone as a person's double, you mean that they look exactly like them.In tennis or badminton, when people play doubles, two teams consisting of two players on each team play against each other on the same court.

voca.title: double down on
voca.explains:
Online protection is no longer a matter of choice. Lawmakers should double down on laws that protect personal information.
Plan A didn't work, so they doubled down on plan B.
The team doubled down on improving their performance.
I really need to double down on losing weight.
We're almost out of time, so we should double down on this project.

voca.title: Double Dutch
voca.means: 두 개의 줄을 서로 반대쪽으로 돌리는 줄넘기 놀이
voca.explains: Meanwhile, Francine and Sue Ellen were jumping double Dutch in the park. A line of kids was waiting for a turn to jump.\n

voca.title: doubly
voca.means: [^더블뤼]\n두 배로, 이중으로, \n두 가지로, 두 가지 이유로
voca.explains: You use doubly to indicate that there are two aspects or features that are having an influence on a particular situation.\nYou use doubly to emphasize that something exists or happens to a greater degree than usual.\n

voca.title: doubt
voca.means: [^다웃t]\n의심,의혹, 의문, 의심스러움, 불확실함\n의심하다, 믿지않다, 확신하지 못하다
voca.explains:
If you have doubt or doubts about something, you feel uncertain about it and do not know whether it is true or possible. If you say you have no doubt about it, you mean that you are certain it is true.
If you doubt whether something is true or possible, you believe that it is probably not true or possible.
If you doubt something, you believe that it might not be true or genuine.
If you doubt someone or doubt their word, you think that they may not be telling the truth.

voca.title: dough
voca.explains: Dough is a fairly firm mixture of flour, water, and sometimes also fat and sugar. It can be cooked to make bread, pastry, and biscuits.\nYou can refer to money as dough.\n

voca.title: doughnut
voca.explains: A doughnut is a bread-like cake made from sweet dough that has been cooked in hot fat.\n

voca.title: dove
voca.explains:
A dove is a bird that looks like pigeon but is smaller and lighter in colour. Doves are often used as a symbol of peace.
In politics, you can refer to people who support the use of peaceful methods to solve difficult situations as doves. Compare hawk.
In American English, dove is sometimes used as the past tense of dive.
In the hush of the cold twilight, the dove spread its wings and flew into the Frog Creek woods.

voca.title: down
voca.means:
[다운]
(더 낮은 장소나 위치로) 아래, 아래에
(높은데서) 아래로
(어떤 기간을) 통틀어
voca.explains:
To go down something such as a slope or a pipe means to go towards the ground or to a lower level.
If you are a particular distance down something, you are that distance below the top or surface of it.
If you go or look down something such as a road or river, you go or look along it. If you are down a road or river, you are somewhere along it.
Down to a particular detail means including everything, even that detail. Down to a particular person means including everyone, even that person.

voca.title: down a few drinks
voca.explains: We went to a nearby restaurant. We asked them to cook our food. When the food arrived, we stuffed ourselves. We also downed a few drinks.\n

voca.title: down in the dumps
voca.explains:
depressed; miserable
I've been feeling a bit down in the dumps since I lost my job.
I've been down in the dumps for the past few days.

voca.title: down the drain
voca.means: 낭비하다. 물거품이 되다.\n허비된, 훨씬 더 나빠진
voca.explains: (be) wasted or lost; (get) much worse\nYou didn't eat your dinner. That's food down the drain.\n

voca.title: down to
voca.explains:
even including the last item of a whole list of people or things
Katie: Ken do you have fifteen dollars?
Ken: (looking in his wallet) No. I'm down to ten dollars.

voca.title: down to earth
voca.explains: If you say that someone is down-to-earth, you approve of the fact that they concern themselves with practical things and actions, rather than with abstract theories.\nYou need to come down to earth!\n

voca.title: downhill
voca.explains:
If something or someone is moving downhill or is downhill, they are moving down a slope or are located towards the bottom of a hill.
If you say that something is going downhill, you mean that it is becoming worse or less successful.
If you say that a task or situation is downhill after a particular stage or time, you mean that it is easy to deal with after that stage or time.
Nearby a wild stream reushed downhill.

voca.title: downpour
voca.explains: A downpour is a sudden and unexpected heavy fall of rain.\nChaba was so strong that the wind speeds were record-breaking. Areas including Jeju, Busan and Ulsan got heavy downpours.\n

voca.title: downright
voca.explains:
You use downright to emphasize unpleasant or bad qualities or behaviour.
As in any programming language, comments can quickly go stale and become meaningless or downright confusing.
After your goal is set in stone, you can sample all the different programs to pinpoint the ones that are most helpful to you. With the right programs, it can be downright fun.

voca.title: downside
voca.explains: The downside of a situation is the aspect of it which is less positive, pleasant, or useful than its other aspects.\nLast fall, I went to enjoy the autumn foliage. The views were staggering. The colorful leaves were a sight to see. The only downside was that there were enormous crowds. Everyone wanted to take in the view. Still, it was worth the trouble.\n

voca.title: downspout
voca.explains: A downspout is a pipe attached to the side of a building, through which water flows from the roof into a drain.\n

voca.title: downstairs
voca.explains:
If you go downstairs in a building, you go down a staircase towards the ground floor.
If something or someone is downstairs in a building, they are on the ground floor or on a lower floor than you.
Downstairs means situated on the ground floor of a building or on a lower floor than you are.
The downstairs of a building is its lower floor or floors.
A : Can you come downstairs for a minute right now? 
The sound was coming from downstairs.

voca.title: downstream
voca.explains: Something that is moving downstream is moving towards the mouth of a river, from a point further up the river. Something that is downstream is further towards the mouth of a river than where you are.\n

voca.title: downtown
voca.explains: Downtown places are in or towards the centre of a large town or city, where the shops and places of business are.\n

voca.title: downward
voca.explains: A downward movement or look is directed towards a lower place or a lower level.\nIf you refer to a downward trend, you mean that something is decreasing or that a situation is getting worse.\n

voca.title: downy
voca.explains:
Something that is downy is filled or covered with small soft feathers.
Something that is downy is covered with very fine hairs.
She stroked the downy feathers on the creature's head.

voca.title: doze
voca.means: [^도우z]\n깜밖 잠이 들다, 졸다\n(보통 낮에) 잠깐 잠, 낮잠
voca.explains: sleep / doze / nap / snooze / slumber / drowse\nWhen you doze, you sleep lightly or for a short period, especially during the daytime.\n

voca.title: doze off
voca.explains:
to go to sleep, especially during the day
B : I dozed off during the last few minutes.
Another time, I got on a bus after an office dinner. I soon dozed off. When I woke up, I was at the end of the line.
I dozed off in the cab.
She tried hard not to doze off.
The worst was when I got a cramp in my sleep. I was fast asleep when I felt a stitch in my side. I woke up with a start. It took a long time for my muscles to loosen up. I didn’t doze off again until the crack of dawn.
A few weeks ago, I had a few too many during dinner with friends. I dozed off on the bus on my way home.
I would constantly doze off if I didn’t. I squeeze in some shut-eye during the day and lie wide-awake in bed at night.
I dozed off during the meeting.
I was dozing off on the couch.

voca.title: dozen
voca.explains:
If you have a dozen things, you have twelve of them.
You can refer to a group of approximately twelve things or people as a dozen. You can refer to a group of approximately six things or people as half a dozen.
If you refer to dozens of things or people, you are emphasizing that there are very many of them.

voca.title: dozens and dozens of
voca.explains: He held out the petition sheets. There were now dozens and dozens of names.\n

voca.title: draft
voca.means:
[듀^뤠-ft]
(아직 완성본이 아닌) 원고, 초고,
(은행이 발행한) 수표
밑그림을 그리다, 작성하다, 
선발/파견하다
(특별 임무를 위해) 선발하다, 뽑다
외풍, 통풍, 밑그림, 도면, 징병, 선발
기초된, 초안의
voca.explains:
A draft is an early version of a letter, book, or speech.
The draft is the practice of ordering people to serve in the armed forces, usually for a limited period of time.
A draft is a written order for payment of money by a bank, especially from one bank to another.
When you draft a letter, book, or speech, you write the first version of it.
If you are drafted, you are ordered to serve in the armed forces, usually for a limited period of time.
For ordinary desk jockeys, a planner is a must-have. On most workdays, I keep a small planner with me at all times. It’s useful to me in many ways. I use it to draft to-do lists. When I attend a meeting, I jot down important notes.

voca.title: drafty
voca.explains: A pair of torched dimly lit the drafty entrance hall of the castle.\n

voca.title: drag
voca.means:
[듀^뤠-g]
(힘들여) 끌다, 끌고 가다
(몸을 끌듯) 힘들게 움직이다
(원치 않는 곳에) 가게/오게 하다
느릿느릿 지나가다/행진되다, 질질 끌다/끌리다
지겨운/짜증나는 사람, ~에 대한 장애물/방해물
(담배 연기 등을) 빨아들이다
voca.explains:
pull / drag / draw / haul / tow / tug
If you drag something, you pull it along the ground, often with difficulty.
To drag a computer image means to use the mouse to move the position of the image on the screen, or to change its size or shape.
If someone drags you somewhere, they pull you there, or force you to go there by physically threatening you.
If someone drags you somewhere you do not want to go, they make you go there.
If you say that you drag yourself somewhere, you are emphasizing that you have to make a very great effort to go there.
If you drag your foot or your leg behind you, you walk with great difficulty because you foot or leg is injured in some way.
If the police drag a river or lake, they pull nets or hooks across the bottom of it in order to look for something.
If a period of time or an event drags, it is very boring and seems to last a long time.
If something is a drag on the development or progress of something, it slows it down or makes it more difficult.
If you say that something is a drag, you mean that it is unpleasant or very dull.
If you take a drag on a cigarette or pipe that you are smoking, you take in air through it.
Drag is the wearing of women's clothes by a male entertainer.
Finally, Jack dragged himself out of the ocean.

voca.title: drag on
voca.explains:
to progress very slowly and take too long
Dan: I usually don't like these meetings because they drag on.
That movie just dragged on. I didn't like it so I left and went home.

voca.title: drag one's feet
voca.means: 늑장을 부리다. 꾸물거리다\n피곤해 느릿느릿 걷다\n일을 더디게 하다 꾸물거리다
voca.explains:
Korea ranks near the bottom in the world for birthrate. There are many reasons. First of all, people are dragging their feet before getting hitched. They want to focus on their careers. They need time to save up for wedding costs.
Why do you drag your feet every morning?
It won't help to drag your feet.
I was so tired I was dragging my feet when I got home.
Grace: Why are you dragging your feet?

voca.title: drag somebody down
voca.explains: to bring somebody down to a lower standard of behaviour, or a lower social or economic level\nto make somebody feel depressed or weak\n

voca.title: drag something out
voca.explains: to make something last longer than it should\n

voca.title: drag something up
voca.explains: to mention in a conversation an unpleasant fact from the past that somebody would prefer to forget\n

voca.title: drain
voca.means:
[^듀뤠인]
물/액체를 빼내다/빠지다, 
(액체를) 따라 내다, 흘러 나가다
(술 등을 다 마셔서 잔을) 비우다
배출시키다, 소비하다, 유츌하다, 비우다
하수구, 배수, 유출, 소비, 출자
voca.explains:
If you drain a liquid from a place or object, you remove the liquid by causing it to flow somewhere else. If a liquid drains somewhere, it flows there.
If you drain a place or object, you dry it by causing water to flow out of it. If a place or object drains, water flows out of it until it is dry.
If you drain food or if food drains, you remove the liquid that it has been in, especially after it has been cooked or soaked in water.
If the colour or the blood drains or is drained from someone's face, they become very pale. You can also say that someone's face drains or is drained of colour.
If something drains you, it leaves you feeling physically and emotionally exhausted.
If you say that a country's or a company's resources or finances are drained, you mean that they are used or spent completely.
A drain is a pipe that carries water or sewage away from a place, or an opening in a surface that leads to the pipe.
If you say that something is a drain on an organization's finances or resources, you mean that it costs the organization a large amount of money, and you do not consider that it is worth it.
If you say that something is going down the drain, you mean that it is being destroyed or wasted.
All the joy of the music drained out of him.
The sink in our bathroom once got clogged up. The water from the tap would not go down the drain.

voca.title: drain one's battery
voca.explains: I am on my phone 24/7, which tends to drain my battery at lightning speed. I peruse e-mail(s), the latest headlines, and social media posts.\n

voca.title: dramatic
voca.explains:
exciting / dramatic / heady / thrilling / exhilarating
A dramatic change or event happens suddenly and is very noticeable and surprising.
A dramatic action, event, or situation is exciting and impressive.
You use dramatic to describe things connected with or relating to the theatre, drama, or plays.
"I just thought it might be nice to start off with a drum roll. For dramatic impact."

voca.title: drape
voca.means:
[듀^뤠입p]
(옷, 천 등을 느슨하게) 걸치다, 씌우다, 
(천 등을) 걸치다, 아릅답게 싸다
덮는 천, 휘장, (두꺼운) 커튼
voca.explains:
If you drape a piece of cloth somewhere, you place it there so that it hangs down in a casual and graceful way.
If someone or something is draped in a piece of cloth, they are loosely covered by it.
If you drape a part of your body somewhere, you lay it there in a relaxed and graceful way.
Drapes are pieces of heavy fabric that you hang from the top of a window and can close to keep the light out or stop people looking in.
He and Francine were wearing the numbers 7 and 3 on their chests. Pal was standing between them with an x, the multiplication symbol, draped over him.

voca.title: draw

[듀^롸-]
(색칠은 하지 않고 연필, 펜, 분필 등으로) 그리다, 
(부드럽게) 끌어당기다, 뽑아내다, 끌다
(공격하기 위해 총, 칼 등을 꺼내서) 겨누다
비기다, 인출하다
잡아당기기, 끌기, 동점, 추첨

draw - drew - drawn
pull / drag / draw / haul / tow / tug
When you draw, or when you draw something, you use a pencil or pen to produce a picture, pattern, or diagram.
When a vehicle draws somewhere, it moves there smoothly and steadily.
If you draw somewhere, you move there slowly.
If you draw something or someone in a particular direction, you move them in that direction, usually by pulling them gently.
When you draw a curtain or blind, you pull it across a window, either to cover or to uncover it.
When they came to the iron gate, the knights drew their swords.
Arcades draw shifty characters the way a garbage dump draws flies. I figured something would come my way if I kept a good lookout.

voca.explains: to move away from somebody/something, especially somebody/something that makes you feel frightened\nto decide not to do something, because you are afraid of what might happen\n

voca.title: draw blood
voca.explains:
The check-up got under way with simple measurements. Members of the staff measured my height, weight, eyesight, blood pressure and lung capacity. A nurse drew some blood.
The mosquito bit my arm and drew blood.
I want to donate blood, but I'm scared of drawing blood.
Then, she injected a needle in my arm to draw blood. After I was finished, I was given a light snack and some movie tickets.

voca.title: draw breath
voca.explains: stop doing something and rest\nlive; be alive\n

voca.title: draw in
voca.means: (겨울이 가까워져서) 점점 날이/해가 짧아지다\n점점 어둠이 빨리 내리다
voca.explains: when evenings or nights are drawing in, it is gradually becoming darker earlier in the evening because winter is coming\n

voca.title: draw on
voca.explains: to slowly pass\n

voca.title: draw out
voca.explains: if a train draws out or draws out of a station, it begins to move and slowly leaves the station\nwhen evenings or nights are drawing out, it is gradually becoming lighter for longer in the evening because spring is coming\n

voca.title: draw the line
voca.means: ~을 (하기를) 거부하다; 한도를 정하다, 선을 긋다\n(~와 ~을) 구별짓다\n한계를 긋다, ~이상은 하지 않다
voca.explains:
refuse to do or accept something
I don’t mind you being late occasionally, but I draw the line at you being late every day.
You really should know when or where to draw the line.

voca.title: drawback
voca.explains:
A drawback is an aspect of something or someone that makes them less acceptable than they would otherwise be.
The drawback is that they are on the pricey side.
As a newlywed, marriage was a blissful time for me. However, there was one unforeseen drawback. I started to gain weight.
If you’re new to water sports, water parks are a good starting point. They offer activities for all skill levels. The one drawback is that they are on the pricey side.

voca.title: drawbridge
voca.explains: A drawbridge is a bridge that can be pulled up, for example to prevent people from getting into a castle or to allow ships to pass underneath it.\n

voca.title: drawer
voca.explains:
A drawer is part of a desk, chest, or other piece of furniture that is shaped like a box and is designed for putting things in. You pull it towards you to open it.
Jack reached into his drawer.
Judy searched her top drawer and her bottom drawer and even her underwear drawer.

voca.title: drawn
voca.explains: Drawn is the past participle of draw.\nIf someone or their face looks drawn, their face is thin and they look very tired, ill, worried, or unhappy.\n

voca.title: dread
voca.means:
[듀^뤠d]
(~을) 몹시 무서워하다, 
(안 좋은 일이 생길까 봐) 두려워하다, 크게 염려하다
근심, 불안, 큰 공포, 공포의 대상
아주 무서운, 지독한
voca.explains:
If you dread something which may happen, you feel very anxious and unhappy about it because you think it will be unpleasant or upsetting.
Dread is a feeling of great anxiety and fear about something that may happen.
Dread means terrible and greatly feared.
If you say that you dread to think what might happen, you mean that you are anxious about it because it is likely to be very unpleasant.
A feeling of dread crept over Jack.
Perhaps the two most dreaded words in the English language.

voca.title: dreaded
voca.explains: Dreaded means terrible and greatly feared.\nYou can use the dreaded to describe something that you, or a particular group of people, find annoying, inconvenient, or undesirable.\n

voca.title: dreadful
voca.explains:
terrible / awful / horrible / dreadful / vile / foul
If you say that something is dreadful, you mean that it is very bad or unpleasant, or very poor in quality.
Dreadful is used to emphasize the degree or extent of something bad.
If someone looks or feels dreadful, they look or feel very ill, tired, or upset.

voca.title: dream
voca.means:
[듀^뤼임]
(자면서 꾸는) 꿈, 
(희망을 담는) 꿈
망상, 
(자면서) 꿈을꾸다, 
(바라는 일을) 꿈꾸다, 상상하다
voca.explains:
A dream is an imaginary series of events that you experience in your mind while you are asleep.
You can refer to a situation or event as a dream if you often think about it because you would like it to happen.
If you describe something as a particular person's dream, you think that it would be ideal for that person and that he or she would like it very much.
If you say that something is a dream, you mean that it is wonderful.
You can refer to a situation or event that does not seem real as a dream, especially if it is very strange or unpleasant.
When you dream, you experience imaginary events in your mind while you are asleep.
If you often think about something that you would very much like to happen or have, you can say that you dream of it.
If you say that you would not dream of doing something, you are emphasizing that you would never do it because you think it is wrong or is not possible or suitable for you.
If you say that you never dreamed that something would happen, you are emphasizing that you did not think that it would happen because it seemed very unlikely.
You can use dream to describe something that you think is ideal or perfect, especially if it is something that you thought you would never be able to have or experience.

voca.title: dream of

voca.title: dreamtime
voca.explains: (in the mythology of Australian Aboriginal peoples) a mythical Golden Age of the past\nany remote period, out of touch with the actualities of the present\n

voca.title: dreamy

[듀^릐미]
(사람 표정이) 꿈을 꾸는(백일몽에 잠긴) 듯한
공상적인
비몽사몽을 헤매는 듯한
꿈결 같은, 감미로운
멋진, 환상적인
voca.explains: If you say that someone has a dreamy expression, you mean that they are not paying attention to things around them and look as if they are thinking about something pleasant.\nIf you describe something as dreamy, you mean that you like it and that it seems gentle and soft, like something in a dream.\n

voca.title: dreary
voca.explains: If you describe something as dreary, you mean that it is dull and depressing.\nEven in the dreary light, the medallion was shining.\n

voca.title: drench
voca.explains: wet / moist / damp / soaked / drenched / dripping / saturated\nTo drench something or someone means to make them completely wet.\n

voca.title: dress
voca.means: [듀^뤠s]\n옷, 의복, 복장, 정장, 예복\n옷을 입히다,  장식하다, 치료하다
voca.explains:
clothes / clothing / garment / dress / wear / gear

You can refer to clothes worn by men or women as dress.
When you dress or dress yourself, you put on clothes.
If you dress someone, for example a child, you put clothes on them.
If someone dresses in a particular way, they wear clothes of a particular style or colour.
If you dress for something, you put on special clothes for it.
When someone dresses a wound, they clean it and cover it.

voca.title: dress casually
voca.explains:
I like to dress casually.
On fridays, we dress casually at work.
It's okay to dress casually at this restaurant.

voca.title: dress code
voca.explains: The dress code of a place is the rules about what kind of clothes people are allowed to wear there.\nThat company is very conservative. They have a dress code that everyone must follow.\n

voca.title: dress down
voca.explains: to wear clothes that are less formal than those you usually wear or those that are usually worn in a particular situation\n

voca.title: dress shirt
voca.means: 드레스 셔츠(정장을 입고 나비넥타이를 맬 때 입는 흰색 셔츠) \n(양복 안에 입는) 와이셔츠
voca.explains: A dress shirt is a special shirt which men wear on formal occasions. It is worn with a dinner jacket and bow tie.\n

voca.title: dress up
voca.means: 변장을 하다/시키다\n(보통때 보다 더) 옷을 갖춰/격식을 차려 입다\n꾸며 입다, 잘 차려입다.
voca.explains:
to make something seem different or better than it really is by the way that you present it

Sometimes, it feels good to dress up.
You don't have to dress up if you don't want to.

voca.title: dressing

[^듀뤠싱]
(요리용) 드레싱(소스)
(상처 위에 덮는) 드레싱, 붕대
옷 입기

voca.title: dressing room
voca.explains:
A dressing room is a room in a theatre where performers can dress and get ready for their performance.
A dressing room is a room at a sports stadium where players can change and get ready for their game.
My favorite piece of furniture is the chest of drawers in our dressing room.
We keep all of our clothes in the dressing room.
It's hard to find anything in the dressing room.

voca.title: drew
voca.explains: Drew is the past tense of draw.\n

voca.title: dribble
voca.means:
[^d뤼블]
(침 등을) 질질 흘리다
(액체가 조금씩) 똑똑 떨어지다
(액체를 조금씩) 붓다, 흘리다
(축구 및 일부 다른 스포츠에서) 드리블하다
(액체가) 조금씩 흘러내리는 것
(스포츠에서의) 드리블

If a person dribbles, saliva drops slowly from their mouth.
Dribble is saliva that drops slowly from someone's mouth.

If someone or something drifts into a situation, they get into that situation in a way that is not planned or controlled.
If you say that someone drifts around, you mean that they travel from place to place without a plan or settled way of life.

If snow drifts, it builds up into piles as a result of the movement of the wind.

voca.explains:
A drill is a tool or machine that you use for making holes.
A drill is a way that teachers teach their students something by making them repeat it many times.
