A drill is a routine exercise or activity, in which people practise what they should do in dangerous situations.
When you drill into something or drill a hole in something, you make a hole in it using a drill.
When people drill for oil or water, they search for it by drilling deep holes in the ground or in the bottom of the sea.

voca.title: drill down
voca.means: 드릴 다운하다\n(더 많은 정보를 찾기 위해 관련 텍스트나 아이콘 등을 클릭하여 마치 뚫고 들어가듯이 검색하는 것)
voca.explains: to go to deeper levels of an organized set of data on a computer or a website in order to find more detail\n

voca.title: drill something into somebody
voca.explains: to make somebody learn or understand something by repeating it frequently\n

voca.title: drink
voca.explains:
When you drink a liquid, you take it into your mouth and swallow it.
To drink means to drink alcohol.
A drink is an amount of a liquid which you drink.
A drink is an alcoholic drink.

voca.title: drink excessively
voca.explains:
For grown-ups, having a few drinks can be a laugh. But if you drink excessively, there is a price to pay.
He drank excessively last night.
We advise against drinking excessively.

voca.title: drink heavily
voca.explains: If you drink heavily or stay up late on New Year's Eve, you might feel sick on the first day of the New Year.\n

voca.title: drink up
voca.explains: to finish all of a drink\n

voca.title: drip
voca.means:
[^듀륍]
똑똑 떨어지다, ~의 물방울을 흘리다
(물) 방울, 떨어지는 물방울 소리
(작은 액체) 방울,
voca.explains:
When liquid drips somewhere, or you drip it somewhere, it falls in individual small drops.
When something drips, drops of liquid fall from it.
If you say that something is dripping with a particular thing, you mean that it contains a lot of that thing.
A drip is a small individual drop of a liquid.
A drip is a piece of medical equipment by which a liquid is slowly passed through a tube into a patient's blood.
Strands of drool dripped from its sharp, pointed teeth.
The situation did not look good. Everything still pointed to just one person-Arthur. Could he really be a criminal mastermind? I tried to picture him in his secret hideout, swimming in a sea of shiny quarters. They dripped through his fingers as he laughed insanely.

voca.title: drive
voca.means:
[d^롸이v]
(챠량을) 몰다, 운전하다, (사냥감을) 몰다, 
태워다 주다, 
(특정한 형태의 차량을) 소유하다/쓰다
(극단적이 되도록) 만들다, 몰아가다
~을 혹사시키다, ~에 무리한 작업을 요구하다
돌진/질주하다
(주택의) 진입로, (조직적인) 운동
voca.explains:
drive - drove - driven
campaign / battle / struggle / drive / war / fight
When you drive somewhere, you operate a car or other vehicle and control its movement and direction.
If you drive someone somewhere, you take them there in a car or other vehicle.
If something drives a machine, it supplies the power that makes it work.
If you drive something such as a nail into something else, you push it in or hammer it in using a lot of effort.
In games such as cricket, golf, or football, if a player drives a ball somewhere, they kick or hit it there with a lot of force.
If the wind, rain, or snow drives in a particular direction, it moves with great force in that direction.
If you drive people or animals somewhere, you make them go to or from that place.
To drive someone into a particular state or situation means to force them into that state or situation.
The desire or feeling that drives a person to do something, especially something extreme, is the desire or feeling that causes them to do it.
A drive is a journey in a car or other vehicle.
A drive is a wide piece of hard ground, or sometimes a private road, that leads from the road to a person's house.
You use drive to refer to the mechanical part of a computer which reads the data on disks and tapes, or writes data onto them.
If you say that someone has drive, you mean they have energy and determination.

voca.title: drive off
voca.explains: to go away in a vehicle; to take somebody away in a vehicle\nto hit the ball to begin a game\n

voca.title: drive on
voca.explains: to continue driving either without stopping or after stopping for a short time\n

voca.title: drive one's way to
voca.explains:
We drove our way to the resort, which took us about three and a half hours.
We drove our way to the airport.
It took three hours to drive our way to that place.

voca.title: drive somebody crazy
voca.explains: That loud music drives me crazy.\nShe drives me crazy when she plays that music so loud.\n

voca.title: drive somebody off
voca.explains: to force somebody/something to move away from a particular place\n

voca.title: drive someone up the wall
voca.explains:
Last night, I was kept awake by mosquitoes. Their whining was driving me up the wall.
The long meeting drove him up the wall.
Noisy eaters drive me up the wall.
That noise is driving me up the wall.
That loud music is going to driving me up the wall.

voca.title: drive to
voca.explains: He pitched again-and the ball sailed right over the plate. The coach lined a drive to Sue Ellen at third base.\n

voca.title: drive up prices
voca.explains:
Most people who buy a home need to get a bank loan, Buying real estate can be a good investment. However, speculative buyers drive up prices even more.
More demand will drive up prices.
Some stores drive up prices during vacation season.

voca.title: drivel
voca.explains: If you describe something that is written or said as drivel, you are critical of it because you think it is very silly\n

voca.title: driveway
voca.means: [^듀롸이v웨이]\n사유 차도, (도로에서 집, 차고까지의) 진입로\n가축을 몰고 가는 길
voca.explains: A driveway is a piece of hard ground that leads from the road to the front of a house or other building.\n

voca.title: driving under the influence
voca.explains:
People can request a designated driver for a fee. It's a great way to avoid driving under the influence.
Driving under the influence is never acceptable.
He was arrested for driving under the influence.

voca.title: drizzle
voca.explains:
Drizzle is light rain falling in fine drops.
If it is drizzling, it is raining very lightly.
As I was walking out of the subway station, it began to drizzle. Soon, it was pouring.
drizzle = light rain = mist = sprinkling
It had been drizzling all day.

voca.title: drizzly
voca.explains: When the weather is drizzly, the sky is dull and grey and it rains steadily but not very hard.\n

voca.title: drool
voca.explains:
To drool over someone or something means to look at them with great pleasure, perhaps in an exaggerated or ridiculous way.
If a person or animal drools, saliva drops slowly from their mouth.
Strands of drool dripped from its sharp, pointed teeth.

voca.title: droop
voca.means: [두^룹-p]\n(특히 지치거나 약해서)  아래로 처지다, 축 늘어지다, \n기운이 빠지다, 의기소침, 풀이 죽다
voca.explains: If something droops, it hangs or leans downwards with no strength or firmness.\n

voca.title: droopy
voca.explains: If you describe something as droopy, you mean that it hangs down with no strength or firmness.\n

voca.title: drop
voca.means:
[d뢉]
(잘못해서) 떨어지다, 떨어뜨리다, 
(너무 지쳐서) 쓰러지다, 쓰러질 것 같다
(아래로) 급 경사를 이루다
감소하다
(하던 일을) 그만 두다, 중단하다
방울, 소량
voca.explains:
If a level or amount drops or if someone or something drops it, it quickly becomes less.
If you drop something, you accidentally let it fall.
If something drops onto something else, it falls onto that thing. If something drops from somewhere, it falls from that place.
If you drop something somewhere or if it drops there, you deliberately let it fall there.
If a person or a part of their body drops to a lower position, or if they drop a part of their body to a lower position, they move to that position, often in a tired and lifeless way.
To drop is used in expressions such as to be about to drop and to dance until you drop to emphasize that you are exhausted and can no longer continue doing something.

voca.title: drop away
voca.explains: if the ground drops away, it slopes down steeply away from where you are\nto become less strong or disappear\n

voca.title: drop back
voca.explains: if a person in a group drops back, they move to a position further back behind other people, often because they are not able to stay at the front\n

voca.title: drop behind
voca.explains: if somebody drops behind or drops behind somebody/something, they move to a position behind other people\n

voca.title: drop by
voca.explains: to pay a short, informal visit to somebody, often without arranging this in advance\nPharmacies often have short operating hours, but not to worry! For basic medications like cold medicine or painkillers, you can just drop by a nearby convenience store.\n

voca.title: drop dead
voca.explains: die very suddenly\nused as a rude way of telling somebody to go away\n

voca.title: drop down
voca.explains: to lower yourself from a high place\n

voca.title: drop down to
voca.explains: On one side of the meadow, a cliff dropped down to the beach and ocean.\n

voca.title: drop in on
voca.explains: I'm going to drop in on Mom and see how she's doing?\n

voca.title: drop in the bucket
voca.explains: I saved $100 for a motorcycle but it's a drop in the bucket.\n

voca.title: drop names
voca.explains: mention famous people you know or have met in order to impress others\n

voca.title: drop off
voca.explains:
asleep / fall asleep / go to sleep / get to sleep / drift off / nod off / drop off
to fall into a light sleep
His father made a face. "For a moment I thought my life was over. The teacher was covered in goop. He shook his fist at me, and goop dropped off his hand onto the floor."

voca.title: drop open
voca.explains: Arthur's mouth dropped open.\n

voca.title: drop out
voca.means:
(참여하던 것에서) 빠지다, (전체에서) 떨어져 나가다, 
중퇴하다, 떠나가다, 낙오/탈퇴하다
탈퇴하다, 퇴거하다
(체제, 인습 등을) 거부하다
voca.explains:
to stop taking part in an activity, being a member of a group, etc.
to leave school, college, university, etc. without finishing your studies
to reject the accepted ideas, morals and values of society
Whether they started school and dropped out or never enrolled at all, these CEOs are proof that success doesn't have to be accompanied by a degree.

voca.title: drop someone off
voca.explains: I will drop you off there.\n

voca.title: drop something off
voca.explains: to stop and let somebody get out of a car, etc.; to deliver something to a place, often when you are on the way to somewhere else\n

voca.title: drop the ball
voca.explains: make a mistake and spoil something that you are responsible for\n

voca.title: drought
voca.explains: A drought is a long period of time during which no rain falls.\n

voca.title: drove
voca.means:
[두^로우-v]
(몰려가는) 가축 때, 대군중
(흔히 떼를 지어 움직이는 사람, 동물의) 무리
drive의 과거형

voca.title: drown
voca.means:
[듀^롸운]
물에 빠져 죽다, 익사하다, 익사 시키다, 물에 빠지다
흠뻑 젖게하다, (액체에) 잠기게 하다
삼켜버리다
voca.explains:
When someone drowns or is drowned, they die because they have gone or been pushed under water and cannot breathe.
If you say that a person or thing is drowning in something, you are emphasizing that they have a very large amount of it, or are completely covered in it.
If something drowns a sound, it is so loud that you cannot hear that sound properly.
If you say that someone is drowning their sorrows, you mean that they are drinking alcohol in order to forget something sad or upsetting that has happened to them.
We'll drown if we try.

voca.title: drown out
voca.means: 떠내려 보내다, \n(홍수로) 대피하다\n(소음이) ~을 들리지 않게 하다
voca.explains: if a sound drowns out somebody/something, it is so loud that they/it cannot be heard.\nA : And it also depends on where I am. If I'm at a coffee shop then I'll put on headphones and drown out the noise. But if I am in my room, I prefer it to be quiet.\n

voca.title: drowse
voca.explains: sleep / doze / nap / snooze / slumber / drowse\nIf you drowse, you are almost asleep or just asleep.\n

voca.title: drowse off
voca.explains: change from a waking to a sleeping state\nAnother time, I got on a bus after an office dinner. I soon dozed off. When I woke up, I was at the end of the line. I had missed my stop. I took a taxi home, and I drowsed off again in the cab.\n

voca.title: drowsy
voca.explains: If you feel drowsy, you feel sleepy and cannot think clearly.\nI pull so many all-nighters a week you would think that I would be out like a light. It’s a vicious cycle. Restless nights lead to drowsy mornings and I can’t get through the day without a power nap.\n

voca.title: drug
voca.explains:
A drug is a chemical which is given to people in order to treat or prevent an illness or disease.
Drugs are substances that some people take because of their pleasant effects, but which are usually illegal.
If you drug a person or animal, you give them a chemical substance in order to make them sleepy or unconscious.
If food or drink is drugged, a chemical substance is added to it in order to make someone sleepy or unconscious when they eat or drink it.

voca.title: drugstore
voca.means: [d^러gs토어r]\n약귝 (약품뿐만 아니라 화장품 같은 다른 품목도 취급함)
voca.explains: In the United States, a drugstore is a shop where drugs and medicines are sold or given out, and where you can buy cosmetics, some household goods, and also drinks and snacks.\n

voca.title: drum
voca.means:
[d^럼]
북, 드럼, (원통형) 통, 드럼통
북/드럼을 치다
(북을 치듯) 계속 두드리다
voca.explains:
A drum is a musical instrument consisting of a skin stretched tightly over a round frame. You play a drum by beating it with sticks or with your hands.
If something drums on a surface, or if you drum something on a surface, it hits it regularly, making a continuous beating sound.
If someone beats the drum or bangs the drum for something, they support it strongly.
"Your father's almost ready." D. W. drummed her fingers on the table. She didn't like to be patient.

voca.title: drum roll
voca.explains: A drum roll is a series of drumbeats that follow each other so quickly that they make a continuous sound. A drum roll is often used to show that someone important is arriving, or to introduce someone. \n"I just thought it might be nice to start off with a drum roll. For dramatic impact."\n

voca.title: dry
voca.means:
[듀^롸-이]
마른, 건조한, (날이) 가문, 비가 오지 않는
달지 않은, 단맛이 없는, 재미없는, 딱딱한
지루한
voca.explains:
boring / dull / tedious / uninteresting / dry
If something is dry, there is no water or moisture on it or in it.
If you say that your skin or hair is dry, you mean that it is less oily than, or not as soft as, normal.
If the weather or a period of time is dry, there is no rain or there is much less rain than average.
A dry place or climate is one that gets very little rainfall.

voca.title: dry flaky skin
voca.explains: Dermatologists label my skin type as combination as opposed to dry or oily. It’s a nightmare. I break out in the t-zone but can’t use harsh acne medication because it will result in dry, flaky skin.\n

voca.title: dry off
voca.explains: to become dry; to make somebody/something/yourself dry\n

voca.title: dry up
voca.means: (연못, 시냇물 등이) 완전이 마르다, 바닥나다, 침묵하다\n(공급이) 줄어들다/고갈되다\n(무슨말을 해야 할지 몰라서) 갑자기 말을 멈추다
voca.explains: if a supply of something dries up, it is no longer available\nif a river or a lake, etc. dries up, or something dries it up, it becomes completely dry\n

voca.title: dub
voca.means: [^닷]\n별명을 붙이다\n(영화 등을 다른 언어로) 재녹음하다, 더빙하다
voca.explains: If someone or something is dubbed a particular thing, they are given that description or name.\nIf a film or soundtrack in a foreign language is dubbed, a new soundtrack is added with actors giving a translation.\n

voca.title: duchess
voca.explains: A duchess is a woman who has the same rank as a duke, or who is a duke's wife or widow.\nTis where the family lives, the duke and duchess.\n

voca.title: duck
voca.means:
[^덕k]
오리
(머리나 몸을) 수그리다, 숨기다, 피하다
(특히 눈에 띄지 않기 위해) 급히 움직이다
(불쾌하거나 힘든 의무, 책무를) 피하다, 모면하다
(물 속에) 빠뜨리다, 밀어 넣다
voca.explains:
A duck is a very common water bird with short legs, a short neck, and a large flat beak.
If you duck, you move your head or the top half of your body quickly downwards to avoid something that might hit you, or to avoid being seen.
If you duck something such as a blow, you avoid it by moving your head or body quickly downwards.
You say that someone ducks a duty or responsibility when you disapprove of the fact that they avoid it.
You say that criticism is like water off a duck's back or water off a duck's back to emphasize that it is not having any effect on the person being criticized.
Jack and Annie ducked behind the rock. / Jack and Annie ducked again. / He ducked into a small tunnel.
Holding his glasses tightly, he ducked under.
They ducked under branches and pushed past bushed.
At the library the next morning, the Crosswires stood at the top of the steps. Muffy kept ducking behind her parents, but they kept pulling her out in front of them.

voca.title: duct
voca.explains: A duct is a pipe, tube, or channel which carries a liquid or gas.\nA duct is a tube in your body which carries a liquid such as tears or bile.\n

voca.title: due
voca.means:
[^듀우]
~로 인한, ~에 의한, ~ 때문/덕분에
~하기로 되어 있는/예정된
(돈을) 지불해야 하는
~을 받아야 하는, 받을 자격이 있는
세금, 수수료, 지불되어야 할 것
때문에, 정당한, 할 예정인, ~로 인한, 마땅한
voca.explains:
If an event is due to something, it happens or exists as a direct result of that thing.
You can say due to to introduce the reason for something happening. Some speakers of English believe that it is not correct to use due to in this way.
If something is due at a particular time, it is expected to happen, be done, or arrive at that time.
Due attention or consideration is the proper, reasonable, or deserved amount of it under the circumstances.
Something that is due, or that is due to someone, is owed to them, either as a debt or because they have a right to it.
If someone is due for something, that thing is planned to happen or be given to them now, or very soon, often after they have been waiting for it for a long time.
Dues are sums of money that you give regularly to an organization that you belong to, for example a social club or trade union, in order to pay for being a member.
Due is used before the words 'north', 'south', 'east', or 'west' to indicate that something is in exactly the direction mentioned.
If you say that something will happen or take place in due course, you mean that you cannot make it happen any quicker and it will happen when the time is right for it.
You can say 'to give him his due', or 'giving him his due' when you are admitting that there are some good things about someone, even though there are things that you do not like about them.

voca.title: due by
voca.explains: B : I had my pocket picked this morning. And my computer wasn't working and I lost two important reports due by tomorrow morning.\n

voca.title: due date
voca.explains: What was the due date?\n

voca.title: due to
voca.explains: Plus, due to the Internet, people get exposed to new styles much more easily.\n

voca.title: dug
voca.explains: Dug is the past tense and past participle of dig.\n

voca.title: dugout
voca.means:
[^덕아웃t]
(땅에 구덩이를 파서 만든) 대피호
(축구장, 야구장의) 선수 대기실
(나무통 안을 파내서 만든) 통나무 배
voca.explains:
A dugout is a small boat that is made by removing the inside of a log.
A dugout is a shelter made by digging a hole in the ground and then covering it or tunnelling so that the shelter has a roof over it.
Buster trudged back to the dugout as the other team ran off the field, cheering in victory.

voca.title: Duke
voca.means: [^듀-k]\n군주, 공작\n(특히 과거 유럽 지역 일부 소규모 독립 국가의) 통치자/군주
voca.explains: A duke is a man with a very high social rank.\n

voca.title: dull
voca.means:
[달]
따분한, 재미없는, 
흐릿한, 칙칙한, 윤기없는, 둔탁한
침체된, 부진한, 
둔해지다, 약해지다, 흐릿해지다
voca.explains:
boring / dull / tedious / uninteresting / dry
If you describe someone or something as dull, you mean they are not interesting or exciting.
Someone or something that is dull is not very lively or energetic.
A dull colour or light is not bright.
You say the weather is dull when it is very cloudy.
Dull sounds are not very clear or loud.
If something dulls or if it is dulled, it becomes less intense, bright, or lively.

voca.title: dumb
voca.means:
[^담]
벙어리의, 말을 못하는, 
침묵시키다, 침묵하다
멍청한, 바보같은, 우둔한, 어리석은
voca.explains:
Someone who is dumb is completely unable to speak.
If someone is dumb on a particular occasion, they cannot speak because they are angry, shocked, or surprised.
If you call a person dumb, you mean that they are stupid or foolish.
If you say that something is dumb, you think that it is silly and annoying.
Francine folded her fingers together. "What do you say, Daddy? Please! I can't even throw straight because I'm worrying what dumb thing Arthur's going to do next."

voca.title: dump
voca.means:
[^담p]
버리다, 염가판매하다
~을 (~에게) 떠넘기다, 
(아무렇게나) 내려놓다
쓰레기 더미, 쓰레기 버리는 곳
voca.explains:
If you dump something somewhere, you put it or unload it there quickly and carelessly.
If something is dumped somewhere, it is put or left there because it is no longer wanted or needed.
To dump something such as an idea, policy, or practice means to stop supporting or using it.
If a firm or company dumps goods, it sells large quantities of them at prices far below their real value, usually in another country, in order to gain a bigger market share or to keep prices high in the home market.
If you dump someone, you end your relationship with them.
To dump computer data or memory means to copy it from one storage system onto another, such as from disk to magnetic tape.
A dump is a place where rubbish is left, for example on open ground outside a town.
If you say that a place is a dump, you think it is ugly and unpleasant to live in or visit.
Arthur dumped some cereal in her bowl.

voca.title: dump on somebody
voca.explains: to treat somebody unfairly, especially by giving them too much to do or unpleasant tasks\nto tell somebody all your problems\n

voca.title: dumpling
voca.means:
[^덤블륑]
덤플링(고기 요리에 넣어 먹는 새알심)
(흔히 안에 과일이 든 디저트용) 경단
만두
voca.explains: Dumplings are small lumps of dough that are cooked and eaten, either with meat and vegetables or as part of a sweet pudding.\nThe owner knew us well, because we were regulars. She used to give us free dumplings sometimes.\n

voca.title: dunce
voca.explains: If you say that someone is a dunce, you think they are rather stupid because they find it difficult or impossible to learn what someone is trying to teach them.\nD.W. was not impressed. "You don't seem to be dealing very well. Have you tried dunce? That sort of rhymes with crunch."\n

voca.title: dungeon
voca.means: [^던젼]\n(과거 특히 성 안에 있던) 지하 감옥
voca.explains: A dungeon is a dark underground prison in a castle.\nHe saw himself chained to the wall of a dark dungeon.\n

voca.title: duplicate
voca.means:
[^듀-플리케잇t]
복사/복제하다, 사본을 만들다
(특히 불필요한 것을) 다시(중복해서) 하다
(다른 무엇과) 똑같은, 꼭 닮은, 사본의
사본
voca.explains:
If you duplicate something that has already been done, you repeat or copy it.
To duplicate something which has been written, drawn, or recorded onto tape means to make exact copies of it.
Duplicate is used to describe things that have been made as an exact copy of other things, usually in order to serve the same purpose.

voca.title: durable
voca.explains: Something that is durable is strong and lasts a long time without breaking or becoming weaker.\n

voca.title: duration
voca.explains: The duration of an event or state is the time during which it happens or exists.\nIf you say that something will happen for the duration, you mean that it will happen for as long as a particular situation continues.\n

voca.title: dusk
voca.explains: Dusk is the time just before night when the daylight has almost gone but when it is not completely dark.\n

voca.title: dusky
voca.explains:
Dusky means rather dark.
A dusky colour is soft rather than bright.
Chimney smoke rose into the dusky sky.
High overhead, a bird was soaring through the dusky sky.

voca.title: dustpan
voca.explains: A dustpan is a small flat container made of metal or plastic. You hold it flat on the floor and put dirt and dust into it using a brush.\n

voca.title: dusty
voca.explains:
dirty / dusty / filthy / soiled / grubby
If places, roads, or other things outside are dusty, they are covered with tiny bits of earth or sand, usually because it has not rained for a long time.
If a room, house, or object is dusty, it is covered with very small pieces of dirt.

voca.title: duty
voca.means: [^듀-디]\n(도덕적, 법률적) 의무, 임무, 직무, \n(특히 국내로 들여오는 물품에 대한) 관세, 세금
voca.explains:
tax / duty / customs / tariff / levy / excise
Duty is work that you have to do for your job.
Your duties are tasks which you have to do because they are part of your job.
If you say that something is your duty, you believe that you ought to do it because it is your responsibility
Duties are taxes which you pay to the government on goods that you buy.

voca.title: duty-free
voca.explains: Duty-free goods are sold at airports or on planes or ships at a cheaper price than usual because you do not have to pay import tax on them.\n

voca.title: duty-free shop
voca.explains: A duty-free shop is a shop, for example at an airport, where you can buy goods at a cheaper price than usual, because no tax is paid on them.\n

voca.title: dwell
voca.explains:
If you dwell on something, especially something unpleasant, you think, speak, or write about it a lot or for quite a long time.
If you dwell somewhere, you live there.
"So there dwells the Raven King! I had thought his nest was in the Otherworld."

voca.title: dwell upon
voca.explains: to think or talk about something for too long, especially something unpleasant\nto look at something for a long time\n

voca.title: dye
voca.explains: If you dye something such as hair or cloth, you change its colour by soaking it in a special liquid.\nDye is a substance made from plants or chemicals which is mixed into a liquid and used to change the colour of something such as cloth or hair.\n

voca.title: dying
voca.explains:
Dying is the present participle of die.
A dying person or animal is very ill and likely to die soon.
You use dying to describe something which happens at the time when someone dies, or is connected with that time.
The dying days or dying minutes of a state of affairs or an activity are its last days or minutes.
A dying tradition or industry is becoming less important and is likely to disappear completely.
"Camelot is dying!" the Christmas Knight boomed.

voca.title: dynamite
voca.explains:
Dynamite is a type of explosive that contains nitroglycerin.
If you describe a piece of information as dynamite, you think that people will react strongly to it.
If you describe someone or something as dynamite, you think that they are exciting.

voca.title: dynasty
voca.explains:
A dynasty is a series of rulers of a country who all belong to the same family.
A dynasty is a period of time during which a country is ruled by members of the same family.
A dynasty is a family which has members from two or more generations who are important in a particular field of activity, for example in business or politics.

voca.title: each
voca.explains:
each / every
If you refer to each thing or each person in a group, you are referring to every member of the group and considering them as individuals.
If you refer to each one of the members of a group, you are emphasizing that something applies to every one of them.
You can refer to each and every member of a group to emphasize that you mean all the members of that group.

voca.title: each other
voca.explains: used when the action, attribution, etc, is reciprocal\n

voca.title: each other's company
voca.explains: When we got to the picnic site, we sprang into action. I lit the fire. My friends prepped the ingredients and doled out drinks. Soon, the barbecue was in full swing. The meat was mouth-watering. We cooked the steaks just so. We enjoyed the meal and each other’s company.\n

voca.title: each time
voca.explains: But each time, he got up and hurled himself closer to shore.\n

voca.title: eager
voca.explains:
If you are eager to do or have something, you want to do or have it very much.
If you look or sound eager, you look or sound as if you expect something interesting or enjoyable to happen.
Jake was eager to get going - before Squanto could ask them questions about the past.
That’s why it’s important to get behind the right candidate. Most get the day off on Election Day. They wake up early, eager to vote.

voca.title: eagle
voca.explains: An eagle is a large bird that lives by eating small animals.\nIf you talk about a person's eagle eye, you mean that they are watching someone or something carefully or are very good at noticing things.\n

voca.title: ear
voca.explains:
Your ears are the two parts of your body, one on each side of your head, with which you hear sounds.
If you have an ear for music or language, you are able to hear its sounds accurately and to interpret them or reproduce them well.
Ear is often used to refer to people's willingness to listen to what someone is saying.
The ears of a cereal plant such as wheat or barley are the parts at the top of the stem, which contain the seeds or grains.

voca.title: earbud
voca.explains: B : Yes. I’m thinking of buying some earbuds or a smartphone cover for him.\n

voca.title: earlier
voca.explains: Earlier is the comparative of early.\nEarlier is used to refer to a point or period in time before the present or before the one you are talking about.\n

voca.title: earlobe
voca.explains: our earlobes are the soft parts at the bottom of your ears.\n

voca.title: early
voca.means:
[^어r-얼뤼]
(어떤 기간, 사건 등의) 초(창)기의, 이른, 조기의
(보통, 예상, 계획보다) 빠른/이른
(어떤 기간, 사건 등의) 초(창)기에, 일찍, 조기에
(현재 시간보다) 앞에, 전에, 
(~보다) 전에, 이미
voca.explains:
Early means before the usual time that a particular event or activity happens.
Early means before the time that was arranged or expected.
Early means near the beginning of a day, week, year, or other period of time.
Early means near the beginning of a period in history, or in the history of something such as the world, a society, or an activity.
Early means near the beginning of something such as a piece of work or a process.
Early refers to plants which flower or crop before or at the beginning of the main season.
Early reports or indications of something are the first reports or indications about it.

voca.title: earmuff
voca.explains: one of a pair of pads of fur or cloth, joined by a headband, for keeping the ears warm\n

voca.title: earn
voca.means:
[^어r-언]
(일을 하여 돈을)벌다, 획득하다
(이자, 수익을) 올리다/받다
(그럴만한 자격, 자질이 되어서 무엇을) 받다
voca.explains:
If you earn money, you receive money in return for work that you do.
If something earns money, it produces money as profit or interest.
If you earn something such as praise, you get it because you deserve it.
earn a wage / earn ~ points
We can live on what I earn.

voca.title: earn a return on one's investment
voca.explains:
However, I couldn’t earn a return on my investment. At time, the losses were quite sizeable. The biggest problem was that stock trading is all-consuming.
It might take some time to rearn a return on your investment.
He couldn't be sure of earning a return on his investment.

voca.title: earnest
voca.explains:
If something is done or happens in earnest, it happens to a much greater extent and more seriously than before.
If you are in earnest, you are sincere in what you are doing and saying.
Earnest people are very serious and sincere in what they say or do, because they think that their actions and beliefs are important.

voca.title: earnestly
voca.explains:
If you say something earnestly, you say it very seriously, often because you believe that it is important or you are trying to persuade someone else to believe it.
If you do something earnestly, you do it in a thorough and serious way, intending to succeed.
If you earnestly hope or wish for something, you hope or wish strongly and sincerely for it.

voca.title: earring
voca.explains: Earrings are pieces of jewellery which you attach to your ears.\n

voca.title: earth
voca.explains:
floor / ground / land / earth / soil
Earth or the Earth is the planet on which we live. People usually say Earth when they are referring to the planet as part of the universe, and the Earth when they are talking about the planet as the place where we live.
The earth is the land surface on which we live and move about.
Earth is the substance on the land surface of the earth, for example clay or sand, in which plants grow.
The earth in an electric plug or piece of electrical equipment is the wire through which electricity can pass into the ground, which makes the equipment safe if something goes wrong with it.

voca.title: earthen
voca.explains: Earthen containers and objects are made of clay that is baked so that it becomes hard.\nAn earthen floor, bank, or mound is made of hard earth.\n

voca.title: earthquake
voca.explains: An earthquake is a shaking of the ground caused by movement of the earth's crust.\nThe Pacific Tsunami Warning System alerts the public of earthquakes or other disturbances that take place at sea.\n

voca.title: ease
voca.means:
[^이-z]
쉬움, 용이함, 편의성, 
(근심, 걱정 없이) 편안함, 안락함
편해지다, 편하게 해 주다, (고통, 불편 등이) 덜해지다
조심조심/천천히 움직이다/옮기다
~을 편하게 하다, 완화하다, 덜어주다
편안함, 안락함
voca.explains:
If you talk about the ease of a particular activity, you are referring to the way that it has been made easier to do, or to the fact that it is already easy to do.
Ease is the state of being very comfortable and able to live as you want, without any worries or problems.
If something unpleasant eases or if you ease it, it is reduced in degree, speed, or intensity.
If you ease your way somewhere or ease somewhere, you move there slowly, carefully, and gently. If you ease something somewhere, you move it there slowly, carefully, and gently.
He swooped with ease back down to Annie.

voca.title: ease off
voca.explains: to gradually become less strong or unpleasant\nto go slower or make less effort\n

voca.title: ease the pain
voca.explains:
However, the pain was back the next morning. I had to apply a new patch before my morning commute. The patch helped to ease the pain.
I took some painkillers to ease the pain.
A hot bath can ease the pain.

voca.title: ease up
voca.explains:
to go slower or make less effort; to do something less
to start being less severe with somebody
"Good. Try again. But this time ease up a little. Don't wear your arm out the first day."

voca.title: easel
voca.explains: An easel is a wooden frame that supports a picture which an artist is painting or drawing.\n

voca.title: easily
voca.means:
[^이즐릐]
쉽게, 수월하게, 용이하게
아마 틀림없이, 필시
분명히(의심할 여지없이) 최고의, 가장 종은 등
쉽게/잘 (~하는 경향이 있는)
voca.explains: You use easily to emphasize that something is very likely to happen, or is very likely to be true.\nYou use easily to say that something happens more quickly or more often than is usual or normal.\n

voca.title: eastern
voca.explains: Eastern means in or from the east of a region, state, or country.\nEastern means coming from or associated with the people or countries of the East, such as India, China, or Japan.\n

voca.title: easy
voca.explains:
If a job or action is easy, you can do it without difficulty or effort, because it is not complicated and causes no problems.
If you describe an action or activity as easy, you mean that it is done in a confident, relaxed way. If someone is easy about something, they feel relaxed and confident about it.
If you say that someone has an easy life, you mean that they live comfortably without any problems or worries.
If you say that something is easy or too easy, you are criticizing someone because they have done the most obvious or least difficult thing, and have not considered the situation carefully enough.
If you describe someone or something as easy prey or as an easy target, you mean that they can easily be attacked or criticized.
If you tell someone to go easy on something, you are telling them to use only a small amount of it.
A little too easy, he thought.

voca.title: easy come, easy go
voca.means: (속담) 쉽게 얻은 것에는 별로 애착을 못 느끼는 법이다[없어져도 별로 아쉬워하지 않는다]
voca.explains: something that has been obtained very easily and quickly may be lost or wasted in the same way\n

voca.title: easy money
voca.explains: money earned for very little work or effort, often by doing something dishonest\n

voca.title: easy-going
voca.explains: If you describe someone as easy-going, you mean that they are not easily annoyed, worried, or upset, and you think this is a good quality.\nThankfully, my friend is very easy-going. He accepted my apology.\n

voca.title: eat
voca.explains:
eat - ate - eaten
When you eat something, you put it into your mouth, chew it, and swallow it.
If you eat sensibly or healthily, you eat food that is good for you.
If you eat, you have a meal.
If something is eating you, it is annoying or worrying you.

voca.title: eat into something
voca.explains: to gradually damage or destroy something\nto use or take away a large part of something valuable, especially money or time\n

voca.title: eat irregularly
voca.explains:
It was just chronic fatigue. There were many reasons for my sluggishness. I wasn’t getting enough exercise. I was eating irregularly.
Eating irregularly is a common problem among people.
I gained weight because I ate irregularly.

voca.title: eat out
voca.explains: to have a meal in a restaurant, etc. rather than at home\nA : It's so nice to eat out and have time together.\n

voca.title: eat somebody up
voca.explains: if an emotion such as anger, etc. eats somebody up, it worries them all the time and they cannot think of anything else\n

voca.title: eat something away
voca.explains: to gradually damage or destroy something over a period of time\n

voca.title: eat something up
voca.explains: to eat all the food you have been given\n

voca.title: eat up
voca.explains: used to tell somebody to eat quickly or to eat everything they have been given\n

voca.title: eatery
voca.explains:
An eatery is a place where you can buy and eat food.
I sometimes post reviews of my favorite eateries on social media. It’s not just to brag. It’s in the hopes that other people will be able to benefit from the information.
We searched for a good eatery to get some dinner.
What's your favorite eatery around here?

voca.title: ebony
voca.explains: Ebony is a very hard, heavy, dark-coloured wood.\nSomething that is ebony is a very deep black colour.\n

voca.title: eclipse
voca.means:
[이^클립s]
(일식, 월식의) 식
(천체가 천체를)가리다, 그늘지게하다
(천문) 식, 빛의 소멸
(중요성, 권력 등이) 빛을 잃음, 퇴색
voca.explains: An eclipse of the sun is an occasion when the moon is between the earth and the sun, so that for a short time you cannot see part or all of the sun. An eclipse of the moon is an occasion when the earth is between the sun and the moon, so that for a short time you cannot see part or all of the moon.\nIf one thing is eclipsed by a second thing that is bigger, newer, or more important than it, the first thing is no longer noticed because the second thing gets all the attention.\n

voca.title: eco-friendly
voca.explains:
In eco-friendly cars, fuel efficiency is getting better every year. Drivers can protect the environment, and also save some cash. Hybrid cars have already been widely commercialized.
I would like to buy a more eco-friendly product.
Organic food is grown in an eco-friendly manner.
The biggest benefit is that a tumbler is eco-friendly. Paper cups are wasteful. That’s why I bring my tumbler wherever I go.
Convenient things are often not eco-friendly.
Riding bicycles is eco-friendly.

voca.title: ecology
voca.explains: Ecology is the study of the relationships between plants, animals, people, and their environment, and the balances between these relationships.\nWhen you talk about the ecology of a place, you are referring to the pattern and balance of relationships between plants, animals, people, and the environment in that place.\n

voca.title: economic
voca.explains:
economic / economical / financial / commercial / monetary / budgetary
Economic means concerned with the organization of the money, industry, and trade of a country, region, or society.
If something is economic, it produces a profit.

voca.title: economics
voca.explains: Economics is the study of the way in which money, industry, and trade are organized in a society.\nThe economics of a society or industry is the system of organizing money and trade in it.\n

voca.title: economy
voca.means:
[이^커너미]
경기, 경제, 절약, 경제 활동, 수입
경제적인
(경기 주체로서의) 국가
할인 가격으로
voca.explains:
An economy is the system according to which the money, industry, and trade of a country or region are organized.
A country's economy is the wealth that it gets from business and industry.
Economy is the use of the minimum amount of money, time, or other resources needed to achieve something, so that nothing is wasted.
Economy services such as travel are cheap and have no luxuries or extras.

voca.title: ecstatic
voca.explains:
excited / ecstatic / elated / rapturous / euphoric / exhilarated / on top of the world
If you are ecstatic, you feel very happy and full of excitement.
You can use ecstatic to describe reactions that are very enthusiastic and excited. For example, if someone receives an ecstatic reception or an ecstatic welcome, they are greeted with great enthusiasm and excitement.

voca.title: edge
voca.means:
[^에엣쥐]
(가운데에서 가장 먼) 끝, 가장자리, 날, 테두리, 경계
(칼 등의) 날, 위기
조금씩 나아가다, 움직이다, 이동시키다, 날을 갈다
voca.explains:
The edge of something is the place or line where it stops, or the part of it that is furthest from the middle.
The edge of something sharp such as a knife or an axe is its sharp or narrow side.
The edge of something, especially something bad, is the point at which it may start to happen.
If someone or something has an edge, they have an advantage that makes them stronger or more likely to be successful than another thing or person.
He edged his way to the door. His mother had reached Mr. Haney's envelope.

voca.title: edit
voca.explains:
If you edit a text such as an article or a book, you correct and adapt it so that it is suitable for publishing.
If you edit a book or a series of books, you collect several pieces of writing by different authors and prepare them for publishing.
If you edit a film or a television or radio programme, you choose some of what has been filmed or recorded and arrange it in a particular order.
Someone who edits a newspaper, magazine, or journal is in charge of it.
An edit is the process of examining and correcting a text so that it is suitable for publishing.

voca.title: educate
voca.explains: When someone, especially a child, is educated, he or she is taught at a school or college.\nTo educate people means to teach them better ways of doing something or a better way of living.\n

voca.title: education
voca.explains: Education involves teaching people various subjects, usually at a school or college, or being taught.\nEducation of a particular kind involves teaching the public about a particular issue.\n

voca.title: eel
voca.explains: An eel is a long, thin fish that looks like a snake.\nAn eel slithered through the water.\n

voca.title: eerie
voca.explains: If you describe something as eerie, you mean that it seems strange and frightening, and makes you feel nervous.\nThey invite you to come with them to an outlying realm of Camelot where strange and eerie things are happening at a duke's castle.\n

voca.title: effect
voca.means:
[이^풱t]
결과, 효과, 영향, 인상
소지품
~을 초래하다, 
(어떤 결과를)) 가져오다
voca.explains:
affect / effect
effect / result / consequence / outcome / repercussion
The effect of one thing on another is the change that the first thing causes in the second thing.
An effect is an impression that someone creates deliberately, for example in a place or in a piece of writing.
The effects in a film are the specially created sounds and scenery.
If you effect something that you are trying to achieve, you succeed in causing it to happen.
If you say that someone is doing something for effect, you mean that they are doing it in order to impress people and to draw attention to themselves.
You add in effect to a statement or opinion that is not precisely accurate, but which you feel is a reasonable description or summary of a particular situation.
If you put, bring, or carry a plan or idea into effect, you cause it to happen in practice.
If a law or policy takes effect or comes into effect at a particular time, it officially begins to apply or be valid from that time. If it remains in effect, it still applies or is still valid.
You can say that something takes effect when it starts to produce the results that are intended.

voca.title: effective
voca.means:
[이^풱디v]
유력한, 유능한
효과적인, 유효한, 감동적인
실질적인, 사실상의
감동적인, 눈에 띄는, 인상적인
시행/발효되는
voca.explains:
Something that is effective works well and produces the results that were intended.
Effective means having a particular role or result in practice, though not officially or in theory.
When something such as a law or an agreement becomes effective, it begins officially to apply or be valid.
Many people tune into radio shows on EBS to learn English. As with most things, EBS programs are most effective when they are used strategically.
The class is effective for raising test scores.
Hot water is effective for cleaning dishes.
Many people tune into radio shows on EBS to learn English. As with most things, EBS programs are most effective when they are used strategically. Tuning in casually is good.

voca.title: effectively
voca.explains: You use effectively with a statement or opinion to indicate that it is not accurate in every detail, but that you feel it is a reasonable description or summary of a particular situation.\n

voca.title: efficiency
voca.explains: Efficiency is the quality of being able to do a task successfully, without wasting time or energy.\nIn physics and engineering, efficiency is the ratio between the amount of energy a machine needs to make it work, and the amount it produces.\n

voca.title: efficient
voca.explains: You'll learn how to use functions to make your code more efficient and flexible.\n

voca.title: effort
voca.means: [^에퍼r-t]\n수고, 애, 수고를 요허는 것, 노력, 공\n(노력의) 결과, 결실
voca.explains:
If you make an effort to do something, you try very hard to do it.
If you say that someone did something with effort or with an effort, you mean it was difficult for them to do.
An effort is a particular series of activities that is organized by a group of people in order to achieve something.
If you say that something is an effort, you mean that an unusual amount of physical or mental energy is needed to do it.

voca.title: effortless
voca.means: [^에퍼r-t뤼s]\n힘들이지 않는, 수월해 보이는\n(행위, 일이) 노력이 필요 없는, 쉽게 되는, 용이한.
voca.explains:
Something that is effortless is done easily and well.
You use effortless to describe a quality that someone has naturally and does not have to learn.
There was something effortless about our heart-to-heart. It was clear that something clicked. A small gesture like opening a door made a world of difference.

voca.title: egotist
voca.explains: An egotist is someone who is egotistic.

voca.title: either
voca.means:
[이더r]
(둘 중) 어느쪽 하나, 어느쪽
(두 개) 각각, 양쪽(의)
어느쪽의,  어느쪽의 ~ 도
(부정문에서) ~도 또한, ~라고는 하지만
(정보를 덧붙일 떄)
voca.explains:
neither / either
You use either in front of the first of two or more alternatives, when you are stating the only possibilities or choices that there are. The other alternatives are introduced by 'or'.
You use either in a negative statement in front of the first of two alternatives to indicate that the negative statement refers to both the alternatives.
You can use either to refer to one of two things, people, or situations, when you want to say that they are both possible and it does not matter which one is chosen or considered.
You use either by itself in negative statements to indicate that there is a similarity or connection with a person or thing that you have just mentioned.
They broke into the circle on either side of the knights.
"Boss, I got to get something off my chest. You're a terrible boss. I don't want to work for you anymore. Either pay me a lot more money or I'm leaving."

voca.title: eject
voca.explains:
If you eject someone from a place, you force them to leave.
To eject something means to remove it or push it out forcefully.
When a pilot ejects from an aircraft, he or she leaves the aircraft quickly using an ejector seat, usually because the plane is about to crash.

voca.title: eke
voca.explains: If you eke a living or eke out an existence, you manage to survive with very little money.\n

voca.title: eke out living
voca.explains: I've been eking out a living for too long.\n

voca.title: eke something out
voca.explains: to make a small supply of something last longer by using only a little at a time or by adding something else to it\neke out somethingto manage to live with very little money\n

voca.title: elaborate
voca.means:
[일^롸버r뤠잇t]
~을 정성들여 만들어 내다, 갈고 다듬다
(더) 자세히 말/설명 하다, 
정교한, 공들인, 정성들인
voca.explains:
You use elaborate to describe something that is very complex because it has a lot of different parts.
Elaborate plans, systems, and procedures are complicated because they have been planned in very great detail, sometimes too much detail.
Elaborate clothing or material is made with a lot of detailed artistic designs.
If you elaborate a plan or theory, you develop it by making it more complicated and more effective.

voca.title: elaborate on
voca.explains: to explain or describe something in a more detailed way\n

voca.title: elapse
voca.explains: When time elapses, it passes.\n

voca.title: elastic
voca.explains:
Elastic is a rubber material that stretches when you pull it and returns to its original size and shape when you let it go. Elastic is often used in clothes to make them fit tightly, for example round the waist.
Something that is elastic is able to stretch easily and then return to its original size and shape.
If ideas, plans, or policies are elastic, they are able to change to suit new circumstances or conditions as they occur.

voca.title: elbow
voca.explains:
Your elbow is the part of your arm where the upper and lower halves of the arm are joined.
If you elbow people aside or elbow your way somewhere, you push people with your elbows in order to move somewhere.
If someone or something elbows their way somewhere, or elbows other people or things out of the way, they achieve success by being aggressive and determined.
I lost my balance and fell over. I got scrapes on my elbows and knees. I also had some light bruising.

voca.title: elder
voca.means: [엘더r]\n나이가 더 많은, (가족 구성원 두 명중) 손윗사람/연장자\n원로들, 장로들, (기독교의) 장로
voca.explains:
older / elder
The elder of two people is the one who was born first.
A person's elder is someone who is older than them, especially someone quite a lot older.
In some societies, an elder is one of the respected older people who have influence and authority.
An elder is a bush or small tree which has groups of small white flowers and black berries.

voca.title: elderly
voca.means: [^엘더뤼]\n연세가 드신 사람들이\n연세 드신 분들, 어르신 들
voca.explains:
old / elderly / aged / long-lived / mature
You use elderly as a polite way of saying that someone is old.
These seats are dedicated to the elderly.

voca.title: elderly parents
voca.explains:
In Korea, cash is a common and widely-accepted gift. Many different occasions call for cash gifts. For example, elderly parents often receive pocket money from their children. Surveys have found that cash is the most popular holiday gift.
She looks after her elderly parents by herself.
HIs elderly parents made many sacrifices for him.

voca.title: eldest
voca.explains: The eldest person in a group is the one who was born before all the others.\n

voca.title: elect
voca.explains:
When people elect someone, they choose that person to represent them, by voting for them.
If you elect to do something, you choose to do it.
Elect is added after words such as 'president' or 'governor' to indicate that a person has been elected to the post but has not officially started to carry out the duties involved.

voca.title: election
voca.explains:
election / vote / poll / referendum / straw poll / ballot / show of hands
An election is a process in which people vote to choose a person or group of people to hold an official position.
The election of a particular person or group of people is their success in winning an election.

voca.title: electric
voca.explains:
electric / electrical
An electric device or machine works by means of electricity, rather than using some other source of power.
An electric current, voltage, or charge is one that is produced by electricity.
Electric plugs, sockets, or power lines are designed to carry electricity.
If you describe the atmosphere of a place or event as electric, you mean that people are in a state of great excitement.

voca.title: electrical
voca.explains:
electric / electrical
Electrical goods, equipment, or appliances work by means of electricity.
Electrical systems or parts supply or use electricity.
Electrical energy is energy in the form of electricity.
Electrical industries, engineers, or workers are involved in the production and supply of electricity or electrical goods.

voca.title: electrician
voca.explains: An electrician is a person whose job is to install and repair electrical equipment.\n

voca.title: electricity
voca.means: [일뤡추^릑시디]\n전기, 전력, 전기학\n(남에게도 감염할 듯한) 심한 흥분, 열정
voca.explains: Electricity is a form of energy that can be carried by wires and is used for heating and lighting, and to provide power for machines.\n

voca.title: electronic
voca.explains: An electronic device has transistors or silicon chips which control and change the electric current passing through the device.\nAn electronic process or activity involves the use of electronic devices.\n

voca.title: electronic gadget
voca.explains: Wireless devices have become mainstream these days. More and more electronic gadgets are going wireless.\n

voca.title: elegant
voca.explains: If you describe a person or thing as elegant, you mean that they are pleasing and graceful in appearance or style.\nIf you describe a piece of writing, an idea, or a plan as elegant, you mean that it is simple, clear, and clever.\n

voca.title: element
voca.means:
[^엘러먼t]
요소, 성분, 구성, 원리
(집단, 사회 내의 특정) 부류/파
원소(그 이상 분해할 수 없는 화학적 요소)
기본 (원리)
(특히 동물 본래의) 환경
voca.explains:
The different elements of something are the different parts it contains.
A particular element of a situation, activity, or process is an important quality or feature that it has or needs.
When you talk about elements within a society or organization, you are referring to groups of people who have similar aims, beliefs, or habits.
If something has an element of a particular quality or emotion, it has a certain amount of this quality or emotion.
An element is a substance such as gold, oxygen, or carbon that consists of only one type of atom.
The element in an electric fire or water heater is the metal part which changes the electric current into heat.
You can refer to the weather, especially wind and rain, as the elements.
If you say that someone is in their element, you mean that they are in a situation they enjoy.

voca.title: elementary
voca.explains: Something that is elementary is very simple and basic.\n

voca.title: elephant
voca.explains: An elephant is a very large animal with a long, flexible nose called a trunk, which it uses to pick up things. Elephants live in India and Africa.\n

voca.title: elicit
voca.means:
[일^리씯]
(정보, 반응을 어렵게) 이끌어 내다
(진리 등을 논리적으로) 도출하다, 이끌어 내다
(사실, 대답, 웃음 등을) 유도해 내다
voca.explains: If you elicit a response or a reaction, you do or say something which makes other people respond or react.\nIf you elicit a piece of information, you get it by asking the right questions.\n

voca.title: elide
voca.explains: If you elide something, especially a distinction, you leave it out or ignore it.\nIn linguistics, if you elide a word, you do not pronounce or write it fully.\n

voca.title: eliminate
voca.means:
[일^뤼미네잇t]
제거하다, 없애다, 삭제하다
(시합 등에서) 탈락시키다
(적, 적수를) 제거하다/죽이다
voca.explains:
To eliminate something, especially something you do not want or need, means to remove it completely.
When a person or team is eliminated from a competition, they are defeated and so take no further part in the competition.
If someone says that they have eliminated an enemy, they mean that they have killed them. By using the word 'eliminate', they are trying to make the action sound more positive than if they used the word 'kill'.
I like to keep my surroundings well-organized. Having too many things on my desk distracts me when I work. That’s why I adore Bluetooth. It eliminates the need for messy wires.

voca.title: elision
voca.explains: the omission of a syllable or vowel at the beginning or end of a word, esp when a word ending with a vowel is next to one beginning with a vowel\nany omission of a part or parts\n

voca.title: elk
voca.explains: An elk is a type of large deer. Elks have big, flat horns called antlers and are found in Northern Europe, Asia, and North America. Some British speakers use elk to refer to the European and Asian varieties of this animal, and moose to refer to the North American variety.\n

voca.title: eloquent
voca.means: [^엘뤄퀀t]\n웅변/연설을 잘 하는, 유창한\n감정을 드러내는, 무언의 웅변을 하는
voca.explains: Speech or writing that is eloquent is well expressed and effective in persuading people.\nA person who is eloquent is good at speaking and able to persuade people.\n

voca.title: eloquent speaker
voca.explains: However, I still have a lot to learn. I plan to try even harder to become a more eloquent speaker.\n

voca.title: else
voca.means: [^엘s]\n(이미 언급된 것에 덧붙여) 또, 그 밖의, 다른\n그렇지 않으면, ~이 아니면
voca.explains:
You use else after words such as 'anywhere', 'someone', and 'what', to refer in a vague way to another person, place, or thing.
You use else after words such as 'everyone', 'everything', and 'everywhere' to refer in a vague way to all the other people, things, or places except the one you are talking about.
You use or else after stating a logical conclusion, to indicate that what you are about to say is evidence for that conclusion.
You use or else to introduce a statement that indicates the unpleasant results that will occur if someone does or does not do something.
You use or else to introduce the second of two possibilities when you do not know which one is true.

voca.title: elsewhere
voca.means: [^엘s웨어r]\n다른 곳, 어떤 딴 곳에, 어느 곳이나
voca.explains: Elsewhere means in other places or to another place.\n

voca.title: embank
voca.means: [엠^뱅k]\n~을 뚝/제방으로 둘러 싸다\n(저수지 등을) 방죽으로 둘러싸다
voca.explains: to protect, enclose, or confine (a waterway, road, etc) with an embankment\n

voca.title: embankment
voca.explains: An embankment is a thick wall of earth that is built to carry a road or railway over an area of low ground, or to prevent water from a river or the sea from flooding the area.\n

voca.title: embark
voca.explains: If you embark on something new, difficult, or exciting, you start doing it.\nWhen someone embarks on a ship, they go on board before the start of a journey.\n

voca.title: embark on
voca.explains: to start to do something new, important or difficult\n

voca.title: embarrass
voca.explains:
If something or someone embarrasses you, they make you feel shy or ashamed.
If something embarrasses a public figure such as a politician or an organization such as a political party, it causes problems for them.
I get embarrassed when I look back on my past.
I lost my balance and fell over. I got scrapes on my elbows and knees. I also had some light bruising. I wasn't hurt, but I was embarrassed. It was very humiliating.

voca.title: embarrassing
voca.explains: Something that is embarrassing makes you feel shy or ashamed.\nSomething that is embarrassing to a public figure such as a politician or an organization such as a political party causes problems for them.\n

voca.title: embarrassment
voca.means:
[임^붸어러s먼t]
어색함, 쑥스러움
곤란한/난처한 상황
(다른 사람을) 곤란하게 하는 사람, 골칫거리
voca.explains:
Embarrassment is the feeling you have when you are embarrassed.
An embarrassment is an action, event, or situation which causes problems for a politician, political party, government, or other public group.
If you refer to a person as an embarrassment, you mean that you disapprove of them but cannot avoid your connection with them.
However, the embarrassment was even worse. I was mortified. I was the center of attention in a crowd of people.

voca.title: embed
voca.means: [임베d]\n(단단히) 박다, 끼워넣다, 새겨넣다, 파묻다\n(다른 절 속에) 절을 끼워 넣다, 내포절을 넣다
voca.explains: If an object embeds itself in a substance or thing, it becomes fixed there firmly and deeply.\nIf something such as an attitude or feeling is embedded in a society or system, or in someone's personality, it becomes a permanent and noticeable feature of it.\n

voca.title: embrace
voca.means:
[임b뤠이s]
(껴)안다, 포옹하다, 
(생각, 제의 등을 열렬히) 받아들이다, 수용하다
포괄하다, 아우르다
voca.explains:
If you embrace someone, you put your arms around them and hold them tightly, usually in order to show your love or affection for them. You can also say that two people embrace.
If you embrace a change, political system, or idea, you accept it and start supporting it or believing in it.
If something embraces a group of people, things, or ideas, it includes them in a larger group or category.

voca.title: embroider
voca.explains: If something such as clothing or cloth is embroidered with a design, the design is stitched into it.\nIf you embroider a story or account of something, or if you embroider on it, you try to make it more interesting by adding details which may be untrue.\n

voca.title: embroidery
voca.explains: Embroidery consists of designs stitched into cloth.\nEmbroidery is the activity of stitching designs onto cloth.\n

voca.title: embryo
voca.explains: An embryo is an unborn animal or human being in the very early stages of development.\nAn embryo idea, system, or organization is in the very early stages of development, but is expected to grow stronger.\n

voca.title: emerald
voca.explains:
An emerald is a precious stone which is clear and bright green.
Something that is emerald is bright green in colour.
Pale pearls, emeralds, and rubies shone and sparkled.

voca.title: emerge
voca.means:
[이^머r-쥐]
(어둠 속이나 숨어 있던 곳에서) 나오다, 나타나다,
드러나다, 부상하다, 명백해지다
(어려움 등을) 해쳐 나오다
voca.explains:
To emerge means to come out from an enclosed or dark space such as a room or a vehicle, or from a position where you could not be seen.
If you emerge from a difficult or bad experience, you come to the end of it.
If a fact or result emerges from a period of thought, discussion, or investigation, it becomes known as a result of it.
If someone or something emerges as a particular thing, they become recognized as that thing.
When something such as an organization or an industry emerges, it comes into existence.

voca.title: emergence
voca.explains: The emergence of something is the process or event of its coming into existence.\n

voca.title: emergency
voca.explains:
An emergency is an unexpected and difficult or dangerous situation, especially an accident, which happens suddenly and which requires quick action to deal with it.
An emergency action is one that is done or arranged quickly and not in the normal way, because an emergency has occurred.
Emergency equipment or supplies are those intended for use in an emergency.

voca.title: emergency room
voca.explains: The emergency room is the room or department in a hospital where people who have severe injuries or sudden illnesses are taken for emergency treatment. The abbreviation ER is often used.\n

voca.title: emergent
voca.means:
[이^뭐r-줜t]
(국가 등이) 신생의, 신흥의
나타나는, 출현하는, 주목을 끌기 시작하는
불시의, 긴급한
voca.explains: An emergent country, political movement, or social group is one that is becoming powerful or coming into existence.\n

voca.title: emotion
voca.explains: An emotion is a feeling such as happiness, love, fear, anger, or hatred, which can be caused by the situation that you are in or the people you are with.\nEmotion is the part of a person's character that consists of their feelings, as opposed to their thoughts.\n

voca.title: emotional
voca.explains:
Emotional means concerned with emotions and feelings.
An emotional situation or issue is one that causes people to have strong feelings.
If someone is or becomes emotional, they show their feelings very openly, especially because they are upset.

voca.title: emotionless
voca.explains: If you describe someone as emotionless, you mean that they do not show any feelings or emotions.\n

voca.title: emperor
voca.explains: An emperor is a man who rules an empire or is the head of state in an empire.\n

voca.title: emphasis
voca.explains:
Emphasis is special or extra importance that is given to an activity or to a part or aspect of something.
Emphasis is extra force that you put on a syllable, word, or phrase when you are speaking in order to make it seem more important.
Cooking shows are all the rage in Korea lately. In the past, cooking shows were only about the food. But nowadays, the shows have a strong emphasis on entertainment.
They want the child to be healthy in body and mind. In Korea, education is a major concern among parents. Korea places great emphasis on learning. Education is considered a ticket to a better life.

voca.title: emphasize
voca.explains: stress / emphasize\nTo emphasize something means to indicate that it is particularly important or true, or to draw special attention to it.\n

voca.title: emphatic
voca.means:
[임^풰릑]
(진술, 대답 등이) 강한, 단호한
(말 따위에) 강세가 있는, 어조가 강한
(분명히) 강조하는, 확실한
(승리나 패배가) 확실한
voca.explains:
An emphatic response or statement is one made in a forceful way, because the speaker feels very strongly about what they are saying.
If you are emphatic about something, you use forceful language which shows that you feel very strongly about what you are saying.
An emphatic win or victory is one in which the winner has won by a large amount or distance.

voca.title: emphatically
voca.explains: If you say something emphatically, you say it in a forceful way which shows that you feel very strongly about what you are saying.\nYou use emphatically to emphasize the statement you are making.\n

voca.title: employ
voca.means:
[임플^뤄이]
고용하다, 사용하다, 소비하다
(기술, 방법 등을) 쓰다, 이용하다
고용, 사용, 근무, 일, 정규직
voca.explains:
If a person or company employs you, they pay you to work for them.
If you employ certain methods, materials, or expressions, you use them.
If your time is employed in doing something, you are using the time you have to do that thing.
If you are in the employ of someone or something, you work for them.

voca.title: employee
voca.explains: An employee is a person who is paid to work for an organization or for another person.\n

voca.title: employment
voca.means:
[임^플로이먼t]
직장, (개인의) 고용
(사람들의) 취업, 고용
고용하는 것, 채용
(기술, 방법 등의) 사용, 이용
voca.explains:
work / employment / career / profession / occupation / trade
Employment is the fact of having a paid job.
Employment is the fact of employing someone.
Employment is the work that is available in a country or area.
Last year, I applied to various companies for work. Finding employment is a tall order these days.

voca.title: empty
voca.means:
[^엠디]
(그릇 등에 든 것을) 비우다, 비게 되다, 비다
(안에 있던 것을) 꺼내다, 쏟다
(한 곳에서 다른 곳으로) 흐르다, 이동하다
비어있는, 빈, 공허한, 무의미한
(마땅히 있어야 할) ~이 없는
voca.explains:
An empty place, vehicle, or container is one that has no people or things in it.
An empty gesture, threat, or relationship has no real value or meaning.
If you describe a person's life or a period of time as empty, you mean that nothing interesting or valuable happens in it.
If you feel empty, you feel unhappy and have no energy, usually because you are very tired or have just experienced something upsetting.
If you empty a container, or empty something out of it, you remove its contents, especially by tipping it up.
If someone empties a room or place, or if it empties, everyone that is in it goes away.
A river or canal that empties into a lake, river, or sea flows into it.
Empties are bottles or containers which no longer have anything in them.

voca.title: empty one's stomach
voca.explains: I became very seasick. I took some medicine, but it was too little too late. I emptied my stomach. I felt disoriented. I broke out in a cold sweat. I was all but begging to get off the boat. It was not a very enjoyable experience.\n

voca.title: empty out
voca.means: (그릇, 물건 따위)를 텅 비게 하다, 몽땅 비워 내다\n(그릇 따위가) 텅 비다
voca.explains: When our vacuum wasn’t working properly, the remedy was simpler. We just had to empty out all the dust.\n

voca.title: empty-handed
voca.explains:
If you come away from somewhere empty-handed, you have failed to get what you wanted.
Soon, our guests showed up. They didn’t come empty-handed. They came bearing gifts. People brought amenities like toilet paper, soap and detergent. They brought food like cake and fruit. The party was Bring Your Own Bottle(BYOB). The party was a riot.
I don't want to go to the party empty-handed.
It's rude to visit people's houses empty-handed.

voca.title: emulate
voca.means: (흠모하는 대상을) 모방하다[따라 가다]\n~와 경쟁하다, 우열을 다투다/겨루다\n(컴퓨터 프로그램 등이) 에뮬레이트하다, 모방하다
voca.explains: If you emulate something or someone, you imitate them because you admire them a great deal.\nAlmost every firms emulate our new product.\n

voca.title: enable
voca.means: [이^네이벌]\n(사람에게) ~을 할 수 있게 하다\n(무엇을) 가능하게 하다
voca.explains:
If someone or something enables you to do a particular thing, they give you the opportunity to do it.
To enable something to happen means to make it possible for it to happen.
To enable someone to do something means to give them permission or the right to do it.

voca.title: encapsulate
voca.means: [인^켑슐뤠잇t]\n캡슐에 싸다, 요약하다\n(몇 마디 말이나 하나의 글 속에) 요약/압축하다
voca.explains: To encapsulate particular facts or ideas means to represent all their most important aspects in a very small space or in a single object or event.\n

voca.title: enchant
voca.explains: If you are enchanted by someone or something, they cause you to have feelings of great delight or pleasure.\nIn fairy stories and legends, to enchant someone or something means to put a magic spell on them.\n

voca.title: enchanted
voca.explains: "It is an ancient, enchanted land beyond the edge of the Earth," said Morgan.\n

voca.title: enchantment
voca.explains: If you say that something has enchantment, you mean that it makes you feel great delight or pleasure. Your enchantment with something is the fact of your feeling great delight and pleasure because of it.\nIn fairy stories and legends, an enchantment is a magic spell.\n

voca.title: enchantress
voca.explains: In fairy stories and legends, an enchantress is a woman who uses magic to put spells on people and things.\nAs always, Jack was very happy to see the enchantress librarian again.\n

voca.title: enclose
voca.explains: If a place or object is enclosed by something, the place or object is inside that thing or completely surrounded by it.\nIf you enclose something with a letter, you put it in the same envelope as the letter.\n

voca.title: encounter
voca.means:
[인^카운더r]
(특히 반갑지 않은 일에) 맞닥뜨리다/부ㅈ히다,
만나다, 마주치다, 직면하다, 부딪치다
(우연히) 마주침, 조우, 시합
voca.explains:
If you encounter problems or difficulties, you experience them.
If you encounter someone, you meet them, usually unexpectedly.
An encounter with someone is a meeting with them, particularly one that is unexpected or significant.
An encounter is a particular type of experience.
You have learned to find the magic in things you encounter on earth every day.

voca.title: encourage
voca.means:
[인^쿼-뤼지]
격려하다, 용기를 북돋다, 
권하다, 장려하다, 자심감 주다
부추기다, 조장하다
voca.explains:
If you encourage someone, you give them confidence, for example by letting them know that what they are doing is good and telling them that they should continue to do it.
If someone is encouraged by something that happens, it gives them hope or confidence.
If you encourage someone to do something, you try to persuade them to do it, for example by telling them that it would be a pleasant thing to do, or by trying to make it easier for them to do it. You can also encourage an activity.
If something encourages a particular activity or state, it causes it to happen or increase.

voca.title: encouragement
voca.explains: Encouragement is the activity of encouraging someone, or something that is said or done in order to encourage them.\n

voca.title: encrypt
voca.explains: If a document or piece of information is encrypted, it is written in a special code, so that only certain people can read it.\n

voca.title: end

An end to something or the end of it is the act or result of stopping it so that it does not continue any longer.
The two ends of something long and narrow are the two points or parts of it that are furthest away from each other.
When a situation, process, or activity ends, or when something or someone ends it, it reaches its final point and stops.
If you say that someone or something ends a period of time in a particular way, you are indicating what the final situation was like. You can also say that a period of time ends in a particular way.

voca.title: end in something
voca.explains: to have something as an ending or as a result\n

voca.title: end it all
voca.explains: kill yourself; commit suicide\n

voca.title: end of the line
voca.explains: The termination point of a railway or similar transportation system.\nAnother time, I got on a bus after an office dinner. I soon dozed off. When I woke up, I was at the end of the line. I had missed my stop. I took a taxi home, and I drowsed off again in the cab.\n

voca.title: end over end
voca.explains: But was it only a rectangle? No, it was a giant envelope, and it was chasing Arthur down a hill. It tumbled end over end. Arthur could barely keep ahead of it.\n

voca.title: end to end
voca.explains: in a line, with the ends touching\n

voca.title: contaminate
voca.explains: If something is contaminated by dirt, chemicals, or radiation, they make it dirty or harmful.\nIf the soap ends up in a forest or river, it won’t contaminate the environment.\n

voca.title: lower the cost
voca.explains:
How did you lower the cost?
The only solution is to lower the cost.
Our sales figures don’t look very good, so we should definitely lower the cost.

voca.title: bear the cost
voca.explains:
Can we bear the cost?
I don’t think we can bear the cost.
Our situation is not good these days, so we cannot bear the cost any more.

voca.title: end up
voca.explains:
You're just copying word for word, you're not actually doing anything active with the material you're listening to. So, working with a computer-and I've seen this in my university-a lot of students also end up going on Facebook during the lesson or lecture. So, a lot of  the times they get very distracted. When they should be listening, they're actually not.
Everyone else took a position. Arthur ended up in right field. Nobody else seemed to want to be there.
His father nodded. "It was when I first got interested in cooking. Of course, I didn't know I would end up as a caterer. I just liked experimenting with food. I was sick the first week and missed the class where the teacher explained how all the equipment worked. The next week I was too shy to ask questions. I just pretended I knew as much as everyone else."
Only baby Kate looked pleased. She liked playing with oatmeal. It always ended up in the most interesting places.
"We've solved the mystery of the missing quarters." Mr. Haney explained. "They ended up in Mrs. MacGrady’s brownies."
Once, I was afraid of running late to a meeting. I left early just in case. Infuriatingly, I couldn’t find a parking space and I ended up being tardy anyway.
You can use this expression when you talk about the result of something whether or not the result came out as expected or unexpected. Before you use this expression, you tend to show the progress of your argument and by using this expression, you can summarize precisely.

voca.title: endanger
voca.explains: To endanger something or someone means to put them in a situation where they might be harmed or destroyed completely.\n

voca.title: endangered
voca.explains: in danger: used esp of animals in danger of extinction\n

voca.title: endless
voca.explains: If you say that something is endless, you mean that it is very large or lasts for a very long time, and it seems as if it will never stop.\n

voca.title: endoscope
voca.explains: a long slender medical instrument used for examining the interior of hollow organs including the lung, stomach, bladder, and bowel\n

voca.title: endoscopy
voca.explains: Then, the more in-depth examinations began. A doctor administered an ultrasound test. I also received endoscopy inspections.\n

voca.title: endoscopy inspection
voca.explains: Then, the more in-depth examinations began. A doctor administered an ultrasound test. I also received endoscopy inspections.\n

voca.title: endurance
voca.explains: Endurance is the ability to continue with an unpleasant or difficult situation, experience, or activity over a long period of time.\n

voca.title: endure
voca.explains:
If you endure a painful or difficult situation, you experience it and do not avoid it or give up, usually because you cannot.
If something endures, it continues to exist without any loss in quality or importance.
However, I am willing to endure it. It's the price to pay to feel confident when I smile.

voca.title: enemy
voca.explains:
If someone is your enemy, they hate you or want to harm you.
If someone is your enemy, they are opposed to you and to what you think or do
The enemy is an army or other force that is opposed to you in a war, or a country with which your country is at war.
If one thing is the enemy of another thing, the second thing cannot happen or succeed because of the first thing.

voca.title: energy
voca.means:
[^에너쥐-]
정력, 활기

voca.explains:
Energy is the ability and strength to do active physical things and the feeling that you are full of physical power and life.
Energy is determination and enthusiasm about doing things.
Your energies are your efforts and attention, which you can direct towards a particular aim.
Energy is the power from sources such as electricity and coal that makes machines work or provides heat.

voca.title: energy hog
voca.explains: The refrigerator is far and away my favorite home appliance. That’s because it’s where we keep our food. Our old fridge was a clunker. It was noisy. It was an energy hog. Our new fridge is much more to my liking.\n

If you engage someone to do a particular job, you appoint them to do it.

voca.title: engage in

voca.title: engineering

voca.title: English
voca.explains: English means belonging or relating to England, or to its people or language. It is also often used to mean belonging or relating to Great Britain, although many people object to this.\nEnglish is the language spoken by people who live in Great Britain and Ireland, the United States, Canada, Australia, and many other countries.\n

voca.explains: Someone or something that is enigmatic is mysterious and difficult to understand.\n

voca.explains: Something that is enjoyable gives you pleasure.\nI became very seasick. I took some medicine, but it was too little too late. I emptied my stomach. I felt disoriented. I broke out in a cold sweat. I was all but begging to get off the boat. It was not a very enjoyable experience.\n

If you say that something is enough, you mean that you do not want it to continue any longer or get any worse.

I’m a big fan of taking selfies. Some might say that I am a selfie enthusiast. Taking selfies is a snap these days because most smartphones are equipped with cameras.
Truth be told, when my nieces and nephews asked me to chaperon their trip to a theme park, the anticipation of going on the rides made my heart race. I had always been a rollercoaster enthusiast.

voca.title: enthusiastic
