voca.explains: You use entire when you want to emphasize that you are referring to the whole of something, for example, the whole of a place, time, or population.\nUsually, traveling is a treat. However, any number of things can go wrong while traveling. Sometimes, a problem can ruin an entire trip.\n

voca.title: entire confidence
voca.explains: He has my entire confidence.\n

voca.title: entirely
voca.explains: Entirely means completely and not just partly.\nEntirely is also used to emphasize what you are saying.\n

[인^타이들]
자격/권리을 주다, 
제목을 붙이다
(남)을 (특별한 칭호, 명칭으로) 부르다, 칭하다

On the third floor, they peered through an arched entrance into a huge room.

voca.explains: Just last week, I did the laundry. I put some sweaters in the washing machine. I made sure to use the gentle cycle. Despite my best efforts, the sweaters were ruined. They had shrunk beyond recognition. Next time, I will just entrust everything to the laundromat.\n

"'Include twenty boxtops with each entry.'" He sighed.

"You like sharks too?" he asked, passing her a small white envelope with her name on it.

Your environment consists of the particular natural surroundings in which you live or exist, considered in relation to their physical characteristics or weather conditions.
The environment is the natural world of land, sea, air, plants, and animals.

voca.title: envy
voca.explains:
Envy is the feeling you have when you wish you could have the same thing or quality that someone else has.
If a thing or quality is the envy of someone, they wish very much that they could have or achieve it.
If you envy someone, you wish that you had the same things or qualities that they have.

His father nodded. "It was when I first got interested in cooking. Of course, I didn't know I would end up as a caterer. I just liked experimenting with food. voca.title: equivalent
voca.explains:
If one amount or value is the equivalent of another, they are the same.
The equivalent of someone or something is a person or thing that has the same function in a different place, time, or system.
You can use equivalent to emphasize the great or severe effect of something.
Lisa: Well, then, you have to use a collect call or pay me the equivalent amount.

voca.title: erase
voca.means:
[이^뤠이s]
(완전히) 지우다, 없애다, 되돌리다
(지우개 등으로) 지우다
(녹음테이프나 컴퓨터에서 내용을) 지우다
voca.explains:
If you erase a thought or feeling, you destroy it completely so that you can no longer remember something or no longer feel a particular emotion.
If you erase sound which has been recorded on a tape or information which has been stored in a computer, you completely remove or destroy it.
If you erase something such as writing or a mark, you remove it, usually by rubbing it with a cloth.

voca.title: eraser
voca.explains: An eraser is an object, usually a piece of rubber or plastic, which is used for removing something that has been written using a pencil or a pen.\n

voca.title: errand
voca.explains:
An errand is a short trip that you make in order to do a job for someone, for example when you go to a shop to buy something for them.
If you run an errand for someone, you do or get something for them, usually by making a short trip somewhere.
When I stop by the bank, I try to make hay while the sun shines. Instead of just one errand, I attend to several errands at once. For example, I make it a point to update my bankbook whenever I go to the bank.

voca.title: errata
voca.explains: the plural of erratum\n

voca.title: erratum
voca.means: [이^뤠움]\n(책 속에 리스트로 명시된) 오자\n(고쳐야 할) 오류, 오자
voca.explains: an error in writing or printing\nanother name for corrigendum\n

voca.title: errily
voca.explains: The thicket had grown eerily silent.\n

voca.title: error
voca.means:
[^에러r-]
실수, 오류
(특히 문제를 일으키거나 결과에 영향을 미치는 것), 
잘못, 오차
voca.explains: mistake / error / inaccuracy / slip / howler / misprint / typo\nAn error is something you have done which is considered to be incorrect or wrong, or which should not have been done.\n

voca.title: erupt
voca.means: [이뢉t]\n(화산, 용암 등이) 분출하다, \n(갑자기 폭력적으로) 분출되다, 터지다
voca.explains:
explode / blow up / go off / burst / erupt / rupture / implode
When a volcano erupts, it throws out a lot of hot, melted rock called lava, as well as ash and steam.
If violence or fighting erupts, it suddenly begins or gets worse in an unexpected, violent way.
When people in a place suddenly become angry or violent, you can say that they erupt or that the place erupts.
You say that someone erupts when they suddenly have a change in mood, usually becoming quite noisy.
If your skin erupts, sores or spots suddenly appear there.
The volcanoes erupted under the ocean.

voca.title: escalate
voca.means:
[^에s끌뤠잇t]
짙어가다, 확대하다, 높이다
확대/증가/악화되다/시키다
단계적으로 확대되다
(임금, 물가가) 차츰 오르다
voca.explains: If a bad situation escalates or if someone or something escalates it, it becomes greater in size, seriousness, or intensity.\n

voca.title: escalator
voca.explains: An escalator is a moving staircase on which people can go from one level of a building to another.\nRecently, I was in a hurry to catch the last subway train. People were lining up for the escalator, so I ran down the stairs. I lost my balance and fell over.\n

voca.title: escape
voca.means:
[이s^께입p]
달아나다, 탈출하다, 벗어나다, 모면하다
(나쁜 상황에서) 벗어나다/빠져 나오다
도망, 탈출, 피난, 누출
현실도피의, 도피하는
(액체, 고체 등의) 누출
voca.explains:
If you escape from a place, you succeed in getting away from it.
You can say that you escape when you survive something such as an accident.
If something escapes you or escapes your attention, you do not know about it, do not remember it, or do not notice it.
When gas, liquid, or heat escapes, it comes out from a pipe, container, or place.
Someone's escape is the act of escaping from a particular place or situation.

voca.title: escort
voca.explains:
take / lead / escort / drive / show / guide / usher / direct
An escort is a person who travels with someone in order to protect or guard them.
An escort is a person who accompanies another person of the opposite sex to a social event. Sometimes people are paid to be escorts.
If you escort someone somewhere, you accompany them there, usually in order to make sure that they leave a place or get to their destination.
They seemed to be escorting Jack and Annie back to the tree house.
Two of them escorted the new member of their flock as he timidly flapped his small wings.

voca.title: especial
voca.explains: Especial means unusual or special in some way.\n

voca.title: especially
voca.explains:
especially / specially
You use especially to emphasize that what you are saying applies more to one person, thing, or area than to any others.
You use especially to emphasize a characteristic or quality.
"Of course." said Buster. "And not just your teammates. The other team is watching, too. And the crowd in the stands. Especially your family."

voca.title: essay
voca.means:
[^엣쎄이]
(학교 학습활동의 일환으로 제출하는 짧은 논문식) 과제물, 리포트, 에세이
에세이, 작문, 논문, 수필
시도하다, 꾀하다
voca.explains: An essay is a short piece of writing on one particular subject written by a student.\nAn essay is a short piece of writing on one particular subject that is written by a writer for publication.\n

voca.title: essence
voca.means:
[^엣센s]
본질, 정수, 가장 중요한/근본적인 성질, 
불가결한 요소: 특질, 속성
(식물, 약물 등에서 추출한) 진엑, 에센스
voca.explains: The essence of something is its basic and most important characteristic which gives it its individual identity.\nEssence is a very concentrated liquid that is used for flavouring food or for its smell.\n

voca.title: essential
voca.means:
[이^쎈숼]
필수적인, 극히 중요한
필수품, 주요점, 필수사항
필수의, 기본적인, 근본적인
(어떤 주제의) 핵심 사항, 요점
voca.explains:
essential / vital / crucial / critical / decisive / indispensable
Something that is essential is extremely important or absolutely necessary to a particular subject, situation, or activity.
The essential aspects of something are its most basic or important aspects.
The essentials are the things that are absolutely necessary for the situation you are in or for the task you are doing.
The essentials are the most important principles, ideas, or facts of a particular subject.
When I plan to travel abroad, I consider three essential factors: food, lodging and transportation.

voca.title: establish
voca.means:
[엣s떼블리쉬]
설립하다, 세우다, 제정하다, 
(공식적인 관계를) 수립하다, 규명하다
(사상, 관습 등을) 확립하다
voca.explains:
If someone establishes something such as an organization, a type of activity, or a set of rules, they create it or introduce it in such a way that it is likely to last for a long time.
If you establish contact with someone, you start to have contact with them. You can also say that two people, groups, or countries establish contact.
If you establish that something is true, you discover facts that show that it is definitely true.
If you establish yourself, your reputation, or a good quality that you have, you succeed in doing something, and achieve respect or a secure position as a result of this.

voca.title: established
voca.explains: If you use established to describe something such as an organization, you mean that it is officially recognized or generally approved of because it has existed for a long time.\n

voca.title: estate
voca.explains:
An estate is a large area of land in the country which is owned by a person, family, or organization.
People sometimes use estate to refer to a housing estate or an industrial estate.
Someone's estate is all the money and property that they leave behind them when they die.

voca.title: esteem
voca.means: [이s띠임]\n(대단한) 존경, 존중, 호의적인 의견\n존경하다, 생각하다, 평가하다
voca.explains: Esteem is the admiration and respect that you feel towards another person.\nIf you esteem someone or something, you respect or admire them.\n

voca.title: estimate
voca.means:
[^에s터메잇t]
~을 어림잡다, ~을 추정하다, 판단/평가하다
견적을 내다
견적, 평가, 판단, 추정, 추산, 견적서
voca.explains:
If you estimate a quantity or value, you make an approximate judgment or calculation of it.
An estimate is an approximate calculation of a quantity or value.
An estimate is a judgment about a person or situation which you make based on the available evidence.
An estimate from someone who you employ to do a job for you, such as a builder or a plumber, is a written statement of how much the job is likely to cost.
I went to a repair shop for an estimate. The quote was eye-popping. I didn’t want to charge it to insurance, because it was my own fault. Since then, I’m much more careful when backing up.

voca.title: etcetera
voca.means: [엑쎄더롸]\n그 밖의 여러가지, 기타 등등, 여분의 것

voca.title: ethic
voca.means:
[^에씍]
(개인 행동 규범으로서의) 윤리
(하나의 가치 체계로서의) 도덕, 윤리
윤리, 도덕, 가치 체계
voca.explains:
Ethics are moral beliefs and rules about right and wrong.
Someone's ethics are the moral principles about right and wrong behaviour which they believe in.
Ethics is the study of questions about what is morally right and wrong.
An ethic of a particular kind is an idea or moral belief that influences the behaviour, attitudes, and philosophy of a group of people.
I’ll hire him depending on his attitude and work ethic.

voca.title: ethics
voca.means:
[^에씍ks]
(단수)윤리학, 윤리,
(개인, 특정 사회, 직업의) 도덕 원리, 윤리, 도의, 덕의 
(복수) 행위의 규범
voca.explains:
the philosophical study of the moral value of human conduct and of the rules and principles that ought to govern it; moral philosophy See also meta-ethics
a social, religious, or civil code of behaviour considered correct, esp that of a particular group, profession, or individual
the moral fitness of a decision, course of action, etc

voca.title: etiquette
voca.means: [^에리킷t]\n(사회, 특정 직종 구성원들 사이의) 예의, 에티켓\n예의, 에티켓, 예법
voca.explains: Etiquette is a set of customs and rules for polite behaviour, especially among a particular class of people or in a particular profession.\n

voca.title: euphemism
voca.explains: A euphemism is a polite word or expression that is used to refer to things which people may find upsetting or embarrassing to talk about, for example sex, the human body, or death.\nFirstly, these soft expressions are also called euphemisms.\n

voca.title: evacuate
voca.means:
[이베뀨에잇t]
(위험지역에서 사람들을) 대피시키다, 
(위험한 장소를) 떠나다, 피난하다
비우다, 피난시키다, 배설하다
voca.explains: To evacuate someone means to send them to a place of safety, away from a dangerous building, town, or area.\nIf people evacuate a place, they move out of it for a period of time, especially because it is dangerous.\n

voca.title: evacuation
voca.explains: An evacuation of the city's four-million inhabitants is planned for later this week.\nVideo shows a brush fire burning in San Bernardino, which has reached multiple homes and prompted area evacuations.\n

voca.title: evaluate
voca.means:
[이^뷀류에잇t]
(양, 가치, 품질 등을) 평가하다, 감정하다
~의 견적을 내다
평가하다, 사정하다, 어림하다
voca.explains: If you evaluate something or someone, you consider them in order to make a judgment about them, for example about how good or bad they are.\n

voca.title: evaluation
voca.explains: You can also combine the results of more than one operation, which enables your programs to make more complex decisions by evaluating the truth values of more than one operation.\n

voca.title: even
voca.means:
[^이-븐]
(예상 밖이나 놀라운 일을 나타내어) ~도, ~조차, 
(비교급을 강조하여) 훨씬
평평한, 같은 높이의, 균등한, 동일한, 대등한
더욱, 오히려, 심지어
voca.explains:
You use even to suggest that what comes just after or just before it in the sentence is rather surprising.
You use even with comparative adjectives and adverbs to emphasize a quality that someone or something has.
An even measurement or rate stays at about the same level.
If there is an even distribution or division of something, each person, group, or area involved has an equal amount.
An even contest or competition is equally balanced between the two sides who are taking part.

voca.title: even after
voca.explains: "Breaking it into steps. Look, when you throw, you need to push off with your legs first and use your shoulder. And even after you release the ball, you still have to follow through."\n

voca.title: even as
voca.explains: just at the same time as somebody does something or as something else happens\n

voca.title: even better
voca.explains: White chocolate cookies taste even better with a glass of milk.\n

voca.title: even if
voca.explains: "It's just a dumb old envelope. People could walk by this envelope for weeks and not even notice it. And even if they did notice it, they wouldn't bother to open a boring envelope like this."\n

voca.title: even less
voca.explains: and certainly not\nD.W. rolled her eyes. “Arthur, you’re making even less sense than usual. What’s going on?”\n

voca.title: even now
voca.explains:
in spite of what has/had happened
at this or that exact moment
When I was younger, I liked singing for an audience. I took part in some talent shows. Even now, I like to sing when people get together for social gatherings.

voca.title: even out
voca.explains: if something evens out, it becomes level or steady after a period when it has gone up and down or changed a lot\n

voca.title: even so
voca.explains:
in spite of that
Also, to be honest, I’m a little lazy. I procrastinate all the time. I always put off things that I should do right away. Ever so, I think I am an open-mined and friendly person overall.
Nowadays, internet and mobile banking are the norm. Trips to the bank are few and far between. Even so, some services call for a visit. Certain tasks require sitting face to face with a teller.

voca.title: even something up
voca.explains: to make a situation, a competition, etc. more equal\n

voca.title: even then
voca.explains: I have to carefully look at the menu. Even then, I have no way of knowing whether I will like a dish.\n

voca.title: even though
voca.explains:
although / even though / though
in spite of the fact or belief that; no matter whether
Even though the cold is hard to bear at times, I'm glad winter comes around each year.
Arthur tiptoed up the steps to D.W.’s room. He peeked inside.
His sister was sitting on her bed, brushing Nadine’s hair. Arthur could tell that even though he couldn’t see Nadine. Only D.W. could see her.

voca.title: even worse
voca.explains: It can be a major issue when the AC doesn’t work in the summer. In the sweltering weather, the house can become unbearably hot. Even worse, the repair costs can be very high.\n

voca.title: event
voca.explains:
An event is something that happens, especially when it is unusual or important. You can use events to describe all the things that are happening in a particular situation.
An event is a planned and organized occasion, for example a social gathering or a sports match.
An event is one of the races or competitions that are part of an organized occasion such as a sports meeting.
You use in the event of, in the event that, and in that event when you are talking about a possible future situation, especially when you are planning what to do if it occurs.

voca.title: eventual
voca.explains: You use eventual to indicate that something happens or is the case at the end of a process or period of time.\n

voca.title: eventually
voca.means: [이^벤춸뤼]\n결국, 종내\n그 언젠가는, 머지않아, 얼마 안 있어
voca.explains:
Eventually means in the end, especially after a lot of delays, problems, or arguments.
Eventually means at the end of a situation or process or as the final result of it.
Eventually, it got so bad that I had to go see the doctor. The doctor said I had the flu. I got an IV and slept for an hour at the clinic.

voca.title: ever
voca.explains:
Ever means at any time. It is used in questions and negative statements.
You use ever in expressions such as 'did you ever' and 'have you ever' to express surprise or shock at something you have just seen, heard, or experienced, especially when you expect people to agree with you.
You use ever after comparatives and superlatives to emphasize the degree to which something is true or when you are comparing a present situation with the past or the future.
You use ever to say that something happens more all the time.
You use ever in questions beginning with words such as 'why', 'when', and 'who' when you want to emphasize your surprise or shock.

voca.title: ever more
voca.explains: more and more…\n

voca.title: ever since
voca.explains: continuously since the time mentioned\n

voca.title: ever since then
voca.explains: Ever since then, we try to head out early in the morning.\nI recently went for a run at the park. As I was jogging, my leg seized up. I keeled over. I massaged my leg, but it cramped up again and again. I learned my lesson. Ever since then, I make sure to stretch before exercising.\n

voca.title: ever so
voca.explains: very\n

voca.title: every
voca.means:
[^에v릐]
(단수 명사와 함께 쓰여) 모든/매/하나하나 다
어느 ~ 도 모두, 온잦, 모든, 매 ~, ~ 마다
가능한 모든, 충분한
voca.explains:
each / every
You use every to indicate that you are referring to all the members of a group or all the parts of something and not only some of them.
You use every in order to say how often something happens or to indicate that something happens at regular intervals.
You use every in front of a number when you are saying what proportion of people or things something happens to or applies to.

voca.title: every last
voca.explains: every person or thing in a group\n

voca.title: every nook and cranny
voca.explains: everywhere; (in) all parts of a place\nRegardless, I was fully moved in and squared away in just half a day. I made sure to clean every nook and cranny of my new home. Now that I’m all settled in, I’m going all out with furnishing my new place.\n

voca.title: every now and then
voca.explains:
Bob doesn't say much, but every now and then he hits the nail right on the head.
I go to the beach every now and then but not every day or weekend.
We all have to do that every now and then.

voca.title: every once in a while
voca.explains: occasionally\n

voca.title: every other
voca.explains: every second (person/thing)\n

voca.title: every other day
voca.explains: At the end of the month, I received my credit card bill. I couldn’t muster up the money to pay it. I fell behind in payment. I received phone calls from the credit card company every other day. I had nowhere to turn to.\n

voca.title: every single day
voca.explains: I chased her around for five years, every single day.\n

voca.title: every which way
voca.explains: in all directions\n

voca.title: everybody
voca.explains: Everybody means the same as everyone.\n

voca.title: everybody and their dog
voca.explains:
Internet security is a hot topic. Everybody and their dog are online these days. As a result, Internet users are juicy targets for hackers.
Everybody and their dog have smartphones these days.
The movie was seen by everybody and their dog.

voca.title: everyday
voca.explains: You use everyday to describe something which happens or is used every day, or forms a regular and basic part of your life, so it is not especially interesting or unusual.\n

voca.title: everyone
voca.explains: You use everyone or everybody to refer to all the people in a particular group.\nYou use everyone or everybody to refer to all people.\n

voca.title: everyone else
voca.explains: All other persons.\n"I wish I knew what everyone else was thinking." Arthur muttered.\n

voca.title: everything
voca.means:
[에v뤼띵]
모든 것, 모두, 
(현재의 일반적인 상황, 생활을 나타내는) 모든 것/만사
전부, 가장 중요한 것
전체, 전체의, 다
voca.explains:
You use everything to refer to all the objects, actions, activities, or facts in a particular situation.
You use everything to refer to all possible or likely actions, activities, or situations.
You use everything to refer to a whole situation or to life in general.
If you say that someone or something is everything, you mean you consider them to be the most important thing in your life, or the most important thing that there is.
If you say that someone or something has everything, you mean they have all the things or qualities that most people consider to be desirable.
Everything was bathed in a golden red glow.

voca.title: everywhere
voca.explains:
You use everywhere to refer to a whole area or to all the places in a particular area.
You use everywhere to refer to all the places that someone goes to.
You use everywhere to emphasize that you are talking about a large number of places, or all possible places.
If you say that someone or something is everywhere, you mean that they are present in a place in very large numbers.

voca.title: eviction
voca.explains: Eviction is the act or process of officially forcing someone to leave a house or piece of land.\n

voca.title: evidence
voca.means: [^에뷔던s]\n~을 분명히하다, 입증하다\n증거, 근거, 징후, 흔적, 증언
voca.explains:
Evidence is anything that you see, experience, read, or are told that causes you to believe that something is true or has really happened.
Evidence is the information which is used in a court of law to try to prove something. Evidence is obtained from documents, objects, or witnesses.
If you give evidence in a court of law or an official enquiry, you officially say what you know about people or events, or describe an occasion at which you were present.
If someone or something is in evidence, they are present and can be clearly seen.
If a particular feeling, ability, or attitude is evidenced by something or someone, it is seen or felt.

voca.title: evident
voca.explains:
clear / obvious / apparent / evident / plain / crystal clear
If something is evident, you notice it easily and clearly.
You use evident to show that you are certain about a situation or fact and your interpretation of it.

voca.title: evil
voca.means:
[^이블]
나쁜, 불길한, 불쾌한
(행위 등이) 사악한, 유해한
약마의
악, 악행, 재앙
voca.explains:
Evil is a powerful force that some people believe to exist, and which causes wicked and bad things to happen.
Evil is used to refer to all the wicked and bad things that happen in the world.
If you refer to an evil, you mean a very unpleasant or harmful situation or activity.
If you describe someone as evil, you mean that they are very wicked by nature and take pleasure in doing things that harm other people.
If you describe something as evil, you mean that you think it causes a great deal of harm to people and is morally bad.
If you describe something as evil, you mean that you think it is influenced by the devil.
You can describe a very unpleasant smell as evil.
If someone is putting off the evil day or the evil hour, they have to do something unpleasant and are trying to avoid doing it for as long as possible.
If you have two choices, but think that they are both bad, you can describe the one which is less bad as the lesser of two evils, or the lesser evil.
Jason: You're right. Doctors are evil.

voca.title: evolve
voca.explains:
When animals or plants evolve, they gradually change and develop into different forms.
If something evolves or you evolve it, it gradually develops over a period of time into something different and usually more advanced.
Their hacking techniques have evolved. They have more tricks up their sleeves. Hacking programs are more sophisticated than ever.

voca.title: exact
voca.means: [이g젝t]\n정확한, 완전한, 딱 맞는, 정밀한\n요구하다, ~을 강제로 거두다, 강요하다
voca.explains:
true / right / correct / exact / precise / accurate / spot on
Exact means correct in every detail. For example, an exact copy is the same in every detail as the thing it is copied from.
You use exact before a noun to emphasize that you are referring to that particular thing and no other, especially something that has a particular significance.
If you describe someone as exact, you mean that they are very careful and detailed in their work, thinking, or methods.
When someone exacts something, they demand and obtain it from another person, especially because they are in a superior or more powerful position.
If someone exacts revenge on a person, they have their revenge on them.
If something exacts a high price, it has a bad effect on a person or situation.

voca.title: exactitude
voca.explains: Exactitude is the quality of being very accurate and careful.\n

voca.title: exactly
voca.means: [익^젝들릐]\n정확하게, 확실히, 꼭, 틀림없이\n(맞장구 치는 말로) 맞아, 바로 그거야
voca.explains:
You use exactly before an amount, number, or position to emphasize that it is no more, no less, or no different from what you are stating.
If you say 'Exactly', you are agreeing with someone or emphasizing the truth of what they say. If you say 'Not exactly', you are telling them politely that they are wrong in part of what they are saying.
You use not exactly to indicate that a meaning or situation is slightly different from what people think or expect.
You can use not exactly to show that you mean the opposite of what you are saying.
You use exactly with a question to show that you disapprove of what the person you are talking to is doing or saying.

voca.title: exaggerate
voca.explains:
If you exaggerate, you indicate that something is, for example, worse or more important than it really is.
If something exaggerates a situation, quality, or feature, it makes the situation, quality, or feature appear greater, more obvious, or more important than it really is.
"Hard to argue with that. But aren't you exaggerating a little? Are these books really flying off the shelves?"

voca.title: exaggerated
voca.explains: Something that is exaggerated is or seems larger, better, worse, or more important than it actually needs to be.\n

voca.title: exam
voca.explains: An exam is a formal test that you take to show your knowledge or ability in a particular subject, or to obtain a qualification.\nIf you have a medical exam, a doctor looks at your body, feels it, or does simple tests in order to check how healthy you are.\n

voca.title: examination
voca.explains: An examination is a formal test that you take to show your knowledge or ability in a particular subject, or to obtain a qualification.\n

voca.title: examine
voca.means:
[익g^제-믠]
시험하다, 조사/검토하다, 검사하다
(~에게) 시험을 실시하다
(특히 법정에서) 심문하다
voca.explains:
check / examine / inspect / go over sth
If you examine something, you look at it carefully.
If a doctor examines you, he or she looks at your body, feels it, or does simple tests in order to check how healthy you are.
If an idea, proposal, or plan is examined, it is considered very carefully.
If you are examined, you are given a formal test in order to show your knowledge of a subject.

voca.title: example
voca.means: [이g^젬쁠]\n(설명, 증명을 위한) 예, 사례, 보기, \n(대표적인) 본보기, 전형, 모범
voca.explains:
example / case / instance / specimen / illustration
An example of something is a particular situation, object, or person which shows that what is being claimed is true.
An example of a particular class of objects or styles is something that has many of the typical features of such a class or style, and that you consider clearly represents it.
If you refer to a person or their behaviour as an example to other people, you mean that he or she behaves in a good or correct way that other people should copy.
In a dictionary entry, an example is a phrase or sentence which shows how a particular word is used.

voca.title: exceed
voca.means:
[익^씨-d]
(특정한 양, 수를) 넘다, 초과하다, 초월하다
(허용 한도를) 넘어서다, 초과하다
~보다 크다, (~만큼) 초과하다
voca.explains:
If something exceeds a particular amount or number, it is greater or larger than that amount or number.
If you exceed a limit or rule, you go beyond it, even though you are not supposed to or it is against the law.
Exceeding the weight limit while checking in for a flight can also be annoying.

voca.title: exceed the weight limit
voca.explains:
Exceeding the weight limit while checking in for a flight can also be annoying.
You will have to pay more if you exceed the weight limit.
We were late boarding the plane because we exceeded the weight limit.

voca.title: excellence
voca.explains: If someone or something has the quality of excellence, they are extremely good in some way.\n

voca.title: excellent
voca.explains:
excellent / outstanding / perfect / superb / marvellous / exceptional
Something that is excellent is very good indeed.
Some people say 'Excellent!' to show that they approve of something.

voca.title: except
voca.means: [익셉t]\n제외하다, 예외로 하다\n~ 을 제외하고, 단(only), 제외하고
voca.explains:
besides / apart from / except
You use except to introduce the only thing or person that a statement does not apply to, or a fact that prevents a statement from being completely true.
You use except for to introduce the only thing or person that prevents a statement from being completely true.
The dancers looked like people-except they all had glittering gold skin and wings that shimmered in the mist like spun silver.
Nothing mattered except the dancing.

voca.title: except for
voca.explains: Except for the swooshing of their wings, they made no noise.\nThe school music room was empty except for Arthur. All the other kids were out at recess, running around and playing in the snow.\n

voca.title: exception
voca.explains:
An exception is a particular thing, person, or situation that is not included in a general statement, judgment, or rule.
If you make a general statement, and then say that something or someone is no exception, you are emphasizing that they are included in that statement.
If you are making a general statement and you say that something is the exception that proves the rule, you mean that although it seems to contradict your statement, in most other cases your statement will be true.
If you take exception to something, you feel offended or annoyed by it, usually with the result that you complain about it.
You use without exception to emphasize that the statement you are making is true in all cases.
You use with the exception of to introduce a thing or person that is not included in a general statement that you are making.

voca.title: exception to the rule
voca.explains: However, there are exceptions to the rule. These day, many older people have no problem using the latest technology.\n

voca.title: excess
voca.means:
[엑^쎄s]
(어떤 정도를) 지나침, 과도, 과잉
초과, 과잉, 지나침, 초과량, 무절제
초과한, 여분의
voca.explains:
An excess of something is a larger amount than is needed, allowed, or usual.
Excess is behaviour that is unacceptable because it is considered too extreme or immoral.
The excess on an insurance policy is a sum of money which the insured person has to pay towards the cost of a claim. The insurance company pays the rest.
Excess is used to describe amounts that are greater than what is needed, allowed, or usual.
Excess is used to refer to additional amounts of money that need to be paid for services and activities that were not originally planned or taken into account.
In excess of means more than a particular amount.
If you do something to excess, you do it too much.

voca.title: excess weight
voca.means: 군살, 과도한 체중\n(항공 여행시) 제한 초과 중량
voca.explains: That’s when I decided to go on a diet. I ate less. I ate mostly vegetables. Above all, I started to exercise. I did lose a bit of the excess weight, but it soon returned. Weight control is a life-long task.\n

voca.title: excessive
voca.explains: If you describe the amount or level of something as excessive, you disapprove of it because it is more or higher than is necessary or reasonable.\n

voca.title: excessive spending
voca.explains: Korean parents usually frown upon excessive spending. Their generation got ahead by tightening their belts.\n

voca.title: excessively
voca.explains: For grown-ups, having a few drinks can be a laugh. But if you drink excessively, there is a price to pay.\n

voca.title: exchange
voca.means:
[익s^췌인쥐]
교환, 주고받음, 맞바꿈
얘기를 나눔, 대화; 말싸움, 언쟁
환전, 
(동일한 종류의 것을) 교환하다, 주고받다, 나누다
(주택, 토지 매매) 계약을 체결하다, 계약하다
voca.explains:
If two or more people exchange things of a particular kind, they give them to each other at the same time.
If you exchange something, you replace it with a different thing, especially something that is better or more satisfactory.
An exchange is a brief conversation, usually an angry one.
An exchange of fire, for example, is an incident in which people use guns or missiles against each other.
An exchange is an arrangement in which people from two different countries visit each other's country, to strengthen links between them.
The exchange is the same as the telephone exchange.
If you do or give something in exchange for something else, you do it or give it in order to get that thing.
Lisa: Excuse me, could I exchange this for another one?

voca.title: exchange business cards
voca.explains:
In Korea, people exchange business cards very frequently. There are rules of etiquette to keep in mind. If you receive a business card during a meeting, you should keep it in front of you.
We started the meeting by exchanging business cards.
Did you exchange business cards with them?

voca.title: excite
voca.means: [익^사잇t]\n(특히 기대감으로) 흥분시키다, 들뜨게 만들다\n흥분/초조하게 만들다, 자극하다
voca.explains: If something excites you, it makes you feel very happy, eager, or enthusiastic.\nIf something excites a particular feeling, emotion, or reaction in someone, it causes them to experience it.\n

voca.title: excitedly
voca.explains: Jack turned excitedly to Morgan.\n

voca.title: excitement
voca.explains: You use excitement to refer to the state of being excited, or to something that excites you.\nMuffy nearly exploded with excitement. \n

voca.title: exciting
voca.explains: exciting / dramatic / heady / thrilling / exhilarating\nIf something is exciting, it makes you feel very happy or enthusiastic.\n

voca.title: exclaim
voca.explains:
call / cry out / exclaim / blurt / burst out
Writers sometimes use exclaim to show that someone is speaking suddenly, loudly, or emphatically, often because they are excited, shocked, or angry.
"I had a dream about Morgan!" exclaimed Annie.
"Interesting!" they exclaimed.

voca.title: exclamation
voca.explains: An exclamation is a sound, word, or sentence that is spoken suddenly, loudly, or emphatically and that expresses excitement, admiration, shock, or anger.\n

voca.title: exclude
voca.explains:
If you exclude someone from a place or activity, you prevent them from entering it or taking part in it.
If you exclude something that has some connection with what you are doing, you deliberately do not use it or consider it.
To exclude a possibility means to decide or prove that it is wrong and not worth considering.
To exclude something such as the sun's rays or harmful germs means to prevent them physically from reaching or entering a particular place.

voca.title: exclusion
voca.means:
[익s끌^루-젼]
제외, 배제, 차단
(가능성에 대한) 배제, 제외
제외되는 사람/것
(비행 학생에 대한) 정학 처분
(출입국 관리 당국에 의한) 입국 거부
voca.explains:
The exclusion of something is the act of deliberately not using, allowing, or considering it.
Exclusion is the act of preventing someone from entering a place or taking part in an activity.
If you do one thing to the exclusion of something else, you only do the first thing and do not do the second thing at all.

voca.title: exclusive
voca.means:
[익s클^루-시 ]
독점적인, 전용의
(집단, 사회 등이) 배타적인, 특권층의
(논리적으로 상호) 배타적인
~을 제외하고
배타적인 사람, 독점판매
배타적인, 독점적인, 유일한, 전용의
voca.explains:
If you describe something as exclusive, you mean that it is limited to people who have a lot of money or who belong to a high social class, and is therefore not available to everyone.
Something that is exclusive is used or owned by only one person or group, and not shared with anyone else.
If a newspaper, magazine, or broadcasting organization describes one of its reports as exclusive, they mean that it is a special report which does not appear in any other publication or on any other channel.
If a company states that its prices, goods, or services are exclusive of something, that thing is not included in the stated price, although it usually still has to be paid for.
If two things are mutually exclusive, they are separate and very different from each other, so that it is impossible for them to exist or happen together.

voca.title: excuse
voca.means:
[익s^뀨-z]
변명, 해명, 구실, 핑계 거리
아주 나쁜 사례, (~라기엔) 보잘것 없는 것
(무례나 작은 실수 등을) 용서하다/봐주다
변명하다, 양해하다/양해를 구하다
면제해 주다
voca.explains:
reason / grounds / excuse / motive / need / justification / cause / pretext
An excuse is a reason which you give in order to explain why something has been done or has not been done, or in order to avoid doing something.
To excuse someone or excuse their behaviour means to provide reasons for their actions, especially when other people disapprove of these actions.
If you excuse someone for something wrong that they have done, you forgive them for it.
If someone is excused from a duty or responsibility, they are told that they do not have to carry it out.
If you excuse yourself, you use a phrase such as 'Excuse me' as a polite way of saying that you are about to leave.
You say 'Excuse me' when you want to politely get someone's attention, especially when you are about to ask them a question.
You use excuse me to apologize to someone when you have disturbed or interrupted them.
You use excuse me or a phrase such as if you'll excuse me as a polite way of indicating that you are about to leave or that you are about to stop talking to someone.
You use excuse me, but to indicate that you are about to disagree with someone.
You say excuse me to apologize when you have bumped into someone, or when you need to move past someone in a crowd.
You say excuse me to apologize when you have done something slightly embarrassing or impolite, such as burping, hiccupping, or sneezing.

voca.title: execute
voca.means:
[^엑서큐t]
처형/사형 하다, 
실행/수행 하다
(어떤 기술적인 동작을) 해내다
(예술 작품을) 만들어 내다
voca.explains:
To execute someone means to kill them as a punishment for a serious crime.
If you execute a plan, you carry it out.
If you execute a difficult action or movement, you successfully perform it.
When someone executes a work of art, they make or produce it, using an idea as a basis.

voca.title: executive
voca.means:
[익g^젝기리v]
(기업이나 조직의) 임원, 대표, 경영자, 책임자
(정부의) 행정부
실행/집행하는, 행정상의
경영/운영의, 행정/집행의, 
고급의, 중요 인물을 위한
voca.explains:
An executive is someone who is employed by a business at a senior level. Executives decide what the business should do, and ensure that it is done.
The executive committee or board of an organization is a committee within that organization which has the authority to make decisions and ensures that these decisions are carried out.
The executive is the part of the government of a country that is concerned with carrying out decisions or orders, as opposed to the part that makes laws or the part that deals with criminals.
The executive sections and tasks of an organization are concerned with the making of decisions and with ensuring that decisions are carried out.

voca.title: exemplary
voca.means:
[이g^쥄플뤄뤼]
모범적인, 본보기의
가혹한, 본보기를 보이기 위한
본이 되는, 모범적인, 전형적인, 대표적인
voca.explains: If you describe someone or something as exemplary, you think they are extremely good.\nAn exemplary punishment is unusually harsh and is intended to stop other people from committing similar crimes.\n

voca.title: exercise
voca.means:
[^엑서사이z]
(육체적 정신적 건강을 위한) 운동, 연습문제
(권력, 권리, 역량 등의) 행사/발휘
(군대의) 훈련
(권력, 권리, 영량 등을) 행사/발휘하다
운동하다, 운동시키다, 운동이 되다
voca.explains:
If you exercise something such as your authority, your rights, or a good quality, you use it or put it into effect.
When you exercise, you move your body energetically in order to get fit and to remain healthy.
If a movement or activity exercises a part of your body, it keeps it strong, healthy, or in good condition.
If something exercises you or your mind, you think or talk about it a great deal, especially because you are worried or concerned about it.
Exercises are a series of movements or actions which you do in order to get fit, remain healthy, or practise for a particular physical activity.
Exercises are military activities and operations which are not part of a real war, but which allow the armed forces to practise for a real war.
An exercise is a short activity or piece of work that you do, for example in school, which is designed to help you learn a particular skill.
If you describe an activity as an exercise in a particular quality or result, you mean that it has that quality or result, especially when it was not intended to have it.

voca.title: exercise equipment
voca.explains: I saw a lot of people during my walk. Along the way, I stopped at the exercise equipment to stretch and catch my breath.\n

voca.title: exfoliate
voca.explains: To exfoliate your skin means to remove the dead cells from its surface using something such as a brush or a special cream.\nI also exfoliate and moisturize my skin regularly.\n

voca.title: exhaust
voca.means:
[이g^져-st]
(자동차 등의) 배기가스, 배기관
기진맥진하게 만들다, 
다 써버리다, 고갈시키다
(어떤 주제에 대해) 샅샅이/철저히 다루다
voca.explains:
If something exhausts you, it makes you so tired, either physically or mentally, that you have no energy left.
If you exhaust something such as money or food, you use or finish it all.
If you have exhausted a subject or topic, you have talked about it so much that there is nothing more to say about it.
The exhaust or the exhaust pipe is the pipe which carries the gas out of the engine of a vehicle.
Exhaust is the gas or steam that is produced when the engine of a vehicle is running.
First of all, I can’t say no to a friend. If someone asks a favor, I almost always say yes. This can be exhausting.
Her day-to-day life is exhausting.

voca.title: exhausted
voca.means: [이g^져-s딛]\n기진맥진한, 진이 다 빠진, 탈진한\n다 써 버린, 고갈된
voca.explains: Exhausted, Jack lay back on his bed.\n

voca.title: exhaustion
voca.explains: Exhaustion is the state of being so tired that you have no energy left.\n

voca.title: exhibit
voca.explains:
If someone or something shows a particular quality, feeling, or type of behaviour, you can say that they exhibit it.
When a painting, sculpture, or object of interest is exhibited, it is put in a public place such as a museum or art gallery so that people can come to look at it. You can also say that animals are exhibited in a zoo.
When artists exhibit, they show their work in public.
An exhibit is a painting, sculpture, or object of interest that is displayed to the public in a museum or art gallery.

voca.title: exhibition
voca.means: [^엑서븨션]\n전시, 작품, 박람회, 시범, 공연\n(기교 등의) 발휘, (감정 등의) 표현/드러냄
voca.explains: An exhibition is a public event at which pictures, sculptures, or other objects of interest are displayed, for example at a museum or art gallery.\nAn exhibition of a particular skilful activity is a display or example of it that people notice or admire.\n

voca.title: exhilarating
voca.explains:
exciting / dramatic / heady / thrilling / exhilarating
If you describe an experience or feeling as exhilarating, you mean that it makes you feel very happy and excited.
Whenever I mentioned that I wanted to picked up a new hobby, many people recommended hiking. At first, I didn’t get it. I couldn’t understand the appeal. However, I kept at it. Soon, I was hooked. It feels exhilarating to stand on a peak and soak in the view.

voca.title: exist
voca.means:
[익g^지-st]
존재/실재/현존 하다, 있다
(특수한 조건 또는 장소에) 있다, 존재하다, 나타나다
(힘들게 근근이) 살아가다
(음식, 급료 등에 의하여) 생존하다, 살아 있다, 살아가다
voca.explains: If something exists, it is present in the world as a real thing.\nTo exist means to live, especially under difficult conditions or with very little food or money.\n

voca.title: existence
voca.means: [익g^지s턴s]\n존재, 생존, 현존, 실체\n(특히 힘들게 근근이 살아가는) 생활/생계
voca.explains: The existence of something is the fact that it is present in the world as a real thing.\nYou can refer to someone's way of life as an existence, especially when they live under difficult conditions.\n

voca.title: existent
voca.explains: You can describe something as existent when it exists.\n

voca.title: exit
voca.means:
[엑싯t]
(공공건물, 차량의) 출구, (특히 배우의) 퇴장, 나감, 떠남
퇴장시키다, 종료시키다
나가다, 떠나다,
voca.explains:
The exit is the door through which you can leave a public building.
An exit on a motorway or highway is a place where traffic can leave it.
If you refer to someone's exit, you are referring to the way that they left a room or building, or the fact that they left it.
If you refer to someone's exit, you are referring to the way that they left a situation or activity, or the fact that they left it.
If you exit from a room or building, you leave it.
If you exit a computer program or system, you stop running it.

voca.title: exotic
voca.explains: Something that is exotic is unusual and interesting, usually because it comes from or is related to a distant country.\n

voca.title: expand
voca.means:
[익s^뺀-d]
확대하다, 확장하다, 팽창하다
확대시키다, 확장시키다, 팽창시키다
펴지다, 발전하다
말을 덧붙이다. 상세히 하다
voca.explains: If something expands or is expanded, it becomes larger.\nIf something such as a business, organization, or service expands, or if you expand it, it becomes bigger and includes more people, goods, or activities.\n

voca.title: expect
voca.means:
[익s^펙t]
예상하다, 기대하다,
(오기로 되어 있는 대상을) 기다리다
(어떤 일을 하기를) 요구하다/기대하다/바라다
(아마 ~ 일 것이라고) 생각하다
voca.explains:
demand / require / expect / insist / ask
If you expect something to happen, you believe that it will happen.
If you are expecting something or someone, you believe that they will be delivered to you or come to you soon, often because this has been arranged earlier.
If you expect something, or expect a person to do something, you believe that it is your right to have that thing, or the person's duty to do it for you.
If you tell someone not to expect something, you mean that the thing is unlikely to happen as they have planned or imagined, and they should not hope that it will.
How does she expect us to get there?
Lisa: Well, I understand your situation but I'm also expecting a phone call right now.

voca.title: expectation
voca.means:
[^엑s펙테이션]
예상
(좋은 일이 있을 것이라는) 기대
(어떤 일을 꼭 하기를 바라는) 기대, 요구
voca.explains:
Your expectations are your strong hopes or beliefs that something will happen or that you will get something that you want.
A person's expectations are strong beliefs which they have about the proper way someone should behave or something should happen.
The view also happens to be breathtaking during the fall season. You will be blown away. I guarantee that it will live up to your expectations.
I was afraid my essay would not live up to my prefessor's expectations.
I want to live up to my parents' expectations.

voca.title: expected
voca.explains: Jason: It's more than I expected. Can you cut down the price a little?\n

voca.title: expedite
voca.explains: If you expedite something, you cause it to be done more quickly.\n

voca.title: expedition
voca.means:
[엑s페디션]
탐험, 원정, 
탐험대, 원정대
(필요한 일을 하기위한 짦은) 여해
voca.explains:
trip / journey / tour / expedition / excursion / outing / day out
An expedition is an organized journey that is made for a particular purpose such as exploration.
You can refer to a group of people who are going on an expedition as an expedition.
An expedition is a short journey or trip that you make for pleasure.

voca.title: expensive
voca.explains: expensive / costly / overpriced / pricey / dear\nIf something is expensive, it costs a lot of money.\n

voca.title: experience

(특정한 감정, 신체적 느낌을) 느끼다

voca.explains:
Experience is knowledge or skill in a particular job or activity, which you have gained because you have done that job or activity for a long time.
Experience is used to refer to the past events, knowledge, and feelings that make up someone's life or character.
An experience is something that you do or that happens to you, especially something important that affects you.
If you experience a particular situation, you are in that situation or it happens to you.
If you experience a feeling, you feel it or are affected by it.

voca.explains:
Most successful people are avid readers. This is no coincidence. Books contain a lot of knowledge and wisdom. We can’t experience everything first-hand. However, we can learn a lot through books.
It is better to experience it first-hand, rather than hearing about it.
Visitors can experience it first-hand at the festival.

voca.title: experiential
voca.explains: Experiential means relating to or resulting from experience.\n

voca.title: experiment
voca.explains:
An experiment is a scientific test which is done in order to discover what happens to something in particular conditions.
An experiment is the trying out of a new idea or method in order to see what it is like and what effects it has.
If you experiment with something or experiment on it, you do a scientific test on it in order to discover what happens to it in particular conditions.
To experiment means to try out a new idea or method to see what it is like and what effects it has.
"The experiment's not over yet." Judy yelled into the phone.

voca.title: expert
voca.explains:
An expert is a person who is very skilled at doing something or who knows a lot about a particular subject.
Someone who is expert at doing something is very skilled at it.
If you say that someone has expert hands or an expert eye, you mean that they are very skilful or experienced in using their hands or eyes for a particular purpose.
Expert advice or help is given by someone who has studied a subject thoroughly or who is very skilled at a particular job.

voca.title: expertise
voca.explains: Expertise is special skill or knowledge that is acquired by training, study, or practice.\n

voca.title: expiration

voca.explains: The expiration of a fixed period of time is its ending.\nJason: What? Really? Today is only one day after the expiration date.\n

voca.title: expire
voca.explains: When something such as a contract, deadline, or visa expires, it comes to an end or is no longer valid.\n

voca.title: expire if
voca.explains:
It expires if I don’t use it.
The coupon will expire if you don’t use it within 3 months.
Your passport will expire if you don’t renew it.

voca.title: explain
voca.explains:
If you explain something, you give details about it or describe it so that it can be understood.
If you explain something that has happened, you give people reasons for it, especially in an attempt to justify it.
"And just when did you do that?" asked her mother. "Mary Alice Crosswire, you've got some fancy explaining to do."

voca.title: explain something away
voca.explains: to give reasons why you should not be blamed for something or why something is not as important or as bad as people think\n

voca.title: explanation
voca.explains:
If you give an explanation of something that has happened, you give people reasons for it, especially in an attempt to justify it.
If you say there is an explanation for something, you mean that there is a reason for it.
If you give an explanation of something, you give details about it or describe it so that it can be understood.

voca.title: explanatory
voca.explains: Explanatory statements or theories are intended to make people understand something by describing it or giving the reasons for it.\n

voca.title: explicit
voca.explains: Something that is explicit is expressed or shown clearly and openly, without any attempt to hide anything.\nIf you are explicit about something, you speak about it very openly and clearly.\n

voca.title: explode
voca.explains:
explode / blow up / go off / burst / erupt / rupture / implode
If an object such as a bomb explodes or if someone or something explodes it, it bursts loudly and with great force, often causing damage or injury.
If someone explodes, they express strong feelings suddenly and violently.
If something explodes, it increases suddenly and rapidly in number or intensity.
If someone explodes a theory or myth, they prove that it is wrong or impossible.
Muffy nearly exploded with excitement.

voca.title: exploit
voca.means:
[엑s^쁠로잇t]

착취하다
(최대한 잘) 활용하다
(사업, 산업용으로) 개발하다
위업, 공적, 활약
voca.explains:
If you say that someone is exploiting you, you think that they are treating you unfairly by using your work or ideas and giving you very little in return.
If you say that someone is exploiting a situation, you disapprove of them because they are using it to gain an advantage for themselves, rather than trying to help other people or do what is right.
If you exploit something, you use it well, and achieve something or gain an advantage from it.
To exploit resources or raw materials means to develop them and use them for industry or commercial activities.
If you refer to someone's exploits, you mean the brave, interesting, or amusing things that they have done.
The exploits of Korean baseball players in the Major League are well known in Korea.

voca.title: explore
voca.explains:
If you explore a place, you travel around it to find out what it is like.
If you explore an idea or suggestion, you think about it or comment on it in detail, in order to assess it carefully.
If people explore an area for a substance such as oil or minerals, they study the area and do tests on the land to see whether they can find it.
If you explore something with your hands or fingers, you touch it to find out what it feels like.

voca.title: explosive
voca.means:
[익s^플러우시v]
폭발성의, 폭발하기 쉬운
(폭력, 분노, 증오를) 촉발하는
(성격이) 격정적인
폭발적으로 증가하는
폭발물, 폭약
voca.explains:

Something that is explosive is capable of causing an explosion.
An explosive growth is a sudden, rapid increase in the size or quantity of something.
An explosive situation is likely to have difficult, serious, or dangerous effects.
If you describe someone as explosive, you mean that they tend to express sudden violent anger.
A sudden loud noise can be described as explosive.

voca.title: exponential
voca.explains: Exponential means growing or increasing very rapidly.\n

voca.title: export

수출, 수출품
voca.explains:
To export products or raw materials means to sell them to another country.
To export something means to introduce it into another country or make it happen there.
In computing, if you export files or information from one type of software into another type, you change their format so that they can be used in the new software.
Exports are goods which are sold to another country and sent there.

voca.title: exportation
voca.explains: the act, business, or process of exporting goods or services\nan exported product or service\n

voca.title: expose
voca.means:
[익s^뽀우z]
(보통 때는 가려져 있는 것을)드러내다, 
(비도덕적, 불법적인 것을)노출하다, 폭로하다
접하게/경험하게 하다
voca.explains:
To expose something that is usually hidden means to uncover it so that it can be seen.
To expose a person or situation means to reveal that they are bad or immoral in some way.
If someone is exposed to something dangerous or unpleasant, they are put in a situation in which it might affect them.
If someone is exposed to an idea or feeling, usually a new one, they are given experience of it, or introduced to it.
A man who exposes himself shows people his genitals in a public place, usually because he is mentally or emotionally disturbed.
An expos? is a film or piece of writing which reveals the truth about a situation or person, especially something involving shocking facts.

voca.title: exposed
voca.explains: If a place is exposed, it has no natural protection against bad weather or enemies, for example because it has no trees or is on very high ground.\n

voca.title: express

[익s쁘^뤠s]

급행, 속달편, 명확한, 신속한, 급행으로
voca.explains:

If an idea or feeling expresses itself in some way, it can be clearly seen in someone's actions or in its effects on a situation.

If you refer to an express intention or purpose, you are emphasizing that it is a deliberate and specific one that you have before you do something.

An expression is a word or phrase.

We will spend the night at my parent’s house. The next morning, we will visit my grandparent’s grave site to pay our respects. Our extended family will all be there.
I don't know the names of everyone in the extended family.

Our extended family had a party for my father’s birthday. Including my kids and nephews, it was a big get-together.

voca.title: extracurricular activity

기이한, 놀라운, 보기 드문,

임시의 특별히 임명된,

voca.explains: Another time, I put the car in reverse on a back street. By accident, I backed it into a wall. The rear fender was in shambles. I went to a repair shop for an estimate. The quote was eye-popping. I didn’t want to charge it to insurance, because it was my own fault. Since then, I’m much more careful when backing up.\n

voca.title: eyesight

얼굴
표면, 겉면, (무엇의 특별한) 측면

voca.explains:
The face value of things such as coins, paper money, investment documents, or tickets is the amount of money that they are worth, and that is written on them.
If you take something at face value, you accept it and believe it without thinking about it very much, even though it might untrue.
However, most people simply take it with a grain of salt. In many ways, the blood type personality theory is like fortune-telling. It can be dangerous to accept at face value.

voca.title: facedown
voca.explains: Jack hit the ground and fell facedown into the dust.\n

voca.title: facilitate
voca.means: [풰씰뤼테잇t]\n가능하게 하다, 용이하게 하다\n~을 수월하게/편하게 하다, 촉진하다
voca.explains: To facilitate an action or process, especially one that you would like to happen, means to make it easier or more likely to happen.\n

voca.title: facility
voca.means:
[풰^씰뤼디]
(생황의 편의를 위한) 시설, 기관
(기계, 서비스 등의 특수) 기능, 특징
(타고난) 재능
voca.explains:
Facilities are buildings, pieces of equipment, or services that are provided for a particular purpose.
A facility is something such as an additional service provided by an organization or an extra feature on a machine which is useful but not essential.
What kind of facilities does it have around?
The park has something for everyone. There are paths for a light stroll. There are lanes set aside for bicycles. There are grassy fields tailor-made for picnics. And there are facilities for all manner of sports.

voca.title: fact
voca.means: [^풱t]\n(~라는) 점, 실상, 실제, \n(특히 입증할 수 있는) 사실
voca.explains:
You use the fact that after some verbs or prepositions, especially in expressions such as in view of the fact that, apart from the fact that, and despite the fact that, to link the verb or preposition with a clause.
You use the fact that instead of a simple that-clause either for emphasis or because the clause is the subject of your sentence.
You use in fact, in actual fact, or in point of fact to indicate that you are giving more detailed information about what you have just said.
When you refer to something as a fact or as fact, you mean that you think it is true or correct.
Facts are pieces of information that can be discovered.

voca.title: fact of life
voca.explains: something difficult or unpleasant that cannot be changed and has to be accepted or dealt with\n

voca.title: factory
voca.explains: factory / plant / mill / works / yard / workshop / foundry\nA factory is a large building where machines are used to make large quantities of goods.\n

voca.title: fad
voca.explains: You use fad to refer to an activity or topic of interest that is very popular for a short time, but which people become bored with very quickly.\nBased on my experience, fad diets usually don’t work. Working out is also very important. It helps to prevent a yo-yo effect. Even when I’m busy, I try to set aside time to exercise.\n

voca.title: fade
voca.means:
[^풰이d]
(색깔이) 바래다, 희미해 지다, 
서서히 사라지다, 점점 희미해지다
흐려지다, 사라지다, 쇠퇴하다
voca.explains:
When a coloured object fades or when the light fades it, it gradually becomes paler.
When light fades, it slowly becomes less bright. When a sound fades, it slowly becomes less loud.
When something that you are looking at fades, it slowly becomes less bright or clear until it disappears.
If memories, feelings, or possibilities fade, they slowly become less intense or less strong.
Sunlight had faded from the late-afternoon sky.
But should they fail to protect it, they would fade from life.
One kind of detective fades back into the shadows once a case is solved. For that detective, solving the mystery is its own reward. He dodges the bright lights of the television cameras and the front page of the newspaper.

voca.title: fade away
voca.explains:
to gradually become less strong, clear or frequent and disappear
to become weaker and die
Before we could even go tell our mother and father, we began to fade away.

voca.title: fade in
voca.means: 점점 더 또렷해지다\n소리가 점점 더 커지다
voca.explains: if a sound or a picture in a film/movie, etc. fades in, or somebody fades it in, it gradually becomes louder or clearer\n

voca.title: fade out
voca.explains: if a sound or a picture in a film/movie, etc. fades in, or somebody fades it in, it gradually becomes louder or clearer\n

voca.title: fade out of
voca.explains: to become quieter, weaker, etc. and gradually disappear\n

voca.title: fading
voca.explains: a variation in the strength of received radio signals due to variations in the conditions of the transmission medium\nThe fading daylight lit a piano in the corner of the room.\n

voca.title: fahrenheit
voca.explains: Fahrenheit is a scale for measuring temperature, in which water freezes at 32 degrees and boils at 212 degrees. It is represented by the symbol F.\n

voca.title: fail
voca.means:
[^풰일]
실패하다, ~하지 못하다, ~하지 않다
부족하다, (시험에) 떨어지다, 
실망시키다, 도움을 못주다
낙제, 불합격
voca.explains:
If you fail to do something that you were trying to do, you are unable to do it or do not succeed in doing it.
If an activity, attempt, or plan fails, it is not successful.
If someone or something fails to do a particular thing that they should have done, they do not do it.
If something fails, it stops working properly, or does not do what it is supposed to do.
If a business, organization, or system fails, it becomes unable to continue in operation or in existence.
If something such as your health or a physical quality is failing, it is becoming gradually weaker or less effective.
But should they fail to protect it, they would fade from life.

voca.title: fail in
voca.explains: "If we don't take a stand now, we will have failed in our trust. We must-"\n

voca.title: failure
voca.means:
[^풰일류어r]
실패, 실수, 부족
실패자, 실패작
~ 하지 않음. ~불이행
고장, (기업의) 도산
voca.explains:
Failure is a lack of success in doing or achieving something, especially in relation to a particular activity.
If something is a failure, it is not a success.
If you say that someone is a failure, you mean that they have not succeeded in a particular activity, or that they are unsuccessful at everything they do.
Your failure to do a particular thing is the fact that you do not do it, even though you were expected to do it.
If there is a failure of something, for example a machine or part of the body, it goes wrong and stops working or developing properly.
If there is a failure of a business or bank, it is no longer able to continue operating.

voca.title: faint
voca.means:
[^풰인t]
(빛, 소리, 냄세 등이) 희미한, 약한, 
(가능성이) 아주 적은, 미약한
현기증이나서졸도하다, 기절하다
기절, 실신
voca.explains:
A faint sound, colour, mark, feeling, or quality has very little strength or intensity.
A faint attempt at something is one that is made without proper effort and with little enthusiasm.
Someone who is faint feels weak and unsteady as if they are about to lose consciousness.
If you faint, you lose consciousness for a short time, especially because you are hungry, or because of pain, heat, or shock.
He felt faint.
From over the hill came the faint sounds of sweet, joyful music.
One kid blew such a long note on his trumpet that he almost fainted.

voca.title: fair
voca.means:
[^풰어r]
품평회, 박람회
공정한, 공평한, 적정한, 타당한, 온당한
(수, 크기, 양)이 상당한, 제법 큰, 꽤 되는, 괜찮은, 
(날씨가) 맑은, 잔잔한, 순풍의
공평하게, 정확하게
voca.explains:
Something or someone that is fair is reasonable, right, and just.
A fair amount, degree, size, or distance is quite a large amount, degree, size, or distance.
A fair guess or idea about something is one that is likely to be correct.
If you describe someone or something as fair, you mean that they are average in standard or quality, neither very good nor very bad.
Someone who is fair, or who has fair hair, has light-coloured hair.
Fair skin is very pale and usually burns easily.
When the weather is fair, it is quite sunny and not raining.
A county, state, or country fair is an event where there are, for example, displays of goods and animals, and amusements, games, and competitions.
A fair is an event at which people display and sell goods, especially goods of a particular type.

voca.title: fairly
voca.explains:
quite / fairly / rather / pretty
Fairly means to quite a large degree. For example, if you say that something is fairly old, you mean that it is old but not very old.
You use fairly instead of 'very' to add emphasis to an adjective or adverb without making it sound too forceful.
The internet is a fairly new medium.

voca.title: fairness
voca.explains: Fairness is the quality of being reasonable, right, and just.\n

voca.title: fairy
voca.explains: A fairy is an imaginary creature with magical powers. Fairies are often represented as small people with wings.\nIf someone describes a man as a fairy, they mean that he is a homosexual and they disapprove of this.\n

voca.title: fairy tale
voca.explains: A fairy tale is a story for children involving magical events and imaginary creatures.\nThe origin story of Korea's founding is a fun fairy tale.\n

voca.title: faith
voca.means: [^풰이쓰]\n(남의 능력, 지식, 약속에 대한) 믿음, 신뢰\n신앙(심), (특정) 종교, 신앙
voca.explains:
If you have faith in someone or something, you feel confident about their ability or goodness.
A faith is a particular religion, for example Christianity, Buddhism, or Islam.
Faith is strong religious belief in a particular God.
If you break faith with someone you made a promise to or something you believed in, you stop acting in a way that supports them.
If you do something in good faith, you seriously believe that what you are doing is right, honest, or legal, even though this may not be the case.
If you keep faith with someone you have made a promise to or something you believe in, you continue to support them even when it is difficult to do so.

voca.title: faithful
voca.explains:
Someone who is faithful to a person, organization, idea, or activity remains firm in their belief in them or support for them.
Someone who is faithful to their husband, wife, or lover does not have a sexual relationship with anyone else.
A faithful account, translation, or copy of something represents or reproduces the original accurately.

voca.title: fake
voca.means:
[풰이k]
~을 날조하다, 꾸며내다, 위조하다, ~인 체 하다
가짜의, 거짓된, 모조의
위조품, 사기꾼, 신빙성 없는 이야기
voca.explains:
artificial / synthetic / false / man-made / fake / imitation
A fake fur or a fake painting, for example, is a fur or painting that has been made to look valuable or genuine, usually in order to deceive people.
If someone fakes something, they try to make it look valuable or genuine, although in fact it is not.
If you fake a feeling, emotion, or reaction, you pretend that you are experiencing it when you are not.
Someone who is a fake is not what they claim to be, for example because they do not have the qualifications that they claim to have.

voca.title: fake out
voca.explains: to trick somebody; to make somebody think you are going to do one thing and then do another\n

voca.title: fall
voca.means:
[^풜-]
떨어지다, 빠지다, 내리다, 감소하다
(양, 수, 강도가) 줄다, 떨어지다, 
가을, 폭포, 멸망, 감소,
voca.explains:
fall - fell - fallen
If someone or something falls, they move quickly downwards onto or towards the ground, by accident or because of a natural force.
If a person or structure that is standing somewhere falls, they move from their upright position, so that they are then lying on the ground.
When rain or snow falls, it comes down from the sky.
If you fall somewhere, you allow yourself to drop there in a hurried or disorganized way, often because you are very tired.
If something falls, it decreases in amount, value, or strength.
If a powerful or successful person falls, they suddenly lose their power or position.
If a place falls in a war or election, an enemy army or a different political party takes control of it.
You can use fall to show that someone or something passes into another state. For example, if someone falls ill, they become ill, and if something falls into disrepair, it is then in a state of disrepair.
He fell right over and lay on his side.
Feeling bruised and battered, he fell onto the sand.

voca.title: fall among
voca.means: 우연히 ~속에 까다, 한패가 되다,\n(도둑 따위)를 만나다

voca.title: fall apart
voca.explains:
to be old or in bad condition and break or break into pieces
to have so many problems that it is no longer possible to exist or operate
to have so many problems or worries that you can no longer think or behave normally
Mark: Carlos it looks like your fence is falling apart.
Because of all the rain we've had my roof is falling apart.

voca.title: fall behind
voca.explains: to drop back; fail to keep up\nto be in arrears, as with a payment\n

voca.title: fall behind in payment
voca.explains:
I was slapped with traffic fines. To make things worse, I had to pay through the nose for treatment at the dentist’s. At the end of the month, I received my credit card bill. I couldn’t muster up the money to pay it. I fell behind in payment.
Falling behind in payment can hurt your credit.
She fell behind in payment because she didn't receive her bill.

voca.title: fall beneath
voca.means: (차, 물건 따위)에 깔리다\n(사람, 사상 따위)에 영향/감화을 받다

voca.title: fall foliage
voca.explains: In Korea, the fall foliage peaks in late October.\n

voca.title: fall for each other
voca.explains:
It reminded me of when we first fell for each other. I think my wife felt the same way.
We didn't fall for each other the first time we met.
We went on a date to the place where we fell for each other.

voca.title: fall head over heels
voca.explains:
I tripped on something, and fell head over heels, I dropped the box. I stubbed my toe.
I fell head over heels on the ski slope.
He fell head over heels for his newborn son.

voca.title: fall in
voca.explains: if a roof or a ceiling falls in, it drops to the ground\nto move into a line\n

voca.title: fall into
voca.explains: It fell silently into a heap at Jack and Annie's feet.\n

voca.title: fall into a funk
voca.explains: My friends are my greatest asset. A while ago, I was going through a rough patch at work. I felt like my career was at a dead end. I fell into a funk. Thankfully, I have good friends who helped me snap out of it.\n

voca.title: fall into a misunderstanding
voca.explains:
A while ago, I fell into a misunderstanding with a friend. I mentioned her in a conversation with a mutual acquaintance. It was just small talk. However, she had the mistaken impression that I was talking behind her back.
With not enough information, he fell into a misunderstanding.
I don't want to fall into a misunderstanding with you.

voca.title: fall into place
voca.means: 제자리에 돌아가다, 꼭 들어맞다, 앞뒤가 맞다

voca.title: fall off
voca.explains: She clutched the mammoth's ears to keep from falling off.\n

voca.title: fall on
voca.explains:
to be the responsibility or duty of a particular person or organization
if your eyes fall on somebody/something, you suddenly see or notice them/it
to attack somebody/something with energy or enthusiasm

voca.title: fall out
voca.explains:
to become loose and drop out
to have an argument with somebody and stop being friendly with them
to move out of lines
The canoe rocked. He nearly fell out.

voca.title: fall out of touch
voca.explains:
We ended up falling out of touch. Recently, we ran into each other by chance. I swallowed my pride and said hello.
It's sad to fall out of touch with old friends.
They talk so often, they will never fall out of touch.

voca.title: fall over
voca.explains:
We don't want to fall over in these suits.
A hush fell over the room.
He fell over when he got a charley horse.

voca.title: fall to something
voca.explains: to start doing something\n

voca.title: false
voca.explains:
artificial / synthetic / false / man-made / fake / imitation
If something is false, it is incorrect, untrue, or mistaken.
You use false to describe objects which are artificial but which are intended to look like the real thing or to be used instead of the real thing.
If you describe a person or their behaviour as false, you are criticizing them for being insincere or for hiding their real feelings.

voca.title: fame
voca.explains: If you achieve fame, you become very well-known.\n

voca.title: familiaize
voca.means: [풰^밀뤼어롸이z]\n익숙하게 하다\n친하게 하다, 익숙하게 하다, 정통하게 하다
voca.explains: If you familiarize yourself with something, or if someone familiarizes you with it, you learn about it and start to understand it.\nOf course, the core piece of knowledge you need to use a language is to know the language itself, and  familiarize yourself with its syntax and modules.\n

voca.title: familiar
voca.means:
[풰^밀뤼어r]
익숙한, 친숙한, 낮익은
~을 아주 잘 아는, ~에 익숙한
(때론 불쾌감을 줄 정도로) 스스럼없는
voca.explains:
If someone or something is familiar to you, you recognize them or know them well.
If you are familiar with something, you know or understand it well.
If someone you do not know well behaves in a familiar way towards you, they treat you very informally in a way that you might find offensive.

voca.title: familiar face
voca.explains: I recently bumped into a friend on the street. I was walking to a store, and I saw a familiar face.\n

voca.title: familiar with
voca.explains:
Koreans are very familiar with Japanese food.
I am very familiar with this neighborhood.
We are very familiar with that brand.

voca.title: family
voca.means:
[^풰밀릐]
(부모와 자녀로 구성된) 가족, 가정, 가구
(가까운 친척들을 포함한) 가족, 집안 식구
가문, 가계
(특히 어린) 자녀
가족/가정의, (특정) 가족과 관련된
가족/집안 소유의
가족에게 알맞은
voca.explains:
A family is a group of people who are related to each other, especially parents and their children.
When people talk about a family, they sometimes mean children.
When people talk about their family, they sometimes mean their ancestors.
A family of animals or plants is a group of related species.
You can use family to describe things that belong to a particular family.
You can use family to describe things that are designed to be used or enjoyed by both parents and children.

voca.title: family of
voca.explains:
It was just the right size for a family of six.
It's a small house for a family of four.
One bathroom is not enough for a family of five.

voca.title: famine
voca.explains: Famine is a situation in which large numbers of people have little or no food, and many of them die.\n

voca.title: famish
voca.explains:
to be or make very hungry or weak
to die or cause to die from starvation
to make very cold

voca.title: famous
voca.explains: Someone or something that is famous is very well known.\nLisa: What is this place famous for?\n

voca.title: famously
voca.explains: You use famously to refer to a fact that is well known, usually because it is remarkable or extreme.\nIf you get on or get along famously with someone, you are very friendly with each other and enjoy meeting and being together.\n

voca.title: fan
voca.means:
[^풴]
팬, 부채, 선풍기, 환풍기
(바람을) 일으키다, 부체질하다
(영화, 스포츠 등의) 팬
voca.explains:
If you are a fan of someone or something, especially a famous person or a sport, you like them very much and are very interested in them.
A fan is a flat object that you hold in your hand and wave in order to move the air and make yourself feel cooler.
A fan is a piece of electrical or mechanical equipment with blades that go round and round. It keeps a room or machine cool or gets rid of unpleasant smells.
If you fan yourself or your face when you are hot, you wave a fan or other flat object in order to make yourself feel cooler.
If you fan a fire, you wave something flat next to it in order to make it burn more strongly. If a wind fans a fire, it blows on it and makes it burn more strongly.
If someone fans an emotion such as fear, hatred, or passion, they deliberately do things to make people feel the emotion more strongly.
It’s very hard to make it through the summer without air conditioning in Korea. I got a taste of it last year. Our air conditioner stopped blowing cold air. It was leaking water. We tried to get by with a fan. But the summer weather was more than it could handle.

voca.title: fan out
voca.explains: to spread out over an area from a central point\n

voca.title: fancy
voca.means:
[^풴시]
~을 상상하다, ~이라고 생각되다, 
원하다, ~하고 싶다
공상, 상상, 바람, 욕망
상상의, 장식이 많은, 고급의, 화려한,
voca.explains:
If you fancy something, you want to have it or to do it.
If you fancy someone, you feel attracted to them, especially in a sexual way.
If you fancy yourself as a particular kind of person or fancy yourself doing a particular thing, you like the idea of being that kind of person or doing that thing.
If you say that someone fancies themselves as a particular kind of person, you mean that they think, often wrongly, that they have the good qualities which that kind of person has.
A fancy is a liking or desire for someone or something, especially one that does not last long.
"'Whereabouts,' huh? That’s a pretty fancy way of asking me where I was. Well, I was right here in the kitchen, making brownies. Buster, keep your hands away from that bowl!"

voca.title: fancy restaurant
voca.explains: We went to a fancy restaurant for dinner. We couldn't stay for long because of our kids.\n

voca.title: fanfare
voca.explains: A fanfare is a short, loud tune played on trumpets or other similar instruments to announce a special event.\nIf something happens with a fanfare, it happens or is announced with a lot of publicity. If something happens without a fanfare, it happens without a lot of fuss or publicity.\n

voca.title: fang
voca.explains: Fangs are the two long, sharp, upper teeth that some animals have.\nA giant tiger with two long sharp fangs.\n

voca.title: fantastic
voca.explains:
great / cool / fantastic / fabulous / terrific / brilliant / awesome
If you say that something is fantastic, you are emphasizing that you think it is very good or that you like it a lot.
A fantastic amount or quantity is an extremely large one.
You describe something as fantastic or fantastical when it seems strange and wonderful or unlikely.

voca.title: fantasy
voca.explains:
A fantasy is a pleasant situation or event that you think about and that you want to happen, especially one that is unlikely to happen.
You can refer to a story or situation that someone creates from their imagination and that is not based on reality as fantasy.
