Fantasy is the activity of imagining things.
Soon you will be called upon to use your knowledge of Everyday Magic in the realm of fantasy.

voca.title: far
voca.means:
[퐈아r]
멀리, (~만큼) 떨어져 (멀리), 
(현재로부터) 오래전에, (특정 시기가) 한참 지나도록, 
훨씬, 아주, 대단히, 
(일의 진척 상황과 관련하여) ~까지, 
훨씬 전의, 먼쪽의, 오래 전에,
voca.explains:
If one place, thing, or person is far away from another, there is a great distance between them.
If you ask how far a place is, you are asking what distance it is from you or from another place. If you ask how far someone went, you are asking what distance they travelled, or what place they reached.
A time or event that is far away in the future or the past is a long time from the present or from a particular point in time.
You can talk about how far someone or something gets to describe the progress that they make.
You can use far to mean 'very much' when you are comparing two things and emphasizing the difference between them. For example, you can say that something is far better or far worse than something else to indicate that it is very much better or worse. You can also say that something is, for example, far too big to indicate that it is very much too big.
When there are two things of the same kind in a place, the far one is the one that is a greater distance from you.

voca.title: far ahead
voca.explains: Arthur wasn't so sure. "Everyone else just seems so far ahead of me. And I feel funny asking for help about stuff that everybody else knows already."\n

voca.title: far and away
voca.explains:
very much; by a very great amount
That’s why it really rubs me the wrong way. Drivers should remember that safety is far and away the most important thing.
The refrigerator is far and away my favorite home appliance. That’s because it’s where we keep our food.
She is far and away the smartest student in class.
He is far and away the best dancer in his group.

voca.title: far and wide
voca.explains: everywhere and many places; over a large area\n

voca.title: far away
voca.explains: How far away is San Francisco?\n

voca.title: far from it
voca.explains: not at all; certainly not\n

voca.title: faraway
voca.explains: A faraway place is a long distance from you or from a particular place.\n

voca.title: fare
voca.explains:
A fare is the money that you pay for a journey that you make, for example, in a bus, train, or taxi.
If you say that someone or something fares well or badly, you are referring to the degree of success they achieve in a particular situation or activity.
What's the fare to the Opera House?
Transportation has also become faster. In the past, plane tickets used to be pricey. Now, there are low-cost carriers. Their fares are much cheaper.
In one voice, tourists rave about the affordable cab rides in Korea. Cab fares are quite reasonable here.

voca.title: farewell
voca.explains: Farewell means the same as goodbye.\n"Farewell, Jack and Annie!" said Sir Galahad.\n

voca.title: farmland
voca.explains: Farmland is land which is farmed, or which is suitable for farming.\n

voca.title: fart
voca.means: [^퐈r-t]\n(특히 소리가 크게 나게) 방귀를 뀌다\n방귀, 시원찮은 놈
voca.explains: If someone farts, air is forced out of their body through their anus.\n

voca.title: farther
voca.means: [^풔r-더r]\n(공간, 시간상으로) 더 멀리, 더 먼\nfar 의 최상급비교
voca.explains:
farther / further / farthest / furthest
Farther is a comparative form of far.
She pointed at a painting farther down the wall.
Without talking, they pushed steadily through the trees and bushes, moving farther and farther from the keepers' cave.
Buster laughed. "Did I? Let me show you. Run out for a long catch." Arthur trotted past a tree. Buster waved him on. "Farther... farther... Okay, stand there. Are you ready? See if you can catch the famous Buster Ball."

voca.title: fashion
voca.means:
[^풰션]
(의상, 머리형 등의) 유행(하는 스타일), 인기
(행동, 문화 등의) 유행하는 방식
패션, 의류업
유행, 일반적 풍습, 인기있는 물건/사람
(재료를 써서) 만들다, (여론 등을) 형성하다
voca.explains:
Fashion is the area of activity that involves styles of clothing and appearance.
A fashion is a style of clothing or a way of behaving that is popular at a particular time.
If you do something in a particular fashion or after a particular fashion, you do it in that way.
If you fashion an object or a work of art, you make it.
If you say that something was done after a fashion, you mean that it was done, but not very well.
If something is in fashion, it is popular and approved of at a particular time. If it is out of fashion, it is not popular or approved of.

voca.title: fashionable
voca.means: [^풰셔너붤]\n유행하는, 유행을 따른\n(유행의 첨단을 걷는 사람들, 특히) 부유층이 애용하는
voca.explains: Something or someone that is fashionable is popular or approved of at a particular time.\nOverall, I'm not a fashionable person. However, I do like to look presentable at all times.\n

voca.title: fashion-conscious
voca.explains:
As a result, people have become a lot more fashion-conscious than in the past.
Teenagers are very fashion-conscious.
You have to be fashion-conscious to work here.

voca.title: fast
voca.means:
[^풰st]
(움직임이) 빠른, (일을) 빨리 하는, (제시간 보다) 빠른
빨리, 빠르게, 단단히, 완전히
단식하다
voca.explains:
quick / quickly / fast
Fast means happening, moving, or doing something at great speed. You also use fast in questions or statements about speed.
If a watch or clock is fast, it is showing a time that is later than the real time.
If colours or dyes are fast, they do not come out of the fabrics they are used on when they get wet.
You use fast to say that something happens without any delay.
If you hold something fast, you hold it tightly and firmly. If something is stuck fast, it is stuck very firmly and cannot move.
If you fast, you eat no food for a period of time, usually for either religious or medical reasons, or as a protest.
If you hold fast to a principle or idea, or if you stand fast, you do not change your mind about it, even though people are trying to persuade you to.

voca.title: fast asleep
voca.explains:
Soon he, too, was fast asleep.
The worst was when I got a cramp in my sleep. I was fast asleep when I felt a stitch in my side. I woke up with a start. It took a long time for my muscles to loosen up. I didn’t doze off again until the crack of dawn.
The baby was adorable when he was fast asleep.
She was fast asleep when I got home.

voca.title: fast food joint
voca.explains: For instance, when I go to my favorite fast food joint, I always order the same combo menu.\n

voca.title: fast learner
voca.explains:
Our son and daughter learned to ski for the first time last year. They are fast learners. This year, they have already gotten the hang of it.
A fast learner will be able to do this very quickly.
I am not a fast learner, but I work hard.

voca.title: fasten
voca.means:
[^풰슨]
(무엇의 두 부분을 연결하여) 매다, 묶다(채우다), 
(단단히) 잠그다, 
(움직이지 않게) 고정시키다, 
정시키다, 집중하다
(별명을) 붙이다, 
(누명/죄를) 씌우다
voca.explains:
When you fasten something, you close it by means of buttons or a strap, or some other device. If something fastens with buttons or straps, you can close it in this way.
If you fasten one thing to another, you attach the first thing to the second, for example with a piece of string or tape.
Jack fastened the red cloak around his neck.

voca.title: fasten off
voca.explains: She fastened the silk off with her watching TV.\n

voca.title: fasten up
voca.means: 꼭 닫다(잠그다), 묶어 놓다, 가두어 놓다
voca.explains: to close, or to make something close, with buttons, etc.\n

voca.title: fat
voca.explains:
If you say that a person or animal is fat, you mean that they have a lot of flesh on their body and that they weigh too much. You usually use the word fat when you think that this is a bad thing.
A fat object, especially a book, is very thick or wide.
A fat profit or fee is a large one.
Fat is the extra flesh that animals and humans have under their skin, which is used to store energy and to help keep them warm.
Fat is a solid or liquid substance obtained from animals or vegetables, which is used in cooking.
Fat is a substance contained in foods such as meat, cheese, and butter which forms an energy store in your body.

voca.title: fat chance
voca.means: 가망이 거의 없는\n가망 없음, 매우 희박한 가망성.
voca.explains: Marshall: Fat chance that she would tell me.\n

voca.title: fatal
voca.explains: A fatal action has very undesirable effects.\nA fatal accident or illness causes someone's death.\n

voca.title: fatality
voca.means:
[풰이탈릐디]
(재난, 질명으로 인한) 사망자(수), 
(특정 질명의) 치사율
재해, 재난, 치사성
voca.explains: A fatality is a death caused by an accident or by violence.\n

voca.title: fate
voca.means: [^쀄잇t]\n운명(운명에 따라 일어나는, 특히 좋지 않은 일)\n(초월적인 힘으로서의) 운명/숙명
voca.explains:
luck / chance / coincidence / accident / fortune / fate / destiny / providence
Fate is a power that some people believe controls and decides everything that happens, in a way that cannot be prevented or changed. You can also refer to the fates.
A person's or thing's fate is what happens to them.
If something seals a person's or thing's fate, it makes it certain that they will fail or that something unpleasant will happen to them.
"Then you choose your fate," said the Christmas Knight.
Arthur sat down in his chair and thought about his fate.
Your fate is determined by your effort.

voca.title: father
voca.means:
[^파r더r]
아버지, 아버지 같은 사람, 
(동물 새끼의) 아비
조상, 시조, 
하느님 아버지, 
(가톨릭 교의) 신부
voca.explains:
Your father is your male parent. You can also call someone your father if he brings you up as if he was this man.
The man who invented or started something is sometimes referred to as the father of that thing.
In some Christian churches, priests are addressed or referred to as Father.
When a man fathers a child, he makes a woman pregnant and their child is born.

voca.title: father-in-law
voca.explains: Someone's father-in-law is the father of their husband or wife.\n

voca.title: fatigue
voca.means:
[풰^티-g]
피로
(금속, 나무의) 피로, 약화
(군인의) 작업복, 훈련복
(군인들에게 특히 벌로 하게 하는) 잡역
voca.explains:
Fatigue is a feeling of extreme physical or mental tiredness.
You can say that people are suffering from a particular kind of fatigue when they have been doing something for a long time and feel they can no longer continue to do it.
Fatigues are clothes that soldiers wear when they are fighting or when they are doing routine jobs.
Fatigue in metal or wood is a weakness in it that is caused by repeated stress. Fatigue can cause the metal or wood to break.

voca.title: fatty
voca.explains: Fatty food contains a lot of fat.\nFatty acids or fatty tissues, for example, contain or consist of fat.\n

voca.title: faucet
voca.explains: A faucet is a device that controls the flow of a liquid or gas from a pipe or container. Sinks and baths have faucets attached to them.\nWhy is there no water coming out when I turn on the faucet?\n

voca.title: fault
voca.explains:
If a bad or undesirable situation is your fault, you caused it or are responsible for it.
A fault is a mistake in what someone is doing or in what they have done.
A fault in someone or something is a weakness in them or something that is not perfect.
If you cannot fault someone, you cannot find any reason for criticizing them or the things that they are doing.

voca.title: favor
voca.means:
[^풰이버r]
친절한 행위, 부탁, 호의, 지지, 원조, 허가
인기, 평판, 유행
찬성하다, 선호하다
voca.explains: Jason: Hi, Donna, could you do me a favor?\n"I see you favor the rolling approach." said her father.\n

voca.title: favorite
voca.means: [^풰이버릿t]\n좋아하는, 마음에 드는, \n좋아하는 사람, 특히 좋아하는 물건

voca.title: fear
voca.means: [^퓌어r]\n두려움, 공포, 불안, 근심, 걱정, 염려\n두려워하다, 무서워하다
voca.explains:
fear / alarm / apprehension / fright / foreboding
Fear is the unpleasant feeling you have when you think that you are in danger.
A fear is a thought that something unpleasant might happen or might have happened.
If you say that there is a fear that something unpleasant or undesirable will happen, you mean that you think it is possible or likely
If you have fears for someone or something, you are very worried because you think that they might be in danger.
If you fear something unpleasant or undesirable, you are worried that it might happen or might have happened.
If you fear for someone or something, you are very worried because you think that they might be in danger
He feared that once they were alone, Squanto would figure out they'd never met before.
His fears slipped away.
With a flatulent sound, they ripped in the seat. All day, I was a bundle of nerves. I stayed seated for fear that someone would see.

voca.title: fearful
voca.explains:
If you are fearful of something, you are afraid of it.
You use fearful to emphasize how serious or bad a situation is.
Fearful is used to emphasize that something is very bad.

voca.title: feast
voca.means: [퓌-st]\n연회, 잔치, 축제, 향연, (종교적인) 제례, 성찬\n대접받다, 즐기다, 성찬으로 대접하다
voca.explains:
A feast is a large and special meal.
A feast is a day or time of the year when a special religious celebration takes place.
If you feast on a particular food, you eat a large amount of it with great enjoyment.
If you feast, you take part in a feast.
The title said A Feast to Remember.
He pictured a beautiful, glowing castle lit with candles and filled with knights and ladies feasting and singing.
"It's the great hall," he said "where they have feasts and stuff."

voca.title: feast your eye
voca.explains: look at somebody/something and get great pleasure\n

voca.title: feat
voca.explains:
action / move / act / gesture / deed / feat
If you refer to an action, or the result of an action, as a feat, you admire it because it is an impressive and difficult achievement.
"Step right up!" Buster went on. "See the Amazing Arthur perform feats of wonder! Then sign your name to save our books."

voca.title: feather
voca.explains:
A bird's feathers are the soft covering on its body. Each feather consists of a lot of smooth hairs on each side of a thin stiff centre.
Its feathers glistened in the golden afternoon light.
One of its tail feathers was bent.
Moonlight shone on its sleek blue-black wings, its shaggy throat feathers, its thick neck and big beak.

voca.title: feature
voca.means:
[^쀠-쳐r]
특징, 기능, 특집기사
이목구비(의 각 부분)
특별히 포함하다, 특징으로 삼다
~의 특징을 이루다
voca.explains:
A feature of something is an interesting or important part or characteristic of it.
Your features are your eyes, nose, mouth, and other parts of your face.
A feature is a special article in a newspaper or magazine, or a special programme on radio or television.
A feature or a feature film or movie is a full-length film about a fictional situation, as opposed to a short film or a documentary.
A geographical feature is something noticeable in a particular area of country, for example a hill, river, or valley.
When something such as a film or exhibition features a particular person or thing, they are an important part of it.
If someone or something features in something such as a show, exhibition, or magazine, they are an important part of it.
Today's choices featured a mystery meat covered in gravy.

voca.title: February
voca.explains: February is the second month of the year in the Western calendar.\n

voca.title: federal
voca.explains:
A federal country or system of government is one in which the different states or provinces of the country have important powers to make their own laws and decisions.
Some people use federal to describe a system of government which they disapprove of, in which the different states or provinces are controlled by a strong central government.
Federal also means belonging or relating to the national government of a federal country rather than to one of the states within it.

voca.title: fedora
voca.explains: A fedora is a type of hat which has a brim and is made from a soft material such as velvet.\n"This hat is not goofy." said Buster. "It's a fedora-part of my new detective kit. I've been snooping-ah, looking for crimes."\n

voca.title: fee
voca.means: [^퓌-]\n(전문적인 서비스에 대한) 요금, 수수료, 금액, 사례금\n(조직 기관등에 내는) 요금/회비/가입비
voca.explains:
rate / charge / fee / rent / dues / toll / rental / tariff
A fee is a sum of money that you pay to be allowed to do something.
A fee is the amount of money that a person or organization is paid for a particular job or service that they provide.

voca.title: feeble
voca.explains:
If you describe someone or something as feeble, you mean that they are weak.
If you describe something that someone says as feeble, you mean that it is not very good or convincing.
He took a few feeble steps.

voca.title: feed
voca.means:
[^퓌-d]
먹이를 주다, 부양하다, 공급하다
(필요, 욕구 등을) 충족시키다
먹이, 사료
voca.explains:
feed - fed - fed
If you feed a person or animal, you give them food to eat and sometimes actually put it in their mouths.
To feed a family or a community means to supply food for them.
When an animal feeds, it eats or drinks something.
When a baby feeds, or when you feed it, it drinks breast milk or milk from a bottle.
Animal feed is food given to animals, especially farm animals.
Never again will I feed good man to the magic and monsters of the Otherworld!
Judy slid her wobbly egg into the napkin on her lap, and fed in to Mouse, their cat, under the table.
I petted a goat, fed a giraffe, and then went on a tour to visit the lion’s den.

voca.title: feed into something
voca.explains: to have an influence on the development of something\n

voca.title: feed on
voca.explains: to use something as food; to eat something; to get strength from something\nto become stronger because of something else\n

voca.title: feed somebody up
voca.explains: to give extra food to a person or an animal to make them stronger and more healthy\n

voca.title: feedback
voca.explains:
If you get feedback on your work or progress, someone tells you how well or badly you are doing, and how you could improve. If you get good feedback you have worked or performed well.
Feedback is the unpleasant high-pitched sound produced by a piece of electrical equipment when part of the signal that comes out goes back into it.
Erica: Yes. I wanted to get some feedback on some ideas I have.

voca.title: feel
voca.means:
[^f읠]
(특정한 감정, 기분을/이) 들다, 느끼다
(촉감으로) 느끼다, (마을으로) 느끼다/인식하다
~인 것 같다, (특정한 느낌, 인상이) 들다
~라고 생각하다
voca.explains:
feel - felt - felt
If you feel a particular emotion or physical sensation, you experience it.
If you talk about how an experience or event feels, you talk about the emotions and sensations connected with it.
If you talk about how an object feels, you talk about the physical quality that you notice when you touch or hold it. For example, if something feels soft, you notice that it is soft when you touch it.
If you talk about how the weather feels, you describe the weather, especially the temperature or whether or not you think it is going to rain or snow.
If you feel an object, you touch it deliberately with your hand, so that you learn what it is like, for example what shape it is or whether it is rough or smooth.
If you can feel something, you are aware of it because it is touching you.

voca.title: feel alert
voca.explains:
As soon as I open my eyes, I check my phone, Then I take a shower. It makes me feel alert.
I didn't sleep much, but I feel alert.
Drink some coffee to fee alert.

voca.title: feel cheated
voca.explains:
But compared to the price, the food was a let-down. It was all flash and no substance. I felt cheated throughout the meal. In my book, it was a big waste of money.
The price was so high that I felt cheated.
Do some research beforehand, if you don't want to feel cheated.

voca.title: feel comfortable
voca.explains: Now I feel comfortable speaking English. It doesn't make me feel nervous.\n

voca.title: feel confident
voca.explains: However, I am willing to endure it. It's the price to pay to feel confident when I smile.\n

voca.title: feel disoriented
voca.explains: I became very seasick. I took some medicine, but it was too little too late. I emptied my stomach. I felt disoriented. I broke out in a cold sweat. I was all but begging to get off the boat. It was not a very enjoyable experience.\n

voca.title: feel down
voca.explains: I paid them back soon, but it still made me feel down in the dumps. However, the experience had a silver lining. It inspired me to work harder. It also taught me the importance of responsible spending.\n

voca.title: feel down in the dumps
voca.explains: I paid them back soon, but it still made me feel down in the dumps. However, the experience had a silver lining. It inspired me to work harder. It also taught me the importance of responsible spending.\n

voca.title: feel lethargic
voca.explains:
I recently had one of the nastiest colds I’d had in years. I first started to feel lethargic and had a fever.
I don't know why, but feel lethargic.
I've been feeling lethargic all day.

voca.title: feel like jelly
voca.means: 힘이 하나도 없다, 힘이 다 빠지다
voca.explains: feel weak because you are nervous or frightened.\n

voca.title: feel like oneself again
voca.explains:
I had to visit an ear, nose and throat (ENT) doctor. The doctor wrote me a prescription for medicine. For the next week, I had to take it easy with my voice. It was a long time before I felt like myself again.
After some rest, she felt like herself again.
The injury was so bad, he never felt like himself again.

voca.title: feel nervous
voca.explains: Now I feel comfortable speaking English. It doesn't make me feel nervous.\n

voca.title: feel on edge
voca.explains: Now, I feel on edge during physical activities.\n

voca.title: feel out of step with
voca.means: ~와 잘 맞지 않다, \n~와 보조가 잘 맞지 않다, \n~와 손발이 잘 맞지 않다
voca.explains: I feel out of step with everyone at work.\n

voca.title: feel pressured
voca.explains:
When I was in college, I had a part-time job as a tutor. I taught English and math to two middle school students. At first, I felt pressured. If the students did poorly, it would be on me.
It's natural to feel presured at a new job.
A leader always feels pressured.

voca.title: feel queasy
voca.explains:
One time, my stomach acted up repeatedly. I had trouble digesting food. I felt queasy all the time.
She felt queasy from the bus ride.
Try taking a deep breath when you feel queasy.

voca.title: feel refreshed
voca.explains:
I felt refreshed when I got home.
It's hard to feel refreshed in this weather.
You will feel refreshed if you get plenty of sleep.
Along the way, I stopped at the exercise equipment to stretch and catch my breath. It was just the right amount of exercise. When I got home, I felt refreshed.
I took a shower and felt refreshed.
I always feel refreshed after a workout.

voca.title: feel relieved
voca.explains: She felt relieved when interview was over.\n

voca.title: feel rushed
voca.explains:
I set off for work at 7:30. The best thing about waking up early is that I don’t feel rushed in the morning.
If you start early, you will not feel rushed.
I felt rushed, but my friend was calm.

voca.title: feel sick
voca.means: 곧 토할 것 같다\n몸 상태가 좋지 않다. 아프다
voca.explains: If you drink heavily or stay up late on New Year's Eve, you might feel sick on the first day of the New Year.\n

voca.title: feel sick to one's stomach
voca.explains:
I also saw several clips of traffic accidents from dash cams in cars. It made me feel sick to my stomach. It remined me again that when driving, safety is paramount.
This food makes me feel sick to my stomach.
He was so nervous that he felt sick to his stomach.

voca.title: feel strange
voca.explains: not feel comfortable in a situation; have an unpleasant physical feeling\n

voca.title: feel under te weather
voca.means: 아프다, 몸이 좋지 않다.\n컨디션이 좋지 않다
voca.explains:
A while ago, I felt under the weather. It persisted for a long time. It wasn’t a specific ailment. It was just chronic fatigue.
You should go home if you're feeling under the weather.
She had to rest because she felt under the weather.

voca.title: feel unfamiliar
voca.explains: Many movies are shot 3D. Others are shot normally, and are converted 3D later on. It felt unfamiliar at first, but more people are getting used to the concept.\n

voca.title: feet
voca.explains: Feet is the plural of foot.\nIt fell silently into a heap at Jack and Annie's feet.\n

voca.title: fellow
voca.means:
[풸로우-]
(남자나 소년을 가리켜) 녀석/친구
동료, 동년배, 
(학술, 전문직 단체의) 회원
연구비를 받는 대학원생
같은 처지에 있는, 동료의
voca.explains:
You use fellow to describe people who are in the same situation as you, or people you feel you have something in common with.
A fellow is a man or boy.
Your fellows are the people who you work with, do things with, or who are like you in some way.
A fellow of an academic or professional association is someone who is a specially elected member of it, usually because of their work or achievements or as a mark of honour.

voca.title: female
voca.explains:
Someone who is female is a woman or a girl.
Female matters and things relate to, belong to, or affect women rather than men.
A female flower or plant contains the part that will become the fruit when it is fertilized.
Women and girls are sometimes referred to as females when they are being considered as a type.
You can refer to any creature that can lay eggs or produce babies from its body as a female.

voca.title: fence
voca.explains:
A fence is a barrier between two areas of land, made of wood or wire supported by posts.
A fence in show jumping or horse racing is an obstacle or barrier that horses have to jump over.
If you fence an area of land, you surround it with a fence.

voca.title: fence something off
voca.explains: to separate one area from another with a fence, often to stop people or animals from entering\n

voca.title: fender
voca.means:
[^풴더r]
(벽난로 앞에 세워 두는) 난로망
(자동차·오토바이 등의) 펜더, 흙받기
(기관차·전차 등의) 완충 장치
voca.explains:
A fender is a low metal wall built around a fireplace, which stops any coals that fall out of the fire from rolling onto the carpet.
A fender is the same as a fireguard.
The fenders of a car are the parts of the body over the wheels.
The fender of a car is a bar at the front or back that protects the car if it bumps into something.
The fenders of a boat are objects which hang against the outside and protect it from damage when it comes next to a harbour wall or another boat.

voca.title: fender-bender
voca.explains: I love my car, so I baby it a lot. However, one time I grazed the bumper while I was parking. I had nobody to blame. I had simply misjudged the angle. Thankfully, the car wasn’t badly dinged up. It was just a minor fender-bender.\n

voca.title: ferment
voca.explains: Ferment is excitement and trouble caused by change or uncertainty.\nIf a food, drink, or other natural substance ferments, or if it is fermented, a chemical change takes place in it so that alcohol is produced. This process forms part of the production of alcoholic drinks such as wine and beer.\n

voca.title: fermented shrimp
voca.explains: Pettitoes have a distinct smell. That's why a lot of people pair them with other foods with strong smells. It's typical to use fermented shrimp as dipping sauce. Garlic and peppers are common side dishes that go well with pettitoes.\n

voca.title: fern
voca.explains: A fern is a plant that has long stems with feathery leaves and no flowers. There are many types of fern.\n

voca.title: Ferris wheel
voca.explains: A Ferris wheel is a very large upright wheel with carriages around the edge of it which people can ride in. Ferris wheels are often found at theme parks or funfairs.\nThe tamer rides like the merry-go-round and the Ferris wheel didn’t seem so sissy anymore. To pass the time, I spent the rest of my day by the churros kiosk.\n

voca.title: ferry
voca.means: [풰뤼]\n(차랑, 사람 등을 운반하는) 연락선\n(보통 짧은 거리를 정기적으로 보트나 다른 차랑으로) 나르다, 수송하다
voca.explains: A ferry is a boat that transports passengers and sometimes also vehicles, usually across rivers or short stretches of sea.\nIf a vehicle ferries people or goods, it transports them, usually by means of regular journeys between the same two places.\n

voca.title: fertilize
voca.explains: When an egg from the ovary of a woman or female animal is fertilized, a sperm from the male joins with the egg, causing a baby or young animal to begin forming. A female plant is fertilized when its reproductive parts come into contact with pollen from the male plant.\nTo fertilize land means to improve its quality in order to make plants grow well on it, by spreading solid animal waste or a chemical mixture on it.\n

voca.title: fertilizer
voca.explains: Fertilizer is a substance such as solid animal waste or a chemical mixture that you spread on the ground in order to make plants grow more successfully.\n

voca.title: festive
voca.explains:
Something that is festive is special, colourful, or exciting, especially because of a holiday or celebration.
Festive means relating to a holiday or celebration, especially Christmas.
Korea is filled with a romantic atmosphere at Christmas. It is a very festive holiday.

voca.title: festive holiday
voca.explains: Korea is filled with a romantic atmosphere at Christmas. It is a very festive holiday.\n

voca.title: fetch
voca.means: [^퓃취]\n(어디를 가서) 가지고 오다, 데리고/불러 오다\n(특정 가격에) 팔리다
voca.explains: If you fetch something or someone, you go and get them from the place where they are.\nIf something fetches a particular sum of money, it is sold for that amount.\n

voca.title: fetch down
voca.means: ~을 쏘아 떨어뜨리다, 쳐 쓰러뜨리다\n(물가 따위)를 하락시키다

voca.title: fetch out
voca.means: ~을 꺼내다, \n(소질 따위)를 발현시키다, (광, 윤 따위)를 내다

voca.title: fetch up
voca.explains: to arrive somewhere by chance\n

voca.title: fever
voca.means:
[퓌-버r]
(의학적 이상 징후로서의) 열, 열병, 흥분, 열광
열기, 과열
~을 발열시키다, 열광시키다
voca.explains: If you have a fever when you are ill, your body temperature is higher than usual and your heart beats faster.\nA fever is extreme excitement or nervousness about something.\n

voca.title: few
voca.means:
[^피유]
(수가) 많지 않은, 적은
소수, 적은 수, 약간의 수, 몇몇
~보다 적은 (수의)
몇 명의 소수 (집단)
voca.explains:
You use a few to indicate that you are talking about a small number of people or things. You can also say a very few.
You use few to indicate that you are talking about a small number of people or things. You can use 'so', 'too' and 'very' in front of few.
You use few after adjectives and determiners to indicate that you are talking about a small number of things or people.
The few means a small set of people considered as separate from the majority, especially because they share a particular opportunity or quality that the others do not have.
You use as few as before a number to suggest that it is surprisingly small.

voca.title: few and far between
voca.explains:
not frequent; not happening often
Then, a nearby driver is dispatched. I use the service late at night, when taxis are few and far between.
Good restaurants like this are few and far between.
He's such a good worker that his mistakes are few and far between.
Nowadays, internet and mobile banking are the norm. Trips to the bank are few and far between.
Talented artists are few and far between.
Good movies these days are few and far between.

voca.title: fewer
voca.means: [^퓨-어r]\n(few의 비교급) 보다 소수의/적은\n보다 소수의, 보다 소수의 사람

voca.title: fiber
voca.means:
[^퐈이버r]
섬유, 섬유질, 섬유질 식품
소질, 성질, 기질, 성격, 
근성, 정신력
강도, 내구성
voca.explains:
the usual US spelling of fibre
They made ropes by braiding plant fibers.
Now, I try to eat healthier foods. I eat a lot of veggies and fruits. They are rich in vitamins and fiber.

voca.title: fickle
voca.explains: If you describe someone as fickle, you disapprove of them because they keep changing their mind about what they like or want.\nIf you say that something is fickle, you mean that it often changes and is unreliable.\n

voca.title: fiction
voca.explains:
Fiction refers to books and stories about imaginary people and events, rather than books about real people or events.
A statement or account that is fiction is not true.
If something is a fiction, it is not true, although people sometimes pretend that it is true.

voca.title: fictional
voca.explains: Fictional characters or events occur only in stories, plays, or films and never actually existed or happened.\n

voca.title: fiddle
voca.explains:
If you fiddle with an object, you keep moving it or touching it with your fingers.
If you fiddle with something, you change it in minor ways.
If you fiddle with a machine, you adjust it.
If someone fiddles financial documents, they alter them dishonestly so that they get money for themselves.
Some people call violins fiddles, especially when they are used to play folk music.
The air was filled with wild fiddle music and bagpipe playing.
Arthur fiddled with his glasses. Sometimes it was hard to keep his eye on the ball.
Arthur paused. He suddenly remembered where all his inspiration had come from. He lowered his eyes and fiddled with his glasses. "I, uh, heard this tune in my head. And then... and then the words just came to me. That’s all."

voca.title: fiddle around
voca.explains: You can use this expression when someone is doing something unimportant or trifling thing instead of doing something productive.\nStop fiddling around with the remote control! Come here and eat!\n

voca.title: fidget
voca.means:
[^픠짓t]
(초조, 지루함, 흥분 등으로) 꼼지락거리다
가만히 못있다.
안절부절못하다, 조바심내다
voca.explains: If you fidget, you keep moving your hands or feet slightly or changing your position slightly, for example because you are nervous, bored, or excited.\nIf you fidget with something, you keep moving it or touching it with your fingers with small movements, for example because you are nervous or bored.\n

voca.title: field
voca.means:
[^퓌일-d]
들판, 밭, (동물) 사육장
지역, 분야, (도서관, 실험실 등이 아닌) 현장
경기장, 수비 팀
(후보, 선수 등을) 내보내다
수비를 보다/맡다
(공을) 잡아서 던지다/처리하다
(질문, 논평을) 받아넘기다, 처리하다
voca.explains:
A field is an area of grass, for example in a park or on a farm. A field is also an area of land on which a crop is grown.
A sports field is an area of grass where sports are played.
A field is an area of land or sea bed under which large amounts of a particular mineral have been found.
A magnetic, gravitational, or electric field is the area in which that particular force is strong enough to have an effect.
A particular field is a particular subject of study or type of activity.
A field is an area of a computer's memory or a program where data can be entered, edited, or stored.
You can refer to the area where fighting or other military action in a war takes place as the field or the field of battle.
Your field of vision or your visual field is the area that you can see without turning your head.
The field is a way of referring to all the competitors taking part in a particular race or sports contest.
You use field to describe work or study that is done in a real, natural environment rather than in a theoretical way or in controlled conditions.
In a game of cricket, baseball, or rounders, the team that is fielding is trying to catch the ball, while the other team is trying to hit it.
If you say that someone fields a question, you mean that they answer it or deal with it, usually successfully.
"I'm not very comfortable yet. The other day I was playing second base. I fielded a sharp grounder but I couldn't get it out of my glove. It was like the ball was stuck with glue."
The Eagles took the field. In the first inning, a ball was hit sharply on the ground to Arthur. He fielded it cleanly and threw to second base.

voca.title: field of research
voca.explains:
Car technology is an important field of research. Carmakers are competing against each other to develop the best new vehicles.
Can you explain your field of research to me?
This is a completely new field of research.

voca.title: fiend
voca.explains: If you describe someone as a fiend, you mean that they are extremely wicked or cruel.\nFiend can be used after a noun to refer to a person who is very interested in the thing mentioned, and enjoys having a lot of it or doing it often.\n

voca.title: fierce
voca.explains:
A fierce animal or person is very aggressive or angry.
Fierce feelings or actions are very intense or enthusiastic, or involve great activity.
Fierce conditions are very intense, great, or strong.
He knew that the samurai were fierce Japanese fighters.
The samurai were fierce Japanese fighers.
These bears were larger and fiercer than toay's grizzlies.

voca.title: fiery
voca.means: [퐈이어뤼]\n불타는 듯한, 불의, 불붙은, \n(성질이) 불 같은, 격렬한
voca.explains:
If you describe something as fiery, you mean that it is burning strongly or contains fire.
You can use fiery for emphasis when you are referring to bright colours such as red or orange.
If you describe food or drink as fiery, you mean that it has a very strong hot or spicy taste.
If you describe someone as fiery, you mean that they express very strong emotions, especially anger, in their behaviour or speech
Jack and Annie slashed the air with their fiery weapons, jabbing at the keepers.

voca.title: fifteen
voca.explains: Fifteen is the number 15.\n"Listen to me," said Arthur. "I got the entry form. I’ve eaten fifteen boxes of Crunch, and this is my jingle. So we’re going to play it my way! Any questions?"\n

voca.title: fig
voca.explains: A fig is a soft sweet fruit that grows in hot countries. It is full of tiny seeds and is often eaten dried.\nA fig or a fig tree is a tree on which figs grow.\n

voca.title: fight
voca.means:
[^퐈잇t]
(적과) 싸우다, 맞서 싸우다, 전투하다
(무엇을 얻기 위해) 분투하다, 다투다, 언쟁을 벌이다
(신체적인 힘을 이용한) 싸움, 승부
voca.explains:
fight - fought - fought
campaign / battle / struggle / drive / war / fight
If you fight something unpleasant, you try in a determined way to prevent it or stop it happening.
If you fight for something, you try in a determined way to get it or achieve it.
If an army or group fights a battle with another army or group, they oppose each other with weapons. You can also say that two armies or groups fight a battle.
If a person or army fights in a battle or a war, they take part in it.
If one person fights with another, or fights them, the two people hit or kick each other because they want to hurt each other. You can also say that two people fight.
If one person fights with another, or fights them, they have an angry disagreement or quarrel. You can also say that two people fight.

voca.title: fight back
voca.explains: to defend yourself with actions or words when somebody attacks you or causes problems\n

voca.title: fight off
voca.means: 싸워서 격퇴하다, 손을 떼려고 애쓰다\n~와 싸워 물리치다
voca.explains: to struggle to avoid or repress\n

voca.title: fight off fatigue
voca.explains:
During work hours, I try to drink a lot of water. This helps to fight off fatigue. Plus, it’s good for my diet.
Light exercise is good way to fight off fatigue.
To fight off fatigue, you need to sleep well at night.

voca.title: fight out something
voca.means: (갈등 등에 대해) 해결/결판이 날 때까지 싸우다

voca.title: fight shy of
voca.explains: avoid something or doing something; not want to do something\n

voca.title: fight something back
voca.explains: to try hard not to show your feelings or not to do something\n

voca.title: fight song
voca.explains:
People sing fight songs.
This is the fight song of our school.
I learned the fight song at the sports match.

voca.title: figurative
voca.means: [^퓌겨러디v]\n(언어, 어구 등이) 비유적인, 수식 문구가 많은\n(그림, 조각 등이) 구상[조형]의
voca.explains: If you use a word or expression in a figurative sense, you use it with a more abstract or imaginative meaning than its ordinary literal one.\nFigurative art is a style of art in which people and things are shown in a realistic way.\n

voca.title: figure
voca.means:
[^퓌겨r]
(특히 공식적인 자료로 제시되는) 수치
모습, 인물, 모양, 숫자, 계산
계산하다, 생각하다, 판단하다, 
(어떤 과정/상황 등에서) 중요하다
voca.explains:
A figure is a particular amount expressed as a number, especially a statistic.
A figure is any of the ten written symbols from 0 to 9 that are used to represent a number.
You refer to someone that you can see as a figure when you cannot see them clearly or when you are describing them.
In art, a figure is a person in a drawing or a painting, or a statue of a person.
Someone who is referred to as a figure of a particular kind is a person who is well-known and important in some way.
If you figure that something is the case, you think or guess that it is the case.
If you say 'That figures' or 'It figures', you mean that the fact referred to is not surprising.

voca.title: figure on something
voca.explains: to include something in your plans; to plan something\n

voca.title: figure out
voca.explains:
to calculate the total amount of something
He feared that once they were alone, Squanto would figure out they'd never met before.
Arthur went into the house to get the package ready. He wrote a quick letter and put it in an envelope with the tape. Grandma Thora helped him figure out how many stamps he needed.

voca.title: figure something out
voca.means: (생각한 끝에) ~을 이해하다, 알아내다\n(양, 비용을) 계산/산출 하다\n~에 대한 답을 찾다
voca.explains:
to calculate the total amount of something
to come to understand somebody/something by thinking carefully
I finally figured out how to use my computer.

voca.title: fill
voca.means:
[^쀨]
(가득) 채우다, (약)조제하다
(구멍, 틈을) 때우다, 매우다, 총족시키다
충분, 가득함
voca.explains:
If you fill a container or area, or if it fills, an amount of something enters it that is enough to make it full.
If something fills a space, it is so big, or there are such large quantities of it, that there is very little room left.
If you fill a crack or hole, you put a substance into it in order to make the surface smooth again.
If a sound, smell, or light fills a space, or the air, it is very strong or noticeable.
If something fills you with an emotion, or if an emotion fills you, you experience this emotion strongly.

voca.title: fill in for somebody
voca.means: (~가 잠깐 자리를 비운 사이에) 대신 일을 봐주다
voca.explains: to take somebody's place for a short time and do the work they normally do\nCan you fill in for me Wednesday through Friday?\n

voca.title: fill out
voca.explains:
to become larger, rounder or fatter
Please fill out this application and give it to me when you're finished.
Please fill out this arrival (landing) card.
I filled out my application.
You have to fill out this application if you want library card.

voca.title: fill out a form
voca.explains:
The last time I donated was last week. I visited a local blood bank. When I got there, I filled out a form with my personal information.
I had to fill out a form for a membership.
I had to fill out a form before I could see the doctor.

voca.title: fill something in
voca.explains:
(fill something out) to complete a form, etc. by writing information on it
to fill something, such as a hole, a crack, etc. completely with a substance
Fill this in, please.

voca.title: fill up
voca.explains:
if a container or a place fills up or somebody fills it up, it becomes completely full
to fill your vehicle with petrol/gas, etc.
Mr. Franklin: Oh I'm sorry Martha but that class is filled up.
"Do the seats often fill up for practice?"

voca.title: fill with
voca.explains: I hope this year is filled with good news.\n

voca.title: fillet
voca.means: [픨^레이]\n(육류, 생선의 뼈를 발라내고 저민) 살코기\n(육류, 생선의) 뼈를 발라내다; 살코기를 저미다
voca.explains:
Fillet is a strip of meat, especially beef, that has no bones in it.
A fillet of fish is the side of a fish with the bones removed.
When you fillet fish or meat, you prepare it by taking the bones out.

voca.title: film
voca.means: [퓜]\n영화, 촬영, 필름, 작품\n~을 촬영하다, 영화를 제작하다
voca.explains:
A film consists of moving pictures that have been recorded so that they can be shown at the cinema or on television. A film tells a story, or shows a real situation.
Film of something is moving pictures of a real event that are shown on television or on a screen.
A film is the narrow roll of plastic that is used in a camera to take photographs.
The making of cinema films, considered as a form of art or a business, can be referred to as film or films.
A film of powder, liquid, or oil is a very thin layer of it.
If you film something, you use a camera to take moving pictures which can be shown on a screen or on television.

voca.title: filmgoer
voca.explains: Some filmgoers are sick and tired of the parade of blockbusters. Instead, they opt for the quirky appeal of Korean movies.\n

voca.title: filter
voca.means:
[^픨터r]
필터, 여과장치
(특정한 빛, 소리만 통과시키는) 여과기
여과하다, 거르다
서서히 이동하다, 서서히 알려지다
새어/스며 들어오다
voca.explains:
To filter a substance means to pass it through a device which is designed to remove certain particles contained in it.
If light or sound filters into a place, it comes in weakly or slowly, either through a partly covered opening, or from a long distance away.
When news or information filters through to people, it gradually reaches them.
A filter is a device through which a substance is passed when it is being filtered.
A filter is a device through which sound or light is passed and which blocks or reduces particular sound or light frequencies.

voca.title: filter something out
voca.means: (액체, 빛 등에서) ~을 걸러 내다\n(원치않는 사람, 물건을) 걸러내다
voca.explains: to remove something using a filter\n

voca.title: filter through
voca.explains: As they walked through the fallen leaves, sunlight filtered down through the tree branches.\n

voca.title: filthy
voca.means: [^픨띄]\n아주 더러운, 불결한, 상스러운, 추잡한\n더럽게, 매우, 상당히
voca.explains:
dirty / dusty / filthy / soiled / grubby
Something that is filthy is very dirty indeed.
It expresses an extreme case of a dirty condition.
If you describe something as filthy, you mean that you think it is morally very unpleasant and disgusting, sometimes in a sexual way.
Your room is absolutely filthy. You need to clean or at least open the windows.

voca.title: fin
voca.explains: A fish's fins are the flat objects which stick out of its body and help it to swim and keep its balance.\nA fin on something such as an aeroplane, rocket, or bomb is a flat part which sticks out and which is intended to help control its movement.\n

voca.title: final
voca.explains:
In a series of events, things, or people, the final one is the last one.
Final means happening at the end of an event or series of events.
If a decision or someone's authority is final, it cannot be changed or questioned.
The final is the last game or contest in a series and decides who is the winner.

voca.title: finalize
voca.means:
[^퐈이널롸이z]
마무리짓다, 완결하다
(계획 등을) 완성하다, 끝내다
~에 결말을 짓다, 최종적으로 승인하다
voca.explains: If you finalize something such as a plan or an agreement, you complete the arrangements for it, especially by discussing it with other people.\nWe need to finalize our travel plans.\n

voca.title: finally
voca.explains:
You use finally to suggest that something happens after a long period of time, usually later than you wanted or expected it to happen.
You use finally to indicate that something is last in a series of actions or events.
You use finally in speech or writing to introduce a final point, question, or topic.
Finally, Jack dragged himself out of the ocean.
Finally, the hugging and crying and laughing died down.
The stag finally came to a halt on the ledge of a steep cliff.

voca.title: finals
voca.explains:
the deciding part or parts of a sports or other competition
the last examination series in an academic or professional course
Compared to high school, college classes were demanding. There were so many tests. There were mid-terms in April and finals in June. We also had some pop quizzes.

voca.title: finance
voca.means: [퐈이넨s]\n재정, 금융, 재무, 자금, 재원\n~에 자금을 공급하다, 출자하다
voca.explains:
When someone finances something such as a project or a purchase, they provide the money that is needed to pay for them.
Finance is the commercial or government activity of managing money, debt, credit, and investment.
You can refer to the amount of money that you have and how well it is organized as your finances.

voca.title: financial
voca.explains: economic / financial / commercial / monetary / budgetary\nFinancial means relating to or involving money.\n

voca.title: find
voca.means:
[퐈인d]
(우연히) 찾아내다, 발견하다
(연구, 생각 끝에) 찾아내다, 알아내다
(자연스럽게) ~하게 되다, ~에 이르다
voca.explains:
If you find someone or something, you see them or learn where they are.
If you find something that you need or want, you succeed in achieving or obtaining it.
If something is found in a particular place or thing, it exists in that place.
If you find someone or something in a particular situation, they are in that situation when you see them or come into contact with them.

voca.title: find employment
voca.explains: Last year, I applied to various companies for work. Finding employment is a tall order these days.\n

voca.title: find one's way to
voca.explains: For my vacation last summer, I went to Thailand. I boarded the plane and found my way to my seat. I put my carry-on suitcase in the overhead compartment.\n

voca.title: find oneself
voca.means: 자신의 천분을 깨닫다, \n(~한) 기분이다\n(깨닫고 보니) ~에 있다

voca.title: find out
voca.means:
(조사하여) 발견하다, 생각해 내다, 
(해답을) 얻어내다
~임을 알아내다, 발견하다, 
~에 대한 진상을 알아내다.
voca.explains:
to learn a fact, a piece of information, or the truth about something/somebody
"But we'll soon find out!" she started waving.
"What did you find out?" Francine asked.
When I found out I was pregnant, I was over the moon.
"I don’t know, Buster. Do you really think you can find out what happened to the quarters?"

voca.title: find some time
voca.explains: I can't find enough time to exercise.\nBarry: Can you find some time for me today?\n

voca.title: find somebody out
voca.explains: to discover that somebody has been dishonest or has done something wrong\n

voca.title: find your feet
voca.explains: become used to a new job, place, etc. and start functioning well\n

voca.title: fine
voca.means:
[^퐈인]
벌금, 과태로
좋은, 순수한, 질 좋은, (제안, 결정 등이) 괜찮은
훌륭하게, 정교하게
voca.explains:
well / all right / OK / fine / healthy / strong / fit
You use fine to describe something that you admire and think is very good.
If you say that something is fine, you mean that it is satisfactory or acceptable.
A fine is a punishment in which a person is ordered to pay a sum of money because they have done something illegal or broken a rule.
If someone is fined, they are punished by being ordered to pay a sum of money because they have done something illegal or broken a rule.

voca.title: finger
voca.explains:
Your fingers are the four long thin parts at the end of each hand.
A finger of something such as smoke or land is an amount of it that is shaped rather like a finger.
If you finger something, you touch or feel it with your fingers.
All during practice, Arthur fingered the good-luck charm. But since no tough balls were hit to him, he couldn't be sure if it was working. When Francine came up to bat, he crouched down to be ready.

voca.title: fingernail
voca.explains: Your fingernails are the thin hard areas at the end of each of your fingers.\n

voca.title: fingerprint
voca.explains: Fingerprints are marks made by a person's fingers which show the lines on the skin. Everyone's fingerprints are different, so they can be used to identify criminals.\nIf someone is fingerprinted, the police take their fingerprints.\n

voca.title: fingerprint scan
voca.explains: Almost anything can be done with mobile banking. I can check my balance. I can make transfers and pay my bills. All the banks have smartphone applications, so it’s very easy. I can even use a fingerprint scan instead of a PIN.\n

voca.title: fingertips
voca.explains: In the past, I turned in to TV broadcasts for the weather forecast. Now, with smartphones, weather updates are at my fingertips.\nYou download an application on your phone, pay a small fee, and you can get access to a huge music archive at your fingertips.\n

voca.title: finish
voca.explains:
When you finish doing or dealing with something, you do or deal with the last part of it, so that there is no more for you to do or deal with.
When you finish something that you are making or producing, you reach the end of making or producing it, so that it is complete.
When something such as a course, film, or sale finishes, especially at a planned time, it ends.
You say that someone or something finishes a period of time or an event in a particular way to indicate what the final situation was like. You can also say that a period of time or an event finishes in a particular way.
The finish of something is the end of it or the last part of it.

voca.title: finish something off
voca.explains:
to destroy or kill somebody/something, especially somebody/something that is already injured
to defeat a person or team that you are competing against
to complete something
to use the last part of something, especially food or drink

voca.title: fir
voca.explains: A fir or a fir tree is a tall evergreen tree that has thin needle-like leaves.\n

voca.title: fir tree
voca.explains: They carried candles, a giant fir tree, and boughs of holly and pine.\n

voca.title: fire
voca.explains:
Fire is the hot, bright flames produced by things that are burning.
Fire or a fire is an occurrence of uncontrolled burning which destroys buildings, forests, or other things.
A fire is a burning pile of wood, coal, or other fuel that you make, for example to use for heat, light, or cooking.
If someone fires a gun or a bullet, or if they fire, a bullet is sent from a gun that they are using.
If you fire an arrow, you send it from a bow.

voca.title: fire away
voca.means: (명령문의 형태로) 말/질문 하세요.\n어서 얘기해 보세요.\n어서 물어보세요, 얘기하세요
voca.explains:
used to tell somebody to begin asking questions or to begin to speak
John: Fire away. What's on your mind?
I'm ready for any questions you want to ask me. Fire away.

voca.title: fire something off
voca.means: ~을 발사하다, \n(흔히 화가나서 말, 글을) 급히 하다/쓰다
voca.explains:
to shoot a bullet from a gun
to ask a lot of questions, etc. quickly, one after the other
to write a letter, report, etc. quickly, often because you are angry
if you fire off an email, you send it

voca.title: fire up
voca.means: 불을때다, 격분하다, 발끈해지다, 열광하다,\n~을 들어올리다\n전원을 켜다, 시동을 걸다
voca.explains: A : You might be all fired up about this game.\nLast week, I tried to fire up my laptop, but nothing happened. It simply refused to boot up. I called up my computer guru friend. He gave me a few pointers. None of them worked. My computer had given up the ghost.\n

voca.title: firecreacker
voca.explains: A firecracker is a firework that makes several loud bangs when it is lit.\n

voca.title: firefighter
voca.explains: Firefighters are people whose job is to put out fires.\n

voca.title: firefly
voca.explains: A firefly is a type of beetle that produces light from its body.\n

voca.title: firelight
voca.explains: Firelight is the light that comes from a fire.\nHis red armor gleamed in the firelight.\n

voca.title: firewood
voca.explains: Firewood is wood that has been cut into pieces so that it can be burned on a fire.\n

voca.title: fireworks
voca.explains:
a show in which large numbers of fireworks are let off simultaneously
an exciting or spectacular exhibition, as of musical virtuosity or wit
a burst of temper

voca.title: firm
voca.means:
[풔-r엄]
회사, 기업, 업체
굳은, 단단한, 확고한
단단히, 굳게, 견고히
다지다, 단단하게 하다
voca.explains:
A firm is an organization which sells or produces something or which provides a service which people pay for.
If something is firm, it does not change much in shape when it is pressed but is not completely hard.
If something is firm, it does not shake or move when you put weight or pressure on it, because it is strongly made or securely fastened.
If someone's grip is firm or if they perform a physical action in a firm way, they do it with quite a lot of force or pressure but also in a controlled way.

voca.title: firm hand
voca.explains: strong discipline and control\n

voca.title: firm up something
voca.explains: if somebody firms up an arrangement, an agreement, etc. it becomes more definite or less likely to change\nto make something, especially part of the body harder, or more solid\n

voca.title: firmly
voca.explains: "That position is filled." Arthur said firmly. He opened the door. "I think I hear Nadine calling you." Nadine was D.W.'s invisible friend. \n

voca.title: first
voca.explains:
The first thing, person, event, or period of time is the one that happens or comes before all the others of the same kind.
When something happens or is done for the first time, it has never happened or been done before.
The first thing, person, or place in a line is the one that is nearest to you or nearest to the front.
You use first to refer to the best or most important thing or person of a particular kind.
First is used in the title of the job or position of someone who has a higher rank than anyone else with the same basic job title.
If you do something first, you do it before anyone else does, or before you do anything else.
You use first when you are talking about what happens in the early part of an event or experience, in contrast to what happens later.
An event that is described as a first has never happened before and is important or exciting

voca.title: first and foremost
voca.explains: before everything else; most importantly\nFirst and foremost, I like the information I can glean. Shopping hosts courteously explain all there is to know about a product.\n

voca.title: first and last
voca.explains: mainly; only\n

voca.title: first come, first served
voca.explains: people will be dealt with, seen, etc. strictly in the order in which they arrive, apply, etc\n

voca.title: first generation of
voca.explains: I also had to do a lot of test prep for the Korean SAT. I gave my all the get ready. I paid attention in class. I also went to cram schools after classes and got private tutoring. I was part of the first generation of Internet lecture students.\n

voca.title: first impression
voca.explains: I’m not a very snappy dresser, but I do like to be presentable. Therefore, the bulk of my clothes are tried-and-true classics. My outfits aren’t eye-catching, but they’re not out of place in any setting. Whatever the case, the clothes you wear are an important part of your first impression.\n

voca.title: first off
voca.explains: before anything else; to begin with\n

voca.title: first order of business
voca.explains: I am a coffee addict. When I wake up in the morning, my first order of business is to make coffee. I can’t get the day started without some coffee.\n

voca.title: first place
voca.explains: Arthur looked up. His 868,233 points were in first place. He even got to put his initials next to them.\n

voca.title: first shot
voca.explains: I’m waiting for my first shot at sky diving.\n

voca.title: first state
voca.explains: The holiday marks the formation of Korean's first state.\n

voca.title: first taste
voca.explains: A country’s currency is an integral part of the local culture. It is often the first taste of a country for visitors from abroad.\n

voca.title: first things first
voca.means: 제일 중요한 걸 맨 먼저 해야 한다.
voca.explains: the most important or necessary duties, matters, etc. must be dealt with before others\n

voca.title: first try
voca.explains: I am loath to admit it, but I once failed my driver’s license exam. I signed up for driving lessons. I took them too lightly. I didn’t pay attention in class. As a result, I failed the exam on my first try.\n

voca.title: first-rate
voca.explains: If you say that something or someone is first-rate, you mean that they are extremely good and of the highest quality.\nI first found it through an internet search. I chose it at the time because it was within my price range. I was happily surprised. The food was first-rate. The staff were courteous and helpful. The rooms were clean and spacious. It was just a lot of bang for the buck.\n

voca.title: fish
voca.means:
[^퓟쉬]
물고기, 어류, 생선
(낚시대, 그물 등으로) 낚시하다, 낚다,
(취미로) 낚시하러 가다, 
(손으로) 찾다
voca.explains:
A fish is a creature that lives in water and has a tail and fins. There are many different kinds of fish.
Fish is the flesh of a fish eaten as food.
If you fish, you try to catch fish, either for food or as a form of sport or recreation.
If you fish a particular area of water, you try to catch fish in it.
If you say that someone is fishing for information or praise, you disapprove of the fact that they are trying to get it from someone in an indirect way.
If you tell someone that there are plenty more fish in the sea, you are comforting them by saying that although their relationship with someone has failed, there are many other people they can have relationships with.
Suddenly fish flopped on the bare sand!

voca.title: fish cake
voca.explains: A fish cake is a mixture of fish and potato that is made into a flat round shape, covered in breadcrumbs, and fried.\n

voca.title: fish for something
voca.explains: to try to make somebody tell you something, say something nice to you, etc. by asking them a question\n

voca.title: fish market
voca.explains: I can never get enough seafood. The fish market is one of my favorite places to visit. I recently went there with some friends for some raw fish.\n

voca.title: fishbowl
voca.means:
[퓌시보올]
(유리) 어항, 
사방에서 빤히 보이는 것, 프라이버시가 전혀 없는 장소
유치장
voca.explains: another name for goldfish bowl\n

voca.title: fishing
voca.explains: Fishing is the sport, hobby, or business of catching fish.\n

voca.title: fist
voca.explains:
Your hand is referred to as your fist when you have bent your fingers in towards the palm in order to hit someone, to make an angry gesture, or to hold something.
"No!" shouted King Arthur, pounding his fists on the table.
His father made a face. "For a moment I thought my life was over. The teacher was covered in goop. He shook his fist at me, and goop dropped off his hand onto the floor."

voca.title: fit
voca.means:
[^퓟t]
(모양, 크기가 어떤 사람, 사물에) 맞다, 적합하다, 
(옷을) 가봉하다, 설치/설비하다, 
(제자리에) 끼우다, 맞추다
적합, 맞는 것(물건), 발작, 경련
꼭맞는, 어울리는, 건강한
voca.explains:
If something fits, it is the right size and shape to go onto a person's body or onto a particular object.
If you are fitted for a particular piece of clothing, you try it on so that the person who is making it can see where it needs to be altered.
If something fits somewhere, it can be put there or is designed to be put there.
If you fit something into a particular space or place, you put it there.
If you fit something somewhere, you attach it there, or put it there carefully and securely.
If something fits something else or fits into it, it goes together well with that thing or is able to be part of it.
If something is fit for a particular purpose, it is suitable for that purpose.
If someone is fit to do something, they have the appropriate qualities or skills that will allow them to do it.

voca.title: fit in
voca.means: 적합하다, 어울리다, ~을 달다, 끼우다, 맞추다\n~와 어울리다
voca.explains: if something fits in, it looks pleasant or suitable with other things or in a particular place\nI want to fit in better with my colleagues.\n

voca.title: fit one's needs
voca.explains:
I need a phone that fits my needs.
Try to buy something that fits your needs.
It looks good, but does it fit your needs?

voca.title: fit somebody in
voca.explains:
to find a place for somebody/something, especially when there is not much space
to manage to find time to see somebody or to do something
I'll try and fit you in after lunch.

voca.title: fit something in
voca.explains: to find a place for somebody/something, especially when there is not much space\nto manage to find time to see somebody or to do something\n

voca.title: fit well
voca.explains: With age, it becomes easier to put on weight. If my weight rises by as little as 2 kilograms, it still bothers me. My clothes don’t fit well. The difference is visible around the jawline.\n

voca.title: fix
voca.means:
[퓍s]
(움직이지 않게) 고정시키다
(날짜, 시간, 양 등을) 정하다, 준비/주선하다
수리하다, 바로잡다
(얼굴, 머리를) 매만지다, 가다듬다
해결책, 곤경, 이해, 파악
voca.explains:
If something is fixed somewhere, it is attached there firmly or securely.
If you fix something, for example a date, price, or policy, you decide and say exactly what it will be.
If you fix something for someone, you arrange for it to happen or you organize it for them.
If you fix something which is damaged or which does not work properly, you repair it.
If you fix a problem or a bad situation, you deal with it and make it satisfactory.
If you fix your eyes on someone or something or if your eyes fix on them, you look at them with complete attention.
If someone or something is fixed in your mind, you remember them well, for example because they are very important, interesting, or unusual.
If someone fixes a gun, camera, or radar on something, they point it at that thing.

voca.title: fix on something
voca.explains: to decide to choose something\n

voca.title: fix someone up
voca.explains:
I started seeing someone a few weeks ago. A colleague fixed me up with one of his friends. We had a lot in common, so I genuinely looked forward to our date.
Are you trying to fix me up with her?
He fixed me up on a blind date.

voca.title: fix something up
voca.explains:
to arrange or organize something; to arrange for somebody to have something
to repair, decorate, etc. a room of a house
to build or make something quickly; to make something ready

voca.title: fixture
voca.means:
[^퓍s쳐r-]
설비, 고정 장치, 오래 붙어있는 사람
(붙박이) 설치물, 설비한 물건, 비품 (움직이지 못하는 것)
(일정한 직업이나 장소에) 늘 붙어 있는[오래 있는] 사람, 터줏대감
voca.explains:
Fixtures are pieces of furniture or equipment, for example baths and sinks, which are fixed inside a house or other building and which stay there if you move.
A fixture is a sports event which takes place on a particular date.
If you describe someone or something as a fixture in a particular place or occasion, you mean that they always seem to be there.

voca.title: flag
voca.means:
[플^뤠g]
(국가, 단체의 상징인) 기, 깃발
신호기, 창포(꽃)
(중요한 정보 앞에) 표시를 하다, 
지치다, 약해지다, 시들해지다
voca.explains:
A flag is a piece of cloth which can be attached to a pole and which is used as a sign, signal, or symbol of something, especially of a particular country.
Journalists sometimes refer to the flag of a particular country or organization as a way of referring to the country or organization itself and its values or power.
If you flag or if your spirits flag, you begin to lose enthusiasm or energy.

voca.title: flag a waiter
voca.explains: We flagged a waiter to ask what had happened. We found out our order hadn’t gone through. We had been served food that was ordered by another table. It was a big mess.\n

voca.title: flag down a cab
voca.explains: There was a time when flagging down a cab was relatively difficult late at night. But that has been rectified by the taxi service smartphone applications. Hailing a cab has become much easier.\n

voca.title: flag something down
voca.explains: to signal to the driver of a moving vehicle to stop, usually by waving your arm\nThere was a time when flagging down a cab was relatively difficult late at night. But that has been rectified by the taxi service smartphone applications. Hailing a cab has become much easier.\n

voca.title: flail
voca.means:
[플^뤠-일]
~을 도리께질 하다, 연타하다, 휘두르다
(곡물을 떠는) 도리께
마구 움직이다, (팔다리를) 마구 흔들다
도리깨
voca.explains: If your arms or legs flail or if you flail them about, they wave about in an energetic but uncontrolled way.\n

voca.title: flair
voca.explains: If you have a flair for a particular thing, you have a natural ability to do it well.\nIf you have flair, you do things in an original, interesting, and stylish way.\n

voca.title: flake
voca.means:
[플뤠익k]
(특히 다른 큰 것에서 떨어져 나온 얇은) 조각
괴짜, 뭘 잘 잊어먹는 사람
(얇게 조각조각) 벗겨지다. 떨어지다
포를 뜨다, 얇게 저미다
voca.explains: A flake is a small thin piece of something, especially one that has broken off a larger piece.\nIf something such as paint flakes, small thin pieces of it come off.\n

voca.title: flake out
voca.means: (극도로 지쳐서) 나가/곯아 떨어지다\n이상하게 굴기/맛이 가기 시작하다\n하기로 약속한 후에 꽁무니빼다
voca.explains:
to collapse or fall asleep because you are very tired
to begin to behave in a strange way
She flaked out on us the last time we went skiing.

voca.title: flaky
voca.means:
[^플뤠이끼-]
(조각조각으로) 얇게 벗겨지는
벗겨지기 쉬운
엷은 조각 모양의, 조각조각의
각질이 일어나는
(사람이) 괴짜인, 뭘 잘 잊어먹는
voca.explains:
Something that is flaky breaks easily into small thin pieces or tends to come off in small thin pieces.
If you describe an idea, argument, or person as flaky, you mean that they are rather eccentric and unreliable.
Dermatologists label my skin type as combination as opposed to dry or oily. It’s a nightmare. I break out in the t-zone but can’t use harsh acne medication because it will result in dry, flaky skin.

voca.title: flame
voca.means: [플레임]\n불길, 불꽃, 화염\n불꽃을 내며 타오르다, 시뻘게 지다, 활활 타오르다
voca.explains:
A flame is a hot bright stream of burning gas that comes from something that is burning.
A flame is an e-mail message which severely criticizes or attacks someone.
If something bursts into flames or bursts into flame, it suddenly starts burning strongly.
If someone or something fans the flames of a situation or feeling, usually a bad one, they make it more intense or extreme in some way.
If something goes up in flames, it starts to burn strongly and is destroyed.
The torches and candles flamed brighter, making the shadows leap wildly on the walls.
The fire blazed with leaping purple flames.

voca.title: flame out
voca.means: (제트 엔진이) 갑자기 멈추다\n기운이 꺽이다, 힘을 전부 발휘하다\n갑자기 타오르다, 불길이 확 치솟다
voca.explains: to fail, especially after succeeding for a while\n

voca.title: flammable
voca.explains: Flammable chemicals, gases, cloth, or other things catch fire and burn easily.\n

voca.title: flap
voca.means:
[플^뤱]
펄럭이다, 휘날리다, 퍼덕이다
(새가 날개를) 퍼덕거리다, 퍼덕이다
펄럭임, 늘어진 물건, 
뚜껑, 흥분 상태, 소동
voca.explains:
If something such as a piece of cloth or paper flaps or if you flap it, it moves quickly up and down or from side to side.
If a bird or insect flaps its wings or if its wings flap, the wings move quickly up and down.
If you flap your arms, you move them quickly up and down as if they were the wings of a bird.
A flap of cloth or skin, for example, is a flat piece of it that can move freely up and down or from side to side because it is held or attached by only one edge.
Ropes flapped and snapped in the wild wind.
The red cloak flapped in the bitter wind.
Arthur put down his backpack on the counter. One corner of Mr. Haney's envelope was sticking out of the flap.
At that moment the roof flew off the house. The top of the envelope rose up, and the flap opened.

voca.title: flap about
voca.means: ~을 (걱정하는 기색으로) 말하다, \n필요 이상으로 걱정하다\n~에 관해 잡담하다

voca.title: flap away
voca.means: 날개를 퍼덕이며 날아가다\n~을 두드려 쫓다, 물리치다

voca.title: flare
voca.means:
[플^뤠어r]
(보통 잠깐 동안) 확 타오르다
(특히 분노, 폭력 사태가) 터지다, 치솟다
버럭 화를 내다, 소리를 지르다
(옷이) 나팔 모양이다, 아랫부분 쪽으로 폭이 넓어지다
(특히 화가 나서 코를) 벌름거리다
(순간적으로) 확 타오르는 불길, 불꽃
신호탄, 조명탄
나팔 모양
voca.explains:
A flare is a small device that produces a bright flame. Flares are used as signals, for example on ships.
Flares are trousers that are very wide at the bottom.
If something such as trouble, violence, or conflict flares, it starts or becomes more violent.
If people's tempers flare, they get angry.
If someone's nostrils flare or if they flare them, their nostrils become wider, often because the person is angry or upset.
If something such as a dress flares, it spreads outwards at one end to form a wide shape.

voca.title: flare up
voca.means:
확 타오르다
벌컥 화를 내다
갑자기 재발하다/심해지다
(통증 등이) 갑작스럽고 강렬하게 발생하다
voca.explains:
to suddenly burn more strongly
if fighting, tension, anger, etc. flares up, it starts very suddenly and violently
if a person flares up, they show sudden anger towards somebody
if an illness or injury flares up, it suddenly starts again or becomes worse
I am a night owl, so sometimes I like to burn the midnight oil. But when I sit at my desk for too long, my shoulders flare up. At times, the pain is so bad, I’m hardly able to move.
When my headaches flare up, I can't do anything.
Emotions flared up in his heart.

voca.title: flash
voca.means:
[^플레시]
(잠깐) 비치다, 번쩍이다, 비추다, 
(불빛으로) 신호를 보내다, 비추다
휙 내보이다, 휙 움직이다/지나가다
(생각이) 불현듯 들다
폭발하다, 번득이다
번쩍임, 섬광, 순간, (잠깐) 반짝임
불빛신호,
voca.explains:
A flash is a sudden burst of light or of something shiny or bright.
You talk about a flash of something when you are saying that it happens very suddenly and unexpectedly.
Flash is the use of special bulbs to give more light when taking a photograph.
A flash is the same as a flashlight.
If a light flashes or if you flash a light, it shines with a sudden bright light, especially as quick, regular flashes of light.
If something flashes past or by, it moves past you so fast that you cannot see it properly.
If something flashes through or into your mind, you suddenly think about it.
If you flash something such as an identity card, you show it to people quickly and then put it away again.
If a picture or message flashes up on a screen, or if you flash it onto a screen, it is displayed there briefly or suddenly, and often repeatedly.
If you flash news or information to a place, you send it there quickly by computer, satellite, or other system.
If you flash a look or a smile at someone, you suddenly look at them or smile at them.
If someone's eyes flash, they suddenly show a strong emotion, especially anger.
If you describe something as flash, you mean that it looks expensive, fashionable, and new.

voca.title: flash back
voca.means: (~을) 회상하다, 떠올리다\n(형화에서) 회상/과거 장면을 보여주다\n톡 쏘아붙이다
voca.explains: if your mind or your thoughts flash back to something that happened in the past, you suddenly remember it\n

voca.title: flash by
voca.explains: to go or pass very quickly; to go very quickly past somebody/something\n

voca.title: flash on somebody
voca.explains: if something flashes on you, you suddenly realize it\n

voca.title: flash on something
voca.explains: to remember or realize something\n

voca.title: flash past
voca.explains: to go or pass very quickly; to go very quickly past somebody/something\n

voca.title: flash something around
voca.explains: to show something valuable, especially money or jewellery to people, or let them see it, to impress them\n

voca.title: flat
voca.means:
[^플뤳t]
평지, 펑크, 내림표
평평한, 납작한, 바람빠진, 김빠진, 
평평하게, 단호하게
voca.explains:
A flat is a set of rooms for living in, usually on one floor and part of a larger building. A flat usually includes a kitchen and bathroom.
A low flat area of uncultivated land, especially an area where the ground is soft and wet, can be referred to as flats or a flat.
You can refer to one of the broad flat surfaces of an object as the flat of that object.
Something that is flat is level, smooth, or even, rather than sloping, curved, or uneven.

voca.title: flat out
voca.explains:
as fast as possible; with all the energy, strength, etc. you have
lying down, especially because you are ill or extremely tired
in a definite and direct way; completely

voca.title: flatfish
voca.explains: Flatfish are sea fish with flat wide bodies, for example plaice or sole.\n

voca.title: flatter
voca.means:
[플^뤠러r]
아첨하다, 알랑거리다
자기가 잘난 줄 착각하다
(실제보다) 돋보이게 하다
voca.explains:
If someone flatters you, they praise you in an exaggerated way that is not sincere, because they want to please you or to persuade you to do something.
If you flatter yourself that something good is the case, you believe that it is true, although others may disagree. If someone says to you 'you're flattering yourself' or 'don't flatter yourself', they mean that they disagree with your good opinion of yourself.
If something flatters you, it makes you appear more attractive.

voca.title: flatulent
voca.means:
[f^뤠처런t]
허풍스런, 허장성세인
(이야기 등이) 과장된, 공허한
배에 가스가 찬, 속이 부글거리는
(배에) 가스가 찬, 헛배부른
voca.explains:
suffering from or caused by an excessive amount of gas in the alimentary canal, producing uncomfortable distension
generating excessive gas in the alimentary canal
pretentious or windy in style
Another time, I was wearing a formal suit. The pants got caught on something. With a flatulent sound, they ripped in the seat. All day, I was a bundle of nerves.

voca.title: flatulent sound
voca.explains: Another time, I was wearing a formal suit. The pants got caught on something. With a flatulent sound, they ripped in the seat. All day, I was a bundle of nerves.\n

voca.title: flavor
voca.means:
[플뤠이버r]
(독특한) 풍미, 향미, 맛, 향, 
멋, 운치, 정취,
(물건, 사람의) 특징, 특색
풍미를 더하다, 맛을 내다

voca.title: flaw
voca.means: [^플롸-]\n흠이 생기게 하다, 손상하다\n결점, 흠, 결함, 금, 균열
voca.explains:
A flaw in something such as a theory or argument is a mistake in it, which causes it to be less effective or valid.
A flaw in someone's character is an undesirable quality that they have.
A flaw in something such as a pattern or material is a fault in it that should not be there.

voca.title: flawless
voca.means: [플^뤄-뤠s]\n흠없는, 완벽한, 흠이 없는, 결점 없는\n나무랄 데 없는
voca.explains: If you say that something or someone is flawless, you mean that they are extremely good and that there are no faults or problems with them.\n

voca.title: flea
voca.explains: A flea is a very small jumping insect that has no wings and feeds on the blood of humans or animals.\n

voca.title: flea market
voca.explains: A flea market is an outdoor market which sells cheap used goods and sometimes also very old furniture.\n

voca.title: fleabag
voca.means:
[^플릐벡]
초라한 공공건물, 싸구려 여인숙
더러운 몰골(을 한 사람)
지저분한 짐승
voca.explains: a dirty or unkempt person\na cheap or dirty hotel\n

voca.title: flee
voca.explains: flee - fled - fled\nIf you flee from something or someone, or flee a person or thing, you escape from them.\n

voca.title: flesh
voca.means:
[플레쉬]
(사람, 동물의) 살, 고기, 
(사람의) 피부, 
(정신, 영혼에 대비되는) 육체
voca.explains:
Flesh is the soft part of a person's or animal's body between the bones and the skin.
You can use flesh to refer to human skin and the human body, especially when you are considering it in a sexual way.
The flesh of a fruit or vegetable is the soft inside part of it.
You use flesh and blood to emphasize that someone has human feelings or weaknesses, often when contrasting them with machines.
If you say that someone is your own flesh and blood, you are emphasizing that they are a member of your family.
If something makes your flesh creep or makes your flesh crawl, it makes you feel disgusted, shocked or frightened.

voca.title: flesh something out
voca.explains: to add more details or information to an argument, an idea, a drawing, etc.\n

voca.title: fleshy
voca.means: [플뤠쉬]\n살집이 있는, 살찐,\n(화초나 과일이) 다육질의, 두껍고 부드러운
voca.explains: If you describe someone as fleshy, you mean that they are slightly too fat.\nFleshy parts of the body or fleshy plants are thick and soft.\n

voca.title: flex
voca.means:
[플^뤡s]
(준비 운동으로) 몸을 풀다
(관절을) 굽히다, 구부리다, 수축시키다, 
굴곡, 굽힘, 탄력성/신축성 있는 밴드
voca.explains:
A flex is an electric cable containing two or more wires that is connected to an electrical appliance.
If you flex your muscles or parts of your body, you bend, move, or stretch them for a short time in order to exercise them.
Arther flexed his hands.

voca.title: flexible
voca.means:
[플^뤡서블]
구부릴 수 있는, 유연한, 적응성
신축성/융통성 있는, 
(사람, 성격 등이) 유순한, 다루기 쉬운, 시키는 대로 하는
융통성 있는, 적응성 있는, 탄력적인
voca.explains: A flexible object or material can be bent easily without breaking.\nSomething or someone that is flexible is able to change easily and adapt to different conditions and circumstances as they occur.\n

voca.title: flick
voca.means:
[플^뤽k]
(손가락 등으로) 튀기다, 털다, 
가볍게 치다, 휘두르다, 잽싸게 움직이다
가볍게 침, 튀기기, 재빨리 움직임
영화, 영화관, 극장
voca.explains:
If something flicks in a particular direction, or if someone flicks it, it moves with a short, sudden movement.
If you flick something away, or off something else, you remove it with a quick movement of your hand or finger.
If you flick something such as a whip or a towel, or flick something with it, you hold one end of it and move your hand quickly up and then forward, so that the other end moves.
If you flick a switch, or flick an electrical appliance on or off, you press the switch sharply so that it moves into a different position and works the equipment.
If you flick through a book or magazine, you turn its pages quickly, for example to get a general idea of its contents or to look for a particular item. If you flick through television channels, you continually change channels very quickly, for example using a remote control.
Finally, I’ve also seen several movie trailers online. The one that stood out for me was the one for “Captain America-Civil War.” I made my way through many versions. The trailers did what they were supposed to do. They made me go watch the flick.

voca.title: flick off
voca.explains: flick the dust off one's hat\n

voca.title: flick through something
voca.means: (책 등을) 휙휙 넘기다\n(텔레비전 채널을) 휙휙 돌리다, 바꾸다
voca.explains: to turn the pages of a book, etc. quickly, or look through a pile of papers, etc. without reading everything\n

voca.title: flicker
voca.means: [^플뤽거r]\n깜박이다, 어른거리다, 나부끼다\n(빛의) 깜박거림, 흔들거리는 불김, 깜박임
voca.explains:
If a light or flame flickers, it shines unsteadily.
If you experience a flicker of emotion, you feel that emotion only for a very short time, and not very strongly.
In the flickering light, Jack saw a dark figure sitting on a woven mat.
In the flickering torchlight, the guards looked like giants.
In retrospect, the lights flickered on and off for a few days prior to the incident. However, I ignored the red flag and blew off the responsibility until the very last minute.

voca.title: flickering
voca.explains: In the flickering light, Jack saw a high ceiling and walls hung with tapestries.\n

voca.title: flight
voca.means:
[^플롸잇t]
비행, 비행기, 항공편, 
탈출, 도피
(공이 멋지게 날아가게) 차다, 치다, 던지다
voca.explains:
A flight is a journey made by flying, usually in an aeroplane.
You can refer to an aeroplane carrying passengers on a particular journey as a particular flight.
Flight is the action of flying, or the ability to fly.
A flight of birds is a group of them flying together.
Flight is the act of running away from a dangerous or unpleasant situation or place.
A flight of steps or stairs is a set of steps or stairs that lead from one level to another without changing direction.
If someone takes flight, they run away from an unpleasant situation or place.

voca.title: flight attendant
voca.explains:
On an aeroplane, the flight attendants are the people whose job is to look after the passengers and serve their meals.
On the plane, the flight attendants were very nice to me because I was so young.
The flight attendants gave a safety demonstration. Soon, we took off. After a while, the attendants came by with the beverage cart. Later on, we had our in-flight meal.
